(function(){const grade5Unit1Selections={"selections":[{"selection_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son","grade":5,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":1,"week":1,"title":"The Path to Paper Son and Louie Share Kim, Paper Son","author":"Grant Din and Barbara D. Krasner","genre":"Paired Informational Text","essential_question":"How do journeys and records shape people\u0027s lives?","weekly_question":"How did paper sons use documents and interviews to enter the United States?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["opportunity","prohibited","immigration","records","interview"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"The Path to Paper Son and Louie Share Kim, Paper Son. How did paper sons use documents and interviews to enter the United States?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"opportunity\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What does the word \"opportunity\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q002","read_aloud":"According to the text, what did the Chinese Exclusion Act do? A. It helped families move to the U.S. B. It forced people to leave California. C. It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing their families. D. It allowed merchants to buy more land.","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\"","stem":"According to the text, what did the Chinese Exclusion Act do?","choices":{"A":"It helped families move to the U.S.","B":"It forced people to leave California.","C":"It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing their families.","D":"It allowed merchants to buy more land."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states that the act prohibited laborers from sending for their families.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q003","read_aloud":"Where was the immigration station for people coming from Asia located? A. In New York B. In California C. In China D. In the Hall of Records","excerpt":"\"In 1910, Angel Island Immigration Station opens in California to process immigrants arriving from Asia.\"","stem":"Where was the immigration station for people coming from Asia located?","choices":{"A":"In New York","B":"In California","C":"In China","D":"In the Hall of Records"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text identifies that the station in California was for those arriving from Asia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1910, Angel Island Immigration Station opens in California to process immigrants arriving from Asia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q004","read_aloud":"How old was Louie Share Kim when he arrived at Angel Island? A. 12 years old B. 14 years old C. 20 years old D. 98 years old","excerpt":"\"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916.\"","stem":"How old was Louie Share Kim when he arrived at Angel Island?","choices":{"A":"12 years old","B":"14 years old","C":"20 years old","D":"98 years old"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states he was fourteen years old when he arrived.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q005","read_aloud":"Why did Louie\u0027s father want him to wear a suit and tie for his photo? A. To make him look American B. Because it was a special holiday C. Because he was a famous person D. To keep him warm on the boat","excerpt":"\"His father made sure he even looked American in his passport photograph by making him wear a suit and tie.\"","stem":"Why did Louie\u0027s father want him to wear a suit and tie for his photo?","choices":{"A":"To make him look American","B":"Because it was a special holiday","C":"Because he was a famous person","D":"To keep him warm on the boat"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that the father wanted his son to look American for the passport photo.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"His father made sure he even looked American in his passport photograph by making him wear a suit and tie.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"citizens\" most likely mean in this excerpt? A. people who visit a country for a short time B. people who belong to a place and have rights there C. people who work in government jobs D. people who travel between countries for business","excerpt":"\"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China. The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\"","stem":"What does the word \"citizens\" most likely mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"people who visit a country for a short time","B":"people who belong to a place and have rights there","C":"people who work in government jobs","D":"people who travel between countries for business"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Citizens are people who belong to a country and have rights there. The text says U.S. citizens could send for families, but laborers could not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China. The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Chinese workers liked to travel alone B. Many Chinese workers left families in China when they came to America C. All Chinese workers were single men D. Families in China did not want to come to America","excerpt":"\"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Chinese workers liked to travel alone","B":"Many Chinese workers left families in China when they came to America","C":"All Chinese workers were single men","D":"Families in China did not want to come to America"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt tells us many Chinese workers were married and had children who stayed in China. This is the main point.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q008","read_aloud":"According to this excerpt, what did the Chinese Exclusion Act do? A. It helped Chinese families move to America B. It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing families to the U.S. C. It gave money to Chinese workers D. It made it easier for all Chinese people to immigrate","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\"","stem":"According to this excerpt, what did the Chinese Exclusion Act do?","choices":{"A":"It helped Chinese families move to America","B":"It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing families to the U.S.","C":"It gave money to Chinese workers","D":"It made it easier for all Chinese people to immigrate"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says the Act \"prohibited\" or stopped Chinese laborers from sending for their families. That is the key detail.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q009","read_aloud":"Who was allowed to send for their families under the Chinese Exclusion Act? A. Only teachers and students B. Merchants and U.S. citizens C. All Chinese workers D. Only people born in California","excerpt":"\"But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\"","stem":"Who was allowed to send for their families under the Chinese Exclusion Act?","choices":{"A":"Only teachers and students","B":"Merchants and U.S. citizens","C":"All Chinese workers","D":"Only people born in California"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to send for their families, but laborers were not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q010","read_aloud":"Why did some people report the birth of sons when they returned from China? A. To get more money from the government B. To create immigration slots that could be used later C. To help build new schools in China D. To make their families happy","excerpt":"\"So each time a member of those groups returned to China for a visit, they often reported the birth of a son or two to the immigration authorities when they came back.\"","stem":"Why did some people report the birth of sons when they returned from China?","choices":{"A":"To get more money from the government","B":"To create immigration slots that could be used later","C":"To help build new schools in China","D":"To make their families happy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that reporting births created \"immigration slots\" that could be used to bring another Chinese person to America.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"So each time a member of those groups returned to China for a visit, they often reported the birth of a son or two to the immigration authorities when they came back.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What does the word \"prohibited\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. allowed B. helped C. stopped D. watched","excerpt":"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.","stem":"What does the word \"prohibited\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"allowed","B":"helped","C":"stopped","D":"watched"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Prohibited\" means not allowed or stopped. The law did not let laborers bring their families.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of these sentences? A. Many Chinese workers left their families in China. B. Chinese workers wanted to become citizens. C. Women came to the United States to work. D. Children traveled alone to America.","excerpt":"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China.","stem":"What is the main idea of these sentences?","choices":{"A":"Many Chinese workers left their families in China.","B":"Chinese workers wanted to become citizens.","C":"Women came to the United States to work.","D":"Children traveled alone to America."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The sentences say most workers were men and many had families left in China.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What did an \"immigration slot\" allow? A. A person to become a citizen B. A person to come to America C. A person to return to China D. A person to find gold","excerpt":"The claim created immigration slots, which could be used to bring another Chinese to America.","stem":"What did an \"immigration slot\" allow?","choices":{"A":"A person to become a citizen","B":"A person to come to America","C":"A person to return to China","D":"A person to find gold"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sentence says the slot could be used to bring another Chinese to America.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The claim created immigration slots, which could be used to bring another Chinese to America."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q014","read_aloud":"What happened to the Hall of Records? A. It was moved to China. B. It was destroyed. C. It was sold to merchants. D. It was turned into a school.","excerpt":"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records.","stem":"What happened to the Hall of Records?","choices":{"A":"It was moved to China.","B":"It was destroyed.","C":"It was sold to merchants.","D":"It was turned into a school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the earthquake and fire destroyed the Hall of Records.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"opportunity\" mean in this sentence? A. a problem B. a chance to do something C. a law D. a punishment","excerpt":"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.","stem":"What does \"opportunity\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a problem","B":"a chance to do something","C":"a law","D":"a punishment"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Opportunity\" means a good chance to do something. Here, it was a chance to claim false births.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What does the word \"citizens\" mean in this sentence? A. people who work in stores B. people who belong to a particular country C. people who travel to other countries D. people who build houses","excerpt":"\"But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so. So each time a member of those groups returned to China for a visit, they often reported the birth of a son or two to the immigration authorities when they came back.\"","stem":"What does the word \"citizens\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"people who work in stores","B":"people who belong to a particular country","C":"people who travel to other countries","D":"people who build houses"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says citizens were allowed to bring family members to the United States. This means they were people who belonged to the United States.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so. So each time a member of those groups returned to China for a visit, they often reported the birth of a son or two to the immigration authorities when they came back.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What happened in San Francisco in 1906? A. A new Hall of Records was built. B. An earthquake and fire destroyed much of the city. C. Many Chinese families moved there. D. The Chinese Exclusion Act was passed.","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records.\"","stem":"What happened in San Francisco in 1906?","choices":{"A":"A new Hall of Records was built.","B":"An earthquake and fire destroyed much of the city.","C":"Many Chinese families moved there.","D":"The Chinese Exclusion Act was passed."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that an earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco in 1906.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q018","read_aloud":"What did the Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 do? A. It helped Chinese workers find jobs. B. It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing their families to America. C. It gave Chinese workers free housing. D. It allowed all Chinese people to become citizens.","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\"","stem":"What did the Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 do?","choices":{"A":"It helped Chinese workers find jobs.","B":"It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing their families to America.","C":"It gave Chinese workers free housing.","D":"It allowed all Chinese people to become citizens."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the Act prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families. \"Prohibited\" means stopped or did not allow.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q019","read_aloud":"Who was allowed to enter the United States from China? A. Only laborers B. Only children C. Diplomats, merchants, students, and teachers D. Everyone who wanted to visit","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States. Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China.\"","stem":"Who was allowed to enter the United States from China?","choices":{"A":"Only laborers","B":"Only children","C":"Diplomats, merchants, students, and teachers","D":"Everyone who wanted to visit"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text lists specific groups like diplomats and merchants who were allowed to enter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States. Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q020","read_aloud":"Why did Share Kim become a \"paper son\"? A. Because his real father lived in San Francisco B. To get around the law that stopped laborers from entering C. Because he wanted to be a teacher D. To help build the Hall of Records","excerpt":"\"Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America. Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China.\"","stem":"Why did Share Kim become a \"paper son\"?","choices":{"A":"Because his real father lived in San Francisco","B":"To get around the law that stopped laborers from entering","C":"Because he wanted to be a teacher","D":"To help build the Hall of Records"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that many immigrants used this method to enter the U.S. when the law blocked them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America. Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q021","read_aloud":"What did the officials at Angel Island do to check if Share Kim was telling the truth? A. They gave him a written test B. They asked questions about his village and family C. They looked at his school grades D. They asked him to bring his father","excerpt":"\"They asked question after question about their family history and their village\u0027s layout. Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America.\"","stem":"What did the officials at Angel Island do to check if Share Kim was telling the truth?","choices":{"A":"They gave him a written test","B":"They asked questions about his village and family","C":"They looked at his school grades","D":"They asked him to bring his father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Officials interrogated immigrants by asking detailed questions about their homes and families.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They asked question after question about their family history and their village\u0027s layout. Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q022","read_aloud":"How did families pay for the paper son documents? A. They sold their homes B. They borrowed money C. They worked for the government D. They traded gold","excerpt":"\"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip.\"","stem":"How did families pay for the paper son documents?","choices":{"A":"They sold their homes","B":"They borrowed money","C":"They worked for the government","D":"They traded gold"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that families had to borrow money because the documents were expensive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q023","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what does \"immigration\" mean? A. The act of moving to a new country to live B. The act of taking a vacation C. The process of building a new house D. The act of buying a plane ticket","excerpt":"\"Angel Island Immigration Station might have looked like this when Share Kim arrived as a child.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what does \"immigration\" mean?","choices":{"A":"The act of moving to a new country to live","B":"The act of taking a vacation","C":"The process of building a new house","D":"The act of buying a plane ticket"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Immigration refers to the process of leaving one country to settle in another.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Angel Island Immigration Station might have looked like this when Share Kim arrived as a child.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q024","read_aloud":"Why did paper sons need a coaching book? A. To learn how to speak English quickly B. To help them remember answers for the officials C. To study for school in America D. To know how to find a job","excerpt":"\"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing. The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers.\"","stem":"Why did paper sons need a coaching book?","choices":{"A":"To learn how to speak English quickly","B":"To help them remember answers for the officials","C":"To study for school in America","D":"To know how to find a job"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The book contained the information needed to pass the interrogation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing. The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l01-q025","read_aloud":"What did the \"Certificate of Identity\" prove? A. That he was a wealthy merchant B. That he was a good student C. That he was allowed to enter as a son of a native D. That he had traveled across the ocean","excerpt":"\"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\"","stem":"What did the \"Certificate of Identity\" prove?","choices":{"A":"That he was a wealthy merchant","B":"That he was a good student","C":"That he was allowed to enter as a son of a native","D":"That he had traveled across the ocean"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The certificate was the legal document showing he was admitted to the country.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q001","read_aloud":"Who was allowed to enter the United States from China? A. Only laborers B. Only children C. Diplomats, merchants, students, and teachers D. Everyone who wanted to visit","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States. Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China.\"","stem":"Who was allowed to enter the United States from China?","choices":{"A":"Only laborers","B":"Only children","C":"Diplomats, merchants, students, and teachers","D":"Everyone who wanted to visit"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text lists specific groups like diplomats and merchants who were allowed to enter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States. Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q002","read_aloud":"Why did Share Kim become a \"paper son\"? A. Because his real father lived in San Francisco B. To get around the law that stopped laborers from entering C. Because he wanted to be a teacher D. To help build the Hall of Records","excerpt":"\"Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America. Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China.\"","stem":"Why did Share Kim become a \"paper son\"?","choices":{"A":"Because his real father lived in San Francisco","B":"To get around the law that stopped laborers from entering","C":"Because he wanted to be a teacher","D":"To help build the Hall of Records"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that many immigrants used this method to enter the U.S. when the law blocked them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America. Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q003","read_aloud":"What did the officials at Angel Island do to check if Share Kim was telling the truth? A. They gave him a written test B. They asked questions about his village and family C. They looked at his school grades D. They asked him to bring his father","excerpt":"\"They asked question after question about their family history and their village\u0027s layout. Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America.\"","stem":"What did the officials at Angel Island do to check if Share Kim was telling the truth?","choices":{"A":"They gave him a written test","B":"They asked questions about his village and family","C":"They looked at his school grades","D":"They asked him to bring his father"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Officials interrogated immigrants by asking detailed questions about their homes and families.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They asked question after question about their family history and their village\u0027s layout. Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q004","read_aloud":"How did families pay for the paper son documents? A. They sold their homes B. They borrowed money C. They worked for the government D. They traded gold","excerpt":"\"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip.\"","stem":"How did families pay for the paper son documents?","choices":{"A":"They sold their homes","B":"They borrowed money","C":"They worked for the government","D":"They traded gold"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that families had to borrow money because the documents were expensive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q005","read_aloud":"What was the effect of the earthquake and fire on birth records? A. New records were created right away B. The birth records were destroyed C. People stopped keeping records D. The records were moved to China","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What was the effect of the earthquake and fire on birth records?","choices":{"A":"New records were created right away","B":"The birth records were destroyed","C":"People stopped keeping records","D":"The records were moved to China"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says the earthquake and fire \"destroyed\" the Hall of Records, which included birth records.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What happened first in this sequence? A. Chinese people claimed they were born in San Francisco B. The earthquake and fire destroyed birth records C. Immigration slots were created D. Families borrowed money for the trip","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco... With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\"","stem":"What happened first in this sequence?","choices":{"A":"Chinese people claimed they were born in San Francisco","B":"The earthquake and fire destroyed birth records","C":"Immigration slots were created","D":"Families borrowed money for the trip"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The earthquake and fire happened first, which destroyed the records. Then people used that as an opportunity to make claims.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco... With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What did some Chinese people claim after the records were destroyed? A. They had never been to San Francisco B. They were born in San Francisco and had family in China C. They wanted to go back to China D. They did not have any children","excerpt":"\"They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\"","stem":"What did some Chinese people claim after the records were destroyed?","choices":{"A":"They had never been to San Francisco","B":"They were born in San Francisco and had family in China","C":"They wanted to go back to China","D":"They did not have any children"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states they claimed birth in San Francisco and having a wife and sons in China.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q008","read_aloud":"Why was the destruction of birth records an \"opportunity\" for some Chinese immigrants? A. It made travel to China cheaper B. It was harder for officials to check if claims about birthplace were true C. It helped them learn English faster D. It gave them free land in California","excerpt":"\"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Why was the destruction of birth records an \"opportunity\" for some Chinese immigrants?","choices":{"A":"It made travel to China cheaper","B":"It was harder for officials to check if claims about birthplace were true","C":"It helped them learn English faster","D":"It gave them free land in California"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Without birth records, officials could not easily prove whether someone was really born in San Francisco or not. This made it easier to claim U.S. citizenship.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q009","read_aloud":"How did families pay for paper son documents? A. They sold their homes. B. They borrowed money. C. They asked the government for help. D. They found gold in California.","excerpt":"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip.","stem":"How did families pay for paper son documents?","choices":{"A":"They sold their homes.","B":"They borrowed money.","C":"They asked the government for help.","D":"They found gold in California."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says families borrowed money to make the trip possible.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q010","read_aloud":"Why did a paper son need to memorize answers? A. To pass a school test B. To impress his friends C. To answer questions during immigration processing D. To become a teacher","excerpt":"The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers.","stem":"Why did a paper son need to memorize answers?","choices":{"A":"To pass a school test","B":"To impress his friends","C":"To answer questions during immigration processing","D":"To become a teacher"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The coaching book had questions and answers for immigration processing, so he had to memorize them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q011","read_aloud":"How old was Louie Share Kim when he arrived at Angel Island? A. 10 years old B. 12 years old C. 14 years old D. 16 years old","excerpt":"Fourteenyearold Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916.","stem":"How old was Louie Share Kim when he arrived at Angel Island?","choices":{"A":"10 years old","B":"12 years old","C":"14 years old","D":"16 years old"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says he was fourteen years old when he arrived in 1916.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Fourteenyearold Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q012","read_aloud":"How did Louie Share Kim\u0027s family feel about him? A. They were angry at him. B. They hoped he would succeed. C. They wanted him to stay in China. D. They did not care about him.","excerpt":"He had little schooling, no job skills, and no place to live, and he did not speak any English. Yet his family pinned all their hopes on him to become a success in America.","stem":"How did Louie Share Kim\u0027s family feel about him?","choices":{"A":"They were angry at him.","B":"They hoped he would succeed.","C":"They wanted him to stay in China.","D":"They did not care about him."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the family pinned all their hopes on him, meaning they hoped he would be successful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: He had little schooling, no job skills, and no place to live, and he did not speak any English. Yet his family pinned all their hopes on him to become a success in America."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q013","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses the word \"immigration\" correctly? A. The immigration of birds happens every spring. B. My grandmother\u0027s immigration from China to America was a long journey. C. The immigration of the book took two hours. D. Immigration means staying in the same town.","excerpt":"\"Immigration is the act of moving to a new country to live there. Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses the word \"immigration\" correctly?","choices":{"A":"The immigration of birds happens every spring.","B":"My grandmother\u0027s immigration from China to America was a long journey.","C":"The immigration of the book took two hours.","D":"Immigration means staying in the same town."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Immigration means moving to a new country to live there. Moving from China to America is an example of immigration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Immigration is the act of moving to a new country to live there. Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What happened first? A. Chinese people claimed to have sons in China. B. The earthquake and fire destroyed the Hall of Records. C. The Chinese Exclusion Act was passed. D. Louie Share Kim arrived at Angel Island.","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What happened first?","choices":{"A":"Chinese people claimed to have sons in China.","B":"The earthquake and fire destroyed the Hall of Records.","C":"The Chinese Exclusion Act was passed.","D":"Louie Share Kim arrived at Angel Island."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The earthquake and fire happened first. After the records were destroyed, Chinese people saw an opportunity to make claims.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q015","read_aloud":"Why did some Chinese claim they were born in San Francisco? A. Because they wanted to visit China. B. Because the earthquake destroyed the birth records, so no one could check. C. Because they liked San Francisco. D. Because the government asked them to.","excerpt":"\"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\"","stem":"Why did some Chinese claim they were born in San Francisco?","choices":{"A":"Because they wanted to visit China.","B":"Because the earthquake destroyed the birth records, so no one could check.","C":"Because they liked San Francisco.","D":"Because the government asked them to."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The earthquake destroyed the Hall of Records with birth records. Without records, officials could not check if claims were true.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What did a paper son buy along with an identity? A. a ticket to China B. a coaching book with questions and answers C. a new house D. a job","excerpt":"\"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.\"","stem":"What did a paper son buy along with an identity?","choices":{"A":"a ticket to China","B":"a coaching book with questions and answers","C":"a new house","D":"a job"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says a paper son purchased a coaching book that had questions and answers for immigration processing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q017","read_aloud":"Which problem did Louie Share Kim NOT have when he arrived? A. He did not speak English. B. He had no place to live. C. He had many job skills. D. He had little schooling.","excerpt":"\"He had traveled alone on a journey that took nearly a month to cross the Pacific Ocean. He had little schooling, no job skills, and no place to live, and he did not speak any English.\"","stem":"Which problem did Louie Share Kim NOT have when he arrived?","choices":{"A":"He did not speak English.","B":"He had no place to live.","C":"He had many job skills.","D":"He had little schooling."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says he had \"no job skills,\" so he did NOT have many job skills. The other choices are problems he did have.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He had traveled alone on a journey that took nearly a month to cross the Pacific Ocean. He had little schooling, no job skills, and no place to live, and he did not speak any English.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q018","read_aloud":"What does the word \"opportunity\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What does the word \"opportunity\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q019","read_aloud":"According to the text, what did the Chinese Exclusion Act do? A. It helped families move to the U.S. B. It forced people to leave California. C. It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing their families. D. It allowed merchants to buy more land.","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\"","stem":"According to the text, what did the Chinese Exclusion Act do?","choices":{"A":"It helped families move to the U.S.","B":"It forced people to leave California.","C":"It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing their families.","D":"It allowed merchants to buy more land."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states that the act prohibited laborers from sending for their families.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q020","read_aloud":"Where was the immigration station for people coming from Asia located? A. In New York B. In California C. In China D. In the Hall of Records","excerpt":"\"In 1910, Angel Island Immigration Station opens in California to process immigrants arriving from Asia.\"","stem":"Where was the immigration station for people coming from Asia located?","choices":{"A":"In New York","B":"In California","C":"In China","D":"In the Hall of Records"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text identifies that the station in California was for those arriving from Asia.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1910, Angel Island Immigration Station opens in California to process immigrants arriving from Asia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q021","read_aloud":"Why did Louie\u0027s father want him to wear a suit and tie for his photo? A. To make him look American B. Because it was a special holiday C. Because he was a famous person D. To keep him warm on the boat","excerpt":"\"His father made sure he even looked American in his passport photograph by making him wear a suit and tie.\"","stem":"Why did Louie\u0027s father want him to wear a suit and tie for his photo?","choices":{"A":"To make him look American","B":"Because it was a special holiday","C":"Because he was a famous person","D":"To keep him warm on the boat"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that the father wanted his son to look American for the passport photo.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"His father made sure he even looked American in his passport photograph by making him wear a suit and tie.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q022","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what does \"immigration\" mean? A. The act of moving to a new country to live B. The act of taking a vacation C. The process of building a new house D. The act of buying a plane ticket","excerpt":"\"Angel Island Immigration Station might have looked like this when Share Kim arrived as a child.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what does \"immigration\" mean?","choices":{"A":"The act of moving to a new country to live","B":"The act of taking a vacation","C":"The process of building a new house","D":"The act of buying a plane ticket"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Immigration refers to the process of leaving one country to settle in another.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Angel Island Immigration Station might have looked like this when Share Kim arrived as a child.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q023","read_aloud":"Why did paper sons need a coaching book? A. To learn how to speak English quickly B. To help them remember answers for the officials C. To study for school in America D. To know how to find a job","excerpt":"\"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing. The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers.\"","stem":"Why did paper sons need a coaching book?","choices":{"A":"To learn how to speak English quickly","B":"To help them remember answers for the officials","C":"To study for school in America","D":"To know how to find a job"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The book contained the information needed to pass the interrogation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing. The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q024","read_aloud":"What did the \"Certificate of Identity\" prove? A. That he was a wealthy merchant B. That he was a good student C. That he was allowed to enter as a son of a native D. That he had traveled across the ocean","excerpt":"\"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\"","stem":"What did the \"Certificate of Identity\" prove?","choices":{"A":"That he was a wealthy merchant","B":"That he was a good student","C":"That he was allowed to enter as a son of a native","D":"That he had traveled across the ocean"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The certificate was the legal document showing he was admitted to the country.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What was a \"transcript\" of the interrogation? A. A list of items to pack B. A written record of what was said C. A map of the village D. A photograph of the family","excerpt":"\"The transcript was 42 single-spaced typed pages.\"","stem":"What was a \"transcript\" of the interrogation?","choices":{"A":"A list of items to pack","B":"A written record of what was said","C":"A map of the village","D":"A photograph of the family"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A transcript is a written copy of words spoken during a meeting or interrogation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The transcript was 42 single-spaced typed pages.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what does \"immigration\" mean? A. The act of moving to a new country to live B. The act of taking a vacation C. The process of building a new house D. The act of buying a plane ticket","excerpt":"\"Angel Island Immigration Station might have looked like this when Share Kim arrived as a child.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what does \"immigration\" mean?","choices":{"A":"The act of moving to a new country to live","B":"The act of taking a vacation","C":"The process of building a new house","D":"The act of buying a plane ticket"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Immigration refers to the process of leaving one country to settle in another.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Angel Island Immigration Station might have looked like this when Share Kim arrived as a child.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q002","read_aloud":"Why did paper sons need a coaching book? A. To learn how to speak English quickly B. To help them remember answers for the officials C. To study for school in America D. To know how to find a job","excerpt":"\"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing. The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers.\"","stem":"Why did paper sons need a coaching book?","choices":{"A":"To learn how to speak English quickly","B":"To help them remember answers for the officials","C":"To study for school in America","D":"To know how to find a job"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The book contained the information needed to pass the interrogation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing. The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What did the \"Certificate of Identity\" prove? A. That he was a wealthy merchant B. That he was a good student C. That he was allowed to enter as a son of a native D. That he had traveled across the ocean","excerpt":"\"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\"","stem":"What did the \"Certificate of Identity\" prove?","choices":{"A":"That he was a wealthy merchant","B":"That he was a good student","C":"That he was allowed to enter as a son of a native","D":"That he had traveled across the ocean"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The certificate was the legal document showing he was admitted to the country.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q004","read_aloud":"What was a \"transcript\" of the interrogation? A. A list of items to pack B. A written record of what was said C. A map of the village D. A photograph of the family","excerpt":"\"The transcript was 42 single-spaced typed pages.\"","stem":"What was a \"transcript\" of the interrogation?","choices":{"A":"A list of items to pack","B":"A written record of what was said","C":"A map of the village","D":"A photograph of the family"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A transcript is a written copy of words spoken during a meeting or interrogation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The transcript was 42 single-spaced typed pages.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q005","read_aloud":"Why did the officials question the family members separately? A. To see if they would give the same answers B. Because they did not speak the same language C. Because they wanted to be fair to the children D. To help the family members find each other","excerpt":"\"Officials questioned each member of the family, even six-year-old Sherman, and they brought Share Kim in a second time for questioning.\"","stem":"Why did the officials question the family members separately?","choices":{"A":"To see if they would give the same answers","B":"Because they did not speak the same language","C":"Because they wanted to be fair to the children","D":"To help the family members find each other"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Officials questioned everyone to make sure their stories matched.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Officials questioned each member of the family, even six-year-old Sherman, and they brought Share Kim in a second time for questioning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q006","read_aloud":"In this sentence, what does \"opportunity\" most likely mean? A. a problem that is hard to solve B. a chance to do something helpful or useful C. a rule that must be followed D. a person who helps others","excerpt":"\"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"In this sentence, what does \"opportunity\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"a problem that is hard to solve","B":"a chance to do something helpful or useful","C":"a rule that must be followed","D":"a person who helps others"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An opportunity is a good chance to do something. Here, the destroyed records gave some Chinese a chance to claim U.S. birth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. All paper sons were real family members B. Paper sons could be real relatives or strangers who bought an identity C. Families never sold identities to strangers D. Only nephews could become paper sons","excerpt":"\"Sometimes the son was truly related, and sometimes the \u0027son\u0027 might be a nephew or another relative. Often, the identity was sold to an unrelated person who lived near the \u0027father\u0027s\u0027 Chinese village.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"All paper sons were real family members","B":"Paper sons could be real relatives or strangers who bought an identity","C":"Families never sold identities to strangers","D":"Only nephews could become paper sons"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt explains that sometimes the son was a real relative, but often the identity was sold to someone unrelated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sometimes the son was truly related, and sometimes the \u0027son\u0027 might be a nephew or another relative. Often, the identity was sold to an unrelated person who lived near the \u0027father\u0027s\u0027 Chinese village.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q008","read_aloud":"Why would a paper son need a coaching book? A. To learn how to speak English quickly B. To memorize answers for questions during immigration questioning C. To find a job in America D. To write letters to family in China","excerpt":"\"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.\"","stem":"Why would a paper son need a coaching book?","choices":{"A":"To learn how to speak English quickly","B":"To memorize answers for questions during immigration questioning","C":"To find a job in America","D":"To write letters to family in China"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The coaching book had questions and answers for immigration processing. This suggests the paper son needed to memorize them to pass the interrogation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q009","read_aloud":"How much were paper son documents worth? A. A few dollars B. Hundreds of dollars C. Thousands of dollars D. They were free","excerpt":"\"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip.\"","stem":"How much were paper son documents worth?","choices":{"A":"A few dollars","B":"Hundreds of dollars","C":"Thousands of dollars","D":"They were free"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states that paper son documents \"were worth thousands of dollars.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q010","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt tell us about the cost of becoming a paper son? A. It was cheap and easy for most families B. Families had to borrow money and work hard to pay it back C. The government paid for the trip D. Only rich families could afford it","excerpt":"\"Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip. It often took several years of hard work to repay the debt.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt tell us about the cost of becoming a paper son?","choices":{"A":"It was cheap and easy for most families","B":"Families had to borrow money and work hard to pay it back","C":"The government paid for the trip","D":"Only rich families could afford it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says families borrowed money and it took years of hard work to repay. This shows it was a big financial sacrifice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip. It often took several years of hard work to repay the debt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What is a \"citizen\"? A. A person who visits a country for one day B. A person who belongs to a particular country C. A person who works on a ship D. A person who has no home","excerpt":"Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China.","stem":"What is a \"citizen\"?","choices":{"A":"A person who visits a country for one day","B":"A person who belongs to a particular country","C":"A person who works on a ship","D":"A person who has no home"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A citizen is someone who legally belongs to a country and has rights there.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q012","read_aloud":"What happened first? A. Share Kim arrived at Angel Island. B. Share Kim\u0027s father made arrangements. C. Share Kim became a citizen. D. Share Jung moved to China.","excerpt":"Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America. Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China. Share Kim\u0027s father made arrangements to have Share Jung claim Share Kim as his son.","stem":"What happened first?","choices":{"A":"Share Kim arrived at Angel Island.","B":"Share Kim\u0027s father made arrangements.","C":"Share Kim became a citizen.","D":"Share Jung moved to China."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the father first made arrangements. Then Share Kim became a paper son.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America. Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China. Share Kim\u0027s father made arrangements to have Share Jung claim Share Kim as his son."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What was one effect of the Chinese Exclusion Act? A. More Chinese laborers came to America. B. Chinese laborers could not enter the United States. C. All Chinese people became citizens. D. The Act helped families stay together.","excerpt":"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States.","stem":"What was one effect of the Chinese Exclusion Act?","choices":{"A":"More Chinese laborers came to America.","B":"Chinese laborers could not enter the United States.","C":"All Chinese people became citizens.","D":"The Act helped families stay together."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The Act stopped Chinese laborers from entering the U.S. That was the direct effect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q014","read_aloud":"What does it mean that officials \"detained\" Share Kim? A. They let him go free. B. They kept him at the station. C. They gave him a gift. D. They sent him to school.","excerpt":"At Angel Island, officials detained Share Kim. They interrogated him and Share Jung. They asked question after question about their family history and their village\u0027s layout.","stem":"What does it mean that officials \"detained\" Share Kim?","choices":{"A":"They let him go free.","B":"They kept him at the station.","C":"They gave him a gift.","D":"They sent him to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Detained\" means kept or held at a place, not allowed to leave.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: At Angel Island, officials detained Share Kim. They interrogated him and Share Jung. They asked question after question about their family history and their village\u0027s layout."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q015","read_aloud":"What did Share Kim receive when he was allowed to enter America? A. A coaching book B. A passport from China C. A Certificate of Identity D. A letter from his father","excerpt":"Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America. He received his Certificate of Identity.","stem":"What did Share Kim receive when he was allowed to enter America?","choices":{"A":"A coaching book","B":"A passport from China","C":"A Certificate of Identity","D":"A letter from his father"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says he received his Certificate of Identity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America. He received his Certificate of Identity."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What does \"opportunity\" mean in this sentence? A. a dangerous situation B. a chance to do something C. a kind of food D. a type of building","excerpt":"\"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\"","stem":"What does \"opportunity\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a dangerous situation","B":"a chance to do something","C":"a kind of food","D":"a type of building"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The Chinese saw a chance to claim they were born in San Francisco because the records were destroyed. \"Opportunity\" means a chance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q017","read_aloud":"Why did Louie Share Kim\u0027s father make him wear a suit and tie? A. Because it was cold on the ship. B. Because he wanted him to look American in his photo. C. Because suits were required on Angel Island. D. Because he was going to a wedding.","excerpt":"\"His father made sure he even looked American in his passport photograph by making him wear a suit and tie.\"","stem":"Why did Louie Share Kim\u0027s father make him wear a suit and tie?","choices":{"A":"Because it was cold on the ship.","B":"Because he wanted him to look American in his photo.","C":"Because suits were required on Angel Island.","D":"Because he was going to a wedding."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says his father wanted him to \"look American\" in his passport photograph, so he made him wear a suit and tie.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"His father made sure he even looked American in his passport photograph by making him wear a suit and tie.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q018","read_aloud":"Who was NOT allowed to enter the United States under the Chinese Exclusion Act? A. teachers B. students C. Chinese laborers D. merchants","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States. Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China.\"","stem":"Who was NOT allowed to enter the United States under the Chinese Exclusion Act?","choices":{"A":"teachers","B":"students","C":"Chinese laborers","D":"merchants"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says the Act \"stopped all Chinese laborers from entering.\" The other groups listed were allowed to enter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States. Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q019","read_aloud":"What does \"on paper only\" mean? A. They wrote on actual paper. B. The relationship was not real; it was only written down. C. They only used one sheet of paper. D. They drew pictures on paper.","excerpt":"\"To get around the law, many immigrants from China claimed to be related to a merchant or a U.S. citizen-on paper only.\"","stem":"What does \"on paper only\" mean?","choices":{"A":"They wrote on actual paper.","B":"The relationship was not real; it was only written down.","C":"They only used one sheet of paper.","D":"They drew pictures on paper."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"On paper only\" means the relationship was not real. It existed only in documents, not in real life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To get around the law, many immigrants from China claimed to be related to a merchant or a U.S. citizen-on paper only.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They believe the system was perfect B. They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese C. They think the government was doing a good job D. They think everyone was treated the same","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They believe the system was perfect","B":"They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese","C":"They think the government was doing a good job","D":"They think everyone was treated the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By quoting this, the author shows that racial bias made the immigration process unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. To make sure they knew the local language B. To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation C. To learn how to get a job in America D. To help their children study for school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"To make sure they knew the local language","B":"To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation","C":"To learn how to get a job in America","D":"To help their children study for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the exact facts that matched the \"father\u0027s\" story was the only way to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l03-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Because it is fun to read about history B. Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives C. Because it shows that the government was always right D. Because it does not matter what happened in the past","excerpt":"\"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Because it is fun to read about history","B":"Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives","C":"Because it shows that the government was always right","D":"Because it does not matter what happened in the past"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Understanding history helps us see the struggles and sacrifices made by others, which is important for learning and respect Section A - Text Information Title: \"The Path to Paper Son\" by Grant Din and \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" by Barbara D. Krasner Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 1, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q001","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"admitted\"? A. Asked B. Denied C. Granted access D. Stopped","excerpt":"\"Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America. He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"admitted\"?","choices":{"A":"Asked","B":"Denied","C":"Granted access","D":"Stopped"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Being admitted means you have been granted permission to enter or be part of a place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America. He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q002","read_aloud":"Why was being a \"paper son\" helpful to Share Kim later in life? A. It made him rich B. It allowed him to travel back and forth to China C. It gave him a job in the government D. It allowed him to buy a house in China","excerpt":"\"When Share Kim was 20 years old, his real father wrote him a letter from China... \u0027It is time to come home.\u0027 Now considered a \u0027son of a native,\u0027 Share Kim could visit his village in China and know that he would be readmitted into the United States.\"","stem":"Why was being a \"paper son\" helpful to Share Kim later in life?","choices":{"A":"It made him rich","B":"It allowed him to travel back and forth to China","C":"It gave him a job in the government","D":"It allowed him to buy a house in China"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because he was legally \"admitted,\" he had the freedom to travel back to his village and return to the U.S.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When Share Kim was 20 years old, his real father wrote him a letter from China... \u0027It is time to come home.\u0027 Now considered a \u0027son of a native,\u0027 Share Kim could visit his village in China and know that he would be readmitted into the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q003","read_aloud":"What was the main reason for Share Kim\u0027s travel back and forth? A. To visit family and work B. To buy books for his children C. To learn how to speak English D. To hide from the government","excerpt":"\"Share Kim returned to America to work. In 1924 and in 1929, he returned to China to visit his village and see his wife... After each visit, Share Kim returned to the United States to work.\"","stem":"What was the main reason for Share Kim\u0027s travel back and forth?","choices":{"A":"To visit family and work","B":"To buy books for his children","C":"To learn how to speak English","D":"To hide from the government"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows he was visiting his family and then returning to the U.S. for work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Kim returned to America to work. In 1924 and in 1929, he returned to China to visit his village and see his wife... After each visit, Share Kim returned to the United States to work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q004","read_aloud":"How did the coaching book help Share Kim\u0027s family? A. It helped the children learn to read B. It helped them prepare for the difficult interrogation C. It listed all the food they would eat D. It gave them directions to San Francisco","excerpt":"\"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning.\"","stem":"How did the coaching book help Share Kim\u0027s family?","choices":{"A":"It helped the children learn to read","B":"It helped them prepare for the difficult interrogation","C":"It listed all the food they would eat","D":"It gave them directions to San Francisco"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By studying the book, they could make sure their answers matched, which was necessary to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q005","read_aloud":"If a person was a Chinese laborer, how could they use the law to their advantage? A. By pretending to be a merchant or citizen B. By working harder than everyone else C. By ignoring the law completely D. By asking the government for special permission","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families... But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\"","stem":"If a person was a Chinese laborer, how could they use the law to their advantage?","choices":{"A":"By pretending to be a merchant or citizen","B":"By working harder than everyone else","C":"By ignoring the law completely","D":"By asking the government for special permission"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Since laborers were blocked but others were not, people lied about their status to gain entry.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families... But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"processing\" most likely mean? A. cooking food for a large group B. the steps officials take to review an immigration application C. traveling across the ocean D. learning a new language","excerpt":"\"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"processing\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"cooking food for a large group","B":"the steps officials take to review an immigration application","C":"traveling across the ocean","D":"learning a new language"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Processing here refers to the official steps immigration officials use to review someone\u0027s application to enter the country.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q007","read_aloud":"What was one effect of the Chinese Exclusion Act? A. More Chinese laborers came to America B. Chinese laborers could not enter, but some other groups could C. All Chinese people were banned from America forever D. The Act helped Chinese families reunite quickly","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States. Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China.\"","stem":"What was one effect of the Chinese Exclusion Act?","choices":{"A":"More Chinese laborers came to America","B":"Chinese laborers could not enter, but some other groups could","C":"All Chinese people were banned from America forever","D":"The Act helped Chinese families reunite quickly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The Act stopped laborers but allowed diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and citizens to enter. So not all Chinese people were banned.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States. Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q008","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"The Path to Paper Son\": \"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Excerpt from \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\": \"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916. How do these two excerpts connect? A. They both talk about how expensive immigration was B. The first explains the system Louie may have used to enter America C. They both describe life in China D. They show that Louie did not need any documents","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"The Path to Paper Son\": \"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Excerpt from \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\": \"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916. How do these two excerpts connect?","choices":{"A":"They both talk about how expensive immigration was","B":"The first explains the system Louie may have used to enter America","C":"They both describe life in China","D":"They show that Louie did not need any documents"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The first excerpt explains the paper son system and its cost. The second introduces Louie, who used that system as a paper son.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q009","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, why might Louie\u0027s family have such high hopes for him? A. Because he was already very rich B. Because they believed America offered opportunities even for someone with little experience C. Because he had many job skills already D. Because he spoke perfect English","excerpt":"\"He had little schooling, no job skills, and no place to live, and he did not speak any English. Yet his family pinned all their hopes on him to become a success in America.\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, why might Louie\u0027s family have such high hopes for him?","choices":{"A":"Because he was already very rich","B":"Because they believed America offered opportunities even for someone with little experience","C":"Because he had many job skills already","D":"Because he spoke perfect English"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Even though Louie had little schooling or skills, his family hoped America would give him chances to succeed. This shows their belief in opportunity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He had little schooling, no job skills, and no place to live, and he did not speak any English. Yet his family pinned all their hopes on him to become a success in America.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q010","read_aloud":"Why might Louie\u0027s father have wanted him to look American in his photo? A. To help Louie feel more comfortable traveling B. To make officials more likely to approve his entry into the U.S. C. Because suits and ties were required by law D. To save money on clothing","excerpt":"\"His father made sure he even looked American in his passport photograph by making him wear a suit and tie.\"","stem":"Why might Louie\u0027s father have wanted him to look American in his photo?","choices":{"A":"To help Louie feel more comfortable traveling","B":"To make officials more likely to approve his entry into the U.S.","C":"Because suits and ties were required by law","D":"To save money on clothing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Looking American in the photo might help Louie seem more acceptable to immigration officials. This shows how families tried to improve their chances.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"His father made sure he even looked American in his passport photograph by making him wear a suit and tie.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"eldest\" mean? A. youngest B. smartest C. oldest D. tallest","excerpt":"When Share Kim was 20 years old, his real father wrote him a letter from China. \u0027Dear Number One Son,\u0027 the letter began, referring to Share Kim as the eldest son.","stem":"What does \"eldest\" mean?","choices":{"A":"youngest","B":"smartest","C":"oldest","D":"tallest"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"\"Eldest\" means the oldest, especially among children in a family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: When Share Kim was 20 years old, his real father wrote him a letter from China. \u0027Dear Number One Son,\u0027 the letter began, referring to Share Kim as the eldest son."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q012","read_aloud":"How was Share Kim different from a regular laborer under the Chinese Exclusion Act? A. He could not visit China. B. He could leave and come back to the U.S. C. He had to stay in China forever. D. He was not allowed to work.","excerpt":"Now considered a \u0027son of a native,\u0027 Share Kim could visit his village in China and know that he would be readmitted into the United States.","stem":"How was Share Kim different from a regular laborer under the Chinese Exclusion Act?","choices":{"A":"He could not visit China.","B":"He could leave and come back to the U.S.","C":"He had to stay in China forever.","D":"He was not allowed to work."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"As a \"son of a native,\" he could visit China and be readmitted, which laborers could not do.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Now considered a \u0027son of a native,\u0027 Share Kim could visit his village in China and know that he would be readmitted into the United States."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q013","read_aloud":"When did Share Kim get married after arriving in China? A. On Tuesday B. On Wednesday C. On Friday D. On Saturday","excerpt":"He arrived in China on a Tuesday. He was married on Saturday to a woman chosen by his parents and whom he had never seen before.","stem":"When did Share Kim get married after arriving in China?","choices":{"A":"On Tuesday","B":"On Wednesday","C":"On Friday","D":"On Saturday"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"He arrived Tuesday and married Saturday, just a few days later.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: He arrived in China on a Tuesday. He was married on Saturday to a woman chosen by his parents and whom he had never seen before."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q014","read_aloud":"Why did Share Kim make a coaching book for his wife? A. To teach her English B. To make sure their answers matched C. To show her how to cook D. To tell her about California gold","excerpt":"Share Kim knew there would be another interrogation. He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning.","stem":"Why did Share Kim make a coaching book for his wife?","choices":{"A":"To teach her English","B":"To make sure their answers matched","C":"To show her how to cook","D":"To tell her about California gold"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He wanted them to give the same answers so they would not be caught lying.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Share Kim knew there would be another interrogation. He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q015","read_aloud":"Why did officials question even a sixyearold child? A. The child had broken a law. B. They wanted to see if the family\u0027s stories matched. C. The child spoke perfect English. D. They needed help with paperwork.","excerpt":"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation. As expected, Share Kim\u0027s wife and children were detained at Angel Island. Officials questioned each member of the family, even sixyearold Sherman.","stem":"Why did officials question even a sixyearold child?","choices":{"A":"The child had broken a law.","B":"They wanted to see if the family\u0027s stories matched.","C":"The child spoke perfect English.","D":"They needed help with paperwork."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Officials questioned everyone, even young children, to check if all answers were the same.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Any wrong answers could lead to deportation. As expected, Share Kim\u0027s wife and children were detained at Angel Island. Officials questioned each member of the family, even sixyearold Sherman."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q016","read_aloud":"How were paper sons different from each other? A. Some were truly related, and some were not related at all. B. All paper sons were brothers. C. All paper sons came from the same village. D. Paper sons were all the same age.","excerpt":"\"Sometimes the son was truly related, and sometimes the \u0027son\u0027 might be a nephew or another relative. Often, the identity was sold to an unrelated person who lived near the \u0027father\u0027s\u0027 Chinese village.\"","stem":"How were paper sons different from each other?","choices":{"A":"Some were truly related, and some were not related at all.","B":"All paper sons were brothers.","C":"All paper sons came from the same village.","D":"Paper sons were all the same age."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that some paper sons were truly related, some were nephews, and some were unrelated people who bought the identity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sometimes the son was truly related, and sometimes the \u0027son\u0027 might be a nephew or another relative. Often, the identity was sold to an unrelated person who lived near the \u0027father\u0027s\u0027 Chinese village.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q017","read_aloud":"Why was Louie Share Jung able to claim Share Kim as his son? A. Because Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco. B. Because Share Jung was very rich. C. Because Share Jung worked for the government. D. Because Share Jung was Share Kim\u0027s real father.","excerpt":"\"Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America. Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China.\"","stem":"Why was Louie Share Jung able to claim Share Kim as his son?","choices":{"A":"Because Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco.","B":"Because Share Jung was very rich.","C":"Because Share Jung worked for the government.","D":"Because Share Jung was Share Kim\u0027s real father."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco. U.S. citizens could bring family members, so he could claim Share Kim as his son.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America. Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q018","read_aloud":"Why did officials ask so many questions? A. Because they were bored. B. Because they wanted to check if Share Kim was really Share Jung\u0027s son. C. Because they wanted to learn about China. D. Because they needed help with their homework.","excerpt":"\"At Angel Island, officials detained Share Kim. They interrogated him and Share Jung. They asked question after question about their family history and their village\u0027s layout.\"","stem":"Why did officials ask so many questions?","choices":{"A":"Because they were bored.","B":"Because they wanted to check if Share Kim was really Share Jung\u0027s son.","C":"Because they wanted to learn about China.","D":"Because they needed help with their homework."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Officials interrogated them to test if their stories matched. If they were really father and son, they would know the same details about family and village.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At Angel Island, officials detained Share Kim. They interrogated him and Share Jung. They asked question after question about their family history and their village\u0027s layout.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q019","read_aloud":"What can you conclude about the interrogation? A. It was easy and short. B. Share Kim and Share Jung gave matching answers that satisfied the officials. C. The officials did not care about the answers. D. Share Kim was sent back to China.","excerpt":"\"Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America. He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\"","stem":"What can you conclude about the interrogation?","choices":{"A":"It was easy and short.","B":"Share Kim and Share Jung gave matching answers that satisfied the officials.","C":"The officials did not care about the answers.","D":"Share Kim was sent back to China."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says officials were \"satisfied with the answers\" and allowed him entry. This means their answers matched and were believable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America. He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They believe the system was perfect B. They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese C. They think the government was doing a good job D. They think everyone was treated the same","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They believe the system was perfect","B":"They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese","C":"They think the government was doing a good job","D":"They think everyone was treated the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By quoting this, the author shows that racial bias made the immigration process unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. To make sure they knew the local language B. To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation C. To learn how to get a job in America D. To help their children study for school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"To make sure they knew the local language","B":"To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation","C":"To learn how to get a job in America","D":"To help their children study for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the exact facts that matched the \"father\u0027s\" story was the only way to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l04-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Because it is fun to read about history B. Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives C. Because it shows that the government was always right D. Because it does not matter what happened in the past","excerpt":"\"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Because it is fun to read about history","B":"Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives","C":"Because it shows that the government was always right","D":"Because it does not matter what happened in the past"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Understanding history helps us see the struggles and sacrifices made by others, which is important for learning and respect Section A - Text Information Title: \"The Path to Paper Son\" by Grant Din and \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" by Barbara D. Krasner Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 1, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is \"processing\"? A. A series of steps in a legal action B. The act of making bread C. A way to travel by boat D. A type of school assignment","excerpt":"\"They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China... The claim created immigration slots, which could be used to bring another Chinese to America.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what is \"processing\"?","choices":{"A":"A series of steps in a legal action","B":"The act of making bread","C":"A way to travel by boat","D":"A type of school assignment"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Processing refers to the steps or actions taken by officials to handle an application or legal case.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China... The claim created immigration slots, which could be used to bring another Chinese to America.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q002","read_aloud":"What does this sentence suggest about the fairness of the immigration system at that time? A. It was very fair to everyone B. It was not fair because of the race of the witnesses C. It was fair because everyone had to have two witnesses D. It was fair because the government wanted to help Chinese people","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"What does this sentence suggest about the fairness of the immigration system at that time?","choices":{"A":"It was very fair to everyone","B":"It was not fair because of the race of the witnesses","C":"It was fair because everyone had to have two witnesses","D":"It was fair because the government wanted to help Chinese people"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text indicates that only white witnesses were trusted, showing the system was biased.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q003","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Paper sons were very rare B. The paper son system was very common C. Most paper sons were from San Francisco D. Scholars do not know how many paper sons there were","excerpt":"\"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Paper sons were very rare","B":"The paper son system was very common","C":"Most paper sons were from San Francisco","D":"Scholars do not know how many paper sons there were"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The high percentage (80 percent) shows that this was a widespread practice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q004","read_aloud":"Why was the \"twin\" brother deported? A. He did not speak English B. He looked different than Share Kim, so officials did not believe they were twins C. He had not paid for his papers D. He lied about his name","excerpt":"\"Share Kim was much taller. The \u0027twin\u0027 was deported back to China, where he died two years later.\"","stem":"Why was the \"twin\" brother deported?","choices":{"A":"He did not speak English","B":"He looked different than Share Kim, so officials did not believe they were twins","C":"He had not paid for his papers","D":"He lied about his name"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The physical difference between the two boys proved they were not related, leading to deportation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Kim was much taller. The \u0027twin\u0027 was deported back to China, where he died two years later.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q005","read_aloud":"Why did Sam Louie keep his father\u0027s history a secret? A. He was ashamed of his father B. He was afraid the family would be sent away C. His father told him it was a game D. He wanted to be a surprise to his friends","excerpt":"\"I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\"","stem":"Why did Sam Louie keep his father\u0027s history a secret?","choices":{"A":"He was ashamed of his father","B":"He was afraid the family would be sent away","C":"His father told him it was a game","D":"He wanted to be a surprise to his friends"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Keeping the secret was necessary to protect the family from being deported by the government.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"admitted\" mean in this excerpt? A. told a secret B. granted access to a place C. asked to leave D. punished for a mistake","excerpt":"\"Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America. He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\"","stem":"What does \"admitted\" mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"told a secret","B":"granted access to a place","C":"asked to leave","D":"punished for a mistake"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Share Kim was \"allowed entry\" and \"admitted as the son of a native.\" Admitted here means he was granted access to enter America.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America. He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What happened right after officials interrogated Share Kim and Share Jung? A. Share Kim was sent back to China B. Share Kim was allowed entry to America C. Share Kim bought a coaching book D. Share Kim got married","excerpt":"\"Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America... At Angel Island, officials detained Share Kim. They interrogated him and Share Jung... Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America.\"","stem":"What happened right after officials interrogated Share Kim and Share Jung?","choices":{"A":"Share Kim was sent back to China","B":"Share Kim was allowed entry to America","C":"Share Kim bought a coaching book","D":"Share Kim got married"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sequence shows: detention → interrogation → officials satisfied → Share Kim allowed entry. So entry happened after interrogation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America... At Angel Island, officials detained Share Kim. They interrogated him and Share Jung... Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q008","read_aloud":"How might this Certificate of Identity help Share Kim in the future? A. It would let him travel back to China and return to the U.S. more easily B. It would make him rich immediately C. It would allow him to avoid all immigration rules D. It would let him bring unlimited family members to America","excerpt":"\"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\"","stem":"How might this Certificate of Identity help Share Kim in the future?","choices":{"A":"It would let him travel back to China and return to the U.S. more easily","B":"It would make him rich immediately","C":"It would allow him to avoid all immigration rules","D":"It would let him bring unlimited family members to America"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Later in the text, Share Kim does travel back to China and returns because he has this status. The certificate proved his claimed identity for future travel.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q009","read_aloud":"Why might it have been easier for Share Jung to claim Share Kim as his son? A. They lived far apart and did not know each other B. They lived close together and knew each other well, so their stories would match C. Share Jung was a government official D. Share Kim had already lived in America","excerpt":"\"Share Kim\u0027s father made arrangements to have Share Jung claim Share Kim as his son. In the village where their two families lived only two houses away from each other, everyone was related.\"","stem":"Why might it have been easier for Share Jung to claim Share Kim as his son?","choices":{"A":"They lived far apart and did not know each other","B":"They lived close together and knew each other well, so their stories would match","C":"Share Jung was a government official","D":"Share Kim had already lived in America"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because the families lived close and knew each other, Share Jung could answer questions about Share Kim\u0027s life accurately. This made the paper son claim more believable.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Kim\u0027s father made arrangements to have Share Jung claim Share Kim as his son. In the village where their two families lived only two houses away from each other, everyone was related.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q010","read_aloud":"What is an \"interrogation\"? A. A party B. A meal C. A questioning by officials D. A train ride","excerpt":"Sam Louie, the youngest son of Share Kim who was born later in San Francisco, says, \u0027The interrogation was a nervous process for everyone.\u0027","stem":"What is an \"interrogation\"?","choices":{"A":"A party","B":"A meal","C":"A questioning by officials","D":"A train ride"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"An interrogation is when officials ask many questions to get information.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sam Louie, the youngest son of Share Kim who was born later in San Francisco, says, \u0027The interrogation was a nervous process for everyone.\u0027"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the \"twin\" paper brother? A. He was actually Share Kim\u0027s real twin. B. Officials believed he was lying because they looked different. C. He chose to go back to China. D. He became a citizen.","excerpt":"Share Kim had a \u0027twin\u0027 paper brother. But when the two boys were placed next to each other, it seemed clear they were not twins at all. Share Kim was much taller. The \u0027twin\u0027 was deported back to China, where he died two years later.","stem":"What can you infer about the \"twin\" paper brother?","choices":{"A":"He was actually Share Kim\u0027s real twin.","B":"Officials believed he was lying because they looked different.","C":"He chose to go back to China.","D":"He became a citizen."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Officials could see they were not twins (one was much taller), so they likely sent him back.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Share Kim had a \u0027twin\u0027 paper brother. But when the two boys were placed next to each other, it seemed clear they were not twins at all. Share Kim was much taller. The \u0027twin\u0027 was deported back to China, where he died two years later."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q012","read_aloud":"Why did Louie keep his father\u0027s story a secret as a child? A. He was ashamed. B. He forgot the story. C. He was afraid his family could be sent back to China. D. He wanted to become a citizen first.","excerpt":"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history. Louie adds, \u0027I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\u0027","stem":"Why did Louie keep his father\u0027s story a secret as a child?","choices":{"A":"He was ashamed.","B":"He forgot the story.","C":"He was afraid his family could be sent back to China.","D":"He wanted to become a citizen first."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Louie says he was afraid they might all get deported if the secret was told.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history. Louie adds, \u0027I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\u0027"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q013","read_aloud":"If you wanted to learn about your own family\u0027s immigration history, what could you do based on Louie\u0027s example? A. Move to China B. Become a paper son C. Research at government archives D. Ask only your neighbors","excerpt":"Louie conducted research at the National Archives and Records Administration in San Bruno, California. He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment.","stem":"If you wanted to learn about your own family\u0027s immigration history, what could you do based on Louie\u0027s example?","choices":{"A":"Move to China","B":"Become a paper son","C":"Research at government archives","D":"Ask only your neighbors"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Louie found records at the National Archives. That is a good place to research family history.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Louie conducted research at the National Archives and Records Administration in San Bruno, California. He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q014","read_aloud":"Why could Share Kim visit China and return to America? A. Because he had a lot of money. B. Because he was now considered a \"son of a native.\" C. Because the Chinese Exclusion Act ended. D. Because he had a new job.","excerpt":"\"Now considered a \u0027son of a native,\u0027 Share Kim could visit his village in China and know that he would be readmitted into the United States.\"","stem":"Why could Share Kim visit China and return to America?","choices":{"A":"Because he had a lot of money.","B":"Because he was now considered a \"son of a native.\"","C":"Because the Chinese Exclusion Act ended.","D":"Because he had a new job."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says because he was a \"son of a native,\" he could visit China and be readmitted. This status protected him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Now considered a \u0027son of a native,\u0027 Share Kim could visit his village in China and know that he would be readmitted into the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q015","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Share Kim\u0027s marriage? A. He planned the wedding himself. B. His parents made the decision for him. C. He had known his wife for many years. D. He did not want to get married.","excerpt":"\"He arrived in China on a Tuesday. He was married on Saturday to a woman chosen by his parents and whom he had never seen before.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Share Kim\u0027s marriage?","choices":{"A":"He planned the wedding himself.","B":"His parents made the decision for him.","C":"He had known his wife for many years.","D":"He did not want to get married."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the woman was \"chosen by his parents\" and he \"had never seen before.\" This tells us his parents made the decision.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He arrived in China on a Tuesday. He was married on Saturday to a woman chosen by his parents and whom he had never seen before.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q016","read_aloud":"Why did Share Kim make a coaching book for his wife? A. So she could learn English. B. So their stories would match during questioning. C. So she could cook American food. D. So she could find a job.","excerpt":"\"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning.\"","stem":"Why did Share Kim make a coaching book for his wife?","choices":{"A":"So she could learn English.","B":"So their stories would match during questioning.","C":"So she could cook American food.","D":"So she could find a job."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the book helped them \"coordinate their stories\" and give \"the same answers.\" Matching answers were needed to pass the interrogation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q017","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt tell you about the immigration process? A. It was quick and easy. B. It was strict and dangerous for families. C. It was fun for children. D. It did not matter what answers people gave.","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation. As expected, Share Kim\u0027s wife and children were detained at Angel Island.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt tell you about the immigration process?","choices":{"A":"It was quick and easy.","B":"It was strict and dangerous for families.","C":"It was fun for children.","D":"It did not matter what answers people gave."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Wrong answers could lead to deportation, and even children were detained and questioned. This shows the process was strict and scary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation. As expected, Share Kim\u0027s wife and children were detained at Angel Island.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q018","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q019","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q020","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q021","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They believe the system was perfect B. They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese C. They think the government was doing a good job D. They think everyone was treated the same","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They believe the system was perfect","B":"They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese","C":"They think the government was doing a good job","D":"They think everyone was treated the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By quoting this, the author shows that racial bias made the immigration process unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. To make sure they knew the local language B. To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation C. To learn how to get a job in America D. To help their children study for school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"To make sure they knew the local language","B":"To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation","C":"To learn how to get a job in America","D":"To help their children study for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the exact facts that matched the \"father\u0027s\" story was the only way to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Because it is fun to read about history B. Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives C. Because it shows that the government was always right D. Because it does not matter what happened in the past","excerpt":"\"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Because it is fun to read about history","B":"Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives","C":"Because it shows that the government was always right","D":"Because it does not matter what happened in the past"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Understanding history helps us see the struggles and sacrifices made by others, which is important for learning and respect Section A - Text Information Title: \"The Path to Paper Son\" by Grant Din and \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" by Barbara D. Krasner Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 1, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. people who visit a country for a short time B. people who belong to a place and have rights there C. people who work in government jobs D. people who travel between countries for business","excerpt":"\"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China. The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"people who visit a country for a short time","B":"people who belong to a place and have rights there","C":"people who work in government jobs","D":"people who travel between countries for business"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Citizens are people who belong to a country and have rights there. The text says U.S. citizens could send for families, but laborers could not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China. The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l05-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Chinese workers liked to travel alone B. Many Chinese workers left families in China when they came to America C. All Chinese workers were single men D. Families in China did not want to come to America","excerpt":"\"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Chinese workers liked to travel alone","B":"Many Chinese workers left families in China when they came to America","C":"All Chinese workers were single men","D":"Families in China did not want to come to America"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt tells us many Chinese workers were married and had children who stayed in China. This is the main point.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China.\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q001","read_aloud":"In this context, what is an \"affidavit\"? A. A type of boat B. A written statement confirmed by oath C. A lesson learned in school D. A question asked by an official","excerpt":"\"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life... They were, in fact, only sons on paper, an affidavit the \u0027father\u0027 signed-thus the term paper son.\"","stem":"In this context, what is an \"affidavit\"?","choices":{"A":"A type of boat","B":"A written statement confirmed by oath","C":"A lesson learned in school","D":"A question asked by an official"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An affidavit is a legal document that serves as proof of a claim.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life... They were, in fact, only sons on paper, an affidavit the \u0027father\u0027 signed-thus the term paper son.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q002","read_aloud":"What does this show about the culture described in the text? A. Marriages were always planned by the couple B. Marriages were often arranged by parents C. It was very unusual for people to get married D. He was forced to marry his best friend","excerpt":"\"He was married on Saturday to a woman chosen by his parents and whom he had never seen before.\"","stem":"What does this show about the culture described in the text?","choices":{"A":"Marriages were always planned by the couple","B":"Marriages were often arranged by parents","C":"It was very unusual for people to get married","D":"He was forced to marry his best friend"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The fact that his parents chose his wife shows that arranged marriages were a practice at that time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He was married on Saturday to a woman chosen by his parents and whom he had never seen before.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q003","read_aloud":"Why does Sam Louie believe his parents did not talk about their experience? A. Because they did not remember it B. Because they did not care C. Because it was a sad and difficult time D. Because they were not allowed to talk","excerpt":"\"I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"Why does Sam Louie believe his parents did not talk about their experience?","choices":{"A":"Because they did not remember it","B":"Because they did not care","C":"Because it was a sad and difficult time","D":"Because they were not allowed to talk"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The emotional weight of being detained likely made it too difficult for them to discuss.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q004","read_aloud":"How long was the Chinese Exclusion Act in effect? A. Less than 10 years B. Over 60 years C. 100 years D. 5 years","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States.\"","stem":"How long was the Chinese Exclusion Act in effect?","choices":{"A":"Less than 10 years","B":"Over 60 years","C":"100 years","D":"5 years"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"From 1882 to 1943 is 61 years, which is over 60 years.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q005","read_aloud":"How did a natural disaster help some immigrants? A. It made it easier for officials to check records B. The destruction of records allowed people to claim they were born in the U.S. C. It destroyed the immigration station D. It forced the government to open the borders","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco... With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"How did a natural disaster help some immigrants?","choices":{"A":"It made it easier for officials to check records","B":"The destruction of records allowed people to claim they were born in the U.S.","C":"It destroyed the immigration station","D":"It forced the government to open the borders"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because records were gone, it was impossible for officials to prove someone was not born in the city.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco... With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what does it mean to be a \"citizen\" of a community like Angel Island Foundation? A. To own property there B. To be a member who helps and participates in the group\u0027s work C. To visit only once D. To be paid to work there","excerpt":"\"Louie is a retired educator and volunteer at Angel Island Immigration Station. In July 2015, the Angel Island Immigration Station Foundation hosted a family history/reunion day event.\"","stem":"In this context, what does it mean to be a \"citizen\" of a community like Angel Island Foundation?","choices":{"A":"To own property there","B":"To be a member who helps and participates in the group\u0027s work","C":"To visit only once","D":"To be paid to work there"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While \"citizens\" usually means belonging to a country, here being part of the Foundation means being a member who helps with its mission, like Louie volunteering.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie is a retired educator and volunteer at Angel Island Immigration Station. In July 2015, the Angel Island Immigration Station Foundation hosted a family history/reunion day event.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q007","read_aloud":"What can you infer about how Share Kim felt when his family was detained? A. He was not worried at all B. He was probably nervous because wrong answers could mean deportation C. He was happy to see them D. He did not care about the process","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation. As expected, Share Kim\u0027s wife and children were detained at Angel Island.\"","stem":"What can you infer about how Share Kim felt when his family was detained?","choices":{"A":"He was not worried at all","B":"He was probably nervous because wrong answers could mean deportation","C":"He was happy to see them","D":"He did not care about the process"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says wrong answers could lead to deportation. Since his family was detained and questioned, it\u0027s logical to infer Share Kim was nervous about their answers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation. As expected, Share Kim\u0027s wife and children were detained at Angel Island.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q008","read_aloud":"Why did Share Kim create a coaching book for his wife? A. To help her learn English B. So their answers would match during immigration questioning and avoid deportation C. To plan their vacation in China D. To teach her about American history","excerpt":"\"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning.\"","stem":"Why did Share Kim create a coaching book for his wife?","choices":{"A":"To help her learn English","B":"So their answers would match during immigration questioning and avoid deportation","C":"To plan their vacation in China","D":"To teach her about American history"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says the book helped them \"coordinate their stories\" and \"give the same answers.\" This was to pass the interrogation and avoid deportation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q009","read_aloud":"If you were an immigration official, why might you question even a young child like Sherman? A. To make the process take longer B. To check if the family\u0027s story was consistent, since children might tell the truth without coaching C. Because children know more about immigration law D. To give the child a chance to visit America","excerpt":"\"Officials questioned each member of the family, even six-year-old Sherman, and they brought Share Kim in a second time for questioning.\"","stem":"If you were an immigration official, why might you question even a young child like Sherman?","choices":{"A":"To make the process take longer","B":"To check if the family\u0027s story was consistent, since children might tell the truth without coaching","C":"Because children know more about immigration law","D":"To give the child a chance to visit America"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Officials questioned everyone, even children, to see if all stories matched. A young child might not have memorized a coached story, so their answers could reveal inconsistencies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Officials questioned each member of the family, even six-year-old Sherman, and they brought Share Kim in a second time for questioning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q010","read_aloud":"How does Sam Louie\u0027s quote help you understand the immigration experience? A. It shows that everyone felt calm and relaxed B. It shows that the questioning was stressful for families, even those with paper son status C. It proves that officials were always kind D. It suggests that children enjoyed the process","excerpt":"\"Sam Louie, the youngest son of Share Kim who was born later in San Francisco, says, \u0027The interrogation was a nervous process for everyone.\u0027\"","stem":"How does Sam Louie\u0027s quote help you understand the immigration experience?","choices":{"A":"It shows that everyone felt calm and relaxed","B":"It shows that the questioning was stressful for families, even those with paper son status","C":"It proves that officials were always kind","D":"It suggests that children enjoyed the process"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Sam Louie, whose family went through the process, says it was \"nervous for everyone.\" This personal perspective helps readers understand the emotional stress of immigration questioning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sam Louie, the youngest son of Share Kim who was born later in San Francisco, says, \u0027The interrogation was a nervous process for everyone.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q011","read_aloud":"What is a \"transcript\"? A. A picture B. A written record of words spoken C. A song D. A ticket","excerpt":"The transcript was 42 singlespaced typed pages.","stem":"What is a \"transcript\"?","choices":{"A":"A picture","B":"A written record of words spoken","C":"A song","D":"A ticket"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A transcript is a written copy of what people said, like during questioning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The transcript was 42 singlespaced typed pages."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q012","read_aloud":"Why did many immigrants not talk about their experiences? A. They forgot everything. B. The experiences were painful. C. They were not asked. D. They moved too many times.","excerpt":"Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027","stem":"Why did many immigrants not talk about their experiences?","choices":{"A":"They forgot everything.","B":"The experiences were painful.","C":"They were not asked.","D":"They moved too many times."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Louie suspects the experiences were painful, so people wanted to forget.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q013","read_aloud":"What did Sam Louie do at the event? A. He cooked Chinese food. B. He acted as his father and told the story. C. He worked as an official. D. He sang a song.","excerpt":"In July 2015, the Angel Island Immigration Station Foundation hosted a family history/reunion day event. Portraying his father, Louie shared his story.","stem":"What did Sam Louie do at the event?","choices":{"A":"He cooked Chinese food.","B":"He acted as his father and told the story.","C":"He worked as an official.","D":"He sang a song."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says he portrayed his father and shared his story.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In July 2015, the Angel Island Immigration Station Foundation hosted a family history/reunion day event. Portraying his father, Louie shared his story."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q014","read_aloud":"Why would the coaching book include the village\u0027s environment? A. To help with a school project B. So the family could describe it the same way during questioning C. To plan a vacation D. To draw a map for tourists","excerpt":"The coaching book contained information about names and birth dates of all family members, the location of the home village and its environment, dates of Share Kim\u0027s travels to China, and more.","stem":"Why would the coaching book include the village\u0027s environment?","choices":{"A":"To help with a school project","B":"So the family could describe it the same way during questioning","C":"To plan a vacation","D":"To draw a map for tourists"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If officials asked about the village, everyone needed to give the same description.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The coaching book contained information about names and birth dates of all family members, the location of the home village and its environment, dates of Share Kim\u0027s travels to China, and more."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q015","read_aloud":"Imagine you are John. You must memorize many facts for interrogation. What would be the most important thing to memorize? A. The price of paper son documents B. The names and birth dates of family members C. The best food in China D. The weather in San Francisco","excerpt":"They gave the boy the name John. John became their paper son.","stem":"Imagine you are John. You must memorize many facts for interrogation. What would be the most important thing to memorize?","choices":{"A":"The price of paper son documents","B":"The names and birth dates of family members","C":"The best food in China","D":"The weather in San Francisco"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the coaching book included names and birth dates. Officials would ask about these.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: They gave the boy the name John. John became their paper son."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q016","read_aloud":"Why was it important that Share Jung was a U.S. citizen? A. Citizens could travel for free. B. Citizens had the right to bring family members to America. C. Citizens did not need to work. D. Citizens were always born in China.","excerpt":"\"Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China. Share Kim\u0027s father made arrangements to have Share Jung claim Share Kim as his son.\"","stem":"Why was it important that Share Jung was a U.S. citizen?","choices":{"A":"Citizens could travel for free.","B":"Citizens had the right to bring family members to America.","C":"Citizens did not need to work.","D":"Citizens were always born in China."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that U.S. citizens could report sons and bring them to America. Share Jung\u0027s citizenship allowed him to claim Share Kim.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China. Share Kim\u0027s father made arrangements to have Share Jung claim Share Kim as his son.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q017","read_aloud":"How were Share Kim\u0027s trips to China similar to his first journey from China? A. Both were one-way trips. B. Both involved traveling across the ocean between China and America. C. Both were made with his whole family. D. Both happened in 1916.","excerpt":"\"In 1924 and in 1929, he returned to China to visit his village and see his wife. They had two children, Wanda and Sherman. After each visit, Share Kim returned to the United States to work.\"","stem":"How were Share Kim\u0027s trips to China similar to his first journey from China?","choices":{"A":"Both were one-way trips.","B":"Both involved traveling across the ocean between China and America.","C":"Both were made with his whole family.","D":"Both happened in 1916."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Share Kim traveled across the Pacific Ocean to go to America the first time. He also traveled across the ocean to visit China and return to America later.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1924 and in 1929, he returned to China to visit his village and see his wife. They had two children, Wanda and Sherman. After each visit, Share Kim returned to the United States to work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q018","read_aloud":"What evidence shows that interrogations were stressful? A. Sam Louie called it a \"nervous process.\" B. The interrogations were very short. C. Everyone enjoyed the interrogations. D. The officials were friendly.","excerpt":"\"Sam Louie, the youngest son of Share Kim who was born later in San Francisco, says, \u0027The interrogation was a nervous process for everyone.\u0027\"","stem":"What evidence shows that interrogations were stressful?","choices":{"A":"Sam Louie called it a \"nervous process.\"","B":"The interrogations were very short.","C":"Everyone enjoyed the interrogations.","D":"The officials were friendly."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Sam Louie directly states that the interrogation was a \"nervous process for everyone.\" This is text evidence showing it was stressful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sam Louie, the youngest son of Share Kim who was born later in San Francisco, says, \u0027The interrogation was a nervous process for everyone.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q019","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about how Chinese immigrants were treated? A. They were treated fairly by officials. B. They were not trusted, even when telling the truth. C. They did not need any witnesses. D. They were given special privileges.","excerpt":"\"Louie showed his father\u0027s Certificate of Identity. He explains that for Share Kim to claim his birth record, he had to find two witnesses who would testify that they knew him as a child. Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"What does this tell you about how Chinese immigrants were treated?","choices":{"A":"They were treated fairly by officials.","B":"They were not trusted, even when telling the truth.","C":"They did not need any witnesses.","D":"They were given special privileges."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Chinese people were \"not trusted,\" so white witnesses were needed. This shows unfair treatment of Chinese immigrants.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie showed his father\u0027s Certificate of Identity. He explains that for Share Kim to claim his birth record, he had to find two witnesses who would testify that they knew him as a child. Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q020","read_aloud":"Why was the \"twin\" deported? A. Because he was sick. B. Because officials could see he and Share Kim did not look alike. C. Because he wanted to go home. D. Because he had the wrong papers.","excerpt":"\"Share Kim had a \u0027twin\u0027 paper brother. But when the two boys were placed next to each other, it seemed clear they were not twins at all. Share Kim was much taller. The \u0027twin\u0027 was deported back to China, where he died two years later.\"","stem":"Why was the \"twin\" deported?","choices":{"A":"Because he was sick.","B":"Because officials could see he and Share Kim did not look alike.","C":"Because he wanted to go home.","D":"Because he had the wrong papers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says when placed next to each other, they \"were not twins at all.\" Share Kim was \"much taller.\" Officials saw they did not match and deported the other boy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Kim had a \u0027twin\u0027 paper brother. But when the two boys were placed next to each other, it seemed clear they were not twins at all. Share Kim was much taller. The \u0027twin\u0027 was deported back to China, where he died two years later.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They believe the system was perfect B. They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese C. They think the government was doing a good job D. They think everyone was treated the same","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They believe the system was perfect","B":"They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese","C":"They think the government was doing a good job","D":"They think everyone was treated the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By quoting this, the author shows that racial bias made the immigration process unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l06-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. To make sure they knew the local language B. To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation C. To learn how to get a job in America D. To help their children study for school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"To make sure they knew the local language","B":"To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation","C":"To learn how to get a job in America","D":"To help their children study for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the exact facts that matched the \"father\u0027s\" story was the only way to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"suspect\" mean in this sentence? A. To know for sure B. To believe something is likely true C. To be afraid of someone D. To prove someone is guilty","excerpt":"\"I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"What does the word \"suspect\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To know for sure","B":"To believe something is likely true","C":"To be afraid of someone","D":"To prove someone is guilty"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Suspect in this context means having an idea or belief about why something happened.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q002","read_aloud":"How did the \"paper son\" system start? A. From a new law passed by the government B. From people taking advantage of destroyed records C. From a trip taken by the President D. From people moving to the West","excerpt":"\"Some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\"","stem":"How did the \"paper son\" system start?","choices":{"A":"From a new law passed by the government","B":"From people taking advantage of destroyed records","C":"From a trip taken by the President","D":"From people moving to the West"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The lack of records after the earthquake allowed people to create false claims.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q003","read_aloud":"What does \"son on paper\" mean? A. A son who liked to draw B. A son who was only related by an official document C. A son who had a paper doll D. A son who was actually born in China","excerpt":"\"Sam Louie, the youngest son of Share Kim... says, \u0027Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be a son of a native... they were, in fact, only sons on paper.\u0027\"","stem":"What does \"son on paper\" mean?","choices":{"A":"A son who liked to draw","B":"A son who was only related by an official document","C":"A son who had a paper doll","D":"A son who was actually born in China"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Being a \"son on paper\" meant they were legally claimed as a son but not biologically related or not actually born to that father.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sam Louie, the youngest son of Share Kim... says, \u0027Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be a son of a native... they were, in fact, only sons on paper.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q004","read_aloud":"Why was the coaching book so important for the survival of the family? A. It helped them learn to write B. It contained the secret answers needed to pass interrogation C. It kept their money safe D. It provided a list of places to visit","excerpt":"\"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories... The coaching book contained information about names and birth dates... Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"Why was the coaching book so important for the survival of the family?","choices":{"A":"It helped them learn to write","B":"It contained the secret answers needed to pass interrogation","C":"It kept their money safe","D":"It provided a list of places to visit"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because the officials tested their knowledge, the book was the only way to ensure they did not make a mistake that would lead to being sent back.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories... The coaching book contained information about names and birth dates... Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q005","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what can you infer about how the U.S. government treated Chinese people at the time? A. They were treated with great respect B. They were treated with suspicion and unfairness C. They were given many extra benefits D. They were welcomed with open arms","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"Based on the text, what can you infer about how the U.S. government treated Chinese people at the time?","choices":{"A":"They were treated with great respect","B":"They were treated with suspicion and unfairness","C":"They were given many extra benefits","D":"They were welcomed with open arms"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The fact that Chinese witnesses were not trusted shows the government held deep biases against them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q006","read_aloud":"In this quote, what is the main reason for \"immigration\" according to Sam Louie? A. To visit America for a short vacation B. To seek a better life for themselves and their family C. To escape from school D. To become famous","excerpt":"\"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life for themselves and their family.\"","stem":"In this quote, what is the main reason for \"immigration\" according to Sam Louie?","choices":{"A":"To visit America for a short vacation","B":"To seek a better life for themselves and their family","C":"To escape from school","D":"To become famous"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Sam Louie directly states that his father and others came to America \"to seek a better life for themselves and their family.\" This is the purpose of their immigration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life for themselves and their family.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q007","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"The Path to Paper Son\": \"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Excerpt from \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\": \"They gave the boy the name John. John became their paper son. How do these excerpts from the two texts work together? A. They show that paper sons were only for rich families B. The first explains the cost of the system; the second shows a real example of a family using it C. They both describe life in China after immigration D. They prove that paper sons were never caught","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"The Path to Paper Son\": \"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Excerpt from \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\": \"They gave the boy the name John. John became their paper son. How do these excerpts from the two texts work together?","choices":{"A":"They show that paper sons were only for rich families","B":"The first explains the cost of the system; the second shows a real example of a family using it","C":"They both describe life in China after immigration","D":"They prove that paper sons were never caught"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The first text explains that paper son identities were expensive. The second shows Share Kim\u0027s family actually using the system by taking a boy named John as their paper son.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q008","read_aloud":"Why might the author include the detail about the 42-page transcript? A. To show how short and simple the questioning was B. To emphasize how thorough and detailed the immigration interrogation process was C. To suggest that Louie did not care about the transcript D. To prove that all transcripts were the same length","excerpt":"\"Louie conducted research at the National Archives and Records Administration in San Bruno, California. He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment. The transcript was 42 single-spaced typed pages.\"","stem":"Why might the author include the detail about the 42-page transcript?","choices":{"A":"To show how short and simple the questioning was","B":"To emphasize how thorough and detailed the immigration interrogation process was","C":"To suggest that Louie did not care about the transcript","D":"To prove that all transcripts were the same length"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mentioning that the transcript was 42 single-spaced pages shows the interrogation was very detailed and long. This helps readers understand the intensity of the process.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie conducted research at the National Archives and Records Administration in San Bruno, California. He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment. The transcript was 42 single-spaced typed pages.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q009","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt suggest about the risks of the paper son system? A. There were no risks; everyone succeeded B. If officials noticed inconsistencies, the paper son could be deported, with serious consequences C. Being taller helped paper sons pass inspection D. Twins were not allowed to immigrate","excerpt":"\"Share Kim had a \u0027twin\u0027 paper brother. But when the two boys were placed next to each other, it seemed clear they were not twins at all. Share Kim was much taller. The \u0027twin\u0027 was deported back to China, where he died two years later.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt suggest about the risks of the paper son system?","choices":{"A":"There were no risks; everyone succeeded","B":"If officials noticed inconsistencies, the paper son could be deported, with serious consequences","C":"Being taller helped paper sons pass inspection","D":"Twins were not allowed to immigrate"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"twin\" was deported because he did not resemble Share Kim. This shows that if the paper son story had inconsistencies, the person could be sent back, with serious outcomes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Kim had a \u0027twin\u0027 paper brother. But when the two boys were placed next to each other, it seemed clear they were not twins at all. Share Kim was much taller. The \u0027twin\u0027 was deported back to China, where he died two years later.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q010","read_aloud":"Based on this quote, do you think keeping the paper son secret was a wise choice for Louie\u0027s family? Use clues from the excerpt. A. No, because secrets are always bad B. Yes, because revealing the secret could have led to deportation for the whole family C. No, because other families did not keep secrets D. Yes, but only because they did not trust their neighbors","excerpt":"\"Louie adds, \u0027I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\u0027\"","stem":"Based on this quote, do you think keeping the paper son secret was a wise choice for Louie\u0027s family? Use clues from the excerpt.","choices":{"A":"No, because secrets are always bad","B":"Yes, because revealing the secret could have led to deportation for the whole family","C":"No, because other families did not keep secrets","D":"Yes, but only because they did not trust their neighbors"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Louie says they kept the secret \"for fear that we might all get deported.\" This suggests that revealing the truth could have serious consequences, so keeping the secret was a protective choice.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie adds, \u0027I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"readmitted\" mean? A. Allowed to enter again B. Sent away forever C. Given a new name D. Made to pay a fine","excerpt":"Now considered a \u0027son of a native,\u0027 Share Kim could visit his village in China and know that he would be readmitted into the United States.","stem":"What does \"readmitted\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Allowed to enter again","B":"Sent away forever","C":"Given a new name","D":"Made to pay a fine"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Re\" means again, so readmitted means allowed to enter again.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Now considered a \u0027son of a native,\u0027 Share Kim could visit his village in China and know that he would be readmitted into the United States."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q012","read_aloud":"Why might the law have treated merchants and citizens differently? A. Merchants and citizens were richer. B. The government thought they were more important or trustworthy. C. Merchants did not want families. D. Citizens were all from Europe.","excerpt":"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.","stem":"Why might the law have treated merchants and citizens differently?","choices":{"A":"Merchants and citizens were richer.","B":"The government thought they were more important or trustworthy.","C":"Merchants did not want families.","D":"Citizens were all from Europe."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The law gave special permission to certain groups. The government likely trusted them more.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q013","read_aloud":"Why was the destroyed Hall of Records an opportunity for some Chinese? A. They could build a new hall. B. Without birth records, they could falsely claim to be born in San Francisco. C. They found gold in the ruins. D. They could move to a new city.","excerpt":"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.","stem":"Why was the destroyed Hall of Records an opportunity for some Chinese?","choices":{"A":"They could build a new hall.","B":"Without birth records, they could falsely claim to be born in San Francisco.","C":"They found gold in the ruins.","D":"They could move to a new city."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Without records, officials could not check if a person was really born in San Francisco, so false claims were easier.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q014","read_aloud":"If you were a Chinese laborer in 1890 who wanted to join your family in the U.S., what might you do based on the text? A. Become a merchant or claim to be a citizen\u0027s son B. Write a letter to the president C. Swim across the ocean D. Become a farmer in China","excerpt":"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States.","stem":"If you were a Chinese laborer in 1890 who wanted to join your family in the U.S., what might you do based on the text?","choices":{"A":"Become a merchant or claim to be a citizen\u0027s son","B":"Write a letter to the president","C":"Swim across the ocean","D":"Become a farmer in China"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows that some became paper sons of merchants or citizens to enter the U.S.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q015","read_aloud":"What \"opportunity\" did the 12-year-old boy receive? A. a chance to go to America with Share Kim\u0027s family B. a chance to stay in the village C. a chance to become a teacher D. a chance to buy a house","excerpt":"\"In 1935, he decided to bring his family to America. He and his wife offered a 12-year-old boy in the village the opportunity to go with them. They gave the boy the name John. John became their paper son.\"","stem":"What \"opportunity\" did the 12-year-old boy receive?","choices":{"A":"a chance to go to America with Share Kim\u0027s family","B":"a chance to stay in the village","C":"a chance to become a teacher","D":"a chance to buy a house"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says they offered the boy the opportunity to go with them to America. He became their paper son.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1935, he decided to bring his family to America. He and his wife offered a 12-year-old boy in the village the opportunity to go with them. They gave the boy the name John. John became their paper son.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q016","read_aloud":"What text structure does the author use in this part of the story? A. cause and effect B. chronological order (time order) C. compare and contrast D. problem and solution","excerpt":"\"When Share Kim was 20 years old, his real father wrote him a letter from China. \u0027Dear Number One Son,\u0027 the letter began, referring to Share Kim as the eldest son. \u0027It is time to come home.\u0027\"","stem":"What text structure does the author use in this part of the story?","choices":{"A":"cause and effect","B":"chronological order (time order)","C":"compare and contrast","D":"problem and solution"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author tells events in the order they happened: Share Kim turned 20, his father wrote a letter, and he went to China. This is chronological order.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When Share Kim was 20 years old, his real father wrote him a letter from China. \u0027Dear Number One Son,\u0027 the letter began, referring to Share Kim as the eldest son. \u0027It is time to come home.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q017","read_aloud":"What can you infer from the fact that the transcript was 42 pages long? A. The interrogation was very short. B. The interrogation was long and detailed. C. The family was not asked many questions. D. The officials did not write anything down.","excerpt":"\"Louie conducted research at the National Archives and Records Administration in San Bruno, California. He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment. The transcript was 42 single-spaced typed pages.\"","stem":"What can you infer from the fact that the transcript was 42 pages long?","choices":{"A":"The interrogation was very short.","B":"The interrogation was long and detailed.","C":"The family was not asked many questions.","D":"The officials did not write anything down."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A 42-page transcript shows the interrogation was very long. Officials asked many questions and wrote down all the answers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie conducted research at the National Archives and Records Administration in San Bruno, California. He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment. The transcript was 42 single-spaced typed pages.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q018","read_aloud":"What does this statistic tell you about the paper son system? A. It was very rare. B. It was very common among Chinese families. C. Only a few people used it. D. Most Chinese families did not need it.","excerpt":"\"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\"","stem":"What does this statistic tell you about the paper son system?","choices":{"A":"It was very rare.","B":"It was very common among Chinese families.","C":"Only a few people used it.","D":"Most Chinese families did not need it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Eighty percent means 8 out of 10. This shows the paper son system was very common, not rare.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q019","read_aloud":"Why did Sam Louie keep his father\u0027s secret? A. Because he was embarrassed. B. Because he was afraid his family would be sent back to China. C. Because his father asked him to forget. D. Because it was not important.","excerpt":"\"Louie adds, \u0027I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\u0027\"","stem":"Why did Sam Louie keep his father\u0027s secret?","choices":{"A":"Because he was embarrassed.","B":"Because he was afraid his family would be sent back to China.","C":"Because his father asked him to forget.","D":"Because it was not important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says he never revealed the secret \"for fear that we might all get deported.\" \"Deported\" means sent back to one\u0027s home country.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie adds, \u0027I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They believe the system was perfect B. They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese C. They think the government was doing a good job D. They think everyone was treated the same","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They believe the system was perfect","B":"They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese","C":"They think the government was doing a good job","D":"They think everyone was treated the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By quoting this, the author shows that racial bias made the immigration process unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. To make sure they knew the local language B. To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation C. To learn how to get a job in America D. To help their children study for school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"To make sure they knew the local language","B":"To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation","C":"To learn how to get a job in America","D":"To help their children study for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the exact facts that matched the \"father\u0027s\" story was the only way to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Because it is fun to read about history B. Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives C. Because it shows that the government was always right D. Because it does not matter what happened in the past","excerpt":"\"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Because it is fun to read about history","B":"Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives","C":"Because it shows that the government was always right","D":"Because it does not matter what happened in the past"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Understanding history helps us see the struggles and sacrifices made by others, which is important for learning and respect Section A - Text Information Title: \"The Path to Paper Son\" by Grant Din and \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" by Barbara D. Krasner Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 1, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q001","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"testify\" mean? A. To tell the truth in a formal way B. To take a test in school C. To write a story for a magazine D. To guess an answer","excerpt":"\"He explains that for Share Kim to claim his birth record, he had to find two witnesses who would testify that they knew him as a child.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"testify\" mean?","choices":{"A":"To tell the truth in a formal way","B":"To take a test in school","C":"To write a story for a magazine","D":"To guess an answer"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To testify is to give formal evidence or make a statement, usually in a legal setting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He explains that for Share Kim to claim his birth record, he had to find two witnesses who would testify that they knew him as a child.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q002","read_aloud":"What does \"deportation\" mean? A. Being allowed to stay in a new country B. Being forced to leave a country C. Being given a new job D. Being sent to school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"What does \"deportation\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Being allowed to stay in a new country","B":"Being forced to leave a country","C":"Being given a new job","D":"Being sent to school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Deportation is the act of expelling someone from a country.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q003","read_aloud":"How does the author use Sam Louie\u0027s perspective to help the reader understand the past? A. He gives a first-hand account of his parents\u0027 feelings B. He explains the history of the law C. He tells about his own life in China D. He lists all the laws about immigration","excerpt":"\"I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"How does the author use Sam Louie\u0027s perspective to help the reader understand the past?","choices":{"A":"He gives a first-hand account of his parents\u0027 feelings","B":"He explains the history of the law","C":"He tells about his own life in China","D":"He lists all the laws about immigration"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"By sharing what his parents went through and how they felt, the reader gets a personal, human connection to the history.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Do you think the \"paper son\" system was a good way for families to stay together? A. Yes, because it was the only way they could be with their families B. No, because it was too expensive C. Yes, because everyone was happy doing it D. No, because it was too much work to memorize the books","excerpt":"\"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\"","stem":"Do you think the \"paper son\" system was a good way for families to stay together?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because it was the only way they could be with their families","B":"No, because it was too expensive","C":"Yes, because everyone was happy doing it","D":"No, because it was too much work to memorize the books"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Given the unfair laws that separated families, this system was a necessary (though risky) way to reunite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q005","read_aloud":"Do you think the officials made a fair decision when they deported the \"twin\"? A. Yes, because they looked different B. No, because they didn\u0027t know for sure if they were related C. Yes, because they were following the rules D. No, because he should have been allowed to stay for free","excerpt":"\"The lack of resemblance between Share Kim (left) and his \u0027twin\u0027 brother made officials determine that they were not related.\"","stem":"Do you think the officials made a fair decision when they deported the \"twin\"?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because they looked different","B":"No, because they didn\u0027t know for sure if they were related","C":"Yes, because they were following the rules","D":"No, because he should have been allowed to stay for free"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Deporting someone based only on looks is not a fair legal process, even if they suspected the claim was false.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The lack of resemblance between Share Kim (left) and his \u0027twin\u0027 brother made officials determine that they were not related.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"opportunity\" in this excerpt have both a positive and a challenging meaning? A. It was only positive because everyone benefited equally B. It was a chance to claim U.S. birth, but it also required risking deportation if caught C. It was only challenging because no one succeeded D. It meant a free trip to China","excerpt":"\"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco...\"","stem":"How does the word \"opportunity\" in this excerpt have both a positive and a challenging meaning?","choices":{"A":"It was only positive because everyone benefited equally","B":"It was a chance to claim U.S. birth, but it also required risking deportation if caught","C":"It was only challenging because no one succeeded","D":"It meant a free trip to China"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The destroyed records created a chance (opportunity) to claim U.S. birth, but using that chance involved risk. If officials discovered the claim was false, the person could be deported.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q007","read_aloud":"Why might the author start Louie\u0027s story with these specific details about his age and journey? A. To make the story longer B. To help readers understand how young and vulnerable Louie was, making his experience more powerful C. To show that travel was easy in 1916 D. To prove that Louie was not really from China","excerpt":"\"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916. He had traveled alone on a journey that took nearly a month to cross the Pacific Ocean.\"","stem":"Why might the author start Louie\u0027s story with these specific details about his age and journey?","choices":{"A":"To make the story longer","B":"To help readers understand how young and vulnerable Louie was, making his experience more powerful","C":"To show that travel was easy in 1916","D":"To prove that Louie was not really from China"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By telling us Louie was only 14 and traveled alone for a month, the author helps readers feel empathy. These details make his challenges and his family\u0027s hopes more meaningful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916. He had traveled alone on a journey that took nearly a month to cross the Pacific Ocean.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q008","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"The Path to Paper Son\" explains the paper son system in general. Excerpt from \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" tells one family\u0027s specific story. How does using both a general explanation and a personal story help the reader? A. It makes the text confusing B. The general text explains the system; the personal story makes it real and emotional for readers C. It shows that personal stories are not important D. It proves that all paper sons had the same experience","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"The Path to Paper Son\" explains the paper son system in general. Excerpt from \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" tells one family\u0027s specific story. How does using both a general explanation and a personal story help the reader?","choices":{"A":"It makes the text confusing","B":"The general text explains the system; the personal story makes it real and emotional for readers","C":"It shows that personal stories are not important","D":"It proves that all paper sons had the same experience"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The first text gives background on how the paper son system worked. The second text shows how it affected one real person. Together, they help readers understand both the facts and the human impact.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Based on this statistic, what can you conclude about the paper son system\u0027s role in Chinese American history? A. It was a rare system that very few people used B. It was a widespread strategy that shaped many Chinese American families\u0027 journeys C. It was only used in California D. It was stopped before many people could use it","excerpt":"\"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\"","stem":"Based on this statistic, what can you conclude about the paper son system\u0027s role in Chinese American history?","choices":{"A":"It was a rare system that very few people used","B":"It was a widespread strategy that shaped many Chinese American families\u0027 journeys","C":"It was only used in California","D":"It was stopped before many people could use it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If 80% of Chinese Americans had a paper son in their history, this shows the system was very common. It played a major role in how many families came to America.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q010","read_aloud":"If you were writing a short story about a paper son, what detail from this excerpt would be most important to include, and why? A. The word \"affidavit,\" because it sounds official and shows the legal nature of the false claim B. The color of the paper used C. The name of the ship they sailed on D. The weather on the day they signed","excerpt":"\"They were, in fact, only sons on paper, an affidavit the \u0027father\u0027 signed-thus the term paper son.\"","stem":"If you were writing a short story about a paper son, what detail from this excerpt would be most important to include, and why?","choices":{"A":"The word \"affidavit,\" because it sounds official and shows the legal nature of the false claim","B":"The color of the paper used","C":"The name of the ship they sailed on","D":"The weather on the day they signed"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The word \"affidavit\" shows that the paper son claim was a formal, legal document. Including this detail would help readers understand that the system involved official paperwork, not just informal lies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were, in fact, only sons on paper, an affidavit the \u0027father\u0027 signed-thus the term paper son.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"on paper only\" mean in this sentence? A. They wrote everything on real paper. B. The relationship was not real; it was a lie on documents. C. They drew pictures of their families. D. They used paper to build houses.","excerpt":"To get around the law, many immigrants from China claimed to be related to a merchant or a U.S. citizen-on paper only.","stem":"What does \"on paper only\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"They wrote everything on real paper.","B":"The relationship was not real; it was a lie on documents.","C":"They drew pictures of their families.","D":"They used paper to build houses."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"On paper only\" means the documents said something that was not true in real life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: To get around the law, many immigrants from China claimed to be related to a merchant or a U.S. citizen-on paper only."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q012","read_aloud":"Do you think selling a paper son identity was fair to immigrants who followed the law? Why or why not? A. Yes, because everyone did it. B. No, because it let people break the law while others could not enter at all. C. Yes, because the government allowed it. D. No, because it cost too much money.","excerpt":"Sometimes the son was truly related, and sometimes the \u0027son\u0027 might be a nephew or another relative. Often, the identity was sold to an unrelated person.","stem":"Do you think selling a paper son identity was fair to immigrants who followed the law? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because everyone did it.","B":"No, because it let people break the law while others could not enter at all.","C":"Yes, because the government allowed it.","D":"No, because it cost too much money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This is an evaluating question. The best answer is that it was unfair to those who obeyed the law but still could not enter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Sometimes the son was truly related, and sometimes the \u0027son\u0027 might be a nephew or another relative. Often, the identity was sold to an unrelated person."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Do you think it is better for families to talk about painful experiences or keep them secret? Use clues from the text. A. Keep them secret, because secrets protect the family. B. Talk about them, because then future generations can learn their history. C. It does not matter. D. Only tell friends, not family.","excerpt":"Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027","stem":"Do you think it is better for families to talk about painful experiences or keep them secret? Use clues from the text.","choices":{"A":"Keep them secret, because secrets protect the family.","B":"Talk about them, because then future generations can learn their history.","C":"It does not matter.","D":"Only tell friends, not family."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that Louie researched and learned his family\u0027s history. Sharing can help people understand the past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Imagine you could make one change to the immigration rules in 1916 to make it fairer for families. What would you change? A. Keep the same rules. B. Allow all laborers to bring their families without lying. C. Make the interrogation longer. D. Stop all immigration forever.","excerpt":"Share Kim\u0027s wife and children were detained at Angel Island. Officials questioned each member of the family, even sixyearold Sherman.","stem":"Imagine you could make one change to the immigration rules in 1916 to make it fairer for families. What would you change?","choices":{"A":"Keep the same rules.","B":"Allow all laborers to bring their families without lying.","C":"Make the interrogation longer.","D":"Stop all immigration forever."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This asks you to create a fair rule. Letting families come together would prevent the need for paper sons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Share Kim\u0027s wife and children were detained at Angel Island. Officials questioned each member of the family, even sixyearold Sherman."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q015","read_aloud":"Why was memorizing the coaching book so important for immigration processing? A. Because it was a school assignment. B. Because wrong answers during processing could lead to deportation. C. Because the book was very expensive. D. Because officials did not ask any questions.","excerpt":"\"The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers. When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.\"","stem":"Why was memorizing the coaching book so important for immigration processing?","choices":{"A":"Because it was a school assignment.","B":"Because wrong answers during processing could lead to deportation.","C":"Because the book was very expensive.","D":"Because officials did not ask any questions."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Immigration processing involved tough questioning. The text later explains that wrong answers could lead to deportation, so memorizing was critical.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers. When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Why did the author include this quote from Sam Louie? A. To show that paper sons were lazy. B. To help readers understand why Chinese immigrants became paper sons. C. To explain how to become a paper son. D. To criticize the Chinese Exclusion Act.","excerpt":"\"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life for themselves and their family.\"","stem":"Why did the author include this quote from Sam Louie?","choices":{"A":"To show that paper sons were lazy.","B":"To help readers understand why Chinese immigrants became paper sons.","C":"To explain how to become a paper son.","D":"To criticize the Chinese Exclusion Act."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Sam Louie explains that his father and others became paper sons to \"seek a better life.\" This helps readers understand their reasons and motivations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life for themselves and their family.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q017","read_aloud":"Why might Share Kim and his wife have stayed silent about their experiences? A. Because they forgot what happened. B. Because the experiences were too painful to talk about. C. Because they did not speak English. D. Because their children were not interested.","excerpt":"\"\u0027My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience,\u0027 he says. \u0027I never even knew they were detained at the Angel Island Immigration Station until after my mother passed away at the age of 98 in 2003.\u0027\"","stem":"Why might Share Kim and his wife have stayed silent about their experiences?","choices":{"A":"Because they forgot what happened.","B":"Because the experiences were too painful to talk about.","C":"Because they did not speak English.","D":"Because their children were not interested."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text later says Louie suspects the experiences \"were painful, something they would rather forget.\" This suggests they stayed silent because it was too painful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience,\u0027 he says. \u0027I never even knew they were detained at the Angel Island Immigration Station until after my mother passed away at the age of 98 in 2003.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Do you think Louie\u0027s suspicion is reasonable? Use clues from the text. A. No, because all parents tell their children everything. B. Yes, because the text describes interrogations, detention, and fear of deportation. C. No, because the experiences were fun and easy. D. Yes, because the parents did not remember anything.","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027\"","stem":"Do you think Louie\u0027s suspicion is reasonable? Use clues from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, because all parents tell their children everything.","B":"Yes, because the text describes interrogations, detention, and fear of deportation.","C":"No, because the experiences were fun and easy.","D":"Yes, because the parents did not remember anything."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes many hard experiences: long interrogations, detention, fear of deportation, and unfair treatment. These clues support Louie\u0027s idea that the experiences were painful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Why do you think the author uses the word \"only\" in this sentence? A. To show that the relationship was not real. B. To show that the sons were lonely. C. To show that there was only one son. D. To show that the paper was very thin.","excerpt":"\"They were, in fact, only sons on paper, an affidavit the \u0027father\u0027 signed-thus the term paper son.\"","stem":"Why do you think the author uses the word \"only\" in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To show that the relationship was not real.","B":"To show that the sons were lonely.","C":"To show that there was only one son.","D":"To show that the paper was very thin."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The word \"only\" emphasizes that the relationship existed only on paper, not in real life. It was a legal document, not a true family connection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They were, in fact, only sons on paper, an affidavit the \u0027father\u0027 signed-thus the term paper son.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They believe the system was perfect B. They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese C. They think the government was doing a good job D. They think everyone was treated the same","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They believe the system was perfect","B":"They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese","C":"They think the government was doing a good job","D":"They think everyone was treated the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By quoting this, the author shows that racial bias made the immigration process unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. To make sure they knew the local language B. To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation C. To learn how to get a job in America D. To help their children study for school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"To make sure they knew the local language","B":"To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation","C":"To learn how to get a job in America","D":"To help their children study for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the exact facts that matched the \"father\u0027s\" story was the only way to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l08-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Because it is fun to read about history B. Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives C. Because it shows that the government was always right D. Because it does not matter what happened in the past","excerpt":"\"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Because it is fun to read about history","B":"Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives","C":"Because it shows that the government was always right","D":"Because it does not matter what happened in the past"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Understanding history helps us see the struggles and sacrifices made by others, which is important for learning and respect Section A - Text Information Title: \"The Path to Paper Son\" by Grant Din and \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" by Barbara D. Krasner Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 1, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"detainment\" mean? A. The state of being kept in a place B. The state of being free to leave C. A type of vacation D. A process of traveling","excerpt":"\"He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment.\"","stem":"What does the word \"detainment\" mean?","choices":{"A":"The state of being kept in a place","B":"The state of being free to leave","C":"A type of vacation","D":"A process of traveling"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Detainment is the act of holding someone, often in an official place, and not allowing them to leave.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q002","read_aloud":"How does the story of Wong Kim Ark connect to the main idea of the text? A. It explains how the immigration system worked B. It shows that birthright citizenship was a legal right for Chinese-Americans C. It describes the earthquake in San Francisco D. It explains why people moved west","excerpt":"\"In 1868, the 14th Amendment to the Constitution established that anyone born in the United States is granted U.S. citizenship. In 1898, American-born Chinese Wong Kim Ark won a U.S. Supreme Court case that reaffirmed that law.\"","stem":"How does the story of Wong Kim Ark connect to the main idea of the text?","choices":{"A":"It explains how the immigration system worked","B":"It shows that birthright citizenship was a legal right for Chinese-Americans","C":"It describes the earthquake in San Francisco","D":"It explains why people moved west"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"His case proved that even Chinese people born in the U.S. were citizens, which is a key part of the legal background for this story.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1868, the 14th Amendment to the Constitution established that anyone born in the United States is granted U.S. citizenship. In 1898, American-born Chinese Wong Kim Ark won a U.S. Supreme Court case that reaffirmed that law.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q003","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the phrase \"As expected\"? A. Because the author knew they would be famous B. Because the family wanted to be detained C. Because it was normal for new immigrants to be held for questioning D. Because the family had a very easy journey","excerpt":"\"As expected, Share Kim\u0027s wife and children were detained at Angel Island.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the phrase \"As expected\"?","choices":{"A":"Because the author knew they would be famous","B":"Because the family wanted to be detained","C":"Because it was normal for new immigrants to be held for questioning","D":"Because the family had a very easy journey"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"It was a standard part of the immigration process for these families to be held at Angel Island.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As expected, Share Kim\u0027s wife and children were detained at Angel Island.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q004","read_aloud":"Do you agree that some memories are better left unsaid? A. Yes, because talking about them always makes things worse B. No, because history should always be remembered to prevent mistakes C. Yes, because children should not know about the past D. No, because it is easy to talk about hard things","excerpt":"\"Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"Do you agree that some memories are better left unsaid?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because talking about them always makes things worse","B":"No, because history should always be remembered to prevent mistakes","C":"Yes, because children should not know about the past","D":"No, because it is easy to talk about hard things"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While memories can be painful, sharing them is important for understanding history, even if it is difficult.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q005","read_aloud":"If you were a paper son, how would you feel about having to memorize all those details? A. Excited because it was a fun game B. Nervous because a wrong answer meant being sent away C. Bored because it was too easy D. Happy because you would learn a lot","excerpt":"\"The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers.\"","stem":"If you were a paper son, how would you feel about having to memorize all those details?","choices":{"A":"Excited because it was a fun game","B":"Nervous because a wrong answer meant being sent away","C":"Bored because it was too easy","D":"Happy because you would learn a lot"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The pressure of deportation would make the process very stressful and scary for any person.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q006","read_aloud":"In the context of immigration \"processing,\" why was it important for the coaching book to include so many specific details? A. To make the book longer and more expensive B. To help the paper son answer detailed questions correctly and pass the official review C. To teach the paper son about geography D. To help officials learn about Chinese villages","excerpt":"\"The coaching book contained information about names and birth dates of all family members, the location of the home village and its environment, dates of Share Kim\u0027s travels to China, and more.\"","stem":"In the context of immigration \"processing,\" why was it important for the coaching book to include so many specific details?","choices":{"A":"To make the book longer and more expensive","B":"To help the paper son answer detailed questions correctly and pass the official review","C":"To teach the paper son about geography","D":"To help officials learn about Chinese villages"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Immigration processing involved detailed questioning. The coaching book had specific facts so the paper son could give consistent answers and avoid being caught.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The coaching book contained information about names and birth dates of all family members, the location of the home village and its environment, dates of Share Kim\u0027s travels to China, and more.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q007","read_aloud":"Why is Louie\u0027s discovery of the transcript important evidence for understanding his family\u0027s history? A. It proves that all immigrants had the same experience B. It provides a firsthand, official record of what his family went through during immigration questioning C. It shows that transcripts were not kept for most families D. It suggests that Louie did not believe his family\u0027s story","excerpt":"\"Louie conducted research at the National Archives and Records Administration in San Bruno, California. He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment.\"","stem":"Why is Louie\u0027s discovery of the transcript important evidence for understanding his family\u0027s history?","choices":{"A":"It proves that all immigrants had the same experience","B":"It provides a firsthand, official record of what his family went through during immigration questioning","C":"It shows that transcripts were not kept for most families","D":"It suggests that Louie did not believe his family\u0027s story"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The transcript is an official document from the time. It gives direct evidence of the questions asked and answers given, helping Louie and readers understand the real experience.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie conducted research at the National Archives and Records Administration in San Bruno, California. He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q008","read_aloud":"he says. \"I never even knew they were detained at the Angel Island Immigration Station until after my mother passed away at the age of 98 in 2003. What does Louie\u0027s statement suggest about how some immigrants felt about sharing their experiences? A. They were proud and told everyone B. The experiences may have been painful or risky to discuss, so they kept them private C. They did not remember what happened D. They wanted their children to figure it out alone","excerpt":"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience,","stem":"he says. \"I never even knew they were detained at the Angel Island Immigration Station until after my mother passed away at the age of 98 in 2003. What does Louie\u0027s statement suggest about how some immigrants felt about sharing their experiences?","choices":{"A":"They were proud and told everyone","B":"The experiences may have been painful or risky to discuss, so they kept them private","C":"They did not remember what happened","D":"They wanted their children to figure it out alone"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Louie did not know about his parents\u0027 detention until after his mother died. This suggests they chose not to share, possibly because the memories were painful or because revealing the paper son status was risky.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience,"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q009","read_aloud":"Do you agree with Louie\u0027s suspicion that the experiences were painful? Use evidence from the text to support your view. A. No, because the text does not mention pain B. Yes, because the detailed questioning, risk of deportation, and need for secrecy would create stress and fear C. No, because everyone enjoyed traveling to America D. Yes, but only because they did not like Angel Island","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027\"","stem":"Do you agree with Louie\u0027s suspicion that the experiences were painful? Use evidence from the text to support your view.","choices":{"A":"No, because the text does not mention pain","B":"Yes, because the detailed questioning, risk of deportation, and need for secrecy would create stress and fear","C":"No, because everyone enjoyed traveling to America","D":"Yes, but only because they did not like Angel Island"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes interrogation, detention, coaching books to avoid deportation, and secrecy. These elements suggest the experience was stressful and potentially traumatic, supporting Louie\u0027s suspicion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q010","read_aloud":"If you were writing a diary entry from Share Kim\u0027s perspective on his wedding day, what feeling might he express, and what detail from the excerpt supports that feeling? A. Excitement, because he had always known his wife B. Nervousness or uncertainty, because he had never seen his wife before and the marriage was arranged C. Anger, because he did not want to get married D. Boredom, because weddings are always the same","excerpt":"\"He was married on Saturday to a woman chosen by his parents and whom he had never seen before.\"","stem":"If you were writing a diary entry from Share Kim\u0027s perspective on his wedding day, what feeling might he express, and what detail from the excerpt supports that feeling?","choices":{"A":"Excitement, because he had always known his wife","B":"Nervousness or uncertainty, because he had never seen his wife before and the marriage was arranged","C":"Anger, because he did not want to get married","D":"Boredom, because weddings are always the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says Share Kim \"had never seen before\" his wife, and she was \"chosen by his parents.\" A diary entry might express nervousness about marrying a stranger, which is a reasonable emotional response to that situation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He was married on Saturday to a woman chosen by his parents and whom he had never seen before.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q011","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"memorize\"? A. Forget B. Write C. Learn by heart D. Guess","excerpt":"The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers.","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"memorize\"?","choices":{"A":"Forget","B":"Write","C":"Learn by heart","D":"Guess"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"To memorize means to learn something so well that you can say it without looking.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q012","read_aloud":"Do you think it was fair that only white witnesses were trusted? Why? A. Yes, because white people never lie. B. No, because trust should not be based on race. C. Yes, because the law said so. D. No, because Chinese people had more records.","excerpt":"The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.","stem":"Do you think it was fair that only white witnesses were trusted? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because white people never lie.","B":"No, because trust should not be based on race.","C":"Yes, because the law said so.","D":"No, because Chinese people had more records."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This asks students to judge fairness. Judging people by race, not by facts, is unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q013","read_aloud":"If this estimate is true, what does that tell you about the Chinese Exclusion Act? A. The Act was very successful. B. The Act did not stop Chinese immigration; it just forced people to lie. C. Most Chinese people chose to stay in China. D. The Act helped Chinese families stay together.","excerpt":"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.","stem":"If this estimate is true, what does that tell you about the Chinese Exclusion Act?","choices":{"A":"The Act was very successful.","B":"The Act did not stop Chinese immigration; it just forced people to lie.","C":"Most Chinese people chose to stay in China.","D":"The Act helped Chinese families stay together."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A very high number of paper sons shows that people found ways around the law.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Imagine you are a museum curator. You want to create an exhibit about paper sons. Besides the Certificate of Identity, what other item from the text would you include and why? A. A gold nugget, because it is valuable B. A coaching book, because it shows how paper sons prepared for interrogation C. A ship ticket, because it is colorful D. A map of China, because it is big","excerpt":"Louie showed his father\u0027s Certificate of Identity.","stem":"Imagine you are a museum curator. You want to create an exhibit about paper sons. Besides the Certificate of Identity, what other item from the text would you include and why?","choices":{"A":"A gold nugget, because it is valuable","B":"A coaching book, because it shows how paper sons prepared for interrogation","C":"A ship ticket, because it is colorful","D":"A map of China, because it is big"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A coaching book directly shows the process paper sons used to memorize answers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Louie showed his father\u0027s Certificate of Identity."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q015","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what was the main reason for Chinese immigration to America during this time? A. to find better opportunities and a better life B. to visit tourist attractions C. to become government officials D. to sell paper documents","excerpt":"\"\u0027Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life for themselves and their family.\u0027\"","stem":"Based on the text, what was the main reason for Chinese immigration to America during this time?","choices":{"A":"to find better opportunities and a better life","B":"to visit tourist attractions","C":"to become government officials","D":"to sell paper documents"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Sam Louie states that his father and others came to America to \"seek a better life.\" This was the main reason for immigration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life for themselves and their family.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q016","read_aloud":"How did the 1906 earthquake affect Chinese immigration? A. It stopped all immigration forever. B. It accidentally created a way for more Chinese to claim U.S. birth and bring others. C. It helped officials keep better records. D. It made Chinese workers want to leave America.","excerpt":"\"The claim created immigration slots, which could be used to bring another Chinese to America. In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records.\"","stem":"How did the 1906 earthquake affect Chinese immigration?","choices":{"A":"It stopped all immigration forever.","B":"It accidentally created a way for more Chinese to claim U.S. birth and bring others.","C":"It helped officials keep better records.","D":"It made Chinese workers want to leave America."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The earthquake destroyed birth records. Without records, Chinese people could claim they were born in San Francisco, creating slots to bring others. This was an unintended effect.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The claim created immigration slots, which could be used to bring another Chinese to America. In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q017","read_aloud":"Why does the author include specific details like \"fourteen-year-old\" and \"nearly a month\"? A. To make the story longer. B. To help readers understand how young and brave Share Kim was. C. To teach math skills. D. To describe the weather.","excerpt":"\"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916. He had traveled alone on a journey that took nearly a month to cross the Pacific Ocean.\"","stem":"Why does the author include specific details like \"fourteen-year-old\" and \"nearly a month\"?","choices":{"A":"To make the story longer.","B":"To help readers understand how young and brave Share Kim was.","C":"To teach math skills.","D":"To describe the weather."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"These details show Share Kim was very young and traveled for a very long time alone. This helps readers understand how difficult and brave his journey was.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916. He had traveled alone on a journey that took nearly a month to cross the Pacific Ocean.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q018","read_aloud":"Why do you think officials questioned even a six-year-old child? A. Because children are easier to trick into telling the truth. B. Because Sherman was the smartest person in the family. C. Because children do not know anything. D. Because officials only liked talking to children.","excerpt":"\"Officials questioned each member of the family, even six-year-old Sherman, and they brought Share Kim in a second time for questioning.\"","stem":"Why do you think officials questioned even a six-year-old child?","choices":{"A":"Because children are easier to trick into telling the truth.","B":"Because Sherman was the smartest person in the family.","C":"Because children do not know anything.","D":"Because officials only liked talking to children."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Officials wanted to catch mistakes in the family\u0027s story. A young child might not remember the coaching book answers and might accidentally tell the truth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Officials questioned each member of the family, even six-year-old Sherman, and they brought Share Kim in a second time for questioning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q019","read_aloud":"If a family could not repay the debt for paper son documents, what might happen? A. They would become very rich. B. They might face serious money problems for many years. C. The government would forgive the debt. D. They would get free tickets to America.","excerpt":"\"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip. It often took several years of hard work to repay the debt.\"","stem":"If a family could not repay the debt for paper son documents, what might happen?","choices":{"A":"They would become very rich.","B":"They might face serious money problems for many years.","C":"The government would forgive the debt.","D":"They would get free tickets to America."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says documents cost thousands of dollars and families borrowed money. If they could not repay, they would have serious money problems for a long time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip. It often took several years of hard work to repay the debt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They believe the system was perfect B. They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese C. They think the government was doing a good job D. They think everyone was treated the same","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They believe the system was perfect","B":"They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese","C":"They think the government was doing a good job","D":"They think everyone was treated the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By quoting this, the author shows that racial bias made the immigration process unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. To make sure they knew the local language B. To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation C. To learn how to get a job in America D. To help their children study for school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"To make sure they knew the local language","B":"To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation","C":"To learn how to get a job in America","D":"To help their children study for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the exact facts that matched the \"father\u0027s\" story was the only way to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l09-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Because it is fun to read about history B. Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives C. Because it shows that the government was always right D. Because it does not matter what happened in the past","excerpt":"\"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Because it is fun to read about history","B":"Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives","C":"Because it shows that the government was always right","D":"Because it does not matter what happened in the past"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Understanding history helps us see the struggles and sacrifices made by others, which is important for learning and respect Section A - Text Information Title: \"The Path to Paper Son\" by Grant Din and \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" by Barbara D. Krasner Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 1, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q001","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for \"testify\"? A. To declare B. To witness C. To stay silent D. To speak","excerpt":"\"He explains that for Share Kim to claim his birth record, he had to find two witnesses who would testify that they knew him as a child.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym (opposite) for \"testify\"?","choices":{"A":"To declare","B":"To witness","C":"To stay silent","D":"To speak"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Testifying involves speaking or giving information, while staying silent is the opposite.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He explains that for Share Kim to claim his birth record, he had to find two witnesses who would testify that they knew him as a child.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q002","read_aloud":"What is the effect of the \"paper son\" system on the lives of families like Share Kim\u0027s? A. It allowed them to live together all the time B. It caused them to be separated for many years C. It made them travel by train D. It gave them more time to spend together","excerpt":"\"Share Kim returned to America to work. In 1924 and in 1929, he returned to China to visit his village and see his wife. They had two children, Wanda and Sherman. After each visit, Share Kim returned to the United States to work.\"","stem":"What is the effect of the \"paper son\" system on the lives of families like Share Kim\u0027s?","choices":{"A":"It allowed them to live together all the time","B":"It caused them to be separated for many years","C":"It made them travel by train","D":"It gave them more time to spend together"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because of the laws and the need for work, families were often forced to live apart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Share Kim returned to America to work. In 1924 and in 1929, he returned to China to visit his village and see his wife. They had two children, Wanda and Sherman. After each visit, Share Kim returned to the United States to work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q003","read_aloud":"Why is this information important to the overall topic? A. It shows that the paper son system was an exception to the rules B. It shows that the practice was very common for the Chinese community C. It proves that paper sons were always wealthy D. It explains why the earthquake happened","excerpt":"\"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\"","stem":"Why is this information important to the overall topic?","choices":{"A":"It shows that the paper son system was an exception to the rules","B":"It shows that the practice was very common for the Chinese community","C":"It proves that paper sons were always wealthy","D":"It explains why the earthquake happened"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This statistic helps the reader understand that this was a normal part of life for many families during that era.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q004","read_aloud":"How would your life be different if you had to keep a big secret about your family\u0027s history? A. I would be happier because secrets are fun B. I would be more anxious and always feel like I was hiding something C. I would not care because it would not affect me D. I would tell everyone because secrets do not matter","excerpt":"\"I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\"","stem":"How would your life be different if you had to keep a big secret about your family\u0027s history?","choices":{"A":"I would be happier because secrets are fun","B":"I would be more anxious and always feel like I was hiding something","C":"I would not care because it would not affect me","D":"I would tell everyone because secrets do not matter"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Living with a fear of deportation would likely create a sense of worry and prevent a person from being completely honest.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q005","read_aloud":"If this law did not exist, how might the story of the \"paper son\" change? A. It would be exactly the same B. The \"paper son\" system would not have been needed C. Everyone would have lived in China D. There would be more earthquakes","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States.\"","stem":"If this law did not exist, how might the story of the \"paper son\" change?","choices":{"A":"It would be exactly the same","B":"The \"paper son\" system would not have been needed","C":"Everyone would have lived in China","D":"There would be more earthquakes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"paper son\" system was a reaction to the Exclusion Act; without the law, people would not have needed to fake their identities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act, in effect from 1882 to 1943, stopped all Chinese laborers from entering the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"admitted\" in this context carry both a legal and a personal meaning for Share Kim? A. It only has a legal meaning about paperwork B. Legally, it means he was granted entry; personally, it represents his family\u0027s hope and sacrifice for a new life C. It only has a personal meaning about feelings D. It means he was admitted to a hospital","excerpt":"\"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the word \"admitted\" in this context carry both a legal and a personal meaning for Share Kim?","choices":{"A":"It only has a legal meaning about paperwork","B":"Legally, it means he was granted entry; personally, it represents his family\u0027s hope and sacrifice for a new life","C":"It only has a personal meaning about feelings","D":"It means he was admitted to a hospital"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Admitted\" legally means officials allowed him to enter the U.S. But for Share Kim and his family, this moment represented years of planning, sacrifice, and hope for opportunity in America.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q007","read_aloud":"Why might the authors choose to include both types of information in these texts? A. To make the texts longer for school assignments B. To help readers understand both the historical context and the human experiences behind the facts C. To prove that personal stories are more important than facts D. To confuse readers about what is true","excerpt":"The text includes both historical facts (dates, laws) and personal stories (Louie Share Kim\u0027s journey).","stem":"Why might the authors choose to include both types of information in these texts?","choices":{"A":"To make the texts longer for school assignments","B":"To help readers understand both the historical context and the human experiences behind the facts","C":"To prove that personal stories are more important than facts","D":"To confuse readers about what is true"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Historical facts give the big picture of laws and events. Personal stories make those facts real and emotional. Together, they help readers fully understand the topic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text includes both historical facts (dates, laws) and personal stories (Louie Share Kim\u0027s journey)."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q008","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for \"environment\"? A. Weather and surroundings B. Food C. Clothing D. Money","excerpt":"The coaching book contained information about names and birth dates of all family members, the location of the home village and its environment, dates of Share Kim\u0027s travels to China, and more.","stem":"Which word is a synonym for \"environment\"?","choices":{"A":"Weather and surroundings","B":"Food","C":"Clothing","D":"Money"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Environment means the natural features and conditions around a place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The coaching book contained information about names and birth dates of all family members, the location of the home village and its environment, dates of Share Kim\u0027s travels to China, and more."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q009","read_aloud":"From Sam Louie\u0027s perspective, what was the worst risk of telling the truth? A. Losing friends B. His family being sent back to China C. Going to jail for one day D. Paying a small fine","excerpt":"I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.","stem":"From Sam Louie\u0027s perspective, what was the worst risk of telling the truth?","choices":{"A":"Losing friends","B":"His family being sent back to China","C":"Going to jail for one day","D":"Paying a small fine"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Louie says he feared they might all get deported, which is a very serious risk.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q010","read_aloud":"Write a question you would want to ask Sam Louie about his family\u0027s history. Choose the best question from below. A. What is your favorite food? B. How did you feel when you found the interrogation transcript? C. What color is your house? D. How old is your car?","excerpt":"Louie says, \u0027I never even knew they were detained at the Angel Island Immigration Station until after my mother passed away at the age of 98 in 2003.\u0027","stem":"Write a question you would want to ask Sam Louie about his family\u0027s history. Choose the best question from below.","choices":{"A":"What is your favorite food?","B":"How did you feel when you found the interrogation transcript?","C":"What color is your house?","D":"How old is your car?"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This question connects to the text and asks about feelings and discovery, which are important to the story.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Louie says, \u0027I never even knew they were detained at the Angel Island Immigration Station until after my mother passed away at the age of 98 in 2003.\u0027"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q011","read_aloud":"Do you think the paper sons were dishonest people, or did they do what they had to do? Use text evidence. A. They were dishonest because lying is always wrong. B. They did what they had to do because the law was unfair and separated families. C. They were lazy and did not want to follow rules. D. They did it only for money.","excerpt":"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life for themselves and their family. They were, in fact, only sons on paper.","stem":"Do you think the paper sons were dishonest people, or did they do what they had to do? Use text evidence.","choices":{"A":"They were dishonest because lying is always wrong.","B":"They did what they had to do because the law was unfair and separated families.","C":"They were lazy and did not want to follow rules.","D":"They did it only for money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows families wanted a better life and the law was very strict, so they found a way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life for themselves and their family. They were, in fact, only sons on paper."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q012","read_aloud":"Why was being \"admitted\" as a \"son of a native\" so important for Share Kim? A. It allowed him to travel to China and return safely to America. B. It gave him free money. C. It made him a government official. D. It meant he did not have to work.","excerpt":"\"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027 Now considered a \u0027son of a native,\u0027 Share Kim could visit his village in China and know that he would be readmitted into the United States.\"","stem":"Why was being \"admitted\" as a \"son of a native\" so important for Share Kim?","choices":{"A":"It allowed him to travel to China and return safely to America.","B":"It gave him free money.","C":"It made him a government official.","D":"It meant he did not have to work."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says once he was admitted as a \"son of a native,\" he could visit China and be \"readmitted\" to America. This status protected his right to return.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He received his Certificate of Identity, which stated he was admitted as the \u0027son of a native.\u0027 Now considered a \u0027son of a native,\u0027 Share Kim could visit his village in China and know that he would be readmitted into the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q013","read_aloud":"Why is it important that Sam Louie shares his father\u0027s story today? A. Because he wants to become famous. B. Because it helps people remember and learn from this part of history. C. Because he needs to practice acting. D. Because the government asked him to.","excerpt":"\"Louie is a retired educator and volunteer at Angel Island Immigration Station. In July 2015, the Angel Island Immigration Station Foundation hosted a family history/reunion day event. Portraying his father, Louie shared his story.\"","stem":"Why is it important that Sam Louie shares his father\u0027s story today?","choices":{"A":"Because he wants to become famous.","B":"Because it helps people remember and learn from this part of history.","C":"Because he needs to practice acting.","D":"Because the government asked him to."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Louie shares his father\u0027s story at a history event. This helps preserve the history of Chinese immigrants and teaches others about their experiences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie is a retired educator and volunteer at Angel Island Immigration Station. In July 2015, the Angel Island Immigration Station Foundation hosted a family history/reunion day event. Portraying his father, Louie shared his story.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q014","read_aloud":"How does Louie\u0027s work as a volunteer connect to his family\u0027s history? A. It has nothing to do with his family. B. It helps him honor his parents and share their story with others. C. It helps him forget his family\u0027s past. D. It is just a job he does for money.","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027\"","stem":"How does Louie\u0027s work as a volunteer connect to his family\u0027s history?","choices":{"A":"It has nothing to do with his family.","B":"It helps him honor his parents and share their story with others.","C":"It helps him forget his family\u0027s past.","D":"It is just a job he does for money."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Louie volunteers at Angel Island, where his family was detained. He shares their story to help others understand what happened. This honors his parents\u0027 experiences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q015","read_aloud":"What does Louie\u0027s research tell you about learning family history? A. Family history is always easy to learn. B. Sometimes you must research to discover stories your family never told. C. Parents always tell their children everything. D. Research is never helpful.","excerpt":"\"\u0027I never even knew they were detained at the Angel Island Immigration Station until after my mother passed away at the age of 98 in 2003.\u0027 Louie conducted research at the National Archives and Records Administration in San Bruno, California. He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment.\"","stem":"What does Louie\u0027s research tell you about learning family history?","choices":{"A":"Family history is always easy to learn.","B":"Sometimes you must research to discover stories your family never told.","C":"Parents always tell their children everything.","D":"Research is never helpful."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Louie did not know about his parents\u0027 detention until after his mother died. He had to research at the National Archives to find the truth. This shows some stories must be discovered through research.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027I never even knew they were detained at the Angel Island Immigration Station until after my mother passed away at the age of 98 in 2003.\u0027 Louie conducted research at the National Archives and Records Administration in San Bruno, California. He found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q016","read_aloud":"If the Chinese Exclusion Act had never existed, how might Share Kim\u0027s life have been different? A. He would not have needed to become a paper son. B. He would have stayed in China forever. C. He would not have wanted to come to America. D. He would have become a government official.","excerpt":"\"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life for themselves and their family.\"","stem":"If the Chinese Exclusion Act had never existed, how might Share Kim\u0027s life have been different?","choices":{"A":"He would not have needed to become a paper son.","B":"He would have stayed in China forever.","C":"He would not have wanted to come to America.","D":"He would have become a government official."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The Chinese Exclusion Act forced Chinese laborers to find other ways to enter America. Without the Act, Share Kim could have entered legally and would not have needed to become a paper son.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life for themselves and their family.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q017","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q018","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q019","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They believe the system was perfect B. They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese C. They think the government was doing a good job D. They think everyone was treated the same","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They believe the system was perfect","B":"They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese","C":"They think the government was doing a good job","D":"They think everyone was treated the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By quoting this, the author shows that racial bias made the immigration process unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. To make sure they knew the local language B. To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation C. To learn how to get a job in America D. To help their children study for school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"To make sure they knew the local language","B":"To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation","C":"To learn how to get a job in America","D":"To help their children study for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the exact facts that matched the \"father\u0027s\" story was the only way to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Because it is fun to read about history B. Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives C. Because it shows that the government was always right D. Because it does not matter what happened in the past","excerpt":"\"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Because it is fun to read about history","B":"Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives","C":"Because it shows that the government was always right","D":"Because it does not matter what happened in the past"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Understanding history helps us see the struggles and sacrifices made by others, which is important for learning and respect Section A - Text Information Title: \"The Path to Paper Son\" by Grant Din and \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" by Barbara D. Krasner Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 1, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. people who visit a country for a short time B. people who belong to a place and have rights there C. people who work in government jobs D. people who travel between countries for business","excerpt":"\"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China. The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"people who visit a country for a short time","B":"people who belong to a place and have rights there","C":"people who work in government jobs","D":"people who travel between countries for business"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Citizens are people who belong to a country and have rights there. The text says U.S. citizens could send for families, but laborers could not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China. The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Chinese workers liked to travel alone B. Many Chinese workers left families in China when they came to America C. All Chinese workers were single men D. Families in China did not want to come to America","excerpt":"\"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Chinese workers liked to travel alone","B":"Many Chinese workers left families in China when they came to America","C":"All Chinese workers were single men","D":"Families in China did not want to come to America"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt tells us many Chinese workers were married and had children who stayed in China. This is the main point.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-l10-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. It helped Chinese families move to America B. It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing families to the U.S. C. It gave money to Chinese workers D. It made it easier for all Chinese people to immigrate","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"It helped Chinese families move to America","B":"It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing families to the U.S.","C":"It gave money to Chinese workers","D":"It made it easier for all Chinese people to immigrate"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says the Act \"prohibited\" or stopped Chinese laborers from sending for their families. That is the key detail.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"opportunity\" mean? A. A big problem B. A chance to succeed C. A sad day D. A new job","excerpt":"\"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"What does \"opportunity\" mean?","choices":{"A":"A big problem","B":"A chance to succeed","C":"A sad day","D":"A new job"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this case, an opportunity is a chance for someone to change their situation for the better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q002","read_aloud":"What is an \"affidavit\"? A. A legal document B. A school book C. A picture D. A boat ticket","excerpt":"\"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life... they were, in fact, only sons on paper, an affidavit the \u0027father\u0027 signed.\"","stem":"What is an \"affidavit\"?","choices":{"A":"A legal document","B":"A school book","C":"A picture","D":"A boat ticket"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"An affidavit is a written legal document used as evidence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many Chinese, including my father, claimed to be \u0027a son of a native\u0027 so they could come to America to seek a better life... they were, in fact, only sons on paper, an affidavit the \u0027father\u0027 signed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q003","read_aloud":"What is a \"transcript\"? A. A picture taken by a camera B. A written record of spoken words C. A map of a city D. A list of rules","excerpt":"\"I found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment.\"","stem":"What is a \"transcript\"?","choices":{"A":"A picture taken by a camera","B":"A written record of spoken words","C":"A map of a city","D":"A list of rules"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A transcript provides a written copy of what was said during the questioning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I found a transcript of the interrogation of his mother and siblings during their detainment.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q004","read_aloud":"What was the primary effect of the Chinese Exclusion Act? A. It made it easier for people to move to America B. It separated many families by preventing immigration C. It helped build new cities D. It encouraged people to travel to China","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\"","stem":"What was the primary effect of the Chinese Exclusion Act?","choices":{"A":"It made it easier for people to move to America","B":"It separated many families by preventing immigration","C":"It helped build new cities","D":"It encouraged people to travel to China"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The law specifically stopped laborers from bringing their families, which is why they were separated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q005","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the immigration process at Angel Island? A. It was simple and fast B. It was difficult and full of intense questioning C. It was always friendly to new immigrants D. It was only for people with a lot of money","excerpt":"\"Officials questioned each member of the family, even six-year-old Sherman, and they brought Share Kim in a second time for questioning.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the immigration process at Angel Island?","choices":{"A":"It was simple and fast","B":"It was difficult and full of intense questioning","C":"It was always friendly to new immigrants","D":"It was only for people with a lot of money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The intense and repeated questioning shows that the process was very difficult and stressful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Officials questioned each member of the family, even six-year-old Sherman, and they brought Share Kim in a second time for questioning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q006","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of the entire text? A. Angel Island was a beautiful place B. Many Chinese immigrants used the \"paper son\" system to overcome unfair laws C. Earthquakes are good for immigration D. Most immigrants were not related to each other","excerpt":"\"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of the entire text?","choices":{"A":"Angel Island was a beautiful place","B":"Many Chinese immigrants used the \"paper son\" system to overcome unfair laws","C":"Earthquakes are good for immigration","D":"Most immigrants were not related to each other"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The entire text explains the reasons for and the experiences of families using the paper son system to bypass immigration laws.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some Chinese scholars estimate that 80 percent of Chinese in America had a paper son in their family history.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q007","read_aloud":"How did the destruction of records allow the \"paper son\" system to work? A. The government had to give everyone new names B. It was impossible for officials to prove someone was not a citizen C. It made people move back to China D. It forced the government to build more houses","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco... With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"How did the destruction of records allow the \"paper son\" system to work?","choices":{"A":"The government had to give everyone new names","B":"It was impossible for officials to prove someone was not a citizen","C":"It made people move back to China","D":"It forced the government to build more houses"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because proof of birth was gone, people could safely lie about where they were born.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco... With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q008","read_aloud":"What does this statement reveal about the author\u0027s perspective on the time period? A. They believe the system was perfect B. They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese C. They think the government was doing a good job D. They think everyone was treated the same","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"What does this statement reveal about the author\u0027s perspective on the time period?","choices":{"A":"They believe the system was perfect","B":"They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese","C":"They think the government was doing a good job","D":"They think everyone was treated the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By quoting this, the author shows that racial bias made the immigration process unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q009","read_aloud":"Why did the families use coaching books to prepare? A. To make sure they knew the local language B. To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation C. To learn how to get a job in America D. To help their children study for school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"Why did the families use coaching books to prepare?","choices":{"A":"To make sure they knew the local language","B":"To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation","C":"To learn how to get a job in America","D":"To help their children study for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the exact facts that matched the \"father\u0027s\" story was the only way to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q010","read_aloud":"Why is it important to learn about this part of history, even if it is painful? A. Because it is fun to read about history B. Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives C. Because it shows that the government was always right D. Because it does not matter what happened in the past","excerpt":"\"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"Why is it important to learn about this part of history, even if it is painful?","choices":{"A":"Because it is fun to read about history","B":"Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives","C":"Because it shows that the government was always right","D":"Because it does not matter what happened in the past"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Understanding history helps us see the struggles and sacrifices made by others, which is important for learning and respect Section A - Text Information Title: \"The Path to Paper Son\" by Grant Din and \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" by Barbara D. Krasner Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 1, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"citizens\" mean in this sentence? A. people who visit a country B. people who belong to a country and have rights there C. people who work on ships D. people who study history","excerpt":"\"But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\"","stem":"What does \"citizens\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"people who visit a country","B":"people who belong to a country and have rights there","C":"people who work on ships","D":"people who study history"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Citizens are people who legally belong to a country. The text contrasts citizens with laborers, showing citizens had rights to bring family.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q012","read_aloud":"Which situation best shows \"immigration\"? A. Taking a vacation in another country B. Moving from China to the United States to live and work C. Visiting grandparents for a holiday D. Studying abroad for one semester","excerpt":"\"immigration the act of moving to a new country to live there\"","stem":"Which situation best shows \"immigration\"?","choices":{"A":"Taking a vacation in another country","B":"Moving from China to the United States to live and work","C":"Visiting grandparents for a holiday","D":"Studying abroad for one semester"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Immigration means moving to a new country to live there permanently or long-term, not just visiting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"immigration the act of moving to a new country to live there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q013","read_aloud":"In this context, \"opportunity\" means: A. a problem that cannot be solved B. a chance to do something that could help achieve a goal C. a rule that must be followed D. a type of document","excerpt":"\"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"In this context, \"opportunity\" means:","choices":{"A":"a problem that cannot be solved","B":"a chance to do something that could help achieve a goal","C":"a rule that must be followed","D":"a type of document"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An opportunity is a favorable chance. Here, destroyed records created a chance to claim U.S. birth, which could help with immigration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Paper son documents were cheap and easy to get B. Becoming a paper son required great financial sacrifice from families C. The government paid for paper son documents D. Only rich families could become paper sons","excerpt":"\"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip. It often took several years of hard work to repay the debt.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Paper son documents were cheap and easy to get","B":"Becoming a paper son required great financial sacrifice from families","C":"The government paid for paper son documents","D":"Only rich families could become paper sons"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt emphasizes the high cost, borrowing money, and years of work to repay. This shows the significant sacrifice families made.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip. It often took several years of hard work to repay the debt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q015","read_aloud":"What was the effect of the Chinese Exclusion Act on how some Chinese families tried to immigrate? A. It stopped all Chinese immigration forever B. It led some families to use the paper son system as a workaround C. It made immigration faster and easier for everyone D. It encouraged families to stay in China","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so. So each time a member of those groups returned to China for a visit, they often reported the birth of a son or two...\"","stem":"What was the effect of the Chinese Exclusion Act on how some Chinese families tried to immigrate?","choices":{"A":"It stopped all Chinese immigration forever","B":"It led some families to use the paper son system as a workaround","C":"It made immigration faster and easier for everyone","D":"It encouraged families to stay in China"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Because laborers were banned but citizens/merchants could bring family, some created paper son claims to use that exception. This was a direct response to the Act\u0027s restrictions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so. So each time a member of those groups returned to China for a visit, they often reported the birth of a son or two...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q016","read_aloud":"What is the correct order of these events in Louie\u0027s immigration? A. Allowed entry → detained → interrogated → arrived B. Arrived → detained → interrogated → allowed entry C. Interrogated → arrived → detained → allowed entry D. Detained → arrived → allowed entry → interrogated","excerpt":"\"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station... He had traveled alone... At Angel Island, officials detained Share Kim. They interrogated him... Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America.\"","stem":"What is the correct order of these events in Louie\u0027s immigration?","choices":{"A":"Allowed entry → detained → interrogated → arrived","B":"Arrived → detained → interrogated → allowed entry","C":"Interrogated → arrived → detained → allowed entry","D":"Detained → arrived → allowed entry → interrogated"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text sequence is: Louie arrived at Angel Island, then was detained, then interrogated, and finally allowed entry after officials were satisfied.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station... He had traveled alone... At Angel Island, officials detained Share Kim. They interrogated him... Once satisfied with the answers, Share Kim was allowed entry to America.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q017","read_aloud":"What event in 1906 helped create the paper son system? A. A new law was passed B. An earthquake and fire destroyed birth records in San Francisco C. A ship sank in the harbor D. A new immigration station opened","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records.\"","stem":"What event in 1906 helped create the paper son system?","choices":{"A":"A new law was passed","B":"An earthquake and fire destroyed birth records in San Francisco","C":"A ship sank in the harbor","D":"A new immigration station opened"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states that the 1906 earthquake and fire destroyed the Hall of Records, which included birth records. This allowed some to claim U.S. birth without proof.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q018","read_aloud":"Why was it so important for Share Kim and his wife to give the same answers? A. To make the questioning go faster B. Because inconsistent answers could lead to deportation, so matching stories were essential for approval C. Because officials only asked one question D. To impress the officials with their memory skills","excerpt":"\"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning.\"","stem":"Why was it so important for Share Kim and his wife to give the same answers?","choices":{"A":"To make the questioning go faster","B":"Because inconsistent answers could lead to deportation, so matching stories were essential for approval","C":"Because officials only asked one question","D":"To impress the officials with their memory skills"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that wrong answers could lead to deportation. If husband and wife gave different answers about family or village details, officials might suspect fraud and deny entry.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q019","read_aloud":"Based on this quote, what does Louie\u0027s childhood experience teach us about the legacy of the paper son system? A. Children were not affected by their parents\u0027 immigration status B. The fear and secrecy surrounding paper son status could affect children and shape family life for years C. All children knew about the paper son system openly D. The system had no long-term effects on families","excerpt":"\"Louie adds, \u0027I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\u0027\"","stem":"Based on this quote, what does Louie\u0027s childhood experience teach us about the legacy of the paper son system?","choices":{"A":"Children were not affected by their parents\u0027 immigration status","B":"The fear and secrecy surrounding paper son status could affect children and shape family life for years","C":"All children knew about the paper son system openly","D":"The system had no long-term effects on families"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Louie had to keep a family secret from childhood due to fear of deportation. This shows how the paper son system created lasting anxiety and shaped how families lived and communicated across generations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie adds, \u0027I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q020","read_aloud":"If you were to create a poster encouraging empathy for immigrants like Louie Share Kim, which message would best reflect the selection\u0027s themes? A. \"Immigration is easy and quick for everyone\" B. \"Behind every immigrant is a story of hope, sacrifice, and the courage to seek a better life\" C. \"All immigrants have the same experience\" D. \"Immigration laws have always been fair\"","excerpt":"\"What motivates people to leave a place they call home?\"","stem":"If you were to create a poster encouraging empathy for immigrants like Louie Share Kim, which message would best reflect the selection\u0027s themes?","choices":{"A":"\"Immigration is easy and quick for everyone\"","B":"\"Behind every immigrant is a story of hope, sacrifice, and the courage to seek a better life\"","C":"\"All immigrants have the same experience\"","D":"\"Immigration laws have always been fair\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The selection shows Louie\u0027s family sacrificing money, enduring separation, and taking risks for hope of opportunity. This message captures those themes of hope, sacrifice, and courage, encouraging empathy. Section A - Text Information Title: The Path to Paper Son and Louie Share Kim, Paper SonAuthors: Grant Din and Barbara D. Krasner","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"What motivates people to leave a place they call home?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q021","read_aloud":"What is a U.S. citizen? A. A person visiting from another country B. A person who belongs legally to the United States C. A person who works on a ship D. A person who has lost their papers","excerpt":"Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China.","stem":"What is a U.S. citizen?","choices":{"A":"A person visiting from another country","B":"A person who belongs legally to the United States","C":"A person who works on a ship","D":"A person who has lost their papers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A citizen is a legal member of a country.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Only diplomats, merchants, students, teachers, visitors, and those claiming U.S. citizenship were able to enter from China."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q022","read_aloud":"Which word means the opposite of \"opportunity\"? A. Chance B. Loss of chance C. Help D. Gift","excerpt":"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.","stem":"Which word means the opposite of \"opportunity\"?","choices":{"A":"Chance","B":"Loss of chance","C":"Help","D":"Gift"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An opportunity is a good chance. The opposite is no chance or a missed chance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q023","read_aloud":"What happens during immigration \"processing\"? A. Immigrants cook food. B. Officials question and check immigrants. C. Immigrants take a vacation. D. Officials give money to immigrants.","excerpt":"The coaching book provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.","stem":"What happens during immigration \"processing\"?","choices":{"A":"Immigrants cook food.","B":"Officials question and check immigrants.","C":"Immigrants take a vacation.","D":"Officials give money to immigrants."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Processing is the series of steps officials use to question and check people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The coaching book provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q024","read_aloud":"Why was Share Jung able to claim a paper son? A. He was a U.S. citizen. B. He was very rich. C. He owned a restaurant. D. He was a teacher.","excerpt":"Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America. Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China.","stem":"Why was Share Jung able to claim a paper son?","choices":{"A":"He was a U.S. citizen.","B":"He was very rich.","C":"He owned a restaurant.","D":"He was a teacher."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The law allowed U.S. citizens to claim sons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Share Kim became a \u0027paper son\u0027 of Louie Share Jung in America. Share Jung was a U.S. citizen born in San Francisco who frequently traveled to China."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q025","read_aloud":"What could happen if a family member gave a wrong answer? A. They would get a prize. B. They would be sent back to China. C. They would become citizens. D. They would get a coaching book.","excerpt":"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.","stem":"What could happen if a family member gave a wrong answer?","choices":{"A":"They would get a prize.","B":"They would be sent back to China.","C":"They would become citizens.","D":"They would get a coaching book."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Deportation means being sent back to your home country.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Any wrong answers could lead to deportation."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q026","read_aloud":"How long was the transcript of Louie\u0027s mother and siblings\u0027 interrogation? A. 10 pages B. 24 pages C. 42 pages D. 100 pages","excerpt":"The transcript was 42 singlespaced typed pages.","stem":"How long was the transcript of Louie\u0027s mother and siblings\u0027 interrogation?","choices":{"A":"10 pages","B":"24 pages","C":"42 pages","D":"100 pages"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says 42 singlespaced typed pages.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The transcript was 42 singlespaced typed pages."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q027","read_aloud":"Was it reasonable for Louie\u0027s family to keep this secret? Why? A. Yes, because deportation was a real danger. B. No, because secrets are always bad. C. Yes, because no one cared. D. No, because the law had changed.","excerpt":"Louie says, \u0027I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\u0027","stem":"Was it reasonable for Louie\u0027s family to keep this secret? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because deportation was a real danger.","B":"No, because secrets are always bad.","C":"Yes, because no one cared.","D":"No, because the law had changed."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says he feared deportation, which was a real and serious risk.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Louie says, \u0027I knew as a child growing up that I was never to reveal to others that my father was a paper son for fear that we might all get deported.\u0027"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q028","read_aloud":"What would be the most important change to make it fair? A. Stop all immigration from everywhere. B. Allow families to come together without lying. C. Charge a very high fee to enter. D. Make everyone become a paper son.","excerpt":"The whole selection.Imagine you could write a new law to replace the Chinese Exclusion Act.","stem":"What would be the most important change to make it fair?","choices":{"A":"Stop all immigration from everywhere.","B":"Allow families to come together without lying.","C":"Charge a very high fee to enter.","D":"Make everyone become a paper son."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The problem in the texts is families were separated. A fair law would let families stay together. Section A - Text information Title: The Path to Paper Son and Louie Share Kim, Paper Son Author: Grant Din and Barbara D. Krasner","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole selection.Imagine you could write a new law to replace the Chinese Exclusion Act."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q029","read_aloud":"In the text, who were the \"citizens\"? A. people who worked for the government B. people who belonged to the United States C. people who lived in China D. people who traveled on ships","excerpt":"\"But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so. So each time a member of those groups returned to China for a visit, they often reported the birth of a son or two to the immigration authorities when they came back.\"","stem":"In the text, who were the \"citizens\"?","choices":{"A":"people who worked for the government","B":"people who belonged to the United States","C":"people who lived in China","D":"people who traveled on ships"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Citizens are people who belong to a particular place. In this text, U.S. citizens were people who belonged to the United States.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so. So each time a member of those groups returned to China for a visit, they often reported the birth of a son or two to the immigration authorities when they came back.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q030","read_aloud":"What does \"opportunity\" mean in this excerpt? A. a chance to do something they could not do before B. a kind of food C. a dangerous storm D. a type of document","excerpt":"\"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\"","stem":"What does \"opportunity\" mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"a chance to do something they could not do before","B":"a kind of food","C":"a dangerous storm","D":"a type of document"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"With records destroyed, Chinese people saw a chance to claim they were born in San Francisco. This was an opportunity they did not have before.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q031","read_aloud":"What is \"immigration processing\"? A. making food for immigrants B. the steps officials take when people enter a country C. building houses for immigrants D. teaching immigrants to read","excerpt":"\"The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers. When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.\"","stem":"What is \"immigration processing\"?","choices":{"A":"making food for immigrants","B":"the steps officials take when people enter a country","C":"building houses for immigrants","D":"teaching immigrants to read"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Immigration processing refers to the steps and questions officials use when people try to enter a country. The coaching book helped paper sons prepare.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The paper son\u0027s job was to memorize the answers. When a \u0027paper son\u0027 bought an identity, he also purchased a coaching book or notes that provided both the questions and answers that might be asked during immigration processing.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q032","read_aloud":"What happened first in Share Kim\u0027s journey? A. He was interrogated at Angel Island. B. He traveled across the Pacific Ocean for nearly a month. C. He received his Certificate of Identity. D. He married a woman in China.","excerpt":"\"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916. He had traveled alone on a journey that took nearly a month to cross the Pacific Ocean.\"","stem":"What happened first in Share Kim\u0027s journey?","choices":{"A":"He was interrogated at Angel Island.","B":"He traveled across the Pacific Ocean for nearly a month.","C":"He received his Certificate of Identity.","D":"He married a woman in China."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Share Kim traveled across the Pacific Ocean first. After that, he arrived at Angel Island and was interrogated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Fourteen-year-old Louie Share Kim arrived at the Angel Island Immigration Station from Guangdong Province, China, in 1916. He had traveled alone on a journey that took nearly a month to cross the Pacific Ocean.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q033","read_aloud":"Why did officials ask about the village\u0027s layout? A. Because they wanted to visit the village. B. Because they wanted to test if Share Kim and Share Jung really knew each other. C. Because they needed directions. D. Because they were writing a book about China.","excerpt":"\"At Angel Island, officials detained Share Kim. They interrogated him and Share Jung. They asked question after question about their family history and their village\u0027s layout.\"","stem":"Why did officials ask about the village\u0027s layout?","choices":{"A":"Because they wanted to visit the village.","B":"Because they wanted to test if Share Kim and Share Jung really knew each other.","C":"Because they needed directions.","D":"Because they were writing a book about China."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If Share Kim was really Share Jung\u0027s son, they would both know details about their village. Asking about the layout tested if their stories matched.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At Angel Island, officials detained Share Kim. They interrogated him and Share Jung. They asked question after question about their family history and their village\u0027s layout.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q034","read_aloud":"Why did families borrow money? A. to buy food B. to pay for paper son documents C. to build houses D. to buy ships","excerpt":"\"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip. It often took several years of hard work to repay the debt.\"","stem":"Why did families borrow money?","choices":{"A":"to buy food","B":"to pay for paper son documents","C":"to build houses","D":"to buy ships"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says paper son documents cost thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money so a child could make the trip to America.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Paper son documents were worth thousands of dollars. Families borrowed money to make it possible for a child to make the trip. It often took several years of hard work to repay the debt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q035","read_aloud":"Why did the coaching book need so much information? A. Because officials asked many detailed questions. B. Because the family wanted to write a history book. C. Because the book was very expensive. D. Because Share Kim liked to read.","excerpt":"\"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning. The coaching book contained information about names and birth dates of all family members, the location of the home village and its environment, dates of Share Kim\u0027s travels to China, and more.\"","stem":"Why did the coaching book need so much information?","choices":{"A":"Because officials asked many detailed questions.","B":"Because the family wanted to write a history book.","C":"Because the book was very expensive.","D":"Because Share Kim liked to read."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says officials asked many questions about family history, village layout, and travel dates. The coaching book needed all this information so answers would match.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He put together a book for his wife so they could coordinate their stories and make certain that they gave the same answers during questioning. The coaching book contained information about names and birth dates of all family members, the location of the home village and its environment, dates of Share Kim\u0027s travels to China, and more.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q036","read_aloud":"What can you conclude about many Chinese immigrant families? A. They talked openly about their experiences all the time. B. They kept their immigration experiences private, possibly because of pain. C. They forgot their experiences immediately. D. They did not have any difficult experiences.","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027\"","stem":"What can you conclude about many Chinese immigrant families?","choices":{"A":"They talked openly about their experiences all the time.","B":"They kept their immigration experiences private, possibly because of pain.","C":"They forgot their experiences immediately.","D":"They did not have any difficult experiences."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Louie says many parents never talked about their experiences. He thinks the experiences were painful. This suggests families kept these stories private because they were hard to remember.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027Many of my friends and relatives said their parents never talked about their immigration experience either. I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q037","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q038","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q039","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. A dangerous place B. A chance to do something C. A way to ask for help D. A sad event","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"A dangerous place","B":"A chance to do something","C":"A way to ask for help","D":"A sad event"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, an opportunity is a chance or situation that allows someone to achieve a goal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q040","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They believe the system was perfect B. They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese C. They think the government was doing a good job D. They think everyone was treated the same","excerpt":"\"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They believe the system was perfect","B":"They believe the system was unfair to the Chinese","C":"They think the government was doing a good job","D":"They think everyone was treated the same"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By quoting this, the author shows that racial bias made the immigration process unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Louie says, \u0027The witnesses had to be white because Chinese were not trusted.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. To make sure they knew the local language B. To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation C. To learn how to get a job in America D. To help their children study for school","excerpt":"\"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"To make sure they knew the local language","B":"To ensure their stories matched and avoid deportation","C":"To learn how to get a job in America","D":"To help their children study for school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Knowing the exact facts that matched the \"father\u0027s\" story was the only way to pass the check.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Any wrong answers could lead to deportation.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q042","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Because it is fun to read about history B. Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives C. Because it shows that the government was always right D. Because it does not matter what happened in the past","excerpt":"\"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Because it is fun to read about history","B":"Because it helps us understand the challenges people faced to start new lives","C":"Because it shows that the government was always right","D":"Because it does not matter what happened in the past"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Understanding history helps us see the struggles and sacrifices made by others, which is important for learning and respect Section A - Text Information Title: \"The Path to Paper Son\" by Grant Din and \"Louie Share Kim, Paper Son\" by Barbara D. Krasner Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 1, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My parents never talked to me about their immigration experience... I suspect those experiences were painful, something they would rather forget.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q043","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. people who visit a country for a short time B. people who belong to a place and have rights there C. people who work in government jobs D. people who travel between countries for business","excerpt":"\"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China. The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"people who visit a country for a short time","B":"people who belong to a place and have rights there","C":"people who work in government jobs","D":"people who travel between countries for business"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Citizens are people who belong to a country and have rights there. The text says U.S. citizens could send for families, but laborers could not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China. The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States. But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q044","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Chinese workers liked to travel alone B. Many Chinese workers left families in China when they came to America C. All Chinese workers were single men D. Families in China did not want to come to America","excerpt":"\"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Chinese workers liked to travel alone","B":"Many Chinese workers left families in China when they came to America","C":"All Chinese workers were single men","D":"Families in China did not want to come to America"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt tells us many Chinese workers were married and had children who stayed in China. This is the main point.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most of the Chinese workers who came to the United States in the mid-1800s were men. Half of them were married, with wives, and sometimes children, who had been left behind in China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q045","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. It helped Chinese families move to America B. It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing families to the U.S. C. It gave money to Chinese workers D. It made it easier for all Chinese people to immigrate","excerpt":"\"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"It helped Chinese families move to America","B":"It stopped Chinese laborers from bringing families to the U.S.","C":"It gave money to Chinese workers","D":"It made it easier for all Chinese people to immigrate"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says the Act \"prohibited\" or stopped Chinese laborers from sending for their families. That is the key detail.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Chinese Exclusion Act of 1882 prohibited Chinese laborers from sending for their families to join them in the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q046","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. Only teachers and students B. Merchants and U.S. citizens C. All Chinese workers D. Only people born in California","excerpt":"\"But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"Only teachers and students","B":"Merchants and U.S. citizens","C":"All Chinese workers","D":"Only people born in California"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to send for their families, but laborers were not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But merchants and U.S. citizens were allowed to do so.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q047","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. To get more money from the government B. To create immigration slots that could be used later C. To help build new schools in China D. To make their families happy","excerpt":"\"So each time a member of those groups returned to China for a visit, they often reported the birth of a son or two to the immigration authorities when they came back.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"To get more money from the government","B":"To create immigration slots that could be used later","C":"To help build new schools in China","D":"To make their families happy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that reporting births created \"immigration slots\" that could be used to bring another Chinese person to America.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"So each time a member of those groups returned to China for a visit, they often reported the birth of a son or two to the immigration authorities when they came back.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q048","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. New records were created right away B. The birth records were destroyed C. People stopped keeping records D. The records were moved to China","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"New records were created right away","B":"The birth records were destroyed","C":"People stopped keeping records","D":"The records were moved to China"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says the earthquake and fire \"destroyed\" the Hall of Records, which included birth records.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco, including the city\u0027s Hall of Records. With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q049","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. Chinese people claimed they were born in San Francisco B. The earthquake and fire destroyed birth records C. Immigration slots were created D. Families borrowed money for the trip","excerpt":"\"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco... With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"Chinese people claimed they were born in San Francisco","B":"The earthquake and fire destroyed birth records","C":"Immigration slots were created","D":"Families borrowed money for the trip"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The earthquake and fire happened first, which destroyed the records. Then people used that as an opportunity to make claims.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1906, a major earthquake and fire destroyed much of San Francisco... With the city\u0027s birth records destroyed, some Chinese saw an opportunity. They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w1-path-to-paper-son-std-q050","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. They had never been to San Francisco B. They were born in San Francisco and had family in China C. They wanted to go back to China D. They did not have any children","excerpt":"\"They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"They had never been to San Francisco","B":"They were born in San Francisco and had family in China","C":"They wanted to go back to China","D":"They did not have any children"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states they claimed birth in San Francisco and having a wife and sons in China.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They claimed that they had been born in San Francisco and that they had a wife and so many sons in China.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond","grade":5,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":1,"week":2,"title":"Life on Earth-and Beyond","author":"Pamela S. Turner","genre":"Informational Text","essential_question":"How do living things survive in extreme places?","weekly_question":"What can scientists learn from life in Earth\u0027s harsh environments?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["microbes","microorganisms","remote","Antarctic","survive"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"Life on Earth-and Beyond. What can scientists learn from life in Earth\u0027s harsh environments?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"microbes\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options: A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"What does the word \"microbes\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q002","read_aloud":"According to the text, what happens to the sun in the Dry Valleys during the winter? Options: A. It shines 24 hours a day, B. It disappears for many months, C. It provides extra warmth, D. It stays low in the sky all day","excerpt":"\"In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September. For months the Dry Valleys are locked in frozen darkness.\"","stem":"According to the text, what happens to the sun in the Dry Valleys during the winter? Options:","choices":{"A":"It shines 24 hours a day,","B":"It disappears for many months,","C":"It provides extra warmth,","D":"It stays low in the sky all day"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states that \"the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September,\" meaning it is gone for months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September. For months the Dry Valleys are locked in frozen darkness.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q003","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? Options: A. Chris loves to travel to warm places, B. It is easy to travel to Antarctica, C. Reaching the remote Dry Valleys was a difficult journey, D. The Antarctic summer is the coldest time of year","excerpt":"\"Chris set off to visit the Dry Valleys in January 2005, during the Antarctic summer. Just getting to such a remote spot was an adventure.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? Options:","choices":{"A":"Chris loves to travel to warm places,","B":"It is easy to travel to Antarctica,","C":"Reaching the remote Dry Valleys was a difficult journey,","D":"The Antarctic summer is the coldest time of year"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The paragraph focuses on the effort and \"adventure\" required just to arrive at the research site.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris set off to visit the Dry Valleys in January 2005, during the Antarctic summer. Just getting to such a remote spot was an adventure.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q004","read_aloud":"Where did the scientists sleep while at the camp? Options: A. In a science tent, B. In a metal hut, C. In the \"suburbs\" (sleeping tents), D. In the kitchen tent","excerpt":"\"The camp was a little \u0027tent city.\u0027 There was a science tent, a kitchen tent, a toilet tent, and the \u0027suburbs\u0027 (the sleeping tents).\"","stem":"Where did the scientists sleep while at the camp? Options:","choices":{"A":"In a science tent,","B":"In a metal hut,","C":"In the \"suburbs\" (sleeping tents),","D":"In the kitchen tent"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly labels the \"suburbs\" as the \"sleeping tents.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The camp was a little \u0027tent city.\u0027 There was a science tent, a kitchen tent, a toilet tent, and the \u0027suburbs\u0027 (the sleeping tents).\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q005","read_aloud":"Why didn\u0027t the scientists need to worry about food rotting? Options: A. The food was stored in a freezer, B. The air was very cold and dry, C. They ate all the food immediately, D. They brought only canned food","excerpt":"\"The scientists just wiped everything with paper towels and let the dishes freeze. Nothing rotted or spoiled in the cold, dry air.\"","stem":"Why didn\u0027t the scientists need to worry about food rotting? Options:","choices":{"A":"The food was stored in a freezer,","B":"The air was very cold and dry,","C":"They ate all the food immediately,","D":"They brought only canned food"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that nothing spoiled because of the \"cold, dry air.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The scientists just wiped everything with paper towels and let the dishes freeze. Nothing rotted or spoiled in the cold, dry air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"astrobiologists\" most likely mean? A. scientists who study stars and planets only B. scientists who study life in the universe C. scientists who build robots for space D. scientists who study weather on Earth","excerpt":"\"astrobiologists scientists who study life in the universe\"","stem":"What does the word \"astrobiologists\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"scientists who study stars and planets only","B":"scientists who study life in the universe","C":"scientists who build robots for space","D":"scientists who study weather on Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines astrobiologists as \"scientists who study life in the universe.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"astrobiologists scientists who study life in the universe\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Antarctica is covered with thick ice everywhere B. The Dry Valleys are bare, ice-free areas in Antarctica C. The Dry Valleys are full of plants and animals D. Antarctica is the warmest place on Earth","excerpt":"\"At the very bottom of the globe, in a land of ice and snow, there are great curving valleys of bare earth: Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Antarctica is covered with thick ice everywhere","B":"The Dry Valleys are bare, ice-free areas in Antarctica","C":"The Dry Valleys are full of plants and animals","D":"Antarctica is the warmest place on Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt tells us the Dry Valleys are \"valleys of bare earth\" in Antarctica. This is the key detail.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the very bottom of the globe, in a land of ice and snow, there are great curving valleys of bare earth: Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q008","read_aloud":"According to this excerpt, what happens in the Dry Valleys during winter? A. The sun shines all day and night B. It is dark for many months C. It rains every day D. The temperature stays warm","excerpt":"\"In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September.\"","stem":"According to this excerpt, what happens in the Dry Valleys during winter?","choices":{"A":"The sun shines all day and night","B":"It is dark for many months","C":"It rains every day","D":"The temperature stays warm"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the sun \"doesn\u0027t come up again until September,\" meaning it is dark for months in winter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q009","read_aloud":"What does the author compare the Dry Valleys to? A. a busy city B. outer space C. a tropical beach D. a mountain forest","excerpt":"\"The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space.\"","stem":"What does the author compare the Dry Valleys to?","choices":{"A":"a busy city","B":"outer space","C":"a tropical beach","D":"a mountain forest"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states the Dry Valleys are \"almost as lonely as outer space.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q010","read_aloud":"Why are astrobiologists interested in the Dry Valleys? A. Because they are warm and wet like Earth B. Because they are similar to Mars, helping scientists study possible life on other planets C. Because they have many tourists D. Because they are easy to reach","excerpt":"\"Yet the Dry Valleys fascinate astrobiologists like Chris McKay. \u0027The Dry Valleys are like Mars,\u0027 explains Chris. \u0027Both are cold and dry.\u0027\"","stem":"Why are astrobiologists interested in the Dry Valleys?","choices":{"A":"Because they are warm and wet like Earth","B":"Because they are similar to Mars, helping scientists study possible life on other planets","C":"Because they have many tourists","D":"Because they are easy to reach"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris McKay says the Dry Valleys are \"like Mars\" because both are cold and dry. This helps scientists learn about life that might exist on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Yet the Dry Valleys fascinate astrobiologists like Chris McKay. \u0027The Dry Valleys are like Mars,\u0027 explains Chris. \u0027Both are cold and dry.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"astrobiologists\" most likely mean? A. Scientists who study stars only B. Scientists who study life in the universe C. Scientists who study rocks D. Scientists who study weather","excerpt":"The Dry Valleys fascinate astrobiologists like Chris McKay.","stem":"What does \"astrobiologists\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"Scientists who study stars only","B":"Scientists who study life in the universe","C":"Scientists who study rocks","D":"Scientists who study weather"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says astrobiologists study life in the universe. The word \"astro\" means space, and \"biologists\" means life scientists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Dry Valleys fascinate astrobiologists like Chris McKay."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of these sentences? A. The Dry Valleys are beautiful. B. The Dry Valleys are a harsh place. C. Many people live in the Dry Valleys. D. The Dry Valleys are hot.","excerpt":"At the very bottom of the globe, in a land of ice and snow, there are great curving valleys of bare earth: Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys. It\u0027s a harsh place.","stem":"What is the main idea of these sentences?","choices":{"A":"The Dry Valleys are beautiful.","B":"The Dry Valleys are a harsh place.","C":"Many people live in the Dry Valleys.","D":"The Dry Valleys are hot."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it is a harsh place with ice, snow, and frozen darkness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: At the very bottom of the globe, in a land of ice and snow, there are great curving valleys of bare earth: Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys. It\u0027s a harsh place."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q013","read_aloud":"How long is the sun gone during Antarctic winter? A. One week B. One month C. About six months D. One year","excerpt":"In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September.","stem":"How long is the sun gone during Antarctic winter?","choices":{"A":"One week","B":"One month","C":"About six months","D":"One year"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"From April to September is about six months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q014","read_aloud":"What season was it in Antarctica when Chris visited? A. Winter B. Spring C. Summer D. Fall","excerpt":"Chris set off to visit the Dry Valleys in January 2005, during the Antarctic summer.","stem":"What season was it in Antarctica when Chris visited?","choices":{"A":"Winter","B":"Spring","C":"Summer","D":"Fall"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says \"during the Antarctic summer.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Chris set off to visit the Dry Valleys in January 2005, during the Antarctic summer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q015","read_aloud":"Is there life on other planets? What is an astrobiologist? A. a person who studies stars in the sky B. a scientist who studies life in the universe C. a doctor who helps sick animals D. a person who drives rovers on Mars","excerpt":"\"As an astrobiologist, Dr. Chris McKay studies life in the universe to answer an important","stem":"Is there life on other planets? What is an astrobiologist?","choices":{"A":"a person who studies stars in the sky","B":"a scientist who studies life in the universe","C":"a doctor who helps sick animals","D":"a person who drives rovers on Mars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says an astrobiologist studies life in the universe. Chris McKay is an astrobiologist who looks for life on other planets.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As an astrobiologist, Dr. Chris McKay studies life in the universe to answer an important"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q016","read_aloud":"How long is the sun down in the Dry Valleys during winter? A. one month B. three months C. about six months D. one year","excerpt":"\"In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September.\"","stem":"How long is the sun down in the Dry Valleys during winter?","choices":{"A":"one month","B":"three months","C":"about six months","D":"one year"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The sun goes down in April and doesn\u0027t come up until September. From April to September is about six months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q017","read_aloud":"Why does the author say the Dry Valleys are \"almost as lonely as outer space\"? A. Because there are many people there. B. Because there isn\u0027t a single weed or tiny insect. C. Because it is very noisy. D. Because there are many animals.","excerpt":"\"The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space.\"","stem":"Why does the author say the Dry Valleys are \"almost as lonely as outer space\"?","choices":{"A":"Because there are many people there.","B":"Because there isn\u0027t a single weed or tiny insect.","C":"Because it is very noisy.","D":"Because there are many animals."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says there isn\u0027t a single weed or tiny insect. This means nothing lives there, so it is lonely like outer space.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q018","read_aloud":"When did Chris visit the Dry Valleys? A. in April 2005 B. in January 2005 C. in September 2005 D. in December 2004","excerpt":"\"Chris set off to visit the Dry Valleys in January 2005, during the Antarctic summer.\"","stem":"When did Chris visit the Dry Valleys?","choices":{"A":"in April 2005","B":"in January 2005","C":"in September 2005","D":"in December 2004"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that Chris set off to visit the Dry Valleys in January 2005 during the Antarctic summer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris set off to visit the Dry Valleys in January 2005, during the Antarctic summer.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q019","read_aloud":"What does the word \"colony\" mean in this sentence? Options:? A. A type of rock, B. A group living together, C. A giant cave, D. A scientific tool","excerpt":"\"Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface.\"","stem":"What does the word \"colony\" mean in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"A type of rock,","B":"A group living together,","C":"A giant cave,","D":"A scientific tool"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines colony in the sidebar as \"a group of animals living in one place,\" which fits the context of microbes living together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q020","read_aloud":"What did Chris do right before he examined the sandstone cliffs? Options:? A. Ate breakfast, B. Drilled tiny holes, C. Attached sensors, D. Went to sleep","excerpt":"\"After breakfast Chris headed to the nearby sandstone cliffs. He examined the sandstone carefully.\"","stem":"What did Chris do right before he examined the sandstone cliffs? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Ate breakfast,","B":"Drilled tiny holes,","C":"Attached sensors,","D":"Went to sleep"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that \"After breakfast Chris headed to the nearby sandstone cliffs,\" indicating the breakfast happened first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After breakfast Chris headed to the nearby sandstone cliffs. He examined the sandstone carefully.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q021","read_aloud":"Why would life on Mars need to be under rock or soil? Options:? A. To stay warm, B. To find water, C. To hide from radiation, D. To find food","excerpt":"\"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun. If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\"","stem":"Why would life on Mars need to be under rock or soil? Options:?","choices":{"A":"To stay warm,","B":"To find water,","C":"To hide from radiation,","D":"To find food"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that the atmosphere is thin, so life must be \"shielded from solar radiation\" by rock or soil.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun. If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q022","read_aloud":"What are the two types of microbes mentioned in the rock? Options:? A. Grass and weeds, B. Cyanobacteria and fungi, C. Bacteria and viruses, D. Insects and plants","excerpt":"\"Chris chipped off another rock sample. Just under the rock\u0027s surface was a thin green line-a minute \u0027forest\u0027 of microbes (cyanobacteria and fungi).\"","stem":"What are the two types of microbes mentioned in the rock? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Grass and weeds,","B":"Cyanobacteria and fungi,","C":"Bacteria and viruses,","D":"Insects and plants"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly identifies the green line as \"cyanobacteria and fungi\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris chipped off another rock sample. Just under the rock\u0027s surface was a thin green line-a minute \u0027forest\u0027 of microbes (cyanobacteria and fungi).\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q023","read_aloud":"According to the text, what do microbes need to \"wake up\"? Options:? A. Sunlight and moisture, B. A loud sound, C. Dark caves, D. New soil","excerpt":"\"They \u0027wake up\u0027 for a few days in the summer, when the sun is shining and a little moisture seeps down through the pores in the rock.\"","stem":"According to the text, what do microbes need to \"wake up\"? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Sunlight and moisture,","B":"A loud sound,","C":"Dark caves,","D":"New soil"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains they wake up when the \"sun is shining\" and \"moisture seeps down\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They \u0027wake up\u0027 for a few days in the summer, when the sun is shining and a little moisture seeps down through the pores in the rock.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q024","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is the best definition of \"rovers\"? Options:? A. Small creatures, B. Vehicles used to explore, C. Types of rock, D. Devices that detect light","excerpt":"\"NASA uses remote-controlled rovers to explore the surface of planets and search for evidence of liquid water.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what is the best definition of \"rovers\"? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Small creatures,","B":"Vehicles used to explore,","C":"Types of rock,","D":"Devices that detect light"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers in the sidebar as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"NASA uses remote-controlled rovers to explore the surface of planets and search for evidence of liquid water.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l01-q025","read_aloud":"Where did the rover named Spirit go? Options:? A. Meridiani Planum, B. Gusev Crater, C. The Dry Valleys, D. Antarctica","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\"","stem":"Where did the rover named Spirit go? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Meridiani Planum,","B":"Gusev Crater,","C":"The Dry Valleys,","D":"Antarctica"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that \"Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"colony\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. A type of rock, B. A group living together, C. A giant cave, D. A scientific tool","excerpt":"\"Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface.\"","stem":"What does the word \"colony\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"A type of rock,","B":"A group living together,","C":"A giant cave,","D":"A scientific tool"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines colony in the sidebar as \"a group of animals living in one place,\" which fits the context of microbes living together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q002","read_aloud":"What did Chris do right before he examined the sandstone cliffs? Options: A. Ate breakfast, B. Drilled tiny holes, C. Attached sensors, D. Went to sleep","excerpt":"\"After breakfast Chris headed to the nearby sandstone cliffs. He examined the sandstone carefully.\"","stem":"What did Chris do right before he examined the sandstone cliffs? Options:","choices":{"A":"Ate breakfast,","B":"Drilled tiny holes,","C":"Attached sensors,","D":"Went to sleep"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that \"After breakfast Chris headed to the nearby sandstone cliffs,\" indicating the breakfast happened first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After breakfast Chris headed to the nearby sandstone cliffs. He examined the sandstone carefully.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q003","read_aloud":"Why would life on Mars need to be under rock or soil? Options: A. To stay warm, B. To find water, C. To hide from radiation, D. To find food","excerpt":"\"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun. If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\"","stem":"Why would life on Mars need to be under rock or soil? Options:","choices":{"A":"To stay warm,","B":"To find water,","C":"To hide from radiation,","D":"To find food"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that the atmosphere is thin, so life must be \"shielded from solar radiation\" by rock or soil.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun. If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q004","read_aloud":"What are the two types of microbes mentioned in the rock? Options: A. Grass and weeds, B. Cyanobacteria and fungi, C. Bacteria and viruses, D. Insects and plants","excerpt":"\"Chris chipped off another rock sample. Just under the rock\u0027s surface was a thin green line-a minute \u0027forest\u0027 of microbes (cyanobacteria and fungi).\"","stem":"What are the two types of microbes mentioned in the rock? Options:","choices":{"A":"Grass and weeds,","B":"Cyanobacteria and fungi,","C":"Bacteria and viruses,","D":"Insects and plants"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly identifies the green line as \"cyanobacteria and fungi\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris chipped off another rock sample. Just under the rock\u0027s surface was a thin green line-a minute \u0027forest\u0027 of microbes (cyanobacteria and fungi).\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q005","read_aloud":"According to the text, what do microbes need to \"wake up\"? Options: A. Sunlight and moisture, B. A loud sound, C. Dark caves, D. New soil","excerpt":"\"They \u0027wake up\u0027 for a few days in the summer, when the sun is shining and a little moisture seeps down through the pores in the rock.\"","stem":"According to the text, what do microbes need to \"wake up\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Sunlight and moisture,","B":"A loud sound,","C":"Dark caves,","D":"New soil"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains they wake up when the \"sun is shining\" and \"moisture seeps down\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They \u0027wake up\u0027 for a few days in the summer, when the sun is shining and a little moisture seeps down through the pores in the rock.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q006","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"microbes\"? A. large animals B. tiny living things C. types of rocks D. space machines","excerpt":"\"microbes the smallest living things\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"microbes\"?","choices":{"A":"large animals","B":"tiny living things","C":"types of rocks","D":"space machines"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines microbes as \"the smallest living things.\" Option b matches this meaning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"microbes the smallest living things\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Rocks are always solid with no spaces B. Tiny microbes can live in small spaces inside rocks C. Microbes cannot live in cold places D. Rocks are too hard for any life to survive","excerpt":"\"Many rocks are honeycombed with little spaces, or pores, that seem like huge caverns to super-small creatures called microbes.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Rocks are always solid with no spaces","B":"Tiny microbes can live in small spaces inside rocks","C":"Microbes cannot live in cold places","D":"Rocks are too hard for any life to survive"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt explains that rocks have small spaces where tiny microbes can live. This is the key point.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many rocks are honeycombed with little spaces, or pores, that seem like huge caverns to super-small creatures called microbes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q008","read_aloud":"What did Chris find on the sandstone cliffs? A. A large animal hiding in a cave B. A colony of microbes living under the rock\u0027s surface C. A map of Mars drawn on the rock D. A new type of plant growing on the rock","excerpt":"\"After breakfast Chris headed to the nearby sandstone cliffs. He examined the sandstone carefully. Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface.\"","stem":"What did Chris find on the sandstone cliffs?","choices":{"A":"A large animal hiding in a cave","B":"A colony of microbes living under the rock\u0027s surface","C":"A map of Mars drawn on the rock","D":"A new type of plant growing on the rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Chris \"spotted little blotches\" and found \"a colony of microbes\" living under the rock\u0027s surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After breakfast Chris headed to the nearby sandstone cliffs. He examined the sandstone carefully. Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q009","read_aloud":"How can scientists see microbes? A. With their eyes alone B. With a telescope C. With a microscope D. With a camera","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"How can scientists see microbes?","choices":{"A":"With their eyes alone","B":"With a telescope","C":"With a microscope","D":"With a camera"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The excerpt states microbes \"can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\" This is the direct answer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q010","read_aloud":"How do the microbes in the rocks survive? A. By eating large amounts of food every day B. By using small amounts of sunlight and melted snow C. By traveling to warmer places in winter D. By sleeping all year long","excerpt":"\"Chris\u0027s sensors showed that the microbes hidden in the rocks survived on tidbits of summer sunlight and a few drops of snowmelt.\"","stem":"How do the microbes in the rocks survive?","choices":{"A":"By eating large amounts of food every day","B":"By using small amounts of sunlight and melted snow","C":"By traveling to warmer places in winter","D":"By sleeping all year long"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the microbes survived on \"tidbits of summer sunlight and a few drops of snowmelt.\" This shows they need very little to live.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris\u0027s sensors showed that the microbes hidden in the rocks survived on tidbits of summer sunlight and a few drops of snowmelt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q011","read_aloud":"What are \"microbes\"? A. Large animals B. Tiny living things C. Rock pieces D. Spaceships","excerpt":"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things.","stem":"What are \"microbes\"?","choices":{"A":"Large animals","B":"Tiny living things","C":"Rock pieces","D":"Spaceships"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they are the tiniest of all living things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q012","read_aloud":"What kind of plane did Chris take from New Zealand to Antarctica? A. A passenger jet B. A small private plane C. An Air Force cargo plane D. A helicopter","excerpt":"To reach the Dry Valleys, Chris flew from San Francisco, California, to New Zealand. In New Zealand he boarded an Air Force cargo plane to McMurdo Station in Antarctica.","stem":"What kind of plane did Chris take from New Zealand to Antarctica?","choices":{"A":"A passenger jet","B":"A small private plane","C":"An Air Force cargo plane","D":"A helicopter"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says he boarded an Air Force cargo plane.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: To reach the Dry Valleys, Chris flew from San Francisco, California, to New Zealand. In New Zealand he boarded an Air Force cargo plane to McMurdo Station in Antarctica."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q013","read_aloud":"How long did the scientists stay on Battleship Promontory? A. One week B. Two weeks C. One month D. Two months","excerpt":"They landed atop a giant lump of sandstone called Battleship Promontory. It would be their home for the next two weeks.","stem":"How long did the scientists stay on Battleship Promontory?","choices":{"A":"One week","B":"Two weeks","C":"One month","D":"Two months"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"their home for the next two weeks.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: They landed atop a giant lump of sandstone called Battleship Promontory. It would be their home for the next two weeks."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What did Chris do first to reach the Dry Valleys? A. He boarded an Air Force cargo plane. B. He flew from San Francisco to New Zealand. C. He went to McMurdo Station. D. He took a helicopter to the Dry Valleys.","excerpt":"\"To reach the Dry Valleys, Chris flew from San Francisco, California, to New Zealand. In New Zealand he boarded an Air Force cargo plane to McMurdo Station in Antarctica.\"","stem":"What did Chris do first to reach the Dry Valleys?","choices":{"A":"He boarded an Air Force cargo plane.","B":"He flew from San Francisco to New Zealand.","C":"He went to McMurdo Station.","D":"He took a helicopter to the Dry Valleys."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Chris first flew from San Francisco to New Zealand. After that, he boarded the cargo plane.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To reach the Dry Valleys, Chris flew from San Francisco, California, to New Zealand. In New Zealand he boarded an Air Force cargo plane to McMurdo Station in Antarctica.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q015","read_aloud":"How are the Dry Valleys and Mars similar? A. Both are hot and wet. B. Both are cold and dry. C. Both have many plants and animals. D. Both are close to the sun.","excerpt":"\"\"The Dry Valleys are like Mars,\" explains Chris. \"Both are cold and dry. It hardly ever snows in the Dry Valleys, and when it does, the air is so cold that very little snow ever melts. Mars is even colder and drier.\"\"","stem":"How are the Dry Valleys and Mars similar?","choices":{"A":"Both are hot and wet.","B":"Both are cold and dry.","C":"Both have many plants and animals.","D":"Both are close to the sun."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris says the Dry Valleys are like Mars because both are cold and dry. This is what makes them similar.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"The Dry Valleys are like Mars,\" explains Chris. \"Both are cold and dry. It hardly ever snows in the Dry Valleys, and when it does, the air is so cold that very little snow ever melts. Mars is even colder and drier.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What was the cargo plane ride like? A. comfortable and quiet B. cramped, cold, and noisy C. short and easy D. warm and relaxing","excerpt":"\"The cargo plane had no reclining seats or meal service. No windows either. \u0027It was eight hours of being cramped and cold, and so noisy you had to wear earplugs,\u0027 Chris later recalled.\"","stem":"What was the cargo plane ride like?","choices":{"A":"comfortable and quiet","B":"cramped, cold, and noisy","C":"short and easy","D":"warm and relaxing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris described the ride as eight hours of being cramped and cold, and so noisy that earplugs were needed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The cargo plane had no reclining seats or meal service. No windows either. \u0027It was eight hours of being cramped and cold, and so noisy you had to wear earplugs,\u0027 Chris later recalled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q017","read_aloud":"What is Battleship Promontory? A. a type of helicopter B. a giant lump of sandstone where the scientists camped C. a city in Antarctica D. a kind of animal","excerpt":"\"After stuffing two helicopters with camping gear, equipment, food, and water, the scientists flew to the Dry Valleys. They landed atop a giant lump of sandstone called Battleship Promontory.\"","stem":"What is Battleship Promontory?","choices":{"A":"a type of helicopter","B":"a giant lump of sandstone where the scientists camped","C":"a city in Antarctica","D":"a kind of animal"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Battleship Promontory is a giant lump of sandstone where the scientists landed and camped for two weeks.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After stuffing two helicopters with camping gear, equipment, food, and water, the scientists flew to the Dry Valleys. They landed atop a giant lump of sandstone called Battleship Promontory.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q018","read_aloud":"What does the word \"microbes\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"What does the word \"microbes\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q019","read_aloud":"According to the text, what happens to the sun in the Dry Valleys during the winter? Options:? A. It shines 24 hours a day, B. It disappears for many months, C. It provides extra warmth, D. It stays low in the sky all day","excerpt":"\"In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September. For months the Dry Valleys are locked in frozen darkness.\"","stem":"According to the text, what happens to the sun in the Dry Valleys during the winter? Options:?","choices":{"A":"It shines 24 hours a day,","B":"It disappears for many months,","C":"It provides extra warmth,","D":"It stays low in the sky all day"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states that \"the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September,\" meaning it is gone for months.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September. For months the Dry Valleys are locked in frozen darkness.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q020","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? Options:? A. Chris loves to travel to warm places, B. It is easy to travel to Antarctica, C. Reaching the remote Dry Valleys was a difficult journey, D. The Antarctic summer is the coldest time of year","excerpt":"\"Chris set off to visit the Dry Valleys in January 2005, during the Antarctic summer. Just getting to such a remote spot was an adventure.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Chris loves to travel to warm places,","B":"It is easy to travel to Antarctica,","C":"Reaching the remote Dry Valleys was a difficult journey,","D":"The Antarctic summer is the coldest time of year"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The paragraph focuses on the effort and \"adventure\" required just to arrive at the research site.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris set off to visit the Dry Valleys in January 2005, during the Antarctic summer. Just getting to such a remote spot was an adventure.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q021","read_aloud":"Where did the scientists sleep while at the camp? Options:? A. In a science tent, B. In a metal hut, C. In the \"suburbs\" (sleeping tents), D. In the kitchen tent","excerpt":"\"The camp was a little \u0027tent city.\u0027 There was a science tent, a kitchen tent, a toilet tent, and the \u0027suburbs\u0027 (the sleeping tents).\"","stem":"Where did the scientists sleep while at the camp? Options:?","choices":{"A":"In a science tent,","B":"In a metal hut,","C":"In the \"suburbs\" (sleeping tents),","D":"In the kitchen tent"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly labels the \"suburbs\" as the \"sleeping tents.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The camp was a little \u0027tent city.\u0027 There was a science tent, a kitchen tent, a toilet tent, and the \u0027suburbs\u0027 (the sleeping tents).\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q022","read_aloud":"Why didn\u0027t the scientists need to worry about food rotting? Options:? A. The food was stored in a freezer, B. The air was very cold and dry, C. They ate all the food immediately, D. They brought only canned food","excerpt":"\"The scientists just wiped everything with paper towels and let the dishes freeze. Nothing rotted or spoiled in the cold, dry air.\"","stem":"Why didn\u0027t the scientists need to worry about food rotting? Options:?","choices":{"A":"The food was stored in a freezer,","B":"The air was very cold and dry,","C":"They ate all the food immediately,","D":"They brought only canned food"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that nothing spoiled because of the \"cold, dry air.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The scientists just wiped everything with paper towels and let the dishes freeze. Nothing rotted or spoiled in the cold, dry air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q023","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is the best definition of \"rovers\"? Options:? A. Small creatures, B. Vehicles used to explore, C. Types of rock, D. Devices that detect light","excerpt":"\"NASA uses remote-controlled rovers to explore the surface of planets and search for evidence of liquid water.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what is the best definition of \"rovers\"? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Small creatures,","B":"Vehicles used to explore,","C":"Types of rock,","D":"Devices that detect light"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers in the sidebar as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"NASA uses remote-controlled rovers to explore the surface of planets and search for evidence of liquid water.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q024","read_aloud":"Where did the rover named Spirit go? Options:? A. Meridiani Planum, B. Gusev Crater, C. The Dry Valleys, D. Antarctica","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\"","stem":"Where did the rover named Spirit go? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Meridiani Planum,","B":"Gusev Crater,","C":"The Dry Valleys,","D":"Antarctica"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that \"Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the Atacama research station? Options:? A. It is a very large city, B. It has plenty of local water, C. It is a very simple place, D. It is built inside a cave","excerpt":"\"The research station was just a desert shack that housed a kitchen and laboratory. Water was brought in by truck.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the Atacama research station? Options:?","choices":{"A":"It is a very large city,","B":"It has plenty of local water,","C":"It is a very simple place,","D":"It is built inside a cave"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes the station as \"just a desert shack\" and notes that water must be brought in by truck, implying it is not a modern, self-sufficient building.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The research station was just a desert shack that housed a kitchen and laboratory. Water was brought in by truck.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is the best definition of \"rovers\"? Options: A. Small creatures, B. Vehicles used to explore, C. Types of rock, D. Devices that detect light","excerpt":"\"NASA uses remote-controlled rovers to explore the surface of planets and search for evidence of liquid water.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what is the best definition of \"rovers\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Small creatures,","B":"Vehicles used to explore,","C":"Types of rock,","D":"Devices that detect light"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers in the sidebar as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"NASA uses remote-controlled rovers to explore the surface of planets and search for evidence of liquid water.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q002","read_aloud":"Where did the rover named Spirit go? Options: A. Meridiani Planum, B. Gusev Crater, C. The Dry Valleys, D. Antarctica","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\"","stem":"Where did the rover named Spirit go? Options:","choices":{"A":"Meridiani Planum,","B":"Gusev Crater,","C":"The Dry Valleys,","D":"Antarctica"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that \"Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the Atacama research station? Options: A. It is a very large city, B. It has plenty of local water, C. It is a very simple place, D. It is built inside a cave","excerpt":"\"The research station was just a desert shack that housed a kitchen and laboratory. Water was brought in by truck.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the Atacama research station? Options:","choices":{"A":"It is a very large city,","B":"It has plenty of local water,","C":"It is a very simple place,","D":"It is built inside a cave"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes the station as \"just a desert shack\" and notes that water must be brought in by truck, implying it is not a modern, self-sufficient building.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The research station was just a desert shack that housed a kitchen and laboratory. Water was brought in by truck.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q004","read_aloud":"What did Chris discover about rainfall in the Atacama during his first visit? Options: A. It rains every day, B. It is the driest place he found, C. It floods every year, D. It has the same weather as Antarctica","excerpt":"\"When Chris first visited the Atacama in 1994, he set up sensors to measure rainfall. For two years his sensors didn\u0027t record a single drop of rain.\"","stem":"What did Chris discover about rainfall in the Atacama during his first visit? Options:","choices":{"A":"It rains every day,","B":"It is the driest place he found,","C":"It floods every year,","D":"It has the same weather as Antarctica"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris records no rain for two years, leading him to conclude it is the \"driest place we\u0027ve found\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When Chris first visited the Atacama in 1994, he set up sensors to measure rainfall. For two years his sensors didn\u0027t record a single drop of rain.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q005","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare the Atacama to Mars? Options: A. They both have blue skies, B. They are both very wet, C. They are both extremely dry, D. They both have many people","excerpt":"\"If the sky over the Atacama were reddish instead of blue, the super-dry desert would look a lot like super-dry Mars.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare the Atacama to Mars? Options:","choices":{"A":"They both have blue skies,","B":"They are both very wet,","C":"They are both extremely dry,","D":"They both have many people"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author makes the comparison because both locations are \"super-dry\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If the sky over the Atacama were reddish instead of blue, the super-dry desert would look a lot like super-dry Mars.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what is the main job of \"sensors\"? A. To cook food for scientists B. To measure or detect things like light and moisture C. To carry heavy equipment D. To write reports about findings","excerpt":"\"sensors devices that detect changes in light, moisture, or other physical conditions\"","stem":"In this context, what is the main job of \"sensors\"?","choices":{"A":"To cook food for scientists","B":"To measure or detect things like light and moisture","C":"To carry heavy equipment","D":"To write reports about findings"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sensors as devices that \"detect changes in light, moisture, or other physical conditions.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"sensors devices that detect changes in light, moisture, or other physical conditions\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q007","read_aloud":"What did Chris discover under the rock\u0027s surface? A. A large animal nest B. A thin green line of tiny microbes C. A pool of liquid water D. A piece of ancient pottery","excerpt":"\"Chris chipped off another rock sample. Just under the rock\u0027s surface was a thin green line-a minute \u0027forest\u0027 of microbes (cyanobacteria and fungi).\"","stem":"What did Chris discover under the rock\u0027s surface?","choices":{"A":"A large animal nest","B":"A thin green line of tiny microbes","C":"A pool of liquid water","D":"A piece of ancient pottery"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes a \"thin green line\" that was a \"minute \u0027forest\u0027 of microbes.\" This is the key finding.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris chipped off another rock sample. Just under the rock\u0027s surface was a thin green line-a minute \u0027forest\u0027 of microbes (cyanobacteria and fungi).\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q008","read_aloud":"Chris later explained. \"Those little green critters are the best Martians we have. Why does Chris compare the microbes to \"Martians\"? A. Because they are green and small, like how people imagine aliens B. Because they came from Mars originally C. Because they can fly in space D. Because they speak to astronauts","excerpt":"If life exists on Mars, it might look something like that,","stem":"Chris later explained. \"Those little green critters are the best Martians we have. Why does Chris compare the microbes to \"Martians\"?","choices":{"A":"Because they are green and small, like how people imagine aliens","B":"Because they came from Mars originally","C":"Because they can fly in space","D":"Because they speak to astronauts"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Chris says the microbes are \"little and green,\" which matches common ideas about what Martians might look like. This helps readers connect Earth life to possible life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If life exists on Mars, it might look something like that,"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q009","read_aloud":"What problem does Mars\u0027 thin atmosphere cause? A. It makes the planet too warm for life B. It cannot block dangerous radiation from the sun C. It causes too much rain D. It makes the planet spin too fast","excerpt":"\"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun.\"","stem":"What problem does Mars\u0027 thin atmosphere cause?","choices":{"A":"It makes the planet too warm for life","B":"It cannot block dangerous radiation from the sun","C":"It causes too much rain","D":"It makes the planet spin too fast"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states that Mars\u0027 thin atmosphere cannot \"block dangerous radiation from the sun.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q010","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, where might life survive on Mars? A. On the open surface in bright sunlight B. Hidden under rocks or soil for protection C. Floating in the thin atmosphere D. Inside volcanoes only","excerpt":"\"If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, where might life survive on Mars?","choices":{"A":"On the open surface in bright sunlight","B":"Hidden under rocks or soil for protection","C":"Floating in the thin atmosphere","D":"Inside volcanoes only"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says life on Mars would need to be \"shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\" This suggests life would survive in protected, hidden places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What did Chris do first after waking up? A. He made pancakes. B. He got out of his sleeping bag. C. He flew a helicopter. D. He chipped a rock sample.","excerpt":"Early on his first morning in the Dry Valleys, sixfootsixinch Chris wormed his way out of his extralong sleeping bag. … Chris dressed quickly and made his way through the scientists\u0027 tent camp.","stem":"What did Chris do first after waking up?","choices":{"A":"He made pancakes.","B":"He got out of his sleeping bag.","C":"He flew a helicopter.","D":"He chipped a rock sample."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says he first wormed his way out of his sleeping bag.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Early on his first morning in the Dry Valleys, sixfootsixinch Chris wormed his way out of his extralong sleeping bag. … Chris dressed quickly and made his way through the scientists\u0027 tent camp."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q012","read_aloud":"Why was it still cold even though the sun was always up? A. The sun is farther away in summer. B. The sun\u0027s rays did not give much warmth. C. The scientists forgot their coats. D. The wind never blew.","excerpt":"The sun is up twentyfour hours a day during the Antarctic summer. However, the sun\u0027s rays didn\u0027t give off much warmth.","stem":"Why was it still cold even though the sun was always up?","choices":{"A":"The sun is farther away in summer.","B":"The sun\u0027s rays did not give much warmth.","C":"The scientists forgot their coats.","D":"The wind never blew."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly says the sun\u0027s rays did not give off much warmth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The sun is up twentyfour hours a day during the Antarctic summer. However, the sun\u0027s rays didn\u0027t give off much warmth."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q013","read_aloud":"Why did nothing rot or spoil? A. Because the scientists ate all the food B. Because it was cold and dry C. Because they used special soap D. Because they had a refrigerator","excerpt":"Cleaning up was easy. The scientists just wiped everything with paper towels and let the dishes freeze. Nothing rotted or spoiled in the cold, dry air.","stem":"Why did nothing rot or spoil?","choices":{"A":"Because the scientists ate all the food","B":"Because it was cold and dry","C":"Because they used special soap","D":"Because they had a refrigerator"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says nothing rotted or spoiled in the cold, dry air.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Cleaning up was easy. The scientists just wiped everything with paper towels and let the dishes freeze. Nothing rotted or spoiled in the cold, dry air."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q014","read_aloud":"Where were the microbes living? A. On top of the rock B. In pores just under the rock\u0027s surface C. In the snow D. Inside the scientists\u0027 tents","excerpt":"Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface.","stem":"Where were the microbes living?","choices":{"A":"On top of the rock","B":"In pores just under the rock\u0027s surface","C":"In the snow","D":"Inside the scientists\u0027 tents"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they were living in pores just under the surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q015","read_aloud":"What is a colony in this sentence? A. a country far away B. a group of animals living in one place C. a type of rock D. a scientific tool","excerpt":"\"Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface.\"","stem":"What is a colony in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a country far away","B":"a group of animals living in one place","C":"a type of rock","D":"a scientific tool"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says a colony of microbes was living in the rock. A colony is a group of animals or living things living in one place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. The scientists had a small camp with different tents for different purposes. B. The scientists lived in a real city. C. The camp had no tents at all. D. The scientists did not have any food.","excerpt":"\"The camp was a little \u0027tent city.\u0027 There was a science tent, a kitchen tent, a toilet tent, and the \u0027suburbs\u0027 (the sleeping tents). Solar panels powered the kitchen tent, fondly nicknamed Café Battleship.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The scientists had a small camp with different tents for different purposes.","B":"The scientists lived in a real city.","C":"The camp had no tents at all.","D":"The scientists did not have any food."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt describes the different tents in the camp: science tent, kitchen tent, toilet tent, and sleeping tents. The main idea is about the camp\u0027s setup.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The camp was a little \u0027tent city.\u0027 There was a science tent, a kitchen tent, a toilet tent, and the \u0027suburbs\u0027 (the sleeping tents). Solar panels powered the kitchen tent, fondly nicknamed Café Battleship.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q017","read_aloud":"Why was cleaning up easy for the scientists? A. Because they had many helpers. B. Because they just wiped dishes and let them freeze. C. Because they did not eat any food. D. Because the dishes were very small.","excerpt":"\"Cleaning up was easy. The scientists just wiped everything with paper towels and let the dishes freeze. Nothing rotted or spoiled in the cold, dry air.\"","stem":"Why was cleaning up easy for the scientists?","choices":{"A":"Because they had many helpers.","B":"Because they just wiped dishes and let them freeze.","C":"Because they did not eat any food.","D":"Because the dishes were very small."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the scientists wiped everything with paper towels and let the dishes freeze. Nothing rotted because of the cold, dry air.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Cleaning up was easy. The scientists just wiped everything with paper towels and let the dishes freeze. Nothing rotted or spoiled in the cold, dry air.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q018","read_aloud":"How do creatures in the Dry Valleys survive the bad weather? A. They live inside rock. B. They wear warm coats. C. They fly to warmer places. D. They build houses out of ice.","excerpt":"\"Chris has been making these camping trips to Antarctica for twenty-five years. He knows there are creatures hidden in the Dry Valleys that can survive some of the world\u0027s worst weather. Their secret? They live inside rock.\"","stem":"How do creatures in the Dry Valleys survive the bad weather?","choices":{"A":"They live inside rock.","B":"They wear warm coats.","C":"They fly to warmer places.","D":"They build houses out of ice."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says their secret is that they live inside rock. This protects them from the harsh weather.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris has been making these camping trips to Antarctica for twenty-five years. He knows there are creatures hidden in the Dry Valleys that can survive some of the world\u0027s worst weather. Their secret? They live inside rock.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q019","read_aloud":"What does the author mean when she says rock is \"honeycombed\"? A. The rock is made of honey. B. The rock has many little spaces or holes in it. C. The rock is very smooth. D. The rock is shaped like a comb.","excerpt":"\"\"Solid\" rock isn\u0027t always solid. Many rocks are honeycombed with little spaces, or pores, that seem like huge caverns to super-small creatures called microbes.\"","stem":"What does the author mean when she says rock is \"honeycombed\"?","choices":{"A":"The rock is made of honey.","B":"The rock has many little spaces or holes in it.","C":"The rock is very smooth.","D":"The rock is shaped like a comb."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that \"honeycombed\" means the rock has little spaces or pores. These spaces are like huge caverns to tiny microbes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Solid\" rock isn\u0027t always solid. Many rocks are honeycombed with little spaces, or pores, that seem like huge caverns to super-small creatures called microbes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They could build shelters for astronauts B. They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions C. They could grow food for the crew D. They could measure the distance to Earth","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They could build shelters for astronauts","B":"They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions","C":"They could grow food for the crew","D":"They could measure the distance to Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines may go on a NASA mission to a planet that \"seems too cold and too dry for life,\" like the Dry Valleys. This suggests they could help search for life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Scientists expect every test to succeed B. Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments C. Scientists only share results when everything works D. Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Scientists expect every test to succeed","B":"Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments","C":"Scientists only share results when everything works","D":"Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explains that science involves testing, and results can vary. This shows that scientists gain knowledge from both working and non-working experiments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l03-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To carry people on long trips on Earth B. To explore the surface of a planet C. To fly through space at high speed D. To measure the temperature of stars","excerpt":"\"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To carry people on long trips on Earth","B":"To explore the surface of a planet","C":"To fly through space at high speed","D":"To measure the temperature of stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"sensors\" mean in the context of this study? Options: A. Machines that record or detect conditions, B. Types of microbes, C. A way to categorize rocks, D. Tools for digging holes","excerpt":"\"The gas chromatograph sensed gases given off by microbes. The spectrometer looked for the kind of light absorbed by microbes.\"","stem":"What does the word \"sensors\" mean in the context of this study? Options:","choices":{"A":"Machines that record or detect conditions,","B":"Types of microbes,","C":"A way to categorize rocks,","D":"Tools for digging holes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines sensors in the sidebar as \"devices that detect changes in light, moisture, or other physical conditions\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The gas chromatograph sensed gases given off by microbes. The spectrometer looked for the kind of light absorbed by microbes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q002","read_aloud":"How does the author show that scientific research can be challenging? Options: A. By explaining that the sun shines all day, B. By describing how scientists eat pancakes, C. By noting that most of the machines failed to work, D. By stating that ink freezes in pens","excerpt":"\"But the gas chromatograph didn\u0027t work at all... Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought to Antarctica, only two, the spectrometer and one UV laser, were good at finding microbes.\"","stem":"How does the author show that scientific research can be challenging? Options:","choices":{"A":"By explaining that the sun shines all day,","B":"By describing how scientists eat pancakes,","C":"By noting that most of the machines failed to work,","D":"By stating that ink freezes in pens"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author uses the example of the machines failing to illustrate the difficulty of testing technology in harsh environments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But the gas chromatograph didn\u0027t work at all... Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought to Antarctica, only two, the spectrometer and one UV laser, were good at finding microbes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q003","read_aloud":"Why does Chris test his machines in the Dry Valleys? Options: A. To see if they can survive a flight, B. To practice using them in an environment like Mars, C. To prove that the machines are broken, D. To find more microbes to study at home","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that... seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"Why does Chris test his machines in the Dry Valleys? Options:","choices":{"A":"To see if they can survive a flight,","B":"To practice using them in an environment like Mars,","C":"To prove that the machines are broken,","D":"To find more microbes to study at home"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that Chris uses the Dry Valleys as a \"testing ground\" to prepare machines for similar conditions on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that... seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q004","read_aloud":"If a scientist\u0027s experiment fails, how would Chris McKay likely react based on this text? Options: A. He would give up on his mission, B. He would be angry at his teammates, C. He would use the failure to learn and try again, D. He would stop using machines entirely","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"If a scientist\u0027s experiment fails, how would Chris McKay likely react based on this text? Options:","choices":{"A":"He would give up on his mission,","B":"He would be angry at his teammates,","C":"He would use the failure to learn and try again,","D":"He would stop using machines entirely"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Chris states that \"science is all about testing,\" implying that failures are a natural part of the learning process.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q005","read_aloud":"How does the UV laser differ from the spectrometer? Options: A. It measures moisture instead of light, B. It looks for a \"glow\" rather than absorbed light, C. It only works in the dark, D. It is the only machine that worked","excerpt":"\"The UV laser sensed the \u0027glow\u0027 given off by microbes when the UV laser shone on them.\"","stem":"How does the UV laser differ from the spectrometer? Options:","choices":{"A":"It measures moisture instead of light,","B":"It looks for a \"glow\" rather than absorbed light,","C":"It only works in the dark,","D":"It is the only machine that worked"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines the spectrometer as looking for absorbed light, while the UV laser looks for a \"glow\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The UV laser sensed the \u0027glow\u0027 given off by microbes when the UV laser shone on them.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q006","read_aloud":"In this sentence, what does \"radiation\" most likely mean? A. A type of food that gives energy B. Invisible, harmful energy rays from the sun C. A machine that measures temperature D. A special kind of rock found on Mars","excerpt":"\"radiation dangerous energy rays that cannot be seen\"","stem":"In this sentence, what does \"radiation\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"A type of food that gives energy","B":"Invisible, harmful energy rays from the sun","C":"A machine that measures temperature","D":"A special kind of rock found on Mars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines radiation as \"dangerous energy rays that cannot be seen.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"radiation dangerous energy rays that cannot be seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q007","read_aloud":"Why did the scientists bring different machines to the Dry Valleys? A. To test which machine looks the most impressive B. To try different ways to detect hidden microbes C. To sell the machines to other scientists D. To use them as camping tools","excerpt":"\"The team brought a gas chromatograph, a spectrometer, and four types of ultraviolet (UV) lasers to test in the Dry Valleys. Each machine used a different technique for sensing hidden microbes.\"","stem":"Why did the scientists bring different machines to the Dry Valleys?","choices":{"A":"To test which machine looks the most impressive","B":"To try different ways to detect hidden microbes","C":"To sell the machines to other scientists","D":"To use them as camping tools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says each machine \"used a different technique for sensing hidden microbes.\" This shows they were testing multiple methods to find life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The team brought a gas chromatograph, a spectrometer, and four types of ultraviolet (UV) lasers to test in the Dry Valleys. Each machine used a different technique for sensing hidden microbes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q008","read_aloud":"What was the result of testing the machines in Antarctica? A. All six machines worked perfectly B. Only two machines were effective at finding microbes C. None of the machines worked at all D. The machines found large animals instead of microbes","excerpt":"\"Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought to Antarctica, only two, the spectrometer and one UV laser, were good at finding microbes.\"","stem":"What was the result of testing the machines in Antarctica?","choices":{"A":"All six machines worked perfectly","B":"Only two machines were effective at finding microbes","C":"None of the machines worked at all","D":"The machines found large animals instead of microbes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that \"only two\" of the six machines \"were good at finding microbes.\" This is the key result.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought to Antarctica, only two, the spectrometer and one UV laser, were good at finding microbes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q009","read_aloud":"How could the machines tested in Antarctica help a future Mars mission? A. They could build shelters for astronauts B. They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions C. They could grow food for the crew D. They could measure the distance to Earth","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"How could the machines tested in Antarctica help a future Mars mission?","choices":{"A":"They could build shelters for astronauts","B":"They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions","C":"They could grow food for the crew","D":"They could measure the distance to Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines may go on a NASA mission to a planet that \"seems too cold and too dry for life,\" like the Dry Valleys. This suggests they could help search for life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q010","read_aloud":"What does this statement tell us about how scientists work? A. Scientists expect every test to succeed B. Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments C. Scientists only share results when everything works D. Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"What does this statement tell us about how scientists work?","choices":{"A":"Scientists expect every test to succeed","B":"Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments","C":"Scientists only share results when everything works","D":"Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explains that science involves testing, and results can vary. This shows that scientists gain knowledge from both working and non-working experiments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What do \"sensors\" do? A. They drill holes. B. They detect changes like light and moisture. C. They cook food. D. They fly helicopters.","excerpt":"Chris had drilled tiny holes into the sandstone and attached sensors. The sensors measured the light and moisture inside the rocks yearround.","stem":"What do \"sensors\" do?","choices":{"A":"They drill holes.","B":"They detect changes like light and moisture.","C":"They cook food.","D":"They fly helicopters."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says sensors measured light and moisture.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Chris had drilled tiny holes into the sandstone and attached sensors. The sensors measured the light and moisture inside the rocks yearround."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q012","read_aloud":"How is Mars different from the Dry Valleys? A. Mars is warmer. B. Mars is even colder and drier. C. Mars has more snow. D. Mars has more microbes.","excerpt":"The Dry Valleys are like Mars,\u0027 explains Chris. \u0027Both are cold and dry. It hardly ever snows in the Dry Valleys… Mars is even colder and drier.\u0027","stem":"How is Mars different from the Dry Valleys?","choices":{"A":"Mars is warmer.","B":"Mars is even colder and drier.","C":"Mars has more snow.","D":"Mars has more microbes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris says Mars is even colder and drier.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Dry Valleys are like Mars,\u0027 explains Chris. \u0027Both are cold and dry. It hardly ever snows in the Dry Valleys… Mars is even colder and drier.\u0027"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q013","read_aloud":"Why would Martian life need rock or soil? A. To find food B. To block dangerous radiation from the sun C. To build houses D. To trap water","excerpt":"If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.","stem":"Why would Martian life need rock or soil?","choices":{"A":"To find food","B":"To block dangerous radiation from the sun","C":"To build houses","D":"To trap water"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it needs to be shielded from solar radiation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q014","read_aloud":"If you were an astrobiologist, why might you test a machine in the Dry Valleys before sending it to Mars? A. Because it is hot there B. Because it is cold, dry, and similar to Mars C. Because many people live there D. Because it rains a lot there","excerpt":"Chris used the Dry Valleys as a testing ground for microbe detection machines.","stem":"If you were an astrobiologist, why might you test a machine in the Dry Valleys before sending it to Mars?","choices":{"A":"Because it is hot there","B":"Because it is cold, dry, and similar to Mars","C":"Because many people live there","D":"Because it rains a lot there"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The Dry Valleys are cold and dry like Mars, so they are a good testing place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Chris used the Dry Valleys as a testing ground for microbe detection machines."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q015","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about scientific exploration? A. Machines always work perfectly. B. Scientists sometimes fail, but they keep trying. C. Scientists never test their machines. D. Only one machine is ever used.","excerpt":"The team brought a gas chromatograph, a spectrometer, and four types of ultraviolet (UV) lasers … But the gas chromatograph didn\u0027t work at all, despite hours of tinkering.","stem":"What does this tell you about scientific exploration?","choices":{"A":"Machines always work perfectly.","B":"Scientists sometimes fail, but they keep trying.","C":"Scientists never test their machines.","D":"Only one machine is ever used."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that some machines failed, but Chris kept working.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The team brought a gas chromatograph, a spectrometer, and four types of ultraviolet (UV) lasers … But the gas chromatograph didn\u0027t work at all, despite hours of tinkering."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q016","read_aloud":"What do the microbes in the rocks need to survive? A. lots of rain and warm weather B. tidbits of summer sunlight and a few drops of snowmelt C. food from the scientists D. heat from the kitchen tent","excerpt":"\"Chris\u0027s sensors showed that the microbes hidden in the rocks survived on tidbits of summer sunlight and a few drops of snowmelt.\"","stem":"What do the microbes in the rocks need to survive?","choices":{"A":"lots of rain and warm weather","B":"tidbits of summer sunlight and a few drops of snowmelt","C":"food from the scientists","D":"heat from the kitchen tent"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sensors showed that the microbes survived on small amounts of summer sunlight and a few drops of melted snow.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris\u0027s sensors showed that the microbes hidden in the rocks survived on tidbits of summer sunlight and a few drops of snowmelt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q017","read_aloud":"Why does Chris think the microbes might be like Martians? A. Because they are green and from Mars. B. Because they can survive in cold, dry conditions like those on Mars. C. Because they have spaceships. D. Because they are very large.","excerpt":"\"\"If life exists on Mars, it might look something like that,\" Chris later explained. \"Those little green critters are the best Martians we have.\"\"","stem":"Why does Chris think the microbes might be like Martians?","choices":{"A":"Because they are green and from Mars.","B":"Because they can survive in cold, dry conditions like those on Mars.","C":"Because they have spaceships.","D":"Because they are very large."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the Dry Valleys are like Mars because both are cold and dry. The microbes survive in these harsh conditions, so similar life might exist on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"If life exists on Mars, it might look something like that,\" Chris later explained. \"Those little green critters are the best Martians we have.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q018","read_aloud":"Why would Martian life need to hide under rock or soil? A. Because there is no air on Mars. B. Because the sun\u0027s radiation is dangerous and the atmosphere is too thin to block it. C. Because rocks are pretty. D. Because there is too much water on Mars.","excerpt":"\"A shelter of rock or dirt would be very important for any Martian life. The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun. If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\"","stem":"Why would Martian life need to hide under rock or soil?","choices":{"A":"Because there is no air on Mars.","B":"Because the sun\u0027s radiation is dangerous and the atmosphere is too thin to block it.","C":"Because rocks are pretty.","D":"Because there is too much water on Mars."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation. Life would need rock or soil to shield itself from this radiation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A shelter of rock or dirt would be very important for any Martian life. The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun. If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q019","read_aloud":"What can you conclude about doing science in Antarctica? A. It is very easy and everything works perfectly. B. It is challenging because of the extreme cold. C. Scientists do not need any machines. D. The weather is always warm.","excerpt":"\"Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought to Antarctica, only two, the spectrometer and one UV laser, were good at finding microbes. Even recording test results was difficult. The ink froze in Chris\u0027s pen!\"","stem":"What can you conclude about doing science in Antarctica?","choices":{"A":"It is very easy and everything works perfectly.","B":"It is challenging because of the extreme cold.","C":"Scientists do not need any machines.","D":"The weather is always warm."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Four of the six machines did not work well, and even the ink in Chris\u0027s pen froze. These problems show that the extreme cold makes science work challenging.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought to Antarctica, only two, the spectrometer and one UV laser, were good at finding microbes. Even recording test results was difficult. The ink froze in Chris\u0027s pen!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They could build shelters for astronauts B. They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions C. They could grow food for the crew D. They could measure the distance to Earth","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They could build shelters for astronauts","B":"They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions","C":"They could grow food for the crew","D":"They could measure the distance to Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines may go on a NASA mission to a planet that \"seems too cold and too dry for life,\" like the Dry Valleys. This suggests they could help search for life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Scientists expect every test to succeed B. Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments C. Scientists only share results when everything works D. Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Scientists expect every test to succeed","B":"Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments","C":"Scientists only share results when everything works","D":"Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explains that science involves testing, and results can vary. This shows that scientists gain knowledge from both working and non-working experiments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l04-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To carry people on long trips on Earth B. To explore the surface of a planet C. To fly through space at high speed D. To measure the temperature of stars","excerpt":"\"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To carry people on long trips on Earth","B":"To explore the surface of a planet","C":"To fly through space at high speed","D":"To measure the temperature of stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"radiation\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. A type of weather, B. Dangerous energy rays, C. Gases in the air, D. Heat from a fire","excerpt":"\"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun.\"","stem":"What does the word \"radiation\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"A type of weather,","B":"Dangerous energy rays,","C":"Gases in the air,","D":"Heat from a fire"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines radiation in the sidebar as \"dangerous energy rays that cannot be seen\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q002","read_aloud":"Why do scientists believe microbial life is more common than complex life? Options: A. Because microbes live in machines, B. Because microbes evolve more quickly and easily, C. Because complex animals require too much water, D. Because microbes are easier to see","excerpt":"\"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve. As a result, microbial life should be far more common in the universe.\"","stem":"Why do scientists believe microbial life is more common than complex life? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because microbes live in machines,","B":"Because microbes evolve more quickly and easily,","C":"Because complex animals require too much water,","D":"Because microbes are easier to see"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text notes that complex animals take longer to evolve, making the simpler microbes more likely to exist elsewhere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve. As a result, microbial life should be far more common in the universe.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q003","read_aloud":"How does the author contrast \"bug-eyed guys\" with actual scientific expectations? Options: A. By suggesting that aliens are actually animals, B. By stating that only microbes can survive in space, C. By explaining that simple life is more likely than complex human-like life, D. By claiming that bug-eyed aliens are a myth","excerpt":"\"Scientists think that aliens on other planets are most likely to be microbes, not bug-eyed guys with flying saucers.\"","stem":"How does the author contrast \"bug-eyed guys\" with actual scientific expectations? Options:","choices":{"A":"By suggesting that aliens are actually animals,","B":"By stating that only microbes can survive in space,","C":"By explaining that simple life is more likely than complex human-like life,","D":"By claiming that bug-eyed aliens are a myth"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text argues that simple, hardy microbes are more common and better suited for harsh environments than complex life forms.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists think that aliens on other planets are most likely to be microbes, not bug-eyed guys with flying saucers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q004","read_aloud":"What does this statement tell us about the history of space exploration? Options: A. Earth is actually a dead planet, B. Early Mars tests might have missed signs of life, C. The Viking spacecraft was broken, D. The Atacama has no life at all","excerpt":"\"If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet.\"","stem":"What does this statement tell us about the history of space exploration? Options:","choices":{"A":"Earth is actually a dead planet,","B":"Early Mars tests might have missed signs of life,","C":"The Viking spacecraft was broken,","D":"The Atacama has no life at all"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"It suggests that if tests on Earth-which definitely has life-can miss it, then tests on Mars might have missed life there too.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q005","read_aloud":"Why might the scientists have been confused by their results in the Atacama? Options: A. Because some areas had life while others were completely dead, B. Because the microbes were larger than expected, C. Because the sensors showed it was raining, D. Because they found complex animals instead","excerpt":"\"The Atacama killed even those hardy microbes. The Atacama isn\u0027t entirely dead, though. Some of the Atacama soil Chris collected did have live microbes.\"","stem":"Why might the scientists have been confused by their results in the Atacama? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because some areas had life while others were completely dead,","B":"Because the microbes were larger than expected,","C":"Because the sensors showed it was raining,","D":"Because they found complex animals instead"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes the Atacama as having areas that kill even hardy microbes, while other areas do have life, which created a confusing discovery for the team.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Atacama killed even those hardy microbes. The Atacama isn\u0027t entirely dead, though. Some of the Atacama soil Chris collected did have live microbes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q006","read_aloud":"What is the main purpose of \"rovers\" according to this definition? A. To carry people on long trips on Earth B. To explore the surface of a planet C. To fly through space at high speed D. To measure the temperature of stars","excerpt":"\"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\"","stem":"What is the main purpose of \"rovers\" according to this definition?","choices":{"A":"To carry people on long trips on Earth","B":"To explore the surface of a planet","C":"To fly through space at high speed","D":"To measure the temperature of stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What did the rovers Spirit and Opportunity do on Mars? A. They built a base for human visitors B. They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface C. They took pictures of Earth from Mars D. They searched for other rovers that were lost","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\"","stem":"What did the rovers Spirit and Opportunity do on Mars?","choices":{"A":"They built a base for human visitors","B":"They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface","C":"They took pictures of Earth from Mars","D":"They searched for other rovers that were lost"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes Spirit exploring Gusev Crater and Opportunity exploring Meridiani Planum. This shows they explored different surface areas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q008","read_aloud":"Why is water important in the search for life on Mars? A. Water is needed for rockets to land safely B. Life as we know it needs liquid water to exist C. Water makes the soil easier to dig D. Water helps rovers move faster","excerpt":"\"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist. In searching for aliens, NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water.\"","stem":"Why is water important in the search for life on Mars?","choices":{"A":"Water is needed for rockets to land safely","B":"Life as we know it needs liquid water to exist","C":"Water makes the soil easier to dig","D":"Water helps rovers move faster"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states NASA\u0027s motto is \"Follow the Water\" when searching for life, and they wanted to know if Mars had \"enough liquid water for life to exist.\" This shows water is key for life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist. In searching for aliens, NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q009","read_aloud":"Why would scientists study a very dry place like the Atacama Desert? A. To prove that no life can exist anywhere without water B. To understand the limits of life and compare to dry places like Mars C. To find new sources of drinking water for Earth D. To test how fast plants can grow in dry soil","excerpt":"\"They weren\u0027t \u0027following the water.\u0027 They were looking for spots with as little water as possible.\"","stem":"Why would scientists study a very dry place like the Atacama Desert?","choices":{"A":"To prove that no life can exist anywhere without water","B":"To understand the limits of life and compare to dry places like Mars","C":"To find new sources of drinking water for Earth","D":"To test how fast plants can grow in dry soil"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The scientists studied the extremely dry Atacama to see where life can and cannot survive. This helps them understand what to expect on dry planets like Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They weren\u0027t \u0027following the water.\u0027 They were looking for spots with as little water as possible.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q010","read_aloud":"said Chris. What does this quote suggest about searching for life on other planets? A. It is easy to find life if you look in the right place B. A planet might have life, but tests could miss it if they look in the wrong spots C. Only Earth has life in the universe D. Spacecraft should never land in deserts","excerpt":"If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet,","stem":"said Chris. What does this quote suggest about searching for life on other planets?","choices":{"A":"It is easy to find life if you look in the right place","B":"A planet might have life, but tests could miss it if they look in the wrong spots","C":"Only Earth has life in the universe","D":"Spacecraft should never land in deserts"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris says that if a Mars lander tested only the driest parts of the Atacama, it might wrongly conclude Earth has no life. This shows that where you look matters when searching for life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet,"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What is \"radiation\"? A. Harmful energy rays that cannot be seen B. A type of food C. A kind of rock D. A cold wind","excerpt":"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun.","stem":"What is \"radiation\"?","choices":{"A":"Harmful energy rays that cannot be seen","B":"A type of food","C":"A kind of rock","D":"A cold wind"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says radiation is dangerous energy rays from the sun.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q012","read_aloud":"What can you infer about working in the Dry Valleys? A. It is easy and comfortable. B. The extreme cold makes work very hard. C. Scientists have heated offices. D. Machines always work better in cold.","excerpt":"Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought to Antarctica, only two … were good at finding microbes. Even recording test results was difficult. The ink froze in Chris\u0027s pen!","stem":"What can you infer about working in the Dry Valleys?","choices":{"A":"It is easy and comfortable.","B":"The extreme cold makes work very hard.","C":"Scientists have heated offices.","D":"Machines always work better in cold."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The ink froze, and most machines failed, showing the cold made work hard.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought to Antarctica, only two … were good at finding microbes. Even recording test results was difficult. The ink froze in Chris\u0027s pen!"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q013","read_aloud":"How did the UV laser detect microbes? A. By smelling them B. By sensing the glow given off by microbes C. By tasting the rock D. By listening for sounds","excerpt":"The spectrometer looked for the kind of light absorbed by microbes. The UV laser sensed the \u0027glow\u0027 given off by microbes when the UV laser shone on them.","stem":"How did the UV laser detect microbes?","choices":{"A":"By smelling them","B":"By sensing the glow given off by microbes","C":"By tasting the rock","D":"By listening for sounds"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it sensed the glow given off by microbes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The spectrometer looked for the kind of light absorbed by microbes. The UV laser sensed the \u0027glow\u0027 given off by microbes when the UV laser shone on them."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q014","read_aloud":"Based on this sentence, what might you do if you wanted to become an astrobiologist like Chris? A. Stop looking at the sky B. Become curious about space and study it C. Only read fiction books D. Move to a big city","excerpt":"Chris can\u0027t wait to find out. He\u0027s been wondering what\u0027s out there ever since he found a dusty old telescope and pointed it into the night sky.","stem":"Based on this sentence, what might you do if you wanted to become an astrobiologist like Chris?","choices":{"A":"Stop looking at the sky","B":"Become curious about space and study it","C":"Only read fiction books","D":"Move to a big city"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris became curious as a child by looking at the night sky.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Chris can\u0027t wait to find out. He\u0027s been wondering what\u0027s out there ever since he found a dusty old telescope and pointed it into the night sky."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q015","read_aloud":"What is radiation in this context? A. a type of food B. dangerous energy rays from the sun that cannot be seen C. a kind of rock D. a scientific tool","excerpt":"\"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun. If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\"","stem":"What is radiation in this context?","choices":{"A":"a type of food","B":"dangerous energy rays from the sun that cannot be seen","C":"a kind of rock","D":"a scientific tool"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes radiation as dangerous energy rays from the sun. These rays cannot be seen but can harm living things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun. If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about Chris\u0027s attitude toward science? A. He gets angry when things don\u0027t work. B. He understands that experiments don\u0027t always succeed, and that\u0027s part of science. C. He only likes science when everything is easy. D. He doesn\u0027t care about the results.","excerpt":"\"Chris was pleased that two machines worked. Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about Chris\u0027s attitude toward science?","choices":{"A":"He gets angry when things don\u0027t work.","B":"He understands that experiments don\u0027t always succeed, and that\u0027s part of science.","C":"He only likes science when everything is easy.","D":"He doesn\u0027t care about the results."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris was pleased that two machines worked even though four failed. He knows that science involves testing and sometimes things don\u0027t work out.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris was pleased that two machines worked. Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q017","read_aloud":"little green men\" might surprise us. Why might NASA send a spectrometer or UV laser to another planet? A. To take pictures of the landscape. B. To search for hidden microbes that might be living there. C. To build houses for astronauts. D. To melt ice on the planet.","excerpt":"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life. Yet","stem":"little green men\" might surprise us. Why might NASA send a spectrometer or UV laser to another planet?","choices":{"A":"To take pictures of the landscape.","B":"To search for hidden microbes that might be living there.","C":"To build houses for astronauts.","D":"To melt ice on the planet."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines were good at finding microbes. NASA might send them to search for life on cold, dry planets like Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life. Yet"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q018","read_aloud":"Why did NASA send rovers to Mars? A. To find out if Mars once had enough liquid water for life to exist. B. To bring rocks back to Earth for decoration. C. To build roads on Mars. D. To look for astronauts lost on Mars.","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum. NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist.\"","stem":"Why did NASA send rovers to Mars?","choices":{"A":"To find out if Mars once had enough liquid water for life to exist.","B":"To bring rocks back to Earth for decoration.","C":"To build roads on Mars.","D":"To look for astronauts lost on Mars."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text clearly states that NASA sent the rovers to find out if Mars once had enough liquid water for life to exist.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum. NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q020","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q021","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They could build shelters for astronauts B. They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions C. They could grow food for the crew D. They could measure the distance to Earth","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They could build shelters for astronauts","B":"They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions","C":"They could grow food for the crew","D":"They could measure the distance to Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines may go on a NASA mission to a planet that \"seems too cold and too dry for life,\" like the Dry Valleys. This suggests they could help search for life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Scientists expect every test to succeed B. Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments C. Scientists only share results when everything works D. Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Scientists expect every test to succeed","B":"Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments","C":"Scientists only share results when everything works","D":"Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explains that science involves testing, and results can vary. This shows that scientists gain knowledge from both working and non-working experiments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To carry people on long trips on Earth B. To explore the surface of a planet C. To fly through space at high speed D. To measure the temperature of stars","excerpt":"\"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To carry people on long trips on Earth","B":"To explore the surface of a planet","C":"To fly through space at high speed","D":"To measure the temperature of stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l05-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. They built a base for human visitors B. They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface C. They took pictures of Earth from Mars D. They searched for other rovers that were lost","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"They built a base for human visitors","B":"They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface","C":"They took pictures of Earth from Mars","D":"They searched for other rovers that were lost"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes Spirit exploring Gusev Crater and Opportunity exploring Meridiani Planum. This shows they explored different surface areas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"sensors\" mean in the context of this study? Options: A. Machines that record or detect conditions, B. Types of microbes, C. A way to categorize rocks, D. Tools for digging holes","excerpt":"\"A small pump hung from the balloon... The pump sucked a bit of air into a sealed dish.\"","stem":"What does the word \"sensors\" mean in the context of this study? Options:","choices":{"A":"Machines that record or detect conditions,","B":"Types of microbes,","C":"A way to categorize rocks,","D":"Tools for digging holes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines sensors in the sidebar as \"devices that detect changes in light, moisture, or other physical conditions\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A small pump hung from the balloon... The pump sucked a bit of air into a sealed dish.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q002","read_aloud":"What did Chris conclude about where microbes live in the Atacama? Options: A. They live everywhere in the desert, B. They are only carried by the wind from other places, C. They grow in the soil in less-dry areas, D. They prefer the driest spots because it is quieter","excerpt":"\"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the super-dry spots had no microbes at all.\"","stem":"What did Chris conclude about where microbes live in the Atacama? Options:","choices":{"A":"They live everywhere in the desert,","B":"They are only carried by the wind from other places,","C":"They grow in the soil in less-dry areas,","D":"They prefer the driest spots because it is quieter"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Chris observed that microbes were present in the air above less-dry dirt, suggesting they grow in the soil there and are blown into the air.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the super-dry spots had no microbes at all.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q003","read_aloud":"Why is finding liquid water so important to astrobiologists? Options: A. They need water to drink while camping, B. Microbes seem to require liquid water to survive, C. Water makes it easier to use the UV lasers, D. They want to prove Mars is a desert","excerpt":"\"At first I hoped I could find a microbe in the Atacama that was somehow adapted to life without liquid water... but it seems that where there is no liquid water, there is no life.\"","stem":"Why is finding liquid water so important to astrobiologists? Options:","choices":{"A":"They need water to drink while camping,","B":"Microbes seem to require liquid water to survive,","C":"Water makes it easier to use the UV lasers,","D":"They want to prove Mars is a desert"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Based on his tests, Chris concludes that \"where there is no liquid water, there is no life,\" highlighting water\u0027s necessity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At first I hoped I could find a microbe in the Atacama that was somehow adapted to life without liquid water... but it seems that where there is no liquid water, there is no life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q004","read_aloud":"How did Chris use the balloon to support his theory? Options: A. He used it to see if microbes were blowing in from other places, B. He used it to measure the temperature of the sky, C. He used it to find water hidden deep underground, D. He used it to prove that microbes fly like birds","excerpt":"\"The Atacama microbes weren\u0027t visitors carried by the wind. Chris thinks that in the less-dry parts of the Atacama, microbes grow in the soil.\"","stem":"How did Chris use the balloon to support his theory? Options:","choices":{"A":"He used it to see if microbes were blowing in from other places,","B":"He used it to measure the temperature of the sky,","C":"He used it to find water hidden deep underground,","D":"He used it to prove that microbes fly like birds"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"By sampling air in different areas, Chris could determine if the microbes were coming from elsewhere or living locally in the soil.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Atacama microbes weren\u0027t visitors carried by the wind. Chris thinks that in the less-dry parts of the Atacama, microbes grow in the soil.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q005","read_aloud":"Why does the history of water on Mars give scientists hope? Options: A. It means Mars is a good place to visit for vacation, B. It suggests there was enough time for life to have evolved, C. It means the rovers can stop searching, D. It proves that Mars is exactly like the Atacama","excerpt":"\"There may be no liquid water on Mars now, yet the Mars rovers Spirit and Opportunity proved that once upon a time Mars did have liquid water-lots of it.\"","stem":"Why does the history of water on Mars give scientists hope? Options:","choices":{"A":"It means Mars is a good place to visit for vacation,","B":"It suggests there was enough time for life to have evolved,","C":"It means the rovers can stop searching,","D":"It proves that Mars is exactly like the Atacama"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text notes that because Mars had water for hundreds of millions of years, that is \"enough time for life to have evolved\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There may be no liquid water on Mars now, yet the Mars rovers Spirit and Opportunity proved that once upon a time Mars did have liquid water-lots of it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q006","read_aloud":"In the context of microbes living in rocks, what does \"colony\" mean? A. A single microbe living alone B. A group of microbes living together in one spot C. A type of rock that microbes eat D. A machine that counts microbes","excerpt":"\"colony a group of animals living in one place\"","stem":"In the context of microbes living in rocks, what does \"colony\" mean?","choices":{"A":"A single microbe living alone","B":"A group of microbes living together in one spot","C":"A type of rock that microbes eat","D":"A machine that counts microbes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines colony as \"a group of animals living in one place.\" For microbes, this means a group living together, as described in the rock pores.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"colony a group of animals living in one place\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q007","read_aloud":"What pattern did Chris discover about microbes and dryness in the Atacama? A. More dryness meant more microbes in the air B. Less dryness meant microbes could live in soil and get into the air C. Microbes lived only in the wettest parts of the desert D. Dryness had no effect on where microbes were found","excerpt":"\"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the super-dry spots had no microbes at all.\"","stem":"What pattern did Chris discover about microbes and dryness in the Atacama?","choices":{"A":"More dryness meant more microbes in the air","B":"Less dryness meant microbes could live in soil and get into the air","C":"Microbes lived only in the wettest parts of the desert","D":"Dryness had no effect on where microbes were found"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows microbes were in the air over less dry areas but not over super-dry spots. This suggests microbes need at least a little moisture to survive and spread.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the super-dry spots had no microbes at all.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q008","read_aloud":"What conclusion can you draw from this excerpt? A. Life can survive anywhere if it tries hard enough B. Even on Earth, there are places too extreme for any life C. The Atacama is the only dry place on Earth D. Scientists should stop studying dry places","excerpt":"\"One thing is clear, however: in the very driest parts of the Atacama, nothing can survive. There does seem to be a limit to life on Earth.\"","stem":"What conclusion can you draw from this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Life can survive anywhere if it tries hard enough","B":"Even on Earth, there are places too extreme for any life","C":"The Atacama is the only dry place on Earth","D":"Scientists should stop studying dry places"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that in the driest parts of the Atacama, \"nothing can survive,\" showing there are limits to where life can exist, even on Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One thing is clear, however: in the very driest parts of the Atacama, nothing can survive. There does seem to be a limit to life on Earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q009","read_aloud":"How do these rover discoveries support the idea that life could have existed on Mars? A. They prove that humans once lived on Mars B. They show Mars once had liquid water, which is needed for life as we know it C. They found fossils of Martian animals D. They proved Mars is exactly like Earth today","excerpt":"\"Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a long-lost sea.\"","stem":"How do these rover discoveries support the idea that life could have existed on Mars?","choices":{"A":"They prove that humans once lived on Mars","B":"They show Mars once had liquid water, which is needed for life as we know it","C":"They found fossils of Martian animals","D":"They proved Mars is exactly like Earth today"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The rovers found evidence that Mars once had liquid water (\"soaked in water,\" \"long-lost sea\"). Since life needs water, this suggests life could have existed on Mars in the past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a long-lost sea.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q010","read_aloud":"Why is the length of time Mars had water important to scientists? A. It helps them plan how long a mission should last B. Evolution of life takes a long time, so hundreds of millions of years gives life a chance to develop C. It proves that Mars will have water again soon D. It shows that Mars is older than Earth","excerpt":"\"Scientists think Mars\u0027s surface had water for hundreds of millions of years. That\u0027s enough time for life to have evolved.\"","stem":"Why is the length of time Mars had water important to scientists?","choices":{"A":"It helps them plan how long a mission should last","B":"Evolution of life takes a long time, so hundreds of millions of years gives life a chance to develop","C":"It proves that Mars will have water again soon","D":"It shows that Mars is older than Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that life evolves over long periods. If Mars had water for \"hundreds of millions of years,\" that would be enough time for life to potentially develop, just as it did on Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists think Mars\u0027s surface had water for hundreds of millions of years. That\u0027s enough time for life to have evolved.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q011","read_aloud":"What is a \"rover\"? A. A person who walks slowly B. A vehicle used to explore a planet\u0027s surface C. A type of star D. A kind of rock","excerpt":"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist.","stem":"What is a \"rover\"?","choices":{"A":"A person who walks slowly","B":"A vehicle used to explore a planet\u0027s surface","C":"A type of star","D":"A kind of rock"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says rovers are vehicles that explore a planet\u0027s surface.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q012","read_aloud":"Why is water so important to NASA\u0027s search for life? A. Water is rare in the universe. B. Liquid water is needed for life as we know it. C. Water is easy to find. D. Water is not important for life.","excerpt":"NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water.","stem":"Why is water so important to NASA\u0027s search for life?","choices":{"A":"Water is rare in the universe.","B":"Liquid water is needed for life as we know it.","C":"Water is easy to find.","D":"Water is not important for life."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sidebar \"Water, the Host with the Most\" explains that water is needed for life\u0027s chemistry.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q013","read_aloud":"and \"Chris and several other scientists and students spent a day flying from San Francisco to Antofagasta, Chile.\"How is traveling to Mars different from traveling to the Atacama? A. Mars takes much longer to reach. B. The Atacama takes longer to reach. C. Both take the same time. D. Mars is closer than the Atacama.","excerpt":"It took Spirit and Opportunity seven months to get from Earth to Mars!","stem":"and \"Chris and several other scientists and students spent a day flying from San Francisco to Antofagasta, Chile.\"How is traveling to Mars different from traveling to the Atacama?","choices":{"A":"Mars takes much longer to reach.","B":"The Atacama takes longer to reach.","C":"Both take the same time.","D":"Mars is closer than the Atacama."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Mars took seven months; the Atacama took one day of flying plus driving.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: It took Spirit and Opportunity seven months to get from Earth to Mars!"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q014","read_aloud":"Why do scientists study the Atacama to learn about Mars? A. It has many cities. B. It is extremely dry and looks similar to Mars. C. It has oceans. D. It is very cold like Mars.","excerpt":"The Atacama is even drier than Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys. … if the sky over the Atacama were reddish instead of blue, the superdry desert would look a lot like superdry Mars.","stem":"Why do scientists study the Atacama to learn about Mars?","choices":{"A":"It has many cities.","B":"It is extremely dry and looks similar to Mars.","C":"It has oceans.","D":"It is very cold like Mars."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it is the driest place and would look like Mars if the sky were reddish.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Atacama is even drier than Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys. … if the sky over the Atacama were reddish instead of blue, the superdry desert would look a lot like superdry Mars."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q015","read_aloud":"said Chris.What does Chris mean by this? A. The Atacama has no life at all anywhere. B. Some parts of the Atacama have so little life that a test could miss it. C. Viking never worked correctly. D. Earth is actually a dead planet.","excerpt":"If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet,","stem":"said Chris.What does Chris mean by this?","choices":{"A":"The Atacama has no life at all anywhere.","B":"Some parts of the Atacama have so little life that a test could miss it.","C":"Viking never worked correctly.","D":"Earth is actually a dead planet."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that some Atacama areas seem dead, so a lander might wrongly think Earth has no life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet,"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q016","read_aloud":"What are rovers? A. people who drive cars B. vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface C. tools for cooking food D. types of plants","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\"","stem":"What are rovers?","choices":{"A":"people who drive cars","B":"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface","C":"tools for cooking food","D":"types of plants"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes rovers as robotic vehicles that landed on Mars and moved around the planet\u0027s surface to explore.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q017","read_aloud":"How was Chris\u0027s trip to the Atacama different from the rovers\u0027 trip to Mars? A. Both trips took the same amount of time. B. Chris\u0027s trip took one day, but the rovers\u0027 trip took seven months. C. The rovers flew on a cargo plane. D. Chris took seven months to get to the Atacama.","excerpt":"\"To get to the Atacama, Chris and several other scientists and students spent a day flying from San Francisco to Antofagasta, Chile. From Antofagasta they drove two hours through the desert to a research station. (It took Spirit and Opportunity seven months to get from Earth to Mars!)\"","stem":"How was Chris\u0027s trip to the Atacama different from the rovers\u0027 trip to Mars?","choices":{"A":"Both trips took the same amount of time.","B":"Chris\u0027s trip took one day, but the rovers\u0027 trip took seven months.","C":"The rovers flew on a cargo plane.","D":"Chris took seven months to get to the Atacama."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Chris spent a day flying to the Atacama. In contrast, it took the rovers seven months to get to Mars. The trips were very different in length.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To get to the Atacama, Chris and several other scientists and students spent a day flying from San Francisco to Antofagasta, Chile. From Antofagasta they drove two hours through the desert to a research station. (It took Spirit and Opportunity seven months to get from Earth to Mars!)\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q018","read_aloud":"What evidence shows that the Atacama is extremely dry? A. It rained every day. B. The sensors did not record a single drop of rain for two years. C. There were many rivers. D. The plants were very green.","excerpt":"\"When Chris first visited the Atacama in 1994, he set up sensors to measure rainfall. For two years his sensors didn\u0027t record a single drop of rain. Chris thought they were broken, but they weren\u0027t. The lack of water was good news. Chris had found the driest desert in the world.\"","stem":"What evidence shows that the Atacama is extremely dry?","choices":{"A":"It rained every day.","B":"The sensors did not record a single drop of rain for two years.","C":"There were many rivers.","D":"The plants were very green."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sensors didn\u0027t record any rain for two whole years. This is strong evidence that the Atacama is the driest desert in the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When Chris first visited the Atacama in 1994, he set up sensors to measure rainfall. For two years his sensors didn\u0027t record a single drop of rain. Chris thought they were broken, but they weren\u0027t. The lack of water was good news. Chris had found the driest desert in the world.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q019","read_aloud":"Why does Chris compare the Atacama to other deserts? A. To show that the Atacama is the driest of all. B. To show that all deserts are exactly the same. C. To show that the Gobi Desert is wetter than the Atacama. D. To show that he has never visited other deserts.","excerpt":"\"\"There are lots of places where people say it doesn\u0027t rain, like the Gobi Desert in Mongolia, or the Australian outback,\" explained Chris. \"But the Atacama is truly the driest place we\u0027ve found.\"\"","stem":"Why does Chris compare the Atacama to other deserts?","choices":{"A":"To show that the Atacama is the driest of all.","B":"To show that all deserts are exactly the same.","C":"To show that the Gobi Desert is wetter than the Atacama.","D":"To show that he has never visited other deserts."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Chris mentions other dry places but says the Atacama is \"truly the driest place we\u0027ve found.\" He compares them to show the Atacama is the driest.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"There are lots of places where people say it doesn\u0027t rain, like the Gobi Desert in Mongolia, or the Australian outback,\" explained Chris. \"But the Atacama is truly the driest place we\u0027ve found.\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q020","read_aloud":"What does Chris mean by this statement? A. The Atacama has so little life that a spacecraft test would not find any. B. The Viking spacecraft was broken. C. Earth is really a dead planet. D. The Atacama is full of life.","excerpt":"\"\"If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet,\" said Chris.\"","stem":"What does Chris mean by this statement?","choices":{"A":"The Atacama has so little life that a spacecraft test would not find any.","B":"The Viking spacecraft was broken.","C":"Earth is really a dead planet.","D":"The Atacama is full of life."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Chris means that the Atacama is so dry and has so little life that a spacecraft test would not detect any life. This shows how extreme the desert is.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet,\" said Chris.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They could build shelters for astronauts B. They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions C. They could grow food for the crew D. They could measure the distance to Earth","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They could build shelters for astronauts","B":"They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions","C":"They could grow food for the crew","D":"They could measure the distance to Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines may go on a NASA mission to a planet that \"seems too cold and too dry for life,\" like the Dry Valleys. This suggests they could help search for life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l06-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Scientists expect every test to succeed B. Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments C. Scientists only share results when everything works D. Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Scientists expect every test to succeed","B":"Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments","C":"Scientists only share results when everything works","D":"Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explains that science involves testing, and results can vary. This shows that scientists gain knowledge from both working and non-working experiments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q001","read_aloud":"Which word is a synonym for \"essential\" as used in this sentence? Options: A. Optional, B. Unnecessary, C. Necessary, D. Interesting","excerpt":"\"But liquid water is a remarkable substance. Water is the essential molecule in the chemistry of life on Earth.\"","stem":"Which word is a synonym for \"essential\" as used in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"Optional,","B":"Unnecessary,","C":"Necessary,","D":"Interesting"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"In the context of life\u0027s chemistry, \"essential\" means something that is required or absolutely necessary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But liquid water is a remarkable substance. Water is the essential molecule in the chemistry of life on Earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q002","read_aloud":"What does the author mean when calling water the \"host\" of the \"party of life\"? Options: A. Water is a guest who arrives late to the party, B. Water brings the ingredients of life together to interact, C. Water is the most boring part of the party, D. Water prevents the guests from ever meeting","excerpt":"\"Imagine that life is a big party, and the most important elements of life... are the guests. Water is the host.\"","stem":"What does the author mean when calling water the \"host\" of the \"party of life\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Water is a guest who arrives late to the party,","B":"Water brings the ingredients of life together to interact,","C":"Water is the most boring part of the party,","D":"Water prevents the guests from ever meeting"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sidebar explains that water \"gathers all the guests together and introduces them to each other\" so they can react and form life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Imagine that life is a big party, and the most important elements of life... are the guests. Water is the host.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q003","read_aloud":"Based on this information, why do scientists \"follow the water\" when looking for aliens? Options: A. Because they want to go swimming, B. Because they believe water is the main requirement for life to exist, C. Because it is the only thing their rovers can find, D. Because water is easy to photograph from space","excerpt":"\"Without water, the chemicals necessary for life couldn\u0027t find each other, mix with each other, and react with each other. Life would never happen.\"","stem":"Based on this information, why do scientists \"follow the water\" when looking for aliens? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they want to go swimming,","B":"Because they believe water is the main requirement for life to exist,","C":"Because it is the only thing their rovers can find,","D":"Because water is easy to photograph from space"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since water is the \"essential molecule\" for life\u0027s chemistry, scientists look for it as the first sign that life might exist somewhere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Without water, the chemicals necessary for life couldn\u0027t find each other, mix with each other, and react with each other. Life would never happen.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q004","read_aloud":"How does water help the \"guests\" at the \"party of life\"? Options: A. By keeping them at the right temperature and helping them mix, B. By hiding them from the sunlight, C. By turning them into gas, D. By forcing them to stay apart","excerpt":"\"Water makes sure everyone\u0027s comfy-neither too hot nor too cold. Without water, the chemicals... couldn\u0027t... react with each other.\"","stem":"How does water help the \"guests\" at the \"party of life\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"By keeping them at the right temperature and helping them mix,","B":"By hiding them from the sunlight,","C":"By turning them into gas,","D":"By forcing them to stay apart"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states water ensures the elements are \"comfy\" (not too hot or col d) and allows them to \"mix\" and \"react\" with each other.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water makes sure everyone\u0027s comfy-neither too hot nor too cold. Without water, the chemicals... couldn\u0027t... react with each other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q005","read_aloud":"Why does the author start the sidebar by saying we take water for granted? Options: A. To show that humans are very wasteful, B. To show that water is rare on Earth, C. To contrast our everyday experience with how important water actually is for life, D. To prove that we do not need water at all","excerpt":"\"Unless lost in a desert, we take water for granted. After all, it falls from the sky, and we flush it down the drain.\"","stem":"Why does the author start the sidebar by saying we take water for granted? Options:","choices":{"A":"To show that humans are very wasteful,","B":"To show that water is rare on Earth,","C":"To contrast our everyday experience with how important water actually is for life,","D":"To prove that we do not need water at all"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author acknowledges that because water is common for us, we ignore its amazing role as the \"essential molecule\" for all life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Unless lost in a desert, we take water for granted. After all, it falls from the sky, and we flush it down the drain.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"complex\" most likely mean? A. Very small and simple B. Made of many parts; more advanced C. Easy to understand D. Found only on Earth","excerpt":"\"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"complex\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"Very small and simple","B":"Made of many parts; more advanced","C":"Easy to understand","D":"Found only on Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text contrasts \"simple\" microbial life with \"complex animals,\" suggesting complex means more advanced or made of many parts. This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q007","read_aloud":"Excerpt from beginning: \"The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space. Excerpt from later: \"If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil. How do these two excerpts work together to support the main idea? A. They show that Mars and the Dry Valleys are both harsh places where life would need protection B. They prove that no life can exist in cold places C. They suggest that scientists should stop studying Mars D. They show that the Dry Valleys are warmer than Mars","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from beginning: \"The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space. Excerpt from later: \"If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil. How do these two excerpts work together to support the main idea?","choices":{"A":"They show that Mars and the Dry Valleys are both harsh places where life would need protection","B":"They prove that no life can exist in cold places","C":"They suggest that scientists should stop studying Mars","D":"They show that the Dry Valleys are warmer than Mars"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The first excerpt describes the Dry Valleys as empty and harsh. The second explains that life on Mars would need shelter. Together, they support the idea that extreme places on Earth help us understand where life might survive on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q008","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this sidebar excerpt? A. Water is important for cleaning and drinking B. Water allows the chemical reactions needed for life to occur C. Water is the most common substance in the universe D. Water is only important on Earth, not on other planets","excerpt":"\"Water is the essential molecule in the chemistry of life on Earth... Without water, the chemicals necessary for life couldn\u0027t find each other, mix with each other, and react with each other. Life would never happen.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this sidebar excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Water is important for cleaning and drinking","B":"Water allows the chemical reactions needed for life to occur","C":"Water is the most common substance in the universe","D":"Water is only important on Earth, not on other planets"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt explains that water helps life\u0027s chemicals \"find each other, mix... and react.\" This shows water is essential for the chemistry of life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water is the essential molecule in the chemistry of life on Earth... Without water, the chemicals necessary for life couldn\u0027t find each other, mix with each other, and react with each other. Life would never happen.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q009","read_aloud":"Why might an \"underground freezer\" on Mars be a good place to look for ancient life? A. Because cold temperatures can preserve evidence of life for a long time B. Because it would be easy for rovers to dig there C. Because it would be warm enough for life to grow today D. Because it would have more radiation than the surface","excerpt":"\"Chris thinks that evidence of early Martian life may be in a natural underground freezer on Mars. A natural underground freezer just like the one in Siberia.\"","stem":"Why might an \"underground freezer\" on Mars be a good place to look for ancient life?","choices":{"A":"Because cold temperatures can preserve evidence of life for a long time","B":"Because it would be easy for rovers to dig there","C":"Because it would be warm enough for life to grow today","D":"Because it would have more radiation than the surface"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The comparison to Siberia suggests that cold, frozen environments can preserve things for long periods. If Mars had an underground freezer, it might preserve signs of ancient life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris thinks that evidence of early Martian life may be in a natural underground freezer on Mars. A natural underground freezer just like the one in Siberia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q010","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, why might it be hard for scientists to define \"life\" when searching for aliens? A. Because all scientists agree on one definition B. Because some things, like viruses, have traits of life but not all, making the definition unclear C. Because aliens will not want to be studied D. Because definitions of life never change","excerpt":"\"So is a virus just a fancy bit of chemistry? Or is it possible for something to be half-alive? Scientists are still arguing over these questions. There\u0027s no easy answer. That\u0027s life!\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, why might it be hard for scientists to define \"life\" when searching for aliens?","choices":{"A":"Because all scientists agree on one definition","B":"Because some things, like viruses, have traits of life but not all, making the definition unclear","C":"Because aliens will not want to be studied","D":"Because definitions of life never change"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sidebar explains that viruses have some life traits (evolve, use energy) but not others (reproduce on their own). This shows that defining life is complex, which matters when looking for unfamiliar alien life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"So is a virus just a fancy bit of chemistry? Or is it possible for something to be half-alive? Scientists are still arguing over these questions. There\u0027s no easy answer. That\u0027s life!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"hardy\" mean in this sentence? A. Weak and easy to kill B. Tough and able to survive harsh conditions C. Very small D. Very large","excerpt":"The Atacama killed even those hardy microbes.","stem":"What does \"hardy\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Weak and easy to kill","B":"Tough and able to survive harsh conditions","C":"Very small","D":"Very large"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Hardy means strong and able to live in difficult places. These microbes lived in other dry places but died in the Atacama.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Atacama killed even those hardy microbes."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q012","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Chris\u0027s work in the Atacama? A. It was easy and relaxing. B. It was challenging because of difficult conditions. C. He never had any problems. D. The balloon worked perfectly.","excerpt":"To find out if the microbes fell from the sky, Chris needed to take samples of the air over the Atacama. … The balloon was hard to handle in the desert wind. It bounced around like a crazed pingpong ball.","stem":"What can you infer about Chris\u0027s work in the Atacama?","choices":{"A":"It was easy and relaxing.","B":"It was challenging because of difficult conditions.","C":"He never had any problems.","D":"The balloon worked perfectly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The balloon bounced wildly, showing that conditions were difficult.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: To find out if the microbes fell from the sky, Chris needed to take samples of the air over the Atacama. … The balloon was hard to handle in the desert wind. It bounced around like a crazed pingpong ball."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q013","read_aloud":"What did the balloon tests show? A. Microbes are everywhere in the Atacama. B. Superdry areas had no microbes in the air. C. All air samples had the same number of microbes. D. The balloon never worked.","excerpt":"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the superdry spots had no microbes at all.","stem":"What did the balloon tests show?","choices":{"A":"Microbes are everywhere in the Atacama.","B":"Superdry areas had no microbes in the air.","C":"All air samples had the same number of microbes.","D":"The balloon never worked."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says superdry spots had no microbes in the air.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the superdry spots had no microbes at all."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q014","read_aloud":"Why is the discovery of past water on Mars important for the search for life? A. Water is heavy and hard to move. B. Liquid water is needed for life as we know it. C. Water is only useful for drinking. D. Past water means there are oceans now.","excerpt":"There may be no liquid water on Mars now, yet the Mars rovers Spirit and Opportunity proved that once upon a time Mars did have liquid water-lots of it.","stem":"Why is the discovery of past water on Mars important for the search for life?","choices":{"A":"Water is heavy and hard to move.","B":"Liquid water is needed for life as we know it.","C":"Water is only useful for drinking.","D":"Past water means there are oceans now."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text and the sidebar \"Water, the Host with the Most\" show water is essential for life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: There may be no liquid water on Mars now, yet the Mars rovers Spirit and Opportunity proved that once upon a time Mars did have liquid water-lots of it."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q015","read_aloud":"If you were a scientist, where would you look for ancient Martian life based on Chris\u0027s idea? A. On the hot surface B. Underground in frozen places C. In the atmosphere D. In the center of Mars","excerpt":"Chris thinks that evidence of early Martian life may be in a natural underground freezer on Mars. A natural underground freezer just like the one in Siberia.","stem":"If you were a scientist, where would you look for ancient Martian life based on Chris\u0027s idea?","choices":{"A":"On the hot surface","B":"Underground in frozen places","C":"In the atmosphere","D":"In the center of Mars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris says evidence may be in a natural underground freezer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Chris thinks that evidence of early Martian life may be in a natural underground freezer on Mars. A natural underground freezer just like the one in Siberia."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q016","read_aloud":"How did Chris\u0027s weather sensors help him in the Atacama? A. They told him how much rain had fallen. B. They cooked his food. C. They flew his helicopter. D. They wrote his reports.","excerpt":"\"Soon after arriving Chris checked his weather sensors. It had rained a few weeks before. \u0027It was the biggest rain since 1994-about a fifth of an inch,\u0027 recalled Chris. \u0027For the Atacama, that\u0027s a flood!\u0027\"","stem":"How did Chris\u0027s weather sensors help him in the Atacama?","choices":{"A":"They told him how much rain had fallen.","B":"They cooked his food.","C":"They flew his helicopter.","D":"They wrote his reports."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Chris checked his weather sensors to find out about rainfall. The sensors helped him measure and record weather conditions in the desert.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Soon after arriving Chris checked his weather sensors. It had rained a few weeks before. \u0027It was the biggest rain since 1994-about a fifth of an inch,\u0027 recalled Chris. \u0027For the Atacama, that\u0027s a flood!\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q017","read_aloud":"What is Chris trying to find out with his air samples? A. If the microbes were blown in by wind or if they actually live in the soil. B. If the air is clean enough to breathe. C. If the wind is too strong for balloons. D. If the microbes can fly.","excerpt":"\"To find out if the microbes fell from the sky, Chris needed to take samples of the air over the Atacama. If the microbes were blown into the Atacama by the wind, the air would have about the same amount of microbes no matter where in the Atacama Chris took a sample.\"","stem":"What is Chris trying to find out with his air samples?","choices":{"A":"If the microbes were blown in by wind or if they actually live in the soil.","B":"If the air is clean enough to breathe.","C":"If the wind is too strong for balloons.","D":"If the microbes can fly."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Chris wanted to know if the microbes were just visitors blown by wind or if they actually grew in the Atacama soil. The air samples would help answer this question.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To find out if the microbes fell from the sky, Chris needed to take samples of the air over the Atacama. If the microbes were blown into the Atacama by the wind, the air would have about the same amount of microbes no matter where in the Atacama Chris took a sample.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q018","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Chris\u0027s balloon experiment? A. It was very easy to do. B. It was difficult because the wind was strong and unpredictable. C. The balloon was too small. D. Chris did not want to use the balloon.","excerpt":"\"Chris brought along a helium balloon. The balloon was hard to handle in the desert wind. It bounced around like a crazed ping-pong ball. \u0027It went every direction but up!\u0027 recalled Chris.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Chris\u0027s balloon experiment?","choices":{"A":"It was very easy to do.","B":"It was difficult because the wind was strong and unpredictable.","C":"The balloon was too small.","D":"Chris did not want to use the balloon."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The balloon bounced around like a \"crazed ping-pong ball\" and went \"every direction but up.\" This shows the wind was strong and made the experiment hard.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris brought along a helium balloon. The balloon was hard to handle in the desert wind. It bounced around like a crazed ping-pong ball. \u0027It went every direction but up!\u0027 recalled Chris.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q019","read_aloud":"What did the balloon tests show about the microbes in the Atacama? A. They were all carried by the wind from far away. B. They were not just visitors carried by wind; they actually lived in the less-dry soil. C. They could only live in the super-dry spots. D. They were all dead.","excerpt":"\"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the super-dry spots had no microbes at all. The balloon tests suggested that the Atacama microbes weren\u0027t visitors carried by the wind.\"","stem":"What did the balloon tests show about the microbes in the Atacama?","choices":{"A":"They were all carried by the wind from far away.","B":"They were not just visitors carried by wind; they actually lived in the less-dry soil.","C":"They could only live in the super-dry spots.","D":"They were all dead."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If the microbes were carried by wind, the air would have the same amount everywhere. But the super-dry spots had no microbes in the air. This suggests the microbes actually live in the less-dry soil.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the super-dry spots had no microbes at all. The balloon tests suggested that the Atacama microbes weren\u0027t visitors carried by the wind.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They could build shelters for astronauts B. They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions C. They could grow food for the crew D. They could measure the distance to Earth","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They could build shelters for astronauts","B":"They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions","C":"They could grow food for the crew","D":"They could measure the distance to Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines may go on a NASA mission to a planet that \"seems too cold and too dry for life,\" like the Dry Valleys. This suggests they could help search for life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Scientists expect every test to succeed B. Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments C. Scientists only share results when everything works D. Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Scientists expect every test to succeed","B":"Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments","C":"Scientists only share results when everything works","D":"Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explains that science involves testing, and results can vary. This shows that scientists gain knowledge from both working and non-working experiments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To carry people on long trips on Earth B. To explore the surface of a planet C. To fly through space at high speed D. To measure the temperature of stars","excerpt":"\"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To carry people on long trips on Earth","B":"To explore the surface of a planet","C":"To fly through space at high speed","D":"To measure the temperature of stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the context, what does \"complex\" mean? Options: A. Very easy to understand, B. Simple and small, C. Having many parts, D. Impossible to study","excerpt":"\"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve. As a result, microbial life should be far more common in the universe.\"","stem":"Based on the context, what does \"complex\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"Very easy to understand,","B":"Simple and small,","C":"Having many parts,","D":"Impossible to study"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text contrasts \"simple\" microbial life with \"complex\" animals that take longer to evolve, indicating complex means having more difficult or many parts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve. As a result, microbial life should be far more common in the universe.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q002","read_aloud":"Why is it difficult for scientists to decide if viruses are \"alive\"? Options: A. Because they are too big to see, B. Because they need a host cell to reproduce, C. Because they don\u0027t evolve, D. Because they don\u0027t cause disease","excerpt":"\"But viruses can\u0027t reproduce by themselves. A virus must invade the cell of a living thing... and hijack the cell\u0027s machinery to make more viruses.\"","stem":"Why is it difficult for scientists to decide if viruses are \"alive\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they are too big to see,","B":"Because they need a host cell to reproduce,","C":"Because they don\u0027t evolve,","D":"Because they don\u0027t cause disease"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that because viruses cannot reproduce on their own and must \"hijack\" other cells, scientists argue whether they are \"half-alive\" or just chemistry.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But viruses can\u0027t reproduce by themselves. A virus must invade the cell of a living thing... and hijack the cell\u0027s machinery to make more viruses.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q003","read_aloud":"What does this show about the nature of viruses? Options: A. They are very slow to change, B. They are very stable and never change, C. They change quickly to adapt, D. They only affect bean plants and bears","excerpt":"\"Flu viruses evolve so quickly that scientists must develop new flu vaccines every year to fight the latest version of the virus.\"","stem":"What does this show about the nature of viruses? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are very slow to change,","B":"They are very stable and never change,","C":"They change quickly to adapt,","D":"They only affect bean plants and bears"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The need for new vaccines every year proves that viruses \"evolve so quickly\" that they constantly change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Flu viruses evolve so quickly that scientists must develop new flu vaccines every year to fight the latest version of the virus.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the sidebar \"What Is Life?\" if there is no simple answer? Options: A. To confuse the reader, B. To show that science is an ongoing process of asking questions, C. To prove that viruses are definitely alive, D. To explain how to cure the common cold","excerpt":"\"So is a virus just a fancy bit of chemistry? Or is it possible for something to be half-alive? Scientists are still arguing over these questions.\"","stem":"Why does the author include the sidebar \"What Is Life?\" if there is no simple answer? Options:","choices":{"A":"To confuse the reader,","B":"To show that science is an ongoing process of asking questions,","C":"To prove that viruses are definitely alive,","D":"To explain how to cure the common cold"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses the sidebar to show that scientific definitions are not always settled and that researchers are still \"arguing over these questions,\" demonstrating the nature of scientific debate.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"So is a virus just a fancy bit of chemistry? Or is it possible for something to be half-alive? Scientists are still arguing over these questions.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q005","read_aloud":"Do you think the author\u0027s use of a car as an example is helpful? Options: A. No, because cars are too expensive, B. Yes, because it clearly shows why just \"eating\" energy isn\u0027t enough to be alive, C. No, because cars are living things, D. Yes, because it proves cars can reproduce","excerpt":"\"A car \u0027eats\u0027 gasoline and gives off heat and exhaust gases. A car isn\u0027t alive. Let\u0027s add the ability to reproduce. A car can\u0027t make baby cars.\"","stem":"Do you think the author\u0027s use of a car as an example is helpful? Options:","choices":{"A":"No, because cars are too expensive,","B":"Yes, because it clearly shows why just \"eating\" energy isn\u0027t enough to be alive,","C":"No, because cars are living things,","D":"Yes, because it proves cars can reproduce"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The example successfully highlights that multiple criteria-like reproduction and evolution-are required to classify something as truly \"alive,\" rather than just using energy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A car \u0027eats\u0027 gasoline and gives off heat and exhaust gases. A car isn\u0027t alive. Let\u0027s add the ability to reproduce. A car can\u0027t make baby cars.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"drier\" help you understand the comparison between the Atacama and the Dry Valleys? A. It shows both places are wet B. It shows the Atacama has even less moisture than the already very dry Dry Valleys C. It shows the Dry Valleys are warmer than the Atacama D. It shows both places have the same amount of rain","excerpt":"\"The Atacama is even drier than Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys.\"","stem":"How does the word \"drier\" help you understand the comparison between the Atacama and the Dry Valleys?","choices":{"A":"It shows both places are wet","B":"It shows the Atacama has even less moisture than the already very dry Dry Valleys","C":"It shows the Dry Valleys are warmer than the Atacama","D":"It shows both places have the same amount of rain"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Drier\" is a comparative word. Since the Dry Valleys are already described as very dry, saying the Atacama is \"even drier\" emphasizes its extreme lack of moisture.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Atacama is even drier than Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q007","read_aloud":"Why would scientists use the same experiments on Earth that were used on Mars? A. To make the experiments easier to do B. To see if the experiments could detect life in a known place before trusting them on Mars C. Because they had no other experiments to use D. To prove that Mars is exactly like the Atacama","excerpt":"\"Chris and his colleagues tested the Atacama\u0027s soil and rocks for evidence of life. They tried some of the same soil experiments used by the Viking spacecrafts when they visited Mars in 1976.\"","stem":"Why would scientists use the same experiments on Earth that were used on Mars?","choices":{"A":"To make the experiments easier to do","B":"To see if the experiments could detect life in a known place before trusting them on Mars","C":"Because they had no other experiments to use","D":"To prove that Mars is exactly like the Atacama"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By testing Mars-style experiments in the Atacama (a place they know has some life), scientists can check if the methods work. This helps them trust the results when using the same tests on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris and his colleagues tested the Atacama\u0027s soil and rocks for evidence of life. They tried some of the same soil experiments used by the Viking spacecrafts when they visited Mars in 1976.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q008","read_aloud":"Why might the author include this descriptive detail about the balloon? A. To show that scientists do not like using balloons B. To help readers imagine the challenging fieldwork conditions and make the story more engaging C. To prove that balloons cannot be used in science D. To suggest that Chris is not a good scientist","excerpt":"\"The balloon was hard to handle in the desert wind. It bounced around like a crazed ping-pong ball. \u0027It went every direction but up!\u0027 recalled Chris.\"","stem":"Why might the author include this descriptive detail about the balloon?","choices":{"A":"To show that scientists do not like using balloons","B":"To help readers imagine the challenging fieldwork conditions and make the story more engaging","C":"To prove that balloons cannot be used in science","D":"To suggest that Chris is not a good scientist"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The vivid description (\"crazed ping-pong ball,\" \"every direction but up\") helps readers picture the difficulty of the work. This makes the scientific process feel real and adds interest to the informational text.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The balloon was hard to handle in the desert wind. It bounced around like a crazed ping-pong ball. \u0027It went every direction but up!\u0027 recalled Chris.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym of \"complex\"? A. Simple B. Hard C. Complicated D. Difficult","excerpt":"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve.","stem":"Which word is an antonym of \"complex\"?","choices":{"A":"Simple","B":"Hard","C":"Complicated","D":"Difficult"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text uses \"simple\" as an antonym for \"complex.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Do you think Chris\u0027s trip was a failure because most machines did not work? A. Yes, because nothing worked. B. No, because scientists learn from failures and two machines succeeded. C. Yes, because he wasted money. D. No, because he found gold.","excerpt":"Of the six machines Chris brought, only two were good at finding microbes. … Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.","stem":"Do you think Chris\u0027s trip was a failure because most machines did not work?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because nothing worked.","B":"No, because scientists learn from failures and two machines succeeded.","C":"Yes, because he wasted money.","D":"No, because he found gold."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says science involves testing, and even failed tests teach lessons.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Of the six machines Chris brought, only two were good at finding microbes. … Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q011","read_aloud":"Do you think this is an effective comparison? Why? A. Yes, because it makes the importance of water easy to understand. B. No, because parties are not scientific. C. Yes, because water is boring. D. No, because water cannot talk.","excerpt":"In the party of life, water is the life of the party!","stem":"Do you think this is an effective comparison? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because it makes the importance of water easy to understand.","B":"No, because parties are not scientific.","C":"Yes, because water is boring.","D":"No, because water cannot talk."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The analogy helps readers understand that water brings all the necessary parts together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: In the party of life, water is the life of the party!"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q012","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what feature would your machine need most? A. The ability to work in extreme cold and dry conditions B. A heater to make the planet warm C. A window to see aliens D. A kitchen to cook food","excerpt":"The whole text.Imagine you must design a new machine to find microbes on a dry, cold planet.","stem":"Based on the text, what feature would your machine need most?","choices":{"A":"The ability to work in extreme cold and dry conditions","B":"A heater to make the planet warm","C":"A window to see aliens","D":"A kitchen to cook food"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows that machines failed in Antarctica\u0027s cold, so a new machine must handle such conditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text.Imagine you must design a new machine to find microbes on a dry, cold planet."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Why do astrobiologists study extreme places on Earth like the Dry Valleys and the Atacama? A. Because they like to go on vacations there. B. Because these places are similar to other planets, so they can learn if life could exist elsewhere. C. Because they want to move to those places. D. Because those places have the best food.","excerpt":"\"McKay and other astrobiologists look for signs of life in extreme climates on Earth. Then they compare those findings to the information they have about climates on other planets, such as Mars, to see if life could exist there.\"","stem":"Why do astrobiologists study extreme places on Earth like the Dry Valleys and the Atacama?","choices":{"A":"Because they like to go on vacations there.","B":"Because these places are similar to other planets, so they can learn if life could exist elsewhere.","C":"Because they want to move to those places.","D":"Because those places have the best food."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Astrobiologists study extreme places on Earth because they are like conditions on other planets. This helps them understand if life could exist on places like Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"McKay and other astrobiologists look for signs of life in extreme climates on Earth. Then they compare those findings to the information they have about climates on other planets, such as Mars, to see if life could exist there.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Is there life on other planets? Why does the author tell us about Chris McKay\u0027s work? A. To teach us how to become astronauts. B. To help us understand how scientists search for life in the universe. C. To tell us about Chris\u0027s favorite hobbies. D. To explain how to build a telescope.","excerpt":"\"As an astrobiologist, Dr. Chris McKay studies life in the universe to answer an important","stem":"Is there life on other planets? Why does the author tell us about Chris McKay\u0027s work?","choices":{"A":"To teach us how to become astronauts.","B":"To help us understand how scientists search for life in the universe.","C":"To tell us about Chris\u0027s favorite hobbies.","D":"To explain how to build a telescope."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author tells us about Chris\u0027s work to help readers understand how astrobiologists search for life on other planets by studying extreme places on Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As an astrobiologist, Dr. Chris McKay studies life in the universe to answer an important"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q015","read_aloud":"Why does the author use humor in this sentence? A. To make the science more interesting and memorable for readers. B. To make fun of Chris McKay. C. To show that microbes are not important. D. To confuse the readers.","excerpt":"\"\"Those little green critters are the best Martians we have. And everyone knows Martians are little and green!\"\"","stem":"Why does the author use humor in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To make the science more interesting and memorable for readers.","B":"To make fun of Chris McKay.","C":"To show that microbes are not important.","D":"To confuse the readers."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author plays with the idea that Martians are \"little and green\" by comparing them to the tiny green microbes. This humor makes the science fun and easier to remember.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\"Those little green critters are the best Martians we have. And everyone knows Martians are little and green!\"\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Why is the discovery of past water on Mars important for the search for life? A. Because water is needed for life, so past water means life might have existed. B. Because astronauts need water to drink. C. Because water makes rocks prettier. D. Because Mars is too hot now.","excerpt":"\"There may be no liquid water on Mars now, yet the Mars rovers Spirit and Opportunity proved that once upon a time Mars did have liquid water-lots of it. Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a long-lost sea.\"","stem":"Why is the discovery of past water on Mars important for the search for life?","choices":{"A":"Because water is needed for life, so past water means life might have existed.","B":"Because astronauts need water to drink.","C":"Because water makes rocks prettier.","D":"Because Mars is too hot now."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that water is essential for life. If Mars had water for hundreds of millions of years, there was enough time for life to have evolved.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There may be no liquid water on Mars now, yet the Mars rovers Spirit and Opportunity proved that once upon a time Mars did have liquid water-lots of it. Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a long-lost sea.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q017","read_aloud":"Why does Chris think evidence of Martian life might be in an \"underground freezer\"? A. Because underground ice could have preserved traces of ancient life. B. Because freezers are good places to store food. C. Because the surface of Mars is too warm. D. Because underground freezers are easy to find.","excerpt":"\"Scientists think Mars\u0027s surface had water for hundreds of millions of years. That\u0027s enough time for life to have evolved. So where might we find traces of ancient Martians? Chris thinks that evidence of early Martian life may be in a natural underground freezer on Mars.\"","stem":"Why does Chris think evidence of Martian life might be in an \"underground freezer\"?","choices":{"A":"Because underground ice could have preserved traces of ancient life.","B":"Because freezers are good places to store food.","C":"Because the surface of Mars is too warm.","D":"Because underground freezers are easy to find."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"An underground freezer would be very cold and could preserve traces of ancient life. Just like freezing food keeps it from spoiling, freezing could keep evidence of life protected.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists think Mars\u0027s surface had water for hundreds of millions of years. That\u0027s enough time for life to have evolved. So where might we find traces of ancient Martians? Chris thinks that evidence of early Martian life may be in a natural underground freezer on Mars.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q019","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They could build shelters for astronauts B. They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions C. They could grow food for the crew D. They could measure the distance to Earth","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They could build shelters for astronauts","B":"They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions","C":"They could grow food for the crew","D":"They could measure the distance to Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines may go on a NASA mission to a planet that \"seems too cold and too dry for life,\" like the Dry Valleys. This suggests they could help search for life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Scientists expect every test to succeed B. Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments C. Scientists only share results when everything works D. Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Scientists expect every test to succeed","B":"Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments","C":"Scientists only share results when everything works","D":"Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explains that science involves testing, and results can vary. This shows that scientists gain knowledge from both working and non-working experiments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To carry people on long trips on Earth B. To explore the surface of a planet C. To fly through space at high speed D. To measure the temperature of stars","excerpt":"\"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To carry people on long trips on Earth","B":"To explore the surface of a planet","C":"To fly through space at high speed","D":"To measure the temperature of stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. They built a base for human visitors B. They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface C. They took pictures of Earth from Mars D. They searched for other rovers that were lost","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"They built a base for human visitors","B":"They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface","C":"They took pictures of Earth from Mars","D":"They searched for other rovers that were lost"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes Spirit exploring Gusev Crater and Opportunity exploring Meridiani Planum. This shows they explored different surface areas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l08-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Water is needed for rockets to land safely B. Life as we know it needs liquid water to exist C. Water makes the soil easier to dig D. Water helps rovers move faster","excerpt":"\"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist. In searching for aliens, NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Water is needed for rockets to land safely","B":"Life as we know it needs liquid water to exist","C":"Water makes the soil easier to dig","D":"Water helps rovers move faster"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states NASA\u0027s motto is \"Follow the Water\" when searching for life, and they wanted to know if Mars had \"enough liquid water for life to exist.\" This shows water is key for life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist. In searching for aliens, NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"wondering\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. Being bored with, B. Having curiosity about, C. Being afraid of, D. Looking at something closely","excerpt":"\"He\u0027s been wondering what\u0027s out there ever since he found a dusty old telescope and pointed it into the night sky.\"","stem":"What does \"wondering\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"Being bored with,","B":"Having curiosity about,","C":"Being afraid of,","D":"Looking at something closely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Wondering here means having interest or curiosity about what is in the night sky, which connects to the author\u0027s note about curiosity in the \"Meet the Author\" section.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He\u0027s been wondering what\u0027s out there ever since he found a dusty old telescope and pointed it into the night sky.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q002","read_aloud":"Based on the text, why is it necessary to send machines like these to Mars? Options: A. To build a new research station, B. Because humans cannot survive the harsh radiation and conditions, C. Because the rovers are too big to explore craters, D. Because the rovers cannot detect microbes","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that... seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"Based on the text, why is it necessary to send machines like these to Mars? Options:","choices":{"A":"To build a new research station,","B":"Because humans cannot survive the harsh radiation and conditions,","C":"Because the rovers are too big to explore craters,","D":"Because the rovers cannot detect microbes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since Mars has dangerous radiation and an atmosphere too thin for humans to live in, robots are needed to perform the exploration tasks.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that... seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q003","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s tone when mentioning \"little green men\"? Options: A. Serious and scientific, B. Playful and lighthearted, C. Angry and upset, D. Sad and lonely","excerpt":"\"The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life. Yet \u0027little green men\u0027 might surprise us.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s tone when mentioning \"little green men\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Serious and scientific,","B":"Playful and lighthearted,","C":"Angry and upset,","D":"Sad and lonely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The phrase \"little green men\" is a humorous, informal reference to alien stereotypes, which the author uses to contrast with the reality of microscopic life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life. Yet \u0027little green men\u0027 might surprise us.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q004","read_aloud":"If you were planning a space mission, how would you use the lessons from Chris McKay\u0027s Dry Valley trip? Options: A. I would bring only one machine to save money, B. I would only pick machines that I know will work perfectly, C. I would bring multiple, different types of machines in case some fail, D. I would skip testing and go straight to Mars","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"If you were planning a space mission, how would you use the lessons from Chris McKay\u0027s Dry Valley trip? Options:","choices":{"A":"I would bring only one machine to save money,","B":"I would only pick machines that I know will work perfectly,","C":"I would bring multiple, different types of machines in case some fail,","D":"I would skip testing and go straight to Mars"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"McKay\u0027s experience showed that only two out of six machines worked; bringing a variety increases the chances of mission success.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q005","read_aloud":"Based on the author\u0027s description, what qualities make a good scientist? Options: A. Being rich and famous, B. Having a big lab and expensive clothes, C. Having curiosity and a love of nature, D. Being able to fix cars quickly","excerpt":"\"Chris can\u0027t wait to find out. He\u0027s been wondering what\u0027s out there ever since he found a dusty old telescope and pointed it into the night sky.\"","stem":"Based on the author\u0027s description, what qualities make a good scientist? Options:","choices":{"A":"Being rich and famous,","B":"Having a big lab and expensive clothes,","C":"Having curiosity and a love of nature,","D":"Being able to fix cars quickly"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The \"Meet the Author\" and the concluding paragraphs emphasize that curiosity and a love of nature are the driving forces behind the work of scientists like Turner and McKay.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris can\u0027t wait to find out. He\u0027s been wondering what\u0027s out there ever since he found a dusty old telescope and pointed it into the night sky.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, why is it important that sensors can measure \"year-round\"? A. So scientists can take a vacation B. So they can collect data in all seasons to understand how microbes survive changing conditions C. So the sensors use less battery power D. So the data is only from summer","excerpt":"\"The sensors measured the light and moisture inside the rocks year-round.\"","stem":"In this context, why is it important that sensors can measure \"year-round\"?","choices":{"A":"So scientists can take a vacation","B":"So they can collect data in all seasons to understand how microbes survive changing conditions","C":"So the sensors use less battery power","D":"So the data is only from summer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Measuring \"year-round\" means collecting data in all seasons. This helps scientists see how microbes survive through different conditions, like summer sunlight and winter darkness.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The sensors measured the light and moisture inside the rocks year-round.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q007","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt suggest about how scientists gain knowledge? A. Scientists learn everything from one quick trip B. Long-term, repeated study helps scientists understand difficult environments and the life within them C. Scientists only study places that are easy to reach D. Weather has no effect on scientific research","excerpt":"\"Chris has been making these camping trips to Antarctica for twenty-five years. He knows there are creatures hidden in the Dry Valleys that can survive some of the world\u0027s worst weather.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt suggest about how scientists gain knowledge?","choices":{"A":"Scientists learn everything from one quick trip","B":"Long-term, repeated study helps scientists understand difficult environments and the life within them","C":"Scientists only study places that are easy to reach","D":"Weather has no effect on scientific research"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris\u0027s 25 years of trips show that deep understanding comes from sustained effort. Repeated study in harsh places allows scientists to discover how life adapts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris has been making these camping trips to Antarctica for twenty-five years. He knows there are creatures hidden in the Dry Valleys that can survive some of the world\u0027s worst weather.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q008","read_aloud":"Based on this sidebar, why is water called \"the host with the most\" in the chemistry of life? A. Because water is the most common liquid on Earth B. Because water brings life\u0027s chemicals together and creates the right conditions for reactions, like a good party host C. Because water is the most expensive resource for scientists D. Because water can exist in three states: solid, liquid, and gas","excerpt":"\"Unless lost in a desert, we take water for granted... Water is the host. Water makes sure everyone\u0027s comfy-neither too hot nor too cold. Without water, the chemicals necessary for life couldn\u0027t find each other, mix with each other, and react with each other. Life would never happen.\"","stem":"Based on this sidebar, why is water called \"the host with the most\" in the chemistry of life?","choices":{"A":"Because water is the most common liquid on Earth","B":"Because water brings life\u0027s chemicals together and creates the right conditions for reactions, like a good party host","C":"Because water is the most expensive resource for scientists","D":"Because water can exist in three states: solid, liquid, and gas"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sidebar uses a party metaphor: water is the \"host\" that gathers the \"guests\" (life\u0027s chemicals) and keeps conditions right for them to interact. This highlights water\u0027s essential role in enabling life\u0027s chemistry.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Unless lost in a desert, we take water for granted... Water is the host. Water makes sure everyone\u0027s comfy-neither too hot nor too cold. Without water, the chemicals necessary for life couldn\u0027t find each other, mix with each other, and react with each other. Life would never happen.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q009","read_aloud":"What does \"entirely\" mean in this sentence? A. Completely B. Partly C. Never D. Sometimes","excerpt":"The Atacama isn\u0027t entirely dead, though. Some of the Atacama soil Chris collected did have live microbes.","stem":"What does \"entirely\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Completely","B":"Partly","C":"Never","D":"Sometimes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Entirely dead\" means completely dead. The text says not entirely dead, so some life exists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Atacama isn\u0027t entirely dead, though. Some of the Atacama soil Chris collected did have live microbes."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q010","read_aloud":"Do you think \"Follow the Water\" is a good motto for searching for life? Why? A. No, because water is not important. B. Yes, because all known life needs liquid water. C. No, because water is everywhere. D. Yes, because water is easy to find.","excerpt":"NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water.","stem":"Do you think \"Follow the Water\" is a good motto for searching for life? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because water is not important.","B":"Yes, because all known life needs liquid water.","C":"No, because water is everywhere.","D":"Yes, because water is easy to find."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that water is essential for life\u0027s chemistry, so it is a good guide.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q011","read_aloud":"Chris later explained. \"Those little green critters are the best Martians we have.\"What is Chris\u0027s perspective about microbes in the Dry Valleys? A. They are not important. B. They are the closest thing to Martians we have on Earth. C. They are dangerous. D. They are not real.","excerpt":"If life exists on Mars, it might look something like that,","stem":"Chris later explained. \"Those little green critters are the best Martians we have.\"What is Chris\u0027s perspective about microbes in the Dry Valleys?","choices":{"A":"They are not important.","B":"They are the closest thing to Martians we have on Earth.","C":"They are dangerous.","D":"They are not real."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris calls them \"the best Martians we have\" because they live in Marslike conditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If life exists on Mars, it might look something like that,"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q012","read_aloud":"If you could send a message to future space explorers, what would you say based on this finding? A. Look only for planets with oceans or ice that can melt. B. Look only for planets with purple skies. C. Avoid any planet with water. D. Only look for planets that are exactly like Earth.","excerpt":"There does seem to be a limit to life on Earth. … where there is no liquid water, there is no life.","stem":"If you could send a message to future space explorers, what would you say based on this finding?","choices":{"A":"Look only for planets with oceans or ice that can melt.","B":"Look only for planets with purple skies.","C":"Avoid any planet with water.","D":"Only look for planets that are exactly like Earth."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Since life on Earth needs liquid water, explorers should look for planets that have or had liquid water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: There does seem to be a limit to life on Earth. … where there is no liquid water, there is no life."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q013","read_aloud":"Do you think it is worth spending money on science experiments that might fail? A. No, because failure is a waste. B. Yes, because even failures teach us something and lead to later success. C. No, because scientists should know everything already. D. Yes, because failing is fun.","excerpt":"Chris was pleased that two machines worked. Science is all about testing new things and ideas.","stem":"Do you think it is worth spending money on science experiments that might fail?","choices":{"A":"No, because failure is a waste.","B":"Yes, because even failures teach us something and lead to later success.","C":"No, because scientists should know everything already.","D":"Yes, because failing is fun."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says science is about testing. Failure is part of learning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Chris was pleased that two machines worked. Science is all about testing new things and ideas."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Based on the text, why are scientists more likely to find microbes than complex animals on other planets? A. Because microbes are simpler and can live in harsh environments. B. Because complex animals are too friendly. C. Because microbes are bigger than complex animals. D. Because complex animals do not need water.","excerpt":"\"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve. As a result, microbial life should be far more common in the universe than complex life.\"","stem":"Based on the text, why are scientists more likely to find microbes than complex animals on other planets?","choices":{"A":"Because microbes are simpler and can live in harsh environments.","B":"Because complex animals are too friendly.","C":"Because microbes are bigger than complex animals.","D":"Because complex animals do not need water."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says microbes are simple and hardy, so they can live in harsh environments. Complex animals take longer to evolve and need better conditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve. As a result, microbial life should be far more common in the universe than complex life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q015","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about how scientists think? A. They guess without any evidence. B. They ask questions and design experiments to find answers. C. They already know all the answers. D. They do not care about microbes.","excerpt":"\"The Atacama isn\u0027t entirely dead, though. Some of the Atacama soil Chris collected did have live microbes. \u0027We wondered how they survived,\u0027 said Chris. \u0027Did they grow in the Atacama? Or were they blown in by the wind, and we found them just before they died?\u0027\"","stem":"What does this tell you about how scientists think?","choices":{"A":"They guess without any evidence.","B":"They ask questions and design experiments to find answers.","C":"They already know all the answers.","D":"They do not care about microbes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris wondered how the microbes survived and designed the balloon experiment to test his questions. This shows scientists ask questions and then test them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Atacama isn\u0027t entirely dead, though. Some of the Atacama soil Chris collected did have live microbes. \u0027We wondered how they survived,\u0027 said Chris. \u0027Did they grow in the Atacama? Or were they blown in by the wind, and we found them just before they died?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the detail that Chris is \"six-foot-six-inch\"? A. To teach us about measuring height. B. To help us picture Chris and understand why he needs an extra-long sleeping bag. C. To show that tall people are better scientists. D. To tell us about basketball.","excerpt":"\"Early on his first morning in the Dry Valleys, six-foot-six-inch Chris wormed his way out of his extra-long sleeping bag. There was plenty of light outside. The sun is up twenty-four hours a day during the Antarctic summer. However, the sun\u0027s rays didn\u0027t give off much warmth.\"","stem":"Why does the author include the detail that Chris is \"six-foot-six-inch\"?","choices":{"A":"To teach us about measuring height.","B":"To help us picture Chris and understand why he needs an extra-long sleeping bag.","C":"To show that tall people are better scientists.","D":"To tell us about basketball."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The detail about Chris\u0027s height helps readers understand why he needs an extra-long sleeping bag. It paints a clearer picture of Chris and his experience.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Early on his first morning in the Dry Valleys, six-foot-six-inch Chris wormed his way out of his extra-long sleeping bag. There was plenty of light outside. The sun is up twenty-four hours a day during the Antarctic summer. However, the sun\u0027s rays didn\u0027t give off much warmth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q017","read_aloud":"Why did Chris use the same experiments as the Viking spacecrafts? A. Because he did not have any new ideas. B. Because he wanted to compare results and see if the tests would work on Earth too. C. Because the Viking spacecrafts were still on Mars. D. Because he wanted to build a new spacecraft.","excerpt":"\"Chris and his colleagues tested the Atacama\u0027s soil and rocks for evidence of life. They tried some of the same soil experiments used by the Viking spacecrafts when they visited Mars in 1976.\"","stem":"Why did Chris use the same experiments as the Viking spacecrafts?","choices":{"A":"Because he did not have any new ideas.","B":"Because he wanted to compare results and see if the tests would work on Earth too.","C":"Because the Viking spacecrafts were still on Mars.","D":"Because he wanted to build a new spacecraft."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris used the same experiments to test them on Earth. If the tests said Earth was \"dead\" in the Atacama, it would show that the tests might miss life on Mars too.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris and his colleagues tested the Atacama\u0027s soil and rocks for evidence of life. They tried some of the same soil experiments used by the Viking spacecrafts when they visited Mars in 1976.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q018","read_aloud":"If scientists find a natural underground freezer on Mars, what should they do next? A. Ignore it and look somewhere else. B. Study it carefully to search for preserved traces of ancient life. C. Use it to store their food. D. Build a restaurant there.","excerpt":"\"Chris thinks that evidence of early Martian life may be in a natural underground freezer on Mars. A natural underground freezer just like the one in Siberia.\"","stem":"If scientists find a natural underground freezer on Mars, what should they do next?","choices":{"A":"Ignore it and look somewhere else.","B":"Study it carefully to search for preserved traces of ancient life.","C":"Use it to store their food.","D":"Build a restaurant there."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris believes an underground freezer might preserve evidence of ancient Martian life. Scientists should study it carefully to search for these traces.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris thinks that evidence of early Martian life may be in a natural underground freezer on Mars. A natural underground freezer just like the one in Siberia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q020","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They could build shelters for astronauts B. They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions C. They could grow food for the crew D. They could measure the distance to Earth","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They could build shelters for astronauts","B":"They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions","C":"They could grow food for the crew","D":"They could measure the distance to Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines may go on a NASA mission to a planet that \"seems too cold and too dry for life,\" like the Dry Valleys. This suggests they could help search for life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Scientists expect every test to succeed B. Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments C. Scientists only share results when everything works D. Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Scientists expect every test to succeed","B":"Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments","C":"Scientists only share results when everything works","D":"Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explains that science involves testing, and results can vary. This shows that scientists gain knowledge from both working and non-working experiments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To carry people on long trips on Earth B. To explore the surface of a planet C. To fly through space at high speed D. To measure the temperature of stars","excerpt":"\"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To carry people on long trips on Earth","B":"To explore the surface of a planet","C":"To fly through space at high speed","D":"To measure the temperature of stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l09-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. They built a base for human visitors B. They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface C. They took pictures of Earth from Mars D. They searched for other rovers that were lost","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"They built a base for human visitors","B":"They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface","C":"They took pictures of Earth from Mars","D":"They searched for other rovers that were lost"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes Spirit exploring Gusev Crater and Opportunity exploring Meridiani Planum. This shows they explored different surface areas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"lonely\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. A place with many people, B. A place that is empty and remote, C. A place that is very loud, D. A place that is easy to reach","excerpt":"\"The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space.\"","stem":"What does \"lonely\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"A place with many people,","B":"A place that is empty and remote,","C":"A place that is very loud,","D":"A place that is easy to reach"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In this context, lonely refers to the isolation and lack of other living things in the Dry Valleys, similar to space.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q002","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare the Dry Valleys to outer space? Options: A. To show that they both have many plants, B. To emphasize that the Dry Valleys are extremely empty and harsh, C. To show that the Dry Valleys are located on Mars, D. To explain why scientists wear spacesuits there","excerpt":"\"There isn\u0027t a single scraggly weed or tiny insect. The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare the Dry Valleys to outer space? Options:","choices":{"A":"To show that they both have many plants,","B":"To emphasize that the Dry Valleys are extremely empty and harsh,","C":"To show that the Dry Valleys are located on Mars,","D":"To explain why scientists wear spacesuits there"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By comparing the barren Antarctic environment to space, the author highlights the extreme, life-free nature of the landscape.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There isn\u0027t a single scraggly weed or tiny insect. The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q003","read_aloud":"Why does the author include questions like these throughout the text? Options: A. To make the reader do homework, B. To encourage the reader to think like a scientist, C. To prove that we cannot visit other planets, D. To show that the author does not know the answer","excerpt":"\"What distant place would you like to visit? What do you think you would discover there?\"","stem":"Why does the author include questions like these throughout the text? Options:","choices":{"A":"To make the reader do homework,","B":"To encourage the reader to think like a scientist,","C":"To prove that we cannot visit other planets,","D":"To show that the author does not know the answer"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"These questions, along with \"Turn and Talk\" sections, encourage students to engage with the material, make their own hypotheses, and think like active researchers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"What distant place would you like to visit? What do you think you would discover there?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q004","read_aloud":"Do you agree with the author that the microbes found by Chris are the \"best Martians we have\"? Options: A. Yes, because they live in conditions similar to what we expect on Mars, B. No, because they are not green enough, C. Yes, because they can travel in flying saucers, D. No, because they are too large to live on Mars","excerpt":"\"If life exists on Mars, it might look something like that... Those little green critters are the best Martians we have.\"","stem":"Do you agree with the author that the microbes found by Chris are the \"best Martians we have\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Yes, because they live in conditions similar to what we expect on Mars,","B":"No, because they are not green enough,","C":"Yes, because they can travel in flying saucers,","D":"No, because they are too large to live on Mars"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Since they survive in extreme, cold, dry, and high-radiation conditions similar to Mars, they serve as the best available model for what Martian life might be like.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If life exists on Mars, it might look something like that... Those little green critters are the best Martians we have.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q005","read_aloud":"If you had the chance to improve one of the machines for a future mission, what would you do? Options: A. I would make it easier to fix in cold weather, B. I would make it faster, C. I would make it prettier to look at, D. I would take out the sensors","excerpt":"\"But the gas chromatograph didn\u0027t work at all, despite hours of tinkering. Of the six machines... only two... were good at finding microbes.\"","stem":"If you had the chance to improve one of the machines for a future mission, what would you do? Options:","choices":{"A":"I would make it easier to fix in cold weather,","B":"I would make it faster,","C":"I would make it prettier to look at,","D":"I would take out the sensors"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Because the ink froze and the machines failed in the cold, improving their durability or ease of repair in freezing conditions would be the most practical solution for mission success.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But the gas chromatograph didn\u0027t work at all, despite hours of tinkering. Of the six machines... only two... were good at finding microbes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q006","read_aloud":"What is a virus? A. A large animal B. A very small, simple microbe that can cause disease C. A type of rock D. A healthy food","excerpt":"Viruses are very small, very simple microbes. They cause many human diseases, including AIDS and the common cold.","stem":"What is a virus?","choices":{"A":"A large animal","B":"A very small, simple microbe that can cause disease","C":"A type of rock","D":"A healthy food"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sidebar \"What Is Life?\" describes viruses as very small, simple microbes that cause diseases.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Viruses are very small, very simple microbes. They cause many human diseases, including AIDS and the common cold."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q007","read_aloud":"said Chris, \"but it seems that where there is no liquid water, there is no life.\"How did Chris\u0027s hope change after his research? A. He still hopes to find life without water. B. He concluded that liquid water is necessary for life on Earth. C. He gave up science. D. He decided to study only volcanoes.","excerpt":"At first I hoped I could find a microbe in the Atacama that was somehow adapted to life without liquid water,","stem":"said Chris, \"but it seems that where there is no liquid water, there is no life.\"How did Chris\u0027s hope change after his research?","choices":{"A":"He still hopes to find life without water.","B":"He concluded that liquid water is necessary for life on Earth.","C":"He gave up science.","D":"He decided to study only volcanoes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris hoped to find a microbe that didn\u0027t need water, but his research showed water is necessary.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: At first I hoped I could find a microbe in the Atacama that was somehow adapted to life without liquid water,"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q008","read_aloud":"Where would you put it and why? A. In a rainforest, because it is warm. B. In a very dry, cold desert like the Dry Valleys or Atacama, to test machines for Mars. C. In a big city, because it is easy to get food. D. On a boat, because water is important.","excerpt":"The whole text.Design a new extremeplace research station based on the text.","stem":"Where would you put it and why?","choices":{"A":"In a rainforest, because it is warm.","B":"In a very dry, cold desert like the Dry Valleys or Atacama, to test machines for Mars.","C":"In a big city, because it is easy to get food.","D":"On a boat, because water is important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that dry, cold places on Earth are good models for Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text.Design a new extremeplace research station based on the text."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think Chris McKay is a good role model for young scientists? Why? A. No, because he failed many times. B. Yes, because he is curious, keeps trying, and loves exploring. C. No, because he only works in cold places. D. Yes, because he never makes mistakes.","excerpt":"Chris can\u0027t wait to find out. He\u0027s been wondering what\u0027s out there ever since he found a dusty old telescope and pointed it into the night sky.","stem":"Do you think Chris McKay is a good role model for young scientists? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because he failed many times.","B":"Yes, because he is curious, keeps trying, and loves exploring.","C":"No, because he only works in cold places.","D":"Yes, because he never makes mistakes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris shows curiosity, persistence, and a love of discovery, which are great traits for scientists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Chris can\u0027t wait to find out. He\u0027s been wondering what\u0027s out there ever since he found a dusty old telescope and pointed it into the night sky."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q010","read_aloud":"Why is it important that Chris found a \"colony\" of microbes rather than just one microbe? A. A colony shows that the microbes can live and reproduce in the rock. B. A colony is prettier than one microbe. C. One microbe is more important than a colony. D. Colonies are easier to hammer.","excerpt":"\"Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface. With a hammer and chisel he carefully chipped off a chunk of rock to take back to his lab at NASA.\"","stem":"Why is it important that Chris found a \"colony\" of microbes rather than just one microbe?","choices":{"A":"A colony shows that the microbes can live and reproduce in the rock.","B":"A colony is prettier than one microbe.","C":"One microbe is more important than a colony.","D":"Colonies are easier to hammer."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"A colony is a group of living things. Finding a colony shows that the microbes are not just surviving but are living and reproducing in the rock.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris spotted little blotches on the rock. A colony of microbes was living in pores just under the surface. With a hammer and chisel he carefully chipped off a chunk of rock to take back to his lab at NASA.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q011","read_aloud":"What does twenty-five years of trips tell you about Chris McKay? A. He gives up easily when things are hard. B. He is dedicated and passionate about his research. C. He does not like his job. D. He is afraid of cold weather.","excerpt":"\"Chris has been making these camping trips to Antarctica for twenty-five years. He knows there are creatures hidden in the Dry Valleys that can survive some of the world\u0027s worst weather.\"","stem":"What does twenty-five years of trips tell you about Chris McKay?","choices":{"A":"He gives up easily when things are hard.","B":"He is dedicated and passionate about his research.","C":"He does not like his job.","D":"He is afraid of cold weather."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Making trips for twenty-five years shows Chris is very dedicated. He keeps going back because he is passionate about finding life in extreme places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris has been making these camping trips to Antarctica for twenty-five years. He knows there are creatures hidden in the Dry Valleys that can survive some of the world\u0027s worst weather.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q012","read_aloud":"How does this idea apply to your own life? A. We should never try new things. B. Trying new things is important, even if we fail sometimes. C. We should only do things that are easy. D. Failure means we should quit.","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"How does this idea apply to your own life?","choices":{"A":"We should never try new things.","B":"Trying new things is important, even if we fail sometimes.","C":"We should only do things that are easy.","D":"Failure means we should quit."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris\u0027s attitude shows that science (and life) involves trying new things. Sometimes we succeed and sometimes we fail, but we learn from both.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q013","read_aloud":"How might this discovery change the way scientists search for life on other planets? A. They will stop searching for life completely. B. They will focus on places where liquid water exists or once existed. C. They will only look at the driest places. D. They will search for life on the sun.","excerpt":"\"\u0027At first I hoped I could find a microbe in the Atacama that was somehow adapted to life without liquid water,\u0027 said Chris, \u0027but it seems that where there is no liquid water, there is no life.\u0027\"","stem":"How might this discovery change the way scientists search for life on other planets?","choices":{"A":"They will stop searching for life completely.","B":"They will focus on places where liquid water exists or once existed.","C":"They will only look at the driest places.","D":"They will search for life on the sun."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If liquid water is needed for life, scientists should look for places with water. The text mentions Mars once had water, so that is a good place to search.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027At first I hoped I could find a microbe in the Atacama that was somehow adapted to life without liquid water,\u0027 said Chris, \u0027but it seems that where there is no liquid water, there is no life.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q014","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q015","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q016","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q017","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They could build shelters for astronauts B. They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions C. They could grow food for the crew D. They could measure the distance to Earth","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They could build shelters for astronauts","B":"They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions","C":"They could grow food for the crew","D":"They could measure the distance to Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines may go on a NASA mission to a planet that \"seems too cold and too dry for life,\" like the Dry Valleys. This suggests they could help search for life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q018","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Scientists expect every test to succeed B. Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments C. Scientists only share results when everything works D. Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Scientists expect every test to succeed","B":"Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments","C":"Scientists only share results when everything works","D":"Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explains that science involves testing, and results can vary. This shows that scientists gain knowledge from both working and non-working experiments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q019","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To carry people on long trips on Earth B. To explore the surface of a planet C. To fly through space at high speed D. To measure the temperature of stars","excerpt":"\"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To carry people on long trips on Earth","B":"To explore the surface of a planet","C":"To fly through space at high speed","D":"To measure the temperature of stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. They built a base for human visitors B. They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface C. They took pictures of Earth from Mars D. They searched for other rovers that were lost","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"They built a base for human visitors","B":"They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface","C":"They took pictures of Earth from Mars","D":"They searched for other rovers that were lost"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes Spirit exploring Gusev Crater and Opportunity exploring Meridiani Planum. This shows they explored different surface areas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Water is needed for rockets to land safely B. Life as we know it needs liquid water to exist C. Water makes the soil easier to dig D. Water helps rovers move faster","excerpt":"\"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist. In searching for aliens, NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Water is needed for rockets to land safely","B":"Life as we know it needs liquid water to exist","C":"Water makes the soil easier to dig","D":"Water helps rovers move faster"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states NASA\u0027s motto is \"Follow the Water\" when searching for life, and they wanted to know if Mars had \"enough liquid water for life to exist.\" This shows water is key for life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist. In searching for aliens, NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. To prove that no life can exist anywhere without water B. To understand the limits of life and compare to dry places like Mars C. To find new sources of drinking water for Earth D. To test how fast plants can grow in dry soil","excerpt":"\"They weren\u0027t \u0027following the water.\u0027 They were looking for spots with as little water as possible.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"To prove that no life can exist anywhere without water","B":"To understand the limits of life and compare to dry places like Mars","C":"To find new sources of drinking water for Earth","D":"To test how fast plants can grow in dry soil"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The scientists studied the extremely dry Atacama to see where life can and cannot survive. This helps them understand what to expect on dry planets like Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They weren\u0027t \u0027following the water.\u0027 They were looking for spots with as little water as possible.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It is easy to find life if you look in the right place B. A planet might have life, but tests could miss it if they look in the wrong spots C. Only Earth has life in the universe D. Spacecraft should never land in deserts","excerpt":"If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet,","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It is easy to find life if you look in the right place","B":"A planet might have life, but tests could miss it if they look in the wrong spots","C":"Only Earth has life in the universe","D":"Spacecraft should never land in deserts"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris says that if a Mars lander tested only the driest parts of the Atacama, it might wrongly conclude Earth has no life. This shows that where you look matters when searching for life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet,"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. A single microbe living alone B. A group of microbes living together in one spot C. A type of rock that microbes eat D. A machine that counts microbes","excerpt":"\"colony a group of animals living in one place\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"A single microbe living alone","B":"A group of microbes living together in one spot","C":"A type of rock that microbes eat","D":"A machine that counts microbes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines colony as \"a group of animals living in one place.\" For microbes, this means a group living together, as described in the rock pores.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"colony a group of animals living in one place\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-l10-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. More dryness meant more microbes in the air B. Less dryness meant microbes could live in soil and get into the air C. Microbes lived only in the wettest parts of the desert D. Dryness had no effect on where microbes were found","excerpt":"\"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the super-dry spots had no microbes at all.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"More dryness meant more microbes in the air","B":"Less dryness meant microbes could live in soil and get into the air","C":"Microbes lived only in the wettest parts of the desert","D":"Dryness had no effect on where microbes were found"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows microbes were in the air over less dry areas but not over super-dry spots. This suggests microbes need at least a little moisture to survive and spread.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the super-dry spots had no microbes at all.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what does the word \"microbes\" mean? Options: A. Planets far away, B. Tiny living things, C. Rocks in the desert, D. Machines that explore space","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what does the word \"microbes\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"Planets far away,","B":"Tiny living things,","C":"Rocks in the desert,","D":"Machines that explore space"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines microbes as the \"tiniest of all living things\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q002","read_aloud":"What does the word \"radiation\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. Dangerous energy rays, B. A source of water, C. A type of computer, D. Bright sunlight","excerpt":"\"If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\"","stem":"What does the word \"radiation\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"Dangerous energy rays,","B":"A source of water,","C":"A type of computer,","D":"Bright sunlight"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The sidebar defines radiation as \"dangerous energy rays that cannot be seen\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"If any life exists on Mars, it would need to be shielded from solar radiation by rock or soil.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q003","read_aloud":"What are \"rovers\" according to the text? Options: A. Types of desert insects, B. Small spaceships for people, C. Vehicles used to explore, D. Machines that measure rain","excerpt":"\"NASA uses remote-controlled rovers to explore the surface of planets.\"","stem":"What are \"rovers\" according to the text? Options:","choices":{"A":"Types of desert insects,","B":"Small spaceships for people,","C":"Vehicles used to explore,","D":"Machines that measure rain"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text identifies rovers as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"NASA uses remote-controlled rovers to explore the surface of planets.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q004","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this entire selection? Options: A. Antarctica is a fun place for a vacation, B. Scientists study extreme places on Earth to understand if life could exist on other planets, C. Machines like spectrometers are the only way to find life, D. Viruses are more important than plants","excerpt":"\"As an astrobiologist, Dr. Chris McKay studies life in extreme climates on Earth... to see if life could exist [on Mars].\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this entire selection? Options:","choices":{"A":"Antarctica is a fun place for a vacation,","B":"Scientists study extreme places on Earth to understand if life could exist on other planets,","C":"Machines like spectrometers are the only way to find life,","D":"Viruses are more important than plants"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text\u0027s main purpose is to explain how research in extreme environments on Earth helps scientists look for life elsewhere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As an astrobiologist, Dr. Chris McKay studies life in extreme climates on Earth... to see if life could exist [on Mars].\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q005","read_aloud":"Which place is described as the driest desert found by Chris? Options: A. The Atacama, B. Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys, C. Mars, D. The Gobi Desert","excerpt":"\"The Atacama is even drier than Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys. In fact, if the sky over the Atacama were reddish instead of blue, the super-dry desert would look a lot like super-dry Mars.\"","stem":"Which place is described as the driest desert found by Chris? Options:","choices":{"A":"The Atacama,","B":"Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys,","C":"Mars,","D":"The Gobi Desert"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states, \"the Atacama is truly the driest place we\u0027ve found\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Atacama is even drier than Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys. In fact, if the sky over the Atacama were reddish instead of blue, the super-dry desert would look a lot like super-dry Mars.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q006","read_aloud":"Based on the text, when were the rovers active on Mars? Options: A. After Chris left the Atacama, B. During the same time Chris was exploring the Atacama, C. Before Chris ever visited Antarctica, D. Never, because they failed to land","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater... While Chris was in the Atacama, NASA rovers were scrambling around Mars.\"","stem":"Based on the text, when were the rovers active on Mars? Options:","choices":{"A":"After Chris left the Atacama,","B":"During the same time Chris was exploring the Atacama,","C":"Before Chris ever visited Antarctica,","D":"Never, because they failed to land"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that \"While Chris was in the Atacama, NASA rovers were scrambling around Mars\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater... While Chris was in the Atacama, NASA rovers were scrambling around Mars.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q007","read_aloud":"Why is liquid water essential for life? Options: A. Because it is easy to find in space, B. Because it helps the chemicals of life mix and react, C. Because it is the only food microbes eat, D. Because it keeps the atmosphere thick","excerpt":"\"Water makes sure everyone\u0027s comfy-neither too hot nor too cold. Without water, the chemicals necessary for life couldn\u0027t... react with each other.\"","stem":"Why is liquid water essential for life? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because it is easy to find in space,","B":"Because it helps the chemicals of life mix and react,","C":"Because it is the only food microbes eat,","D":"Because it keeps the atmosphere thick"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that water acts as the \"host\" that allows the essential chemicals of life to \"mix with each other, and react with each other\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water makes sure everyone\u0027s comfy-neither too hot nor too cold. Without water, the chemicals necessary for life couldn\u0027t... react with each other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q008","read_aloud":"How did the scientists solve the mystery of the microbes in the Atacama? Options: A. By testing the air with a balloon, B. By bringing more water to the desert, C. By using a giant shovel to dig deeper, D. By moving the rocks to Antarctica","excerpt":"\"Some of the Atacama soil Chris collected did have live microbes. \u0027We wondered how they survived,\u0027 said Chris. \u0027Did they grow in the Atacama? Or were they blown in by the wind?\u0027\"","stem":"How did the scientists solve the mystery of the microbes in the Atacama? Options:","choices":{"A":"By testing the air with a balloon,","B":"By bringing more water to the desert,","C":"By using a giant shovel to dig deeper,","D":"By moving the rocks to Antarctica"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes how Chris used a helium balloon with a pump to sample the air to see if microbes were being blown in or living locally.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Some of the Atacama soil Chris collected did have live microbes. \u0027We wondered how they survived,\u0027 said Chris. \u0027Did they grow in the Atacama? Or were they blown in by the wind?\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q009","read_aloud":"What does the author mean by saying \"That\u0027s life!\" at the end of the sidebar? Options: A. Life is very simple to understand, B. The question of what makes something alive is complicated and debated, C. Viruses are definitely alive, D. Scientists do not like to study living things","excerpt":"\"Scientists are still arguing over [whether viruses are alive]. There\u0027s no easy answer. That\u0027s life!\"","stem":"What does the author mean by saying \"That\u0027s life!\" at the end of the sidebar? Options:","choices":{"A":"Life is very simple to understand,","B":"The question of what makes something alive is complicated and debated,","C":"Viruses are definitely alive,","D":"Scientists do not like to study living things"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses the phrase to show that the definition of life is a difficult, ongoing debate among scientists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists are still arguing over [whether viruses are alive]. There\u0027s no easy answer. That\u0027s life!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q010","read_aloud":"If you were designing a mission to look for life on a cold planet, what is one important thing you would include? Options: A. Only a camera to take pictures, B. A machine that can work in extreme cold and detect microbes, C. A giant heater to melt the whole planet, D. A large box to carry the rocks back home","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that... seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"If you were designing a mission to look for life on a cold planet, what is one important thing you would include? Options:","choices":{"A":"Only a camera to take pictures,","B":"A machine that can work in extreme cold and detect microbes,","C":"A giant heater to melt the whole planet,","D":"A large box to carry the rocks back home"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Based on Chris McKay\u0027s experiences in the Dry Valleys, the machines must be able to handle harsh, freezing conditions and be capable of finding microscopic life. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Life on Earth-and Beyond\" Author: Pamela S. Turner Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 2, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that... seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q011","read_aloud":"What is the best definition of \"astrobiologists\"? A. Scientists who study only stars B. Scientists who study life in the universe C. Scientists who build telescopes D. Scientists who study Earth\u0027s weather","excerpt":"\"astrobiologists scientists who study life in the universe\"","stem":"What is the best definition of \"astrobiologists\"?","choices":{"A":"Scientists who study only stars","B":"Scientists who study life in the universe","C":"Scientists who build telescopes","D":"Scientists who study Earth\u0027s weather"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly defines astrobiologists as scientists who \"study life in the universe.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"astrobiologists scientists who study life in the universe\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q012","read_aloud":"Which sentence best shows how \"sensors\" are used in the text? A. Sensors helped Chris cook meals in Antarctica B. Sensors measured light and moisture inside rocks to study how microbes survive C. Sensors were used to fly the helicopters to the Dry Valleys D. Sensors wrote the reports about the research","excerpt":"\"sensors devices that detect changes in light, moisture, or other physical conditions\"","stem":"Which sentence best shows how \"sensors\" are used in the text?","choices":{"A":"Sensors helped Chris cook meals in Antarctica","B":"Sensors measured light and moisture inside rocks to study how microbes survive","C":"Sensors were used to fly the helicopters to the Dry Valleys","D":"Sensors wrote the reports about the research"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Chris attached sensors to rocks to \"measure the light and moisture inside the rocks year-round\" to understand microbe survival. This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"sensors devices that detect changes in light, moisture, or other physical conditions\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q013","read_aloud":"Why is radiation a concern for possible life on Mars? A. Because it makes the planet too cold B. Because Mars\u0027 thin atmosphere cannot block it, so life would need shelter C. Because it helps plants grow faster D. Because it is a type of food for microbes","excerpt":"\"radiation dangerous energy rays that cannot be seen\"","stem":"Why is radiation a concern for possible life on Mars?","choices":{"A":"Because it makes the planet too cold","B":"Because Mars\u0027 thin atmosphere cannot block it, so life would need shelter","C":"Because it helps plants grow faster","D":"Because it is a type of food for microbes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that Mars\u0027 atmosphere is \"too thin to block dangerous radiation,\" so any life would need protection \"by rock or soil.\" This shows radiation is a hazard that shapes where life could survive.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"radiation dangerous energy rays that cannot be seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q014","read_aloud":"(Note: This is from previous text; correct excerpt for this selection:) What was the main goal of sending the rovers Spirit and Opportunity to Mars? A. To build a base for astronauts B. To search for evidence of past liquid water, which is needed for life C. To take pictures of Earth from Mars D. To mine rocks for valuable minerals","excerpt":"\"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist.\"","stem":"(Note: This is from previous text; correct excerpt for this selection:) What was the main goal of sending the rovers Spirit and Opportunity to Mars?","choices":{"A":"To build a base for astronauts","B":"To search for evidence of past liquid water, which is needed for life","C":"To take pictures of Earth from Mars","D":"To mine rocks for valuable minerals"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states the rovers were sent \"to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist.\" This was their primary mission.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q015","read_aloud":"What do these discoveries suggest about Mars\u0027 history? A. Mars has always been dry and lifeless B. Mars once had significant amounts of liquid water on its surface C. Mars is exactly like Earth today D. The rovers made mistakes in their measurements","excerpt":"\"Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a long-lost sea.\"","stem":"What do these discoveries suggest about Mars\u0027 history?","choices":{"A":"Mars has always been dry and lifeless","B":"Mars once had significant amounts of liquid water on its surface","C":"Mars is exactly like Earth today","D":"The rovers made mistakes in their measurements"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Soaked in water\" and \"long-lost sea\" are strong evidence that Mars once had liquid water. This supports the idea that Mars was wetter in the past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a long-lost sea.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q016","read_aloud":"(Note: Incorrect excerpt; correct one:) What comparison does the author make about the Dry Valleys? A. They are as busy as a city B. They are as empty and isolated as outer space C. They are as warm as a tropical island D. They are as colorful as a rainbow","excerpt":"\"The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space.\"","stem":"(Note: Incorrect excerpt; correct one:) What comparison does the author make about the Dry Valleys?","choices":{"A":"They are as busy as a city","B":"They are as empty and isolated as outer space","C":"They are as warm as a tropical island","D":"They are as colorful as a rainbow"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states the Dry Valleys are \"almost as lonely as outer space,\" emphasizing their emptiness and isolation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Dry Valleys are almost as lonely as outer space.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q017","read_aloud":"Based on the entire selection, if you were to create a poster encouraging support for astrobiology research, which message would best reflect the text\u0027s main ideas? Section A - Text Information Title: Life on Earth-and BeyondAuthor: Pamela S. Turner A. \"Space is empty, so we should not waste money studying it\" B. \"By studying life in Earth\u0027s extreme places, we learn where and how to search for life beyond our planet\" C. \"Only robots can do science; humans should stay on Earth\" D. \"All planets are exactly like Earth, so research is not needed\"","excerpt":"\"What can scientists discover by traveling to distant places?\"","stem":"Based on the entire selection, if you were to create a poster encouraging support for astrobiology research, which message would best reflect the text\u0027s main ideas? Section A - Text Information Title: Life on Earth-and BeyondAuthor: Pamela S. Turner","choices":{"A":"\"Space is empty, so we should not waste money studying it\"","B":"\"By studying life in Earth\u0027s extreme places, we learn where and how to search for life beyond our planet\"","C":"\"Only robots can do science; humans should stay on Earth\"","D":"\"All planets are exactly like Earth, so research is not needed\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The correct answer is supported by the details in the excerpt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"What can scientists discover by traveling to distant places?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q018","read_aloud":"What do astrobiologists study? A. Rocks and minerals B. Life in the universe C. Ocean animals D. Weather patterns","excerpt":"Yet the Dry Valleys fascinate astrobiologists like Chris McKay.","stem":"What do astrobiologists study?","choices":{"A":"Rocks and minerals","B":"Life in the universe","C":"Ocean animals","D":"Weather patterns"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Astrobiologists study life in the universe, including on Earth and other planets.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Yet the Dry Valleys fascinate astrobiologists like Chris McKay."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q019","read_aloud":"Why can\u0027t we see microbes without a microscope? A. They are invisible. B. They are too tiny. C. They live inside rocks. D. They run away.","excerpt":"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.","stem":"Why can\u0027t we see microbes without a microscope?","choices":{"A":"They are invisible.","B":"They are too tiny.","C":"They live inside rocks.","D":"They run away."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they are the tiniest of all living things and cannot be seen without a microscope.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q020","read_aloud":"Why is radiation dangerous on Mars? A. Because it heats the planet too much. B. Because the thin atmosphere cannot block it. C. Because it makes snow fall. D. Because it helps plants grow.","excerpt":"The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun.","stem":"Why is radiation dangerous on Mars?","choices":{"A":"Because it heats the planet too much.","B":"Because the thin atmosphere cannot block it.","C":"Because it makes snow fall.","D":"Because it helps plants grow."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Mars\u0027s atmosphere is too thin to block dangerous radiation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The atmosphere on Mars is too thin to block dangerous radiation from the sun."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q021","read_aloud":"What can you infer about why scientists study the Atacama? A. It has many people. B. It is very similar to Mars in dryness and appearance. C. It rains every day. D. It has polar bears.","excerpt":"The Atacama is even drier than Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys. … if the sky over the Atacama were reddish instead of blue, the superdry desert would look a lot like superdry Mars.","stem":"What can you infer about why scientists study the Atacama?","choices":{"A":"It has many people.","B":"It is very similar to Mars in dryness and appearance.","C":"It rains every day.","D":"It has polar bears."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly compares the Atacama to Mars in dryness and looks.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The Atacama is even drier than Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys. … if the sky over the Atacama were reddish instead of blue, the superdry desert would look a lot like superdry Mars."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q022","read_aloud":"What did the rovers prove about Mars? A. Mars has no rocks. B. Mars once had liquid water. C. Mars has cities. D. Mars is made of cheese.","excerpt":"Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a longlost sea.","stem":"What did the rovers prove about Mars?","choices":{"A":"Mars has no rocks.","B":"Mars once had liquid water.","C":"Mars has cities.","D":"Mars is made of cheese."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the rovers proved that Mars once had liquid water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a longlost sea."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q023","read_aloud":"Which place would you choose and why? A. A rainforest, because it has many animals. B. The Dry Valleys or the Atacama, because they are cold, dry, and Marslike. C. An ocean, because Mars has water. D. A volcano, because Mars has volcanoes.","excerpt":"The whole text.Imagine you are an astrobiologist. You must choose one place on Earth to study before sending a rover to Mars.","stem":"Which place would you choose and why?","choices":{"A":"A rainforest, because it has many animals.","B":"The Dry Valleys or the Atacama, because they are cold, dry, and Marslike.","C":"An ocean, because Mars has water.","D":"A volcano, because Mars has volcanoes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that these dry, cold places are the best Earth models for Mars conditions. Section A - Text information Title: Life on Earth-and Beyond Author: Pamela S. Turner","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text.Imagine you are an astrobiologist. You must choose one place on Earth to study before sending a rover to Mars."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q024","read_aloud":"Is there life on other planets? What does an astrobiologist do? A. studies only animals in zoos B. studies life in the universe and searches for life on other planets C. builds rockets for NASA D. studies only plants in rainforests","excerpt":"\"As an astrobiologist, Dr. Chris McKay studies life in the universe to answer an important","stem":"Is there life on other planets? What does an astrobiologist do?","choices":{"A":"studies only animals in zoos","B":"studies life in the universe and searches for life on other planets","C":"builds rockets for NASA","D":"studies only plants in rainforests"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says an astrobiologist studies life in the universe to answer questions about life on other planets.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As an astrobiologist, Dr. Chris McKay studies life in the universe to answer an important"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q025","read_aloud":"What do sensors do in this text? A. They cook food for the scientists. B. They detect and measure light and moisture inside rocks. C. They fly helicopters to the Dry Valleys. D. They write scientific reports.","excerpt":"\"On previous visits Chris had drilled tiny holes into the sandstone and attached sensors. The sensors measured the light and moisture inside the rocks year-round.\"","stem":"What do sensors do in this text?","choices":{"A":"They cook food for the scientists.","B":"They detect and measure light and moisture inside rocks.","C":"They fly helicopters to the Dry Valleys.","D":"They write scientific reports."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sensors measured light and moisture inside the rocks all year. They are devices that detect physical conditions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"On previous visits Chris had drilled tiny holes into the sandstone and attached sensors. The sensors measured the light and moisture inside the rocks year-round.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q026","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. The Dry Valleys are a warm and sunny place. B. The Dry Valleys are a harsh, cold place with months of darkness. C. The Dry Valleys have many animals. D. The Dry Valleys are close to the equator.","excerpt":"\"At the very bottom of the globe, in a land of ice and snow, there are great curving valleys of bare earth: Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys. It\u0027s a harsh place. In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The Dry Valleys are a warm and sunny place.","B":"The Dry Valleys are a harsh, cold place with months of darkness.","C":"The Dry Valleys have many animals.","D":"The Dry Valleys are close to the equator."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes the Dry Valleys as harsh, with ice and snow, and months of darkness when the sun doesn\u0027t rise.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the very bottom of the globe, in a land of ice and snow, there are great curving valleys of bare earth: Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys. It\u0027s a harsh place. In April, the beginning of the Antarctic winter, the sun goes down and doesn\u0027t come up again until September.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q027","read_aloud":"What was the last step in Chris\u0027s journey to the Dry Valleys? A. flying from San Francisco to New Zealand B. boarding the cargo plane to McMurdo Station C. flying in helicopters to the Dry Valleys D. packing the helicopters with gear","excerpt":"\"To reach the Dry Valleys, Chris flew from San Francisco, California, to New Zealand. In New Zealand he boarded an Air Force cargo plane to McMurdo Station in Antarctica. After stuffing two helicopters with camping gear, equipment, food, and water, the scientists flew to the Dry Valleys.\"","stem":"What was the last step in Chris\u0027s journey to the Dry Valleys?","choices":{"A":"flying from San Francisco to New Zealand","B":"boarding the cargo plane to McMurdo Station","C":"flying in helicopters to the Dry Valleys","D":"packing the helicopters with gear"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The last step was flying in helicopters to the Dry Valleys after packing them with gear at McMurdo Station.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To reach the Dry Valleys, Chris flew from San Francisco, California, to New Zealand. In New Zealand he boarded an Air Force cargo plane to McMurdo Station in Antarctica. After stuffing two helicopters with camping gear, equipment, food, and water, the scientists flew to the Dry Valleys.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q028","read_aloud":"What problem did the scientists face in Antarctica? A. They had too many machines that worked perfectly. B. The extreme cold made many machines fail and even froze the ink in pens. C. They did not bring enough machines. D. The weather was too warm.","excerpt":"\"Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought to Antarctica, only two, the spectrometer and one UV laser, were good at finding microbes. Even recording test results was difficult. The ink froze in Chris\u0027s pen!\"","stem":"What problem did the scientists face in Antarctica?","choices":{"A":"They had too many machines that worked perfectly.","B":"The extreme cold made many machines fail and even froze the ink in pens.","C":"They did not bring enough machines.","D":"The weather was too warm."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Four of six machines did not work well, and the ink froze in Chris\u0027s pen. The extreme cold caused these problems.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought to Antarctica, only two, the spectrometer and one UV laser, were good at finding microbes. Even recording test results was difficult. The ink froze in Chris\u0027s pen!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q029","read_aloud":"Why is the discovery of ancient water on Mars important? A. It proves Mars is a good place for swimming now. B. It shows that Mars once had conditions that could support life. C. It means Mars has no rocks. D. It shows that rovers are not useful.","excerpt":"\"There may be no liquid water on Mars now, yet the Mars rovers Spirit and Opportunity proved that once upon a time Mars did have liquid water-lots of it. Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a long-lost sea.\"","stem":"Why is the discovery of ancient water on Mars important?","choices":{"A":"It proves Mars is a good place for swimming now.","B":"It shows that Mars once had conditions that could support life.","C":"It means Mars has no rocks.","D":"It shows that rovers are not useful."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Water is needed for life. The rovers found evidence that Mars once had lots of water for hundreds of millions of years. This means life might have evolved there.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There may be no liquid water on Mars now, yet the Mars rovers Spirit and Opportunity proved that once upon a time Mars did have liquid water-lots of it. Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a long-lost sea.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q030","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q031","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q032","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. Tiny living things, B. Large space creatures, C. Specialized camera lenses, D. Types of rock formations","excerpt":"\"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"Tiny living things,","B":"Large space creatures,","C":"Specialized camera lenses,","D":"Types of rock formations"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that microbes are \"the tiniest of all living things,\" which is the definition of the word.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbes (also called microorganisms) are the tiniest of all living things. They are so small that they can\u0027t be seen without a microscope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q033","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They could build shelters for astronauts B. They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions C. They could grow food for the crew D. They could measure the distance to Earth","excerpt":"\"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They could build shelters for astronauts","B":"They could search for signs of life in harsh, Mars-like conditions","C":"They could grow food for the crew","D":"They could measure the distance to Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says these machines may go on a NASA mission to a planet that \"seems too cold and too dry for life,\" like the Dry Valleys. This suggests they could help search for life on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A spectrometer or UV laser may travel on a future NASA mission. The machines may land on a planet that-like the Dry Valleys-seems too cold and too dry for life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q034","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. Scientists expect every test to succeed B. Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments C. Scientists only share results when everything works D. Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail","excerpt":"\"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"Scientists expect every test to succeed","B":"Scientists learn from both successes and failures in their experiments","C":"Scientists only share results when everything works","D":"Scientists avoid testing ideas that might fail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The quote explains that science involves testing, and results can vary. This shows that scientists gain knowledge from both working and non-working experiments.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Science is all about testing new things and ideas. Sometimes things work out, and sometimes they don\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q035","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To carry people on long trips on Earth B. To explore the surface of a planet C. To fly through space at high speed D. To measure the temperature of stars","excerpt":"\"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To carry people on long trips on Earth","B":"To explore the surface of a planet","C":"To fly through space at high speed","D":"To measure the temperature of stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines rovers as \"vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"rovers vehicles used to explore a planet\u0027s surface\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q036","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. They built a base for human visitors B. They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface C. They took pictures of Earth from Mars D. They searched for other rovers that were lost","excerpt":"\"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"They built a base for human visitors","B":"They explored different areas on the planet\u0027s surface","C":"They took pictures of Earth from Mars","D":"They searched for other rovers that were lost"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes Spirit exploring Gusev Crater and Opportunity exploring Meridiani Planum. This shows they explored different surface areas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In January 2004 two robotic rovers landed on Mars. Spirit rolled through Gusev Crater. On the opposite side of the planet, Opportunity puttered around a dusty plain called the Meridiani Planum.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q037","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Water is needed for rockets to land safely B. Life as we know it needs liquid water to exist C. Water makes the soil easier to dig D. Water helps rovers move faster","excerpt":"\"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist. In searching for aliens, NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Water is needed for rockets to land safely","B":"Life as we know it needs liquid water to exist","C":"Water makes the soil easier to dig","D":"Water helps rovers move faster"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states NASA\u0027s motto is \"Follow the Water\" when searching for life, and they wanted to know if Mars had \"enough liquid water for life to exist.\" This shows water is key for life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"NASA sent the rovers to Mars to find out if the planet once had liquid water-enough liquid water for life to exist. In searching for aliens, NASA\u0027s motto is Follow the Water.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q038","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. To prove that no life can exist anywhere without water B. To understand the limits of life and compare to dry places like Mars C. To find new sources of drinking water for Earth D. To test how fast plants can grow in dry soil","excerpt":"\"They weren\u0027t \u0027following the water.\u0027 They were looking for spots with as little water as possible.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"To prove that no life can exist anywhere without water","B":"To understand the limits of life and compare to dry places like Mars","C":"To find new sources of drinking water for Earth","D":"To test how fast plants can grow in dry soil"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The scientists studied the extremely dry Atacama to see where life can and cannot survive. This helps them understand what to expect on dry planets like Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They weren\u0027t \u0027following the water.\u0027 They were looking for spots with as little water as possible.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q039","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. It is easy to find life if you look in the right place B. A planet might have life, but tests could miss it if they look in the wrong spots C. Only Earth has life in the universe D. Spacecraft should never land in deserts","excerpt":"If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet,","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"It is easy to find life if you look in the right place","B":"A planet might have life, but tests could miss it if they look in the wrong spots","C":"Only Earth has life in the universe","D":"Spacecraft should never land in deserts"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Chris says that if a Mars lander tested only the driest parts of the Atacama, it might wrongly conclude Earth has no life. This shows that where you look matters when searching for life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: If Viking had landed in certain areas of the Atacama, its tests would have said Earth is a dead planet,"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q040","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. A single microbe living alone B. A group of microbes living together in one spot C. A type of rock that microbes eat D. A machine that counts microbes","excerpt":"\"colony a group of animals living in one place\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"A single microbe living alone","B":"A group of microbes living together in one spot","C":"A type of rock that microbes eat","D":"A machine that counts microbes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines colony as \"a group of animals living in one place.\" For microbes, this means a group living together, as described in the rock pores.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"colony a group of animals living in one place\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. More dryness meant more microbes in the air B. Less dryness meant microbes could live in soil and get into the air C. Microbes lived only in the wettest parts of the desert D. Dryness had no effect on where microbes were found","excerpt":"\"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the super-dry spots had no microbes at all.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"More dryness meant more microbes in the air","B":"Less dryness meant microbes could live in soil and get into the air","C":"Microbes lived only in the wettest parts of the desert","D":"Dryness had no effect on where microbes were found"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows microbes were in the air over less dry areas but not over super-dry spots. This suggests microbes need at least a little moisture to survive and spread.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris found that the air over the less dry areas of the Atacama had microbes, while the air over the super-dry spots had no microbes at all.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q042","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. Life can survive anywhere if it tries hard enough B. Even on Earth, there are places too extreme for any life C. The Atacama is the only dry place on Earth D. Scientists should stop studying dry places","excerpt":"\"One thing is clear, however: in the very driest parts of the Atacama, nothing can survive. There does seem to be a limit to life on Earth.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"Life can survive anywhere if it tries hard enough","B":"Even on Earth, there are places too extreme for any life","C":"The Atacama is the only dry place on Earth","D":"Scientists should stop studying dry places"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that in the driest parts of the Atacama, \"nothing can survive,\" showing there are limits to where life can exist, even on Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One thing is clear, however: in the very driest parts of the Atacama, nothing can survive. There does seem to be a limit to life on Earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q043","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. They prove that humans once lived on Mars B. They show Mars once had liquid water, which is needed for life as we know it C. They found fossils of Martian animals D. They proved Mars is exactly like Earth today","excerpt":"\"Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a long-lost sea.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"They prove that humans once lived on Mars","B":"They show Mars once had liquid water, which is needed for life as we know it","C":"They found fossils of Martian animals","D":"They proved Mars is exactly like Earth today"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The rovers found evidence that Mars once had liquid water (\"soaked in water,\" \"long-lost sea\"). Since life needs water, this suggests life could have existed on Mars in the past.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Spirit found rock that had once been soaked in water. Opportunity discovered wavy bands of rocks formed by a long-lost sea.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q044","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 512. A. It helps them plan how long a mission should last B. Evolution of life takes a long time, so hundreds of millions of years gives life a chance to develop C. It proves that Mars will have water again soon D. It shows that Mars is older than Earth","excerpt":"\"Scientists think Mars\u0027s surface had water for hundreds of millions of years. That\u0027s enough time for life to have evolved.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 512.","choices":{"A":"It helps them plan how long a mission should last","B":"Evolution of life takes a long time, so hundreds of millions of years gives life a chance to develop","C":"It proves that Mars will have water again soon","D":"It shows that Mars is older than Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that life evolves over long periods. If Mars had water for \"hundreds of millions of years,\" that would be enough time for life to potentially develop, just as it did on Earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Scientists think Mars\u0027s surface had water for hundreds of millions of years. That\u0027s enough time for life to have evolved.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q045","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 513. A. Very small and simple B. Made of many parts; more advanced C. Easy to understand D. Found only on Earth","excerpt":"\"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 513.","choices":{"A":"Very small and simple","B":"Made of many parts; more advanced","C":"Easy to understand","D":"Found only on Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text contrasts \"simple\" microbial life with \"complex animals,\" suggesting complex means more advanced or made of many parts. This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Microbial life is the simplest kind. Complex animals take much longer to evolve.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q046","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 514. A. Water is important for cleaning and drinking B. Water allows the chemical reactions needed for life to occur C. Water is the most common substance in the universe D. Water is only important on Earth, not on other planets","excerpt":"\"Water is the essential molecule in the chemistry of life on Earth... Without water, the chemicals necessary for life couldn\u0027t find each other, mix with each other, and react with each other. Life would never happen.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 514.","choices":{"A":"Water is important for cleaning and drinking","B":"Water allows the chemical reactions needed for life to occur","C":"Water is the most common substance in the universe","D":"Water is only important on Earth, not on other planets"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt explains that water helps life\u0027s chemicals \"find each other, mix... and react.\" This shows water is essential for the chemistry of life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Water is the essential molecule in the chemistry of life on Earth... Without water, the chemicals necessary for life couldn\u0027t find each other, mix with each other, and react with each other. Life would never happen.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q047","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 515. A. Because cold temperatures can preserve evidence of life for a long time B. Because it would be easy for rovers to dig there C. Because it would be warm enough for life to grow today D. Because it would have more radiation than the surface","excerpt":"\"Chris thinks that evidence of early Martian life may be in a natural underground freezer on Mars. A natural underground freezer just like the one in Siberia.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 515.","choices":{"A":"Because cold temperatures can preserve evidence of life for a long time","B":"Because it would be easy for rovers to dig there","C":"Because it would be warm enough for life to grow today","D":"Because it would have more radiation than the surface"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The comparison to Siberia suggests that cold, frozen environments can preserve things for long periods. If Mars had an underground freezer, it might preserve signs of ancient life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris thinks that evidence of early Martian life may be in a natural underground freezer on Mars. A natural underground freezer just like the one in Siberia.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q048","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 516. A. Because all scientists agree on one definition B. Because some things, like viruses, have traits of life but not all, making the definition unclear C. Because aliens will not want to be studied D. Because definitions of life never change","excerpt":"\"So is a virus just a fancy bit of chemistry? Or is it possible for something to be half-alive? Scientists are still arguing over these questions. There\u0027s no easy answer. That\u0027s life!\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 516.","choices":{"A":"Because all scientists agree on one definition","B":"Because some things, like viruses, have traits of life but not all, making the definition unclear","C":"Because aliens will not want to be studied","D":"Because definitions of life never change"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The sidebar explains that viruses have some life traits (evolve, use energy) but not others (reproduce on their own). This shows that defining life is complex, which matters when looking for unfamiliar alien life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"So is a virus just a fancy bit of chemistry? Or is it possible for something to be half-alive? Scientists are still arguing over these questions. There\u0027s no easy answer. That\u0027s life!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q049","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 517. A. It shows both places are wet B. It shows the Atacama has even less moisture than the already very dry Dry Valleys C. It shows the Dry Valleys are warmer than the Atacama D. It shows both places have the same amount of rain","excerpt":"\"The Atacama is even drier than Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 517.","choices":{"A":"It shows both places are wet","B":"It shows the Atacama has even less moisture than the already very dry Dry Valleys","C":"It shows the Dry Valleys are warmer than the Atacama","D":"It shows both places have the same amount of rain"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Drier\" is a comparative word. Since the Dry Valleys are already described as very dry, saying the Atacama is \"even drier\" emphasizes its extreme lack of moisture.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The Atacama is even drier than Antarctica\u0027s Dry Valleys.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w2-life-on-earth-and-beyond-std-q050","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 518. A. To make the experiments easier to do B. To see if the experiments could detect life in a known place before trusting them on Mars C. Because they had no other experiments to use D. To prove that Mars is exactly like the Atacama","excerpt":"\"Chris and his colleagues tested the Atacama\u0027s soil and rocks for evidence of life. They tried some of the same soil experiments used by the Viking spacecrafts when they visited Mars in 1976.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 518.","choices":{"A":"To make the experiments easier to do","B":"To see if the experiments could detect life in a known place before trusting them on Mars","C":"Because they had no other experiments to use","D":"To prove that Mars is exactly like the Atacama"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By testing Mars-style experiments in the Atacama (a place they know has some life), scientists can check if the methods work. This helps them trust the results when using the same tests on Mars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Chris and his colleagues tested the Atacama\u0027s soil and rocks for evidence of life. They tried some of the same soil experiments used by the Viking spacecrafts when they visited Mars in 1976.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal","grade":5,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":1,"week":3,"title":"Ivy\u0027s Journal","author":"Lisa Benjamin","genre":"Historical Fiction","essential_question":"How can a journal reveal a person\u0027s life and time period?","weekly_question":"What does Ivy\u0027s journal show about her family and community?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["sharecropper","percentage","journal","crop","supplies"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"Ivy\u0027s Journal. What does Ivy\u0027s journal show about her family and community?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What is a sharecropper? Options: A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What is a sharecropper? Options:","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q002","read_aloud":"What special gift did Ivy receive for her twelfth birthday? Options: A. A new pair of shoes, B. An old shoebox, C. A journal, D. A photograph","excerpt":"\"Today is my twelfth birthday... I tore off the newspaper to find this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now!\"","stem":"What special gift did Ivy receive for her twelfth birthday? Options:","choices":{"A":"A new pair of shoes,","B":"An old shoebox,","C":"A journal,","D":"A photograph"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that Ivy opened her gift to find \"this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now!\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today is my twelfth birthday... I tore off the newspaper to find this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q003","read_aloud":"What did Ivy do after she ate dinner on her birthday? Options: A. She sang \"Happy Birthday,\" B. She went to her room and wrote her name in her journal, C. She looked for a present under the table, D. She opened an old shoebox","excerpt":"\"After we ate, I went to the room I share with my sister and brother. I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover: Ivy Mitchell.\"","stem":"What did Ivy do after she ate dinner on her birthday? Options:","choices":{"A":"She sang \"Happy Birthday,\"","B":"She went to her room and wrote her name in her journal,","C":"She looked for a present under the table,","D":"She opened an old shoebox"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly describes that after they ate, she went to her room and wrote her name in the journal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After we ate, I went to the room I share with my sister and brother. I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover: Ivy Mitchell.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q004","read_aloud":"Where does Ivy\u0027s family live? Options: A. Los Angeles, California, B. Mississippi, C. New York City, D. Chicago, Illinois","excerpt":"\"My family has a small farm in Mississippi, and I spent the day with my parents and siblings plowing the field and planting cotton seeds.\"","stem":"Where does Ivy\u0027s family live? Options:","choices":{"A":"Los Angeles, California,","B":"Mississippi,","C":"New York City,","D":"Chicago, Illinois"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states in the May 11 entry that Ivy\u0027s family has a small farm in Mississippi.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My family has a small farm in Mississippi, and I spent the day with my parents and siblings plowing the field and planting cotton seeds.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q005","read_aloud":"What kind of business does Mr. Greenfield run in town? Options: A. A school, B. A library, C. A store, D. A factory","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield also runs a store in town where we get everything we need for the farm, like seeds, fertilizer, and tools.\"","stem":"What kind of business does Mr. Greenfield run in town? Options:","choices":{"A":"A school,","B":"A library,","C":"A store,","D":"A factory"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that Mr. Greenfield runs a store where the family gets supplies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield also runs a store in town where we get everything we need for the farm, like seeds, fertilizer, and tools.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"sharecroppers\" most likely mean in this excerpt? A. farmers who own their land and keep all their crops B. farmers who pay rent by giving part of their crops to the landowner C. people who work in factories for wages D. people who sell crops at the market","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What does the word \"sharecroppers\" most likely mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"farmers who own their land and keep all their crops","B":"farmers who pay rent by giving part of their crops to the landowner","C":"people who work in factories for wages","D":"people who sell crops at the market"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says sharecroppers \"pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\" This matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Ivy is sad about her birthday B. Ivy receives a surprise present on her birthday C. Ivy\u0027s family forgot her birthday D. Ivy doesn\u0027t like newspaper","excerpt":"\"Today is my twelfth birthday. When Mama called me for dinner, I found a present waiting for me at the table. It was wrapped in old newspaper, and I wondered what it could be.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Ivy is sad about her birthday","B":"Ivy receives a surprise present on her birthday","C":"Ivy\u0027s family forgot her birthday","D":"Ivy doesn\u0027t like newspaper"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes Ivy finding a present at the table on her birthday, which is the key event.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today is my twelfth birthday. When Mama called me for dinner, I found a present waiting for me at the table. It was wrapped in old newspaper, and I wondered what it could be.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q008","read_aloud":"According to this excerpt, why was Ivy surprised to get a present? A. Because she didn\u0027t like journals B. Because her daddy said not to expect presents that year C. Because it was wrapped in newspaper D. Because she already had a journal","excerpt":"\"I tore off the newspaper to find this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now! I was surprised to get a present at all because Daddy had told us not to expect anything for our birthdays this year.\"","stem":"According to this excerpt, why was Ivy surprised to get a present?","choices":{"A":"Because she didn\u0027t like journals","B":"Because her daddy said not to expect presents that year","C":"Because it was wrapped in newspaper","D":"Because she already had a journal"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states Ivy was surprised \"because Daddy had told us not to expect anything for our birthdays this year.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I tore off the newspaper to find this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now! I was surprised to get a present at all because Daddy had told us not to expect anything for our birthdays this year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q009","read_aloud":"What did Ivy write in her new journal first? A. A story about her day B. Her name and the year C. A letter to her friend D. A poem about Mississippi","excerpt":"\"After we ate, I went to the room I share with my sister and brother. I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover: Ivy Mitchell. Below that, I added the year: 1942.\"","stem":"What did Ivy write in her new journal first?","choices":{"A":"A story about her day","B":"Her name and the year","C":"A letter to her friend","D":"A poem about Mississippi"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The excerpt clearly states Ivy wrote her name \"Ivy Mitchell\" and the year \"1942\" in the journal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After we ate, I went to the room I share with my sister and brother. I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover: Ivy Mitchell. Below that, I added the year: 1942.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q010","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy keep these items in a shoebox? A. Because they are valuable and worth money B. Because they are special things she loves C. Because she needs to sell them someday D. Because her parents told her to","excerpt":"\"Then I pulled out an old shoebox I keep under my bed. It holds all the things I love most in the world: a bright, white pebble, a dried red rose pressed flat, and an old-fashioned hair comb.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy keep these items in a shoebox?","choices":{"A":"Because they are valuable and worth money","B":"Because they are special things she loves","C":"Because she needs to sell them someday","D":"Because her parents told her to"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the shoebox \"holds all the things I love most in the world,\" showing these items are special to Ivy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then I pulled out an old shoebox I keep under my bed. It holds all the things I love most in the world: a bright, white pebble, a dried red rose pressed flat, and an old-fashioned hair comb.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"journal\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. A newspaper B. A book for writing personal thoughts C. A school textbook D. A letter to a friend","excerpt":"\"I tore off the newspaper to find this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now!\"","stem":"What does \"journal\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"A newspaper","B":"A book for writing personal thoughts","C":"A school textbook","D":"A letter to a friend"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy writes in the journal, so it is a book for recording her thoughts and experiences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I tore off the newspaper to find this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q012","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of these sentences? A. The farm is doing very well. B. Ivy\u0027s family does not have much money, but they bought her a gift. C. Ivy does not like her journal. D. Ivy\u0027s parents are angry.","excerpt":"\"Our farm is struggling, and money is tight. I don\u0027t know how my parents found a way to buy the journal, but I\u0027m so grateful that they did!\"","stem":"What is the main idea of these sentences?","choices":{"A":"The farm is doing very well.","B":"Ivy\u0027s family does not have much money, but they bought her a gift.","C":"Ivy does not like her journal.","D":"Ivy\u0027s parents are angry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says money is tight, but her parents still bought the journal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our farm is struggling, and money is tight. I don\u0027t know how my parents found a way to buy the journal, but I\u0027m so grateful that they did!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What three things does Ivy keep in her shoebox? A. A book, a pen, and a letter B. A pebble, a rose, and a hair comb C. A doll, a dress, and a shoe D. A photograph, a key, and a coin","excerpt":"\"Then I pulled out an old shoebox I keep under my bed. It holds all the things I love most in the world: a bright, white pebble, a dried red rose pressed flat, and an old‑fashioned hair comb.\"","stem":"What three things does Ivy keep in her shoebox?","choices":{"A":"A book, a pen, and a letter","B":"A pebble, a rose, and a hair comb","C":"A doll, a dress, and a shoe","D":"A photograph, a key, and a coin"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text lists a pebble, a dried rose, and a hair comb.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then I pulled out an old shoebox I keep under my bed. It holds all the things I love most in the world: a bright, white pebble, a dried red rose pressed flat, and an old‑fashioned hair comb.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q014","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy put a photo in her journal? A. To hide it from her family B. To start decorating her journal with something special C. To throw it away D. To give it to her friend","excerpt":"\"Then I put some glue on the back of the photo and pressed it inside the journal, below my name. \u0027There,\u0027 I said to myself, \u0027that\u0027s a good start.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Ivy put a photo in her journal?","choices":{"A":"To hide it from her family","B":"To start decorating her journal with something special","C":"To throw it away","D":"To give it to her friend"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She calls it \"a good start,\" meaning she is beginning to make the journal her own.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Then I put some glue on the back of the photo and pressed it inside the journal, below my name. \u0027There,\u0027 I said to myself, \u0027that\u0027s a good start.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What are sharecroppers? A. farmers who own their own land B. farmers who pay rent with a percentage of their crop C. people who work in factories D. people who own stores in town","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What are sharecroppers?","choices":{"A":"farmers who own their own land","B":"farmers who pay rent with a percentage of their crop","C":"people who work in factories","D":"people who own stores in town"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says sharecroppers pay rent by giving a large percentage of their crop to the landowner. Mr. Greenfield owns the land, and Ivy\u0027s family pays him with their crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What was Ivy\u0027s birthday present? A. a new dress B. a journal C. a book D. a toy","excerpt":"\"I tore off the newspaper to find this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now!\"","stem":"What was Ivy\u0027s birthday present?","choices":{"A":"a new dress","B":"a journal","C":"a book","D":"a toy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Ivy tore off the newspaper and found the journal she is writing in. Her present was a journal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I tore off the newspaper to find this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q017","read_aloud":"Why did Ivy not expect a birthday present? A. Because she was naughty. B. Because her family\u0027s farm is struggling and they do not have much money. C. Because she already has too many toys. D. Because her birthday is not important.","excerpt":"\"I was surprised to get a present at all because Daddy had told us not to expect anything for our birthdays this year. Our farm is struggling, and money is tight.\"","stem":"Why did Ivy not expect a birthday present?","choices":{"A":"Because she was naughty.","B":"Because her family\u0027s farm is struggling and they do not have much money.","C":"Because she already has too many toys.","D":"Because her birthday is not important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the farm is struggling and money is tight. This means the family does not have much money to buy presents.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I was surprised to get a present at all because Daddy had told us not to expect anything for our birthdays this year. Our farm is struggling, and money is tight.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q018","read_aloud":"What year does Ivy write in her journal? A. 1940 B. 1941 C. 1942 D. 1943","excerpt":"\"I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover: Ivy Mitchell. Below that, I added the year: 1942.\"","stem":"What year does Ivy write in her journal?","choices":{"A":"1940","B":"1941","C":"1942","D":"1943"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text clearly states that Ivy added the year 1942 below her name in the journal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover: Ivy Mitchell. Below that, I added the year: 1942.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q019","read_aloud":"What does the word \"discrimination\" mean? Options:? A. Unfair treatment of a group based on race, B. Moving from one home to another, C. Working hard on a farm, D. A type of school building","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face. So, many black people are stuck working on small farms and facing a mountain of debt.\"","stem":"What does the word \"discrimination\" mean? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Unfair treatment of a group based on race,","B":"Moving from one home to another,","C":"Working hard on a farm,","D":"A type of school building"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The glossary defines discrimination as the unfair treatment of a group of people based on categories like race.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face. So, many black people are stuck working on small farms and facing a mountain of debt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q020","read_aloud":"How is the school for white children different from Ivy\u0027s school? Options:? A. It is further away from home, B. It is nicer and does not have a hole in the roof, C. It has fewer books for the students, D. It is smaller than Ivy\u0027s school","excerpt":"\"The school for white children is not only closer, it\u0027s also nicer. It doesn\u0027t have a hole in the roof like my school does.\"","stem":"How is the school for white children different from Ivy\u0027s school? Options:?","choices":{"A":"It is further away from home,","B":"It is nicer and does not have a hole in the roof,","C":"It has fewer books for the students,","D":"It is smaller than Ivy\u0027s school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly compares the schools and mentions the hole in the roof of Ivy\u0027s school as a problem the other school does not have.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The school for white children is not only closer, it\u0027s also nicer. It doesn\u0027t have a hole in the roof like my school does.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q021","read_aloud":"What caused Ivy to get wet on her walk home? Options:? A. She fell into a creek, B. She had to cross a river, C. A heavy rainstorm began, D. She was washing dishes","excerpt":"\"I got soaking wet walking home from school today... Then buckets of rain began to fall from the sky.\"","stem":"What caused Ivy to get wet on her walk home? Options:?","choices":{"A":"She fell into a creek,","B":"She had to cross a river,","C":"A heavy rainstorm began,","D":"She was washing dishes"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy explains that it started to rain, and then \"buckets of rain began to fall,\" causing her to get soaked.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I got soaking wet walking home from school today... Then buckets of rain began to fall from the sky.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q022","read_aloud":"What does Mr. Greenfield\u0027s comment to Ivy\u0027s father show about his personality? Options:? A. He is kind and helpful, B. He is mean and disrespectful, C. He is a hard worker on the farm, D. He is worried about the family","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield makes me nervous... I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\"","stem":"What does Mr. Greenfield\u0027s comment to Ivy\u0027s father show about his personality? Options:?","choices":{"A":"He is kind and helpful,","B":"He is mean and disrespectful,","C":"He is a hard worker on the farm,","D":"He is worried about the family"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"His harsh tone and calling an adult \"boy\" demonstrate his disrespectful and mean attitude.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield makes me nervous... I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q023","read_aloud":"What does \"war effort\" mean in the text? Options:? A. A type of airplane engine, B. Working hard to help the military during a war, C. Fighting in a battle on the front lines, D. Traveling to a new city to find work","excerpt":"\"The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\"","stem":"What does \"war effort\" mean in the text? Options:?","choices":{"A":"A type of airplane engine,","B":"Working hard to help the military during a war,","C":"Fighting in a battle on the front lines,","D":"Traveling to a new city to find work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The glossary defines war effort as the pulling together of people and resources to support the military during a war.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q024","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy\u0027s father struggle to make money? Options:? A. He does not want to work in a store, B. There are no factories in the South, C. Local businesses refuse to hire black workers, D. He prefers to work on a farm","excerpt":"\"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy\u0027s father struggle to make money? Options:?","choices":{"A":"He does not want to work in a store,","B":"There are no factories in the South,","C":"Local businesses refuse to hire black workers,","D":"He prefers to work on a farm"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that local stores and factories will not hire black workers, limiting his job opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l01-q025","read_aloud":"Where did Uncle Eugene move to find work? Options:? A. New York, B. Mississippi, C. Los Angeles, California, D. Chicago","excerpt":"\"He took a train all the way out west and moved to a city called Los Angeles in California... he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes.\"","stem":"Where did Uncle Eugene move to find work? Options:?","choices":{"A":"New York,","B":"Mississippi,","C":"Los Angeles, California,","D":"Chicago"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states clearly that Uncle Eugene moved to Los Angeles, California.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He took a train all the way out west and moved to a city called Los Angeles in California... he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q001","read_aloud":"What does the word \"discrimination\" mean? Options: A. Unfair treatment of a group based on race, B. Moving from one home to another, C. Working hard on a farm, D. A type of school building","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face. So, many black people are stuck working on small farms and facing a mountain of debt.\"","stem":"What does the word \"discrimination\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"Unfair treatment of a group based on race,","B":"Moving from one home to another,","C":"Working hard on a farm,","D":"A type of school building"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The glossary defines discrimination as the unfair treatment of a group of people based on categories like race.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face. So, many black people are stuck working on small farms and facing a mountain of debt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q002","read_aloud":"How is the school for white children different from Ivy\u0027s school? Options: A. It is further away from home, B. It is nicer and does not have a hole in the roof, C. It has fewer books for the students, D. It is smaller than Ivy\u0027s school","excerpt":"\"The school for white children is not only closer, it\u0027s also nicer. It doesn\u0027t have a hole in the roof like my school does.\"","stem":"How is the school for white children different from Ivy\u0027s school? Options:","choices":{"A":"It is further away from home,","B":"It is nicer and does not have a hole in the roof,","C":"It has fewer books for the students,","D":"It is smaller than Ivy\u0027s school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly compares the schools and mentions the hole in the roof of Ivy\u0027s school as a problem the other school does not have.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The school for white children is not only closer, it\u0027s also nicer. It doesn\u0027t have a hole in the roof like my school does.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q003","read_aloud":"What caused Ivy to get wet on her walk home? Options: A. She fell into a creek, B. She had to cross a river, C. A heavy rainstorm began, D. She was washing dishes","excerpt":"\"I got soaking wet walking home from school today... Then buckets of rain began to fall from the sky.\"","stem":"What caused Ivy to get wet on her walk home? Options:","choices":{"A":"She fell into a creek,","B":"She had to cross a river,","C":"A heavy rainstorm began,","D":"She was washing dishes"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy explains that it started to rain, and then \"buckets of rain began to fall,\" causing her to get soaked.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I got soaking wet walking home from school today... Then buckets of rain began to fall from the sky.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q004","read_aloud":"What does Mr. Greenfield\u0027s comment to Ivy\u0027s father show about his personality? Options: A. He is kind and helpful, B. He is mean and disrespectful, C. He is a hard worker on the farm, D. He is worried about the family","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield makes me nervous... I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\"","stem":"What does Mr. Greenfield\u0027s comment to Ivy\u0027s father show about his personality? Options:","choices":{"A":"He is kind and helpful,","B":"He is mean and disrespectful,","C":"He is a hard worker on the farm,","D":"He is worried about the family"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"His harsh tone and calling an adult \"boy\" demonstrate his disrespectful and mean attitude.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield makes me nervous... I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q005","read_aloud":"In this context, what does being a \"sharecropper\" mean for Ivy\u0027s family? A. They own their farm and make all their own decisions B. They work land owned by someone else and give part of their crop as payment C. They work for wages at a factory D. They travel from farm to farm looking for work","excerpt":"\"We all help out on our farm, even Buck. Days like today, we have to skip school to plant seeds or pick cotton. But I don\u0027t have a choice, because there\u0027s no one to work on the farm but us. That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers.\"","stem":"In this context, what does being a \"sharecropper\" mean for Ivy\u0027s family?","choices":{"A":"They own their farm and make all their own decisions","B":"They work land owned by someone else and give part of their crop as payment","C":"They work for wages at a factory","D":"They travel from farm to farm looking for work"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that sharecroppers like Ivy\u0027s family work land they don\u0027t own and pay rent through their crops.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"We all help out on our farm, even Buck. Days like today, we have to skip school to plant seeds or pick cotton. But I don\u0027t have a choice, because there\u0027s no one to work on the farm but us. That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What problem does Ivy\u0027s family face with Mr. Greenfield\u0027s store? A. The store is too far away to reach B. They owe money for supplies and struggle to pay it back C. The store doesn\u0027t sell what they need D. Mr. Greenfield refuses to sell to them","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield also runs a store in town where we get everything we need for the farm, like seeds, fertilizer, and tools. We also owe him for that, and it\u0027s hard to grow enough cotton to pay for everything.\"","stem":"What problem does Ivy\u0027s family face with Mr. Greenfield\u0027s store?","choices":{"A":"The store is too far away to reach","B":"They owe money for supplies and struggle to pay it back","C":"The store doesn\u0027t sell what they need","D":"Mr. Greenfield refuses to sell to them"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The excerpt states they \"owe him for that\" and \"it\u0027s hard to grow enough cotton to pay for everything.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield also runs a store in town where we get everything we need for the farm, like seeds, fertilizer, and tools. We also owe him for that, and it\u0027s hard to grow enough cotton to pay for everything.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What does Ivy hope will happen this year? A. That Mr. Greenfield will forgive their debt B. That they will have a good cotton crop to help pay their debt C. That they will move to a different farm D. That they won\u0027t have to work anymore","excerpt":"\"I once heard Mama whisper to Daddy, \u0027We can never get out from under this debt if he piles on more and more each year.\u0027 I\u0027m crossing my fingers that we have a good crop this year.\"","stem":"What does Ivy hope will happen this year?","choices":{"A":"That Mr. Greenfield will forgive their debt","B":"That they will have a good cotton crop to help pay their debt","C":"That they will move to a different farm","D":"That they won\u0027t have to work anymore"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy says she\u0027s \"crossing my fingers that we have a good crop this year\" after discussing their debt, showing she hopes a good crop will help them pay what they owe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I once heard Mama whisper to Daddy, \u0027We can never get out from under this debt if he piles on more and more each year.\u0027 I\u0027m crossing my fingers that we have a good crop this year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q008","read_aloud":"According to this excerpt, why can\u0027t Ivy go to the closer school? A. Because it\u0027s too expensive B. Because only white children are allowed to attend that school C. Because her parents don\u0027t want her to go there D. Because the school is full","excerpt":"\"But my school is far away, and it\u0027s a long walk there and back. There\u0027s another school that\u0027s much closer; it\u0027s only half a mile from home. But Eve and I are not allowed to go there. Only white children can attend that school.\"","stem":"According to this excerpt, why can\u0027t Ivy go to the closer school?","choices":{"A":"Because it\u0027s too expensive","B":"Because only white children are allowed to attend that school","C":"Because her parents don\u0027t want her to go there","D":"Because the school is full"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states \"Only white children can attend that school.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But my school is far away, and it\u0027s a long walk there and back. There\u0027s another school that\u0027s much closer; it\u0027s only half a mile from home. But Eve and I are not allowed to go there. Only white children can attend that school.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q009","read_aloud":"How is Ivy\u0027s school different from the school for white children? A. Ivy\u0027s school has more books and better facilities B. Ivy\u0027s school has fewer resources and students must share books C. Ivy\u0027s school is closer to home D. Ivy\u0027s school has smaller classes","excerpt":"\"The school for white children is not only closer, it\u0027s also nicer. It doesn\u0027t have a hole in the roof like my school does. Each student has his or her own books, too. At my school, we have to share, and Eve and I sit together so we can pass a set of math, science, reading, and history books back and forth or read over each other\u0027s shoulders.\"","stem":"How is Ivy\u0027s school different from the school for white children?","choices":{"A":"Ivy\u0027s school has more books and better facilities","B":"Ivy\u0027s school has fewer resources and students must share books","C":"Ivy\u0027s school is closer to home","D":"Ivy\u0027s school has smaller classes"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The excerpt describes how Ivy\u0027s school has a hole in the roof and students must share books, while the white children\u0027s school is nicer with individual books for each student.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The school for white children is not only closer, it\u0027s also nicer. It doesn\u0027t have a hole in the roof like my school does. Each student has his or her own books, too. At my school, we have to share, and Eve and I sit together so we can pass a set of math, science, reading, and history books back and forth or read over each other\u0027s shoulders.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"sharecroppers\" mean? A. Farmers who own their own land B. Farmers who pay rent with part of their crop C. People who work in factories D. People who do not farm at all","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What does \"sharecroppers\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Farmers who own their own land","B":"Farmers who pay rent with part of their crop","C":"People who work in factories","D":"People who do not farm at all"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says sharecroppers pay rent by giving a percentage of their crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q011","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy have to skip school sometimes? A. She is sick. B. She has to help on the farm. C. The school is closed. D. She does not like her teacher.","excerpt":"\"We all help out on our farm, even Buck. Days like today, we have to skip school to plant seeds or pick cotton. I don\u0027t like skipping school, because if I miss too many classes, it\u0027s hard to keep up.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy have to skip school sometimes?","choices":{"A":"She is sick.","B":"She has to help on the farm.","C":"The school is closed.","D":"She does not like her teacher."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says she skips school to plant seeds or pick cotton.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"We all help out on our farm, even Buck. Days like today, we have to skip school to plant seeds or pick cotton. I don\u0027t like skipping school, because if I miss too many classes, it\u0027s hard to keep up.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q012","read_aloud":"Why is it hard for Ivy\u0027s family to pay everything they owe? A. They do not work hard. B. Growing enough cotton to pay for everything is difficult. C. Mr. Greenfield gives them free supplies. D. They do not need seeds or tools.","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield also runs a store in town where we get everything we need for the farm, like seeds, fertilizer, and tools. We also owe him for that, and it\u0027s hard to grow enough cotton to pay for everything.\"","stem":"Why is it hard for Ivy\u0027s family to pay everything they owe?","choices":{"A":"They do not work hard.","B":"Growing enough cotton to pay for everything is difficult.","C":"Mr. Greenfield gives them free supplies.","D":"They do not need seeds or tools."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it is hard to grow enough cotton to pay for everything.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield also runs a store in town where we get everything we need for the farm, like seeds, fertilizer, and tools. We also owe him for that, and it\u0027s hard to grow enough cotton to pay for everything.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q013","read_aloud":"Who is Ivy\u0027s best friend? A. Mary B. Sally C. Eve D. Buck","excerpt":"\"I got soaking wet walking home from school today. I was with my best friend Eve when it started to rain. At first, it was just a few drops, but then buckets of rain began to fall from the sky.\"","stem":"Who is Ivy\u0027s best friend?","choices":{"A":"Mary","B":"Sally","C":"Eve","D":"Buck"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says, \"I was with my best friend Eve.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I got soaking wet walking home from school today. I was with my best friend Eve when it started to rain. At first, it was just a few drops, but then buckets of rain began to fall from the sky.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q014","read_aloud":"Why can\u0027t Ivy go to the closer school? A. It is too expensive. B. Only white children can attend. C. It is closed. D. She does not want to go.","excerpt":"\"There\u0027s another school that\u0027s much closer; it\u0027s only half a mile from home. But Eve and I are not allowed to go there. Only white children can attend that school.\"","stem":"Why can\u0027t Ivy go to the closer school?","choices":{"A":"It is too expensive.","B":"Only white children can attend.","C":"It is closed.","D":"She does not want to go."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says only white children can attend that school.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There\u0027s another school that\u0027s much closer; it\u0027s only half a mile from home. But Eve and I are not allowed to go there. Only white children can attend that school.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"war effort\" mean in this sentence? A. a war that is easy to win B. the pulling together of people and resources to support the military during a war C. a war that is over D. a war that only soldiers fight","excerpt":"\"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort.\"","stem":"What does \"war effort\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"a war that is easy to win","B":"the pulling together of people and resources to support the military during a war","C":"a war that is over","D":"a war that only soldiers fight"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the planes will carry supplies and soldiers. \"War effort\" means people and resources working together to help the military during a war.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What did Ivy do after writing her name in the journal? A. She went to sleep. B. She pulled out an old shoebox from under her bed. C. She ate dinner. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"I went to the room I share with my sister and brother. I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover. Then I pulled out an old shoebox I keep under my bed.\"","stem":"What did Ivy do after writing her name in the journal?","choices":{"A":"She went to sleep.","B":"She pulled out an old shoebox from under her bed.","C":"She ate dinner.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says after writing her name, Ivy pulled out an old shoebox she keeps under her bed. This is the next thing she did.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I went to the room I share with my sister and brother. I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover. Then I pulled out an old shoebox I keep under my bed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q017","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy have to skip school? A. Because she does not like school. B. Because her family needs her to work on the farm. C. Because the school is closed. D. Because she is sick.","excerpt":"\"Days like today, we have to skip school to plant seeds or pick cotton. I don\u0027t like skipping school, because if I miss too many classes, it\u0027s hard to keep up. But I don\u0027t have a choice, because there\u0027s no one to work on the farm but us.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy have to skip school?","choices":{"A":"Because she does not like school.","B":"Because her family needs her to work on the farm.","C":"Because the school is closed.","D":"Because she is sick."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says there is no one to work on the farm but her family. So Ivy has to skip school to help plant seeds or pick cotton.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Days like today, we have to skip school to plant seeds or pick cotton. I don\u0027t like skipping school, because if I miss too many classes, it\u0027s hard to keep up. But I don\u0027t have a choice, because there\u0027s no one to work on the farm but us.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q018","read_aloud":"Who owns the land that Ivy\u0027s family lives on? A. Ivy\u0027s father B. Mr. Greenfield C. The government D. Ivy\u0027s uncle","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Who owns the land that Ivy\u0027s family lives on?","choices":{"A":"Ivy\u0027s father","B":"Mr. Greenfield","C":"The government","D":"Ivy\u0027s uncle"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that Mr. Greenfield, a white businessman, owns the land that Ivy\u0027s family lives on.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q019","read_aloud":"What is a sharecropper? Options:? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What is a sharecropper? Options:?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q020","read_aloud":"What special gift did Ivy receive for her twelfth birthday? Options:? A. A new pair of shoes, B. An old shoebox, C. A journal, D. A photograph","excerpt":"\"Today is my twelfth birthday... I tore off the newspaper to find this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now!\"","stem":"What special gift did Ivy receive for her twelfth birthday? Options:?","choices":{"A":"A new pair of shoes,","B":"An old shoebox,","C":"A journal,","D":"A photograph"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that Ivy opened her gift to find \"this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now!\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today is my twelfth birthday... I tore off the newspaper to find this very journal that I\u0027m writing in now!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q021","read_aloud":"What did Ivy do after she ate dinner on her birthday? Options:? A. She sang \"Happy Birthday,\" B. She went to her room and wrote her name in her journal, C. She looked for a present under the table, D. She opened an old shoebox","excerpt":"\"After we ate, I went to the room I share with my sister and brother. I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover: Ivy Mitchell.\"","stem":"What did Ivy do after she ate dinner on her birthday? Options:?","choices":{"A":"She sang \"Happy Birthday,\"","B":"She went to her room and wrote her name in her journal,","C":"She looked for a present under the table,","D":"She opened an old shoebox"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly describes that after they ate, she went to her room and wrote her name in the journal.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After we ate, I went to the room I share with my sister and brother. I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover: Ivy Mitchell.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q022","read_aloud":"Where does Ivy\u0027s family live? Options:? A. Los Angeles, California, B. Mississippi, C. New York City, D. Chicago, Illinois","excerpt":"\"My family has a small farm in Mississippi, and I spent the day with my parents and siblings plowing the field and planting cotton seeds.\"","stem":"Where does Ivy\u0027s family live? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Los Angeles, California,","B":"Mississippi,","C":"New York City,","D":"Chicago, Illinois"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states in the May 11 entry that Ivy\u0027s family has a small farm in Mississippi.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My family has a small farm in Mississippi, and I spent the day with my parents and siblings plowing the field and planting cotton seeds.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q023","read_aloud":"What kind of business does Mr. Greenfield run in town? Options:? A. A school, B. A library, C. A store, D. A factory","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield also runs a store in town where we get everything we need for the farm, like seeds, fertilizer, and tools.\"","stem":"What kind of business does Mr. Greenfield run in town? Options:?","choices":{"A":"A school,","B":"A library,","C":"A store,","D":"A factory"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that Mr. Greenfield runs a store where the family gets supplies.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield also runs a store in town where we get everything we need for the farm, like seeds, fertilizer, and tools.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q024","read_aloud":"What does \"war effort\" mean in the text? Options:? A. A type of airplane engine, B. Working hard to help the military during a war, C. Fighting in a battle on the front lines, D. Traveling to a new city to find work","excerpt":"\"The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\"","stem":"What does \"war effort\" mean in the text? Options:?","choices":{"A":"A type of airplane engine,","B":"Working hard to help the military during a war,","C":"Fighting in a battle on the front lines,","D":"Traveling to a new city to find work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The glossary defines war effort as the pulling together of people and resources to support the military during a war.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l02-q025","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy\u0027s father struggle to make money? Options:? A. He does not want to work in a store, B. There are no factories in the South, C. Local businesses refuse to hire black workers, D. He prefers to work on a farm","excerpt":"\"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy\u0027s father struggle to make money? Options:?","choices":{"A":"He does not want to work in a store,","B":"There are no factories in the South,","C":"Local businesses refuse to hire black workers,","D":"He prefers to work on a farm"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that local stores and factories will not hire black workers, limiting his job opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"war effort\" mean in the text? Options: A. A type of airplane engine, B. Working hard to help the military during a war, C. Fighting in a battle on the front lines, D. Traveling to a new city to find work","excerpt":"\"The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\"","stem":"What does \"war effort\" mean in the text? Options:","choices":{"A":"A type of airplane engine,","B":"Working hard to help the military during a war,","C":"Fighting in a battle on the front lines,","D":"Traveling to a new city to find work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The glossary defines war effort as the pulling together of people and resources to support the military during a war.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q002","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy\u0027s father struggle to make money? Options: A. He does not want to work in a store, B. There are no factories in the South, C. Local businesses refuse to hire black workers, D. He prefers to work on a farm","excerpt":"\"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy\u0027s father struggle to make money? Options:","choices":{"A":"He does not want to work in a store,","B":"There are no factories in the South,","C":"Local businesses refuse to hire black workers,","D":"He prefers to work on a farm"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains that local stores and factories will not hire black workers, limiting his job opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q003","read_aloud":"Where did Uncle Eugene move to find work? Options: A. New York, B. Mississippi, C. Los Angeles, California, D. Chicago","excerpt":"\"He took a train all the way out west and moved to a city called Los Angeles in California... he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes.\"","stem":"Where did Uncle Eugene move to find work? Options:","choices":{"A":"New York,","B":"Mississippi,","C":"Los Angeles, California,","D":"Chicago"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states clearly that Uncle Eugene moved to Los Angeles, California.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He took a train all the way out west and moved to a city called Los Angeles in California... he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q004","read_aloud":"What happened to the cotton crop in October? Options: A. It grew very large and healthy, B. It was destroyed by boll weevils, C. It was ruined by a rainstorm, D. It was stolen by Mr. Greenfield","excerpt":"\"Boll weevils are a problem every year. But this time, there were so many that most of the crop was ruined!\"","stem":"What happened to the cotton crop in October? Options:","choices":{"A":"It grew very large and healthy,","B":"It was destroyed by boll weevils,","C":"It was ruined by a rainstorm,","D":"It was stolen by Mr. Greenfield"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that the boll weevils attacked the crop and ruined most of it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boll weevils are a problem every year. But this time, there were so many that most of the crop was ruined!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q005","read_aloud":"Why is the family planning to move to California? Options: A. To visit Uncle Eugene for a holiday, B. To find a job in a cotton field, C. To make more money and have more freedom, D. To get away from the rain in Mississippi","excerpt":"\"Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here.\"","stem":"Why is the family planning to move to California? Options:","choices":{"A":"To visit Uncle Eugene for a holiday,","B":"To find a job in a cotton field,","C":"To make more money and have more freedom,","D":"To get away from the rain in Mississippi"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explicitly mentions the goals of earning better money and escaping Jim Crow laws for more freedom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"segregation\" mean based on this excerpt? A. A system that brings all people together equally B. A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places C. A law that helps black people get better jobs D. A way to make schools better for everyone","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"What does \"segregation\" mean based on this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"A system that brings all people together equally","B":"A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places","C":"A law that helps black people get better jobs","D":"A way to make schools better for everyone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines segregation as \"a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people\" with separate facilities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q007","read_aloud":"What is the effect of Jim Crow laws according to this excerpt? A. They make life easier for black people in the South B. They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go C. They help black people get better education D. They allow black and white people to mix freely","excerpt":"\"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\"","stem":"What is the effect of Jim Crow laws according to this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"They make life easier for black people in the South","B":"They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go","C":"They help black people get better education","D":"They allow black and white people to mix freely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Jim Crow laws require separate sections and prevent black people from entering certain places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q008","read_aloud":"What does Ivy want based on this excerpt? A. To move to a different country B. To have the same rights and opportunities as white children C. To become a lawyer and change the laws D. To stop going to school","excerpt":"\"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\"","stem":"What does Ivy want based on this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"To move to a different country","B":"To have the same rights and opportunities as white children","C":"To become a lawyer and change the laws","D":"To stop going to school"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy directly states \"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\" after her mama explains Jim Crow limits opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q009","read_aloud":"What did Mr. Greenfield bring to Ivy\u0027s family? A. A gift for Ivy\u0027s birthday B. A bill showing how much money they owe C. New seeds for planting D. A letter from Uncle Eugene","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\"","stem":"What did Mr. Greenfield bring to Ivy\u0027s family?","choices":{"A":"A gift for Ivy\u0027s birthday","B":"A bill showing how much money they owe","C":"New seeds for planting","D":"A letter from Uncle Eugene"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Mr. Greenfield \"gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q010","read_aloud":"How does Mr. Greenfield treat Ivy\u0027s parents? A. With respect and kindness B. Like they are children and with disrespect C. Like they are his close friends D. Like they are business partners","excerpt":"\"He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children. I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\"","stem":"How does Mr. Greenfield treat Ivy\u0027s parents?","choices":{"A":"With respect and kindness","B":"Like they are children and with disrespect","C":"Like they are his close friends","D":"Like they are business partners"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states Mr. Greenfield \"is disrespectful\" and \"talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children. I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"segregation\" mean? A. Bringing people together B. Keeping groups of people apart C. Sharing everything equally D. Going to the same schools","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people.\"","stem":"What does \"segregation\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Bringing people together","B":"Keeping groups of people apart","C":"Sharing everything equally","D":"Going to the same schools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says segregation keeps white people apart from black people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q012","read_aloud":"How is Ivy\u0027s school different from the white children\u0027s school? A. Ivy\u0027s school has a hole in the roof. B. Ivy\u0027s school has newer books. C. Ivy\u0027s school is closer. D. Ivy\u0027s school has more students.","excerpt":"\"The school for white children is not only closer, it\u0027s also nicer. It doesn\u0027t have a hole in the roof like my school does. Each student has his or her own books, too.\"","stem":"How is Ivy\u0027s school different from the white children\u0027s school?","choices":{"A":"Ivy\u0027s school has a hole in the roof.","B":"Ivy\u0027s school has newer books.","C":"Ivy\u0027s school is closer.","D":"Ivy\u0027s school has more students."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Ivy\u0027s school has a hole in the roof, and the white children\u0027s school does not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The school for white children is not only closer, it\u0027s also nicer. It doesn\u0027t have a hole in the roof like my school does. Each student has his or her own books, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What can you infer about how Ivy feels about segregation? A. She likes it. B. She thinks it is unfair. C. She does not care. D. She thinks it is funny.","excerpt":"\"I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\"","stem":"What can you infer about how Ivy feels about segregation?","choices":{"A":"She likes it.","B":"She thinks it is unfair.","C":"She does not care.","D":"She thinks it is funny."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy says she wishes they didn\u0027t have to live that way and wants the same rights as others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q014","read_aloud":"What did Mr. Greenfield give Ivy\u0027s father? A. A gift B. A job offer C. A bill for what they owe D. A new tractor","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\"","stem":"What did Mr. Greenfield give Ivy\u0027s father?","choices":{"A":"A gift","B":"A job offer","C":"A bill for what they owe","D":"A new tractor"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says he gave Daddy a bill for everything they owe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q015","read_aloud":"How does Ivy\u0027s father feel when Mr. Greenfield speaks to him? A. Happy B. Angry or upset C. Sleepy D. Surprised","excerpt":"\"I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\"","stem":"How does Ivy\u0027s father feel when Mr. Greenfield speaks to him?","choices":{"A":"Happy","B":"Angry or upset","C":"Sleepy","D":"Surprised"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"His jaw tightening shows he is trying to control his anger.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What is discrimination? A. the fair treatment of all people B. the unfair treatment of a group of people based on certain categories, such as race C. a way to help people find jobs D. a type of school","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people.\"","stem":"What is discrimination?","choices":{"A":"the fair treatment of all people","B":"the unfair treatment of a group of people based on certain categories, such as race","C":"a way to help people find jobs","D":"a type of school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes segregation as a system that keeps white and black people apart. Discrimination is the unfair treatment of people based on their race.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q017","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Segregation keeps white and black people apart in many places. B. Everyone in Mississippi is treated the same. C. There are no rules in Mississippi. D. Black people and white people go to the same schools.","excerpt":"\"We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains. At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Segregation keeps white and black people apart in many places.","B":"Everyone in Mississippi is treated the same.","C":"There are no rules in Mississippi.","D":"Black people and white people go to the same schools."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt describes how segregation works. It lists separate schools, bathrooms, water fountains, and sections at movies and restaurants. The main idea is that segregation keeps people apart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains. At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q018","read_aloud":"What does Mr. Greenfield sell at his store? A. clothes and shoes B. seeds, fertilizer, and tools for the farm C. food and candy D. books and paper","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield also runs a store in town where we get everything we need for the farm, like seeds, fertilizer, and tools. We also owe him for that, and it\u0027s hard to grow enough cotton to pay for everything.\"","stem":"What does Mr. Greenfield sell at his store?","choices":{"A":"clothes and shoes","B":"seeds, fertilizer, and tools for the farm","C":"food and candy","D":"books and paper"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Mr. Greenfield\u0027s store has seeds, fertilizer, and tools that Ivy\u0027s family needs for their farm.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield also runs a store in town where we get everything we need for the farm, like seeds, fertilizer, and tools. We also owe him for that, and it\u0027s hard to grow enough cotton to pay for everything.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q019","read_aloud":"What is Mama worried about? A. That the family will have too much money. B. That the family will never be able to pay off their debt to Mr. Greenfield. C. That Mr. Greenfield will give them free land. D. That they will grow too much cotton.","excerpt":"\"I once heard Mama whisper to Daddy, \u0027We can never get out from under this debt if he piles on more and more each year.\u0027\"","stem":"What is Mama worried about?","choices":{"A":"That the family will have too much money.","B":"That the family will never be able to pay off their debt to Mr. Greenfield.","C":"That Mr. Greenfield will give them free land.","D":"That they will grow too much cotton."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mama whispers that they can never get out from under the debt if Mr. Greenfield keeps adding more. She is worried about the growing debt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I once heard Mama whisper to Daddy, \u0027We can never get out from under this debt if he piles on more and more each year.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q020","read_aloud":"Why does the author include this detail about the black man who was beaten? A. To show that the South is a dangerous place for black people. B. To tell a funny story. C. To describe a happy event. D. To explain how to avoid bumping into people.","excerpt":"\"Last year, a black man in our town was beaten for accidentally bumping into a white man in the street. The South can be a very, very hard place for black people to live.\"","stem":"Why does the author include this detail about the black man who was beaten?","choices":{"A":"To show that the South is a dangerous place for black people.","B":"To tell a funny story.","C":"To describe a happy event.","D":"To explain how to avoid bumping into people."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author includes this detail to show that black people face danger and unfair treatment in the South. Ivy says the South can be a very hard place for black people to live.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Last year, a black man in our town was beaten for accidentally bumping into a white man in the street. The South can be a very, very hard place for black people to live.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. A system that brings all people together equally B. A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places C. A law that helps black people get better jobs D. A way to make schools better for everyone","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"A system that brings all people together equally","B":"A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places","C":"A law that helps black people get better jobs","D":"A way to make schools better for everyone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines segregation as \"a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people\" with separate facilities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l03-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. They make life easier for black people in the South B. They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go C. They help black people get better education D. They allow black and white people to mix freely","excerpt":"\"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"They make life easier for black people in the South","B":"They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go","C":"They help black people get better education","D":"They allow black and white people to mix freely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Jim Crow laws require separate sections and prevent black people from entering certain places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the context, what does \"integrated\" mean? Options: A. No longer separated by race, B. A place with very few students, C. A school that only white children attend, D. A type of school that has no textbooks","excerpt":"\"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together. We sit in the same classrooms, side by side, and no one thinks anything of it.\"","stem":"Based on the context, what does \"integrated\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"No longer separated by race,","B":"A place with very few students,","C":"A school that only white children attend,","D":"A type of school that has no textbooks"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that integrated means white and black children attend together, which is the opposite of segregation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together. We sit in the same classrooms, side by side, and no one thinks anything of it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q002","read_aloud":"How does the author explain the purpose of Jim Crow laws? Options: A. To help everyone learn in the same schools, B. To make sure everyone has a job at a factory, C. To keep black people from having equal opportunities, D. To teach people how to farm cotton","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027 Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do.\"","stem":"How does the author explain the purpose of Jim Crow laws? Options:","choices":{"A":"To help everyone learn in the same schools,","B":"To make sure everyone has a job at a factory,","C":"To keep black people from having equal opportunities,","D":"To teach people how to farm cotton"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text directly states that Mama says Jim Crow is a way to limit opportunities for black people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027 Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q003","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy\u0027s father stay quiet when Mr. Greenfield speaks to him disrespectfully? Options: A. He agrees with Mr. Greenfield, B. He is afraid of being hurt for talking back, C. He does not know what to say, D. He is tired from working all day","excerpt":"\"I could tell Daddy was trying not to answer angrily because men like Mr. Greenfield sometimes hurt Negroes for \u0027talking back.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does Ivy\u0027s father stay quiet when Mr. Greenfield speaks to him disrespectfully? Options:","choices":{"A":"He agrees with Mr. Greenfield,","B":"He is afraid of being hurt for talking back,","C":"He does not know what to say,","D":"He is tired from working all day"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text notes the father is trying not to answer because of the danger of being hurt for speaking up.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I could tell Daddy was trying not to answer angrily because men like Mr. Greenfield sometimes hurt Negroes for \u0027talking back.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q004","read_aloud":"Based on what you read about Jim Crow, why were the passengers separated on the train? Options: A. To keep the train balanced, B. Because the Jim Crow car was nicer, C. Because of laws requiring racial separation, D. Because the family had too much luggage","excerpt":"\"The train slowed to a stop, the doors opened, and we all climbed on board. Negro passengers had to sit in the Jim Crow car. It was separate from the rest of the train.\"","stem":"Based on what you read about Jim Crow, why were the passengers separated on the train? Options:","choices":{"A":"To keep the train balanced,","B":"Because the Jim Crow car was nicer,","C":"Because of laws requiring racial separation,","D":"Because the family had too much luggage"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes the separation as part of the Jim Crow system which keeps white and black people apart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The train slowed to a stop, the doors opened, and we all climbed on board. Negro passengers had to sit in the Jim Crow car. It was separate from the rest of the train.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q005","read_aloud":"Why is Ivy so amazed when she visits the library in California? Options: A. Because she has never been allowed in a library before, B. Because the library has no books, C. Because the library is very small, D. Because she does not like to read","excerpt":"\"I had never seen so many books in one place! Everywhere I looked, there were shelves and shelves filled with books.\"","stem":"Why is Ivy so amazed when she visits the library in California? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because she has never been allowed in a library before,","B":"Because the library has no books,","C":"Because the library is very small,","D":"Because she does not like to read"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"In her home state, she was not allowed to go to the library, so seeing a library full of books is a new and amazing experience.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I had never seen so many books in one place! Everywhere I looked, there were shelves and shelves filled with books.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"discrimination\" mean? A. Treating everyone exactly the same B. Unfair treatment of people based on their race or other characteristics C. Helping people find good jobs D. Making rules that benefit everyone equally","excerpt":"\"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"discrimination\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Treating everyone exactly the same","B":"Unfair treatment of people based on their race or other characteristics","C":"Helping people find good jobs","D":"Making rules that benefit everyone equally"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text shows discrimination means black workers are refused jobs that white workers can get, which is unfair treatment based on race.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q007","read_aloud":"Why did Uncle Eugene leave Mississippi? A. Because he wanted to visit California for vacation B. Because the bills got too high and he needed better opportunities C. Because he didn\u0027t like the weather D. Because he was forced to leave by Mr. Greenfield","excerpt":"\"Today, we got a letter from Mama\u0027s brother, Uncle Eugene. He used to be a sharecropper like us, but he left Mississippi not long ago when the bills got too high. At the beginning of the year, he took a train all the way out west and moved to a city called Los Angeles in California.\"","stem":"Why did Uncle Eugene leave Mississippi?","choices":{"A":"Because he wanted to visit California for vacation","B":"Because the bills got too high and he needed better opportunities","C":"Because he didn\u0027t like the weather","D":"Because he was forced to leave by Mr. Greenfield"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text says Uncle Eugene left \"when the bills got too high,\" showing he sought better opportunities elsewhere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today, we got a letter from Mama\u0027s brother, Uncle Eugene. He used to be a sharecropper like us, but he left Mississippi not long ago when the bills got too high. At the beginning of the year, he took a train all the way out west and moved to a city called Los Angeles in California.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q008","read_aloud":"How is work in California different from work in Mississippi for black people, according to Uncle Eugene\u0027s letter? A. Factories in California don\u0027t need many workers B. California factories hire black workers and women, unlike Mississippi C. Jobs in California pay less than sharecropping D. Black people can only work on farms in California too","excerpt":"\"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\"","stem":"How is work in California different from work in Mississippi for black people, according to Uncle Eugene\u0027s letter?","choices":{"A":"Factories in California don\u0027t need many workers","B":"California factories hire black workers and women, unlike Mississippi","C":"Jobs in California pay less than sharecropping","D":"Black people can only work on farms in California too"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Uncle Eugene\u0027s letter states factories \"need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs,\" contrasting with Mississippi where such jobs refused to hire black workers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q009","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, how could Ivy\u0027s family use this new rule to their advantage? A. They could ignore Mr. Greenfield\u0027s bills B. They could apply for factory jobs in California that now must hire without discrimination C. They could move back to their old farm D. They could stop working altogether","excerpt":"\"At dinner, Daddy told us that he had been asking our neighbors what they know about living and working in places like California. He found out that last year President Franklin Roosevelt signed a special order. It said companies that manufacture equipment for the military cannot practice discrimination.\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, how could Ivy\u0027s family use this new rule to their advantage?","choices":{"A":"They could ignore Mr. Greenfield\u0027s bills","B":"They could apply for factory jobs in California that now must hire without discrimination","C":"They could move back to their old farm","D":"They could stop working altogether"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The special order means military equipment factories can\u0027t discriminate, so Ivy\u0027s family could seek those jobs in California where they were previously excluded.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At dinner, Daddy told us that he had been asking our neighbors what they know about living and working in places like California. He found out that last year President Franklin Roosevelt signed a special order. It said companies that manufacture equipment for the military cannot practice discrimination.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q010","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt reveal about Ivy\u0027s hopes for the future? A. She wants to stay on the farm forever B. She dreams of having more choices and freedom in where she lives and works C. She wants to become a sharecropper like her parents D. She hopes to move back to Mississippi someday","excerpt":"\"I tried to picture what it might be like to live in a place where Negroes have more freedom. Where people like me could apply for any job they wanted. Maybe I didn\u0027t have to live on small farms all my life. Maybe one day, I could move somewhere else and do other kinds of work when I grow up.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt reveal about Ivy\u0027s hopes for the future?","choices":{"A":"She wants to stay on the farm forever","B":"She dreams of having more choices and freedom in where she lives and works","C":"She wants to become a sharecropper like her parents","D":"She hopes to move back to Mississippi someday"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy imagines \"a place where Negroes have more freedom\" and applying \"for any job they wanted,\" showing her hope for expanded opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I tried to picture what it might be like to live in a place where Negroes have more freedom. Where people like me could apply for any job they wanted. Maybe I didn\u0027t have to live on small farms all my life. Maybe one day, I could move somewhere else and do other kinds of work when I grow up.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"discrimination\" mean in this sentence? A. Treating people fairly B. Treating people unfairly because of their race C. Giving everyone the same job D. Helping people find work","excerpt":"\"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\"","stem":"What does \"discrimination\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Treating people fairly","B":"Treating people unfairly because of their race","C":"Giving everyone the same job","D":"Helping people find work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Discrimination means unfair treatment, here refusing to hire Negro workers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q012","read_aloud":"How is the Great Migration different in the past and \"today\" in the story? A. In the past, people went west; today, they go north. B. In the past, people went north; today, they go west. C. In the past, people stayed home; today, they move. D. There is no difference.","excerpt":"\"In the past, they traveled to New York, Philadelphia, Chicago, Detroit, and other cities in the North to find work. Today, a lot of people are heading out west to places like Los Angeles.\"","stem":"How is the Great Migration different in the past and \"today\" in the story?","choices":{"A":"In the past, people went west; today, they go north.","B":"In the past, people went north; today, they go west.","C":"In the past, people stayed home; today, they move.","D":"There is no difference."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says in the past people went north; now they go west to Los Angeles.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In the past, they traveled to New York, Philadelphia, Chicago, Detroit, and other cities in the North to find work. Today, a lot of people are heading out west to places like Los Angeles.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q013","read_aloud":"Based on this sentence, what kind of place does Ivy hope to find? A. A place with more farms B. A place with more freedom and job opportunities C. A place with colder weather D. A place with no schools","excerpt":"\"I tried to picture what it might be like to live in a place where Negroes have more freedom. Where people like me could apply for any job they wanted.\"","stem":"Based on this sentence, what kind of place does Ivy hope to find?","choices":{"A":"A place with more farms","B":"A place with more freedom and job opportunities","C":"A place with colder weather","D":"A place with no schools"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy imagines a place with more freedom and jobs for Negroes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I tried to picture what it might be like to live in a place where Negroes have more freedom. Where people like me could apply for any job they wanted.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q014","read_aloud":"Why is the ruined crop a serious problem for Ivy\u0027s family? A. They love eating cotton. B. They owe money to Mr. Greenfield and need the crop to pay him. C. They wanted to sell the cotton to buy toys. D. The boll weevils are their pets.","excerpt":"\"We picked for hours and hours until our fingers ached. But, sadly, we didn\u0027t have much to show for it. Boll weevils had attacked our crop. … most of the crop was ruined!\"","stem":"Why is the ruined crop a serious problem for Ivy\u0027s family?","choices":{"A":"They love eating cotton.","B":"They owe money to Mr. Greenfield and need the crop to pay him.","C":"They wanted to sell the cotton to buy toys.","D":"The boll weevils are their pets."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Earlier entries explain the family is in debt to Mr. Greenfield and needs the cotton crop to pay.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"We picked for hours and hours until our fingers ached. But, sadly, we didn\u0027t have much to show for it. Boll weevils had attacked our crop. … most of the crop was ruined!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q015","read_aloud":"What are boll weevils? A. small insects that feed on the fiber of cotton plants B. large birds that eat seeds C. helpful bugs that protect plants D. a type of fertilizer","excerpt":"\"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant.\"","stem":"What are boll weevils?","choices":{"A":"small insects that feed on the fiber of cotton plants","B":"large birds that eat seeds","C":"helpful bugs that protect plants","D":"a type of fertilizer"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says boll weevils are tiny bugs that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young hatch, they eat parts of the plant. They are pests that ruin cotton crops.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q016","read_aloud":"What effect did the boll weevils have on Ivy\u0027s family? A. They helped the cotton grow better. B. They ruined most of the cotton crop. C. They made the family rich. D. They scared away Mr. Greenfield.","excerpt":"\"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant. Boll weevils are a problem every year. But this time, there were so many that most of the crop was ruined!\"","stem":"What effect did the boll weevils have on Ivy\u0027s family?","choices":{"A":"They helped the cotton grow better.","B":"They ruined most of the cotton crop.","C":"They made the family rich.","D":"They scared away Mr. Greenfield."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says there were so many boll weevils that most of the crop was ruined. This means the family lost most of their cotton.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant. Boll weevils are a problem every year. But this time, there were so many that most of the crop was ruined!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q017","read_aloud":"What can you infer about how Daddy and Mama feel? A. They are happy and excited. B. They are worried because they cannot pay their debt. C. They are angry at Ivy. D. They are planning a party.","excerpt":"\"At the end of the day as we walked back to the house, I saw Daddy give Mama a look. I knew they were thinking about all of the money that we owe Mr. Greenfield, and I knew we have no way to pay it.\"","stem":"What can you infer about how Daddy and Mama feel?","choices":{"A":"They are happy and excited.","B":"They are worried because they cannot pay their debt.","C":"They are angry at Ivy.","D":"They are planning a party."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy sees Daddy give Mama a look and knows they are thinking about the money they owe. She knows they have no way to pay it. This shows they are worried.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the end of the day as we walked back to the house, I saw Daddy give Mama a look. I knew they were thinking about all of the money that we owe Mr. Greenfield, and I knew we have no way to pay it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q018","read_aloud":"Why does Mr. Greenfield make Ivy nervous? A. Because he is very kind and friendly. B. Because he frowns, is disrespectful, and talks to her parents like they are children. C. Because he gives them free gifts. D. Because he plays games with them.","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield makes me nervous. He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children.\"","stem":"Why does Mr. Greenfield make Ivy nervous?","choices":{"A":"Because he is very kind and friendly.","B":"Because he frowns, is disrespectful, and talks to her parents like they are children.","C":"Because he gives them free gifts.","D":"Because he plays games with them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Mr. Greenfield frowns a lot, is disrespectful, and talks to Ivy\u0027s parents like they are children. This rude behavior makes Ivy nervous.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield makes me nervous. He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q019","read_aloud":"Why is Mr. Greenfield\u0027s statement unfair? A. Because Ivy\u0027s family works very hard and is not lazy. B. Because he is giving them free money. C. Because he is helping them find a better job. D. Because he is being too nice.","excerpt":"\"\u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\"","stem":"Why is Mr. Greenfield\u0027s statement unfair?","choices":{"A":"Because Ivy\u0027s family works very hard and is not lazy.","B":"Because he is giving them free money.","C":"Because he is helping them find a better job.","D":"Because he is being too nice."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Mr. Greenfield knows they work hard and are not lazy. He also knows the children miss school to work on the farm. Calling them lazy is unfair.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. A system that brings all people together equally B. A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places C. A law that helps black people get better jobs D. A way to make schools better for everyone","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"A system that brings all people together equally","B":"A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places","C":"A law that helps black people get better jobs","D":"A way to make schools better for everyone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines segregation as \"a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people\" with separate facilities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. They make life easier for black people in the South B. They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go C. They help black people get better education D. They allow black and white people to mix freely","excerpt":"\"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"They make life easier for black people in the South","B":"They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go","C":"They help black people get better education","D":"They allow black and white people to mix freely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Jim Crow laws require separate sections and prevent black people from entering certain places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l04-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To move to a different country B. To have the same rights and opportunities as white children C. To become a lawyer and change the laws D. To stop going to school","excerpt":"\"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To move to a different country","B":"To have the same rights and opportunities as white children","C":"To become a lawyer and change the laws","D":"To stop going to school"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy directly states \"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\" after her mama explains Jim Crow limits opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q001","read_aloud":"What are \"boll weevils\"? Options: A. Types of farm machines, B. Small insects that eat cotton, C. A type of cotton plant, D. People who pick cotton","excerpt":"\"Boll weevils are a problem every year. But this time, there were so many that most of the crop was ruined! These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants.\"","stem":"What are \"boll weevils\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Types of farm machines,","B":"Small insects that eat cotton,","C":"A type of cotton plant,","D":"People who pick cotton"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines them as tiny pests that eat parts of the cotton plant.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boll weevils are a problem every year. But this time, there were so many that most of the crop was ruined! These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q002","read_aloud":"How does Ivy describe the difference between her new home and her old home? Options: A. Los Angeles is a small, quiet town, B. Mississippi is a big, busy city, C. Los Angeles is a large, busy city with palm trees, D. There is no difference between the two places","excerpt":"\"Los Angeles looks really different from Mississippi. This is a big city with houses, offices, and other buildings spread out all over. Palm trees line the streets-I\u0027d never seen a palm tree before.\"","stem":"How does Ivy describe the difference between her new home and her old home? Options:","choices":{"A":"Los Angeles is a small, quiet town,","B":"Mississippi is a big, busy city,","C":"Los Angeles is a large, busy city with palm trees,","D":"There is no difference between the two places"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy notes the size, the many buildings, and the presence of palm trees as big differences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Los Angeles looks really different from Mississippi. This is a big city with houses, offices, and other buildings spread out all over. Palm trees line the streets-I\u0027d never seen a palm tree before.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q003","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt tell you about Ivy\u0027s feelings toward the new city? Options: A. She is used to the noise and likes it, B. She is overwhelmed by the change and the noise, C. She thinks the city is too quiet, D. She wants to buy a car to make more noise","excerpt":"\"I wanted to cover my ears to block out all of the noise from the cars, buses, trucks, and their horns. It was so different from the quiet fields and dirt roads that I know from home.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt tell you about Ivy\u0027s feelings toward the new city? Options:","choices":{"A":"She is used to the noise and likes it,","B":"She is overwhelmed by the change and the noise,","C":"She thinks the city is too quiet,","D":"She wants to buy a car to make more noise"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The desire to cover her ears and her comparison to the quiet fields show she is adjusting to a difficult change.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I wanted to cover my ears to block out all of the noise from the cars, buses, trucks, and their horns. It was so different from the quiet fields and dirt roads that I know from home.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q004","read_aloud":"How does Ivy\u0027s point of view about Jim Crow laws affect her life? Options: A. She is happy to have fewer opportunities, B. She feels sad and wants equal rights, C. She does not notice the laws at all, D. She wants to move to a farm in the South","excerpt":"\"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way.\"","stem":"How does Ivy\u0027s point of view about Jim Crow laws affect her life? Options:","choices":{"A":"She is happy to have fewer opportunities,","B":"She feels sad and wants equal rights,","C":"She does not notice the laws at all,","D":"She wants to move to a farm in the South"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Her wish to have the same rights as other kids shows she understands the injustice of the situation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q005","read_aloud":"Why might Ivy feel nervous about her new neighborhood in California? Options: A. Because the apartment is too small, B. Because she misses Mr. Greenfield, C. Because she encounters unfriendly people who treat her differently, D. Because she does not want to go to school","excerpt":"\"We moved into our new apartment today, and it\u0027s bigger than the house we had in Mississippi... Mostly white residents live in this neighborhood, and we will be one of the few Negro families.\"","stem":"Why might Ivy feel nervous about her new neighborhood in California? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because the apartment is too small,","B":"Because she misses Mr. Greenfield,","C":"Because she encounters unfriendly people who treat her differently,","D":"Because she does not want to go to school"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text shows an example of a mother and son being unfriendly, indicating that discrimination still exists even in California.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"We moved into our new apartment today, and it\u0027s bigger than the house we had in Mississippi... Mostly white residents live in this neighborhood, and we will be one of the few Negro families.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q006","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, what are \"boll weevils\"? A. Helpful insects that protect cotton plants B. Small pests that damage cotton crops by eating the plants C. A type of fertilizer for farming D. Tools used to pick cotton","excerpt":"\"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant. Boll weevils are a problem every year.\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, what are \"boll weevils\"?","choices":{"A":"Helpful insects that protect cotton plants","B":"Small pests that damage cotton crops by eating the plants","C":"A type of fertilizer for farming","D":"Tools used to pick cotton"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines boll weevils as \"tiny bugs\" that \"eat parts of the plant\" and are \"a problem every year\" for cotton.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant. Boll weevils are a problem every year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What was the result of the boll weevil attack on Ivy\u0027s family\u0027s crop? A. They harvested more cotton than ever B. Most of their cotton crop was destroyed C. The boll weevils helped the cotton grow better D. They were able to sell the boll weevils for money","excerpt":"\"Harvest time is finally here, and our crop of cotton is ready to be picked... But, sadly, we didn\u0027t have much to show for it. Boll weevils had attacked our crop... But this time, there were so many that most of the crop was ruined!\"","stem":"What was the result of the boll weevil attack on Ivy\u0027s family\u0027s crop?","choices":{"A":"They harvested more cotton than ever","B":"Most of their cotton crop was destroyed","C":"The boll weevils helped the cotton grow better","D":"They were able to sell the boll weevils for money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states \"most of the crop was ruined\" because of the boll weevils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Harvest time is finally here, and our crop of cotton is ready to be picked... But, sadly, we didn\u0027t have much to show for it. Boll weevils had attacked our crop... But this time, there were so many that most of the crop was ruined!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q008","read_aloud":"Why is Ivy\u0027s family deciding to move to California? A. Because they want to visit Uncle Eugene for a short trip B. Because they hope for better jobs, more money, and more freedom there C. Because Mississippi has too much cotton to harvest D. Because California has no factories or jobs","excerpt":"\"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California... Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here.\"","stem":"Why is Ivy\u0027s family deciding to move to California?","choices":{"A":"Because they want to visit Uncle Eugene for a short trip","B":"Because they hope for better jobs, more money, and more freedom there","C":"Because Mississippi has too much cotton to harvest","D":"Because California has no factories or jobs"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains they\u0027re moving for \"a better life\" with higher-paying factory jobs and Mama mentions \"no Jim Crow laws\" meaning more freedom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California... Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q009","read_aloud":"If you were Ivy, what might be one challenge about moving to California? A. Finding a new school with Jim Crow laws B. Missing friends and adjusting to a completely new place C. Having too much money to spend D. Not being able to work in factories","excerpt":"\"Also, Mama says there are no Jim Crow laws in California, so we\u0027ll have so much more freedom. I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again! Also, I have only ever lived in Mississippi; I\u0027ve never even visited another state.\"","stem":"If you were Ivy, what might be one challenge about moving to California?","choices":{"A":"Finding a new school with Jim Crow laws","B":"Missing friends and adjusting to a completely new place","C":"Having too much money to spend","D":"Not being able to work in factories"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy expresses worry about leaving friends and never seeing them again, plus uncertainty about a place she\u0027s never visited, showing the emotional challenge of the move.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Also, Mama says there are no Jim Crow laws in California, so we\u0027ll have so much more freedom. I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again! Also, I have only ever lived in Mississippi; I\u0027ve never even visited another state.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q010","read_aloud":"What do these questions reveal about how Ivy feels about the move? A. She is completely excited and has no worries B. She feels hopeful but also nervous and uncertain about the change C. She is angry that her parents are making this decision D. She doesn\u0027t care about making friends","excerpt":"\"What if I hate California? What if no one likes me and I can\u0027t make any friends?\"","stem":"What do these questions reveal about how Ivy feels about the move?","choices":{"A":"She is completely excited and has no worries","B":"She feels hopeful but also nervous and uncertain about the change","C":"She is angry that her parents are making this decision","D":"She doesn\u0027t care about making friends"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Ivy\u0027s \"what if\" questions show she has hopes for California but also fears about fitting in and making friends, revealing mixed feelings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"What if I hate California? What if no one likes me and I can\u0027t make any friends?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What are \"boll weevils\"? A. Farmers who pick cotton B. Small insects that ruin cotton plants C. Machines for planting seeds D. A type of weather","excerpt":"\"These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant. Boll weevils are a problem every year.\"","stem":"What are \"boll weevils\"?","choices":{"A":"Farmers who pick cotton","B":"Small insects that ruin cotton plants","C":"Machines for planting seeds","D":"A type of weather"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they are tiny bugs that eat parts of the cotton plant.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant. Boll weevils are a problem every year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q012","read_aloud":"What happened before the family decided to move? A. They won a lot of money. B. The cotton crop was ruined by boll weevils. C. Ivy started a new school. D. They bought a new car.","excerpt":"\"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California. Daddy wrote Uncle Eugene for his help finding work.\"","stem":"What happened before the family decided to move?","choices":{"A":"They won a lot of money.","B":"The cotton crop was ruined by boll weevils.","C":"Ivy started a new school.","D":"They bought a new car."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The ruined crop comes right before the decision to move.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California. Daddy wrote Uncle Eugene for his help finding work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q013","read_aloud":"What two reasons does Ivy\u0027s family give for moving to California? A. Better schools and bigger houses B. More money and more freedom C. More friends and better weather D. Faster trains and bigger cities","excerpt":"\"Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here. Also, Mama says there are no Jim Crow laws in California, so we\u0027ll have so much more freedom.\"","stem":"What two reasons does Ivy\u0027s family give for moving to California?","choices":{"A":"Better schools and bigger houses","B":"More money and more freedom","C":"More friends and better weather","D":"Faster trains and bigger cities"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Daddy says more money; Mama says more freedom (no Jim Crow laws).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here. Also, Mama says there are no Jim Crow laws in California, so we\u0027ll have so much more freedom.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q014","read_aloud":"What mixed feelings does Ivy have about moving? A. She is only happy. B. She is only sad. C. She is excited but also worried about leaving friends and fitting in. D. She does not care at all.","excerpt":"\"I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again! Also, I have only ever lived in Mississippi; I\u0027ve never even visited another state. What if I hate California? What if no one likes me and I can\u0027t make any friends?\"","stem":"What mixed feelings does Ivy have about moving?","choices":{"A":"She is only happy.","B":"She is only sad.","C":"She is excited but also worried about leaving friends and fitting in.","D":"She does not care at all."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy is excited to move but also sad to leave friends and worried about a new place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again! Also, I have only ever lived in Mississippi; I\u0027ve never even visited another state. What if I hate California? What if no one likes me and I can\u0027t make any friends?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q015","read_aloud":"If you were traveling with Ivy\u0027s family, what problem would you have because of this rule? A. You could not eat in the dining car. B. You could not buy a ticket. C. You could not see out the window. D. You could not talk to your family.","excerpt":"\"Negro passengers had to sit in the Jim Crow car. It was separate from the rest of the train, where white passengers sat. We couldn\u0027t leave that one car, not even to go to the dining car to get a meal.\"","stem":"If you were traveling with Ivy\u0027s family, what problem would you have because of this rule?","choices":{"A":"You could not eat in the dining car.","B":"You could not buy a ticket.","C":"You could not see out the window.","D":"You could not talk to your family."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says they could not leave the Jim Crow car, not even to go to the dining car.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Negro passengers had to sit in the Jim Crow car. It was separate from the rest of the train, where white passengers sat. We couldn\u0027t leave that one car, not even to go to the dining car to get a meal.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What does \"integrated\" mean in this sentence? A. separated by race B. no longer subject to segregation; white and black children attend together C. only for white children D. only for black children","excerpt":"\"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together. We sit in the same classrooms, side by side, and no one thinks anything of it.\"","stem":"What does \"integrated\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"separated by race","B":"no longer subject to segregation; white and black children attend together","C":"only for white children","D":"only for black children"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says integrated means white and black children attend together. This is the opposite of segregation, where they are kept apart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together. We sit in the same classrooms, side by side, and no one thinks anything of it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q017","read_aloud":"Why was Uncle Eugene able to get a factory job in California? A. Because he was the best worker in Mississippi. B. Because President Roosevelt signed an order that said companies cannot discriminate based on race. C. Because Mr. Greenfield helped him. D. Because he did not need any skills.","excerpt":"\"He found out that last year President Franklin Roosevelt signed a special order. It said companies that manufacture equipment for the military cannot practice discrimination. That means they can\u0027t refuse to hire workers because of their race or ethnicity.\"","stem":"Why was Uncle Eugene able to get a factory job in California?","choices":{"A":"Because he was the best worker in Mississippi.","B":"Because President Roosevelt signed an order that said companies cannot discriminate based on race.","C":"Because Mr. Greenfield helped him.","D":"Because he did not need any skills."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says President Roosevelt signed a special order. Companies that make military equipment cannot discriminate. This means they must hire workers regardless of race.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He found out that last year President Franklin Roosevelt signed a special order. It said companies that manufacture equipment for the military cannot practice discrimination. That means they can\u0027t refuse to hire workers because of their race or ethnicity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q018","read_aloud":"What can you infer about how Ivy feels about moving? A. She is only excited and has no worries. B. She has mixed feelings-she is nervous about leaving friends but also hopeful about a better life. C. She does not care about moving at all. D. She wants to stay in Mississippi forever.","excerpt":"\"I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again! Also, I have only ever lived in Mississippi; I\u0027ve never even visited another state. What if I hate California? What if no one likes me and I can\u0027t make any friends?\"","stem":"What can you infer about how Ivy feels about moving?","choices":{"A":"She is only excited and has no worries.","B":"She has mixed feelings-she is nervous about leaving friends but also hopeful about a better life.","C":"She does not care about moving at all.","D":"She wants to stay in Mississippi forever."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy says she does not want to leave her friends. She also worries about making new friends. But she also knows California might offer a better life. This shows mixed feelings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again! Also, I have only ever lived in Mississippi; I\u0027ve never even visited another state. What if I hate California? What if no one likes me and I can\u0027t make any friends?\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q019","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about train travel for black people? A. They could sit anywhere they wanted. B. They were forced to sit in a separate car and could not use the dining car. C. They had better seats than white passengers. D. They did not have to pay for tickets.","excerpt":"\"Negro passengers had to sit in the Jim Crow car. It was separate from the rest of the train, where white passengers sat. We couldn\u0027t leave that one car, not even to go to the dining car to get a meal.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about train travel for black people?","choices":{"A":"They could sit anywhere they wanted.","B":"They were forced to sit in a separate car and could not use the dining car.","C":"They had better seats than white passengers.","D":"They did not have to pay for tickets."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says black passengers had to sit in a separate Jim Crow car. They could not leave that car, not even to get a meal. This shows unfair treatment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Negro passengers had to sit in the Jim Crow car. It was separate from the rest of the train, where white passengers sat. We couldn\u0027t leave that one car, not even to go to the dining car to get a meal.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q020","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy\u0027s family want to move to California? A. Because they want to live in a smaller house. B. Because factory workers make more money and there are no Jim Crow laws. C. Because they want to farm more cotton. D. Because Mr. Greenfield is moving there too.","excerpt":"\"Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here. Also, Mama says there are no Jim Crow laws in California, so we\u0027ll have so much more freedom.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy\u0027s family want to move to California?","choices":{"A":"Because they want to live in a smaller house.","B":"Because factory workers make more money and there are no Jim Crow laws.","C":"Because they want to farm more cotton.","D":"Because Mr. Greenfield is moving there too."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says factory workers in California make much more money. Also, there are no Jim Crow laws, so they will have more freedom. These are the reasons for moving.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here. Also, Mama says there are no Jim Crow laws in California, so we\u0027ll have so much more freedom.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. A system that brings all people together equally B. A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places C. A law that helps black people get better jobs D. A way to make schools better for everyone","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"A system that brings all people together equally","B":"A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places","C":"A law that helps black people get better jobs","D":"A way to make schools better for everyone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines segregation as \"a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people\" with separate facilities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l05-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. They make life easier for black people in the South B. They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go C. They help black people get better education D. They allow black and white people to mix freely","excerpt":"\"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"They make life easier for black people in the South","B":"They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go","C":"They help black people get better education","D":"They allow black and white people to mix freely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Jim Crow laws require separate sections and prevent black people from entering certain places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q001","read_aloud":"If you \"speed\" down the track, you are: Options: A. Moving very slowly, B. Moving very quickly, C. Stopping at a station, D. Walking on foot","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m trying to write, but the seats of the train are shaking as we speed down the track, so I\u0027ll keep this short.\"","stem":"If you \"speed\" down the track, you are: Options:","choices":{"A":"Moving very slowly,","B":"Moving very quickly,","C":"Stopping at a station,","D":"Walking on foot"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Speed\" in this context means moving at a high rate of speed or moving quickly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m trying to write, but the seats of the train are shaking as we speed down the track, so I\u0027ll keep this short.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q002","read_aloud":"Based on this, why is Ivy\u0027s family so worried about the cotton harvest? Options: A. They want to win a farming prize, B. They need to pay off their debt to Mr. Greenfield, C. They are planning to start a new business, D. They want to buy a new house in the country","excerpt":"\"Everything depends on this new crop. It\u0027s the only thing that will save us.\"","stem":"Based on this, why is Ivy\u0027s family so worried about the cotton harvest? Options:","choices":{"A":"They want to win a farming prize,","B":"They need to pay off their debt to Mr. Greenfield,","C":"They are planning to start a new business,","D":"They want to buy a new house in the country"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The family is in debt, and the text says the crop is the only thing that can save them from that debt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Everything depends on this new crop. It\u0027s the only thing that will save us.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q003","read_aloud":"What major change happens to Ivy\u0027s family after the harvest fails? Options: A. They move to California, B. They buy a bigger farm in Mississippi, C. Mr. Greenfield gives them more money, D. They start a new school in town","excerpt":"\"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California.\"","stem":"What major change happens to Ivy\u0027s family after the harvest fails? Options:","choices":{"A":"They move to California,","B":"They buy a bigger farm in Mississippi,","C":"Mr. Greenfield gives them more money,","D":"They start a new school in town"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"After the disappointment of the failed crop, the family decides to move to California to seek better opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q004","read_aloud":"How does Ivy feel about her life at the end of the journal? Options: A. She hates California and wants to go back, B. She is sad because she has no friends, C. She realizes life has challenges, but she feels at home, D. She is angry at her parents for moving","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s funny that this time last year all of us were living thousands of miles away. Not everything is perfect in Los Angeles. Sometimes, white people are friendly to us, and sometimes they aren\u0027t.\"","stem":"How does Ivy feel about her life at the end of the journal? Options:","choices":{"A":"She hates California and wants to go back,","B":"She is sad because she has no friends,","C":"She realizes life has challenges, but she feels at home,","D":"She is angry at her parents for moving"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"While she acknowledges the challenges, she states, \"I can\u0027t think of anywhere that I would rather be,\" showing she accepts her new home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s funny that this time last year all of us were living thousands of miles away. Not everything is perfect in Los Angeles. Sometimes, white people are friendly to us, and sometimes they aren\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q005","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy\u0027s friend Sally take her to the library? Options: A. To play games, B. To do research for a school report, C. To hide from the rain, D. To meet the librarian","excerpt":"\"Sally took Ivy to a library in Los Angeles, Ivy stopped and stared in amazement. The shelves of books stretched up to the ceiling.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy\u0027s friend Sally take her to the library? Options:","choices":{"A":"To play games,","B":"To do research for a school report,","C":"To hide from the rain,","D":"To meet the librarian"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy needs to write a current events report, and Sally suggests using the library to find newspapers for research.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sally took Ivy to a library in Los Angeles, Ivy stopped and stared in amazement. The shelves of books stretched up to the ceiling.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q006","read_aloud":"In this travel context, what does the \"Jim Crow car\" represent? A. A special luxury car for important passengers B. A segregated car where black passengers were forced to sit separately C. A dining car where all passengers could eat together D. A sleeping car for long train journeys","excerpt":"\"Negro passengers had to sit in the Jim Crow car. It was separate from the rest of the train, where white passengers sat. We couldn\u0027t leave that one car, not even to go to the dining car to get a meal.\"","stem":"In this travel context, what does the \"Jim Crow car\" represent?","choices":{"A":"A special luxury car for important passengers","B":"A segregated car where black passengers were forced to sit separately","C":"A dining car where all passengers could eat together","D":"A sleeping car for long train journeys"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains the Jim Crow car was \"separate from the rest of the train\" and black passengers \"couldn\u0027t leave that one car,\" showing it was a segregated space.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Negro passengers had to sit in the Jim Crow car. It was separate from the rest of the train, where white passengers sat. We couldn\u0027t leave that one car, not even to go to the dining car to get a meal.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q007","read_aloud":"Why was Ivy so careful with her train ticket? A. Because it was a valuable collector\u0027s item B. Because losing it would mean they couldn\u0027t afford to replace it C. Because her journal was more important than the ticket D. Because the train conductor would punish her","excerpt":"\"This morning, I stood with my family on the platform of the railroad station near our town. I had a train ticket tucked inside my journal, which I clutched tightly in my arm. I didn\u0027t want to take any chance that the ticket might slip through my fingers because we didn\u0027t have enough money to buy another one.\"","stem":"Why was Ivy so careful with her train ticket?","choices":{"A":"Because it was a valuable collector\u0027s item","B":"Because losing it would mean they couldn\u0027t afford to replace it","C":"Because her journal was more important than the ticket","D":"Because the train conductor would punish her"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy says she didn\u0027t want the ticket to slip away \"because we didn\u0027t have enough money to buy another one,\" showing the financial stakes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This morning, I stood with my family on the platform of the railroad station near our town. I had a train ticket tucked inside my journal, which I clutched tightly in my arm. I didn\u0027t want to take any chance that the ticket might slip through my fingers because we didn\u0027t have enough money to buy another one.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q008","read_aloud":"What does seeing \"farm field after farm field\" make Ivy think about? A. How excited she is to farm in California B. The life and home she is leaving behind in Mississippi C. How much she wants to go back to Mississippi D. How similar California farms are to Mississippi farms","excerpt":"\"As the whistle sounded again, the train slowly pulled out of the station, and we were on our way to California!... Looking out the window, I watch the countryside go by and see farm field after farm field. It reminds me of everything that we are leaving behind.\"","stem":"What does seeing \"farm field after farm field\" make Ivy think about?","choices":{"A":"How excited she is to farm in California","B":"The life and home she is leaving behind in Mississippi","C":"How much she wants to go back to Mississippi","D":"How similar California farms are to Mississippi farms"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states the farm fields \"reminds me of everything that we are leaving behind,\" showing Ivy is reflecting on what she\u0027s leaving.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As the whistle sounded again, the train slowly pulled out of the station, and we were on our way to California!... Looking out the window, I watch the countryside go by and see farm field after farm field. It reminds me of everything that we are leaving behind.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q009","read_aloud":"How might the difference in air between Mississippi and California symbolize Ivy\u0027s experience? A. The lighter air represents the heavy burden she still carries B. The less thick air could represent a feeling of more freedom and possibility C. The warm air means nothing has really changed D. The heavy air means California will be harder than Mississippi","excerpt":"\"We arrived in Los Angeles this morning. As I stepped off the train, the first thing I noticed was the air. Mississippi is still hot this time of year. California is warm as well, but the air is not as thick and heavy as it is in the South.\"","stem":"How might the difference in air between Mississippi and California symbolize Ivy\u0027s experience?","choices":{"A":"The lighter air represents the heavy burden she still carries","B":"The less thick air could represent a feeling of more freedom and possibility","C":"The warm air means nothing has really changed","D":"The heavy air means California will be harder than Mississippi"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy notices California\u0027s air is \"not as thick and heavy\" right after leaving the segregated South, which could symbolize the lighter feeling of having more opportunities and freedom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"We arrived in Los Angeles this morning. As I stepped off the train, the first thing I noticed was the air. Mississippi is still hot this time of year. California is warm as well, but the air is not as thick and heavy as it is in the South.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q010","read_aloud":"How does Ivy\u0027s description of Los Angeles help readers understand her experience as a newcomer? A. She focuses only on the good things and ignores challenges B. She notices both exciting new things and overwhelming differences, showing adjustment takes time C. She immediately feels completely at home and comfortable D. She wishes she had never left Mississippi","excerpt":"\"Los Angeles looks really different from Mississippi. This is a big city with houses, offices, and other buildings spread out all over. Palm trees line the streets-I\u0027d never seen a palm tree before-and the roads are packed with cars, buses, and trucks. Sitting on the bus, I wanted to cover my ears to block out all of the noise from the cars, buses, trucks, and their horns.\"","stem":"How does Ivy\u0027s description of Los Angeles help readers understand her experience as a newcomer?","choices":{"A":"She focuses only on the good things and ignores challenges","B":"She notices both exciting new things and overwhelming differences, showing adjustment takes time","C":"She immediately feels completely at home and comfortable","D":"She wishes she had never left Mississippi"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy describes fascinating new things like palm trees but also wants to \"cover my ears\" from the noise, showing she\u0027s experiencing both wonder and overwhelm as she adjusts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Los Angeles looks really different from Mississippi. This is a big city with houses, offices, and other buildings spread out all over. Palm trees line the streets-I\u0027d never seen a palm tree before-and the roads are packed with cars, buses, and trucks. Sitting on the bus, I wanted to cover my ears to block out all of the noise from the cars, buses, trucks, and their horns.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"integrated\" mean? A. Separated by race B. Open only to white children C. Open only to black children D. Open to children of all races together","excerpt":"\"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together. We sit in the same classrooms, side by side, and no one thinks anything of it.\"","stem":"What does \"integrated\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Separated by race","B":"Open only to white children","C":"Open only to black children","D":"Open to children of all races together"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text says integrated means white and black children attend together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together. We sit in the same classrooms, side by side, and no one thinks anything of it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q012","read_aloud":"How is Ivy\u0027s new school different from her old school? A. She has to share books at the new school. B. She has her own textbooks at the new school. C. The new school has a hole in the roof. D. The new school is farther away.","excerpt":"Compare Ivy\u0027s school in Mississippi (page 10) with her new school in California (page 21).","stem":"How is Ivy\u0027s new school different from her old school?","choices":{"A":"She has to share books at the new school.","B":"She has her own textbooks at the new school.","C":"The new school has a hole in the roof.","D":"The new school is farther away."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In Mississippi she shared books; in California she has her own textbooks.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Compare Ivy\u0027s school in Mississippi (page 10) with her new school in California (page 21)."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q013","read_aloud":"What can you infer about why the librarian looked surprised? A. Ivy was very tall. B. Few Negro children came to that library. C. The library was closed. D. Ivy was too loud.","excerpt":"\"The librarian who greeted us at the front desk looked a little surprised to see me walk in. I felt uncomfortable at first, and worried that she might frown like Mr. Greenfield and some of my white neighbors do. But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed.\"","stem":"What can you infer about why the librarian looked surprised?","choices":{"A":"Ivy was very tall.","B":"Few Negro children came to that library.","C":"The library was closed.","D":"Ivy was too loud."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text earlier says mostly white people live in that community, so the librarian may not have seen many Negro children there.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The librarian who greeted us at the front desk looked a little surprised to see me walk in. I felt uncomfortable at first, and worried that she might frown like Mr. Greenfield and some of my white neighbors do. But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q014","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy think there are not many other Negroes at the library? A. They do not like to read. B. The library is far away. C. Mostly white people live in that area. D. The library only allows white people.","excerpt":"\"Even though there\u0027s no segregation, there weren\u0027t many other Negroes at the library. That\u0027s probably because mostly white people live and work in this community.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy think there are not many other Negroes at the library?","choices":{"A":"They do not like to read.","B":"The library is far away.","C":"Mostly white people live in that area.","D":"The library only allows white people."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy says that\u0027s probably because mostly white people live and work in that community.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even though there\u0027s no segregation, there weren\u0027t many other Negroes at the library. That\u0027s probably because mostly white people live and work in this community.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q015","read_aloud":"What does owning a radio for the first time suggest about the family\u0027s new life in California? A. They have less money than before. B. They have more money and can afford things they could not before. C. They do not like music. D. Radios are free in California.","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s Thanksgiving Day, so we all have the day off. Last night, Daddy brought home a surprise: a radio! We\u0027ve never had a radio of our own.\"","stem":"What does owning a radio for the first time suggest about the family\u0027s new life in California?","choices":{"A":"They have less money than before.","B":"They have more money and can afford things they could not before.","C":"They do not like music.","D":"Radios are free in California."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Having a new radio they never owned before shows they have more money now.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s Thanksgiving Day, so we all have the day off. Last night, Daddy brought home a surprise: a radio! We\u0027ve never had a radio of our own.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q016","read_aloud":"Why are many black people \"stuck\" working as sharecroppers? A. Because they love farming more than any other job. B. Because stores and factories refuse to hire them, so they have no other choice. C. Because they do not know how to do other jobs. D. Because Mr. Greenfield forces them to farm.","excerpt":"\"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face. So, many black people are stuck working on small farms and facing a mountain of debt.\"","stem":"Why are many black people \"stuck\" working as sharecroppers?","choices":{"A":"Because they love farming more than any other job.","B":"Because stores and factories refuse to hire them, so they have no other choice.","C":"Because they do not know how to do other jobs.","D":"Because Mr. Greenfield forces them to farm."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says stores and factories refuse to hire black workers. This discrimination means many black people are stuck working on small farms as sharecroppers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face. So, many black people are stuck working on small farms and facing a mountain of debt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q017","read_aloud":"How is Ivy\u0027s new school in California different from her old school in Mississippi? A. She has to share books and walk a long distance in California. B. She has her own books and takes a short bus ride in California. C. The schools are exactly the same. D. She does not go to school in California.","excerpt":"\"One great thing about my new school is that I have my own textbooks now, and I don\u0027t have to share with anyone. No more walking to and from school either. I take a bus now, and it\u0027s just a short ride.\"","stem":"How is Ivy\u0027s new school in California different from her old school in Mississippi?","choices":{"A":"She has to share books and walk a long distance in California.","B":"She has her own books and takes a short bus ride in California.","C":"The schools are exactly the same.","D":"She does not go to school in California."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In Mississippi, Ivy had to share books and walk a long way. In California, she has her own books and takes a short bus ride. These are important differences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One great thing about my new school is that I have my own textbooks now, and I don\u0027t have to share with anyone. No more walking to and from school either. I take a bus now, and it\u0027s just a short ride.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q018","read_aloud":"What evidence shows that Ivy\u0027s family is surprised and hopeful about California? A. They cry and say they do not want to go. B. Ivy asks if they hire black people, and the family chuckles because it sounds so different. C. They say California is exactly like Mississippi. D. They refuse to read Uncle Eugene\u0027s letter.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Wow, they hire Negroes to work in factories there?\u0027 I asked. \u0027California sure sounds different from Mississippi!\u0027 Buck said, and we all chuckled.\"","stem":"What evidence shows that Ivy\u0027s family is surprised and hopeful about California?","choices":{"A":"They cry and say they do not want to go.","B":"Ivy asks if they hire black people, and the family chuckles because it sounds so different.","C":"They say California is exactly like Mississippi.","D":"They refuse to read Uncle Eugene\u0027s letter."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy\u0027s question shows surprise that black people can get factory jobs. The family chuckles because California sounds so different from Mississippi. This shows hope.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Wow, they hire Negroes to work in factories there?\u0027 I asked. \u0027California sure sounds different from Mississippi!\u0027 Buck said, and we all chuckled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q019","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about Ivy\u0027s hopes for the future? A. She wants to be a sharecropper forever. B. She hopes to have more freedom and choices for work when she grows up. C. She does not want to ever leave Mississippi. D. She wants to work for Mr. Greenfield.","excerpt":"\"I tried to picture what it might be like to live in a place where Negroes have more freedom. Where people like me could apply for any job they wanted. Maybe I didn\u0027t have to live on small farms all my life.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about Ivy\u0027s hopes for the future?","choices":{"A":"She wants to be a sharecropper forever.","B":"She hopes to have more freedom and choices for work when she grows up.","C":"She does not want to ever leave Mississippi.","D":"She wants to work for Mr. Greenfield."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy pictures a place with more freedom where she can apply for any job. She hopes she does not have to live on small farms all her life. This shows she wants more choices.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I tried to picture what it might be like to live in a place where Negroes have more freedom. Where people like me could apply for any job they wanted. Maybe I didn\u0027t have to live on small farms all my life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q020","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt show about discrimination? A. It only exists in the South. B. It exists in California too, even though there are no Jim Crow laws. C. It does not exist anywhere in America. D. Only white people face discrimination.","excerpt":"\"Mostly white residents live in this neighborhood, and we will be one of the few Negro families. Not everyone was welcoming when we arrived. A white mother and son were standing on the sidewalk as Mama and I carried a couple of our bags into the building. The mother frowned at us just like Mr. Greenfield used to, then the son stuck out his tongue and spit on the ground near our feet.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt show about discrimination?","choices":{"A":"It only exists in the South.","B":"It exists in California too, even though there are no Jim Crow laws.","C":"It does not exist anywhere in America.","D":"Only white people face discrimination."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that even in California, some white people are not welcoming. The mother frowns and the son spits near their feet. This shows discrimination exists outside the South too.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mostly white residents live in this neighborhood, and we will be one of the few Negro families. Not everyone was welcoming when we arrived. A white mother and son were standing on the sidewalk as Mama and I carried a couple of our bags into the building. The mother frowned at us just like Mr. Greenfield used to, then the son stuck out his tongue and spit on the ground near our feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. A system that brings all people together equally B. A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places C. A law that helps black people get better jobs D. A way to make schools better for everyone","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"A system that brings all people together equally","B":"A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places","C":"A law that helps black people get better jobs","D":"A way to make schools better for everyone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines segregation as \"a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people\" with separate facilities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l06-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. They make life easier for black people in the South B. They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go C. They help black people get better education D. They allow black and white people to mix freely","excerpt":"\"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"They make life easier for black people in the South","B":"They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go","C":"They help black people get better education","D":"They allow black and white people to mix freely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Jim Crow laws require separate sections and prevent black people from entering certain places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q001","read_aloud":"What is a \"bill\" in this story? Options: A. A bird\u0027s beak, B. A document showing money owed, C. A type of cotton plant, D. A piece of farming equipment","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season.\"","stem":"What is a \"bill\" in this story? Options:","choices":{"A":"A bird\u0027s beak,","B":"A document showing money owed,","C":"A type of cotton plant,","D":"A piece of farming equipment"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that the bill is a record of the money the family owes Mr. Greenfield.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q002","read_aloud":"How does the author show that scientific research can be challenging? (From context of the whole text, not just Ivy\u0027s journal) Options: A. By explaining that the sun shines all day, B. By describing how scientists eat pancakes, C. By noting that most of the machines failed to work, D. By stating that ink freezes in pens","excerpt":"\"But the gas chromatograph didn\u0027t work at all... Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought... only two... were good at finding microbes.\"","stem":"How does the author show that scientific research can be challenging? (From context of the whole text, not just Ivy\u0027s journal) Options:","choices":{"A":"By explaining that the sun shines all day,","B":"By describing how scientists eat pancakes,","C":"By noting that most of the machines failed to work,","D":"By stating that ink freezes in pens"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The author uses the example of machines failing to test technology in harsh environments, showing the difficulty of the scientific process. (Note: This question uses the text evidence from the provided informational overview within the file).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But the gas chromatograph didn\u0027t work at all... Of the six machines Chris and the other scientists brought... only two... were good at finding microbes.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q003","read_aloud":"What does Mama mean when she says \"some things will still be the same\"? Options: A. She thinks the weather is the same, B. She knows that prejudice and challenges exist even in California, C. She thinks they will have to farm cotton again, D. She thinks they will have to go back to Mississippi","excerpt":"\"Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\"","stem":"What does Mama mean when she says \"some things will still be the same\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"She thinks the weather is the same,","B":"She knows that prejudice and challenges exist even in California,","C":"She thinks they will have to farm cotton again,","D":"She thinks they will have to go back to Mississippi"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Even though the laws are different, they have already experienced unfriendly behavior, showing Mama that discrimination is a problem in many places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q004","read_aloud":"How did Ivy\u0027s experience with the librarian change her opinion? Options: A. She realized that not all white people are unkind, B. She decided she did not want to be a student, C. She realized that librarians are too busy to help, D. She thought the library was a scary place","excerpt":"\"I felt uncomfortable at first, and worried that she might frown like Mr. Greenfield and some of my white neighbors do. But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed.\"","stem":"How did Ivy\u0027s experience with the librarian change her opinion? Options:","choices":{"A":"She realized that not all white people are unkind,","B":"She decided she did not want to be a student,","C":"She realized that librarians are too busy to help,","D":"She thought the library was a scary place"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The librarian\u0027s kindness surprised Ivy and helped her overcome her worry about being judged.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I felt uncomfortable at first, and worried that she might frown like Mr. Greenfield and some of my white neighbors do. But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q005","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy feel conflicted about the news of moving? Options: A. She wants to move but her parents do not, B. She is excited about the job, but she hates airplane factories, C. She is hopeful for a better life but sad to leave her home and friends, D. She wants to go to school but her parents say no","excerpt":"\"I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again! Also, I have only ever lived in Mississippi; I\u0027ve never even visited another state.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy feel conflicted about the news of moving? Options:","choices":{"A":"She wants to move but her parents do not,","B":"She is excited about the job, but she hates airplane factories,","C":"She is hopeful for a better life but sad to leave her home and friends,","D":"She wants to go to school but her parents say no"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy expresses both hope for a better life and the sadness of leaving everything she has ever known.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again! Also, I have only ever lived in Mississippi; I\u0027ve never even visited another state.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q006","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, what does \"integrated\" mean in the context of schools? A. Schools that only allow white children to attend B. Schools where children of different races learn together in the same classes C. Schools that are only for black children D. Schools that don\u0027t teach reading and math","excerpt":"\"Today was the first day at my new school, and it is such a big change from Mississippi! This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together. We sit in the same classrooms, side by side, and no one thinks anything of it.\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, what does \"integrated\" mean in the context of schools?","choices":{"A":"Schools that only allow white children to attend","B":"Schools where children of different races learn together in the same classes","C":"Schools that are only for black children","D":"Schools that don\u0027t teach reading and math"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines integrated as meaning \"white and black children attend together\" and \"sit in the same classrooms, side by side.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today was the first day at my new school, and it is such a big change from Mississippi! This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together. We sit in the same classrooms, side by side, and no one thinks anything of it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q007","read_aloud":"How is Ivy\u0027s new school better than her old school in Mississippi? A. It has longer school days and more homework B. She has her own books, takes a bus, and doesn\u0027t walk in the rain C. It has more students and bigger classrooms D. It doesn\u0027t teach the same subjects","excerpt":"\"One great thing about my new school is that I have my own textbooks now, and I don\u0027t have to share with anyone. No more walking to and from school either. I take a bus now, and it\u0027s just a short ride. The next time it rains, I won\u0027t have to worry about getting soaked on the way home!\"","stem":"How is Ivy\u0027s new school better than her old school in Mississippi?","choices":{"A":"It has longer school days and more homework","B":"She has her own books, takes a bus, and doesn\u0027t walk in the rain","C":"It has more students and bigger classrooms","D":"It doesn\u0027t teach the same subjects"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy lists specific improvements: her own textbooks, bus transportation, and not getting soaked walking in rain-contrasting with her Mississippi school experience.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One great thing about my new school is that I have my own textbooks now, and I don\u0027t have to share with anyone. No more walking to and from school either. I take a bus now, and it\u0027s just a short ride. The next time it rains, I won\u0027t have to worry about getting soaked on the way home!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q008","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt show about Ivy\u0027s experience in her new neighborhood? A. Everyone in California is friendly and welcoming B. Even in California, Ivy\u0027s family sometimes faces unfriendly treatment because of their race C. Ivy\u0027s family is the only black family in all of California D. The white neighbors immediately became Ivy\u0027s best friends","excerpt":"\"Mostly white residents live in this neighborhood, and we will be one of the few Negro families. Not everyone was welcoming when we arrived. A white mother and son were standing on the sidewalk as Mama and I carried a couple of our bags into the building. The mother frowned at us just like Mr. Greenfield used to, then the son stuck out his tongue and spit on the ground near our feet.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt show about Ivy\u0027s experience in her new neighborhood?","choices":{"A":"Everyone in California is friendly and welcoming","B":"Even in California, Ivy\u0027s family sometimes faces unfriendly treatment because of their race","C":"Ivy\u0027s family is the only black family in all of California","D":"The white neighbors immediately became Ivy\u0027s best friends"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt describes a white mother frowning and a boy spitting near them, showing that discrimination still exists even after moving to California.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mostly white residents live in this neighborhood, and we will be one of the few Negro families. Not everyone was welcoming when we arrived. A white mother and son were standing on the sidewalk as Mama and I carried a couple of our bags into the building. The mother frowned at us just like Mr. Greenfield used to, then the son stuck out his tongue and spit on the ground near our feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q009","read_aloud":"Based on Mama\u0027s words, what lesson is she teaching Ivy about life? A. Moving to a new place solves all problems B. Change brings new opportunities but also continued challenges that require strength C. They should move back to Mississippi immediately D. They should never talk about their experiences with others","excerpt":"\"Mama put an arm around me and hurried us both inside. As we climbed the three flights to our apartment, she said, \u0027Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\u0027\"","stem":"Based on Mama\u0027s words, what lesson is she teaching Ivy about life?","choices":{"A":"Moving to a new place solves all problems","B":"Change brings new opportunities but also continued challenges that require strength","C":"They should move back to Mississippi immediately","D":"They should never talk about their experiences with others"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Mama acknowledges that \"some things will still be the same\" (challenges) even though \"things are different here\" (new opportunities), teaching Ivy to face difficulties with resilience.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama put an arm around me and hurried us both inside. As we climbed the three flights to our apartment, she said, \u0027Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q010","read_aloud":"How does this excerpt show Ivy coping with disappointment? A. She ignores all problems and only focuses on good things B. She acknowledges sadness about discrimination but finds comfort in positive changes like her new room C. She decides to move back to Mississippi D. She blames her parents for the move","excerpt":"\"The idea that discrimination wasn\u0027t only in the South made me sad, but I felt better when I saw my new bedroom. I still had to share it with Mary and Buck, but it was bigger than our old room, and it had a set of bunk beds!\"","stem":"How does this excerpt show Ivy coping with disappointment?","choices":{"A":"She ignores all problems and only focuses on good things","B":"She acknowledges sadness about discrimination but finds comfort in positive changes like her new room","C":"She decides to move back to Mississippi","D":"She blames her parents for the move"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy admits feeling sad about ongoing discrimination but then shifts to appreciating her bigger room with bunk beds, showing she balances acknowledging hard truths with finding joy in improvements.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The idea that discrimination wasn\u0027t only in the South made me sad, but I felt better when I saw my new bedroom. I still had to share it with Mary and Buck, but it was bigger than our old room, and it had a set of bunk beds!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"current events\" mean? A. Stories from long ago B. Important things happening in the present time C. Fictional stories D. Science experiments","excerpt":"\"I have to write a current events report for school, so my new friend Sally said we should go to the library to look through newspapers for research.\"","stem":"What does \"current events\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Stories from long ago","B":"Important things happening in the present time","C":"Fictional stories","D":"Science experiments"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Current events are news and happenings that are happening now or recently.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I have to write a current events report for school, so my new friend Sally said we should go to the library to look through newspapers for research.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q012","read_aloud":"Why did Ivy almost say that Negroes aren\u0027t allowed in the library? A. She forgot where she was. B. In Mississippi, Negroes were not allowed in many libraries. C. Sally told her to say that. D. She wanted to make Sally angry.","excerpt":"\"My mouth dropped open when she made the suggestion. I almost said that Negroes aren\u0027t allowed to go to the library, but then I remembered that things are different in California.\"","stem":"Why did Ivy almost say that Negroes aren\u0027t allowed in the library?","choices":{"A":"She forgot where she was.","B":"In Mississippi, Negroes were not allowed in many libraries.","C":"Sally told her to say that.","D":"She wanted to make Sally angry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In Mississippi, segregation kept Negroes out of many public places like libraries.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"My mouth dropped open when she made the suggestion. I almost said that Negroes aren\u0027t allowed to go to the library, but then I remembered that things are different in California.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q013","read_aloud":"What can you infer about discrimination in California from this passage? A. There is no discrimination in California. B. Discrimination still exists in California, even if laws are different. C. Only children discriminate in California. D. Everyone in California is friendly.","excerpt":"\"We moved into our new apartment today, and it\u0027s bigger than the house we had in Mississippi. … Not everyone was welcoming when we arrived. A white mother and son were standing on the sidewalk … The mother frowned at us just like Mr. Greenfield used to, then the son stuck out his tongue and spit on the ground near our feet.\"","stem":"What can you infer about discrimination in California from this passage?","choices":{"A":"There is no discrimination in California.","B":"Discrimination still exists in California, even if laws are different.","C":"Only children discriminate in California.","D":"Everyone in California is friendly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Even though there are no Jim Crow laws, some people still act in unfriendly, discriminatory ways.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"We moved into our new apartment today, and it\u0027s bigger than the house we had in Mississippi. … Not everyone was welcoming when we arrived. A white mother and son were standing on the sidewalk … The mother frowned at us just like Mr. Greenfield used to, then the son stuck out his tongue and spit on the ground near our feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q014","read_aloud":"What lesson is Ivy\u0027s mother trying to teach her? A. They should move back to Mississippi. B. Even in a better place, problems may still happen, and they must face them bravely. C. They should never leave their apartment. D. Discrimination is not real.","excerpt":"\"Mama put an arm around me and hurried us both inside. As we climbed the three flights to our apartment, she said, \u0027Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\u0027\"","stem":"What lesson is Ivy\u0027s mother trying to teach her?","choices":{"A":"They should move back to Mississippi.","B":"Even in a better place, problems may still happen, and they must face them bravely.","C":"They should never leave their apartment.","D":"Discrimination is not real."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The mother says some things will still be the same, and they must face them the best they can.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama put an arm around me and hurried us both inside. As we climbed the three flights to our apartment, she said, \u0027Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q015","read_aloud":"Why did factories need more workers during this time? A. Because they were building airplanes for the war effort. B. Because all the workers were on vacation. C. Because the factories were closing. D. Because there were no customers.","excerpt":"\"He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\"","stem":"Why did factories need more workers during this time?","choices":{"A":"Because they were building airplanes for the war effort.","B":"Because all the workers were on vacation.","C":"Because the factories were closing.","D":"Because there were no customers."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Uncle Eugene works at a factory that builds airplanes to carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. The war created a need for more workers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q016","read_aloud":"Why was going to the library special for Ivy? A. Because she had never been to a library before. B. Because libraries in Mississippi did not allow black people. C. Both a and b. D. Because she did not like books.","excerpt":"\"Today was a special day-I went to a library for the first time! I have to write a current events report for school, so my new friend Sally said we should go to the library to look through newspapers for research.\"","stem":"Why was going to the library special for Ivy?","choices":{"A":"Because she had never been to a library before.","B":"Because libraries in Mississippi did not allow black people.","C":"Both a and b.","D":"Because she did not like books."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy says it was her first time at a library. She also almost said that black people are not allowed in libraries, showing that in Mississippi, libraries were segregated. Both reasons make it special.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today was a special day-I went to a library for the first time! I have to write a current events report for school, so my new friend Sally said we should go to the library to look through newspapers for research.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q017","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the librarian? A. She was rude and told Ivy to leave. B. She was surprised but then friendly and helpful. C. She did not know how to help. D. She was angry that Ivy came to the library.","excerpt":"\"The librarian who greeted us at the front desk looked a little surprised to see me walk in. I felt uncomfortable at first, and worried that she might frown like Mr. Greenfield and some of my white neighbors do. But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the librarian?","choices":{"A":"She was rude and told Ivy to leave.","B":"She was surprised but then friendly and helpful.","C":"She did not know how to help.","D":"She was angry that Ivy came to the library."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The librarian looked surprised at first, but then she smiled and helped Ivy find articles. This shows she was friendly and welcoming despite her initial surprise.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The librarian who greeted us at the front desk looked a little surprised to see me walk in. I felt uncomfortable at first, and worried that she might frown like Mr. Greenfield and some of my white neighbors do. But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q018","read_aloud":"What is Mama trying to teach Ivy? A. That life in California will be perfect with no problems. B. That even though they have more freedom, they will still face some discrimination, and they must be strong. C. That they should move back to Mississippi. D. That they should never talk to white people.","excerpt":"\"Mama put an arm around me and hurried us both inside. As we climbed the three flights to our apartment, she said, \u0027Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\u0027\"","stem":"What is Mama trying to teach Ivy?","choices":{"A":"That life in California will be perfect with no problems.","B":"That even though they have more freedom, they will still face some discrimination, and they must be strong.","C":"That they should move back to Mississippi.","D":"That they should never talk to white people."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mama says some things will still be the same. She means they will still face discrimination. She tells Ivy they must face these challenges the best they can. This teaches Ivy to be strong.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama put an arm around me and hurried us both inside. As we climbed the three flights to our apartment, she said, \u0027Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q019","read_aloud":"What does Ivy mean when she says \"Not everything is perfect\"? A. She hates living in California. B. She knows that life is better but still has challenges, like some unfriendly white people. C. She wants to move back to Mississippi immediately. D. She thinks California is exactly the same as Mississippi.","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s funny that this time last year all of us were living thousands of miles away. Not everything is perfect in Los Angeles. Sometimes, white people are friendly to us, and sometimes they aren\u0027t.\"","stem":"What does Ivy mean when she says \"Not everything is perfect\"?","choices":{"A":"She hates living in California.","B":"She knows that life is better but still has challenges, like some unfriendly white people.","C":"She wants to move back to Mississippi immediately.","D":"She thinks California is exactly the same as Mississippi."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy says some white people are friendly and some are not. She knows life is better in California but understands that not everything is perfect. There are still challenges.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s funny that this time last year all of us were living thousands of miles away. Not everything is perfect in Los Angeles. Sometimes, white people are friendly to us, and sometimes they aren\u0027t.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. A system that brings all people together equally B. A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places C. A law that helps black people get better jobs D. A way to make schools better for everyone","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"A system that brings all people together equally","B":"A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places","C":"A law that helps black people get better jobs","D":"A way to make schools better for everyone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines segregation as \"a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people\" with separate facilities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. They make life easier for black people in the South B. They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go C. They help black people get better education D. They allow black and white people to mix freely","excerpt":"\"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"They make life easier for black people in the South","B":"They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go","C":"They help black people get better education","D":"They allow black and white people to mix freely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Jim Crow laws require separate sections and prevent black people from entering certain places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To move to a different country B. To have the same rights and opportunities as white children C. To become a lawyer and change the laws D. To stop going to school","excerpt":"\"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To move to a different country","B":"To have the same rights and opportunities as white children","C":"To become a lawyer and change the laws","D":"To stop going to school"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy directly states \"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\" after her mama explains Jim Crow limits opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q001","read_aloud":"What is a \"migration\"? Options: A. Staying in one place forever, B. The movement of people from one place to another, C. A type of vacation, D. Learning about a new country","excerpt":"\"This kind of movement of people from one place to another is called a \u0027migration.\u0027\"","stem":"What is a \"migration\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Staying in one place forever,","B":"The movement of people from one place to another,","C":"A type of vacation,","D":"Learning about a new country"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text provides a definition stating that the movement of people is called a migration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This kind of movement of people from one place to another is called a \u0027migration.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q002","read_aloud":"How does the author\u0027s description of the rain contribute to the mood of the entry? Options: A. It makes the scene feel peaceful and slow, B. It creates a sense of urgency and haste, C. It makes the reader feel happy about the weather, D. It shows that the girls like to play in the rain","excerpt":"\"At first, it was just a few drops, but then buckets of rain began to fall from the sky. Eve and I broke into a run to get home as fast as we could.\"","stem":"How does the author\u0027s description of the rain contribute to the mood of the entry? Options:","choices":{"A":"It makes the scene feel peaceful and slow,","B":"It creates a sense of urgency and haste,","C":"It makes the reader feel happy about the weather,","D":"It shows that the girls like to play in the rain"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The transition from \"a few drops\" to \"buckets of rain\" and the girls \"breaking into a run\" creates an urgent and hurried feeling.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At first, it was just a few drops, but then buckets of rain began to fall from the sky. Eve and I broke into a run to get home as fast as we could.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q003","read_aloud":"Do you think Ivy\u0027s family made the right decision to move? Why or why not? Options: A. No, because California is too loud and noisy, B. Yes, because they gain better opportunities and freedom, C. No, because they still have to work hard at a factory, D. Yes, because they wanted to travel by train","excerpt":"\"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way.\"","stem":"Do you think Ivy\u0027s family made the right decision to move? Why or why not? Options:","choices":{"A":"No, because California is too loud and noisy,","B":"Yes, because they gain better opportunities and freedom,","C":"No, because they still have to work hard at a factory,","D":"Yes, because they wanted to travel by train"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that despite the changes, the family gains better wages, freedom from Jim Crow, and safer working conditions, justifying the decision.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q004","read_aloud":"How do these thoughts change Ivy\u0027s outlook for the future? Options: A. She becomes worried about finding a job, B. She begins to see new possibilities for her life, C. She decides she wants to return to the cotton farm, D. She realizes she will always be a sharecropper","excerpt":"\"Maybe I didn\u0027t have to live on small farms all my life. Maybe one day, I could move somewhere else and do other kinds of work when I grow up.\"","stem":"How do these thoughts change Ivy\u0027s outlook for the future? Options:","choices":{"A":"She becomes worried about finding a job,","B":"She begins to see new possibilities for her life,","C":"She decides she wants to return to the cotton farm,","D":"She realizes she will always be a sharecropper"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy starts to imagine a future where she isn\u0027t stuck on a farm, showing she is becoming more hopeful about her own choices.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maybe I didn\u0027t have to live on small farms all my life. Maybe one day, I could move somewhere else and do other kinds of work when I grow up.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q005","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy almost say Negroes aren\u0027t allowed in the library? A. Because libraries in California have the same rules as Mississippi B. Because she\u0027s so used to segregation in Mississippi that she forgets rules can be different elsewhere C. Because her friend Sally told her not to go in D. Because she doesn\u0027t like to read books","excerpt":"\"Today was a special day-I went to a library for the first time!... I almost said that Negroes aren\u0027t allowed to go to the library, but then I remembered that things are different in California.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy almost say Negroes aren\u0027t allowed in the library?","choices":{"A":"Because libraries in California have the same rules as Mississippi","B":"Because she\u0027s so used to segregation in Mississippi that she forgets rules can be different elsewhere","C":"Because her friend Sally told her not to go in","D":"Because she doesn\u0027t like to read books"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy\u0027s automatic assumption reflects how deeply Mississippi\u0027s segregation rules shaped her thinking, even though she\u0027s now in California where \"things are different.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today was a special day-I went to a library for the first time!... I almost said that Negroes aren\u0027t allowed to go to the library, but then I remembered that things are different in California.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q006","read_aloud":"What does Ivy\u0027s reaction to the library reveal about her previous experiences? A. She has visited many large libraries before B. She had limited access to books and libraries in Mississippi due to segregation C. She doesn\u0027t care about books or reading D. She prefers to borrow books from friends instead","excerpt":"\"When I stepped inside, I stopped and stared in amazement. I had never seen so many books in one place! Everywhere I looked, there were shelves and shelves filled with books. The shelves stretched up to the ceiling and were so high that ladders leaned against them, so the librarians could climb up to the top shelves.\"","stem":"What does Ivy\u0027s reaction to the library reveal about her previous experiences?","choices":{"A":"She has visited many large libraries before","B":"She had limited access to books and libraries in Mississippi due to segregation","C":"She doesn\u0027t care about books or reading","D":"She prefers to borrow books from friends instead"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy\u0027s amazement at seeing \"so many books in one place\" and her earlier thought that \"Negroes aren\u0027t allowed to go to the library\" suggest she had very limited library access in Mississippi.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When I stepped inside, I stopped and stared in amazement. I had never seen so many books in one place! Everywhere I looked, there were shelves and shelves filled with books. The shelves stretched up to the ceiling and were so high that ladders leaned against them, so the librarians could climb up to the top shelves.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q007","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the librarian\u0027s reaction to Ivy? A. The librarian was angry that Ivy came to the library B. The librarian wasn\u0027t used to seeing black children in that library, even though segregation wasn\u0027t the law C. The librarian immediately knew Ivy from Mississippi D. The librarian refused to help Ivy find books","excerpt":"\"Even though there\u0027s no segregation, there weren\u0027t many other Negroes at the library. That\u0027s probably because mostly white people live and work in this community. The librarian who greeted us at the front desk looked a little surprised to see me walk in.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the librarian\u0027s reaction to Ivy?","choices":{"A":"The librarian was angry that Ivy came to the library","B":"The librarian wasn\u0027t used to seeing black children in that library, even though segregation wasn\u0027t the law","C":"The librarian immediately knew Ivy from Mississippi","D":"The librarian refused to help Ivy find books"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The librarian \"looked a little surprised\" and the text notes few Negroes were there because mostly white people lived in the community, suggesting the librarian wasn\u0027t accustomed to black visitors despite no legal segregation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even though there\u0027s no segregation, there weren\u0027t many other Negroes at the library. That\u0027s probably because mostly white people live and work in this community. The librarian who greeted us at the front desk looked a little surprised to see me walk in.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q008","read_aloud":"Do you think the librarian\u0027s actions show that things are changing for the better? Use clues from the excerpt. A. No, because the librarian was surprised to see Ivy B. Yes, because even though she was surprised, the librarian smiled and helped Ivy, showing kindness and acceptance C. No, because Ivy still felt uncomfortable D. Yes, but only because Sally was with Ivy","excerpt":"\"But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed. She helped us find just the right articles for our report.\"","stem":"Do you think the librarian\u0027s actions show that things are changing for the better? Use clues from the excerpt.","choices":{"A":"No, because the librarian was surprised to see Ivy","B":"Yes, because even though she was surprised, the librarian smiled and helped Ivy, showing kindness and acceptance","C":"No, because Ivy still felt uncomfortable","D":"Yes, but only because Sally was with Ivy"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Though initially surprised, the librarian\u0027s smile and helpfulness show she treated Ivy with respect and kindness, suggesting positive change even if old attitudes linger.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed. She helped us find just the right articles for our report.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Which word is an antonym of \"integrated\"? A. Together B. Segregated C. Mixed D. United","excerpt":"\"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together.\"","stem":"Which word is an antonym of \"integrated\"?","choices":{"A":"Together","B":"Segregated","C":"Mixed","D":"United"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Segregated means kept apart, which is the opposite of integrated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Do you think Ivy\u0027s father made a wise choice by not answering angrily? Why? A. No, he should have yelled at Mr. Greenfield. B. Yes, because speaking angrily could have led to violence against him. C. No, because Mr. Greenfield was being kind. D. Yes, because he wanted to be friends with Mr. Greenfield.","excerpt":"\"I could tell Daddy was trying not to answer angrily because men like Mr. Greenfield sometimes hurt Negroes for \u0027talking back.\u0027\"","stem":"Do you think Ivy\u0027s father made a wise choice by not answering angrily? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, he should have yelled at Mr. Greenfield.","B":"Yes, because speaking angrily could have led to violence against him.","C":"No, because Mr. Greenfield was being kind.","D":"Yes, because he wanted to be friends with Mr. Greenfield."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says men like Mr. Greenfield sometimes hurt Negroes for talking back, so staying calm was safer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I could tell Daddy was trying not to answer angrily because men like Mr. Greenfield sometimes hurt Negroes for \u0027talking back.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q011","read_aloud":"Do you think Ivy\u0027s positive attitude about the small things (like a top bunk) is a helpful trait? Why? A. No, she should complain more. B. Yes, focusing on good things helps her adjust to big changes. C. No, a top bunk is not important. D. Yes, but only because she is young.","excerpt":"\"I still had to share it with Mary and Buck, but it was bigger than our old room, and it had a set of bunk beds! Buck was too scared to sleep on the top bed, and Mary didn\u0027t care. I took the top bunk, and I love it already!\"","stem":"Do you think Ivy\u0027s positive attitude about the small things (like a top bunk) is a helpful trait? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, she should complain more.","B":"Yes, focusing on good things helps her adjust to big changes.","C":"No, a top bunk is not important.","D":"Yes, but only because she is young."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Finding joy in small positives can help someone cope with difficult changes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I still had to share it with Mary and Buck, but it was bigger than our old room, and it had a set of bunk beds! Buck was too scared to sleep on the top bed, and Mary didn\u0027t care. I took the top bunk, and I love it already!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q012","read_aloud":"How does discrimination affect Ivy\u0027s family? A. It helps them get rich. B. It limits their job choices and keeps them stuck in debt as sharecroppers. C. It gives them free land. D. It makes them popular in town.","excerpt":"\"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\"","stem":"How does discrimination affect Ivy\u0027s family?","choices":{"A":"It helps them get rich.","B":"It limits their job choices and keeps them stuck in debt as sharecroppers.","C":"It gives them free land.","D":"It makes them popular in town."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Discrimination means stores and factories refuse to hire black workers. This limits their choices and keeps them stuck as sharecroppers with debt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Why did the author write \"Ivy\u0027s Journal\" as a historical fiction story? A. To make up a story that has nothing to do with real history. B. To help readers understand the real experiences of families during the Great Migration through a personal story. C. To teach readers how to write a journal. D. To describe what life is like in California today.","excerpt":"\"Ivy\u0027s Journal is a fictionalized account of one such family.\"","stem":"Why did the author write \"Ivy\u0027s Journal\" as a historical fiction story?","choices":{"A":"To make up a story that has nothing to do with real history.","B":"To help readers understand the real experiences of families during the Great Migration through a personal story.","C":"To teach readers how to write a journal.","D":"To describe what life is like in California today."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author says the story is a fictionalized account of a real family. She uses Ivy\u0027s personal story to help readers understand what the Great Migration was like for real people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ivy\u0027s Journal is a fictionalized account of one such family.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Why does the author include the detail about Daddy\u0027s jaw tightening? A. To show that Daddy is happy. B. To show that Daddy is angry but must control himself because talking back could be dangerous. C. To show that Daddy is sleepy. D. To show that Daddy is hungry.","excerpt":"\"I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\"","stem":"Why does the author include the detail about Daddy\u0027s jaw tightening?","choices":{"A":"To show that Daddy is happy.","B":"To show that Daddy is angry but must control himself because talking back could be dangerous.","C":"To show that Daddy is sleepy.","D":"To show that Daddy is hungry."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Daddy\u0027s jaw tightening shows he is angry. But he does not talk back because, as the text says, black men can be hurt for \"talking back.\" This shows the danger and unfairness they face.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q015","read_aloud":"Why is this statement important to the story\u0027s theme? A. It shows that Ivy wants special privileges. B. It shows that Ivy believes in fairness and equality, which is a central theme of the story. C. It shows that Ivy is selfish. D. It shows that Ivy does not like other kids.","excerpt":"\"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\"","stem":"Why is this statement important to the story\u0027s theme?","choices":{"A":"It shows that Ivy wants special privileges.","B":"It shows that Ivy believes in fairness and equality, which is a central theme of the story.","C":"It shows that Ivy is selfish.","D":"It shows that Ivy does not like other kids."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy\u0027s wish for the same rights as other kids shows her belief in fairness. This is a central theme of the story, which is about discrimination and the fight for equality.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the phrase \"crossing my fingers\"? A. To show that Ivy is playing a game. B. To show that Ivy is hoping for good luck because the family\u0027s survival depends on the crop. C. To show that Ivy is angry. D. To show that Ivy is tired.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m crossing my fingers that we have a good crop this year.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the phrase \"crossing my fingers\"?","choices":{"A":"To show that Ivy is playing a game.","B":"To show that Ivy is hoping for good luck because the family\u0027s survival depends on the crop.","C":"To show that Ivy is angry.","D":"To show that Ivy is tired."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Crossing my fingers\" is a way to wish for good luck. Ivy hopes for a good crop because her family needs it to pay their debt and survive. This shows how much is at stake.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m crossing my fingers that we have a good crop this year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q017","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q018","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q019","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. A system that brings all people together equally B. A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places C. A law that helps black people get better jobs D. A way to make schools better for everyone","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"A system that brings all people together equally","B":"A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places","C":"A law that helps black people get better jobs","D":"A way to make schools better for everyone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines segregation as \"a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people\" with separate facilities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. They make life easier for black people in the South B. They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go C. They help black people get better education D. They allow black and white people to mix freely","excerpt":"\"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"They make life easier for black people in the South","B":"They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go","C":"They help black people get better education","D":"They allow black and white people to mix freely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Jim Crow laws require separate sections and prevent black people from entering certain places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To move to a different country B. To have the same rights and opportunities as white children C. To become a lawyer and change the laws D. To stop going to school","excerpt":"\"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To move to a different country","B":"To have the same rights and opportunities as white children","C":"To become a lawyer and change the laws","D":"To stop going to school"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy directly states \"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\" after her mama explains Jim Crow limits opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. A gift for Ivy\u0027s birthday B. A bill showing how much money they owe C. New seeds for planting D. A letter from Uncle Eugene","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"A gift for Ivy\u0027s birthday","B":"A bill showing how much money they owe","C":"New seeds for planting","D":"A letter from Uncle Eugene"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Mr. Greenfield \"gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. With respect and kindness B. Like they are children and with disrespect C. Like they are his close friends D. Like they are business partners","excerpt":"\"He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children. I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"With respect and kindness","B":"Like they are children and with disrespect","C":"Like they are his close friends","D":"Like they are business partners"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states Mr. Greenfield \"is disrespectful\" and \"talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children. I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l08-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Treating everyone exactly the same B. Unfair treatment of people based on their race or other characteristics C. Helping people find good jobs D. Making rules that benefit everyone equally","excerpt":"\"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Treating everyone exactly the same","B":"Unfair treatment of people based on their race or other characteristics","C":"Helping people find good jobs","D":"Making rules that benefit everyone equally"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text shows discrimination means black workers are refused jobs that white workers can get, which is unfair treatment based on race.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q001","read_aloud":"What does \"disrespectful\" mean? Options: A. Treating someone with kindness, B. Treating someone without politeness or respect, C. Being very helpful, D. Listening to someone carefully","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield makes me nervous. He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us.\"","stem":"What does \"disrespectful\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"Treating someone with kindness,","B":"Treating someone without politeness or respect,","C":"Being very helpful,","D":"Listening to someone carefully"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Disrespectful is the opposite of being respectful and polite, which fits Ivy\u0027s description of how he treats her parents.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield makes me nervous. He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q002","read_aloud":"What does this reveal about the setting of the story in the South? Options: A. It is a place where everyone is equal, B. It is a place where people are free to speak their minds, C. It is a dangerous and unfair place for black people, D. It is a place where people never get angry","excerpt":"\"I could tell Daddy was trying not to answer angrily because men like Mr. Greenfield sometimes hurt Negroes for \u0027talking back.\u0027\"","stem":"What does this reveal about the setting of the story in the South? Options:","choices":{"A":"It is a place where everyone is equal,","B":"It is a place where people are free to speak their minds,","C":"It is a dangerous and unfair place for black people,","D":"It is a place where people never get angry"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The threat of violence for \"talking back\" shows how dangerous and oppressive the environment was for black families.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I could tell Daddy was trying not to answer angrily because men like Mr. Greenfield sometimes hurt Negroes for \u0027talking back.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q003","read_aloud":"Why is the ticket so important to Ivy? Options: A. Because it is a souvenir, B. Because it cost a lot of money and represents their chance to leave, C. Because she wants to frame it in her room, D. Because she wants to trade it for more toys","excerpt":"\"I had a train ticket tucked inside my journal, which I clutched tightly in my arm. I didn\u0027t want to take any chance that the ticket might slip through my fingers.\"","stem":"Why is the ticket so important to Ivy? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because it is a souvenir,","B":"Because it cost a lot of money and represents their chance to leave,","C":"Because she wants to frame it in her room,","D":"Because she wants to trade it for more toys"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The family sold almost everything they owned to buy those tickets, and they did not have the money to buy more if they lost them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I had a train ticket tucked inside my journal, which I clutched tightly in my arm. I didn\u0027t want to take any chance that the ticket might slip through my fingers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q004","read_aloud":"How does the librarian\u0027s reaction compare to Ivy\u0027s expectations? Options: A. She was meaner than Ivy expected, B. She was surprised but kind, which was different from Ivy\u0027s past experiences, C. She did not want to help them at all, D. She asked them to leave immediately","excerpt":"\"The librarian who greeted us at the front desk looked a little surprised to see me walk in. I felt uncomfortable at first, and worried that she might frown... But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed.\"","stem":"How does the librarian\u0027s reaction compare to Ivy\u0027s expectations? Options:","choices":{"A":"She was meaner than Ivy expected,","B":"She was surprised but kind, which was different from Ivy\u0027s past experiences,","C":"She did not want to help them at all,","D":"She asked them to leave immediately"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy expected a mean reaction based on her life in the South, but the librarian\u0027s smile showed that not everyone behaved the same way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The librarian who greeted us at the front desk looked a little surprised to see me walk in. I felt uncomfortable at first, and worried that she might frown... But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q005","read_aloud":"How would the story change if Ivy\u0027s family had stayed in Mississippi? Options: A. They would have become rich farmers, B. They would have continued to face debt, limited opportunities, and the Jim Crow system, C. They would have moved to a different city in the South, D. They would have been allowed to go to the white school","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s hard not knowing what to expect, but this is our home now. And at the moment, I can\u0027t think of anywhere that I would rather be.\"","stem":"How would the story change if Ivy\u0027s family had stayed in Mississippi? Options:","choices":{"A":"They would have become rich farmers,","B":"They would have continued to face debt, limited opportunities, and the Jim Crow system,","C":"They would have moved to a different city in the South,","D":"They would have been allowed to go to the white school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Based on the text, staying in Mississippi meant continuing the cycle of debt, restricted education, and lack of equal rights under Jim Crow.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s hard not knowing what to expect, but this is our home now. And at the moment, I can\u0027t think of anywhere that I would rather be.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, how does \"war effort\" connect to opportunities for Ivy\u0027s family? A. The war effort meant fewer jobs for everyone B. The war effort created new job opportunities because factories needed more workers to support the military C. The war effort only helped white workers get jobs D. The war effort made it harder to travel between states","excerpt":"\"The war effort needed workers, so factories hired people who were usually not given jobs. This was part of the war effort-the pulling together of people and resources to support the military during a war.\"","stem":"In this context, how does \"war effort\" connect to opportunities for Ivy\u0027s family?","choices":{"A":"The war effort meant fewer jobs for everyone","B":"The war effort created new job opportunities because factories needed more workers to support the military","C":"The war effort only helped white workers get jobs","D":"The war effort made it harder to travel between states"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains the \"war effort\" involved \"pulling together of people and resources to support the military,\" which led factories to hire workers like Ivy\u0027s family who were previously excluded.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The war effort needed workers, so factories hired people who were usually not given jobs. This was part of the war effort-the pulling together of people and resources to support the military during a war.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q007","read_aloud":"How has Ivy\u0027s family\u0027s life improved since moving to California? A. They still worry about debt and crop failures B. They have a radio, a nice home, steady factory jobs, and freedom from Mr. Greenfield C. They miss sharecropping and want to go back D. They have more problems than they did in Mississippi","excerpt":"\"Last night, Daddy brought home a surprise: a radio! We\u0027ve never had a radio of our own. This morning, we listened to news about the war. Daddy and Mama are proud that their work helps the soldiers. The money they make helps us, too. We have a nice home, and we don\u0027t have worry about Mr. Greenfield or boll weevils anymore.\"","stem":"How has Ivy\u0027s family\u0027s life improved since moving to California?","choices":{"A":"They still worry about debt and crop failures","B":"They have a radio, a nice home, steady factory jobs, and freedom from Mr. Greenfield","C":"They miss sharecropping and want to go back","D":"They have more problems than they did in Mississippi"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt lists concrete improvements: a radio, nice home, pride in helping the war effort, and no more worries about Mr. Greenfield or boll weevils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Last night, Daddy brought home a surprise: a radio! We\u0027ve never had a radio of our own. This morning, we listened to news about the war. Daddy and Mama are proud that their work helps the soldiers. The money they make helps us, too. We have a nice home, and we don\u0027t have worry about Mr. Greenfield or boll weevils anymore.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q008","read_aloud":"What connection does Ivy make between her family and the Johnsons? A. They are related by blood B. They both migrated from the segregated South seeking better opportunities in the West C. They work at the same factory in the same job D. They plan to move back to Mississippi together","excerpt":"\"Like us, the Johnsons left the segregated South to find a better life in the West. It\u0027s funny that this time last year all of us were living thousands of miles away.\"","stem":"What connection does Ivy make between her family and the Johnsons?","choices":{"A":"They are related by blood","B":"They both migrated from the segregated South seeking better opportunities in the West","C":"They work at the same factory in the same job","D":"They plan to move back to Mississippi together"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy notes the Johnsons \"left the segregated South to find a better life in the West\" just like her family, showing a shared experience of the Great Migration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Like us, the Johnsons left the segregated South to find a better life in the West. It\u0027s funny that this time last year all of us were living thousands of miles away.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q009","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, do you think Ivy\u0027s family made the right choice to move to California? Support your answer with evidence. A. No, because everything is still difficult and they face discrimination B. Yes, because despite ongoing challenges, Ivy feels this is home and wouldn\u0027t rather be anywhere else C. No, because they should have moved to the North instead of the West D. Yes, but only because they had no other choice","excerpt":"\"Not everything is perfect in Los Angeles. Sometimes, white people are friendly to us, and sometimes they aren\u0027t. It\u0027s hard not knowing what to expect, but this is our home now. And at the moment, I can\u0027t think of anywhere that I would rather be.\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, do you think Ivy\u0027s family made the right choice to move to California? Support your answer with evidence.","choices":{"A":"No, because everything is still difficult and they face discrimination","B":"Yes, because despite ongoing challenges, Ivy feels this is home and wouldn\u0027t rather be anywhere else","C":"No, because they should have moved to the North instead of the West","D":"Yes, but only because they had no other choice"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy acknowledges challenges (\"not everything is perfect\") but concludes \"this is our home now\" and she \"can\u0027t think of anywhere that I would rather be,\" showing the move brought meaningful improvements worth the difficulties.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Not everything is perfect in Los Angeles. Sometimes, white people are friendly to us, and sometimes they aren\u0027t. It\u0027s hard not knowing what to expect, but this is our home now. And at the moment, I can\u0027t think of anywhere that I would rather be.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q010","read_aloud":"Based on the text, which word means almost the same as \"segregation\"? A. Separation B. Friendship C. Equality D. Celebration","excerpt":"\"We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people.\"","stem":"Based on the text, which word means almost the same as \"segregation\"?","choices":{"A":"Separation","B":"Friendship","C":"Equality","D":"Celebration"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Segregation means keeping groups apart, or separation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q011","read_aloud":"What does Ivy\u0027s wish tell you about her perspective on segregation? A. She thinks segregation is good. B. She believes all children should have equal rights. C. She does not care about rights. D. She only wants rights for herself, not others.","excerpt":"\"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\"","stem":"What does Ivy\u0027s wish tell you about her perspective on segregation?","choices":{"A":"She thinks segregation is good.","B":"She believes all children should have equal rights.","C":"She does not care about rights.","D":"She only wants rights for herself, not others."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy wants the same rights as other kids, showing she believes in equality.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q012","read_aloud":"Do you think Ivy\u0027s feeling better because of a new bedroom shows she is ignoring the real problem? Why or why not? A. Yes, she should only be sad. B. No, it is normal to feel both sad about problems and happy about good things. C. Yes, a bedroom cannot fix discrimination. D. No, she should be angry forever.","excerpt":"\"The idea that discrimination wasn\u0027t only in the South made me sad, but I felt better when I saw my new bedroom.\"","stem":"Do you think Ivy\u0027s feeling better because of a new bedroom shows she is ignoring the real problem? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, she should only be sad.","B":"No, it is normal to feel both sad about problems and happy about good things.","C":"Yes, a bedroom cannot fix discrimination.","D":"No, she should be angry forever."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"People can feel multiple emotions at once. Finding joy in small things does not mean ignoring larger problems.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The idea that discrimination wasn\u0027t only in the South made me sad, but I felt better when I saw my new bedroom.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q013","read_aloud":"The author chose to tell this story through Ivy\u0027s journal entries instead of a regular book chapter. How does that choice affect the reader? A. It makes the story less personal. B. It makes the reader feel closer to Ivy\u0027s private thoughts and feelings. C. It makes the story harder to understand. D. It does not change anything.","excerpt":"The whole story.","stem":"The author chose to tell this story through Ivy\u0027s journal entries instead of a regular book chapter. How does that choice affect the reader?","choices":{"A":"It makes the story less personal.","B":"It makes the reader feel closer to Ivy\u0027s private thoughts and feelings.","C":"It makes the story harder to understand.","D":"It does not change anything."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A journal feels personal and private, helping readers connect deeply with Ivy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole story."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy want to keep her journal hidden? A. Because she is ashamed of her writing. B. Because a journal is private, and she wants to keep her thoughts and feelings safe. C. Because she does not like the journal. D. Because she wants to lose it.","excerpt":"\"I decided to keep this journal tucked underneath my new mattress where no one will find it.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy want to keep her journal hidden?","choices":{"A":"Because she is ashamed of her writing.","B":"Because a journal is private, and she wants to keep her thoughts and feelings safe.","C":"Because she does not like the journal.","D":"Because she wants to lose it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy writes her private thoughts and feelings in her journal. Keeping it hidden under her mattress shows she values her privacy and wants to protect her personal thoughts.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I decided to keep this journal tucked underneath my new mattress where no one will find it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q015","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare the city noise to the quiet fields of Mississippi? A. To show that Ivy is deaf. B. To help readers understand how different and overwhelming the city feels to Ivy. C. To show that Mississippi is a noisy place. D. To teach about different types of vehicles.","excerpt":"\"Sitting on the bus, I wanted to cover my ears to block out all of the noise from the cars, buses, trucks, and their horns. It was so different from the quiet fields and dirt roads that I know from home.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare the city noise to the quiet fields of Mississippi?","choices":{"A":"To show that Ivy is deaf.","B":"To help readers understand how different and overwhelming the city feels to Ivy.","C":"To show that Mississippi is a noisy place.","D":"To teach about different types of vehicles."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The comparison helps readers feel what Ivy feels. The quiet fields are what she knows. The noisy city is new and overwhelming. This shows how much her life has changed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Sitting on the bus, I wanted to cover my ears to block out all of the noise from the cars, buses, trucks, and their horns. It was so different from the quiet fields and dirt roads that I know from home.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q016","read_aloud":"What does Ivy\u0027s sigh tell you about her character? A. She gives up easily. B. She is patient and understands that adjusting to change takes time. C. She is angry at her family. D. She hates California.","excerpt":"\"I sighed, realizing that getting used to this new place will take a while.\"","stem":"What does Ivy\u0027s sigh tell you about her character?","choices":{"A":"She gives up easily.","B":"She is patient and understands that adjusting to change takes time.","C":"She is angry at her family.","D":"She hates California."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy sighs but realizes getting used to the new place will take time. She does not complain or give up. This shows she is patient and willing to adapt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I sighed, realizing that getting used to this new place will take a while.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q017","read_aloud":"If Sally and Ivy become good friends, how might this help Ivy adjust to her new life? A. It would make her feel more lonely. B. Having a friend would help Ivy feel welcome and happy in her new school and city. C. It would make her forget about Eve completely. D. It would make her want to move back to Mississippi.","excerpt":"\"I hope as Sally and I get to know each other, we can become friends, too.\"","stem":"If Sally and Ivy become good friends, how might this help Ivy adjust to her new life?","choices":{"A":"It would make her feel more lonely.","B":"Having a friend would help Ivy feel welcome and happy in her new school and city.","C":"It would make her forget about Eve completely.","D":"It would make her want to move back to Mississippi."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Making a new friend like Sally would help Ivy feel less lonely. It would help her feel welcome and adjust to her new life in California.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I hope as Sally and I get to know each other, we can become friends, too.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q018","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q019","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. A system that brings all people together equally B. A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places C. A law that helps black people get better jobs D. A way to make schools better for everyone","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"A system that brings all people together equally","B":"A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places","C":"A law that helps black people get better jobs","D":"A way to make schools better for everyone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines segregation as \"a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people\" with separate facilities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. They make life easier for black people in the South B. They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go C. They help black people get better education D. They allow black and white people to mix freely","excerpt":"\"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"They make life easier for black people in the South","B":"They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go","C":"They help black people get better education","D":"They allow black and white people to mix freely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Jim Crow laws require separate sections and prevent black people from entering certain places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To move to a different country B. To have the same rights and opportunities as white children C. To become a lawyer and change the laws D. To stop going to school","excerpt":"\"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To move to a different country","B":"To have the same rights and opportunities as white children","C":"To become a lawyer and change the laws","D":"To stop going to school"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy directly states \"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\" after her mama explains Jim Crow limits opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. A gift for Ivy\u0027s birthday B. A bill showing how much money they owe C. New seeds for planting D. A letter from Uncle Eugene","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"A gift for Ivy\u0027s birthday","B":"A bill showing how much money they owe","C":"New seeds for planting","D":"A letter from Uncle Eugene"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Mr. Greenfield \"gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l09-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. With respect and kindness B. Like they are children and with disrespect C. Like they are his close friends D. Like they are business partners","excerpt":"\"He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children. I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"With respect and kindness","B":"Like they are children and with disrespect","C":"Like they are his close friends","D":"Like they are business partners"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states Mr. Greenfield \"is disrespectful\" and \"talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children. I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is segregation? Options: A. A system that keeps people together, B. A system that keeps people apart based on race, C. A school that is integrated, D. A type of job in a factory","excerpt":"\"They leave to find better jobs, get a better education, and escape segregation. This kind of movement of people from one place to another is called a \u0027migration.\u0027\"","stem":"Based on the text, what is segregation? Options:","choices":{"A":"A system that keeps people together,","B":"A system that keeps people apart based on race,","C":"A school that is integrated,","D":"A type of job in a factory"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains in the September 28 entry that segregation is a system set up to keep white and black people apart.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They leave to find better jobs, get a better education, and escape segregation. This kind of movement of people from one place to another is called a \u0027migration.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q002","read_aloud":"How does the author show that the South is a \"very, very hard place\" to live? Options: A. By describing the nice weather, B. By listing the unfair laws, the debt, and the danger of violence, C. By explaining that the jobs were easy to find, D. By saying that everyone had plenty of books","excerpt":"\"The South can be a very, very hard place for black people to live.\"","stem":"How does the author show that the South is a \"very, very hard place\" to live? Options:","choices":{"A":"By describing the nice weather,","B":"By listing the unfair laws, the debt, and the danger of violence,","C":"By explaining that the jobs were easy to find,","D":"By saying that everyone had plenty of books"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author uses Ivy\u0027s daily experiences-the debt, the restricted schools, and the fear of harm-to show the hardship.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The South can be a very, very hard place for black people to live.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q003","read_aloud":"Why are there more job opportunities in California? Options: A. California does not have factories, B. The government signed an order forbidding discrimination in military manufacturing, C. There are no schools in California, D. The South has too many jobs already","excerpt":"\"Most factories that make those kinds of products are out west. You don\u0027t find them here in the South. That\u0027s why Uncle Eugene was able to get a factory job in California even though it\u0027s impossible for black people to get that kind of work here.\"","stem":"Why are there more job opportunities in California? Options:","choices":{"A":"California does not have factories,","B":"The government signed an order forbidding discrimination in military manufacturing,","C":"There are no schools in California,","D":"The South has too many jobs already"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states that President Roosevelt signed a special order saying companies making military equipment could not discriminate, which helped people like Uncle Eugene.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Most factories that make those kinds of products are out west. You don\u0027t find them here in the South. That\u0027s why Uncle Eugene was able to get a factory job in California even though it\u0027s impossible for black people to get that kind of work here.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q004","read_aloud":"Do you agree with Mama\u0027s advice to Ivy? Why? Options: A. No, because moving should mean all problems disappear, B. Yes, because it is realistic to understand that challenges exist everywhere, C. No, because they should move again immediately, D. Yes, because she tells them not to work hard","excerpt":"\"Mama put an arm around me and hurried us both inside... \u0027Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\u0027\"","stem":"Do you agree with Mama\u0027s advice to Ivy? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"No, because moving should mean all problems disappear,","B":"Yes, because it is realistic to understand that challenges exist everywhere,","C":"No, because they should move again immediately,","D":"Yes, because she tells them not to work hard"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mama\u0027s advice teaches Ivy that while life is better, she should be prepared for challenges, which helps Ivy manage her expectations.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama put an arm around me and hurried us both inside... \u0027Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q005","read_aloud":"Why do you think Ivy feels the need to hide her journal in her new home? Options: A. She does not like the journal anymore, B. She is used to living in a place where she had to be careful, C. She wants to surprise her brother, D. She does not want to write in it anymore","excerpt":"\"I decided to keep this journal tucked underneath my new mattress where no one will find it.\"","stem":"Why do you think Ivy feels the need to hide her journal in her new home? Options:","choices":{"A":"She does not like the journal anymore,","B":"She is used to living in a place where she had to be careful,","C":"She wants to surprise her brother,","D":"She does not want to write in it anymore"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy is adjusting to a new place after a lifetime of living in a segregated, often dangerous environment, so her habit of keeping her private thoughts safe persists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I decided to keep this journal tucked underneath my new mattress where no one will find it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q006","read_aloud":"Why might the author choose to tell Ivy\u0027s story through journal entries rather than a regular narrative? A. To make the story shorter and easier to read B. To let readers experience events through Ivy\u0027s immediate thoughts and feelings as they happen, creating intimacy and authenticity C. To confuse readers about the order of events D. To avoid describing what Ivy looks like","excerpt":"The text is written as a journal with dated entries from May to November 1942.","stem":"Why might the author choose to tell Ivy\u0027s story through journal entries rather than a regular narrative?","choices":{"A":"To make the story shorter and easier to read","B":"To let readers experience events through Ivy\u0027s immediate thoughts and feelings as they happen, creating intimacy and authenticity","C":"To confuse readers about the order of events","D":"To avoid describing what Ivy looks like"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Journal entries use first-person, present-tense reflections that let readers feel Ivy\u0027s emotions in real-time-her hopes, fears, and observations-making the historical experience more personal and immediate.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text is written as a journal with dated entries from May to November 1942."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q007","read_aloud":"Which sentence uses \"discrimination\" correctly, like in the text? A. The discrimination of the cake was delicious. B. Discrimination means treating people unfairly because of their race. C. I went for a discrimination in the park. D. The discrimination was very fast.","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\"","stem":"Which sentence uses \"discrimination\" correctly, like in the text?","choices":{"A":"The discrimination of the cake was delicious.","B":"Discrimination means treating people unfairly because of their race.","C":"I went for a discrimination in the park.","D":"The discrimination was very fast."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Discrimination means unfair treatment, as shown in the text.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q008","read_aloud":"What is the biggest change in Ivy from the beginning to the end? A. She no longer wants to read. B. She goes from feeling trapped and treated unfairly to feeling hopeful and at home. C. She forgets all her Mississippi friends. D. She decides she hates California.","excerpt":"Review Ivy\u0027s feelings in Mississippi (pages 9‑12) and her feelings at the end in California (pages 23‑24).","stem":"What is the biggest change in Ivy from the beginning to the end?","choices":{"A":"She no longer wants to read.","B":"She goes from feeling trapped and treated unfairly to feeling hopeful and at home.","C":"She forgets all her Mississippi friends.","D":"She decides she hates California."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy starts with hardship and unfairness; she ends hopeful and calling California home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Review Ivy\u0027s feelings in Mississippi (pages 9‑12) and her feelings at the end in California (pages 23‑24)."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q009","read_aloud":"What does Ivy\u0027s mother\u0027s statement reveal about her view of the world? A. She thinks problems will magically disappear. B. She is realistic: change can help, but challenges may still exist. C. She wants to move back to Mississippi. D. She believes discrimination only exists in the South.","excerpt":"\"Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\"","stem":"What does Ivy\u0027s mother\u0027s statement reveal about her view of the world?","choices":{"A":"She thinks problems will magically disappear.","B":"She is realistic: change can help, but challenges may still exist.","C":"She wants to move back to Mississippi.","D":"She believes discrimination only exists in the South."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The mother knows moving improves things but does not solve every problem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q010","read_aloud":"If you were to write a sequel to \"Ivy\u0027s Journal\" set one year later, what would be an important event to include? A. Ivy forgetting her old life completely B. Ivy facing a new challenge or success at her integrated school C. The family moving back to Mississippi D. Ivy buying a car","excerpt":"The whole story.","stem":"If you were to write a sequel to \"Ivy\u0027s Journal\" set one year later, what would be an important event to include?","choices":{"A":"Ivy forgetting her old life completely","B":"Ivy facing a new challenge or success at her integrated school","C":"The family moving back to Mississippi","D":"Ivy buying a car"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The story focuses on school and adjustment, so a sequel would likely continue that.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole story."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q011","read_aloud":"Was the Great Migration worth it for Ivy\u0027s family? Use evidence from the text. A. No, because they faced discrimination in California too. B. Yes, because they gained better jobs, a better home, more freedom, and hope for the future. C. No, because they lost their farm. D. Yes, because they never faced any problems again.","excerpt":"The whole story.","stem":"Was the Great Migration worth it for Ivy\u0027s family? Use evidence from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, because they faced discrimination in California too.","B":"Yes, because they gained better jobs, a better home, more freedom, and hope for the future.","C":"No, because they lost their farm.","D":"Yes, because they never faced any problems again."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows clear improvements despite continued challenges.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole story."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q012","read_aloud":"Why is it important that the author\u0027s family were sharecroppers? A. It means the story is completely made up with no real connection to history. B. It means the author has personal family connections to the story, making it more authentic and meaningful. C. It means the author does not know anything about farming. D. It means the story is only about the author\u0027s life.","excerpt":"\"Lisa Benjamin\u0027s grandparents were sharecroppers who ran a small cotton farm in the segregated South. The tales she learned from her grandparents, father, aunts, and uncles all helped to shape the story of \u0027Ivy\u0027s Journal.\u0027\"","stem":"Why is it important that the author\u0027s family were sharecroppers?","choices":{"A":"It means the story is completely made up with no real connection to history.","B":"It means the author has personal family connections to the story, making it more authentic and meaningful.","C":"It means the author does not know anything about farming.","D":"It means the story is only about the author\u0027s life."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author\u0027s family history connects to the story. This makes the story more authentic because she understands the real experiences of sharecroppers through her family\u0027s tales.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Lisa Benjamin\u0027s grandparents were sharecroppers who ran a small cotton farm in the segregated South. The tales she learned from her grandparents, father, aunts, and uncles all helped to shape the story of \u0027Ivy\u0027s Journal.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q013","read_aloud":"Why does the author think remembering the past is important? A. Because the past is more fun than the future. B. Because understanding history helps us learn from it and make a better future. C. Because we should forget about the future. D. Because the past is not important at all.","excerpt":"\"She believes it\u0027s important to remember the past as we work toward the future.\"","stem":"Why does the author think remembering the past is important?","choices":{"A":"Because the past is more fun than the future.","B":"Because understanding history helps us learn from it and make a better future.","C":"Because we should forget about the future.","D":"Because the past is not important at all."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author says remembering the past helps us work toward the future. This means we learn from history to make better choices and create a better world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She believes it\u0027s important to remember the past as we work toward the future.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q014","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q015","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q016","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q017","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. A system that brings all people together equally B. A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places C. A law that helps black people get better jobs D. A way to make schools better for everyone","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"A system that brings all people together equally","B":"A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places","C":"A law that helps black people get better jobs","D":"A way to make schools better for everyone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines segregation as \"a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people\" with separate facilities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q018","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. They make life easier for black people in the South B. They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go C. They help black people get better education D. They allow black and white people to mix freely","excerpt":"\"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"They make life easier for black people in the South","B":"They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go","C":"They help black people get better education","D":"They allow black and white people to mix freely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Jim Crow laws require separate sections and prevent black people from entering certain places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q019","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To move to a different country B. To have the same rights and opportunities as white children C. To become a lawyer and change the laws D. To stop going to school","excerpt":"\"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To move to a different country","B":"To have the same rights and opportunities as white children","C":"To become a lawyer and change the laws","D":"To stop going to school"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy directly states \"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\" after her mama explains Jim Crow limits opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. A gift for Ivy\u0027s birthday B. A bill showing how much money they owe C. New seeds for planting D. A letter from Uncle Eugene","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"A gift for Ivy\u0027s birthday","B":"A bill showing how much money they owe","C":"New seeds for planting","D":"A letter from Uncle Eugene"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Mr. Greenfield \"gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. With respect and kindness B. Like they are children and with disrespect C. Like they are his close friends D. Like they are business partners","excerpt":"\"He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children. I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"With respect and kindness","B":"Like they are children and with disrespect","C":"Like they are his close friends","D":"Like they are business partners"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states Mr. Greenfield \"is disrespectful\" and \"talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children. I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Treating everyone exactly the same B. Unfair treatment of people based on their race or other characteristics C. Helping people find good jobs D. Making rules that benefit everyone equally","excerpt":"\"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Treating everyone exactly the same","B":"Unfair treatment of people based on their race or other characteristics","C":"Helping people find good jobs","D":"Making rules that benefit everyone equally"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text shows discrimination means black workers are refused jobs that white workers can get, which is unfair treatment based on race.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. Because he wanted to visit California for vacation B. Because the bills got too high and he needed better opportunities C. Because he didn\u0027t like the weather D. Because he was forced to leave by Mr. Greenfield","excerpt":"\"Today, we got a letter from Mama\u0027s brother, Uncle Eugene. He used to be a sharecropper like us, but he left Mississippi not long ago when the bills got too high. At the beginning of the year, he took a train all the way out west and moved to a city called Los Angeles in California.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"Because he wanted to visit California for vacation","B":"Because the bills got too high and he needed better opportunities","C":"Because he didn\u0027t like the weather","D":"Because he was forced to leave by Mr. Greenfield"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text says Uncle Eugene left \"when the bills got too high,\" showing he sought better opportunities elsewhere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today, we got a letter from Mama\u0027s brother, Uncle Eugene. He used to be a sharecropper like us, but he left Mississippi not long ago when the bills got too high. At the beginning of the year, he took a train all the way out west and moved to a city called Los Angeles in California.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. Factories in California don\u0027t need many workers B. California factories hire black workers and women, unlike Mississippi C. Jobs in California pay less than sharecropping D. Black people can only work on farms in California too","excerpt":"\"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"Factories in California don\u0027t need many workers","B":"California factories hire black workers and women, unlike Mississippi","C":"Jobs in California pay less than sharecropping","D":"Black people can only work on farms in California too"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Uncle Eugene\u0027s letter states factories \"need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs,\" contrasting with Mississippi where such jobs refused to hire black workers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-l10-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. They could ignore Mr. Greenfield\u0027s bills B. They could apply for factory jobs in California that now must hire without discrimination C. They could move back to their old farm D. They could stop working altogether","excerpt":"\"At dinner, Daddy told us that he had been asking our neighbors what they know about living and working in places like California. He found out that last year President Franklin Roosevelt signed a special order. It said companies that manufacture equipment for the military cannot practice discrimination.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"They could ignore Mr. Greenfield\u0027s bills","B":"They could apply for factory jobs in California that now must hire without discrimination","C":"They could move back to their old farm","D":"They could stop working altogether"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The special order means military equipment factories can\u0027t discriminate, so Ivy\u0027s family could seek those jobs in California where they were previously excluded.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At dinner, Daddy told us that he had been asking our neighbors what they know about living and working in places like California. He found out that last year President Franklin Roosevelt signed a special order. It said companies that manufacture equipment for the military cannot practice discrimination.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q001","read_aloud":"What does a \"sharecropper\" do? Options: A. They own the land they farm, B. They pay rent by giving a portion of their crop to the landowner, C. They work in an airplane factory, D. They work at a library","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What does a \"sharecropper\" do? Options:","choices":{"A":"They own the land they farm,","B":"They pay rent by giving a portion of their crop to the landowner,","C":"They work in an airplane factory,","D":"They work at a library"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q002","read_aloud":"What are Jim Crow laws? Options: A. Laws that ensure everyone is treated equally, B. Laws that were used to separate and limit opportunities for black people, C. Laws about how to plant cotton, D. Laws about library hours","excerpt":"\"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do.\"","stem":"What are Jim Crow laws? Options:","choices":{"A":"Laws that ensure everyone is treated equally,","B":"Laws that were used to separate and limit opportunities for black people,","C":"Laws about how to plant cotton,","D":"Laws about library hours"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mama explains that Jim Crow is a system to keep black people from having the same opportunities as white people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q003","read_aloud":"What does it mean for a school to be \"integrated\"? Options: A. White and black children go to school together, B. Only white children go there, C. Only black children go there, D. It is a private school","excerpt":"\"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together.\"","stem":"What does it mean for a school to be \"integrated\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"White and black children go to school together,","B":"Only white children go there,","C":"Only black children go there,","D":"It is a private school"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explicitly defines integrated as children attending school together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q004","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of Ivy\u0027s journal? Options: A. Ivy loves to write about school, B. Ivy\u0027s family moves from Mississippi to California to find a better life, C. Ivy\u0027s family wants to learn how to farm cotton, D. Ivy wants to visit Uncle Eugene","excerpt":"\"Today, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of Ivy\u0027s journal? Options:","choices":{"A":"Ivy loves to write about school,","B":"Ivy\u0027s family moves from Mississippi to California to find a better life,","C":"Ivy\u0027s family wants to learn how to farm cotton,","D":"Ivy wants to visit Uncle Eugene"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The journal chronicles the family\u0027s life in the South and their decision to move to California to find better opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q005","read_aloud":"What job did Uncle Eugene find in California? Options: A. Farming cotton, B. Building airplanes in a factory, C. Running a store, D. Working in a library","excerpt":"\"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort.\"","stem":"What job did Uncle Eugene find in California? Options:","choices":{"A":"Farming cotton,","B":"Building airplanes in a factory,","C":"Running a store,","D":"Working in a library"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The September 22 entry describes Uncle Eugene\u0027s job at a factory that builds airplanes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q006","read_aloud":"What happened after the family decided to move? Options: A. They bought a new farm, B. They sold most of their belongings and took a train to California, C. They stayed in Mississippi, D. They visited the library","excerpt":"\"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! ... This morning, I stood with my family on the platform of the railroad station near our town.\"","stem":"What happened after the family decided to move? Options:","choices":{"A":"They bought a new farm,","B":"They sold most of their belongings and took a train to California,","C":"They stayed in Mississippi,","D":"They visited the library"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"After deciding to move, they sold their items to pay debts and for train tickets before starting the journey.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! ... This morning, I stood with my family on the platform of the railroad station near our town.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q007","read_aloud":"Why did Ivy\u0027s parents decide that moving was necessary? Options: A. They were bored with the farm, B. They were in debt and wanted a better life for their children, C. They wanted to live in a big city, D. Uncle Eugene asked them to move","excerpt":"\"Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here.\"","stem":"Why did Ivy\u0027s parents decide that moving was necessary? Options:","choices":{"A":"They were bored with the farm,","B":"They were in debt and wanted a better life for their children,","C":"They wanted to live in a big city,","D":"Uncle Eugene asked them to move"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The failure of the cotton crop and the heavy debt made staying in the South impossible, leading them to seek a better future.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q008","read_aloud":"How does Ivy\u0027s experience in the library show the change in her world? Options: A. It shows she is still living in the segregated South, B. It shows she is in a new environment where her previous fears do not always apply, C. It shows she still cannot read, D. It shows that all white people are unfriendly","excerpt":"\"I felt uncomfortable at first, and worried that she might frown like Mr. Greenfield and some of my white neighbors do... But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed.\"","stem":"How does Ivy\u0027s experience in the library show the change in her world? Options:","choices":{"A":"It shows she is still living in the segregated South,","B":"It shows she is in a new environment where her previous fears do not always apply,","C":"It shows she still cannot read,","D":"It shows that all white people are unfriendly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The librarian\u0027s kindness contrasts with her past experiences, proving she is in a new place with different social rules.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I felt uncomfortable at first, and worried that she might frown like Mr. Greenfield and some of my white neighbors do... But the librarian broke into a smile and asked us what we needed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q009","read_aloud":"What does Mama\u0027s statement tell us about her view of the move to California? Options: A. She thinks the move was a mistake, B. She knows that while their lives have improved, they will still encounter some prejudice, C. She thinks California is exactly like Mississippi, D. She does not want to work in a factory","excerpt":"\"Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\"","stem":"What does Mama\u0027s statement tell us about her view of the move to California? Options:","choices":{"A":"She thinks the move was a mistake,","B":"She knows that while their lives have improved, they will still encounter some prejudice,","C":"She thinks California is exactly like Mississippi,","D":"She does not want to work in a factory"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mama\u0027s wisdom helps Ivy stay grounded; she knows the family has better chances but understands discrimination isn\u0027t magically gone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q010","read_aloud":"How has Ivy changed from the beginning of the journal to the end? Options: A. She has become sadder, B. She has become more confident and has accepted her new life, C. She wants to return to the farm, D. She stopped writing in her journal","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s hard not knowing what to expect, but this is our home now. And at the moment, I can\u0027t think of anywhere that I would rather be.\"","stem":"How has Ivy changed from the beginning of the journal to the end? Options:","choices":{"A":"She has become sadder,","B":"She has become more confident and has accepted her new life,","C":"She wants to return to the farm,","D":"She stopped writing in her journal"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy moves from being a scared girl leaving her home to someone who appreciates her new opportunities and feels comfortable, showing her personal growth. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Ivy\u0027s Journal\" Author: Lisa Benjamin Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 3, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s hard not knowing what to expect, but this is our home now. And at the moment, I can\u0027t think of anywhere that I would rather be.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"sharecroppers\" mean in this context? A. People who own their own farms and keep all their profits B. Farmers who rent land by paying with a portion of their harvest C. Workers who are paid wages in money at factories D. People who travel from farm to farm looking for seasonal work","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What does \"sharecroppers\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"People who own their own farms and keep all their profits","B":"Farmers who rent land by paying with a portion of their harvest","C":"Workers who are paid wages in money at factories","D":"People who travel from farm to farm looking for seasonal work"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains sharecroppers \"pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop,\" which matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q012","read_aloud":"Based on this excerpt, what is the main effect of boll weevils on cotton farming? A. They help cotton plants grow stronger B. They damage or destroy cotton crops by eating the plants C. They provide food for other farm animals D. They make cotton easier to harvest","excerpt":"\"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant.\"","stem":"Based on this excerpt, what is the main effect of boll weevils on cotton farming?","choices":{"A":"They help cotton plants grow stronger","B":"They damage or destroy cotton crops by eating the plants","C":"They provide food for other farm animals","D":"They make cotton easier to harvest"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states boll weevils \"eat parts of the plant\" and later notes \"most of the crop was ruined,\" showing they harm cotton farming.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q013","read_aloud":"What does \"integrated\" mean in this school context? A. A school that only allows one race to attend B. A school where students of different races learn together in the same classes C. A school that doesn\u0027t teach history or social studies D. A school that is only for children who live nearby","excerpt":"\"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together. We sit in the same classrooms, side by side, and no one thinks anything of it.\"","stem":"What does \"integrated\" mean in this school context?","choices":{"A":"A school that only allows one race to attend","B":"A school where students of different races learn together in the same classes","C":"A school that doesn\u0027t teach history or social studies","D":"A school that is only for children who live nearby"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly defines integrated as meaning \"white and black children attend together\" in the same classrooms.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together. We sit in the same classrooms, side by side, and no one thinks anything of it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Segregation makes life more convenient for everyone B. Segregation is a system that legally separates black and white people in public life C. Segregation only affects schools and not other places D. Segregation was a choice that black families made","excerpt":"\"We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Segregation makes life more convenient for everyone","B":"Segregation is a system that legally separates black and white people in public life","C":"Segregation only affects schools and not other places","D":"Segregation was a choice that black families made"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt explains segregation as a \"system\" with \"separate\" facilities, showing it was an organized policy of separation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q015","read_aloud":"How did the war effort create new opportunities for Ivy\u0027s family? A. It reduced the number of jobs available to everyone B. It increased demand for workers, leading factories to hire people who were previously excluded C. It only created jobs for men who had served in the military D. It made it illegal for black people to work in factories","excerpt":"\"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\"","stem":"How did the war effort create new opportunities for Ivy\u0027s family?","choices":{"A":"It reduced the number of jobs available to everyone","B":"It increased demand for workers, leading factories to hire people who were previously excluded","C":"It only created jobs for men who had served in the military","D":"It made it illegal for black people to work in factories"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states factories \"need a lot of workers\" for the war effort, so they hired \"women and Negroes\" who previously couldn\u0027t get such jobs.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q016","read_aloud":"What are two reasons Ivy\u0027s family decides to move to California? A. To visit Uncle Eugene and to go on vacation B. For higher-paying factory jobs and more freedom from segregation laws C. Because Mississippi has too much cotton to harvest D. Because California has no schools or jobs","excerpt":"\"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California... Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here. Also, Mama says there are no Jim Crow laws in California, so we\u0027ll have so much more freedom.\"","stem":"What are two reasons Ivy\u0027s family decides to move to California?","choices":{"A":"To visit Uncle Eugene and to go on vacation","B":"For higher-paying factory jobs and more freedom from segregation laws","C":"Because Mississippi has too much cotton to harvest","D":"Because California has no schools or jobs"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states two motivations: factory jobs pay more than sharecropping, and California lacks Jim Crow laws, offering more freedom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California... Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here. Also, Mama says there are no Jim Crow laws in California, so we\u0027ll have so much more freedom.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q017","read_aloud":"What year does Ivy write in her journal? A. 1922 B. 1942 C. 1962 D. 1982","excerpt":"\"I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover: Ivy Mitchell. Below that, I added the year: 1942.\"","stem":"What year does Ivy write in her journal?","choices":{"A":"1922","B":"1942","C":"1962","D":"1982"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states Ivy \"added the year: 1942.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I opened the journal and wrote my name on the inside cover: Ivy Mitchell. Below that, I added the year: 1942.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q018","read_aloud":"Based on the entire selection, was the Mitchell family\u0027s migration successful? Use evidence to support your view. A. No, because they still face some discrimination and uncertainty B. Yes, because despite ongoing challenges, they gained economic stability, more freedom, and a sense of home C. No, because they should have moved to the North instead D. Yes, but only because they had no other choice","excerpt":"\"Not everything is perfect in Los Angeles. Sometimes, white people are friendly to us, and sometimes they aren\u0027t. It\u0027s hard not knowing what to expect, but this is our home now. And at the moment, I can\u0027t think of anywhere that I would rather be.\"","stem":"Based on the entire selection, was the Mitchell family\u0027s migration successful? Use evidence to support your view.","choices":{"A":"No, because they still face some discrimination and uncertainty","B":"Yes, because despite ongoing challenges, they gained economic stability, more freedom, and a sense of home","C":"No, because they should have moved to the North instead","D":"Yes, but only because they had no other choice"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy acknowledges imperfection (\"not everything is perfect\") but emphasizes gains: factory jobs, no Jim Crow laws, a nice home, and feeling that California is \"home.\" This balanced view shows success isn\u0027t about perfection but meaningful improvement.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Not everything is perfect in Los Angeles. Sometimes, white people are friendly to us, and sometimes they aren\u0027t. It\u0027s hard not knowing what to expect, but this is our home now. And at the moment, I can\u0027t think of anywhere that I would rather be.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q019","read_aloud":"How do sharecroppers pay rent? A. With money from factory jobs B. By giving a percentage of their crop C. By working for free D. By selling their furniture","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"How do sharecroppers pay rent?","choices":{"A":"With money from factory jobs","B":"By giving a percentage of their crop","C":"By working for free","D":"By selling their furniture"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they pay rent by giving a large percentage of their crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q020","read_aloud":"What does segregation separate? A. Boys from girls B. White people from black people C. Teachers from students D. Cities from farms","excerpt":"\"We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people.\"","stem":"What does segregation separate?","choices":{"A":"Boys from girls","B":"White people from black people","C":"Teachers from students","D":"Cities from farms"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says it keeps white people apart from black people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q021","read_aloud":"What is the opposite of an integrated school? A. A public school B. A segregated school C. A large school D. A private school","excerpt":"\"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together.\"","stem":"What is the opposite of an integrated school?","choices":{"A":"A public school","B":"A segregated school","C":"A large school","D":"A private school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Segregated means separated, the opposite of integrated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This elementary school is integrated, which means that white and black children attend together.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q022","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of \"Ivy\u0027s Journal\"? A. A girl describes her daily chores on a farm. B. A girl moves from Mississippi to California during the Great Migration for a better life. C. A girl learns to bake a cake. D. A girl wants a new pet.","excerpt":"The whole story.","stem":"What is the main idea of \"Ivy\u0027s Journal\"?","choices":{"A":"A girl describes her daily chores on a farm.","B":"A girl moves from Mississippi to California during the Great Migration for a better life.","C":"A girl learns to bake a cake.","D":"A girl wants a new pet."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The story follows Ivy\u0027s family leaving the South for California during the Great Migration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole story."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q023","read_aloud":"What caused the crop to be ruined? A. Too much rain B. A fire C. Boll weevils D. Lack of seeds","excerpt":"\"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. … most of the crop was ruined!\"","stem":"What caused the crop to be ruined?","choices":{"A":"Too much rain","B":"A fire","C":"Boll weevils","D":"Lack of seeds"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text says boll weevils attacked and ruined most of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. … most of the crop was ruined!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q024","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Ivy\u0027s feelings for Eve? A. Ivy does not like Eve. B. Eve is a close friend Ivy will miss very much. C. Eve is moving with Ivy. D. Ivy forgot Eve\u0027s name.","excerpt":"\"I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again!\"","stem":"What can you infer about Ivy\u0027s feelings for Eve?","choices":{"A":"Ivy does not like Eve.","B":"Eve is a close friend Ivy will miss very much.","C":"Eve is moving with Ivy.","D":"Ivy forgot Eve\u0027s name."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy is sad to leave because she may never see Eve again, showing strong friendship.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q025","read_aloud":"What kind of factory job did Uncle Eugene get? A. Building cars B. Building airplanes C. Building houses D. Building ships","excerpt":"\"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. … the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\"","stem":"What kind of factory job did Uncle Eugene get?","choices":{"A":"Building cars","B":"Building airplanes","C":"Building houses","D":"Building ships"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says he builds airplanes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. … the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q026","read_aloud":"Do you think the author included this scene to show that moving solved all problems? Why or why not? A. Yes, because everyone was friendly. B. No, the author shows that even after moving, discrimination still exists. C. Yes, because the family ignored them. D. No, because the author forgot to write a happy scene.","excerpt":"\"Not everyone was welcoming when we arrived. A white mother and son were standing on the sidewalk … The mother frowned at us just like Mr. Greenfield used to, then the son stuck out his tongue and spit on the ground near our feet.\"","stem":"Do you think the author included this scene to show that moving solved all problems? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because everyone was friendly.","B":"No, the author shows that even after moving, discrimination still exists.","C":"Yes, because the family ignored them.","D":"No, because the author forgot to write a happy scene."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author shows that while laws changed, some people\u0027s attitudes did not.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Not everyone was welcoming when we arrived. A white mother and son were standing on the sidewalk … The mother frowned at us just like Mr. Greenfield used to, then the son stuck out his tongue and spit on the ground near our feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q027","read_aloud":"Imagine you could write a letter to Ivy after reading her journal. What is one question you would ask her about her experience? A. What is your favorite color? B. How did you find the courage to leave everything you knew and start over? C. How many shoes do you own? D. What is your favorite TV show?","excerpt":"The whole story.","stem":"Imagine you could write a letter to Ivy after reading her journal. What is one question you would ask her about her experience?","choices":{"A":"What is your favorite color?","B":"How did you find the courage to leave everything you knew and start over?","C":"How many shoes do you own?","D":"What is your favorite TV show?"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This question connects to the central theme of courage and starting over. Section A - Text information Title: Ivy\u0027s Journal Author: Lisa Benjamin","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole story."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q028","read_aloud":"What does it mean to be a sharecropper? A. to own a large farm with many workers B. to farm land owned by someone else and pay rent with part of the crop C. to work in a factory building airplanes D. to own a store in town","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"What does it mean to be a sharecropper?","choices":{"A":"to own a large farm with many workers","B":"to farm land owned by someone else and pay rent with part of the crop","C":"to work in a factory building airplanes","D":"to own a store in town"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says sharecroppers pay rent by giving a percentage of their crop to the landowner. Ivy\u0027s family does not own the land; they work on Mr. Greenfield\u0027s land.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q029","read_aloud":"How does discrimination affect Ivy\u0027s family? A. It helps them find good jobs. B. It unfairly limits their job choices and keeps them in debt. C. It gives them free land. D. It makes them very popular.","excerpt":"\"It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face. So, many black people are stuck working on small farms and facing a mountain of debt.\"","stem":"How does discrimination affect Ivy\u0027s family?","choices":{"A":"It helps them find good jobs.","B":"It unfairly limits their job choices and keeps them in debt.","C":"It gives them free land.","D":"It makes them very popular."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Discrimination means stores and factories refuse to hire black workers. This unfairly limits their choices and keeps them stuck as sharecroppers with debt.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face. So, many black people are stuck working on small farms and facing a mountain of debt.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q030","read_aloud":"What are boll weevils? A. helpful bugs that protect cotton plants B. small insects that feed on cotton plants and ruin crops C. large birds that eat seeds D. a type of fertilizer used by farmers","excerpt":"\"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant.\"","stem":"What are boll weevils?","choices":{"A":"helpful bugs that protect cotton plants","B":"small insects that feed on cotton plants and ruin crops","C":"large birds that eat seeds","D":"a type of fertilizer used by farmers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says boll weevils are tiny bugs that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young hatch, they eat parts of the plant and ruin the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q031","read_aloud":"What did Ivy\u0027s family do first when they decided to move to California? A. They sold their furniture. B. Daddy wrote to Uncle Eugene for help finding work. C. They bought train tickets. D. They stood on the train platform.","excerpt":"\"Ivy\u0027s family is moving to California. First, Daddy wrote Uncle Eugene for help finding work. Then they sold their furniture to pay some of the money they owed Mr. Greenfield and to buy train tickets. Finally, they stood on the platform waiting for the train.\"","stem":"What did Ivy\u0027s family do first when they decided to move to California?","choices":{"A":"They sold their furniture.","B":"Daddy wrote to Uncle Eugene for help finding work.","C":"They bought train tickets.","D":"They stood on the train platform."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Daddy first wrote Uncle Eugene for help finding work. After that, they sold furniture to pay debts and buy tickets. Finally, they went to the train platform.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Ivy\u0027s family is moving to California. First, Daddy wrote Uncle Eugene for help finding work. Then they sold their furniture to pay some of the money they owed Mr. Greenfield and to buy train tickets. Finally, they stood on the platform waiting for the train.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q032","read_aloud":"Why does Ivy\u0027s family chuckle when they hear about California? A. Because they think it is funny that black people can get factory jobs. B. Because they are happy and hopeful that life in California might be better and fairer. C. Because they do not believe Uncle Eugene. D. Because they want to make fun of Mississippi.","excerpt":"\"\u0027Wow, they hire Negroes to work in factories there?\u0027 I asked. \u0027California sure sounds different from Mississippi!\u0027 Buck said, and we all chuckled.\"","stem":"Why does Ivy\u0027s family chuckle when they hear about California?","choices":{"A":"Because they think it is funny that black people can get factory jobs.","B":"Because they are happy and hopeful that life in California might be better and fairer.","C":"Because they do not believe Uncle Eugene.","D":"Because they want to make fun of Mississippi."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The family chuckles because California sounds so different from Mississippi. They are surprised but also happy and hopeful that black people can get good jobs there.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"\u0027Wow, they hire Negroes to work in factories there?\u0027 I asked. \u0027California sure sounds different from Mississippi!\u0027 Buck said, and we all chuckled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q033","read_aloud":"What does Mama mean when she says \"some things will still be the same\"? A. She means everything in California will be exactly like Mississippi. B. She means they will still face some discrimination, but they must be strong and face it together. C. She means they should move back to Mississippi. D. She means they will never make any friends.","excerpt":"\"Mama put an arm around me and hurried us both inside. As we climbed the three flights to our apartment, she said, \u0027Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\u0027\"","stem":"What does Mama mean when she says \"some things will still be the same\"?","choices":{"A":"She means everything in California will be exactly like Mississippi.","B":"She means they will still face some discrimination, but they must be strong and face it together.","C":"She means they should move back to Mississippi.","D":"She means they will never make any friends."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Mama knows that even in California, some white people will not be welcoming. She tells Ivy they must face these challenges the best they can. This means they will still face discrimination but must be strong.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama put an arm around me and hurried us both inside. As we climbed the three flights to our apartment, she said, \u0027Even though things are different here, some things will still be the same. We will have to face them the best that we can.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q034","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q035","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q036","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. A person who owns a large store in town, B. A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop, C. A teacher who works at a school for white children, D. A factory worker who builds airplanes","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"A person who owns a large store in town,","B":"A farmer who pays for land with a part of their crop,","C":"A teacher who works at a school for white children,","D":"A factory worker who builds airplanes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text defines sharecroppers as farmers who pay for the land they rent with a percentage of the crop.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s because we\u0027re sharecroppers. A white businessman named Mr. Greenfield owns the land that we live on, and we pay rent by giving him a large percentage of our crop.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q037","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. A system that brings all people together equally B. A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places C. A law that helps black people get better jobs D. A way to make schools better for everyone","excerpt":"\"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"A system that brings all people together equally","B":"A system that keeps white and black people separate in public places","C":"A law that helps black people get better jobs","D":"A way to make schools better for everyone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines segregation as \"a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people\" with separate facilities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That\u0027s how the world works here in Mississippi. We live with segregation, which is a system that\u0027s set up to keep white people apart from black people. There are separate schools, separate bathrooms, even separate water fountains.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q038","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. They make life easier for black people in the South B. They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go C. They help black people get better education D. They allow black and white people to mix freely","excerpt":"\"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"They make life easier for black people in the South","B":"They force black people to use separate facilities and limit where they can go","C":"They help black people get better education","D":"They allow black and white people to mix freely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt shows Jim Crow laws require separate sections and prevent black people from entering certain places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At the movies or restaurants, black people have to sit in a separate section. There are some places that we\u0027re not allowed to go into at all, like certain hotels or libraries. It\u0027s like that all over the South because of a set of laws that people call \u0027Jim Crow.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q039","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. To move to a different country B. To have the same rights and opportunities as white children C. To become a lawyer and change the laws D. To stop going to school","excerpt":"\"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"To move to a different country","B":"To have the same rights and opportunities as white children","C":"To become a lawyer and change the laws","D":"To stop going to school"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Ivy directly states \"I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\" after her mama explains Jim Crow limits opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mama says that Jim Crow is a way to keep black people from having the same opportunities that white people do. I wish that we didn\u0027t have to live this way. I only want to have the same rights as other kids!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q040","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. A gift for Ivy\u0027s birthday B. A bill showing how much money they owe C. New seeds for planting D. A letter from Uncle Eugene","excerpt":"\"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"A gift for Ivy\u0027s birthday","B":"A bill showing how much money they owe","C":"New seeds for planting","D":"A letter from Uncle Eugene"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Mr. Greenfield \"gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Mr. Greenfield stopped by the farm today to see how this year\u0027s crop is coming along. He gave Daddy a bill for everything that we owe so far this season. It was added to the money that we still owe from last year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. With respect and kindness B. Like they are children and with disrespect C. Like they are his close friends D. Like they are business partners","excerpt":"\"He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children. I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"With respect and kindness","B":"Like they are children and with disrespect","C":"Like they are his close friends","D":"Like they are business partners"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states Mr. Greenfield \"is disrespectful\" and \"talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He frowns a lot and is disrespectful to us. He talks to Mama and Daddy like they are children. I saw Daddy\u0027s jaw tighten as Mr. Greenfield said, \u0027You better pay off all your bills this year, boy. I won\u0027t stand for any laziness on one of my farms.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q042","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. Treating everyone exactly the same B. Unfair treatment of people based on their race or other characteristics C. Helping people find good jobs D. Making rules that benefit everyone equally","excerpt":"\"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"Treating everyone exactly the same","B":"Unfair treatment of people based on their race or other characteristics","C":"Helping people find good jobs","D":"Making rules that benefit everyone equally"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text shows discrimination means black workers are refused jobs that white workers can get, which is unfair treatment based on race.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"People who work in stores and factories in our area can make good money, but those places refuse to hire Negro workers. It\u0027s another part of the discrimination that we face.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q043","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. Because he wanted to visit California for vacation B. Because the bills got too high and he needed better opportunities C. Because he didn\u0027t like the weather D. Because he was forced to leave by Mr. Greenfield","excerpt":"\"Today, we got a letter from Mama\u0027s brother, Uncle Eugene. He used to be a sharecropper like us, but he left Mississippi not long ago when the bills got too high. At the beginning of the year, he took a train all the way out west and moved to a city called Los Angeles in California.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"Because he wanted to visit California for vacation","B":"Because the bills got too high and he needed better opportunities","C":"Because he didn\u0027t like the weather","D":"Because he was forced to leave by Mr. Greenfield"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The text says Uncle Eugene left \"when the bills got too high,\" showing he sought better opportunities elsewhere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today, we got a letter from Mama\u0027s brother, Uncle Eugene. He used to be a sharecropper like us, but he left Mississippi not long ago when the bills got too high. At the beginning of the year, he took a train all the way out west and moved to a city called Los Angeles in California.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q044","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. Factories in California don\u0027t need many workers B. California factories hire black workers and women, unlike Mississippi C. Jobs in California pay less than sharecropping D. Black people can only work on farms in California too","excerpt":"\"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"Factories in California don\u0027t need many workers","B":"California factories hire black workers and women, unlike Mississippi","C":"Jobs in California pay less than sharecropping","D":"Black people can only work on farms in California too"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Uncle Eugene\u0027s letter states factories \"need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs,\" contrasting with Mississippi where such jobs refused to hire black workers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In his letter, he told us that he found a job at a factory that builds airplanes. The planes will help carry supplies and soldiers for the war effort. He says that the factories need a lot of workers, so women and Negroes have the chance to get good jobs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q045","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. They could ignore Mr. Greenfield\u0027s bills B. They could apply for factory jobs in California that now must hire without discrimination C. They could move back to their old farm D. They could stop working altogether","excerpt":"\"At dinner, Daddy told us that he had been asking our neighbors what they know about living and working in places like California. He found out that last year President Franklin Roosevelt signed a special order. It said companies that manufacture equipment for the military cannot practice discrimination.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"They could ignore Mr. Greenfield\u0027s bills","B":"They could apply for factory jobs in California that now must hire without discrimination","C":"They could move back to their old farm","D":"They could stop working altogether"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The special order means military equipment factories can\u0027t discriminate, so Ivy\u0027s family could seek those jobs in California where they were previously excluded.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At dinner, Daddy told us that he had been asking our neighbors what they know about living and working in places like California. He found out that last year President Franklin Roosevelt signed a special order. It said companies that manufacture equipment for the military cannot practice discrimination.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q046","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. She wants to stay on the farm forever B. She dreams of having more choices and freedom in where she lives and works C. She wants to become a sharecropper like her parents D. She hopes to move back to Mississippi someday","excerpt":"\"I tried to picture what it might be like to live in a place where Negroes have more freedom. Where people like me could apply for any job they wanted. Maybe I didn\u0027t have to live on small farms all my life. Maybe one day, I could move somewhere else and do other kinds of work when I grow up.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"She wants to stay on the farm forever","B":"She dreams of having more choices and freedom in where she lives and works","C":"She wants to become a sharecropper like her parents","D":"She hopes to move back to Mississippi someday"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy imagines \"a place where Negroes have more freedom\" and applying \"for any job they wanted,\" showing her hope for expanded opportunities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I tried to picture what it might be like to live in a place where Negroes have more freedom. Where people like me could apply for any job they wanted. Maybe I didn\u0027t have to live on small farms all my life. Maybe one day, I could move somewhere else and do other kinds of work when I grow up.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q047","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. Helpful insects that protect cotton plants B. Small pests that damage cotton crops by eating the plants C. A type of fertilizer for farming D. Tools used to pick cotton","excerpt":"\"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant. Boll weevils are a problem every year.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"Helpful insects that protect cotton plants","B":"Small pests that damage cotton crops by eating the plants","C":"A type of fertilizer for farming","D":"Tools used to pick cotton"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text defines boll weevils as \"tiny bugs\" that \"eat parts of the plant\" and are \"a problem every year\" for cotton.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Boll weevils had attacked our crop. These tiny bugs are pests that lay eggs in cotton plants. When the young insects hatch, they eat parts of the plant. Boll weevils are a problem every year.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q048","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 512. A. They harvested more cotton than ever B. Most of their cotton crop was destroyed C. The boll weevils helped the cotton grow better D. They were able to sell the boll weevils for money","excerpt":"\"Harvest time is finally here, and our crop of cotton is ready to be picked... But, sadly, we didn\u0027t have much to show for it. Boll weevils had attacked our crop... But this time, there were so many that most of the crop was ruined!\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 512.","choices":{"A":"They harvested more cotton than ever","B":"Most of their cotton crop was destroyed","C":"The boll weevils helped the cotton grow better","D":"They were able to sell the boll weevils for money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states \"most of the crop was ruined\" because of the boll weevils.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Harvest time is finally here, and our crop of cotton is ready to be picked... But, sadly, we didn\u0027t have much to show for it. Boll weevils had attacked our crop... But this time, there were so many that most of the crop was ruined!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q049","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 513. A. Because they want to visit Uncle Eugene for a short trip B. Because they hope for better jobs, more money, and more freedom there C. Because Mississippi has too much cotton to harvest D. Because California has no factories or jobs","excerpt":"\"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California... Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 513.","choices":{"A":"Because they want to visit Uncle Eugene for a short trip","B":"Because they hope for better jobs, more money, and more freedom there","C":"Because Mississippi has too much cotton to harvest","D":"Because California has no factories or jobs"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text explains they\u0027re moving for \"a better life\" with higher-paying factory jobs and Mama mentions \"no Jim Crow laws\" meaning more freedom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Tonight, as we sat down to dinner, I got the surprise of my life-we\u0027re moving! Daddy and Mama told us that we\u0027re leaving Mississippi and going to live in Los Angeles, California... Daddy says we\u0027ll be able to live a better life in California, partly because factory workers there make much more money than sharecroppers do here.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w3-ivys-journal-std-q050","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 514. A. Finding a new school with Jim Crow laws B. Missing friends and adjusting to a completely new place C. Having too much money to spend D. Not being able to work in factories","excerpt":"\"Also, Mama says there are no Jim Crow laws in California, so we\u0027ll have so much more freedom. I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again! Also, I have only ever lived in Mississippi; I\u0027ve never even visited another state.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 514.","choices":{"A":"Finding a new school with Jim Crow laws","B":"Missing friends and adjusting to a completely new place","C":"Having too much money to spend","D":"Not being able to work in factories"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ivy expresses worry about leaving friends and never seeing them again, plus uncertainty about a place she\u0027s never visited, showing the emotional challenge of the move.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Also, Mama says there are no Jim Crow laws in California, so we\u0027ll have so much more freedom. I don\u0027t want to leave Eve and my other friends, though, because I may never see them again! Also, I have only ever lived in Mississippi; I\u0027ve never even visited another state.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection","grade":5,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":1,"week":4,"title":"Poetry Collection","author":"Kristine O\u0027Connell George, Drew Lamm, James Hildreth, Karen O\u0027Donnell Taylor, and Marilyn Singer","genre":"Poetry","essential_question":"How can poems show curiosity about the world?","weekly_question":"How do poets use images to describe places, maps, and discovery?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["peering","memorizing","tracing","curious","perspective"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"Poetry Collection. How do poets use images to describe places, maps, and discovery?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q001","read_aloud":": What does the word \"peering\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options: A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":": What does the word \"peering\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q002","read_aloud":": Which of these things is the speaker in the poem learning? Options: A. how to cook B. mountain ranges C. how to drive D. building houses","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges.\"","stem":": Which of these things is the speaker in the poem learning? Options:","choices":{"A":"how to cook","B":"mountain ranges","C":"how to drive","D":"building houses"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states that the speaker is learning mountain ranges.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q003","read_aloud":": What is the main idea of this part of the poem? Options: A. The speaker is learning about the world through a map. B. The speaker is traveling to many mountains. C. The speaker wants to buy a new telescope. D. The speaker is cleaning their room.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges... wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":": What is the main idea of this part of the poem? Options:","choices":{"A":"The speaker is learning about the world through a map.","B":"The speaker is traveling to many mountains.","C":"The speaker wants to buy a new telescope.","D":"The speaker is cleaning their room."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker is studying map features like oceans and rivers to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges... wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q004","read_aloud":": What does the speaker do with the map in this excerpt? Options: A. tears it B. rolls it C. colors it D. hides it","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":": What does the speaker do with the map in this excerpt? Options:","choices":{"A":"tears it","B":"rolls it","C":"colors it","D":"hides it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the speaker is \"rolling it into a tube.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q005","read_aloud":": How does the speaker feel in this part of the poem? Options: A. bored and tired B. excited about the future C. curious to see the world D. angry at their parents","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":": How does the speaker feel in this part of the poem? Options:","choices":{"A":"bored and tired","B":"excited about the future","C":"curious to see the world","D":"angry at their parents"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The speaker is \"wishing\" to see the whole world, which shows their strong curiosity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What does the word \"peering\" most likely mean in this excerpt? A. looking closely at something hard to see B. shouting loudly to get attention C. running quickly across a field D. drawing a picture with crayons","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope...\"","stem":"What does the word \"peering\" most likely mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"looking closely at something hard to see","B":"shouting loudly to get attention","C":"running quickly across a field","D":"drawing a picture with crayons"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows the speaker rolling a map and looking through it like a telescope. \"Peering\" means looking closely at something, which matches option a.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q007","read_aloud":"What is the speaker doing in this excerpt? A. playing a game with friends B. studying a map to learn about the world C. writing a letter to a pen pal D. planning a birthday party","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"What is the speaker doing in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"playing a game with friends","B":"studying a map to learn about the world","C":"writing a letter to a pen pal","D":"planning a birthday party"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt lists actions like \"memorizing,\" \"tracing,\" and \"learning\" about places on a map. This shows the speaker is studying to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q008","read_aloud":"According to this excerpt, how did Magellan navigate his ship? A. by following birds in the sky B. by using the stars to guide his way C. by asking other sailors for directions D. by using a modern GPS device","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"According to this excerpt, how did Magellan navigate his ship?","choices":{"A":"by following birds in the sky","B":"by using the stars to guide his way","C":"by asking other sailors for directions","D":"by using a modern GPS device"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Magellan moved \"via stars\" and \"steered his ship by celestial rays.\" This means he used the stars to guide his journey.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q009","read_aloud":"What does the speaker wish the rolled-up map could be? A. a telescope to see the whole world B. a boat to sail across oceans C. a book to read stories about travel D. a flag to wave at explorers","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope...\"","stem":"What does the speaker wish the rolled-up map could be?","choices":{"A":"a telescope to see the whole world","B":"a boat to sail across oceans","C":"a book to read stories about travel","D":"a flag to wave at explorers"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt directly states the speaker is \"wishing it were a telescope\" to see farther, which matches option a.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q010","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker want to see \"the whole world\"? A. because the speaker wants to become a mapmaker B. because the speaker is curious and wants to learn about distant places C. because the speaker needs to find a lost pet D. because the speaker is writing a school report","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"Why does the speaker want to see \"the whole world\"?","choices":{"A":"because the speaker wants to become a mapmaker","B":"because the speaker is curious and wants to learn about distant places","C":"because the speaker needs to find a lost pet","D":"because the speaker is writing a school report"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker\u0027s wishes show curiosity about the world beyond their street. This desire to see and learn matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"peering\" most likely mean? A. Closing your eyes tightly B. Looking closely at something hard to see C. Running away fast D. Drawing a picture","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope.\"","stem":"What does \"peering\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"Closing your eyes tightly","B":"Looking closely at something hard to see","C":"Running away fast","D":"Drawing a picture"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Peering means looking closely, especially when something is hard to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q012","read_aloud":"What is the speaker doing with the map? A. Drawing on it B. Memorizing and tracing places on it C. Folding it into a small square D. Giving it away","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"What is the speaker doing with the map?","choices":{"A":"Drawing on it","B":"Memorizing and tracing places on it","C":"Folding it into a small square","D":"Giving it away"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker says she is memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, and learning about countries.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What does the speaker wish for? A. A new map B. To see beyond her street C. A bigger house D. To stop studying geography","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope, wishing I could see past my street.\"","stem":"What does the speaker wish for?","choices":{"A":"A new map","B":"To see beyond her street","C":"A bigger house","D":"To stop studying geography"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker wishes she could see past her street and the whole world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope, wishing I could see past my street.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q014","read_aloud":"What does the speaker want to see beneath her feet? A. The ocean B. The whole world C. A map D. A telescope","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"What does the speaker want to see beneath her feet?","choices":{"A":"The ocean","B":"The whole world","C":"A map","D":"A telescope"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker says she wishes she could see the whole world spread beneath her feet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What does the speaker think maps are like? A. Boring pieces of paper B. Keys to secret places C. Difficult puzzles D. School homework","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs . . . Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\"","stem":"What does the speaker think maps are like?","choices":{"A":"Boring pieces of paper","B":"Keys to secret places","C":"Difficult puzzles","D":"School homework"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker says maps are keys to secret places and new worlds.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs . . . Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What does \"peering\" mean in this poem? A. sleeping quietly B. looking closely at something C. running very fast D. singing loudly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\"","stem":"What does \"peering\" mean in this poem?","choices":{"A":"sleeping quietly","B":"looking closely at something","C":"running very fast","D":"singing loudly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker rolls the map into a tube and looks through it like a telescope. \"Peering\" means looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q017","read_aloud":"What does the speaker do with the map? A. tears it into pieces B. rolls it into a tube C. paints it with colors D. folds it into a boat","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\"","stem":"What does the speaker do with the map?","choices":{"A":"tears it into pieces","B":"rolls it into a tube","C":"paints it with colors","D":"folds it into a boat"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the speaker smooths out the map and rolls it into a tube. This is what the speaker does with the map.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q018","read_aloud":"How did Magellan steer his ship? A. by using a map from a store B. by using the stars and celestial rays C. by asking other sailors D. by using a telephone","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"How did Magellan steer his ship?","choices":{"A":"by using a map from a store","B":"by using the stars and celestial rays","C":"by asking other sailors","D":"by using a telephone"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Magellan moved via stars and steered his ship by celestial rays. This means he used the stars to guide his ship.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q019","read_aloud":": What does \"celestial\" most likely describe in this sentence? Options:? A. something from the stars or sky B. something under the ground C. a type of boat D. a kind of map","excerpt":"\"Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":": What does \"celestial\" most likely describe in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"something from the stars or sky","B":"something under the ground","C":"a type of boat","D":"a kind of map"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Celestial relates to the heavens or the sky, which matches the mention of rays (light) from space.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q020","read_aloud":": According to the poem, what are the explorers crossing? Options:? A. mountains only B. deserts only C. rivers, ice, and trees D. cities and buildings","excerpt":"\"Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\"","stem":": According to the poem, what are the explorers crossing? Options:?","choices":{"A":"mountains only","B":"deserts only","C":"rivers, ice, and trees","D":"cities and buildings"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text specifically lists \"rivers, ice, and trees\" as things being crossed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q021","read_aloud":": How did Magellan steer his ship? Options:? A. by a compass B. by the stars C. by looking at the shore D. by following other ships","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":": How did Magellan steer his ship? Options:?","choices":{"A":"by a compass","B":"by the stars","C":"by looking at the shore","D":"by following other ships"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states he steered by \"celestial rays,\" which refers to light from the stars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q022","read_aloud":": What does it mean to \"set their course\"? Options:? A. to decide where to go B. to build a new ship C. to take a rest D. to write a book","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":": What does it mean to \"set their course\"? Options:?","choices":{"A":"to decide where to go","B":"to build a new ship","C":"to take a rest","D":"to write a book"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Setting a course means planning the direction a journey will take.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q023","read_aloud":": What is the \"girth\" of the earth? Options:? A. its distance around B. its top part C. its color D. its hidden treasure","excerpt":"\"Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe\"","stem":": What is the \"girth\" of the earth? Options:?","choices":{"A":"its distance around","B":"its top part","C":"its color","D":"its hidden treasure"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Girth means the distance around the middle of an object; in this case, the planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q024","read_aloud":": Why are maps called \"keys\" in this poem? Options:? A. They are made of metal. B. They open up new ideas and places for us. C. They are used to lock doors. D. They are very small.","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\"","stem":": Why are maps called \"keys\" in this poem? Options:?","choices":{"A":"They are made of metal.","B":"They open up new ideas and places for us.","C":"They are used to lock doors.","D":"They are very small."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Just as a key opens a door, a map \"opens\" a place to our understanding or imagination.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l01-q025","read_aloud":": What does the poet say maps are not just made of? Options:? A. colored dots and lines B. mountains and rivers C. secret places D. dreams and faces","excerpt":"\"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs...\"","stem":": What does the poet say maps are not just made of? Options:?","choices":{"A":"colored dots and lines","B":"mountains and rivers","C":"secret places","D":"dreams and faces"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poem says maps are \"more than tiny lines\" and \"colored dots.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs...\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q001","read_aloud":": What does \"celestial\" most likely describe in this sentence? Options: A. something from the stars or sky B. something under the ground C. a type of boat D. a kind of map","excerpt":"\"Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":": What does \"celestial\" most likely describe in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"something from the stars or sky","B":"something under the ground","C":"a type of boat","D":"a kind of map"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Celestial relates to the heavens or the sky, which matches the mention of rays (light) from space.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q002","read_aloud":": According to the poem, what are the explorers crossing? Options: A. mountains only B. deserts only C. rivers, ice, and trees D. cities and buildings","excerpt":"\"Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\"","stem":": According to the poem, what are the explorers crossing? Options:","choices":{"A":"mountains only","B":"deserts only","C":"rivers, ice, and trees","D":"cities and buildings"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text specifically lists \"rivers, ice, and trees\" as things being crossed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q003","read_aloud":": How did Magellan steer his ship? Options: A. by a compass B. by the stars C. by looking at the shore D. by following other ships","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":": How did Magellan steer his ship? Options:","choices":{"A":"by a compass","B":"by the stars","C":"by looking at the shore","D":"by following other ships"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states he steered by \"celestial rays,\" which refers to light from the stars.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q004","read_aloud":": What does it mean to \"set their course\"? Options: A. to decide where to go B. to build a new ship C. to take a rest D. to write a book","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":": What does it mean to \"set their course\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"to decide where to go","B":"to build a new ship","C":"to take a rest","D":"to write a book"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Setting a course means planning the direction a journey will take.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q005","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"via\" most likely mean? A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"via\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of\" or \"using,\" which matches how he navigated.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Maps are only useful for finding tourist spots B. Maps contain many details but are more than just lines and labels C. Maps are too complicated for most people to understand D. Maps should only show rivers and mountains","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs... More than names and colored dots, rivers, mountains, tourist spots.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Maps are only useful for finding tourist spots","B":"Maps contain many details but are more than just lines and labels","C":"Maps are too complicated for most people to understand","D":"Maps should only show rivers and mountains"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says maps are \"more than\" just lines, dots, and names. This shows maps have deeper value beyond their basic features.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs... More than names and colored dots, rivers, mountains, tourist spots.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What did Columbus do according to this excerpt? A. He stayed in one place and studied maps B. He sailed and discovered new lands and water routes C. He built ships for other explorers to use D. He wrote books about the stars and navigation","excerpt":"\"Columbus sailed on over the edge Discovering lands and waterways.\"","stem":"What did Columbus do according to this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"He stayed in one place and studied maps","B":"He sailed and discovered new lands and water routes","C":"He built ships for other explorers to use","D":"He wrote books about the stars and navigation"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Columbus \"sailed on\" and was \"discovering lands and waterways.\" This describes his actions as an explorer.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Columbus sailed on over the edge Discovering lands and waterways.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q008","read_aloud":"According to this excerpt, what can maps help the speaker do? A. unlock doors to hidden rooms B. discover new places and meet new people C. draw better pictures of landscapes D. remember names of famous explorers","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\"","stem":"According to this excerpt, what can maps help the speaker do?","choices":{"A":"unlock doors to hidden rooms","B":"discover new places and meet new people","C":"draw better pictures of landscapes","D":"remember names of famous explorers"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt calls maps \"keys to secret places\" and \"unknown faces.\" This means maps help the speaker find new places and people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q009","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt tell us about the explorers\u0027 journeys? A. The explorers only traveled in their imagination B. The explorers followed their dreams and traveled across real oceans C. The explorers were afraid to leave their homes D. The explorers only sailed on calm, small lakes","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":"What does this excerpt tell us about the explorers\u0027 journeys?","choices":{"A":"The explorers only traveled in their imagination","B":"The explorers followed their dreams and traveled across real oceans","C":"The explorers were afraid to leave their homes","D":"The explorers only sailed on calm, small lakes"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Traversed their dreams\" and \"voyaging over oceans\" show the explorers pursued their goals and traveled across real seas, matching option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q010","read_aloud":"Which word means almost the same as \"trace\" in this poem? A. Erase B. Follow along C. Ignore D. Break","excerpt":"\"I can trace each graceful line . . . Close my eyes and in my mind I can travel anywhere . . . A map, a dream can take me there!\"","stem":"Which word means almost the same as \"trace\" in this poem?","choices":{"A":"Erase","B":"Follow along","C":"Ignore","D":"Break"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To trace means to follow along the lines of something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I can trace each graceful line . . . Close my eyes and in my mind I can travel anywhere . . . A map, a dream can take me there!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q011","read_aloud":"What are some things on maps mentioned in this stanza? A. Foods and animals B. Names, colored dots, rivers, mountains, tourist spots C. Cars and roads D. Clouds and stars","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs . . . More than names and colored dots, rivers, mountains, tourist spots.\"","stem":"What are some things on maps mentioned in this stanza?","choices":{"A":"Foods and animals","B":"Names, colored dots, rivers, mountains, tourist spots","C":"Cars and roads","D":"Clouds and stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem lists names, colored dots, rivers, mountains, and tourist spots.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs . . . More than names and colored dots, rivers, mountains, tourist spots.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q012","read_aloud":"What does the speaker mean by \"unknown faces\"? A. People she has never met B. Monsters on maps C. Drawings of animals D. Her own reflection","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\"","stem":"What does the speaker mean by \"unknown faces\"?","choices":{"A":"People she has never met","B":"Monsters on maps","C":"Drawings of animals","D":"Her own reflection"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Unknown faces\" suggests people she has not met yet in faraway places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q013","read_aloud":"What animals left tracks in the snow in Antarctica? A. Polar bears B. Penguins C. Seals D. Whales","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden / under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow.\"","stem":"What animals left tracks in the snow in Antarctica?","choices":{"A":"Polar bears","B":"Penguins","C":"Seals","D":"Whales"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says penguins laid tracks in the snow.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden / under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What does the speaker mean by \"crossed and crossed again\"? A. People made X marks on maps B. Animals and explorers have traveled through those places many times C. The places are impossible to reach D. The places are frozen","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed and crossed again.\"","stem":"What does the speaker mean by \"crossed and crossed again\"?","choices":{"A":"People made X marks on maps","B":"Animals and explorers have traveled through those places many times","C":"The places are impossible to reach","D":"The places are frozen"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Crossed\" means traveled across. The speaker says these places have been traveled many times.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed and crossed again.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q015","read_aloud":"What does the speaker do first? A. learns crops and industries B. memorizes oceans C. traces countries D. learns mountain ranges","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges. / I\u0027m memorizing capitals, / tracing countries, / learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"What does the speaker do first?","choices":{"A":"learns crops and industries","B":"memorizes oceans","C":"traces countries","D":"learns mountain ranges"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The first line says the speaker is memorizing oceans. This is the first thing the speaker does in the poem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges. / I\u0027m memorizing capitals, / tracing countries, / learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What did Columbus discover? A. only new lands B. new lands and dreams C. only old maps D. new stars","excerpt":"\"Columbus sailed on over the edge / Discovering lands and dreams.\"","stem":"What did Columbus discover?","choices":{"A":"only new lands","B":"new lands and dreams","C":"only old maps","D":"new stars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Columbus discovered lands and dreams. This means he found new places and also inspired new hopes and dreams.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Columbus sailed on over the edge / Discovering lands and dreams.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q017","read_aloud":"What did the explorers do? A. stayed at home B. traveled across oceans and seas following their dreams C. slept all day D. cooked meals on ships","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":"What did the explorers do?","choices":{"A":"stayed at home","B":"traveled across oceans and seas following their dreams","C":"slept all day","D":"cooked meals on ships"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they traversed their dreams and voyaged over oceans and seas. This means they traveled across the water following their dreams.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q018","read_aloud":"What are \"these lines\" in the poem? A. lines on a road B. lines of latitude and longitude C. lines in a coloring book D. lines of a song","excerpt":"\"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth\"","stem":"What are \"these lines\" in the poem?","choices":{"A":"lines on a road","B":"lines of latitude and longitude","C":"lines in a coloring book","D":"lines of a song"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem is about latitude and longitude. The lines that slide from pole to pole and wrap around the earth are lines of latitude and longitude.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q019","read_aloud":": What does the word \"peering\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":": What does the word \"peering\" most likely mean in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q020","read_aloud":": Which of these things is the speaker in the poem learning? Options:? A. how to cook B. mountain ranges C. how to drive D. building houses","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges.\"","stem":": Which of these things is the speaker in the poem learning? Options:?","choices":{"A":"how to cook","B":"mountain ranges","C":"how to drive","D":"building houses"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states that the speaker is learning mountain ranges.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q021","read_aloud":": What is the main idea of this part of the poem? Options:? A. The speaker is learning about the world through a map. B. The speaker is traveling to many mountains. C. The speaker wants to buy a new telescope. D. The speaker is cleaning their room.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges... wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":": What is the main idea of this part of the poem? Options:?","choices":{"A":"The speaker is learning about the world through a map.","B":"The speaker is traveling to many mountains.","C":"The speaker wants to buy a new telescope.","D":"The speaker is cleaning their room."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker is studying map features like oceans and rivers to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges... wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q022","read_aloud":": What does the speaker do with the map in this excerpt? Options:? A. tears it B. rolls it C. colors it D. hides it","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":": What does the speaker do with the map in this excerpt? Options:?","choices":{"A":"tears it","B":"rolls it","C":"colors it","D":"hides it"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the speaker is \"rolling it into a tube.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q023","read_aloud":": How does the speaker feel in this part of the poem? Options:? A. bored and tired B. excited about the future C. curious to see the world D. angry at their parents","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":": How does the speaker feel in this part of the poem? Options:?","choices":{"A":"bored and tired","B":"excited about the future","C":"curious to see the world","D":"angry at their parents"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The speaker is \"wishing\" to see the whole world, which shows their strong curiosity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q024","read_aloud":": What is the \"girth\" of the earth? Options:? A. its distance around B. its top part C. its color D. its hidden treasure","excerpt":"\"Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe\"","stem":": What is the \"girth\" of the earth? Options:?","choices":{"A":"its distance around","B":"its top part","C":"its color","D":"its hidden treasure"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Girth means the distance around the middle of an object; in this case, the planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l02-q025","read_aloud":": Why are maps called \"keys\" in this poem? Options:? A. They are made of metal. B. They open up new ideas and places for us. C. They are used to lock doors. D. They are very small.","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\"","stem":": Why are maps called \"keys\" in this poem? Options:?","choices":{"A":"They are made of metal.","B":"They open up new ideas and places for us.","C":"They are used to lock doors.","D":"They are very small."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Just as a key opens a door, a map \"opens\" a place to our understanding or imagination.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q001","read_aloud":": What is the \"girth\" of the earth? Options: A. its distance around B. its top part C. its color D. its hidden treasure","excerpt":"\"Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe\"","stem":": What is the \"girth\" of the earth? Options:","choices":{"A":"its distance around","B":"its top part","C":"its color","D":"its hidden treasure"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Girth means the distance around the middle of an object; in this case, the planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q002","read_aloud":": Why are maps called \"keys\" in this poem? Options: A. They are made of metal. B. They open up new ideas and places for us. C. They are used to lock doors. D. They are very small.","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\"","stem":": Why are maps called \"keys\" in this poem? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are made of metal.","B":"They open up new ideas and places for us.","C":"They are used to lock doors.","D":"They are very small."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Just as a key opens a door, a map \"opens\" a place to our understanding or imagination.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q003","read_aloud":": What does the poet say maps are not just made of? Options: A. colored dots and lines B. mountains and rivers C. secret places D. dreams and faces","excerpt":"\"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs...\"","stem":": What does the poet say maps are not just made of? Options:","choices":{"A":"colored dots and lines","B":"mountains and rivers","C":"secret places","D":"dreams and faces"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poem says maps are \"more than tiny lines\" and \"colored dots.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q004","read_aloud":": What are two things maps have according to this excerpt? Options: A. names and colored dots B. keys and faces C. rivers and mountains D. dreams and secrets","excerpt":"\"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs . . . / More than names / and colored dots\"","stem":": What are two things maps have according to this excerpt? Options:","choices":{"A":"names and colored dots","B":"keys and faces","C":"rivers and mountains","D":"dreams and secrets"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text directly mentions \"names\" and \"colored dots\" as features of a map.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs . . . / More than names / and colored dots\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q005","read_aloud":": What does the speaker do to help them \"travel\" in their mind? Options: A. They buy a plane ticket. B. They close their eyes and trace a line. C. They walk outside. D. They talk to a partner.","excerpt":"\"I can trace each / graceful line . . . / Close my eyes / and in my mind / I can travel / anywhere\"","stem":": What does the speaker do to help them \"travel\" in their mind? Options:","choices":{"A":"They buy a plane ticket.","B":"They close their eyes and trace a line.","C":"They walk outside.","D":"They talk to a partner."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker describes tracing a line and closing their eyes to travel anywhere using their imagination.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I can trace each / graceful line . . . / Close my eyes / and in my mind / I can travel / anywhere\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"traversed\" most likely mean? A. traveled through or across something B. dreamed about without taking action C. avoided or stayed away from D. drew pictures of on a map","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"traversed\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"traveled through or across something","B":"dreamed about without taking action","C":"avoided or stayed away from","D":"drew pictures of on a map"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text pairs \"traversed\" with \"set their course\" and \"voyaging,\" which all describe traveling. \"Traversed\" means traveled through or across.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q007","read_aloud":"What is the effect of the speaker\u0027s wishes in this excerpt? A. The wishes make the speaker feel sad about staying home B. The wishes show the speaker\u0027s strong desire to explore and learn C. The wishes prove that maps are not helpful for travel D. The wishes mean the speaker will never leave home","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"What is the effect of the speaker\u0027s wishes in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The wishes make the speaker feel sad about staying home","B":"The wishes show the speaker\u0027s strong desire to explore and learn","C":"The wishes prove that maps are not helpful for travel","D":"The wishes mean the speaker will never leave home"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The repeated wishes to \"see past my street\" and \"see the whole world\" show strong curiosity and a desire to explore, which matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q008","read_aloud":"What can the speaker do by using a map, according to this excerpt? A. The speaker can only learn facts about places B. The speaker can imagine traveling to new places and meeting new people C. The speaker can build real boats to sail across oceans D. The speaker can change the lines on a map to create new countries","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces. I can trace each graceful line... Close my eyes and in my mind I can travel anywhere...\"","stem":"What can the speaker do by using a map, according to this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"The speaker can only learn facts about places","B":"The speaker can imagine traveling to new places and meeting new people","C":"The speaker can build real boats to sail across oceans","D":"The speaker can change the lines on a map to create new countries"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says maps let the speaker \"travel anywhere\" in their mind and discover \"unknown faces.\" This shows maps spark imagination and mental travel.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces. I can trace each graceful line... Close my eyes and in my mind I can travel anywhere...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q009","read_aloud":"What do the \"lines\" in this excerpt refer to? A. telephone wires connecting cities B. lines of latitude and longitude on a globe C. ropes used to tie ships to docks D. paths that birds follow when migrating","excerpt":"\"These lines that slide from pole to pole Wrapping around the watery girth Coordinate all of us on this globe\"","stem":"What do the \"lines\" in this excerpt refer to?","choices":{"A":"telephone wires connecting cities","B":"lines of latitude and longitude on a globe","C":"ropes used to tie ships to docks","D":"paths that birds follow when migrating"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt mentions lines sliding \"from pole to pole\" and wrapping around Earth\u0027s \"girth.\" This describes latitude and longitude lines on a globe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These lines that slide from pole to pole Wrapping around the watery girth Coordinate all of us on this globe\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q010","read_aloud":"What does this metaphor suggest about Earth? A. Earth is only a place to live, not to explore B. Earth is like a ship that carries us all on a journey together C. Earth is too big for people to understand or care for D. Earth should be divided into separate countries with no connection","excerpt":"\"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"What does this metaphor suggest about Earth?","choices":{"A":"Earth is only a place to live, not to explore","B":"Earth is like a ship that carries us all on a journey together","C":"Earth is too big for people to understand or care for","D":"Earth should be divided into separate countries with no connection"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calling Earth \"our ship\" suggests we are all traveling together on this planet. This metaphor emphasizes shared responsibility and connection.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"intersecting\" mean in this line? A. Crossing or overlapping B. Running away C. Singing loudly D. Hiding","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs.\"","stem":"What does \"intersecting\" mean in this line?","choices":{"A":"Crossing or overlapping","B":"Running away","C":"Singing loudly","D":"Hiding"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Intersecting lines are lines that cross each other.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q012","read_aloud":"Who does the speaker say has crossed these places? A. Only famous explorers B. Adventurers we will never know C. Only birds D. Only penguins","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen.\"","stem":"Who does the speaker say has crossed these places?","choices":{"A":"Only famous explorers","B":"Adventurers we will never know","C":"Only birds","D":"Only penguins"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says adventurers we will never know and explorers who will never tell us.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of these lines? A. Some places on Earth have never been seen. B. Every place on Earth has been visited by some kind of creature. C. Only humans explore new places. D. Antarctica is the only undiscovered place.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered … all have been crossed and crossed again by wings whirring or silent feet furred or scaled hoofed or bare.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of these lines?","choices":{"A":"Some places on Earth have never been seen.","B":"Every place on Earth has been visited by some kind of creature.","C":"Only humans explore new places.","D":"Antarctica is the only undiscovered place."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says all places have been crossed by animals and explorers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered … all have been crossed and crossed again by wings whirring or silent feet furred or scaled hoofed or bare.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q014","read_aloud":"What will these explorers never tell us? A. Their names B. What wonders they have seen C. How old they are D. Where they live","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen.\"","stem":"What will these explorers never tell us?","choices":{"A":"Their names","B":"What wonders they have seen","C":"How old they are","D":"Where they live"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says they will never tell us what wonders they have seen.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q015","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker wish the map were a telescope? A. To see stars B. To see faraway places as if they were right there C. To read small print D. To watch birds","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"Why does the speaker wish the map were a telescope?","choices":{"A":"To see stars","B":"To see faraway places as if they were right there","C":"To read small print","D":"To watch birds"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A telescope lets you see distant things up close, so the speaker could see the whole world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What does \"traversed\" mean? A. traveled through; moved across B. stopped moving C. slept peacefully D. ate quickly","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":"What does \"traversed\" mean?","choices":{"A":"traveled through; moved across","B":"stopped moving","C":"slept peacefully","D":"ate quickly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says they traversed their dreams while voyaging over oceans. \"Traversed\" means traveled through or moved across.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q017","read_aloud":"What does the poet compare maps to? A. doors B. keys C. windows D. locks","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\"","stem":"What does the poet compare maps to?","choices":{"A":"doors","B":"keys","C":"windows","D":"locks"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says \"Maps are keys to secret places.\" The poet compares maps to keys that can unlock new worlds and places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q018","read_aloud":"How can the speaker travel anywhere? A. by taking a bus B. by using their imagination and a map C. by running very fast D. by flying on a plane","excerpt":"\"I can trace each / graceful line ... / Close my eyes / and in my mind / I can travel / anywhere ...\"","stem":"How can the speaker travel anywhere?","choices":{"A":"by taking a bus","B":"by using their imagination and a map","C":"by running very fast","D":"by flying on a plane"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker traces lines on a map, closes their eyes, and uses their mind to travel. This shows the speaker uses imagination and a map to travel anywhere.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I can trace each / graceful line ... / Close my eyes / and in my mind / I can travel / anywhere ...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q019","read_aloud":"What does the poet mean by this line? A. Maps and dreams can help you imagine traveling to new places. B. You need a real map to sleep. C. Dreams are not important. D. Maps are too heavy to carry.","excerpt":"\"A map, a dream / can take me there!\"","stem":"What does the poet mean by this line?","choices":{"A":"Maps and dreams can help you imagine traveling to new places.","B":"You need a real map to sleep.","C":"Dreams are not important.","D":"Maps are too heavy to carry."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poet says a map and a dream can take her anywhere. This means using a map and imagination together can help you explore new places in your mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A map, a dream / can take me there!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of,\" showing the stars were his navigation tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Map lines cross over each other like lace patterns. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping, which fits this image.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l03-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. playing a game with friends B. studying a map to learn about the world C. writing a letter to a pen pal D. planning a birthday party","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"playing a game with friends","B":"studying a map to learn about the world","C":"writing a letter to a pen pal","D":"planning a birthday party"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker lists actions like \"memorizing\" and \"tracing\" places on a map. This shows they are studying to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q001","read_aloud":": If two roads are \"intersecting,\" what are they doing? Options: A. running away from each other B. crossing or overlapping C. staying in one place D. being painted","excerpt":"\"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs . . .\"","stem":": If two roads are \"intersecting,\" what are they doing? Options:","choices":{"A":"running away from each other","B":"crossing or overlapping","C":"staying in one place","D":"being painted"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To intersect means to cross over or meet at a point.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs . . .\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q002","read_aloud":": What can you infer about the world from this poem? Options: A. Humans have visited every single spot. B. There are places that have been traveled even if humans haven\u0027t been there. C. Deserts are easy to cross. D. The world is very small.","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed / and crossed again\"","stem":": What can you infer about the world from this poem? Options:","choices":{"A":"Humans have visited every single spot.","B":"There are places that have been traveled even if humans haven\u0027t been there.","C":"Deserts are easy to cross.","D":"The world is very small."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says places where \"none of us\" have been are still \"crossed again,\" suggesting other travelers (like animals) are there.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed / and crossed again\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q003","read_aloud":": What is the main point of this poem? Options: A. Penguins like to travel in the snow. B. Explorers are always humans. C. Nature is always explored, even without humans. D. Antarctica is the best place to live.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica... penguins already laid shambling tracks\"","stem":": What is the main point of this poem? Options:","choices":{"A":"Penguins like to travel in the snow.","B":"Explorers are always humans.","C":"Nature is always explored, even without humans.","D":"Antarctica is the best place to live."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem argues that the earth is constantly being traveled by animals, so \"undiscovered\" is just a human idea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica... penguins already laid shambling tracks\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q004","read_aloud":": How would you describe the \"adventurers\" in this poem? Options: A. Famous people in history books. B. Animals or creatures that explore silently. C. Only people who travel by plane. D. People who are lost.","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\"","stem":": How would you describe the \"adventurers\" in this poem? Options:","choices":{"A":"Famous people in history books.","B":"Animals or creatures that explore silently.","C":"Only people who travel by plane.","D":"People who are lost."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem describes them as having feet that are \"furred or scaled,\" which fits the description of animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q005","read_aloud":": Why does the poet mention the \"hottest desert\" and \"deepest jungle\"? Options: A. To show that even hard-to-reach places have been traveled. B. To tell us where to go on vacation. C. To explain how hot the weather is. D. To show that maps are always wrong.","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been\"","stem":": Why does the poet mention the \"hottest desert\" and \"deepest jungle\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"To show that even hard-to-reach places have been traveled.","B":"To tell us where to go on vacation.","C":"To explain how hot the weather is.","D":"To show that maps are always wrong."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poet is emphasizing that no matter how difficult a place is to reach, it has already been explored.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"girth\" most likely mean? A. the distance around something; the circumference B. the height of a mountain from base to peak C. the speed at which a ship travels across water D. the number of people living in one place","excerpt":"\"These lines that slide from pole to pole Wrapping around the watery girth Coordinate all of us on this globe\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"girth\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"the distance around something; the circumference","B":"the height of a mountain from base to peak","C":"the speed at which a ship travels across water","D":"the number of people living in one place"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes lines \"wrapping around\" Earth\u0027s \"watery girth.\" Girth means the distance around something, which fits how lines circle the globe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These lines that slide from pole to pole Wrapping around the watery girth Coordinate all of us on this globe\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q007","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Humans are the first to explore every part of Earth B. Animals have already explored places before humans arrived C. Antarctica is the only place that is truly undiscovered D. Mountains under ice cannot be explored by anyone","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Humans are the first to explore every part of Earth","B":"Animals have already explored places before humans arrived","C":"Antarctica is the only place that is truly undiscovered","D":"Mountains under ice cannot be explored by anyone"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states that even in Antarctica, \"penguins already laid shambling tracks\" before humans came. This shows animals explored first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q008","read_aloud":"What pattern does this excerpt show about exploration? A. Only humans with special equipment can explore difficult places B. Many creatures, not just humans, have traveled through extreme environments C. Deserts and jungles are too dangerous for any living thing to cross D. Exploration only happens in places where people already live","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert the deepest jungle where none of us have ever been all have been crossed and crossed again by wings whirring or silent feet furred or scaled hoofed or bare\"","stem":"What pattern does this excerpt show about exploration?","choices":{"A":"Only humans with special equipment can explore difficult places","B":"Many creatures, not just humans, have traveled through extreme environments","C":"Deserts and jungles are too dangerous for any living thing to cross","D":"Exploration only happens in places where people already live"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt lists \"wings,\" \"feet furred or scaled,\" and \"hoofed or bare\" travelers crossing harsh places. This shows many creatures explore, not just humans.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert the deepest jungle where none of us have ever been all have been crossed and crossed again by wings whirring or silent feet furred or scaled hoofed or bare\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q009","read_aloud":"If you used a map like the speaker does, how could you \"travel\" without leaving your room? A. By memorizing every fact on the map B. By using your imagination to picture places and adventures the map shows C. By drawing new lines on the map to create fake countries D. By folding the map into a boat and pretending to sail","excerpt":"\"I can trace each graceful line... Close my eyes and in my mind I can travel anywhere... A map, a dream can take me there!\"","stem":"If you used a map like the speaker does, how could you \"travel\" without leaving your room?","choices":{"A":"By memorizing every fact on the map","B":"By using your imagination to picture places and adventures the map shows","C":"By drawing new lines on the map to create fake countries","D":"By folding the map into a boat and pretending to sail"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker says closing their eyes and using a map lets them \"travel anywhere\" in their mind. This shows imagination can create mental journeys.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I can trace each graceful line... Close my eyes and in my mind I can travel anywhere... A map, a dream can take me there!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q010","read_aloud":"How does the phrase \"invisible designs\" help you understand the explorers\u0027 impact? A. It shows explorers only made maps that no one could see B. It suggests explorers\u0027 journeys left lasting but not always visible marks on the world C. It proves explorers never actually traveled, only dreamed D. It means explorers tried to hide their routes from others","excerpt":"\"Etching earth with invisible designs Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\"","stem":"How does the phrase \"invisible designs\" help you understand the explorers\u0027 impact?","choices":{"A":"It shows explorers only made maps that no one could see","B":"It suggests explorers\u0027 journeys left lasting but not always visible marks on the world","C":"It proves explorers never actually traveled, only dreamed","D":"It means explorers tried to hide their routes from others"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Invisible designs\" suggests explorers\u0027 paths and influences shaped the world in ways that aren\u0027t always obvious, like cultural connections or knowledge shared.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Etching earth with invisible designs Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q011","read_aloud":"Excerpt from poem: \"all have been crossed and crossed again by wings whirring or silent feet furred or scaled hoofed or bare. If a place has been \"traversed,\" what has happened? A. It has been hidden. B. It has been traveled across. C. It has been destroyed. D. It has been drawn on a map.","excerpt":"The preview vocabulary list includes \"traversed.\"","stem":"Excerpt from poem: \"all have been crossed and crossed again by wings whirring or silent feet furred or scaled hoofed or bare. If a place has been \"traversed,\" what has happened?","choices":{"A":"It has been hidden.","B":"It has been traveled across.","C":"It has been destroyed.","D":"It has been drawn on a map."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To traverse means to travel across. The poem says places have been \"crossed,\" which means traversed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The preview vocabulary list includes \"traversed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q012","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"Learning the World\" and \"A Map and a Dream. How are the speakers in both poems similar? A. Both are afraid of traveling. B. Both use maps to imagine or learn about faraway places. C. Both have traveled to many countries. D. Both dislike geography.","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"Learning the World\" and \"A Map and a Dream. How are the speakers in both poems similar?","choices":{"A":"Both are afraid of traveling.","B":"Both use maps to imagine or learn about faraway places.","C":"Both have traveled to many countries.","D":"Both dislike geography."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In \"Learning the World,\" the speaker memorizes a map. In \"A Map and a Dream,\" the speaker says a map can take her anywhere.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q013","read_aloud":"What happens when the speaker closes her eyes? A. She falls asleep. B. She can travel anywhere in her mind. C. She forgets the map. D. She sees only darkness.","excerpt":"\"I can trace each graceful line . . . Close my eyes and in my mind I can travel anywhere.\"","stem":"What happens when the speaker closes her eyes?","choices":{"A":"She falls asleep.","B":"She can travel anywhere in her mind.","C":"She forgets the map.","D":"She sees only darkness."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says when she closes her eyes, she can travel anywhere in her mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I can trace each graceful line . . . Close my eyes and in my mind I can travel anywhere.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q014","read_aloud":"If you wanted to memorize a map like the speaker, what would you do first? A. Fold the map and put it away B. Look closely at the names of oceans, rivers, and mountains C. Draw a new map from memory D. Throw the map in the trash","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges.\"","stem":"If you wanted to memorize a map like the speaker, what would you do first?","choices":{"A":"Fold the map and put it away","B":"Look closely at the names of oceans, rivers, and mountains","C":"Draw a new map from memory","D":"Throw the map in the trash"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To memorize a map, you first need to look closely at its features.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q015","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker call maps \"keys\"? A. Maps are made of metal. B. Maps unlock the ability to imagine or find new places. C. Maps have locks on them. D. Maps are difficult to open.","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\"","stem":"Why does the speaker call maps \"keys\"?","choices":{"A":"Maps are made of metal.","B":"Maps unlock the ability to imagine or find new places.","C":"Maps have locks on them.","D":"Maps are difficult to open."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A key opens something. Maps \"open up\" the idea of new places to explore.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q016","read_aloud":"What does \"girth\" mean in this poem? A. the distance around something; circumference B. the height of a mountain C. the speed of a ship D. the color of the ocean","excerpt":"\"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth\"","stem":"What does \"girth\" mean in this poem?","choices":{"A":"the distance around something; circumference","B":"the height of a mountain","C":"the speed of a ship","D":"the color of the ocean"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says the lines wrap around the watery girth of the earth. \"Girth\" means the distance around something, like the circumference of the earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q017","read_aloud":"Why did Magellan use the stars to steer his ship? A. Because he liked looking at pretty lights. B. Because the stars helped him find his way across the ocean. C. Because he was afraid of the dark. D. Because the stars told him stories.","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays. / Columbus sailed on over the edge / Discovering lands and dreams.\"","stem":"Why did Magellan use the stars to steer his ship?","choices":{"A":"Because he liked looking at pretty lights.","B":"Because the stars helped him find his way across the ocean.","C":"Because he was afraid of the dark.","D":"Because the stars told him stories."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Sailors used stars to navigate across oceans. The stars helped them know which direction to go. This is why Magellan steered by celestial rays.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays. / Columbus sailed on over the edge / Discovering lands and dreams.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q018","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the speaker\u0027s life? A. The speaker lives in a very busy city. B. The speaker wants to explore beyond their small, everyday world. C. The speaker has already traveled everywhere. D. The speaker does not like maps.","excerpt":"\"wishing it were a telescope, / wishing I could see past my street\"","stem":"What can you infer about the speaker\u0027s life?","choices":{"A":"The speaker lives in a very busy city.","B":"The speaker wants to explore beyond their small, everyday world.","C":"The speaker has already traveled everywhere.","D":"The speaker does not like maps."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker wishes to see past their street. This shows they want to explore beyond their small, everyday world and see more of the earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing it were a telescope, / wishing I could see past my street\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q019","read_aloud":"What does \"invisible designs\" mean in this poem? A. lines that you can see with your eyes B. lines of latitude and longitude that you cannot see but can imagine C. pictures painted on the ground D. designs on a ship","excerpt":"\"Etching earth with invisible designs / Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\"","stem":"What does \"invisible designs\" mean in this poem?","choices":{"A":"lines that you can see with your eyes","B":"lines of latitude and longitude that you cannot see but can imagine","C":"pictures painted on the ground","D":"designs on a ship"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Latitude and longitude lines are not real lines you can see on the ground. They are invisible designs that people imagine to help locate places on earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Etching earth with invisible designs / Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Why does the poet call the earth \"our ship\"? A. Because the earth is made of wood. B. Because the earth carries us through space like a ship carries people through water. C. Because the earth is very small. D. Because the earth has sails.","excerpt":"\"Coordinate all of us on this globe / Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"Why does the poet call the earth \"our ship\"?","choices":{"A":"Because the earth is made of wood.","B":"Because the earth carries us through space like a ship carries people through water.","C":"Because the earth is very small.","D":"Because the earth has sails."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet uses a metaphor. The earth is compared to a ship because it carries all of us through space, just like a ship carries people across the ocean.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Coordinate all of us on this globe / Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of,\" showing the stars were his navigation tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l04-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Map lines cross over each other like lace patterns. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping, which fits this image.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q001","read_aloud":": If the explorers \"traversed\" their dreams, what did they do? Options: A. They traveled through them. B. They gave up on them. C. They forgot them. D. They wrote them down.","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":": If the explorers \"traversed\" their dreams, what did they do? Options:","choices":{"A":"They traveled through them.","B":"They gave up on them.","C":"They forgot them.","D":"They wrote them down."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Traversed means to travel across or through an area or path.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q002","read_aloud":": Why does the speaker wish the map were a telescope? Options: A. To see if it is broken. B. To see past their street and further into the world. C. To make the map bigger. D. To use it to find lost keys.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map... peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope\"","stem":": Why does the speaker wish the map were a telescope? Options:","choices":{"A":"To see if it is broken.","B":"To see past their street and further into the world.","C":"To make the map bigger.","D":"To use it to find lost keys."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they wish it were a telescope so they could \"see past my street\" and see the \"whole world.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map... peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q003","read_aloud":": What does the speaker do before smoothing out the map? Options: A. They travel to the mountains. B. They memorize oceans and learn mountain ranges. C. They buy a telescope. D. They talk to a partner.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges... I\u0027m smoothing out this map\"","stem":": What does the speaker do before smoothing out the map? Options:","choices":{"A":"They travel to the mountains.","B":"They memorize oceans and learn mountain ranges.","C":"They buy a telescope.","D":"They talk to a partner."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem lists these learning activities at the beginning, before the speaker starts smoothing out the map.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges... I\u0027m smoothing out this map\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q004","read_aloud":": If you were the speaker, how would you use a map to \"see the whole world\"? Options: A. By drawing on it with markers. B. By imagining you are standing above the map looking down. C. By throwing the map away. D. By folding it up and putting it in a pocket.","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see / the whole world / spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":": If you were the speaker, how would you use a map to \"see the whole world\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"By drawing on it with markers.","B":"By imagining you are standing above the map looking down.","C":"By throwing the map away.","D":"By folding it up and putting it in a pocket."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker imagines the map spreading beneath their feet, which is an act of imagination.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see / the whole world / spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q005","read_aloud":": Why is the speaker doing these things? Options: A. They have a test at school. B. They want to learn about the world beyond their street. C. They want to be a mountain climber. D. They are bored with their toys.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges.\"","stem":": Why is the speaker doing these things? Options:","choices":{"A":"They have a test at school.","B":"They want to learn about the world beyond their street.","C":"They want to be a mountain climber.","D":"They are bored with their toys."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem shows a desire for travel and discovery, suggesting a motivation to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"intersecting\" most likely mean? A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"intersecting\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text describes map lines as \"intersecting,\" like lace patterns that cross over each other. This matches the meaning of crossing or overlapping.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the speaker\u0027s feelings toward maps? A. The speaker finds maps boring and useless B. The speaker sees maps as tools for imagination and discovery C. The speaker wants to become a professional mapmaker D. The speaker believes maps are only for school assignments","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope, wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"What can you infer about the speaker\u0027s feelings toward maps?","choices":{"A":"The speaker finds maps boring and useless","B":"The speaker sees maps as tools for imagination and discovery","C":"The speaker wants to become a professional mapmaker","D":"The speaker believes maps are only for school assignments"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker\u0027s actions and wishes show excitement about using a map to \"see the whole world.\" This suggests maps spark imagination and curiosity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope, wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q008","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt suggest about some explorers? A. All explorers write books about their journeys B. Some explorers\u0027 stories and discoveries are lost to history C. Only famous explorers are worth remembering D. Modern explorers are less brave than ancient ones","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen\"","stem":"What does this excerpt suggest about some explorers?","choices":{"A":"All explorers write books about their journeys","B":"Some explorers\u0027 stories and discoveries are lost to history","C":"Only famous explorers are worth remembering","D":"Modern explorers are less brave than ancient ones"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt mentions \"adventurers we will never know\" who \"will never tell us\" their wonders. This suggests many explorers\u0027 stories were never recorded.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q009","read_aloud":"How could you use this idea about maps in your own life? A. By ignoring maps and only using GPS on a phone B. By using maps to imagine adventures and learn about new cultures and places C. By collecting maps but never looking at them D. By drawing maps only of places you have already visited","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\"","stem":"How could you use this idea about maps in your own life?","choices":{"A":"By ignoring maps and only using GPS on a phone","B":"By using maps to imagine adventures and learn about new cultures and places","C":"By collecting maps but never looking at them","D":"By drawing maps only of places you have already visited"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"If maps are \"keys to secret places,\" you can use them to spark curiosity, imagine journeys, and learn about people and places you haven\u0027t met or seen.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q010","read_aloud":"How does repeating \"our\" three times strengthen the poem\u0027s message? A. It shows the poet is unsure who owns Earth B. It emphasizes that everyone shares responsibility for caring for our planet C. It suggests Earth belongs only to sailors and explorers D. It means Earth is too big for any one person to understand","excerpt":"\"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"How does repeating \"our\" three times strengthen the poem\u0027s message?","choices":{"A":"It shows the poet is unsure who owns Earth","B":"It emphasizes that everyone shares responsibility for caring for our planet","C":"It suggests Earth belongs only to sailors and explorers","D":"It means Earth is too big for any one person to understand"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Repeating \"our\" highlights shared ownership and connection. This reinforces the idea that we all share Earth and should care for it together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What is a synonym for \"peering\"? A. Shouting B. Looking carefully C. Walking away D. Sleeping","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end.\"","stem":"What is a synonym for \"peering\"?","choices":{"A":"Shouting","B":"Looking carefully","C":"Walking away","D":"Sleeping"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Peering means looking carefully, especially at something small or far.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q012","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker repeat the word \"wishing\"? A. To show she is happy with what she has B. To emphasize her strong desire to see the world C. To make the poem shorter D. To confuse the reader","excerpt":"\"wishing it were a telescope, wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"Why does the speaker repeat the word \"wishing\"?","choices":{"A":"To show she is happy with what she has","B":"To emphasize her strong desire to see the world","C":"To make the poem shorter","D":"To confuse the reader"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Repetition of \"wishing\" shows how much she wants to see faraway places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing it were a telescope, wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q013","read_aloud":"What does \"shambling tracks\" describe? A. Fast, straight lines B. Wobbly, clumsy footprints C. Deep holes in the snow D. Airplane trails","excerpt":"\"penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there.\"","stem":"What does \"shambling tracks\" describe?","choices":{"A":"Fast, straight lines","B":"Wobbly, clumsy footprints","C":"Deep holes in the snow","D":"Airplane trails"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Shambling\" means clumsy or unsteady, like a penguin\u0027s walk.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q014","read_aloud":"What does this line suggest about Antarctica? A. No living thing has ever been there. B. Even in a frozen, remote place, animals have already explored it. C. Penguins built the mountains. D. Humans were the first to see Antarctica.","excerpt":"\"Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there.\"","stem":"What does this line suggest about Antarctica?","choices":{"A":"No living thing has ever been there.","B":"Even in a frozen, remote place, animals have already explored it.","C":"Penguins built the mountains.","D":"Humans were the first to see Antarctica."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says penguins left tracks before humans traveled there.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q015","read_aloud":"If you wanted to find a truly undiscovered place on Earth based on this poem, what would you learn? A. It is easy to find undiscovered places. B. Almost every place has already been visited by some creature. C. Only deserts are undiscovered. D. Jungles are never visited.","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed and crossed again.\"","stem":"If you wanted to find a truly undiscovered place on Earth based on this poem, what would you learn?","choices":{"A":"It is easy to find undiscovered places.","B":"Almost every place has already been visited by some creature.","C":"Only deserts are undiscovered.","D":"Jungles are never visited."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says all places have been crossed and crossed again by animals or explorers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed and crossed again.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What does \"intersecting\" mean? A. crossing or overlapping B. running away C. standing still D. disappearing","excerpt":"\"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs ...\"","stem":"What does \"intersecting\" mean?","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping","B":"running away","C":"standing still","D":"disappearing"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says lines are intersecting like lace designs. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping each other, like lines on a map.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs ...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q017","read_aloud":"Why is no place on earth ever undiscovered? A. Because penguins and other animals have already been there. B. Because humans have built houses everywhere. C. Because the earth is very small. D. Because no one likes to explore.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice / penguins already laid shambling tracks / in the snow / before we traveled there\"","stem":"Why is no place on earth ever undiscovered?","choices":{"A":"Because penguins and other animals have already been there.","B":"Because humans have built houses everywhere.","C":"Because the earth is very small.","D":"Because no one likes to explore."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poem says even in Antarctica, penguins have already laid tracks in the snow. Animals have explored places before humans, so no place is truly undiscovered.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice / penguins already laid shambling tracks / in the snow / before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q018","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the \"adventurers\" the poet describes? A. They are only human explorers. B. They are animals that have crossed these places before humans. C. They are imaginary creatures. D. They are only birds.","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed / and crossed again / by wings whirring or silent / feet furred or scaled / hoofed or bare\"","stem":"What can you infer about the \"adventurers\" the poet describes?","choices":{"A":"They are only human explorers.","B":"They are animals that have crossed these places before humans.","C":"They are imaginary creatures.","D":"They are only birds."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet describes wings, furred feet, scaled feet, hooves, and bare feet. These are animals, not humans. The poet means animals have explored these places before us.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed / and crossed again / by wings whirring or silent / feet furred or scaled / hoofed or bare\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q019","read_aloud":"Who are these \"adventurers we will never know\"? A. famous human explorers like Magellan B. animals that have explored places but cannot tell us what they saw C. people from the future D. characters in a book","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\"","stem":"Who are these \"adventurers we will never know\"?","choices":{"A":"famous human explorers like Magellan","B":"animals that have explored places but cannot tell us what they saw","C":"people from the future","D":"characters in a book"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet says these adventurers will never tell us what they saw. Animals cannot speak or write, so they are explorers we will never truly know.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q020","read_aloud":"What does the word \"shambling\" suggest about the penguins? A. They move slowly and awkwardly. B. They fly very fast. C. They sleep all day. D. They sing beautifully.","excerpt":"\"Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice / penguins already laid shambling tracks / in the snow / before we traveled there\"","stem":"What does the word \"shambling\" suggest about the penguins?","choices":{"A":"They move slowly and awkwardly.","B":"They fly very fast.","C":"They sleep all day.","D":"They sing beautifully."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Shambling\" means moving in a slow, awkward, or shuffling way. Penguins waddle when they walk, so this word describes their slow, awkward movement across the snow.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice / penguins already laid shambling tracks / in the snow / before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of,\" showing the stars were his navigation tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l05-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Map lines cross over each other like lace patterns. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping, which fits this image.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q001","read_aloud":": What is the meaning of the word \"undiscovered\"? Options: A. something that has been seen or found before B. something that nobody knows about C. something that is very cold D. something that is very old","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered\"","stem":": What is the meaning of the word \"undiscovered\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"something that has been seen or found before","B":"something that nobody knows about","C":"something that is very cold","D":"something that is very old"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Undiscovered means that something has not yet been seen or explored by someone.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q002","read_aloud":": Who does the poet think has \"crossed\" these places? Options: A. Only famous map makers. B. Animals like birds, and other wild creatures. C. People with fast cars. D. Only people who have been to school.","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed / and crossed again\"","stem":": Who does the poet think has \"crossed\" these places? Options:","choices":{"A":"Only famous map makers.","B":"Animals like birds, and other wild creatures.","C":"People with fast cars.","D":"Only people who have been to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem mentions \"wings whirring\" and \"feet furred or scaled,\" which refers to animal explorers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed / and crossed again\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q003","read_aloud":": How is the explorer in this poem different from a human explorer? Options: A. The explorer in the poem is an animal. B. The explorer has a map. C. The explorer uses a boat. D. The explorer can talk.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered... by wings whirring or silent / feet furred or scaled\"","stem":": How is the explorer in this poem different from a human explorer? Options:","choices":{"A":"The explorer in the poem is an animal.","B":"The explorer has a map.","C":"The explorer uses a boat.","D":"The explorer can talk."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poem describes physical traits like \"wings\" and \"furred\" feet, which belong to animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered... by wings whirring or silent / feet furred or scaled\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q004","read_aloud":": What does the poet mean by saying these places have been \"crossed\"? Options: A. Someone walked or flew over them. B. Someone drew an X on them. C. Someone got angry at them. D. Someone sold them.","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed\"","stem":": What does the poet mean by saying these places have been \"crossed\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Someone walked or flew over them.","B":"Someone drew an X on them.","C":"Someone got angry at them.","D":"Someone sold them."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To cross a place means to travel across the land or water.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q005","read_aloud":": Why does the poet say these explorers \"will never tell us\" about what they see? Options: A. Because they are animals and cannot talk. B. Because they are too shy. C. Because they don\u0027t have enough time. D. Because they are lost.","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\"","stem":": Why does the poet say these explorers \"will never tell us\" about what they see? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they are animals and cannot talk.","B":"Because they are too shy.","C":"Because they don\u0027t have enough time.","D":"Because they are lost."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Animals cannot communicate their experiences to humans in words, which is the poet\u0027s point.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"peering\" help show the speaker\u0027s attitude? A. It shows the speaker is careless and not paying attention B. It shows the speaker is curious and trying hard to see farther C. It shows the speaker is angry about being stuck at home D. It shows the speaker is only pretending to be interested","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope...\"","stem":"How does the word \"peering\" help show the speaker\u0027s attitude?","choices":{"A":"It shows the speaker is careless and not paying attention","B":"It shows the speaker is curious and trying hard to see farther","C":"It shows the speaker is angry about being stuck at home","D":"It shows the speaker is only pretending to be interested"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Peering\" means looking closely with effort. This word choice shows the speaker\u0027s active curiosity and desire to see beyond their immediate view.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q007","read_aloud":"What is the effect of comparing Earth to a ship in this metaphor? A. It suggests Earth is dangerous and should be avoided B. It suggests we are all traveling together and must work as a crew C. It suggests Earth is small and unimportant in the universe D. It suggests only explorers should care about Earth\u0027s future","excerpt":"\"Coordinate all of us on this globe Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"What is the effect of comparing Earth to a ship in this metaphor?","choices":{"A":"It suggests Earth is dangerous and should be avoided","B":"It suggests we are all traveling together and must work as a crew","C":"It suggests Earth is small and unimportant in the universe","D":"It suggests only explorers should care about Earth\u0027s future"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A ship requires teamwork to sail safely. Comparing Earth to a ship suggests we all share the journey and must cooperate to care for our planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Coordinate all of us on this globe Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q008","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"Learning the World\": \"wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet. Excerpt from \"Early Explorers\": \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered How do these two excerpts connect to the theme of exploration? A. They both say exploration is impossible for regular people B. They both show that curiosity and imagination are part of exploring, whether in mind or in person C. They both argue that only famous explorers matter in history D. They both suggest maps are outdated and not useful today","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"Learning the World\": \"wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet. Excerpt from \"Early Explorers\": \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered How do these two excerpts connect to the theme of exploration?","choices":{"A":"They both say exploration is impossible for regular people","B":"They both show that curiosity and imagination are part of exploring, whether in mind or in person","C":"They both argue that only famous explorers matter in history","D":"They both suggest maps are outdated and not useful today"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The first excerpt shows mental exploration through imagination; the second shows physical exploration by many creatures. Together, they show exploration happens in many ways.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q009","read_aloud":"If you discovered a new place, what might you do to share your experience, based on this poem\u0027s message? A. Keep the discovery secret so no one else finds it B. Record your journey through writing, art, or storytelling so others can learn from it C. Only tell your closest friends and family about it D. Wait for someone else to discover it first before sharing","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen\"","stem":"If you discovered a new place, what might you do to share your experience, based on this poem\u0027s message?","choices":{"A":"Keep the discovery secret so no one else finds it","B":"Record your journey through writing, art, or storytelling so others can learn from it","C":"Only tell your closest friends and family about it","D":"Wait for someone else to discover it first before sharing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem notes that some explorers\u0027 wonders are never shared. To avoid losing discoveries, you could record and share your experiences so others benefit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q010","read_aloud":"How does the poet\u0027s word choice help you picture the variety of explorers? A. By using only scientific terms that are hard to understand B. By listing different types of feet and movement to show many creatures explore in different ways C. By focusing only on human explorers with maps and compasses D. By describing explorers as all looking and moving the same way","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert the deepest jungle where none of us have ever been all have been crossed and crossed again by wings whirring or silent feet furred or scaled hoofed or bare\"","stem":"How does the poet\u0027s word choice help you picture the variety of explorers?","choices":{"A":"By using only scientific terms that are hard to understand","B":"By listing different types of feet and movement to show many creatures explore in different ways","C":"By focusing only on human explorers with maps and compasses","D":"By describing explorers as all looking and moving the same way"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Words like \"wings whirring,\" \"feet furred or scaled,\" and \"hoofed or bare\" create vivid images of birds, mammals, and other animals traveling, showing exploration is not just human.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert the deepest jungle where none of us have ever been all have been crossed and crossed again by wings whirring or silent feet furred or scaled hoofed or bare\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q011","read_aloud":"Which of these shows intersecting lines? A. Two parallel lines that never meet B. A plus sign (+) where lines cross C. A single straight line D. A circle with no lines","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs.\"","stem":"Which of these shows intersecting lines?","choices":{"A":"Two parallel lines that never meet","B":"A plus sign (+) where lines cross","C":"A single straight line","D":"A circle with no lines"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Intersecting lines cross each other, like the lines in a plus sign.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q012","read_aloud":"What type of figurative language is this? A. Simile B. Onomatopoeia C. Metaphor D. Rhyme","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys to secret places.\"","stem":"What type of figurative language is this?","choices":{"A":"Simile","B":"Onomatopoeia","C":"Metaphor","D":"Rhyme"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"A metaphor compares two unlike things without using \"like\" or \"as.\" Here, maps are compared to keys.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys to secret places.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q013","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"A Map and a Dream\": \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs. What sound device is used with the words \"lines\" and \"lace\" and \"designs\"? A. Rhyme at the end of lines B. Repeated consonant sounds at the beginning of words (alliteration) C. Long vowels only D. No sound devices","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"A Map and a Dream\": \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs. What sound device is used with the words \"lines\" and \"lace\" and \"designs\"?","choices":{"A":"Rhyme at the end of lines","B":"Repeated consonant sounds at the beginning of words (alliteration)","C":"Long vowels only","D":"No sound devices"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The \"l\" sound in \"lines,\" \"lace,\" and \"designs\" is repeated (alliteration).","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q014","read_aloud":"What does the speaker mean by \"a map, a dream\"? A. She needs an actual map and a sleeping dream to travel. B. A map can inspire dreams of travel, and together they let her imagine going anywhere. C. Dreams are more important than maps. D. Maps are useless without a dream.","excerpt":"\"I can travel anywhere . . . A map, a dream can take me there!\"","stem":"What does the speaker mean by \"a map, a dream\"?","choices":{"A":"She needs an actual map and a sleeping dream to travel.","B":"A map can inspire dreams of travel, and together they let her imagine going anywhere.","C":"Dreams are more important than maps.","D":"Maps are useless without a dream."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The combination of a physical map and the imagination (dream) allows her to \"travel\" in her mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I can travel anywhere . . . A map, a dream can take me there!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q015","read_aloud":"If this is true, what might an explorer today try to discover instead of a new place? A. New animals or plants in known places B. A way to fly to the moon C. A new flavor of ice cream D. A taller building","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered.\"","stem":"If this is true, what might an explorer today try to discover instead of a new place?","choices":{"A":"New animals or plants in known places","B":"A way to fly to the moon","C":"A new flavor of ice cream","D":"A taller building"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"If all places are discovered, explorers might look for new species or hidden details within known places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker roll the map into a tube? A. to make it easier to carry B. to pretend it is a telescope and look through it C. to throw it away D. to give it to a friend","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\"","stem":"Why does the speaker roll the map into a tube?","choices":{"A":"to make it easier to carry","B":"to pretend it is a telescope and look through it","C":"to throw it away","D":"to give it to a friend"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker rolls the map into a tube and peers through it, wishing it were a telescope. This shows the speaker is using imagination to pretend the map is a telescope.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q017","read_aloud":"AND \"I can trace each / graceful line ... / Close my eyes / and in my mind / I can travel / anywhere How are the speakers in \"Learning the World\" and \"A Map and a Dream\" similar? A. Both use maps to learn about and imagine traveling the world. B. Both want to stay home forever. C. Both are professional explorers. D. Both do not like maps.","excerpt":"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges.","stem":"AND \"I can trace each / graceful line ... / Close my eyes / and in my mind / I can travel / anywhere How are the speakers in \"Learning the World\" and \"A Map and a Dream\" similar?","choices":{"A":"Both use maps to learn about and imagine traveling the world.","B":"Both want to stay home forever.","C":"Both are professional explorers.","D":"Both do not like maps."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Both speakers use maps to explore the world. One memorizes and traces maps, while the other uses a map to travel in their mind. Both use maps to learn and imagine.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q018","read_aloud":"What evidence shows that the poet thinks maps are special? A. The poet says maps are only paper. B. The poet says maps are keys to secret places and vast new worlds. C. The poet says maps are boring. D. The poet says maps are too expensive.","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\"","stem":"What evidence shows that the poet thinks maps are special?","choices":{"A":"The poet says maps are only paper.","B":"The poet says maps are keys to secret places and vast new worlds.","C":"The poet says maps are boring.","D":"The poet says maps are too expensive."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet compares maps to keys that open secret places and new worlds. This shows the poet thinks maps are special and powerful tools for discovery.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q019","read_aloud":"What do the explorers \"etch\" on the earth? A. real lines with paint B. invisible lines of latitude and longitude C. their names in stone D. pictures of ships","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas. / Etching earth with invisible designs / Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\"","stem":"What do the explorers \"etch\" on the earth?","choices":{"A":"real lines with paint","B":"invisible lines of latitude and longitude","C":"their names in stone","D":"pictures of ships"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The explorers etch invisible designs on the earth. These invisible designs are lines of latitude and longitude that help people navigate and find their way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas. / Etching earth with invisible designs / Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q020","read_aloud":"What does \"crossed and crossed again\" mean? A. Animals have traveled through these places many times. B. People have built bridges there. C. The places are very small. D. No one has ever visited.","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed / and crossed again\"","stem":"What does \"crossed and crossed again\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Animals have traveled through these places many times.","B":"People have built bridges there.","C":"The places are very small.","D":"No one has ever visited."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Crossed and crossed again\" means animals have traveled through these places over and over, many times, long before humans arrived.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed / and crossed again\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of,\" showing the stars were his navigation tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l06-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Map lines cross over each other like lace patterns. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping, which fits this image.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q001","read_aloud":": If a map has \"invisible designs\" like latitude and longitude, what does \"invisible\" mean? Options: A. something you can see very clearly B. something you cannot see C. something that is very colorful D. something that is very big","excerpt":"\"Etching earth with invisible designs / Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\"","stem":": If a map has \"invisible designs\" like latitude and longitude, what does \"invisible\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"something you can see very clearly","B":"something you cannot see","C":"something that is very colorful","D":"something that is very big"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Invisible means that something cannot be seen by the eye.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Etching earth with invisible designs / Crossing rivers, ice, and trees.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q002","read_aloud":": Why does the poet call the planet \"our ship\"? Options: A. It floats on water. B. We are all traveling together on it through space. C. It is made of metal. D. It has sails.","excerpt":"\"Coordinate all of us on this globe / Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":": Why does the poet call the planet \"our ship\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"It floats on water.","B":"We are all traveling together on it through space.","C":"It is made of metal.","D":"It has sails."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The metaphor suggests we are all on a journey together on one planet, just like sailors on a ship.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Coordinate all of us on this globe / Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q003","read_aloud":": How can someone \"traverse a dream\"? Options: A. By waking up. B. By working hard to make their dream a reality. C. By falling asleep. D. By buying a map.","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":": How can someone \"traverse a dream\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"By waking up.","B":"By working hard to make their dream a reality.","C":"By falling asleep.","D":"By buying a map."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In poetry, to traverse a dream means to take action to achieve what you desire.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q004","read_aloud":": How does the poet help us understand latitude and longitude? Options: A. By describing them as lines wrapping around the earth. B. By saying they are secret codes. C. By saying they are invisible and useless. D. By drawing them on the ocean.","excerpt":"\"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth\"","stem":": How does the poet help us understand latitude and longitude? Options:","choices":{"A":"By describing them as lines wrapping around the earth.","B":"By saying they are secret codes.","C":"By saying they are invisible and useless.","D":"By drawing them on the ocean."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poet uses visual language to explain that these lines are a system covering the globe.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q005","read_aloud":"How does the word \"via\" help explain the relationship between Magellan and the stars? A. It shows Magellan fought against the stars to find his way B. It shows Magellan used the stars as a tool or guide for navigation C. It shows Magellan ignored the stars and used only maps D. It shows Magellan believed the stars controlled his fate","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"How does the word \"via\" help explain the relationship between Magellan and the stars?","choices":{"A":"It shows Magellan fought against the stars to find his way","B":"It shows Magellan used the stars as a tool or guide for navigation","C":"It shows Magellan ignored the stars and used only maps","D":"It shows Magellan believed the stars controlled his fate"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Via\" means \"by way of.\" This shows Magellan used the stars as a navigation tool, not as enemies, ignorances, or controllers of his life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q006","read_aloud":"How does the repetition of \"I\u0027m\" at the start of each phrase affect the poem\u0027s rhythm and meaning? A. It makes the poem confusing and hard to follow B. It creates a steady, determined rhythm that shows the speaker\u0027s focused effort to learn C. It suggests the speaker is bored and repeating words without meaning D. It shows the speaker is listing things they already know perfectly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"How does the repetition of \"I\u0027m\" at the start of each phrase affect the poem\u0027s rhythm and meaning?","choices":{"A":"It makes the poem confusing and hard to follow","B":"It creates a steady, determined rhythm that shows the speaker\u0027s focused effort to learn","C":"It suggests the speaker is bored and repeating words without meaning","D":"It shows the speaker is listing things they already know perfectly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Repeating \"I\u0027m\" creates a rhythmic pattern that mirrors the speaker\u0027s steady, purposeful actions. This emphasizes their dedication to learning about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q007","read_aloud":"How does the poet use contrast to develop the main idea about maps? A. By saying maps are only useful for finding tourist spots B. By showing maps are both simple visual tools and powerful gateways to imagination and discovery C. By arguing that maps should be replaced by digital technology D. By suggesting that only artists can truly understand maps","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs... Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\"","stem":"How does the poet use contrast to develop the main idea about maps?","choices":{"A":"By saying maps are only useful for finding tourist spots","B":"By showing maps are both simple visual tools and powerful gateways to imagination and discovery","C":"By arguing that maps should be replaced by digital technology","D":"By suggesting that only artists can truly understand maps"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet contrasts maps as \"tiny lines\" with maps as \"keys to secret places.\" This shows maps have both practical and imaginative value.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs... Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q008","read_aloud":"Based on this idea, how might your view of \"exploration\" change? A. Exploration only counts if humans are the first to go somewhere B. Exploration can mean learning from and respecting the creatures and places that were there before us C. Exploration is pointless because animals already know everything D. Exploration should focus only on places no living thing has ever visited","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\"","stem":"Based on this idea, how might your view of \"exploration\" change?","choices":{"A":"Exploration only counts if humans are the first to go somewhere","B":"Exploration can mean learning from and respecting the creatures and places that were there before us","C":"Exploration is pointless because animals already know everything","D":"Exploration should focus only on places no living thing has ever visited"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem shows animals explored first. This suggests true exploration includes learning from nature and respecting prior inhabitants, not just being \"first.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q009","read_aloud":"Why might the poet choose to end the poem with this metaphor? A. To suggest Earth is too small to matter in the universe B. To leave readers with a powerful image of shared responsibility and unity on our planet C. To argue that only sailors understand Earth\u0027s true value D. To imply that Earth will soon be abandoned for space travel","excerpt":"\"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"Why might the poet choose to end the poem with this metaphor?","choices":{"A":"To suggest Earth is too small to matter in the universe","B":"To leave readers with a powerful image of shared responsibility and unity on our planet","C":"To argue that only sailors understand Earth\u0027s true value","D":"To imply that Earth will soon be abandoned for space travel"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Ending with \"our home, our ship, our planet earth\" creates a memorable, unifying image. It emphasizes that we all share Earth and must care for it together.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q010","read_aloud":"Why will \"we never know\" these adventurers? A. They are invisible. B. They are animals whose names we do not know. C. They are famous and everyone knows them. D. They are from the future.","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen.\"","stem":"Why will \"we never know\" these adventurers?","choices":{"A":"They are invisible.","B":"They are animals whose names we do not know.","C":"They are famous and everyone knows them.","D":"They are from the future."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem includes wings, feet, fur, scales, and hooves, so many of these \"adventurers\" are animals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q011","read_aloud":"Why does the speaker want the world \"spread beneath my feet\"? A. She wants to step on the world. B. She wants to see everything all at once, as if from a high view. C. She wants to hide the world. D. She wants to draw the world.","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"Why does the speaker want the world \"spread beneath my feet\"?","choices":{"A":"She wants to step on the world.","B":"She wants to see everything all at once, as if from a high view.","C":"She wants to hide the world.","D":"She wants to draw the world."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Having the world \"spread beneath\" her feet means seeing it all from above, like on a map or from a high place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q012","read_aloud":"If you wanted to \"travel\" to a faraway country without leaving your room, what would you do based on this poem? A. Buy an airplane ticket B. Look at a map and imagine being there C. Wait for the country to come to you D. Close your eyes and hope","excerpt":"\"I can travel anywhere . . . A map, a dream can take me there!\"","stem":"If you wanted to \"travel\" to a faraway country without leaving your room, what would you do based on this poem?","choices":{"A":"Buy an airplane ticket","B":"Look at a map and imagine being there","C":"Wait for the country to come to you","D":"Close your eyes and hope"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker uses a map and her imagination (dream) to travel in her mind.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I can travel anywhere . . . A map, a dream can take me there!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q013","read_aloud":"Why does the poet use the word \"via\" instead of \"using\"? A. Because \"via\" is a shorter word. B. Because \"via\" sounds more poetic and fits the rhythm of the poem. C. Because \"via\" is easier to spell. D. Because \"via\" means something different.","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays. / Columbus sailed on over the edge / Discovering lands and dreams.\"","stem":"Why does the poet use the word \"via\" instead of \"using\"?","choices":{"A":"Because \"via\" is a shorter word.","B":"Because \"via\" sounds more poetic and fits the rhythm of the poem.","C":"Because \"via\" is easier to spell.","D":"Because \"via\" means something different."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Poets choose words carefully for sound and rhythm. \"Via\" means the same as \"using\" or \"by way of,\" but it sounds more poetic and fits the rhythm of the line better.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays. / Columbus sailed on over the edge / Discovering lands and dreams.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q014","read_aloud":"What pattern does the poet use in these lines? A. The lines are random and have no pattern. B. The poet repeats the pattern: \"I\u0027m [verb]ing [noun], / [verb]ing [noun], / [verb]ing [noun].\" C. The lines get shorter and shorter. D. The lines rhyme in pairs.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges. / I\u0027m memorizing capitals, / tracing countries, / learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"What pattern does the poet use in these lines?","choices":{"A":"The lines are random and have no pattern.","B":"The poet repeats the pattern: \"I\u0027m [verb]ing [noun], / [verb]ing [noun], / [verb]ing [noun].\"","C":"The lines get shorter and shorter.","D":"The lines rhyme in pairs."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet uses a repeating pattern: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges.\" Then repeats with \"capitals, countries, crops and industries.\" This pattern makes the poem rhythmic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges. / I\u0027m memorizing capitals, / tracing countries, / learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q015","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the speaker in \"A Map and a Dream\"? A. The speaker has traveled everywhere in real life. B. The speaker has a strong imagination and uses it to explore the world. C. The speaker does not like to read. D. The speaker is afraid of maps.","excerpt":"\"I can trace each / graceful line ... / Close my eyes / and in my mind / I can travel / anywhere ... / A map, a dream / can take me there!\"","stem":"What can you infer about the speaker in \"A Map and a Dream\"?","choices":{"A":"The speaker has traveled everywhere in real life.","B":"The speaker has a strong imagination and uses it to explore the world.","C":"The speaker does not like to read.","D":"The speaker is afraid of maps."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker closes their eyes and travels anywhere in their mind. This shows the speaker has a strong imagination and uses it to explore the world through maps and dreams.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I can trace each / graceful line ... / Close my eyes / and in my mind / I can travel / anywhere ... / A map, a dream / can take me there!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q016","read_aloud":"What is the purpose of the lines that \"slide from pole to pole\"? A. to decorate the earth B. to help people find locations and navigate the globe C. to make the earth look smaller D. to block the sun","excerpt":"\"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe / Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"What is the purpose of the lines that \"slide from pole to pole\"?","choices":{"A":"to decorate the earth","B":"to help people find locations and navigate the globe","C":"to make the earth look smaller","D":"to block the sun"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The lines of latitude and longitude coordinate all of us on the globe. They help people find locations and navigate, which is their purpose.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe / Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q017","read_aloud":"What does the poet mean by \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered\"? A. Humans have been everywhere on earth. B. Even places humans have not visited have been explored by animals. C. The earth is too small to have new places. D. There are no mountains under ice.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice\"","stem":"What does the poet mean by \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered\"?","choices":{"A":"Humans have been everywhere on earth.","B":"Even places humans have not visited have been explored by animals.","C":"The earth is too small to have new places.","D":"There are no mountains under ice."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet says even in Antarctica, penguins have left tracks. This means animals have explored places before humans, so no place is truly undiscovered by all living things.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q018","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q019","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of,\" showing the stars were his navigation tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Map lines cross over each other like lace patterns. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping, which fits this image.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. playing a game with friends B. studying a map to learn about the world C. writing a letter to a pen pal D. planning a birthday party","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"playing a game with friends","B":"studying a map to learn about the world","C":"writing a letter to a pen pal","D":"planning a birthday party"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker lists actions like \"memorizing\" and \"tracing\" places on a map. This shows they are studying to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Humans are always the first to explore any place B. Animals have explored many places before humans arrived C. Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing D. Only places with mountains are worth exploring","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Humans are always the first to explore any place","B":"Animals have explored many places before humans arrived","C":"Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing","D":"Only places with mountains are worth exploring"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states penguins \"laid shambling tracks\" before humans came to Antarctica. This shows animals explored first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. It suggests Earth is only a place to live, not to explore B. It suggests we all share Earth and must care for it together like a crew on a ship C. It suggests Earth is too big for people to understand D. It suggests only sailors should care about Earth","excerpt":"\"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"It suggests Earth is only a place to live, not to explore","B":"It suggests we all share Earth and must care for it together like a crew on a ship","C":"It suggests Earth is too big for people to understand","D":"It suggests only sailors should care about Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparing Earth to \"our ship\" suggests we are all traveling together. This emphasizes shared responsibility for our planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q001","read_aloud":": What does \"vast\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. very small B. very large or huge C. very old D. very colorful","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\"","stem":": What does \"vast\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"very small","B":"very large or huge","C":"very old","D":"very colorful"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Vast means very large in size or area.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q002","read_aloud":": What is the poet\u0027s attitude toward maps? Options: A. They think maps are boring. B. They think maps are beautiful and full of meaning. C. They think maps are just paper. D. They think maps are for grownups only.","excerpt":"\"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs . . . / More than names / and colored dots\"","stem":": What is the poet\u0027s attitude toward maps? Options:","choices":{"A":"They think maps are boring.","B":"They think maps are beautiful and full of meaning.","C":"They think maps are just paper.","D":"They think maps are for grownups only."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet uses words like \"lace designs\" and \"keys,\" which shows they find maps special and interesting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs . . . / More than names / and colored dots\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q003","read_aloud":": Do you think a map can really be a \"key\"? Why? Options: A. Yes, it unlocks the imagination to see places you have not been. B. No, a key must be made of metal. C. Yes, it helps you find the front door. D. No, it is just a piece of paper.","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\"","stem":": Do you think a map can really be a \"key\"? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"Yes, it unlocks the imagination to see places you have not been.","B":"No, a key must be made of metal.","C":"Yes, it helps you find the front door.","D":"No, it is just a piece of paper."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poet is using figurative language; a map isn\u0027t a metal key, but it acts like one by opening up new knowledge.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q004","read_aloud":": If you had to draw a map of your \"dream,\" what would you draw to represent it? Options: A. A map of my house. B. A map of a magical land with things I love. C. A map of my school. D. A list of words only.","excerpt":"\"A map, a dream / can take me there!\"","stem":": If you had to draw a map of your \"dream,\" what would you draw to represent it? Options:","choices":{"A":"A map of my house.","B":"A map of a magical land with things I love.","C":"A map of my school.","D":"A list of words only."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem suggests that maps and dreams are linked; a dream map would naturally include the things that make the dreamer happy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A map, a dream / can take me there!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q005","read_aloud":"How does \"traversed\" carry both a literal and figurative meaning in this excerpt? A. It only describes physical travel across oceans B. It describes both traveling across real oceans and pursuing dreams and goals C. It only refers to drawing lines on a map D. It suggests the explorers never actually moved from home","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":"How does \"traversed\" carry both a literal and figurative meaning in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"It only describes physical travel across oceans","B":"It describes both traveling across real oceans and pursuing dreams and goals","C":"It only refers to drawing lines on a map","D":"It suggests the explorers never actually moved from home"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Traversed\" literally means traveled across, but paired with \"their dreams,\" it also suggests pursuing hopes and ambitions. This dual meaning enriches the poem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q006","read_aloud":"How does comparing map lines to \"lace designs\" help readers understand the poet\u0027s view of maps? A. It suggests maps are fragile and should not be used for travel B. It suggests maps are beautiful, intricate, and worthy of careful attention C. It suggests maps are old-fashioned and no longer useful D. It suggests only artists can create or understand maps","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"How does comparing map lines to \"lace designs\" help readers understand the poet\u0027s view of maps?","choices":{"A":"It suggests maps are fragile and should not be used for travel","B":"It suggests maps are beautiful, intricate, and worthy of careful attention","C":"It suggests maps are old-fashioned and no longer useful","D":"It suggests only artists can create or understand maps"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Lace is delicate, detailed, and beautiful. Comparing map lines to lace suggests maps are not just tools but also works of art that invite close, appreciative looking.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q007","read_aloud":"How does the poet use the example of penguins to challenge a common idea about exploration? A. By proving that only animals can truly explore B. By showing that \"discovery\" depends on perspective-humans may be late to places animals already know C. By arguing that Antarctica is not worth exploring D. By suggesting penguins are better navigators than humans","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\"","stem":"How does the poet use the example of penguins to challenge a common idea about exploration?","choices":{"A":"By proving that only animals can truly explore","B":"By showing that \"discovery\" depends on perspective-humans may be late to places animals already know","C":"By arguing that Antarctica is not worth exploring","D":"By suggesting penguins are better navigators than humans"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The penguin example shows that a place humans call \"undiscovered\" may already be familiar to animals. This challenges the idea that human arrival equals true discovery.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q008","read_aloud":"Do you think it is important to record and share exploration stories? Use clues from the poem to support your view. A. No, because exploration is only valuable if kept secret B. Yes, because sharing stories helps others learn and prevents wonders from being lost forever C. No, because only famous explorers deserve to have their stories told D. Yes, but only if the stories are written in poetry form","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen\"","stem":"Do you think it is important to record and share exploration stories? Use clues from the poem to support your view.","choices":{"A":"No, because exploration is only valuable if kept secret","B":"Yes, because sharing stories helps others learn and prevents wonders from being lost forever","C":"No, because only famous explorers deserve to have their stories told","D":"Yes, but only if the stories are written in poetry form"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem notes that some explorers\u0027 wonders are never shared. This implies that recording stories helps preserve knowledge and inspires others, making sharing important.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q009","read_aloud":"The word \"traversed\" is not in this excerpt, but if a bird traversed the sky, what did it do? A. Built a nest B. Flew across the sky C. Sang a song D. Landed on a branch","excerpt":"\"all have been crossed and crossed again by wings whirring or silent feet furred or scaled hoofed or bare.\"","stem":"The word \"traversed\" is not in this excerpt, but if a bird traversed the sky, what did it do?","choices":{"A":"Built a nest","B":"Flew across the sky","C":"Sang a song","D":"Landed on a branch"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Traverse means to travel across. A bird traversing the sky flies across it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"all have been crossed and crossed again by wings whirring or silent feet furred or scaled hoofed or bare.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Do you agree with the speaker\u0027s statement? Why or why not? A. Yes, because animals and people have been almost everywhere. B. No, because deep oceans and some caves are still unexplored. C. Yes, because maps show everything. D. No, because the speaker is lying.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered.\"","stem":"Do you agree with the speaker\u0027s statement? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because animals and people have been almost everywhere.","B":"No, because deep oceans and some caves are still unexplored.","C":"Yes, because maps show everything.","D":"No, because the speaker is lying."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While the poem says this, scientifically, some deep ocean areas and remote caves have never been visited.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q011","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"Early Explorers\": \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered … all have been crossed and crossed again. Why did the author include animals as explorers? A. To make the poem longer B. To show that discovery is not only done by humans C. To make fun of explorers D. To teach about penguins only","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"Early Explorers\": \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered … all have been crossed and crossed again. Why did the author include animals as explorers?","choices":{"A":"To make the poem longer","B":"To show that discovery is not only done by humans","C":"To make fun of explorers","D":"To teach about penguins only"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"By including animals, the poet shows that many creatures have \"discovered\" places before humans.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q012","read_aloud":"Do you think memorizing a map is a good way to learn about the world? Why? A. No, because maps are boring. B. Yes, because it helps you remember where places are without looking. C. No, because you can never remember everything. D. Yes, because it is easy.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges.\"","stem":"Do you think memorizing a map is a good way to learn about the world? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because maps are boring.","B":"Yes, because it helps you remember where places are without looking.","C":"No, because you can never remember everything.","D":"Yes, because it is easy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Memorizing maps helps you learn geography and locate places quickly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"A Map and a Dream\": \"A map, a dream can take me there! If you wrote a new line after this one, what would be a good ending? A. \"But I\u0027d rather stay home.\" B. \"And my mind becomes a traveler without a care.\" C. \"Maps are too hard to read.\" D. \"Dreams are for sleeping.\"","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"A Map and a Dream\": \"A map, a dream can take me there! If you wrote a new line after this one, what would be a good ending?","choices":{"A":"\"But I\u0027d rather stay home.\"","B":"\"And my mind becomes a traveler without a care.\"","C":"\"Maps are too hard to read.\"","D":"\"Dreams are for sleeping.\""},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This line continues the theme of imagination and travel without leaving home.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Why does the poet say the explorers \"traversed their dreams\" instead of just \"followed their dreams\"? A. Because \"traversed\" means they physically traveled through their dreams like a journey. B. Because \"traversed\" is a shorter word. C. Because the explorers were sleeping. D. Because \"followed\" is not a real word.","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":"Why does the poet say the explorers \"traversed their dreams\" instead of just \"followed their dreams\"?","choices":{"A":"Because \"traversed\" means they physically traveled through their dreams like a journey.","B":"Because \"traversed\" is a shorter word.","C":"Because the explorers were sleeping.","D":"Because \"followed\" is not a real word."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Traversed\" means traveled through or moved across. The poet uses this word to show that the explorers\u0027 dreams were like a real journey they traveled through, not just something they followed.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q015","read_aloud":"Why does the poet repeat the word \"wishing\" three times? A. To show that the speaker is bored. B. To show the speaker\u0027s strong desire to see and explore the world. C. To make the poem longer. D. To confuse the reader.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope, / wishing I could see past my street, / wishing I could see / the whole world / spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"Why does the poet repeat the word \"wishing\" three times?","choices":{"A":"To show that the speaker is bored.","B":"To show the speaker\u0027s strong desire to see and explore the world.","C":"To make the poem longer.","D":"To confuse the reader."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Repeating \"wishing\" three times shows how much the speaker wants to explore. It emphasizes the speaker\u0027s strong desire to see beyond their street and explore the whole world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope, / wishing I could see past my street, / wishing I could see / the whole world / spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the poet compare map lines to \"lace designs\"? A. To show that maps are made of fabric. B. To show that map lines are delicate, beautiful, and carefully connected like lace. C. To show that maps are only for women. D. To show that maps are ugly.","excerpt":"\"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs ... / More than names / and colored dots, / rivers, mountains, / tourist spots.\"","stem":"Why does the poet compare map lines to \"lace designs\"?","choices":{"A":"To show that maps are made of fabric.","B":"To show that map lines are delicate, beautiful, and carefully connected like lace.","C":"To show that maps are only for women.","D":"To show that maps are ugly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Lace is delicate and beautiful with carefully connected patterns. Comparing map lines to lace shows that the lines are intricate, beautiful, and artfully connected.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs ... / More than names / and colored dots, / rivers, mountains, / tourist spots.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q017","read_aloud":"Do you think the poet admires these unknown adventurers? Use clues from the text. A. No, the poet thinks they are not important. B. Yes, the poet calls them \"adventurers\" and \"explorers\" and wonders about the wonders they have seen. C. No, the poet is angry at them. D. Yes, but only because they are famous.","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\"","stem":"Do you think the poet admires these unknown adventurers? Use clues from the text.","choices":{"A":"No, the poet thinks they are not important.","B":"Yes, the poet calls them \"adventurers\" and \"explorers\" and wonders about the wonders they have seen.","C":"No, the poet is angry at them.","D":"Yes, but only because they are famous."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet calls them \"adventurers\" and \"explorers,\" which are respectful words. The poet also wonders about \"what wonders they have seen,\" showing admiration for their unknown journeys.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q018","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q019","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of,\" showing the stars were his navigation tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Map lines cross over each other like lace patterns. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping, which fits this image.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. playing a game with friends B. studying a map to learn about the world C. writing a letter to a pen pal D. planning a birthday party","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"playing a game with friends","B":"studying a map to learn about the world","C":"writing a letter to a pen pal","D":"planning a birthday party"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker lists actions like \"memorizing\" and \"tracing\" places on a map. This shows they are studying to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Humans are always the first to explore any place B. Animals have explored many places before humans arrived C. Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing D. Only places with mountains are worth exploring","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Humans are always the first to explore any place","B":"Animals have explored many places before humans arrived","C":"Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing","D":"Only places with mountains are worth exploring"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states penguins \"laid shambling tracks\" before humans came to Antarctica. This shows animals explored first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l08-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. It suggests Earth is only a place to live, not to explore B. It suggests we all share Earth and must care for it together like a crew on a ship C. It suggests Earth is too big for people to understand D. It suggests only sailors should care about Earth","excerpt":"\"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"It suggests Earth is only a place to live, not to explore","B":"It suggests we all share Earth and must care for it together like a crew on a ship","C":"It suggests Earth is too big for people to understand","D":"It suggests only sailors should care about Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparing Earth to \"our ship\" suggests we are all traveling together. This emphasizes shared responsibility for our planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q001","read_aloud":": What does \"shambling\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. walking in a clumsy or slow way B. running very fast C. flying high D. jumping very high","excerpt":"\"where whole mountains are hidden / under ice / penguins already laid shambling tracks\"","stem":": What does \"shambling\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"walking in a clumsy or slow way","B":"running very fast","C":"flying high","D":"jumping very high"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Shambling describes a slow, awkward, or clumsy movement, which is how penguins walk.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"where whole mountains are hidden / under ice / penguins already laid shambling tracks\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q002","read_aloud":": Why does the poet mention the penguins? Options: A. To show that they are the first ones to discover the land. B. To show that they are hungry. C. To show that they like to play. D. To show that they are lost.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica... penguins already laid shambling tracks\"","stem":": Why does the poet mention the penguins? Options:","choices":{"A":"To show that they are the first ones to discover the land.","B":"To show that they are hungry.","C":"To show that they like to play.","D":"To show that they are lost."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poet uses the penguins to argue that humans aren\u0027t the only ones who explore the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica... penguins already laid shambling tracks\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q003","read_aloud":": How is this description different from a map of Antarctica? Options: A. A map shows the mountains, but the poem says they are hidden. B. A map says it is hot. C. The poem says there is no ice. D. There is no difference.","excerpt":"\"Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice\"","stem":": How is this description different from a map of Antarctica? Options:","choices":{"A":"A map shows the mountains, but the poem says they are hidden.","B":"A map says it is hot.","C":"The poem says there is no ice.","D":"There is no difference."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"A map might label the hidden geography, but the poem highlights the feeling of it being covered and hidden.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q004","read_aloud":": Do you think the poet admires these \"unknown explorers\"? Why? Options: A. Yes, they respect their hidden work. B. No, they think they are unimportant. C. Yes, they want to eat them. D. No, they think they are noisy.","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\"","stem":": Do you think the poet admires these \"unknown explorers\"? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"Yes, they respect their hidden work.","B":"No, they think they are unimportant.","C":"Yes, they want to eat them.","D":"No, they think they are noisy."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The tone of the poem is thoughtful and respectful, focusing on the \"wonders\" they have seen.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q005","read_aloud":": If you were an explorer of a place no human has ever seen, what would you want to find there? Options: A. A new store. B. A new kind of animal or plant. C. A road. D. My house.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered\"","stem":": If you were an explorer of a place no human has ever seen, what would you want to find there? Options:","choices":{"A":"A new store.","B":"A new kind of animal or plant.","C":"A road.","D":"My house."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This question asks the student to imagine themselves in the role of an explorer, engaging with the theme of discovery presented in the poem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"girth\" help convey the scale and unity of Earth in this poem? A. It makes Earth seem small and unimportant B. It emphasizes Earth\u0027s roundness and how lines connect everyone on the planet C. It suggests Earth is only water with no land D. It implies that only sailors understand Earth\u0027s shape","excerpt":"\"These lines that slide from pole to pole Wrapping around the watery girth Coordinate all of us on this globe\"","stem":"How does the word \"girth\" help convey the scale and unity of Earth in this poem?","choices":{"A":"It makes Earth seem small and unimportant","B":"It emphasizes Earth\u0027s roundness and how lines connect everyone on the planet","C":"It suggests Earth is only water with no land","D":"It implies that only sailors understand Earth\u0027s shape"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Girth\" means distance around. Describing Earth\u0027s \"watery girth\" highlights its round shape and how latitude/longitude lines wrap around to connect all people.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These lines that slide from pole to pole Wrapping around the watery girth Coordinate all of us on this globe\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q007","read_aloud":"How do the speaker\u0027s actions and wishes work together to develop the poem\u0027s theme? A. They show that studying maps is boring and frustrating B. They show that learning about the world through maps can spark dreams of real exploration and connection C. They prove that maps are only useful for school tests D. They suggest the speaker will never leave home to explore","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges... wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"How do the speaker\u0027s actions and wishes work together to develop the poem\u0027s theme?","choices":{"A":"They show that studying maps is boring and frustrating","B":"They show that learning about the world through maps can spark dreams of real exploration and connection","C":"They prove that maps are only useful for school tests","D":"They suggest the speaker will never leave home to explore"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker\u0027s active learning (\"memorizing,\" \"tracing\") combines with big wishes (\"see the whole world\"). This shows how knowledge fuels imagination and the desire to explore.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges... wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q008","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"Latitude Longitude Dreams\": \"Our home, our ship, our planet earth. Excerpt from \"Early Explorers\": \"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen How do these two excerpts together deepen the theme of shared human experience? A. They suggest only famous explorers matter in history B. They show that exploration connects us across time and space, and that we share responsibility for our planet C. They argue that exploration is only valuable if it is recorded in writing D. They imply that Earth is too big for people to truly understand or care for","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"Latitude Longitude Dreams\": \"Our home, our ship, our planet earth. Excerpt from \"Early Explorers\": \"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen How do these two excerpts together deepen the theme of shared human experience?","choices":{"A":"They suggest only famous explorers matter in history","B":"They show that exploration connects us across time and space, and that we share responsibility for our planet","C":"They argue that exploration is only valuable if it is recorded in writing","D":"They imply that Earth is too big for people to truly understand or care for"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The first excerpt emphasizes shared ownership of Earth; the second honors unknown explorers. Together, they show exploration is a shared, ongoing human story that connects us.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q009","read_aloud":"Based on the entire collection, do you think the poets view exploration as mainly a human activity? Why or why not? A. Yes, because all the poems focus only on human explorers like Magellan and Columbus B. No, because the poems show animals explore too, and imagination lets anyone \"travel\" without moving C. Yes, because only humans can write poems about exploration D. No, because the poets believe exploration is pointless","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\"","stem":"Based on the entire collection, do you think the poets view exploration as mainly a human activity? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because all the poems focus only on human explorers like Magellan and Columbus","B":"No, because the poems show animals explore too, and imagination lets anyone \"travel\" without moving","C":"Yes, because only humans can write poems about exploration","D":"No, because the poets believe exploration is pointless"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poems include animal explorers (\"penguins,\" \"wings whirring\") and mental journeys (\"in my mind I can travel anywhere\"). This shows exploration is broader than just human physical travel.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q010","read_aloud":"Do you think this is an effective way to describe maps? Why? A. Yes, because it compares maps to something beautiful and detailed (lace). B. No, because lace is not related to maps. C. Yes, because maps are made of cloth. D. No, because lines are boring.","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs.\"","stem":"Do you think this is an effective way to describe maps? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because it compares maps to something beautiful and detailed (lace).","B":"No, because lace is not related to maps.","C":"Yes, because maps are made of cloth.","D":"No, because lines are boring."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Lace is delicate and intricate. Comparing map lines to lace makes them sound artistic and interesting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q011","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"Learning the World\": \"wishing it were a telescope. What does this wish tell you about the speaker\u0027s perspective? A. She thinks maps are useless. B. She wants a more active, \"seeing\" way to explore the world. C. She prefers stars over maps. D. She does not like geography.","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"Learning the World\": \"wishing it were a telescope. What does this wish tell you about the speaker\u0027s perspective?","choices":{"A":"She thinks maps are useless.","B":"She wants a more active, \"seeing\" way to explore the world.","C":"She prefers stars over maps.","D":"She does not like geography."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A telescope would let her see real places, not just read about them on a map.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q012","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"Early Explorers\": \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen. Do you think it matters that we will never know these explorers? Why? A. Yes, because only famous people matter. B. No, because the wonders still happened even if no one recorded them. C. Yes, because we need to give them awards. D. No, because they were probably not real.","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"Early Explorers\": \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen. Do you think it matters that we will never know these explorers? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because only famous people matter.","B":"No, because the wonders still happened even if no one recorded them.","C":"Yes, because we need to give them awards.","D":"No, because they were probably not real."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem suggests discovery is valuable even without fame or records.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q013","read_aloud":"If you were to add a new poem to this collection called \"The Imaginary Journey,\" what would it be about? A. A trip to the grocery store B. Traveling to faraway places using only your imagination and a map C. The history of airplanes D. How to pack a suitcase","excerpt":"The whole poetry collection.","stem":"If you were to add a new poem to this collection called \"The Imaginary Journey,\" what would it be about?","choices":{"A":"A trip to the grocery store","B":"Traveling to faraway places using only your imagination and a map","C":"The history of airplanes","D":"How to pack a suitcase"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The collection focuses on map‑based imagination and discovery, so this fits the theme.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole poetry collection."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q014","read_aloud":"Why does the poet call the earth\u0027s girth \"watery\"? A. Because the earth is mostly covered with water. B. Because the earth is made of ice. C. Because the earth has no water. D. Because the earth is very dry.","excerpt":"\"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe / Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"Why does the poet call the earth\u0027s girth \"watery\"?","choices":{"A":"Because the earth is mostly covered with water.","B":"Because the earth is made of ice.","C":"Because the earth has no water.","D":"Because the earth is very dry."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The earth is mostly covered with oceans and water. Calling it \"watery girth\" reminds us that most of the earth\u0027s surface is water, which is why the lines wrap around a \"watery\" circumference.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe / Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q015","read_aloud":"How does the poet use the map as a symbol in this poem? A. The map symbolizes the speaker\u0027s desire to learn and explore the world. B. The map symbolizes the speaker\u0027s wish to sleep. C. The map symbolizes the speaker\u0027s fear of travel. D. The map symbolizes the speaker\u0027s love of food.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges. / I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\"","stem":"How does the poet use the map as a symbol in this poem?","choices":{"A":"The map symbolizes the speaker\u0027s desire to learn and explore the world.","B":"The map symbolizes the speaker\u0027s wish to sleep.","C":"The map symbolizes the speaker\u0027s fear of travel.","D":"The map symbolizes the speaker\u0027s love of food."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The map is not just paper; it represents the speaker\u0027s curiosity and desire to learn. The speaker memorizes, traces, and wishes to see the whole world, showing the map symbolizes a desire to explore.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges. / I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the poet list different types of feet (furred, scaled, hoofed, bare)? A. To show that only certain animals can explore. B. To show the variety of animals that have explored the earth before humans. C. To teach about animal body parts. D. To make the poem shorter.","excerpt":"\"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed / and crossed again / by wings whirring or silent / feet furred or scaled / hoofed or bare\"","stem":"Why does the poet list different types of feet (furred, scaled, hoofed, bare)?","choices":{"A":"To show that only certain animals can explore.","B":"To show the variety of animals that have explored the earth before humans.","C":"To teach about animal body parts.","D":"To make the poem shorter."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Listing different types of feet shows many kinds of animals have explored. Birds, mammals, reptiles, and other creatures have all crossed these places, showing the variety of unknown explorers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The hottest desert / the deepest jungle / where none of us have ever been / all have been crossed / and crossed again / by wings whirring or silent / feet furred or scaled / hoofed or bare\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q017","read_aloud":"What does the poet mean by \"A map, a dream can take me there\"? A. You need both a real map and imagination to explore the world. B. You only need money to travel. C. You cannot travel without a plane. D. Dreams are not useful for anything.","excerpt":"\"I can trace each / graceful line ... / Close my eyes / and in my mind / I can travel / anywhere ... / A map, a dream / can take me there!\"","stem":"What does the poet mean by \"A map, a dream can take me there\"?","choices":{"A":"You need both a real map and imagination to explore the world.","B":"You only need money to travel.","C":"You cannot travel without a plane.","D":"Dreams are not useful for anything."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poet says a map and a dream together can take her anywhere. This means you need both knowledge (the map) and imagination (the dream) to explore and learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I can trace each / graceful line ... / Close my eyes / and in my mind / I can travel / anywhere ... / A map, a dream / can take me there!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q018","read_aloud":"If you had a map of a place you have never visited, what could you learn from it? Use ideas from the poem. A. Nothing, because maps are useless. B. You could learn about the geography and imagine what it would be like to visit. C. You could only learn the weather. D. You could learn how to cook food from that place.","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\"","stem":"If you had a map of a place you have never visited, what could you learn from it? Use ideas from the poem.","choices":{"A":"Nothing, because maps are useless.","B":"You could learn about the geography and imagine what it would be like to visit.","C":"You could only learn the weather.","D":"You could learn how to cook food from that place."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem says maps are keys to secret places and new worlds. A map can teach you about geography and help you imagine visiting, just like the speaker in the poems uses maps to explore.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q020","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of,\" showing the stars were his navigation tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Map lines cross over each other like lace patterns. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping, which fits this image.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. playing a game with friends B. studying a map to learn about the world C. writing a letter to a pen pal D. planning a birthday party","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"playing a game with friends","B":"studying a map to learn about the world","C":"writing a letter to a pen pal","D":"planning a birthday party"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker lists actions like \"memorizing\" and \"tracing\" places on a map. This shows they are studying to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l09-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Humans are always the first to explore any place B. Animals have explored many places before humans arrived C. Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing D. Only places with mountains are worth exploring","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Humans are always the first to explore any place","B":"Animals have explored many places before humans arrived","C":"Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing","D":"Only places with mountains are worth exploring"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states penguins \"laid shambling tracks\" before humans came to Antarctica. This shows animals explored first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q001","read_aloud":": Which word means almost the same as \"intersecting\" as used in the poem? Options: A. crossing B. fading C. drawing D. ignoring","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs...\"","stem":": Which word means almost the same as \"intersecting\" as used in the poem? Options:","choices":{"A":"crossing","B":"fading","C":"drawing","D":"ignoring"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"When lines on a map cross or overlap, they are intersecting.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q002","read_aloud":": What can you infer about the \"explorers\" mentioned in the poem? Options: A. They are only humans. B. Animals are also explorers of the earth. C. They only travel in the desert. D. They are not very smart.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica... penguins already laid shambling tracks\"","stem":": What can you infer about the \"explorers\" mentioned in the poem? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are only humans.","B":"Animals are also explorers of the earth.","C":"They only travel in the desert.","D":"They are not very smart."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poem describes penguins making tracks in Antarctica, suggesting they traveled there before humans.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica... penguins already laid shambling tracks\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q003","read_aloud":": Why does the poet say these explorers will \"never tell us\" what they have seen? Options: A. They cannot speak our language. B. They have forgotten. C. They are probably animals. D. They are hiding on purpose.","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\"","stem":": Why does the poet say these explorers will \"never tell us\" what they have seen? Options:","choices":{"A":"They cannot speak our language.","B":"They have forgotten.","C":"They are probably animals.","D":"They are hiding on purpose."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text previously lists \"feet furred or scaled,\" which refers to animals, not humans who can talk.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q004","read_aloud":": Do you agree with the author that no place is \"undiscovered\"? Why? Options: A. Yes, because animals go everywhere. B. No, because we have maps for everything. C. Yes, because humans have been to every single inch. D. No, because Antarctica is too cold.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered... all have been crossed / and crossed again\"","stem":": Do you agree with the author that no place is \"undiscovered\"? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"Yes, because animals go everywhere.","B":"No, because we have maps for everything.","C":"Yes, because humans have been to every single inch.","D":"No, because Antarctica is too cold."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poem provides evidence that even remote places have been visited by animals like penguins, supporting the idea that \"undiscovered\" is a human perspective.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered... all have been crossed / and crossed again\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q005","read_aloud":": If you were to create a map of your own \"secret place,\" what would you include? Options: A. Only places I have been to before. B. Just the places my friends live. C. Imaginary places and hidden treasures. D. A list of all my chores.","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\"","stem":": If you were to create a map of your own \"secret place,\" what would you include? Options:","choices":{"A":"Only places I have been to before.","B":"Just the places my friends live.","C":"Imaginary places and hidden treasures.","D":"A list of all my chores."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem describes maps as keys to \"secret places\" and \"vast new worlds,\" suggesting that maps can represent imagination.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys / to secret places / vast new worlds / and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"intersecting\" work on both a literal and figurative level in this poem? A. It only describes how map lines cross on paper B. It describes both crossing lines on a map and how dreams, places, and people connect in our lives C. It only refers to the artist\u0027s technique for drawing lace D. It suggests maps are confusing and should be avoided","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"How does the word \"intersecting\" work on both a literal and figurative level in this poem?","choices":{"A":"It only describes how map lines cross on paper","B":"It describes both crossing lines on a map and how dreams, places, and people connect in our lives","C":"It only refers to the artist\u0027s technique for drawing lace","D":"It suggests maps are confusing and should be avoided"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Literally, map lines intersect. Figuratively, \"intersecting\" suggests how our dreams, travels, and relationships overlap and connect, enriching the poem\u0027s theme of discovery.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q007","read_aloud":"Excerpt from beginning of \"Learning the World\": \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. Excerpt from end of \"Early Explorers\": \"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen How do these excerpts frame the poetry collection\u0027s message about exploration? A. They show exploration is only about memorizing facts B. They show exploration begins with personal curiosity and extends to honoring all who explore, known and unknown C. They suggest exploration is only valuable if it is recorded in books D. They imply that modern exploration is less important than ancient journeys","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from beginning of \"Learning the World\": \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. Excerpt from end of \"Early Explorers\": \"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen How do these excerpts frame the poetry collection\u0027s message about exploration?","choices":{"A":"They show exploration is only about memorizing facts","B":"They show exploration begins with personal curiosity and extends to honoring all who explore, known and unknown","C":"They suggest exploration is only valuable if it is recorded in books","D":"They imply that modern exploration is less important than ancient journeys"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The first excerpt shows personal, active learning; the last honors unnamed explorers. Together, they frame exploration as a personal and collective human experience across time.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q008","read_aloud":"Why might the poets choose poetry, rather than informational text, to explore the theme of journeys? A. Because poetry is shorter and easier to write than reports B. Because poetry\u0027s sound, imagery, and figurative language can express the emotions, imagination, and wonder of exploration in powerful, memorable ways C. Because poetry cannot include facts, so it is better for fantasy D. Because the poets did not know how to write informational texts","excerpt":"The collection uses rhyme, rhythm, metaphor, and vivid imagery across four poems about maps, dreams, and explorers.","stem":"Why might the poets choose poetry, rather than informational text, to explore the theme of journeys?","choices":{"A":"Because poetry is shorter and easier to write than reports","B":"Because poetry\u0027s sound, imagery, and figurative language can express the emotions, imagination, and wonder of exploration in powerful, memorable ways","C":"Because poetry cannot include facts, so it is better for fantasy","D":"Because the poets did not know how to write informational texts"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Poetry uses rhyme, rhythm, and metaphor to evoke feelings and images. These tools help express the excitement, curiosity, and unity of exploration in ways that engage readers emotionally.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The collection uses rhyme, rhythm, metaphor, and vivid imagery across four poems about maps, dreams, and explorers."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q009","read_aloud":"Which word means \"crossing or overlapping\"? A. Peering B. Traversed C. Intersecting D. Girth","excerpt":"The preview vocabulary includes \"girth,\" \"intersecting,\" \"traversed,\" \"peering,\" \"via.\"","stem":"Which word means \"crossing or overlapping\"?","choices":{"A":"Peering","B":"Traversed","C":"Intersecting","D":"Girth"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Intersecting means crossing or overlapping, like lines on a map.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The preview vocabulary includes \"girth,\" \"intersecting,\" \"traversed,\" \"peering,\" \"via.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q010","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"A Map and a Dream\": \"I can travel anywhere . . . A map, a dream can take me there! What does the exclamation mark at the end show about the speaker\u0027s feelings? A. Boredom B. Excitement and joy C. Sadness D. Fear","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"A Map and a Dream\": \"I can travel anywhere . . . A map, a dream can take me there! What does the exclamation mark at the end show about the speaker\u0027s feelings?","choices":{"A":"Boredom","B":"Excitement and joy","C":"Sadness","D":"Fear"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An exclamation mark often shows strong, positive emotion like excitement.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q011","read_aloud":"If you could write a letter to the author of \"Early Explorers,\" what question would you ask about the poem? A. What is your favorite color? B. Why did you choose to include animals as explorers? C. How old are you? D. Do you like pizza?","excerpt":"The whole collection.","stem":"If you could write a letter to the author of \"Early Explorers,\" what question would you ask about the poem?","choices":{"A":"What is your favorite color?","B":"Why did you choose to include animals as explorers?","C":"How old are you?","D":"Do you like pizza?"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This question asks about the poet\u0027s choice, which is thoughtful and connected to the poem\u0027s meaning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole collection."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q012","read_aloud":"Why does the poet say maps are \"more than\" just lines and dots? A. Because the poet thinks maps are too simple. B. Because maps represent possibilities for discovery, travel, and imagination. C. Because maps are too expensive. D. Because maps are only for tourists.","excerpt":"\"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs ... / More than names / and colored dots, / rivers, mountains, / tourist spots.\"","stem":"Why does the poet say maps are \"more than\" just lines and dots?","choices":{"A":"Because the poet thinks maps are too simple.","B":"Because maps represent possibilities for discovery, travel, and imagination.","C":"Because maps are too expensive.","D":"Because maps are only for tourists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet says maps are keys to secret places and new worlds. They are more than just lines because they represent possibilities for discovery, travel, and imagination.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs ... / More than names / and colored dots, / rivers, mountains, / tourist spots.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q013","read_aloud":"What message is the poet trying to share about exploration? A. Only humans can be explorers. B. Exploration is something that happens naturally, and animals are explorers too. C. We should stop exploring. D. Antarctica is the only place with animals.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice / penguins already laid shambling tracks / in the snow / before we traveled there\"","stem":"What message is the poet trying to share about exploration?","choices":{"A":"Only humans can be explorers.","B":"Exploration is something that happens naturally, and animals are explorers too.","C":"We should stop exploring.","D":"Antarctica is the only place with animals."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet says no place is undiscovered because animals have already been there. This message shows that exploration is natural and animals are explorers too, not just humans.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice / penguins already laid shambling tracks / in the snow / before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q014","read_aloud":"How do the poets in \"Latitude Longitude Dreams\" honor famous explorers? A. By making fun of them. B. By describing their brave journeys and showing how they followed their dreams. C. By saying they were lazy. D. By ignoring their achievements.","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays. / Columbus sailed on over the edge / Discovering lands and dreams. / They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":"How do the poets in \"Latitude Longitude Dreams\" honor famous explorers?","choices":{"A":"By making fun of them.","B":"By describing their brave journeys and showing how they followed their dreams.","C":"By saying they were lazy.","D":"By ignoring their achievements."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poets describe Magellan and Columbus as brave dreamers who voyaged over oceans. Words like \"discovering lands and dreams\" and \"traversed their dreams\" honor their courage and achievements.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays. / Columbus sailed on over the edge / Discovering lands and dreams. / They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q015","read_aloud":"How does the structure of \"Learning the World\" help create rhythm? A. The lines are all different lengths with no pattern. B. The poet uses repeating patterns of three lines with similar structure, creating a rhythmic beat. C. The poem has no rhythm at all. D. The poem uses only one-syllable words.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges. / I\u0027m memorizing capitals, / tracing countries, / learning crops and industries. / I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\"","stem":"How does the structure of \"Learning the World\" help create rhythm?","choices":{"A":"The lines are all different lengths with no pattern.","B":"The poet uses repeating patterns of three lines with similar structure, creating a rhythmic beat.","C":"The poem has no rhythm at all.","D":"The poem uses only one-syllable words."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet repeats the pattern of three lines: \"I\u0027m [verb]ing [noun], / [verb]ing [noun], / [verb]ing [noun].\" This repeating structure creates a rhythmic beat that sounds like the speaker is listing things they are learning.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges. / I\u0027m memorizing capitals, / tracing countries, / learning crops and industries. / I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q016","read_aloud":"The author titled this collection \"Poetry Collection\" with the theme \"Journeys.\" Why do you think the poets chose to write about maps, explorers, and dreams together? Use clues from the texts. A. Because they all wanted to write about cooking. B. Because maps, explorers, and dreams all connect to the idea of journeying and discovering the world. C. Because they were asked to write about animals. D. Because they do not like to travel.","excerpt":"\"All four poems in the collection are about journeys, exploration, and discovering the world.\"","stem":"The author titled this collection \"Poetry Collection\" with the theme \"Journeys.\" Why do you think the poets chose to write about maps, explorers, and dreams together? Use clues from the texts.","choices":{"A":"Because they all wanted to write about cooking.","B":"Because maps, explorers, and dreams all connect to the idea of journeying and discovering the world.","C":"Because they were asked to write about animals.","D":"Because they do not like to travel."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"All four poems connect to journeys. \"Learning the World\" uses a map to imagine travel. \"Latitude Longitude Dreams\" celebrates explorers. \"A Map and a Dream\" shows how maps unlock imagination. \"Early Explorers\" shows that exploration is natural. Together, they show different ways of journeying and discovering.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"All four poems in the collection are about journeys, exploration, and discovering the world.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q017","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q018","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q019","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of,\" showing the stars were his navigation tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Map lines cross over each other like lace patterns. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping, which fits this image.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. playing a game with friends B. studying a map to learn about the world C. writing a letter to a pen pal D. planning a birthday party","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"playing a game with friends","B":"studying a map to learn about the world","C":"writing a letter to a pen pal","D":"planning a birthday party"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker lists actions like \"memorizing\" and \"tracing\" places on a map. This shows they are studying to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Humans are always the first to explore any place B. Animals have explored many places before humans arrived C. Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing D. Only places with mountains are worth exploring","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Humans are always the first to explore any place","B":"Animals have explored many places before humans arrived","C":"Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing","D":"Only places with mountains are worth exploring"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states penguins \"laid shambling tracks\" before humans came to Antarctica. This shows animals explored first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. It suggests Earth is only a place to live, not to explore B. It suggests we all share Earth and must care for it together like a crew on a ship C. It suggests Earth is too big for people to understand D. It suggests only sailors should care about Earth","excerpt":"\"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"It suggests Earth is only a place to live, not to explore","B":"It suggests we all share Earth and must care for it together like a crew on a ship","C":"It suggests Earth is too big for people to understand","D":"It suggests only sailors should care about Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparing Earth to \"our ship\" suggests we are all traveling together. This emphasizes shared responsibility for our planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-l10-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. only their own street and neighborhood B. the whole world as if from above C. a picture of their house on a map D. a list of countries and capitals","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"only their own street and neighborhood","B":"the whole world as if from above","C":"a picture of their house on a map","D":"a list of countries and capitals"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states the speaker wishes to \"see the whole world spread beneath my feet,\" which matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q001","read_aloud":": In this context, what does \"traversed\" mean? Options: A. ran away from B. traveled through C. forgot about D. hid under","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":": In this context, what does \"traversed\" mean? Options:","choices":{"A":"ran away from","B":"traveled through","C":"forgot about","D":"hid under"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To traverse a dream or a land means to move across or travel through it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q002","read_aloud":": Based on the text, what is the \"girth\" of the earth? Options: A. its color B. its distance around C. its cold temperature D. its mountain height","excerpt":"\"Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe\"","stem":": Based on the text, what is the \"girth\" of the earth? Options:","choices":{"A":"its color","B":"its distance around","C":"its cold temperature","D":"its mountain height"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Girth means the distance around something; here, it refers to the circumference of the planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q003","read_aloud":": If someone moves \"via\" the stars, how are they moving? Options: A. by way of the stars B. ignoring the stars C. faster than stars D. looking for stars","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":": If someone moves \"via\" the stars, how are they moving? Options:","choices":{"A":"by way of the stars","B":"ignoring the stars","C":"faster than stars","D":"looking for stars"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Via\" means by way of or through the use of something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars / Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q004","read_aloud":": What is a main theme shared by all the poems in this collection? Options: A. Maps are better than books. B. Exploration and the spirit of discovery. C. Animals are the best explorers. D. Learning how to draw lines.","excerpt":"","stem":": What is a main theme shared by all the poems in this collection? Options:","choices":{"A":"Maps are better than books.","B":"Exploration and the spirit of discovery.","C":"Animals are the best explorers.","D":"Learning how to draw lines."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"All the poems focus on the excitement of travel, discovery, and exploring the world.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q005","read_aloud":": How is \"Learning the World\" different from \"Early Explorers\"? Options: A. One is about a map, the other is about animals exploring. B. Both are about the exact same explorers. C. One is about the moon, the other is about Mars. D. One is very short, the other is a book.","excerpt":"","stem":": How is \"Learning the World\" different from \"Early Explorers\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"One is about a map, the other is about animals exploring.","B":"Both are about the exact same explorers.","C":"One is about the moon, the other is about Mars.","D":"One is very short, the other is a book."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Learning the World\" focuses on a speaker using a map to learn, while \"Early Explorers\" focuses on animals traveling in nature.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q006","read_aloud":": How does the poet use rhyme in these poems? Options: A. To make the words sound serious. B. To create a musical rhythm for the reader. C. To make the poem harder to read. D. To tell the reader to stop reading.","excerpt":"","stem":": How does the poet use rhyme in these poems? Options:","choices":{"A":"To make the words sound serious.","B":"To create a musical rhythm for the reader.","C":"To make the poem harder to read.","D":"To tell the reader to stop reading."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rhyming creates a pattern of sounds that adds rhythm and makes poetry more enjoyable to read aloud.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q007","read_aloud":": Why do the poets in this collection compare maps to \"keys\"? Options: A. They open doors to rooms. B. They help us find hidden treasure. C. They unlock our imagination and new ideas. D. They are made of metal.","excerpt":"","stem":": Why do the poets in this collection compare maps to \"keys\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"They open doors to rooms.","B":"They help us find hidden treasure.","C":"They unlock our imagination and new ideas.","D":"They are made of metal."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poems suggest that maps help us visualize places we have never been, acting like a key to our imagination.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q008","read_aloud":": How does the structure of the lines in \"Early Explorers\" help the poem? Options: A. It makes the poem look like a long story. B. It creates a sense of movement or rhythm. C. It makes the poem easier to copy. D. It hides the meaning of the poem.","excerpt":"","stem":": How does the structure of the lines in \"Early Explorers\" help the poem? Options:","choices":{"A":"It makes the poem look like a long story.","B":"It creates a sense of movement or rhythm.","C":"It makes the poem easier to copy.","D":"It hides the meaning of the poem."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Line breaks and rhythm help the reader \"feel\" the movement of the explorers being described.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q009","read_aloud":": How does the use of metaphors like \"earth with invisible designs\" help the reader? Options: A. It makes the earth sound like a puzzle. B. It shows that the earth is empty. C. It helps us see the imaginary lines of latitude and longitude. D. It proves that maps are wrong.","excerpt":"","stem":": How does the use of metaphors like \"earth with invisible designs\" help the reader? Options:","choices":{"A":"It makes the earth sound like a puzzle.","B":"It shows that the earth is empty.","C":"It helps us see the imaginary lines of latitude and longitude.","D":"It proves that maps are wrong."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"Metaphors compare things to help us visualize abstract ideas, like the lines of latitude and longitude on a globe.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q010","read_aloud":": Which poem do you think best inspires a reader to go on their own journey, and why? Options: A. \"Learning the World,\" because it shows how one map can lead to dreaming. B. \"Early Explorers,\" because it lists all the animals. C. \"A Map and a Dream,\" because it is about tourist spots. D. \"Latitude Longitude Dreams,\" because it is about ships.","excerpt":"","stem":": Which poem do you think best inspires a reader to go on their own journey, and why? Options:","choices":{"A":"\"Learning the World,\" because it shows how one map can lead to dreaming.","B":"\"Early Explorers,\" because it lists all the animals.","C":"\"A Map and a Dream,\" because it is about tourist spots.","D":"\"Latitude Longitude Dreams,\" because it is about ships."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Learning the World\" focuses on the personal desire to see the world, which is a strong inspiration for a reader to explore. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Poetry Collection\" Authors: Kristine O\u0027Connell George; Drew Lamm and James Hildreth; Karen O\u0027Donnell Taylor; Marilyn Singer Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 4, Savvas Learning Company LLC","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"peering\" mean in this context? A. looking closely at something hard to see B. shouting to call for help C. running quickly across a field D. drawing a picture with bright colors","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope...\"","stem":"What does \"peering\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"looking closely at something hard to see","B":"shouting to call for help","C":"running quickly across a field","D":"drawing a picture with bright colors"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker rolls a map and looks through it like a telescope. \"Peering\" means looking closely, which matches the action described.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q012","read_aloud":"What does \"via\" mean here? A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"What does \"via\" mean here?","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of,\" showing the stars were his navigation tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q013","read_aloud":"What does \"intersecting\" mean in this excerpt? A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"What does \"intersecting\" mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Map lines cross over each other like lace patterns. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping, which fits this image.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q014","read_aloud":"What is the speaker doing in this excerpt? A. playing a game with friends B. studying a map to learn about the world C. writing a letter to a pen pal D. planning a birthday party","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"What is the speaker doing in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"playing a game with friends","B":"studying a map to learn about the world","C":"writing a letter to a pen pal","D":"planning a birthday party"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker lists actions like \"memorizing\" and \"tracing\" places on a map. This shows they are studying to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q015","read_aloud":"What main idea does this excerpt support? A. Humans are always the first to explore any place B. Animals have explored many places before humans arrived C. Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing D. Only places with mountains are worth exploring","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\"","stem":"What main idea does this excerpt support?","choices":{"A":"Humans are always the first to explore any place","B":"Animals have explored many places before humans arrived","C":"Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing","D":"Only places with mountains are worth exploring"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states penguins \"laid shambling tracks\" before humans came to Antarctica. This shows animals explored first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q016","read_aloud":"What is the effect of this metaphor? A. It suggests Earth is only a place to live, not to explore B. It suggests we all share Earth and must care for it together like a crew on a ship C. It suggests Earth is too big for people to understand D. It suggests only sailors should care about Earth","excerpt":"\"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"What is the effect of this metaphor?","choices":{"A":"It suggests Earth is only a place to live, not to explore","B":"It suggests we all share Earth and must care for it together like a crew on a ship","C":"It suggests Earth is too big for people to understand","D":"It suggests only sailors should care about Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparing Earth to \"our ship\" suggests we are all traveling together. This emphasizes shared responsibility for our planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q017","read_aloud":"What does the speaker wish to see? A. only their own street and neighborhood B. the whole world as if from above C. a picture of their house on a map D. a list of countries and capitals","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"What does the speaker wish to see?","choices":{"A":"only their own street and neighborhood","B":"the whole world as if from above","C":"a picture of their house on a map","D":"a list of countries and capitals"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states the speaker wishes to \"see the whole world spread beneath my feet,\" which matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q018","read_aloud":"What does this excerpt suggest about the history of exploration? A. All explorers wrote detailed records of their journeys B. Many explorers\u0027 stories and discoveries were never recorded or shared C. Only modern explorers are worth remembering D. Exploration only happened in the last 100 years","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen\"","stem":"What does this excerpt suggest about the history of exploration?","choices":{"A":"All explorers wrote detailed records of their journeys","B":"Many explorers\u0027 stories and discoveries were never recorded or shared","C":"Only modern explorers are worth remembering","D":"Exploration only happened in the last 100 years"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt mentions \"adventurers we will never know\" who \"will never tell us\" their wonders. This implies many explorers\u0027 stories were lost.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q019","read_aloud":"Based on the entire collection, is this statement about maps supported by the poems? Why or why not? A. No, because the poems say maps are only for finding tourist spots B. Yes, because the poems show maps spark imagination, learning, and connection to people and places C. No, because the poems argue that digital maps are better than paper maps D. Yes, but only because the poems are very short","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\"","stem":"Based on the entire collection, is this statement about maps supported by the poems? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"No, because the poems say maps are only for finding tourist spots","B":"Yes, because the poems show maps spark imagination, learning, and connection to people and places","C":"No, because the poems argue that digital maps are better than paper maps","D":"Yes, but only because the poems are very short"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poems show maps helping speakers imagine travel (\"I can travel anywhere\") and connect to \"unknown faces.\" This supports the idea that maps unlock discovery.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q020","read_aloud":"Why is the speaker peering through the rolled map? A. To clean the map B. To pretend it is a telescope and see faraway places C. To read small words D. To hide her face","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end.\"","stem":"Why is the speaker peering through the rolled map?","choices":{"A":"To clean the map","B":"To pretend it is a telescope and see faraway places","C":"To read small words","D":"To hide her face"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker wishes it were a telescope so she could see past her street.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q021","read_aloud":"What do map lines do when they intersect? A. They run parallel without touching. B. They cross each other. C. They disappear. D. They change color.","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs.\"","stem":"What do map lines do when they intersect?","choices":{"A":"They run parallel without touching.","B":"They cross each other.","C":"They disappear.","D":"They change color."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Intersecting lines cross each other.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q022","read_aloud":"If a place has been \"traversed,\" it has been ______. A. hidden B. traveled across C. destroyed D. drawn","excerpt":"\"all have been crossed and crossed again.\"","stem":"If a place has been \"traversed,\" it has been ______.","choices":{"A":"hidden","B":"traveled across","C":"destroyed","D":"drawn"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Traversed means crossed or traveled across.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"all have been crossed and crossed again.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q023","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of \"Learning the World\"? A. The speaker hates geography. B. The speaker uses a map to imagine seeing the whole world. C. The speaker wants to throw away the map. D. The speaker is lost.","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. … wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of \"Learning the World\"?","choices":{"A":"The speaker hates geography.","B":"The speaker uses a map to imagine seeing the whole world.","C":"The speaker wants to throw away the map.","D":"The speaker is lost."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker studies the map and wishes to see the real world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. … wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q024","read_aloud":"What animal left tracks in Antarctica? A. Seals B. Polar bears C. Penguins D. Whales","excerpt":"\"penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there.\"","stem":"What animal left tracks in Antarctica?","choices":{"A":"Seals","B":"Polar bears","C":"Penguins","D":"Whales"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The poem specifically names penguins.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q025","read_aloud":"Excerpt from \"Learning the World\" and \"A Map and a Dream. How do both poems use maps similarly? A. Both speakers want to burn the maps. B. Both speakers use maps to imagine or learn about faraway places. C. Both speakers have traveled everywhere. D. Both speakers are lost.","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from \"Learning the World\" and \"A Map and a Dream. How do both poems use maps similarly?","choices":{"A":"Both speakers want to burn the maps.","B":"Both speakers use maps to imagine or learn about faraway places.","C":"Both speakers have traveled everywhere.","D":"Both speakers are lost."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"In both poems, maps help the speakers imagine travel and discovery.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q026","read_aloud":"Do you think dreaming about a place is as good as actually going there? Why or why not? A. Yes, because dreams are free. B. No, because real travel lets you see, hear, and feel things directly. C. Yes, because dreams are more fun. D. No, because dreaming is boring.","excerpt":"\"A map, a dream can take me there!\"","stem":"Do you think dreaming about a place is as good as actually going there? Why or why not?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because dreams are free.","B":"No, because real travel lets you see, hear, and feel things directly.","C":"Yes, because dreams are more fun.","D":"No, because dreaming is boring."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Real travel uses all your senses, while imagination is only in your mind. Both have value, but they are different.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"A map, a dream can take me there!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q027","read_aloud":"Imagine you are the speaker in \"A Map and a Dream.\" You find a new map of Mars. What would you do with it? A. Throw it away because it is not Earth. B. Trace the lines and dream about exploring Mars. C. Use it as a tablecloth. D. Give it to a friend.","excerpt":"The whole collection.","stem":"Imagine you are the speaker in \"A Map and a Dream.\" You find a new map of Mars. What would you do with it?","choices":{"A":"Throw it away because it is not Earth.","B":"Trace the lines and dream about exploring Mars.","C":"Use it as a tablecloth.","D":"Give it to a friend."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker loves to trace maps and dream about travel, so a Mars map would inspire space exploration dreams. Section A - Text information Title: Poetry Collection Author: Various Authors (Kristine O\u0027Connell George, Drew Lamm, James Hildreth, Karen O\u0027Donnell Taylor, Marilyn Singer)","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole collection."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q028","read_aloud":"What does \"peering\" mean in this poem? A. looking closely through something B. sleeping quietly C. running fast D. singing loudly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\"","stem":"What does \"peering\" mean in this poem?","choices":{"A":"looking closely through something","B":"sleeping quietly","C":"running fast","D":"singing loudly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The speaker rolls the map into a tube and looks through it like a telescope. \"Peering\" means looking closely through something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, / rolling it into a tube, / peering through one end, / wishing it were a telescope\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q029","read_aloud":"What does \"traversed\" mean? A. traveled through; moved across B. stopped moving C. slept peacefully D. ate quickly","excerpt":"\"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\"","stem":"What does \"traversed\" mean?","choices":{"A":"traveled through; moved across","B":"stopped moving","C":"slept peacefully","D":"ate quickly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The explorers traversed their dreams while voyaging over oceans. \"Traversed\" means traveled through or moved across.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"They traversed their dreams, set their course / Voyaging over oceans and seas.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q030","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of these lines? A. Maps are only lines and dots. B. Maps are more than just lines and dots; they are special and meaningful. C. Maps are not useful. D. Maps are only for tourists.","excerpt":"\"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs ... / More than names / and colored dots, / rivers, mountains, / tourist spots.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of these lines?","choices":{"A":"Maps are only lines and dots.","B":"Maps are more than just lines and dots; they are special and meaningful.","C":"Maps are not useful.","D":"Maps are only for tourists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet says maps are MORE than tiny lines and dots. The main idea is that maps have deeper meaning beyond just their physical appearance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more / than tiny lines / intersecting / lace designs ... / More than names / and colored dots, / rivers, mountains, / tourist spots.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q031","read_aloud":"What does the speaker do first? A. learns crops and industries B. memorizes oceans C. traces countries D. learns mountain ranges","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges. / I\u0027m memorizing capitals, / tracing countries, / learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"What does the speaker do first?","choices":{"A":"learns crops and industries","B":"memorizes oceans","C":"traces countries","D":"learns mountain ranges"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The first line says the speaker is memorizing oceans. This is the first thing the speaker does in the poem.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, / tracing rivers, / learning mountain ranges. / I\u0027m memorizing capitals, / tracing countries, / learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q032","read_aloud":"What can you infer about the speaker\u0027s life? A. The speaker lives in a very busy city. B. The speaker wants to explore beyond their small, everyday world. C. The speaker has already traveled everywhere. D. The speaker does not like maps.","excerpt":"\"wishing it were a telescope, / wishing I could see past my street\"","stem":"What can you infer about the speaker\u0027s life?","choices":{"A":"The speaker lives in a very busy city.","B":"The speaker wants to explore beyond their small, everyday world.","C":"The speaker has already traveled everywhere.","D":"The speaker does not like maps."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker wishes to see past their street. This shows they want to explore beyond their small, everyday world and see more of the earth.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing it were a telescope, / wishing I could see past my street\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q033","read_aloud":"Why is no place on earth ever undiscovered? A. Because penguins and other animals have already been there. B. Because humans have built houses everywhere. C. Because the earth is very small. D. Because no one likes to explore.","excerpt":"\"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice / penguins already laid shambling tracks / in the snow / before we traveled there\"","stem":"Why is no place on earth ever undiscovered?","choices":{"A":"Because penguins and other animals have already been there.","B":"Because humans have built houses everywhere.","C":"Because the earth is very small.","D":"Because no one likes to explore."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The poem says even in Antarctica, penguins have already laid tracks in the snow. Animals have explored places before humans, so no place is truly undiscovered.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth / is ever undiscovered / Even in Antarctica / where whole mountains are hidden / under ice / penguins already laid shambling tracks / in the snow / before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q034","read_aloud":"Why does the poet call the earth \"our ship\"? A. Because the earth is made of wood. B. Because the earth carries us through space like a ship carries people through water. C. Because the earth is very small. D. Because the earth has sails.","excerpt":"\"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe / Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"Why does the poet call the earth \"our ship\"?","choices":{"A":"Because the earth is made of wood.","B":"Because the earth carries us through space like a ship carries people through water.","C":"Because the earth is very small.","D":"Because the earth has sails."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet uses a metaphor. The earth is compared to a ship because it carries all of us through space, just like a ship carries people across the ocean.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"These lines that slide from pole to pole / Wrapping around the watery girth / Coordinate all of us on this globe / Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q035","read_aloud":"Who are these \"adventurers we will never know\"? A. famous human explorers like Magellan B. animals that have explored places but cannot tell us what they saw C. people from the future D. characters in a book","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\"","stem":"Who are these \"adventurers we will never know\"?","choices":{"A":"famous human explorers like Magellan","B":"animals that have explored places but cannot tell us what they saw","C":"people from the future","D":"characters in a book"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poet says these adventurers will never tell us what they saw. Animals cannot speak or write, so they are explorers we will never truly know.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know / explorers who will never tell us / what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q036","read_aloud":"The author titled this collection \"Poetry Collection\" with the theme \"Journeys.\" Why do you think the poets chose to write about maps, explorers, and dreams together? Use clues from the texts. A. Because they all wanted to write about cooking. B. Because maps, explorers, and dreams all connect to the idea of journeying and discovering the world. C. Because they were asked to write about animals. D. Because they do not like to travel.","excerpt":"\"All four poems in the collection are about journeys, exploration, and discovering the world.\"","stem":"The author titled this collection \"Poetry Collection\" with the theme \"Journeys.\" Why do you think the poets chose to write about maps, explorers, and dreams together? Use clues from the texts.","choices":{"A":"Because they all wanted to write about cooking.","B":"Because maps, explorers, and dreams all connect to the idea of journeying and discovering the world.","C":"Because they were asked to write about animals.","D":"Because they do not like to travel."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"All four poems connect to journeys. \"Learning the World\" uses a map to imagine travel. \"Latitude Longitude Dreams\" celebrates explorers. \"A Map and a Dream\" shows how maps unlock imagination. \"Early Explorers\" shows that exploration is natural. Together, they show different ways of journeying and discovering.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"All four poems in the collection are about journeys, exploration, and discovering the world.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q037","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q038","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q039","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. looking closely B. walking fast C. throwing away D. sleeping soundly","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"looking closely","B":"walking fast","C":"throwing away","D":"sleeping soundly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The context of looking through a rolled-up map shows that the speaker is looking closely at something.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q040","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. by way of; using something as a guide B. against; fighting with something C. without; ignoring something D. after; following something later","excerpt":"\"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"by way of; using something as a guide","B":"against; fighting with something","C":"without; ignoring something","D":"after; following something later"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Magellan used stars to guide his ship. \"Via\" means \"by way of,\" showing the stars were his navigation tool.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Magellan moved via stars Steered his ship by celestial rays.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. crossing or overlapping each other B. disappearing or fading away C. stretching in one straight direction D. coloring in bright, bold patterns","excerpt":"\"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"crossing or overlapping each other","B":"disappearing or fading away","C":"stretching in one straight direction","D":"coloring in bright, bold patterns"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Map lines cross over each other like lace patterns. \"Intersecting\" means crossing or overlapping, which fits this image.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are more than tiny lines intersecting lace designs...\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q042","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. playing a game with friends B. studying a map to learn about the world C. writing a letter to a pen pal D. planning a birthday party","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"playing a game with friends","B":"studying a map to learn about the world","C":"writing a letter to a pen pal","D":"planning a birthday party"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker lists actions like \"memorizing\" and \"tracing\" places on a map. This shows they are studying to learn about the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q043","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. Humans are always the first to explore any place B. Animals have explored many places before humans arrived C. Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing D. Only places with mountains are worth exploring","excerpt":"\"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"Humans are always the first to explore any place","B":"Animals have explored many places before humans arrived","C":"Antarctica cannot be explored by any living thing","D":"Only places with mountains are worth exploring"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states penguins \"laid shambling tracks\" before humans came to Antarctica. This shows animals explored first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No place on earth is ever undiscovered Even in Antarctica where whole mountains are hidden under ice penguins already laid shambling tracks in the snow before we traveled there\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q044","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. It suggests Earth is only a place to live, not to explore B. It suggests we all share Earth and must care for it together like a crew on a ship C. It suggests Earth is too big for people to understand D. It suggests only sailors should care about Earth","excerpt":"\"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"It suggests Earth is only a place to live, not to explore","B":"It suggests we all share Earth and must care for it together like a crew on a ship","C":"It suggests Earth is too big for people to understand","D":"It suggests only sailors should care about Earth"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparing Earth to \"our ship\" suggests we are all traveling together. This emphasizes shared responsibility for our planet.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Our home, our ship, our planet earth.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q045","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. only their own street and neighborhood B. the whole world as if from above C. a picture of their house on a map D. a list of countries and capitals","excerpt":"\"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"only their own street and neighborhood","B":"the whole world as if from above","C":"a picture of their house on a map","D":"a list of countries and capitals"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states the speaker wishes to \"see the whole world spread beneath my feet,\" which matches option b.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"wishing I could see past my street, wishing I could see the whole world spread beneath my feet.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q046","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. All explorers wrote detailed records of their journeys B. Many explorers\u0027 stories and discoveries were never recorded or shared C. Only modern explorers are worth remembering D. Exploration only happened in the last 100 years","excerpt":"\"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"All explorers wrote detailed records of their journeys","B":"Many explorers\u0027 stories and discoveries were never recorded or shared","C":"Only modern explorers are worth remembering","D":"Exploration only happened in the last 100 years"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt mentions \"adventurers we will never know\" who \"will never tell us\" their wonders. This implies many explorers\u0027 stories were lost.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"By adventurers we will never know explorers who will never tell us what wonders they have seen\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q047","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. No, because the poems say maps are only for finding tourist spots B. Yes, because the poems show maps spark imagination, learning, and connection to people and places C. No, because the poems argue that digital maps are better than paper maps D. Yes, but only because the poems are very short","excerpt":"\"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"No, because the poems say maps are only for finding tourist spots","B":"Yes, because the poems show maps spark imagination, learning, and connection to people and places","C":"No, because the poems argue that digital maps are better than paper maps","D":"Yes, but only because the poems are very short"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The poems show maps helping speakers imagine travel (\"I can travel anywhere\") and connect to \"unknown faces.\" This supports the idea that maps unlock discovery.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Maps are keys to secret places vast new worlds and unknown faces.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q048","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. Closing your eyes tightly B. Looking closely at something hard to see C. Running away fast D. Drawing a picture","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"Closing your eyes tightly","B":"Looking closely at something hard to see","C":"Running away fast","D":"Drawing a picture"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Peering means looking closely, especially when something is hard to see.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q049","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. Drawing on it B. Memorizing and tracing places on it C. Folding it into a small square D. Giving it away","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"Drawing on it","B":"Memorizing and tracing places on it","C":"Folding it into a small square","D":"Giving it away"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker says she is memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, and learning about countries.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m memorizing oceans, tracing rivers, learning mountain ranges. I\u0027m memorizing capitals, tracing countries, learning crops and industries.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w4-poetry-collection-std-q050","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511. A. A new map B. To see beyond her street C. A bigger house D. To stop studying geography","excerpt":"\"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope, wishing I could see past my street.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 511.","choices":{"A":"A new map","B":"To see beyond her street","C":"A bigger house","D":"To stop studying geography"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The speaker wishes she could see past her street and the whole world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I\u0027m smoothing out this map, rolling it into a tube, peering through one end, wishing it were a telescope, wishing I could see past my street.\""}]}},{"selection_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys","grade":5,"curriculum":"myView Literacy","unit":1,"week":5,"title":"Picturesque Journeys","author":"Yanitzia Canetti","genre":"Informational Text","essential_question":"How can places and experiences inspire artists?","weekly_question":"How did journeys and life events influence famous painters?","reading_skill":"Selection Assessment","reading_strategy":"Use text evidence","vocabulary":["inspired","determined","easel","self-portrait","journey"],"text_policy":"This prototype uses short assessment excerpts and questions only. Students should read the full selection in their licensed myView Literacy textbook or classroom materials.","read_aloud":"Picturesque Journeys. How did journeys and life events influence famous painters?. Read the full selection in your textbook, then answer each question using text evidence.","assessment_levels":[{"level":1,"level_name":"Level 1","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q001","read_aloud":"What happened to Kahlo when she was six years old? Options: A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What happened to Kahlo when she was six years old? Options:","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q002","read_aloud":"Where did Kahlo paint when she was recovering from her accident? Options: A. In a studio B. In her bedroom C. In a garden D. At school","excerpt":"\"Her parents decided to give her a box of paints and an easel that she could use in bed. Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\"","stem":"Where did Kahlo paint when she was recovering from her accident? Options:","choices":{"A":"In a studio","B":"In her bedroom","C":"In a garden","D":"At school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says her parents gave her paints to use in bed, so she painted everything she saw in her bedroom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Her parents decided to give her a box of paints and an easel that she could use in bed. Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q003","read_aloud":"What did Kahlo paint most often because of the mirror in her room? Options: A. Pictures of her parents B. Pictures of her garden C. Pictures of herself D. Pictures of the sky","excerpt":"\"Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom. Painting became her daily habit. Because she had a huge mirror in front of her bed, she started to paint images of herself.\"","stem":"What did Kahlo paint most often because of the mirror in her room? Options:","choices":{"A":"Pictures of her parents","B":"Pictures of her garden","C":"Pictures of herself","D":"Pictures of the sky"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that because she had a mirror, she started to paint images of herself.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom. Painting became her daily habit. Because she had a huge mirror in front of her bed, she started to paint images of herself.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q004","read_aloud":"Why did Kahlo have to spend months resting in bed? Options: A. She was bored. B. She was seriously injured in a bus crash. C. She wanted to learn how to paint. D. She was traveling to a new place.","excerpt":"\"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering.\"","stem":"Why did Kahlo have to spend months resting in bed? Options:","choices":{"A":"She was bored.","B":"She was seriously injured in a bus crash.","C":"She wanted to learn how to paint.","D":"She was traveling to a new place."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that her need for rest was caused by being seriously injured in a bus crash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q005","read_aloud":"What does the word \"inspired\" most likely mean in this excerpt? A. caused something to be created; motivated artistic work B. made someone feel tired and sleepy C. confused someone about what to paint D. stopped someone from finishing their artwork","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\"","stem":"What does the word \"inspired\" most likely mean in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"caused something to be created; motivated artistic work","B":"made someone feel tired and sleepy","C":"confused someone about what to paint","D":"stopped someone from finishing their artwork"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows locations \"inspired\" painters \"to create their best works.\" This means the places motivated or caused the art to be made.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q006","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Frida Kahlo was born in Mexico with a diverse family background B. Frida Kahlo did not like her family members C. Mexico City is a very large and busy city D. Frida Kahlo\u0027s father was originally from Spain","excerpt":"\"Frida Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico. Her father was Hungarian, and her mother was of Spanish and Mexican Indian descent.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Frida Kahlo was born in Mexico with a diverse family background","B":"Frida Kahlo did not like her family members","C":"Mexico City is a very large and busy city","D":"Frida Kahlo\u0027s father was originally from Spain"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt tells us where Kahlo was born and about her parents\u0027 backgrounds. This shows her diverse heritage from different cultures.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Frida Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico. Her father was Hungarian, and her mother was of Spanish and Mexican Indian descent.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q007","read_aloud":"According to this excerpt, what did Kahlo do after getting polio? A. She stopped playing sports forever and stayed inside B. She continued to play sports and won swimming competitions C. She moved to a different country to get better care D. She became a painter right away instead of playing sports","excerpt":"\"When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other. However, this didn\u0027t slow her down. Kahlo still played sports, and she won several swimming competitions.\"","stem":"According to this excerpt, what did Kahlo do after getting polio?","choices":{"A":"She stopped playing sports forever and stayed inside","B":"She continued to play sports and won swimming competitions","C":"She moved to a different country to get better care","D":"She became a painter right away instead of playing sports"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says polio \"didn\u0027t slow her down\" and that Kahlo \"still played sports\" and \"won several swimming competitions.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other. However, this didn\u0027t slow her down. Kahlo still played sports, and she won several swimming competitions.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q008","read_aloud":"What happened to Kahlo when she was 18 years old? A. She got married to the painter Diego Rivera B. She was in a serious bus crash that injured her C. She moved to the United States to study art D. She painted her very first self-portrait painting","excerpt":"\"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering.\"","stem":"What happened to Kahlo when she was 18 years old?","choices":{"A":"She got married to the painter Diego Rivera","B":"She was in a serious bus crash that injured her","C":"She moved to the United States to study art","D":"She painted her very first self-portrait painting"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states that at age 18, Kahlo \"was in a bus crash and was seriously injured.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q009","read_aloud":"Why did Kahlo start painting while she was recovering? A. Because her parents gave her paints while she rested after her injury B. Because she wanted to become famous very quickly C. Because her teacher told her she had to paint every day D. Because she had nothing else to do at school that year","excerpt":"\"Kahlo became bored lying in bed, staring at the ceiling. Her parents decided to give her a box of paints and an easel that she could use in bed. Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\"","stem":"Why did Kahlo start painting while she was recovering?","choices":{"A":"Because her parents gave her paints while she rested after her injury","B":"Because she wanted to become famous very quickly","C":"Because her teacher told her she had to paint every day","D":"Because she had nothing else to do at school that year"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows Kahlo received paints from her parents while resting after her crash, and she began painting what she saw around her bedroom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo became bored lying in bed, staring at the ceiling. Her parents decided to give her a box of paints and an easel that she could use in bed. Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q010","read_aloud":"What does \"inspired\" most likely mean in this sentence? A. Caused someone to create something B. Stopped someone from working C. Made someone tired D. Confused someone","excerpt":"\"Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\"","stem":"What does \"inspired\" most likely mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Caused someone to create something","B":"Stopped someone from working","C":"Made someone tired","D":"Confused someone"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Inspired\" means something gave someone an idea or feeling to create art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q011","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of these sentences? A. Travel is boring for most people. B. Travel has a powerful effect, especially on artists. C. Only artists should travel. D. Travel is too expensive.","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of these sentences?","choices":{"A":"Travel is boring for most people.","B":"Travel has a powerful effect, especially on artists.","C":"Only artists should travel.","D":"Travel is too expensive."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says travel has a powerful effect, especially on artists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q012","read_aloud":"Where was Frida Kahlo born? A. San Francisco, California B. Coyoacan, outside Mexico City C. Paris, France D. New York City","excerpt":"\"Frida Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacan, outside Mexico City, Mexico.\"","stem":"Where was Frida Kahlo born?","choices":{"A":"San Francisco, California","B":"Coyoacan, outside Mexico City","C":"Paris, France","D":"New York City"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states she was born in Coyoacan, outside Mexico City.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Frida Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacan, outside Mexico City, Mexico.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q013","read_aloud":"What illness did Frida Kahlo have at age six? A. The flu B. Polio C. A cold D. Measles","excerpt":"\"When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What illness did Frida Kahlo have at age six?","choices":{"A":"The flu","B":"Polio","C":"A cold","D":"Measles"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says she became ill with polio.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q014","read_aloud":"What does this sentence tell you about Frida Kahlo? A. She gave up easily. B. She was determined and strong. C. She did not like sports. D. She was afraid of water.","excerpt":"\"However, this didn\u0027t slow her down. Kahlo still played sports, and she won several swimming competitions.\"","stem":"What does this sentence tell you about Frida Kahlo?","choices":{"A":"She gave up easily.","B":"She was determined and strong.","C":"She did not like sports.","D":"She was afraid of water."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Even with polio, she played sports and won competitions, showing determination.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"However, this didn\u0027t slow her down. Kahlo still played sports, and she won several swimming competitions.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q015","read_aloud":"What does \"inspired\" mean in this sentence? A. caused something to be created B. stopped someone from working C. made someone sleepy D. broke something into pieces","excerpt":"\"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys. Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\"","stem":"What does \"inspired\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"caused something to be created","B":"stopped someone from working","C":"made someone sleepy","D":"broke something into pieces"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says visiting different places inspired the themes and colors of the artists\u0027 works. \"Inspired\" means it caused them to create new art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys. Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q016","read_aloud":"What happened to Frida Kahlo when she was six? A. She won a painting contest. B. She became ill with polio, which made one leg weaker. C. She moved to the United States. D. She started painting.","excerpt":"\"When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other. However, this didn\u0027t slow her down. Kahlo still played sports, and she won several swimming competitions.\"","stem":"What happened to Frida Kahlo when she was six?","choices":{"A":"She won a painting contest.","B":"She became ill with polio, which made one leg weaker.","C":"She moved to the United States.","D":"She started painting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Kahlo became ill with polio at age six. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other. However, this didn\u0027t slow her down. Kahlo still played sports, and she won several swimming competitions.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q017","read_aloud":"Why did Kahlo start painting? A. Because she was bored while recovering from a bus crash. B. Because her teacher told her to. C. Because she wanted to sell paintings. D. Because she did not like sports.","excerpt":"\"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering. Kahlo became bored lying in bed, staring at the ceiling.\"","stem":"Why did Kahlo start painting?","choices":{"A":"Because she was bored while recovering from a bus crash.","B":"Because her teacher told her to.","C":"Because she wanted to sell paintings.","D":"Because she did not like sports."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Kahlo became bored lying in bed after her bus crash. Her parents gave her paints, and she began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering. Kahlo became bored lying in bed, staring at the ceiling.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q018","read_aloud":"In this context, what does it mean that Kahlo did not want to \"imitate\" anyone? Options:? A. She did not want to copy others. B. She did not want to talk to others. C. She did not want to travel. D. She did not want to paint flowers.","excerpt":"\"Her paintings often include green, red, and white too. Those are the colors of the Mexican flag. Even though she often lived in cities, Kahlo rarely painted urban scenes. She always preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to. She did not want to imitated anyone.\"","stem":"In this context, what does it mean that Kahlo did not want to \"imitate\" anyone? Options:?","choices":{"A":"She did not want to copy others.","B":"She did not want to talk to others.","C":"She did not want to travel.","D":"She did not want to paint flowers."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To imitate means to copy or try to do the same thing as someone else.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Her paintings often include green, red, and white too. Those are the colors of the Mexican flag. Even though she often lived in cities, Kahlo rarely painted urban scenes. She always preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to. She did not want to imitated anyone.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q019","read_aloud":"Where did Kahlo spend many hours alone? Options:? A. Mexico City B. San Francisco C. Detroit D. Coyoacán","excerpt":"\"Kahlo and Rivera lived in San Francisco, California. But it was time spent in another American city-Detroit, Michigan-that began to influence Kahlo\u0027s paintings. She passed many hours alone in Detroit while Rivera painted murals for a North American company.\"","stem":"Where did Kahlo spend many hours alone? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Mexico City","B":"San Francisco","C":"Detroit","D":"Coyoacán"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text specifically mentions that she passed many hours alone in Detroit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo and Rivera lived in San Francisco, California. But it was time spent in another American city-Detroit, Michigan-that began to influence Kahlo\u0027s paintings. She passed many hours alone in Detroit while Rivera painted murals for a North American company.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q020","read_aloud":"Why did Kahlo include objects from her culture in her paintings? Options:? A. Because she lived in Detroit. B. Because she missed her warm homeland. C. Because she was bored in bed. D. Because she wanted to sell them to a company.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"Why did Kahlo include objects from her culture in her paintings? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Because she lived in Detroit.","B":"Because she missed her warm homeland.","C":"Because she was bored in bed.","D":"Because she wanted to sell them to a company."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states she did this because she missed her homeland.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q021","read_aloud":"What does the text say about Kahlo\u0027s spirit when she was young? Options:? A. She was very quiet. B. She was determined. C. She was scared of painting. D. She was always sick.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo\u0027s diverse background helped define both her identity and her vision of the world. Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age.\"","stem":"What does the text say about Kahlo\u0027s spirit when she was young? Options:?","choices":{"A":"She was very quiet.","B":"She was determined.","C":"She was scared of painting.","D":"She was always sick."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author describes her as having a \"determined spirit\" from an early age.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo\u0027s diverse background helped define both her identity and her vision of the world. Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q022","read_aloud":"What major life change happened to Kahlo shortly after she married Diego Rivera? Options:? A. She moved to the United States. B. She went back to school. C. She retired from painting. D. She moved to the mountains.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo and Rivera married. Soon after that, they moved to the United States.\"","stem":"What major life change happened to Kahlo shortly after she married Diego Rivera? Options:?","choices":{"A":"She moved to the United States.","B":"She went back to school.","C":"She retired from painting.","D":"She moved to the mountains."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that soon after they married, they moved to the United States.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo and Rivera married. Soon after that, they moved to the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q023","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what does \"express\" mean in this sentence? Options:? A. To hide or cover up B. To show or tell thoughts and feelings C. To paint quickly D. To destroy a picture","excerpt":"\"Many of Kahlo\u0027s paintings include things she missed about her childhood and her home in Mexico. An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul, her Blue House outside Mexico City... Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to express her trademark thick, black eyebrows.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what does \"express\" mean in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"To hide or cover up","B":"To show or tell thoughts and feelings","C":"To paint quickly","D":"To destroy a picture"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Express is defined in the text as to show or tell thoughts and feelings to others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many of Kahlo\u0027s paintings include things she missed about her childhood and her home in Mexico. An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul, her Blue House outside Mexico City... Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to express her trademark thick, black eyebrows.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q024","read_aloud":"What did the spider monkey represent to Kahlo? Options:? A. Her life in the United States B. A symbol of home C. Her favorite sport D. The bus accident","excerpt":"\"An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul.\"","stem":"What did the spider monkey represent to Kahlo? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Her life in the United States","B":"A symbol of home","C":"Her favorite sport","D":"The bus accident"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states, \"To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l01-q025","read_aloud":"What is one physical feature of Kahlo that the author mentions? Options:? A. Her blue eyes B. Her long, curly hair C. Her thick eyebrows D. Her tall height","excerpt":"\"The parrot on Kahlo\u0027s shoulder and the fuzzy-leaved plants behind her also reflect the Blue House and its garden. Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to enhance her trademark thick, black eyebrows that meet in the middle.\"","stem":"What is one physical feature of Kahlo that the author mentions? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Her blue eyes","B":"Her long, curly hair","C":"Her thick eyebrows","D":"Her tall height"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes her trademark as \"thick, black eyebrows that meet in the middle\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The parrot on Kahlo\u0027s shoulder and the fuzzy-leaved plants behind her also reflect the Blue House and its garden. Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to enhance her trademark thick, black eyebrows that meet in the middle.\""}]},{"level":2,"level_name":"Level 2","difficulty_band":"foundation","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q001","read_aloud":"In this context, what does it mean that Kahlo did not want to \"imitate\" anyone? Options: A. She did not want to copy others. B. She did not want to talk to others. C. She did not want to travel. D. She did not want to paint flowers.","excerpt":"\"Her paintings often include green, red, and white too. Those are the colors of the Mexican flag. Even though she often lived in cities, Kahlo rarely painted urban scenes. She always preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to. She did not want to imitated anyone.\"","stem":"In this context, what does it mean that Kahlo did not want to \"imitate\" anyone? Options:","choices":{"A":"She did not want to copy others.","B":"She did not want to talk to others.","C":"She did not want to travel.","D":"She did not want to paint flowers."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To imitate means to copy or try to do the same thing as someone else.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Her paintings often include green, red, and white too. Those are the colors of the Mexican flag. Even though she often lived in cities, Kahlo rarely painted urban scenes. She always preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to. She did not want to imitated anyone.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q002","read_aloud":"Where did Kahlo spend many hours alone? Options: A. Mexico City B. San Francisco C. Detroit D. Coyoacán","excerpt":"\"Kahlo and Rivera lived in San Francisco, California. But it was time spent in another American city-Detroit, Michigan-that began to influence Kahlo\u0027s paintings. She passed many hours alone in Detroit while Rivera painted murals for a North American company.\"","stem":"Where did Kahlo spend many hours alone? Options:","choices":{"A":"Mexico City","B":"San Francisco","C":"Detroit","D":"Coyoacán"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text specifically mentions that she passed many hours alone in Detroit.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo and Rivera lived in San Francisco, California. But it was time spent in another American city-Detroit, Michigan-that began to influence Kahlo\u0027s paintings. She passed many hours alone in Detroit while Rivera painted murals for a North American company.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q003","read_aloud":"Why did Kahlo include objects from her culture in her paintings? Options: A. Because she lived in Detroit. B. Because she missed her warm homeland. C. Because she was bored in bed. D. Because she wanted to sell them to a company.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"Why did Kahlo include objects from her culture in her paintings? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because she lived in Detroit.","B":"Because she missed her warm homeland.","C":"Because she was bored in bed.","D":"Because she wanted to sell them to a company."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states she did this because she missed her homeland.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q004","read_aloud":"What does the text say about Kahlo\u0027s spirit when she was young? Options: A. She was very quiet. B. She was determined. C. She was scared of painting. D. She was always sick.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo\u0027s diverse background helped define both her identity and her vision of the world. Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age.\"","stem":"What does the text say about Kahlo\u0027s spirit when she was young? Options:","choices":{"A":"She was very quiet.","B":"She was determined.","C":"She was scared of painting.","D":"She was always sick."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author describes her as having a \"determined spirit\" from an early age.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo\u0027s diverse background helped define both her identity and her vision of the world. Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q005","read_aloud":"What major life change happened to Kahlo shortly after she married Diego Rivera? Options: A. She moved to the United States. B. She went back to school. C. She retired from painting. D. She moved to the mountains.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo and Rivera married. Soon after that, they moved to the United States.\"","stem":"What major life change happened to Kahlo shortly after she married Diego Rivera? Options:","choices":{"A":"She moved to the United States.","B":"She went back to school.","C":"She retired from painting.","D":"She moved to the mountains."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text states that soon after they married, they moved to the United States.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo and Rivera married. Soon after that, they moved to the United States.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q006","read_aloud":"What does \"express\" most likely mean when artists use art to express feelings? A. show or tell thoughts and feelings to others through creative work B. hide feelings from other people and keep them secret C. forget about important memories and move on quickly D. copy someone else\u0027s artwork without changing it","excerpt":"\"Because she had a huge mirror in front of her bed, she started to paint images of herself. Kahlo would continue to create self-portraits throughout her life.\"","stem":"What does \"express\" most likely mean when artists use art to express feelings?","choices":{"A":"show or tell thoughts and feelings to others through creative work","B":"hide feelings from other people and keep them secret","C":"forget about important memories and move on quickly","D":"copy someone else\u0027s artwork without changing it"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Artists use art to \"express\" by showing their thoughts and feelings. This matches the definition of sharing emotions through creative work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Because she had a huge mirror in front of her bed, she started to paint images of herself. Kahlo would continue to create self-portraits throughout her life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q007","read_aloud":"What happened when Kahlo showed her paintings to Rivera? A. He said she was not talented and should stop painting B. He told her she was talented and they became friends C. He refused to look at her work or give any opinion D. He bought all of her paintings for a large amount of money","excerpt":"\"One day, she passed by a building where the famous painter Diego Rivera was painting a huge mural. She decided to show Rivera some of her paintings and ask him for his opinion. Rivera agreed to take a look. He told her she was talented.\"","stem":"What happened when Kahlo showed her paintings to Rivera?","choices":{"A":"He said she was not talented and should stop painting","B":"He told her she was talented and they became friends","C":"He refused to look at her work or give any opinion","D":"He bought all of her paintings for a large amount of money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Rivera \"told her she was talented\" and that this was \"the beginning of a long friendship between the two artists.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One day, she passed by a building where the famous painter Diego Rivera was painting a huge mural. She decided to show Rivera some of her paintings and ask him for his opinion. Rivera agreed to take a look. He told her she was talented.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q008","read_aloud":"What effect did living in Detroit have on Kahlo\u0027s art? A. It made her stop painting altogether and focus on other hobbies B. It made her miss Mexico and paint images related to how she felt C. It made her only paint city scenes and forget about nature D. It made her forget about her Mexican heritage completely","excerpt":"\"Kahlo and Rivera lived in San Francisco, California. But it was time spent in another American city-Detroit, Michigan-that began to influence Kahlo\u0027s paintings. She found that she greatly missed her homeland of Mexico.\"","stem":"What effect did living in Detroit have on Kahlo\u0027s art?","choices":{"A":"It made her stop painting altogether and focus on other hobbies","B":"It made her miss Mexico and paint images related to how she felt","C":"It made her only paint city scenes and forget about nature","D":"It made her forget about her Mexican heritage completely"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt states that in Detroit, Kahlo \"greatly missed her homeland of Mexico\" and \"began to paint images that related to how she felt.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo and Rivera lived in San Francisco, California. But it was time spent in another American city-Detroit, Michigan-that began to influence Kahlo\u0027s paintings. She found that she greatly missed her homeland of Mexico.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q009","read_aloud":"What did Kahlo paint most often, no matter where she lived? A. Landscapes of different countries she visited on trips B. Images of herself, or self-portraits, showing her feelings C. Pictures of famous buildings in the cities where she lived D. Scenes of busy city life with many people and cars","excerpt":"\"No matter where she went, she painted what she could identify with most: herself.\"","stem":"What did Kahlo paint most often, no matter where she lived?","choices":{"A":"Landscapes of different countries she visited on trips","B":"Images of herself, or self-portraits, showing her feelings","C":"Pictures of famous buildings in the cities where she lived","D":"Scenes of busy city life with many people and cars"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states Kahlo painted \"what she could identify with most: herself,\" meaning she often painted self-portraits.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No matter where she went, she painted what she could identify with most: herself.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q010","read_aloud":"Why did Kahlo include monkeys and parrots in her paintings? A. Because they were symbols of her home in Mexico and things she missed B. Because monkeys and parrots were her favorite animals to study in books C. Because she wanted to paint only animals and never paint people D. Because Diego Rivera told her she had to paint them in every work","excerpt":"\"Many of Kahlo\u0027s paintings include things she missed about her childhood and her home in Mexico. An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942.\"","stem":"Why did Kahlo include monkeys and parrots in her paintings?","choices":{"A":"Because they were symbols of her home in Mexico and things she missed","B":"Because monkeys and parrots were her favorite animals to study in books","C":"Because she wanted to paint only animals and never paint people","D":"Because Diego Rivera told her she had to paint them in every work"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that to Kahlo, the spider monkey \"was a symbol of home\" and that these animals reflected her Blue House and garden in Mexico.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many of Kahlo\u0027s paintings include things she missed about her childhood and her home in Mexico. An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q011","read_aloud":"What is a \"habit\"? A. Something you do only once B. Something you do regularly, often without thinking C. A type of paint D. A kind of accident","excerpt":"\"Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom. Painting became her daily habit.\"","stem":"What is a \"habit\"?","choices":{"A":"Something you do only once","B":"Something you do regularly, often without thinking","C":"A type of paint","D":"A kind of accident"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"A habit is something you do often and regularly.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom. Painting became her daily habit.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q012","read_aloud":"Why did Kahlo\u0027s parents give her paints? A. She asked for them. B. She was bored resting in bed after the accident. C. She wanted to become famous. D. She was already a great painter.","excerpt":"\"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering. Kahlo became bored lying in bed, staring at the ceiling. Her parents decided to give her a box of paints and an easel that she could use in bed.\"","stem":"Why did Kahlo\u0027s parents give her paints?","choices":{"A":"She asked for them.","B":"She was bored resting in bed after the accident.","C":"She wanted to become famous.","D":"She was already a great painter."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says she became bored, so her parents gave her paints.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering. Kahlo became bored lying in bed, staring at the ceiling. Her parents decided to give her a box of paints and an easel that she could use in bed.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q013","read_aloud":"What did Diego Rivera tell Kahlo about her paintings? A. She should stop painting. B. She was talented. C. Her paintings were ugly. D. She needed more practice.","excerpt":"\"One day, she passed by a building where the famous painter Diego Rivera was painting a huge mural. She decided to show Rivera some of her paintings and ask him for his opinion. Rivera agreed to take a look. He told her she was talented.\"","stem":"What did Diego Rivera tell Kahlo about her paintings?","choices":{"A":"She should stop painting.","B":"She was talented.","C":"Her paintings were ugly.","D":"She needed more practice."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Rivera told her she was talented.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One day, she passed by a building where the famous painter Diego Rivera was painting a huge mural. She decided to show Rivera some of her paintings and ask him for his opinion. Rivera agreed to take a look. He told her she was talented.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q014","read_aloud":"What happened after Rivera told Kahlo she was talented? A. They became enemies. B. They became friends and later married. C. She moved away. D. She stopped painting.","excerpt":"\"That was the beginning of a long friendship between the two artists. A year after they met, Kahlo and Rivera married.\"","stem":"What happened after Rivera told Kahlo she was talented?","choices":{"A":"They became enemies.","B":"They became friends and later married.","C":"She moved away.","D":"She stopped painting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says they became friends and then married.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"That was the beginning of a long friendship between the two artists. A year after they met, Kahlo and Rivera married.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q015","read_aloud":"AND \"There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading. What does \"express\" mean in this context? A. to show or tell thoughts and feelings to others B. to hide everything C. to run very fast D. to eat quickly","excerpt":"As a result, the young artist found a new way to share her feelings and ideas through her art.","stem":"AND \"There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading. What does \"express\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"to show or tell thoughts and feelings to others","B":"to hide everything","C":"to run very fast","D":"to eat quickly"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading. \"Express\" means to show or tell your thoughts and feelings to others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: As a result, the young artist found a new way to share her feelings and ideas through her art."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q016","read_aloud":"What did Kahlo do after recovering from her accident? A. She stopped painting forever. B. She went out and showed her paintings to Diego Rivera. C. She moved to Europe. D. She became a teacher.","excerpt":"\"After she recovered from the accident, Kahlo began going out and about again. One day, she passed by a building where the famous painter Diego Rivera was painting a huge mural. She decided to show Rivera some of her paintings and ask him for his opinion.\"","stem":"What did Kahlo do after recovering from her accident?","choices":{"A":"She stopped painting forever.","B":"She went out and showed her paintings to Diego Rivera.","C":"She moved to Europe.","D":"She became a teacher."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says after recovering, Kahlo began going out again. She passed by a building where Diego Rivera was painting and decided to show him her paintings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After she recovered from the accident, Kahlo began going out and about again. One day, she passed by a building where the famous painter Diego Rivera was painting a huge mural. She decided to show Rivera some of her paintings and ask him for his opinion.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q017","read_aloud":"How were San Francisco and Detroit different for Kahlo? A. Both cities had the same effect on her paintings. B. Detroit, not San Francisco, began to influence her paintings. C. She liked San Francisco more than Detroit. D. She never visited either city.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo and Rivera lived in San Francisco, California. But it was time spent in another American city-Detroit, Michigan-that began to influence Kahlo\u0027s paintings.\"","stem":"How were San Francisco and Detroit different for Kahlo?","choices":{"A":"Both cities had the same effect on her paintings.","B":"Detroit, not San Francisco, began to influence her paintings.","C":"She liked San Francisco more than Detroit.","D":"She never visited either city."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Kahlo and Rivera lived in San Francisco, but it was time spent in Detroit that began to influence her paintings. This shows Detroit had a different effect on her art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo and Rivera lived in San Francisco, California. But it was time spent in another American city-Detroit, Michigan-that began to influence Kahlo\u0027s paintings.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q018","read_aloud":"What did the spider monkey symbolize for Kahlo? A. a symbol of danger B. a symbol of home C. a symbol of travel D. a symbol of school","excerpt":"\"To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul, her Blue House outside Mexico City.\"","stem":"What did the spider monkey symbolize for Kahlo?","choices":{"A":"a symbol of danger","B":"a symbol of home","C":"a symbol of travel","D":"a symbol of school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that to Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept them as pets at her Blue House.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul, her Blue House outside Mexico City.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q019","read_aloud":"What did O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s parents do for a living? A. They were stockbrokers. B. They were dairy farmers. C. They were painters. D. They were teachers.","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe was born in 1887 in the rural town of Sun Prairie, Wisconsin. Her parents were dairy farmers of Irish and Hungarian backgrounds.\"","stem":"What did O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s parents do for a living?","choices":{"A":"They were stockbrokers.","B":"They were dairy farmers.","C":"They were painters.","D":"They were teachers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s parents were dairy farmers. They lived in Sun Prairie, Wisconsin.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe was born in 1887 in the rural town of Sun Prairie, Wisconsin. Her parents were dairy farmers of Irish and Hungarian backgrounds.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q020","read_aloud":"What happened to Kahlo when she was six years old? Options:? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What happened to Kahlo when she was six years old? Options:?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q021","read_aloud":"Where did Kahlo paint when she was recovering from her accident? Options:? A. In a studio B. In her bedroom C. In a garden D. At school","excerpt":"\"Her parents decided to give her a box of paints and an easel that she could use in bed. Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\"","stem":"Where did Kahlo paint when she was recovering from her accident? Options:?","choices":{"A":"In a studio","B":"In her bedroom","C":"In a garden","D":"At school"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says her parents gave her paints to use in bed, so she painted everything she saw in her bedroom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Her parents decided to give her a box of paints and an easel that she could use in bed. Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q022","read_aloud":"What did Kahlo paint most often because of the mirror in her room? Options:? A. Pictures of her parents B. Pictures of her garden C. Pictures of herself D. Pictures of the sky","excerpt":"\"Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom. Painting became her daily habit. Because she had a huge mirror in front of her bed, she started to paint images of herself.\"","stem":"What did Kahlo paint most often because of the mirror in her room? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Pictures of her parents","B":"Pictures of her garden","C":"Pictures of herself","D":"Pictures of the sky"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that because she had a mirror, she started to paint images of herself.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom. Painting became her daily habit. Because she had a huge mirror in front of her bed, she started to paint images of herself.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q023","read_aloud":"Why did Kahlo have to spend months resting in bed? Options:? A. She was bored. B. She was seriously injured in a bus crash. C. She wanted to learn how to paint. D. She was traveling to a new place.","excerpt":"\"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering.\"","stem":"Why did Kahlo have to spend months resting in bed? Options:?","choices":{"A":"She was bored.","B":"She was seriously injured in a bus crash.","C":"She wanted to learn how to paint.","D":"She was traveling to a new place."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that her need for rest was caused by being seriously injured in a bus crash.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q024","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what does \"express\" mean in this sentence? Options:? A. To hide or cover up B. To show or tell thoughts and feelings C. To paint quickly D. To destroy a picture","excerpt":"\"Many of Kahlo\u0027s paintings include things she missed about her childhood and her home in Mexico. An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul, her Blue House outside Mexico City... Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to express her trademark thick, black eyebrows.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what does \"express\" mean in this sentence? Options:?","choices":{"A":"To hide or cover up","B":"To show or tell thoughts and feelings","C":"To paint quickly","D":"To destroy a picture"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Express is defined in the text as to show or tell thoughts and feelings to others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many of Kahlo\u0027s paintings include things she missed about her childhood and her home in Mexico. An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul, her Blue House outside Mexico City... Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to express her trademark thick, black eyebrows.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l02-q025","read_aloud":"What did the spider monkey represent to Kahlo? Options:? A. Her life in the United States B. A symbol of home C. Her favorite sport D. The bus accident","excerpt":"\"An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul.\"","stem":"What did the spider monkey represent to Kahlo? Options:?","choices":{"A":"Her life in the United States","B":"A symbol of home","C":"Her favorite sport","D":"The bus accident"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states, \"To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul.\""}]},{"level":3,"level_name":"Level 3","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what does \"express\" mean in this sentence? Options: A. To hide or cover up B. To show or tell thoughts and feelings C. To paint quickly D. To destroy a picture","excerpt":"\"Many of Kahlo\u0027s paintings include things she missed about her childhood and her home in Mexico. An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul, her Blue House outside Mexico City... Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to express her trademark thick, black eyebrows.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what does \"express\" mean in this sentence? Options:","choices":{"A":"To hide or cover up","B":"To show or tell thoughts and feelings","C":"To paint quickly","D":"To destroy a picture"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Express is defined in the text as to show or tell thoughts and feelings to others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many of Kahlo\u0027s paintings include things she missed about her childhood and her home in Mexico. An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul, her Blue House outside Mexico City... Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to express her trademark thick, black eyebrows.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q002","read_aloud":"What did the spider monkey represent to Kahlo? Options: A. Her life in the United States B. A symbol of home C. Her favorite sport D. The bus accident","excerpt":"\"An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul.\"","stem":"What did the spider monkey represent to Kahlo? Options:","choices":{"A":"Her life in the United States","B":"A symbol of home","C":"Her favorite sport","D":"The bus accident"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states, \"To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"An example is Self Portrait with Monkey and Parrot, painted in 1942. To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q003","read_aloud":"What is one physical feature of Kahlo that the author mentions? Options: A. Her blue eyes B. Her long, curly hair C. Her thick eyebrows D. Her tall height","excerpt":"\"The parrot on Kahlo\u0027s shoulder and the fuzzy-leaved plants behind her also reflect the Blue House and its garden. Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to enhance her trademark thick, black eyebrows that meet in the middle.\"","stem":"What is one physical feature of Kahlo that the author mentions? Options:","choices":{"A":"Her blue eyes","B":"Her long, curly hair","C":"Her thick eyebrows","D":"Her tall height"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text describes her trademark as \"thick, black eyebrows that meet in the middle\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The parrot on Kahlo\u0027s shoulder and the fuzzy-leaved plants behind her also reflect the Blue House and its garden. Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to enhance her trademark thick, black eyebrows that meet in the middle.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q004","read_aloud":"Besides home, what else did the spider monkey symbolize? Options: A. Her painting teacher B. The children she could not have C. Her swimming competitions D. The city of Detroit","excerpt":"\"To Kahlo, the spider monkey in the painting was also a symbol of the children she couldn\u0027t have because of her bus accident.\"","stem":"Besides home, what else did the spider monkey symbolize? Options:","choices":{"A":"Her painting teacher","B":"The children she could not have","C":"Her swimming competitions","D":"The city of Detroit"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that the animals were also a symbol of the children she could not have due to her accident.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To Kahlo, the spider monkey in the painting was also a symbol of the children she couldn\u0027t have because of her bus accident.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q005","read_aloud":"Roughly how many of Kahlo\u0027s paintings featured spider monkeys? Options: A. 181 B. 10 C. 55 D. 100","excerpt":"\"The animals meant so much to her that of 181 works she made in her lifetime, 55 of them include spider monkeys!\"","stem":"Roughly how many of Kahlo\u0027s paintings featured spider monkeys? Options:","choices":{"A":"181","B":"10","C":"55","D":"100"},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states that 55 of her 181 works included spider monkeys.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The animals meant so much to her that of 181 works she made in her lifetime, 55 of them include spider monkeys!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"exhibit\" most likely mean? A. a group of artworks arranged for public viewing in a gallery B. a type of painting technique using bright and bold colors C. a special kind of mirror artists use to paint self-portraits D. a famous artist\u0027s signature style that others try to copy","excerpt":"\"Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to enhance her trademark thick, black eyebrows that meet in the middle.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"exhibit\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"a group of artworks arranged for public viewing in a gallery","B":"a type of painting technique using bright and bold colors","C":"a special kind of mirror artists use to paint self-portraits","D":"a famous artist\u0027s signature style that others try to copy"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The preview vocabulary defines \"exhibit\" as \"a group of artworks or other objects arranged for public viewing.\" This matches option a.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo herself is stern-faced and serious-looking, painted to enhance her trademark thick, black eyebrows that meet in the middle.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q007","read_aloud":"What is a \"visual autobiography\" based on this excerpt? A. A painting that tells the story of the artist\u0027s life and feelings using images B. A book with many photographs showing the artist at different ages C. A collection of letters written by the artist to family members D. A movie about the artist\u0027s childhood that others can watch","excerpt":"\"No matter where Kahlo lived, she made paintings that were like visual autobiographies. Every painting tells the story of something remarkable she lived through and how she felt about it.\"","stem":"What is a \"visual autobiography\" based on this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"A painting that tells the story of the artist\u0027s life and feelings using images","B":"A book with many photographs showing the artist at different ages","C":"A collection of letters written by the artist to family members","D":"A movie about the artist\u0027s childhood that others can watch"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that Kahlo\u0027s paintings were \"like visual autobiographies\" that \"tell the story of something remarkable she lived through and how she felt about it.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No matter where Kahlo lived, she made paintings that were like visual autobiographies. Every painting tells the story of something remarkable she lived through and how she felt about it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q008","read_aloud":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt? A. Cause: Kahlo missed Mexico; Effect: She painted herself with Mexican cultural items B. Cause: Kahlo liked jewelry; Effect: She became a famous artist worldwide C. Cause: Kahlo moved to America; Effect: She forgot about Mexico completely D. Cause: Kahlo painted self-portraits; Effect: She stopped traveling to new places","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"What is the cause-and-effect relationship in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Cause: Kahlo missed Mexico; Effect: She painted herself with Mexican cultural items","B":"Cause: Kahlo liked jewelry; Effect: She became a famous artist worldwide","C":"Cause: Kahlo moved to America; Effect: She forgot about Mexico completely","D":"Cause: Kahlo painted self-portraits; Effect: She stopped traveling to new places"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt uses \"That\u0027s why\" to show cause and effect: because Kahlo missed Mexico, she included Mexican cultural items in her paintings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q009","read_aloud":"According to this excerpt, what does the color yellow represent in Kahlo\u0027s paintings? A. The sun and happiness of Mexico, her warm homeland B. Sadness and loneliness from being far away from home C. The ocean and water from her childhood memories D. Danger and warning signs she saw in cities","excerpt":"\"Her use of color, too, often expressed her yearning for home, as well as other powerful feelings. Yellow, for example, represents the sun and happiness of Mexico.\"","stem":"According to this excerpt, what does the color yellow represent in Kahlo\u0027s paintings?","choices":{"A":"The sun and happiness of Mexico, her warm homeland","B":"Sadness and loneliness from being far away from home","C":"The ocean and water from her childhood memories","D":"Danger and warning signs she saw in cities"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text directly states that \"Yellow, for example, represents the sun and happiness of Mexico.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Her use of color, too, often expressed her yearning for home, as well as other powerful feelings. Yellow, for example, represents the sun and happiness of Mexico.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q010","read_aloud":"Why did Kahlo rarely paint city scenes even when she lived in cities? A. Because she preferred to paint the Mexican world she dreamed of returning to B. Because she did not know how to paint buildings or city streets C. Because cities were too noisy for her to concentrate on her work D. Because Diego Rivera told her not to paint any city scenes ever","excerpt":"\"Even though she often lived in cities, Kahlo rarely painted urban scenes. She always preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to.\"","stem":"Why did Kahlo rarely paint city scenes even when she lived in cities?","choices":{"A":"Because she preferred to paint the Mexican world she dreamed of returning to","B":"Because she did not know how to paint buildings or city streets","C":"Because cities were too noisy for her to concentrate on her work","D":"Because Diego Rivera told her not to paint any city scenes ever"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that Kahlo \"preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to\" rather than the urban scenes around her.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even though she often lived in cities, Kahlo rarely painted urban scenes. She always preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"identify with\" mean? A. To feel connected to or understand someone or something B. To draw a picture of someone else C. To forget about something D. To run away from something","excerpt":"\"No matter where she went, she painted what she could identify with most: herself.\"","stem":"What does \"identify with\" mean?","choices":{"A":"To feel connected to or understand someone or something","B":"To draw a picture of someone else","C":"To forget about something","D":"To run away from something"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To identify with something means you feel a strong connection to it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No matter where she went, she painted what she could identify with most: herself.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q012","read_aloud":"What did the spider monkey symbolize for Kahlo? A. Fear B. Home C. Sickness D. Travel","excerpt":"\"To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul, her Blue House outside Mexico City.\"","stem":"What did the spider monkey symbolize for Kahlo?","choices":{"A":"Fear","B":"Home","C":"Sickness","D":"Travel"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the spider monkey was a symbol of home.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. She kept spider monkeys as pets in the garden of La Casa Azul, her Blue House outside Mexico City.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q013","read_aloud":"What can you infer about how Kahlo felt about spider monkeys? A. She did not like them. B. She loved them and included them in many paintings. C. She was afraid of them. D. She only painted them once.","excerpt":"\"The animals meant so much to her that of 181 works she made in her lifetime, 55 of them include spider monkeys!\"","stem":"What can you infer about how Kahlo felt about spider monkeys?","choices":{"A":"She did not like them.","B":"She loved them and included them in many paintings.","C":"She was afraid of them.","D":"She only painted them once."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Painting spider monkeys in 55 works shows she loved them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The animals meant so much to her that of 181 works she made in her lifetime, 55 of them include spider monkeys!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q014","read_aloud":"What is an exhibit? A. a group of artworks arranged for public viewing B. a private home C. a type of food D. a school building","excerpt":"\"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"What is an exhibit?","choices":{"A":"a group of artworks arranged for public viewing","B":"a private home","C":"a type of food","D":"a school building"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work. An exhibit is a group of artworks or objects arranged for people to view.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q015","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Kahlo forgot about Mexico. B. Kahlo missed Mexico, so she painted things that showed her cultural heritage. C. Kahlo did not like jewelry. D. Kahlo never painted herself.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Kahlo forgot about Mexico.","B":"Kahlo missed Mexico, so she painted things that showed her cultural heritage.","C":"Kahlo did not like jewelry.","D":"Kahlo never painted herself."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt says Kahlo missed her homeland. Because of this, she painted herself with jewelry and objects from her cultural heritage. This is the main idea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q016","read_aloud":"What does yellow represent in Kahlo\u0027s paintings? A. only sadness B. the sun and happiness of Mexico C. only night time D. only water","excerpt":"\"Yellow, for example, represents the sun and happiness of Mexico. But in some cases, it also represents illness or fear. Cobalt blue represents electricity and purity.\"","stem":"What does yellow represent in Kahlo\u0027s paintings?","choices":{"A":"only sadness","B":"the sun and happiness of Mexico","C":"only night time","D":"only water"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says yellow represents the sun and happiness of Mexico. It can also represent illness or fear in some cases.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Yellow, for example, represents the sun and happiness of Mexico. But in some cases, it also represents illness or fear. Cobalt blue represents electricity and purity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q017","read_aloud":"When did O\u0027Keeffe decide to become a painter? A. when she was in college B. when she was in eighth grade C. when she was 30 years old D. when she retired","excerpt":"\"When she was in eighth grade, O\u0027Keeffe decided to become a painter. She took art lessons and began to focus on flowers as one of her favorite subjects.\"","stem":"When did O\u0027Keeffe decide to become a painter?","choices":{"A":"when she was in college","B":"when she was in eighth grade","C":"when she was 30 years old","D":"when she retired"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that when O\u0027Keeffe was in eighth grade, she decided to become a painter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When she was in eighth grade, O\u0027Keeffe decided to become a painter. She took art lessons and began to focus on flowers as one of her favorite subjects.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q018","read_aloud":"What is abstract art? A. art that shows things in a realistic way B. art that does not try to show people, places, or things realistically C. art that only uses one color D. art that is only about animals","excerpt":"\"In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings. Abstract art is a painting or other art form that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way.\"","stem":"What is abstract art?","choices":{"A":"art that shows things in a realistic way","B":"art that does not try to show people, places, or things realistically","C":"art that only uses one color","D":"art that is only about animals"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says abstract art is a painting that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way. It uses shapes, colors, and lines instead.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings. Abstract art is a painting or other art form that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q020","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q021","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They all painted only city buildings. B. They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas. C. They all used only dull, dark colors. D. They all painted exactly the same subjects.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They all painted only city buildings.","B":"They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas.","C":"They all used only dull, dark colors.","D":"They all painted exactly the same subjects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While their subjects varied (flowers, monkeys, tropical islands), they all looked to their environments for personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It is a way to stop painting for a while. B. Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential. C. It makes the artist famous without any work. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It is a way to stop painting for a while.","B":"Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential.","C":"It makes the artist famous without any work.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that by moving away from traditional styles and experimenting, these artists gained recognition and influence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Kahlo, because she had many health problems. B. Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti. C. O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States. D. None of them, because they did not travel enough.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Kahlo, because she had many health problems.","B":"Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti.","C":"O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States.","D":"None of them, because they did not travel enough."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin\u0027s story involves the most diverse range of locations (Peru, France, Panama, Martinique, Tahiti), making him a primary example of how traveling influences an artist\u0027s entire career. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Picturesque Journeys\" Author: Yanitzia Canetti Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 5, Savvas Learning Company LLC Preview Vocabulary: inspired, express, exhibit, imitated, compositions","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l03-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. caused something to be created; motivated artistic work B. made someone feel tired and sleepy C. confused someone about what to paint D. stopped someone from finishing their artwork","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"caused something to be created; motivated artistic work","B":"made someone feel tired and sleepy","C":"confused someone about what to paint","D":"stopped someone from finishing their artwork"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows locations \"inspired\" painters \"to create their best works.\" This means the places motivated or caused the art to be made.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\""}]},{"level":4,"level_name":"Level 4","difficulty_band":"developing","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q001","read_aloud":"What is an \"exhibit\"? Options: A. A group of artworks arranged for public viewing B. A private collection no one can see C. A type of paint D. A book about an artist","excerpt":"\"The famous photographer and art gallery owner Alfred Stieglitz saw O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s abstract drawings and was very impressed. In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"What is an \"exhibit\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"A group of artworks arranged for public viewing","B":"A private collection no one can see","C":"A type of paint","D":"A book about an artist"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"An exhibit is a group of artworks or objects arranged for public viewing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The famous photographer and art gallery owner Alfred Stieglitz saw O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s abstract drawings and was very impressed. In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q002","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? Options: A. O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s family was very loud. B. O\u0027Keeffe enjoyed being in nature and was quiet. C. O\u0027Keeffe lived in the city. D. O\u0027Keeffe did not like art as a child.","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe grew up in a farmhouse, surrounded by trees, wildflowers, and grasslands. O\u0027Keeffe was surrounded by a big family, but she was quiet and independent. Growing up, she enjoyed spending long hours observing the natural environment.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this paragraph? Options:","choices":{"A":"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s family was very loud.","B":"O\u0027Keeffe enjoyed being in nature and was quiet.","C":"O\u0027Keeffe lived in the city.","D":"O\u0027Keeffe did not like art as a child."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The details focus on her quiet nature and her love for observing the natural environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe grew up in a farmhouse, surrounded by trees, wildflowers, and grasslands. O\u0027Keeffe was surrounded by a big family, but she was quiet and independent. Growing up, she enjoyed spending long hours observing the natural environment.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q003","read_aloud":"Why did O\u0027Keeffe like to paint flowers? Options: A. Because they were easy to draw. B. Because she was fascinated by their soft colors and irregular forms. C. Because her parents told her to. D. Because they reminded her of the city.","excerpt":"\"When she was in eighth grade, O\u0027Keeffe decided to become a painter. She took art lessons and began to focus on flowers as one of her favorite subjects. She was fascinated by their soft colors and irregular forms.\"","stem":"Why did O\u0027Keeffe like to paint flowers? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they were easy to draw.","B":"Because she was fascinated by their soft colors and irregular forms.","C":"Because her parents told her to.","D":"Because they reminded her of the city."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states she was fascinated by these features of flowers.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When she was in eighth grade, O\u0027Keeffe decided to become a painter. She took art lessons and began to focus on flowers as one of her favorite subjects. She was fascinated by their soft colors and irregular forms.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q004","read_aloud":"How did Arthur Wesley Dow influence O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work? Options: A. He told her to stop painting flowers. B. He taught her to use color, lines, and shading to express herself. C. He made her move to New Mexico. D. He told her to only paint in black and white.","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s style and ideas about art took a turn in 1912 when she attended a summer school class at the University of Virginia. There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\"","stem":"How did Arthur Wesley Dow influence O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work? Options:","choices":{"A":"He told her to stop painting flowers.","B":"He taught her to use color, lines, and shading to express herself.","C":"He made her move to New Mexico.","D":"He told her to only paint in black and white."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that she was inspired by his ideas about using color, lines, and shading.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s style and ideas about art took a turn in 1912 when she attended a summer school class at the University of Virginia. There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q005","read_aloud":"How is abstract art different from realistic art? Options: A. It is always darker. B. It does not try to look exactly like real things. C. It is only painted in New York. D. It is always very small.","excerpt":"\"In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings. Abstract art is a painting or other art form that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way.\"","stem":"How is abstract art different from realistic art? Options:","choices":{"A":"It is always darker.","B":"It does not try to look exactly like real things.","C":"It is only painted in New York.","D":"It is always very small."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt defines abstract art as not trying to show things in a realistic way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings. Abstract art is a painting or other art form that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"imitated\" most likely mean? A. copied; tried to do the same things others did in their artwork B. created something completely new and different from others C. traveled to many different countries to find inspiration D. painted only self-portraits and no other subjects at all","excerpt":"\"Much as she missed Mexico, however, Kahlo\u0027s travels had a major effect on the art she created. Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"imitated\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"copied; tried to do the same things others did in their artwork","B":"created something completely new and different from others","C":"traveled to many different countries to find inspiration","D":"painted only self-portraits and no other subjects at all"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The preview vocabulary defines \"imitated\" as \"copied; tried to do the same things others did.\" This matches option a.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Much as she missed Mexico, however, Kahlo\u0027s travels had a major effect on the art she created. Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q007","read_aloud":"How is O\u0027Keeffe similar to Kahlo according to this excerpt? A. Both were deeply influenced by their cultural backgrounds and travels B. Both were born in Mexico and painted similar subjects C. Both painted only flowers and nothing else in their careers D. Both moved to Europe as children and stayed there","excerpt":"\"Like Kahlo, the American artist Georgia O\u0027Keeffe was deeply influenced by her cultural background and her travels. O\u0027Keeffe was born in 1887 in the rural town of Sun Prairie, Wisconsin.\"","stem":"How is O\u0027Keeffe similar to Kahlo according to this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Both were deeply influenced by their cultural backgrounds and travels","B":"Both were born in Mexico and painted similar subjects","C":"Both painted only flowers and nothing else in their careers","D":"Both moved to Europe as children and stayed there"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt begins with \"Like Kahlo\" and states O\u0027Keeffe \"was deeply influenced by her cultural background and her travels,\" showing their similarity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Like Kahlo, the American artist Georgia O\u0027Keeffe was deeply influenced by her cultural background and her travels. O\u0027Keeffe was born in 1887 in the rural town of Sun Prairie, Wisconsin.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q008","read_aloud":"What is the sequence of events in O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s early life? A. She decided to paint, took lessons, focused on flowers, and this influenced her later work B. She painted flowers first, then decided to become a painter, then took lessons C. She moved to Wisconsin, then painted flowers, then took art lessons D. She became famous, then took art lessons, then focused on flowers","excerpt":"\"When she was in eighth grade, O\u0027Keeffe decided to become a painter. She took art lessons and began to focus on flowers as one of her favorite subjects. She was fascinated by their soft colors and irregular forms. This early experience strongly influenced her paintings years later.\"","stem":"What is the sequence of events in O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s early life?","choices":{"A":"She decided to paint, took lessons, focused on flowers, and this influenced her later work","B":"She painted flowers first, then decided to become a painter, then took lessons","C":"She moved to Wisconsin, then painted flowers, then took art lessons","D":"She became famous, then took art lessons, then focused on flowers"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt shows the order: eighth grade decision → art lessons → focus on flowers → influence on later paintings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When she was in eighth grade, O\u0027Keeffe decided to become a painter. She took art lessons and began to focus on flowers as one of her favorite subjects. She was fascinated by their soft colors and irregular forms. This early experience strongly influenced her paintings years later.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q009","read_aloud":"If an artist today wanted to follow Dow\u0027s ideas, what might they do? A. Focus on expressing feelings through color, lines, and shading rather than realistic detail B. Copy famous paintings exactly as they appear without any changes C. Only paint landscapes and never paint people or flowers D. Use only black and white colors in all of their artwork","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s style and ideas about art took a turn in 1912 when she attended a summer school class at the University of Virginia. There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\"","stem":"If an artist today wanted to follow Dow\u0027s ideas, what might they do?","choices":{"A":"Focus on expressing feelings through color, lines, and shading rather than realistic detail","B":"Copy famous paintings exactly as they appear without any changes","C":"Only paint landscapes and never paint people or flowers","D":"Use only black and white colors in all of their artwork"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Dow believed artists should \"express themselves using color, lines, and shading\" rather than focusing on realism. An artist following his ideas would prioritize expression over realistic detail.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s style and ideas about art took a turn in 1912 when she attended a summer school class at the University of Virginia. There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q010","read_aloud":"How did learning about abstract art change O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s approach to painting? A. It allowed her to share feelings and ideas without focusing on realistic representation B. It made her stop painting altogether and focus on photography instead C. It forced her to only paint realistic portraits of people she knew D. It made her copy other artists\u0027 work exactly without adding her own style","excerpt":"\"As a result, the young artist found a new way to share her feelings and ideas through her art. In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings. Abstract art is a painting or other art form that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way.\"","stem":"How did learning about abstract art change O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s approach to painting?","choices":{"A":"It allowed her to share feelings and ideas without focusing on realistic representation","B":"It made her stop painting altogether and focus on photography instead","C":"It forced her to only paint realistic portraits of people she knew","D":"It made her copy other artists\u0027 work exactly without adding her own style"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows that abstract art let O\u0027Keeffe \"share her feelings and ideas\" without trying to show things \"in a realistic way,\" representing a shift from realism to expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As a result, the young artist found a new way to share her feelings and ideas through her art. In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings. Abstract art is a painting or other art form that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"express\" mean in this sentence? A. To hide feelings B. To show or tell thoughts and feelings C. To copy someone else D. To erase a drawing","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s style and ideas about art took a turn in 1912 when she attended a summer school class at the University of Virginia. There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\"","stem":"What does \"express\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"To hide feelings","B":"To show or tell thoughts and feelings","C":"To copy someone else","D":"To erase a drawing"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To express means to show or communicate your thoughts and feelings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s style and ideas about art took a turn in 1912 when she attended a summer school class at the University of Virginia. There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q012","read_aloud":"How was Arthur Wesley Dow\u0027s idea different from realism? A. Realism uses color, lines, and shading. B. Realism tries to show things exactly as they look. Dow\u0027s idea focused on expression. C. They were exactly the same. D. Dow\u0027s idea was about copying photos.","excerpt":"\"This was very different from the realistic style of painting, known as realism, that O\u0027Keeffe had studied until then.\"","stem":"How was Arthur Wesley Dow\u0027s idea different from realism?","choices":{"A":"Realism uses color, lines, and shading.","B":"Realism tries to show things exactly as they look. Dow\u0027s idea focused on expression.","C":"They were exactly the same.","D":"Dow\u0027s idea was about copying photos."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Realism shows things realistically. Dow believed artists should express themselves.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"This was very different from the realistic style of painting, known as realism, that O\u0027Keeffe had studied until then.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q013","read_aloud":"What happened as a result of learning about Dow\u0027s ideas? A. She stopped painting. B. She began making abstract drawings to express feelings. C. She moved to New York. D. She became a teacher.","excerpt":"\"As a result, the young artist found a new way to share her feelings and ideas through her art. In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings.\"","stem":"What happened as a result of learning about Dow\u0027s ideas?","choices":{"A":"She stopped painting.","B":"She began making abstract drawings to express feelings.","C":"She moved to New York.","D":"She became a teacher."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The new ideas led her to create abstract drawings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"As a result, the young artist found a new way to share her feelings and ideas through her art. In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q014","read_aloud":"If you were an artist, why might you want someone like Stieglitz to see your work? A. He could hide your paintings. B. He could help show your art to more people. C. He would buy all your art for himself. D. He would tell you to stop painting.","excerpt":"\"The famous photographer and art gallery owner Alfred Stieglitz saw O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s abstract drawings and was very impressed. In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"If you were an artist, why might you want someone like Stieglitz to see your work?","choices":{"A":"He could hide your paintings.","B":"He could help show your art to more people.","C":"He would buy all your art for himself.","D":"He would tell you to stop painting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Stieglitz was a gallery owner who could exhibit her art to the public.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The famous photographer and art gallery owner Alfred Stieglitz saw O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s abstract drawings and was very impressed. In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q015","read_aloud":"What does the word \"captivated\" tell you about how O\u0027Keeffe felt about skyscrapers? A. She was bored by them. B. She was very interested and fascinated. C. She was afraid of them. D. She wanted to knock them down.","excerpt":"\"Living in New York City, O\u0027Keeffe was captivated by skyscrapers. She made these tall buildings the subjects of such paintings as The Shelton with Sunspots, N.Y.; City Night; and Radiator Building-Night, New York.\"","stem":"What does the word \"captivated\" tell you about how O\u0027Keeffe felt about skyscrapers?","choices":{"A":"She was bored by them.","B":"She was very interested and fascinated.","C":"She was afraid of them.","D":"She wanted to knock them down."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Captivated\" means fascinated or very interested.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Living in New York City, O\u0027Keeffe was captivated by skyscrapers. She made these tall buildings the subjects of such paintings as The Shelton with Sunspots, N.Y.; City Night; and Radiator Building-Night, New York.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q016","read_aloud":"What caused Kahlo to become a painter? A. She wanted to win a contest. B. She was bored while recovering from a bus crash, so her parents gave her paints. C. She saw a beautiful painting in a museum. D. Her teacher forced her to paint.","excerpt":"\"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering. Kahlo became bored lying in bed, staring at the ceiling. Her parents gave her some paints. She began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\"","stem":"What caused Kahlo to become a painter?","choices":{"A":"She wanted to win a contest.","B":"She was bored while recovering from a bus crash, so her parents gave her paints.","C":"She saw a beautiful painting in a museum.","D":"Her teacher forced her to paint."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The bus crash caused Kahlo to be stuck in bed. She became bored, so her parents gave her paints. This led to her becoming a painter.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering. Kahlo became bored lying in bed, staring at the ceiling. Her parents gave her some paints. She began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q017","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Kahlo\u0027s feelings toward Mexico? A. She did not like Mexico at all. B. She loved Mexico and missed it when she was away. C. She forgot about Mexico. D. She was afraid of Mexico.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Kahlo\u0027s feelings toward Mexico?","choices":{"A":"She did not like Mexico at all.","B":"She loved Mexico and missed it when she was away.","C":"She forgot about Mexico.","D":"She was afraid of Mexico."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. She painted herself with objects from her cultural heritage. This shows she loved Mexico and missed it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q018","read_aloud":"How did Stieglitz help O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s career? A. He discouraged her from painting. B. He showed her other artists\u0027 work, encouraged her, and opened her first exhibit. C. He bought all her paintings and hid them. D. He told her to stop painting flowers.","excerpt":"\"Stieglitz showed her the work of other modern artists. He encouraged her to continue painting and took some of her drawings to New York. In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"How did Stieglitz help O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s career?","choices":{"A":"He discouraged her from painting.","B":"He showed her other artists\u0027 work, encouraged her, and opened her first exhibit.","C":"He bought all her paintings and hid them.","D":"He told her to stop painting flowers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Stieglitz showed O\u0027Keeffe other artists\u0027 work, encouraged her to continue painting, and opened her first exhibit in New York. These actions helped her career.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Stieglitz showed her the work of other modern artists. He encouraged her to continue painting and took some of her drawings to New York. In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q019","read_aloud":"Why did O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings change after moving to New Mexico? A. Because she stopped painting flowers. B. Because the desert landscape inspired her to paint new subjects like mountains and bones. C. Because she forgot how to paint. D. Because she only painted cities.","excerpt":"\"After her husband\u0027s death, O\u0027Keeffe moved to New Mexico. She spent the rest of her life there, painting the desert and its flowers, mountains, and bones.\"","stem":"Why did O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings change after moving to New Mexico?","choices":{"A":"Because she stopped painting flowers.","B":"Because the desert landscape inspired her to paint new subjects like mountains and bones.","C":"Because she forgot how to paint.","D":"Because she only painted cities."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says O\u0027Keeffe painted the desert and its flowers, mountains, and bones. The new landscape inspired her to paint different subjects than before.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After her husband\u0027s death, O\u0027Keeffe moved to New Mexico. She spent the rest of her life there, painting the desert and its flowers, mountains, and bones.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They all painted only city buildings. B. They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas. C. They all used only dull, dark colors. D. They all painted exactly the same subjects.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They all painted only city buildings.","B":"They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas.","C":"They all used only dull, dark colors.","D":"They all painted exactly the same subjects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While their subjects varied (flowers, monkeys, tropical islands), they all looked to their environments for personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It is a way to stop painting for a while. B. Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential. C. It makes the artist famous without any work. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It is a way to stop painting for a while.","B":"Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential.","C":"It makes the artist famous without any work.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that by moving away from traditional styles and experimenting, these artists gained recognition and influence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l04-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Kahlo, because she had many health problems. B. Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti. C. O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States. D. None of them, because they did not travel enough.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Kahlo, because she had many health problems.","B":"Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti.","C":"O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States.","D":"None of them, because they did not travel enough."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin\u0027s story involves the most diverse range of locations (Peru, France, Panama, Martinique, Tahiti), making him a primary example of how traveling influences an artist\u0027s entire career. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Picturesque Journeys\" Author: Yanitzia Canetti Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 5, Savvas Learning Company LLC Preview Vocabulary: inspired, express, exhibit, imitated, compositions","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""}]},{"level":5,"level_name":"Level 5","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q001","read_aloud":"Why did Gauguin want to move away from the popular Impressionist style? Options: A. Because he thought the paint was too expensive. B. Because he felt artists were just copying each other. C. Because he was forced to by his family. D. Because he did not have enough time to paint.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone. In Brittany, he started to move away from the Impressionist style that was so popular at the time.\"","stem":"Why did Gauguin want to move away from the popular Impressionist style? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because he thought the paint was too expensive.","B":"Because he felt artists were just copying each other.","C":"Because he was forced to by his family.","D":"Because he did not have enough time to paint."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says he felt artists \"imitated each other\" and he did not want to do that.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone. In Brittany, he started to move away from the Impressionist style that was so popular at the time.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q002","read_aloud":"What effect did sailing to Brazil have on Gauguin? Options: A. He stopped being a sailor. B. He learned that he loved traveling and other cultures. C. He became a famous doctor. D. He decided to never travel again.","excerpt":"\"During this time, Gauguin sailed twice to Brazil. He discovered that he loved traveling and learning about other cultures. These passions would become important parts of his life and art.\"","stem":"What effect did sailing to Brazil have on Gauguin? Options:","choices":{"A":"He stopped being a sailor.","B":"He learned that he loved traveling and other cultures.","C":"He became a famous doctor.","D":"He decided to never travel again."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains he discovered a love for travel and other cultures during these trips.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"During this time, Gauguin sailed twice to Brazil. He discovered that he loved traveling and learning about other cultures. These passions would become important parts of his life and art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q003","read_aloud":"What caused Gauguin to become a full-time painter? Options: A. He won a contest. B. He wanted to travel to Tahiti. C. He lost his job when the stock market crashed. D. He was told to move by his mother.","excerpt":"\"In 1882, the stock market crashed in France, and Gauguin lost his job. He decided to take the risk of becoming a full-time painter. He moved to Brittany, in the north of France.\"","stem":"What caused Gauguin to become a full-time painter? Options:","choices":{"A":"He won a contest.","B":"He wanted to travel to Tahiti.","C":"He lost his job when the stock market crashed.","D":"He was told to move by his mother."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text states the crash caused him to lose his job, leading to his decision to paint full-time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1882, the stock market crashed in France, and Gauguin lost his job. He decided to take the risk of becoming a full-time painter. He moved to Brittany, in the north of France.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q004","read_aloud":"How did Gauguin show he was trying to create something different from other French artists? Options: A. He moved back to Peru. B. He painted using bold colors and strong lines. C. He stopped painting for many years. D. He only painted in black and white.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different... Gauguin instead started painting scenes of Brittany\u0027s countryside in bold colors, with strong lines.\"","stem":"How did Gauguin show he was trying to create something different from other French artists? Options:","choices":{"A":"He moved back to Peru.","B":"He painted using bold colors and strong lines.","C":"He stopped painting for many years.","D":"He only painted in black and white."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text describes his new approach as using bold colors and strong lines instead of the popular style.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different... Gauguin instead started painting scenes of Brittany\u0027s countryside in bold colors, with strong lines.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q005","read_aloud":"What happened as a result of Gauguin\u0027s visit to Martinique? Options: A. He started to include tropical landscapes in his art. B. He decided to stay in Panama forever. C. He stopped painting people. D. He became a stockbroker again.","excerpt":"\"In 1887, after a brief trip to Panama, Gauguin visited the island of Martinique, in the Caribbean. The beauty of the Caribbean landscape amazed him. He also became friendly with people on the island.\"","stem":"What happened as a result of Gauguin\u0027s visit to Martinique? Options:","choices":{"A":"He started to include tropical landscapes in his art.","B":"He decided to stay in Panama forever.","C":"He stopped painting people.","D":"He became a stockbroker again."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explains that because of his experience, he started to include tropical landscapes in his work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1887, after a brief trip to Panama, Gauguin visited the island of Martinique, in the Caribbean. The beauty of the Caribbean landscape amazed him. He also became friendly with people on the island.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q006","read_aloud":"Based on the preview vocabulary, what is an \"exhibit\"? A. a group of artworks arranged for public viewing in a gallery or museum B. a type of abstract painting technique using unusual colors C. a special camera used by photographers to take pictures D. a famous artist\u0027s signature on their work that proves authenticity","excerpt":"\"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"Based on the preview vocabulary, what is an \"exhibit\"?","choices":{"A":"a group of artworks arranged for public viewing in a gallery or museum","B":"a type of abstract painting technique using unusual colors","C":"a special camera used by photographers to take pictures","D":"a famous artist\u0027s signature on their work that proves authenticity"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The preview vocabulary defines \"exhibit\" as \"a group of artworks or other objects arranged for public viewing.\" This matches the context of Stieglitz showing O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q007","read_aloud":"What effect did living in New York City have on O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s art? A. She began painting skyscrapers and city scenes as major subjects B. She stopped painting and focused on photography instead of art C. She only painted flowers and nature scenes from her childhood D. She moved back to Wisconsin immediately and never returned","excerpt":"\"Living in New York City, O\u0027Keeffe was captivated by skyscrapers. She made these tall buildings the subjects of such paintings as The Shelton with Sunspots, N.Y.; City Night; and Radiator Building-Night, New York.\"","stem":"What effect did living in New York City have on O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s art?","choices":{"A":"She began painting skyscrapers and city scenes as major subjects","B":"She stopped painting and focused on photography instead of art","C":"She only painted flowers and nature scenes from her childhood","D":"She moved back to Wisconsin immediately and never returned"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt states O\u0027Keeffe was \"captivated by skyscrapers\" in New York and \"made these tall buildings the subjects\" of her paintings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Living in New York City, O\u0027Keeffe was captivated by skyscrapers. She made these tall buildings the subjects of such paintings as The Shelton with Sunspots, N.Y.; City Night; and Radiator Building-Night, New York.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q008","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. O\u0027Keeffe painted large, close-up images of nature during summer visits to Lake George B. O\u0027Keeffe disliked spending time in the mountains with her husband\u0027s family C. O\u0027Keeffe only painted small, detailed miniatures that were hard to see D. O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s husband did not like her art and told her to stop painting","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe spent summers at her husband\u0027s family home, in the village of Lake George in the Adirondack Mountains of New York. While there, she began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range, as if she were looking through a magnifying glass.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"O\u0027Keeffe painted large, close-up images of nature during summer visits to Lake George","B":"O\u0027Keeffe disliked spending time in the mountains with her husband\u0027s family","C":"O\u0027Keeffe only painted small, detailed miniatures that were hard to see","D":"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s husband did not like her art and told her to stop painting"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt explains that during summers at Lake George, O\u0027Keeffe \"began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range,\" which is the key point.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe spent summers at her husband\u0027s family home, in the village of Lake George in the Adirondack Mountains of New York. While there, she began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range, as if she were looking through a magnifying glass.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q009","read_aloud":"If you were an artist visiting New Mexico for the first time, what might inspire your artwork based on O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s experience? A. The unique desert landscape with rocks, bones, and wide open spaces B. Only the cities and buildings in the area with busy streets C. Copying paintings you saw in museums without adding your own ideas D. Ignoring the landscape and painting only from your memory of other places","excerpt":"\"In the late 1920s, she became fascinated with the landscapes of the Southwest. In the deserts of New Mexico, she found rough terrain with monumental rocks and animal bones that were partly buried in the arid ground.\"","stem":"If you were an artist visiting New Mexico for the first time, what might inspire your artwork based on O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s experience?","choices":{"A":"The unique desert landscape with rocks, bones, and wide open spaces","B":"Only the cities and buildings in the area with busy streets","C":"Copying paintings you saw in museums without adding your own ideas","D":"Ignoring the landscape and painting only from your memory of other places"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"O\u0027Keeffe was inspired by New Mexico\u0027s \"rough terrain,\" \"monumental rocks,\" and \"animal bones.\" An artist following her example might find similar inspiration in the distinctive desert environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In the late 1920s, she became fascinated with the landscapes of the Southwest. In the deserts of New Mexico, she found rough terrain with monumental rocks and animal bones that were partly buried in the arid ground.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q010","read_aloud":"How did O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s feelings about New Mexico influence her life choices? A. Her inspiration and sense of freedom led her to buy a home there and eventually move permanently B. She felt bored in New Mexico and left as soon as possible to go somewhere else C. She only visited New Mexico once and never returned to paint there again D. She painted New Mexico but preferred living in New York for the rest of her life","excerpt":"\"In New Mexico, she felt inspired and felt a new freedom to paint. In 1934, O\u0027Keeffe bought a home in New Mexico, in the desert she so often painted. Then, after 1946, O\u0027Keeffe decided to move to New Mexico permanently.\"","stem":"How did O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s feelings about New Mexico influence her life choices?","choices":{"A":"Her inspiration and sense of freedom led her to buy a home there and eventually move permanently","B":"She felt bored in New Mexico and left as soon as possible to go somewhere else","C":"She only visited New Mexico once and never returned to paint there again","D":"She painted New Mexico but preferred living in New York for the rest of her life"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows a cause-and-effect chain: feeling \"inspired\" and having \"new freedom\" in New Mexico led O\u0027Keeffe to buy a home there and later move permanently.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In New Mexico, she felt inspired and felt a new freedom to paint. In 1934, O\u0027Keeffe bought a home in New Mexico, in the desert she so often painted. Then, after 1946, O\u0027Keeffe decided to move to New Mexico permanently.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"terrain\" mean? A. Type of weather B. Type of land or ground C. Type of animal D. Type of building","excerpt":"\"In the deserts of New Mexico, she found rough terrain with monumental rocks and animal bones that were partly buried in the arid ground.\"","stem":"What does \"terrain\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Type of weather","B":"Type of land or ground","C":"Type of animal","D":"Type of building"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Terrain means the features of an area of land.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In the deserts of New Mexico, she found rough terrain with monumental rocks and animal bones that were partly buried in the arid ground.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q012","read_aloud":"How did O\u0027Keeffe feel in New Mexico? A. Bored and trapped B. Inspired and free C. Sad and lonely D. Angry and tired","excerpt":"\"In New Mexico, she felt inspired and felt a new freedom to paint.\"","stem":"How did O\u0027Keeffe feel in New Mexico?","choices":{"A":"Bored and trapped","B":"Inspired and free","C":"Sad and lonely","D":"Angry and tired"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says she felt inspired and a new freedom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In New Mexico, she felt inspired and felt a new freedom to paint.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q013","read_aloud":"What can you infer about O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s feelings for the Southwest? A. She disliked it. B. She loved it more than any other place. C. She thought it was dangerous. D. She never wanted to paint it.","excerpt":"\"She said of the Southwest, \u0027To me it is the best place in the world.\u0027\"","stem":"What can you infer about O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s feelings for the Southwest?","choices":{"A":"She disliked it.","B":"She loved it more than any other place.","C":"She thought it was dangerous.","D":"She never wanted to paint it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calling it \"the best place in the world\" shows deep love.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She said of the Southwest, \u0027To me it is the best place in the world.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q014","read_aloud":"What pattern do you notice about what O\u0027Keeffe painted? A. She only painted flowers. B. She painted places she visited on her journeys. C. She only painted cities. D. She never painted nature.","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe continued traveling and discovering new places. Some of her artworks reflected these journeys. She painted lava bridges in Hawaii, the mountain peaks of Peru, and Mount Fuji in Japan.\"","stem":"What pattern do you notice about what O\u0027Keeffe painted?","choices":{"A":"She only painted flowers.","B":"She painted places she visited on her journeys.","C":"She only painted cities.","D":"She never painted nature."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She painted lava bridges, mountain peaks, and Mount Fuji-places she traveled to.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe continued traveling and discovering new places. Some of her artworks reflected these journeys. She painted lava bridges in Hawaii, the mountain peaks of Peru, and Mount Fuji in Japan.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q015","read_aloud":"If you were an artist who loved big, open spaces, what might you paint? A. A crowded city street B. A wide desert with a huge sky C. A small closet D. A tiny room","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe was attracted to big, open spaces, so her work often includes paintings of clouds and endless skies.\"","stem":"If you were an artist who loved big, open spaces, what might you paint?","choices":{"A":"A crowded city street","B":"A wide desert with a huge sky","C":"A small closet","D":"A tiny room"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Big, open spaces like deserts and skies match her interest.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe was attracted to big, open spaces, so her work often includes paintings of clouds and endless skies.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q016","read_aloud":"What are compositions in this context? A. musical songs B. works of art, such as paintings C. mathematical problems D. building designs","excerpt":"\"In 1888, he went to live in the town of Arles in the south of France. There he created some of his best-known compositions, such as Starry Night.\"","stem":"What are compositions in this context?","choices":{"A":"musical songs","B":"works of art, such as paintings","C":"mathematical problems","D":"building designs"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Van Gogh created compositions such as Starry Night. Compositions in this context are works of art, specifically paintings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1888, he went to live in the town of Arles in the south of France. There he created some of his best-known compositions, such as Starry Night.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q017","read_aloud":"Why did Van Gogh\u0027s paintings become brighter and more emotional? A. Because he was sad. B. Because the beautiful landscape and bright light of southern France inspired him. C. Because he ran out of dark paint. D. Because he did not like his old paintings.","excerpt":"\"But the beautiful landscape and the bright light and colors of the South inspired him. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.\"","stem":"Why did Van Gogh\u0027s paintings become brighter and more emotional?","choices":{"A":"Because he was sad.","B":"Because the beautiful landscape and bright light of southern France inspired him.","C":"Because he ran out of dark paint.","D":"Because he did not like his old paintings."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the beautiful landscape and bright light and colors of the South inspired Van Gogh. This caused him to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But the beautiful landscape and the bright light and colors of the South inspired him. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q018","read_aloud":"Why might an artist choose to create abstract art? A. Because they cannot draw realistically. B. Because they want to express feelings and ideas using shapes and colors instead of realistic images. C. Because abstract art is easier to sell. D. Because realistic art is against the law.","excerpt":"\"In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings. Abstract art is a painting or other art form that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way.\"","stem":"Why might an artist choose to create abstract art?","choices":{"A":"Because they cannot draw realistically.","B":"Because they want to express feelings and ideas using shapes and colors instead of realistic images.","C":"Because abstract art is easier to sell.","D":"Because realistic art is against the law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says abstract art doesn\u0027t try to show things realistically. Artists use shapes, colors, and lines to express feelings and ideas in a different way.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings. Abstract art is a painting or other art form that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q019","read_aloud":"How are bones and flowers similar in O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings? A. They are both living things. B. They both show how the desert inspired her. C. They are both found in cities. D. They are both the same color.","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings of bones and flowers seem very different. But they both show how she was inspired by the New Mexico desert.\"","stem":"How are bones and flowers similar in O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings?","choices":{"A":"They are both living things.","B":"They both show how the desert inspired her.","C":"They are both found in cities.","D":"They are both the same color."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says both bones and flowers show how O\u0027Keeffe was inspired by the New Mexico desert. Even though they seem different, they both connect to the same place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings of bones and flowers seem very different. But they both show how she was inspired by the New Mexico desert.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q021","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q022","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They all painted only city buildings. B. They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas. C. They all used only dull, dark colors. D. They all painted exactly the same subjects.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They all painted only city buildings.","B":"They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas.","C":"They all used only dull, dark colors.","D":"They all painted exactly the same subjects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While their subjects varied (flowers, monkeys, tropical islands), they all looked to their environments for personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It is a way to stop painting for a while. B. Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential. C. It makes the artist famous without any work. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It is a way to stop painting for a while.","B":"Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential.","C":"It makes the artist famous without any work.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that by moving away from traditional styles and experimenting, these artists gained recognition and influence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l05-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Kahlo, because she had many health problems. B. Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti. C. O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States. D. None of them, because they did not travel enough.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Kahlo, because she had many health problems.","B":"Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti.","C":"O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States.","D":"None of them, because they did not travel enough."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin\u0027s story involves the most diverse range of locations (Peru, France, Panama, Martinique, Tahiti), making him a primary example of how traveling influences an artist\u0027s entire career. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Picturesque Journeys\" Author: Yanitzia Canetti Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 5, Savvas Learning Company LLC Preview Vocabulary: inspired, express, exhibit, imitated, compositions","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""}]},{"level":6,"level_name":"Level 6","difficulty_band":"strategic","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what are \"compositions\"? Options: A. Types of tropical fruits B. Works of art like paintings C. Types of bamboo huts D. Rules for traveling","excerpt":"\"Gauguin was fascinated by the strength and simplicity of art from Africa, Asia, and Latin America. In Tahiti, he strived to use these qualities in his own artworks. He used vivid colors and simple compositions to paint the tropical environment.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what are \"compositions\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Types of tropical fruits","B":"Works of art like paintings","C":"Types of bamboo huts","D":"Rules for traveling"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text identifies compositions as works of art, such as paintings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin was fascinated by the strength and simplicity of art from Africa, Asia, and Latin America. In Tahiti, he strived to use these qualities in his own artworks. He used vivid colors and simple compositions to paint the tropical environment.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q002","read_aloud":"Why did Gauguin move to Tahiti? Options: A. He wanted to find a better job as a stockbroker. B. He was looking for personal and creative freedom. C. He wanted to paint volcanoes. D. He was forced to move by the government.","excerpt":"\"He thought that this Polynesian island might offer him personal and creative freedom. He moved into a bamboo hut and started to paint the scenery and people of Tahiti.\"","stem":"Why did Gauguin move to Tahiti? Options:","choices":{"A":"He wanted to find a better job as a stockbroker.","B":"He was looking for personal and creative freedom.","C":"He wanted to paint volcanoes.","D":"He was forced to move by the government."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text mentions he hoped the island would provide him with freedom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He thought that this Polynesian island might offer him personal and creative freedom. He moved into a bamboo hut and started to paint the scenery and people of Tahiti.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q003","read_aloud":"What does the author mean when saying Gauguin used colors with \"great freedom\"? Options: A. He always used the correct colors for things. B. He was afraid to use bright colors. C. He chose colors based on his feelings, even if they were not realistic. D. He only used green and blue.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin not only used intense, bright colors to reflect the landscape of the Polynesian Islands, but he also used colors with great freedom. For example, he painted grass red if he felt it should be red.\"","stem":"What does the author mean when saying Gauguin used colors with \"great freedom\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"He always used the correct colors for things.","B":"He was afraid to use bright colors.","C":"He chose colors based on his feelings, even if they were not realistic.","D":"He only used green and blue."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The example of him painting grass red shows he chose colors based on how he felt, not reality.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin not only used intense, bright colors to reflect the landscape of the Polynesian Islands, but he also used colors with great freedom. For example, he painted grass red if he felt it should be red.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q004","read_aloud":"Based on this quote, how did Gauguin feel about \"civilization\"? Options: A. He loved it and wanted more of it. B. He wanted to get away from its influence. C. He thought it was the best place for art. D. He thought it was too cheap.","excerpt":"\"I am leaving in order to have peace and quiet, to be rid of the influence of civilization... I want only to do simple, very simple art.\"","stem":"Based on this quote, how did Gauguin feel about \"civilization\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"He loved it and wanted more of it.","B":"He wanted to get away from its influence.","C":"He thought it was the best place for art.","D":"He thought it was too cheap."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin wrote that he wanted to be \"rid of the influence of civilization\".","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"I am leaving in order to have peace and quiet, to be rid of the influence of civilization... I want only to do simple, very simple art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q005","read_aloud":"Why did Gauguin use techniques from other cultures in his art? Options: A. He was trying to copy the style of other French artists. B. He was fascinated by their strength and simplicity. C. He thought it would make him rich. D. He was told it was the only way to paint in Tahiti.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin was fascinated by the strength and simplicity of art from Africa, Asia, and Latin America. In Tahiti, he strived to use these qualities in his own artworks.\"","stem":"Why did Gauguin use techniques from other cultures in his art? Options:","choices":{"A":"He was trying to copy the style of other French artists.","B":"He was fascinated by their strength and simplicity.","C":"He thought it would make him rich.","D":"He was told it was the only way to paint in Tahiti."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explicitly states he was fascinated by the qualities of art from those regions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin was fascinated by the strength and simplicity of art from Africa, Asia, and Latin America. In Tahiti, he strived to use these qualities in his own artworks.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q006","read_aloud":"In this context, what does \"compositions\" most likely mean? A. works of art, such as paintings and songs, created by artists B. scientific reports about travel destinations and their features C. maps showing different countries and landscapes around the world D. letters written to family members while traveling to new places","excerpt":"\"She painted lava bridges in Hawaii, the mountain peaks of Peru, and Mount Fuji in Japan. O\u0027Keeffe was attracted to big, open spaces, so her work often includes paintings of clouds and endless skies.\"","stem":"In this context, what does \"compositions\" most likely mean?","choices":{"A":"works of art, such as paintings and songs, created by artists","B":"scientific reports about travel destinations and their features","C":"maps showing different countries and landscapes around the world","D":"letters written to family members while traveling to new places"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The preview vocabulary defines \"compositions\" as \"works of art, such as paintings and songs.\" This fits the context of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s artwork.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She painted lava bridges in Hawaii, the mountain peaks of Peru, and Mount Fuji in Japan. O\u0027Keeffe was attracted to big, open spaces, so her work often includes paintings of clouds and endless skies.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q007","read_aloud":"What does O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s quote reveal about her relationship with the Southwest? A. She felt a strong connection to the place and wanted to keep painting it B. She was afraid of the lonely feeling and avoided returning to the area C. She thought the Southwest was boring and uninteresting for artists D. She only painted the Southwest because other artists told her to do so","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe took many exploratory drives across the Southwest. After one of her trips, she said, \u0027Such a beautiful, untouched, lonely-feeling place.... It is a place I have painted before... even now I must do it again.\u0027\"","stem":"What does O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s quote reveal about her relationship with the Southwest?","choices":{"A":"She felt a strong connection to the place and wanted to keep painting it","B":"She was afraid of the lonely feeling and avoided returning to the area","C":"She thought the Southwest was boring and uninteresting for artists","D":"She only painted the Southwest because other artists told her to do so"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"O\u0027Keeffe calls the Southwest \"beautiful\" and says \"I must do it again,\" showing her ongoing desire to paint this place she felt connected to.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe took many exploratory drives across the Southwest. After one of her trips, she said, \u0027Such a beautiful, untouched, lonely-feeling place.... It is a place I have painted before... even now I must do it again.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q008","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. O\u0027Keeffe painted diverse subjects and influenced other artists through her work B. O\u0027Keeffe only painted flowers and nothing else throughout her career C. O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings were not popular with other artists at the time D. O\u0027Keeffe copied the styles of artists who came before her without changes","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings were of oversized flowers, cityscapes, rugged landscapes, remote hills, lonely crosses, and images of bones against the desert sky. Through them, O\u0027Keeffe greatly influenced other artists of the twentieth century.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"O\u0027Keeffe painted diverse subjects and influenced other artists through her work","B":"O\u0027Keeffe only painted flowers and nothing else throughout her career","C":"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings were not popular with other artists at the time","D":"O\u0027Keeffe copied the styles of artists who came before her without changes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt lists the variety of subjects O\u0027Keeffe painted and states she \"greatly influenced other artists,\" which together form the main idea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings were of oversized flowers, cityscapes, rugged landscapes, remote hills, lonely crosses, and images of bones against the desert sky. Through them, O\u0027Keeffe greatly influenced other artists of the twentieth century.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q009","read_aloud":"Based on the pattern shown with Kahlo and O\u0027Keeffe, what might you predict about Gauguin\u0027s art? A. His travels and cultural background likely influenced the themes and styles in his paintings B. He probably painted only scenes from Paris and never traveled to other places C. He likely ignored his cultural background in his artwork and copied others D. He probably copied other artists instead of developing his own unique style","excerpt":"\"Like both Frida Kahlo and Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, the French artist Paul Gauguin was greatly influenced by his cultural background and travels. Gauguin was born in Paris, France, in 1848. His family left Paris to move to South America while he was still very young.\"","stem":"Based on the pattern shown with Kahlo and O\u0027Keeffe, what might you predict about Gauguin\u0027s art?","choices":{"A":"His travels and cultural background likely influenced the themes and styles in his paintings","B":"He probably painted only scenes from Paris and never traveled to other places","C":"He likely ignored his cultural background in his artwork and copied others","D":"He probably copied other artists instead of developing his own unique style"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text establishes that both Kahlo and O\u0027Keeffe were \"greatly influenced by their cultural background and travels.\" Since Gauguin is introduced with the same pattern, readers can predict his art was similarly influenced.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Like both Frida Kahlo and Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, the French artist Paul Gauguin was greatly influenced by his cultural background and travels. Gauguin was born in Paris, France, in 1848. His family left Paris to move to South America while he was still very young.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q010","read_aloud":"How did Gauguin\u0027s childhood experiences in Peru connect to his later interest in art? A. The colorful objects and costumes he saw as a child helped spark his artistic interest B. He disliked the pottery and costumes, which made him want to paint different things C. His mother forced him to become an artist against his will when he was young D. He forgot about Peru and only painted French scenes as an adult artist","excerpt":"\"Paul spent his childhood in Lima, Peru, surrounded by South American pottery and other objects that his mother loved. His mother also liked to dress in colorful traditional costumes of Lima. All of these things helped spark Gauguin\u0027s interest in art and creativity.\"","stem":"How did Gauguin\u0027s childhood experiences in Peru connect to his later interest in art?","choices":{"A":"The colorful objects and costumes he saw as a child helped spark his artistic interest","B":"He disliked the pottery and costumes, which made him want to paint different things","C":"His mother forced him to become an artist against his will when he was young","D":"He forgot about Peru and only painted French scenes as an adult artist"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text uses \"helped spark\" to show the connection: Gauguin\u0027s exposure to colorful South American objects and costumes in childhood contributed to his developing interest in art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Paul spent his childhood in Lima, Peru, surrounded by South American pottery and other objects that his mother loved. His mother also liked to dress in colorful traditional costumes of Lima. All of these things helped spark Gauguin\u0027s interest in art and creativity.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q011","read_aloud":"What is an \"exhibit\"? A. A group of artworks arranged for public viewing B. A single painting hidden in a closet C. A type of paintbrush D. A ticket to a museum","excerpt":"\"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"What is an \"exhibit\"?","choices":{"A":"A group of artworks arranged for public viewing","B":"A single painting hidden in a closet","C":"A type of paintbrush","D":"A ticket to a museum"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"An exhibit is a public showing of art or objects.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q012","read_aloud":"Where did Gauguin live first? A. Lima, Peru B. Paris, France C. Martinique D. Tahiti","excerpt":"\"Paul Gauguin was born in Paris, France, in 1848. His family left Paris to move to South America while he was still very young. Paul spent his childhood in Lima, Peru.\"","stem":"Where did Gauguin live first?","choices":{"A":"Lima, Peru","B":"Paris, France","C":"Martinique","D":"Tahiti"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He was born in Paris, so that was first.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Paul Gauguin was born in Paris, France, in 1848. His family left Paris to move to South America while he was still very young. Paul spent his childhood in Lima, Peru.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q013","read_aloud":"Why did Gauguin become a full-time painter? A. He won a contest. B. He lost his job when the stock market crashed. C. His family forced him. D. He was tired of painting.","excerpt":"\"In 1882, the stock market crashed in France, and Gauguin lost his job. He decided to take the risk of becoming a full-time painter.\"","stem":"Why did Gauguin become a full-time painter?","choices":{"A":"He won a contest.","B":"He lost his job when the stock market crashed.","C":"His family forced him.","D":"He was tired of painting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Losing his job led him to paint full-time.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1882, the stock market crashed in France, and Gauguin lost his job. He decided to take the risk of becoming a full-time painter.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q014","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about Gauguin\u0027s personality? A. He wanted to be like everyone else. B. He wanted to be original and unique. C. He was afraid of trying new things. D. He copied other artists.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about Gauguin\u0027s personality?","choices":{"A":"He wanted to be like everyone else.","B":"He wanted to be original and unique.","C":"He was afraid of trying new things.","D":"He copied other artists."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He didn\u0027t want to imitate; he wanted to be different.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q015","read_aloud":"Why might an artist keep using sketches from a trip long after the trip is over? A. Because they ran out of paint B. Because the trip was a strong source of inspiration C. Because they forgot how to draw D. Because they lost their other paintings","excerpt":"\"After he left the island, he used sketches he made in Martinique as the basis of many more paintings. The people of Martinique remained a popular subject in his artworks.\"","stem":"Why might an artist keep using sketches from a trip long after the trip is over?","choices":{"A":"Because they ran out of paint","B":"Because the trip was a strong source of inspiration","C":"Because they forgot how to draw","D":"Because they lost their other paintings"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The trip inspired him, so he kept using those ideas.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After he left the island, he used sketches he made in Martinique as the basis of many more paintings. The people of Martinique remained a popular subject in his artworks.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the author say the artists were \"inspired\" by their journeys? A. Because journeys made them stop painting. B. Because journeys gave them new ideas for their art. C. Because journeys made them forget about art. D. Because journeys were boring.","excerpt":"\"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys. Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\"","stem":"Why does the author say the artists were \"inspired\" by their journeys?","choices":{"A":"Because journeys made them stop painting.","B":"Because journeys gave them new ideas for their art.","C":"Because journeys made them forget about art.","D":"Because journeys were boring."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says visiting different places inspired the themes, colors, and styles of their works. Journeys gave them new ideas and experiences to use in their art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys. Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q017","read_aloud":"AND \"After her husband\u0027s death, O\u0027Keeffe moved to New Mexico. She spent the rest of her life there, painting the desert and its flowers, mountains, and bones. How were Kahlo and O\u0027Keeffe similar in their art? A. Both painted only portraits of people. B. Both were inspired by places they lived in or missed. C. Both only painted in black and white. D. Both never traveled anywhere.","excerpt":"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.","stem":"AND \"After her husband\u0027s death, O\u0027Keeffe moved to New Mexico. She spent the rest of her life there, painting the desert and its flowers, mountains, and bones. How were Kahlo and O\u0027Keeffe similar in their art?","choices":{"A":"Both painted only portraits of people.","B":"Both were inspired by places they lived in or missed.","C":"Both only painted in black and white.","D":"Both never traveled anywhere."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Kahlo painted objects from her Mexican heritage because she missed her homeland. O\u0027Keeffe painted the New Mexico desert because she lived there. Both were inspired by places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q018","read_aloud":"What evidence shows that Van Gogh changed his painting style? A. He stopped painting completely. B. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion after moving to the South. C. He only painted at night. D. He used only one color.","excerpt":"\"But the beautiful landscape and the bright light and colors of the South inspired him. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.\"","stem":"What evidence shows that Van Gogh changed his painting style?","choices":{"A":"He stopped painting completely.","B":"He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion after moving to the South.","C":"He only painted at night.","D":"He used only one color."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly states that Van Gogh began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion. This is evidence that his style changed after moving to southern France.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But the beautiful landscape and the bright light and colors of the South inspired him. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q019","read_aloud":"How might Van Gogh\u0027s family background have influenced his interest in art? A. His family had nothing to do with art. B. His mother came from a family of art dealers, which may have exposed him to art. C. His father was a painter. D. His family did not support his interest in art.","excerpt":"\"Van Gogh was born in 1853 in Groot Zundert, a small town in the Netherlands. His father was a minister, and his mother came from a wealthy family of art dealers.\"","stem":"How might Van Gogh\u0027s family background have influenced his interest in art?","choices":{"A":"His family had nothing to do with art.","B":"His mother came from a family of art dealers, which may have exposed him to art.","C":"His father was a painter.","D":"His family did not support his interest in art."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Van Gogh\u0027s mother came from a wealthy family of art dealers. This family connection likely exposed him to art from an early age and influenced his interest.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Van Gogh was born in 1853 in Groot Zundert, a small town in the Netherlands. His father was a minister, and his mother came from a wealthy family of art dealers.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q020","read_aloud":"Why might Arles be important in art history? A. Because it is a very large city. B. Because Van Gogh created some of his best-known paintings there. C. Because no artists ever visited there. D. Because it is the capital of France.","excerpt":"\"In 1888, he went to live in the town of Arles in the south of France. There he created some of his best-known compositions, such as Starry Night.\"","stem":"Why might Arles be important in art history?","choices":{"A":"Because it is a very large city.","B":"Because Van Gogh created some of his best-known paintings there.","C":"Because no artists ever visited there.","D":"Because it is the capital of France."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Van Gogh created some of his best-known compositions, such as Starry Night, in Arles. This makes Arles an important place in art history.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1888, he went to live in the town of Arles in the south of France. There he created some of his best-known compositions, such as Starry Night.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q022","read_aloud":"What should readers understand about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What should readers understand about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q023","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q024","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They all painted only city buildings. B. They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas. C. They all used only dull, dark colors. D. They all painted exactly the same subjects.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They all painted only city buildings.","B":"They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas.","C":"They all used only dull, dark colors.","D":"They all painted exactly the same subjects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While their subjects varied (flowers, monkeys, tropical islands), they all looked to their environments for personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l06-q025","read_aloud":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It is a way to stop painting for a while. B. Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential. C. It makes the artist famous without any work. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"How does the detail in the excerpt help answer ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It is a way to stop painting for a while.","B":"Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential.","C":"It makes the artist famous without any work.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that by moving away from traditional styles and experimenting, these artists gained recognition and influence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""}]},{"level":7,"level_name":"Level 7","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q001","read_aloud":"If an artist \"inspires\" others, what have they likely done? Options: A. They have taught others to paint in a way that gives them new ideas. B. They have ignored all other artists. C. They have traveled to fewer places than anyone else. D. They have stopped others from painting.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style. That style made her one of the world\u0027s most famous artists, one who has inspired many others.\"","stem":"If an artist \"inspires\" others, what have they likely done? Options:","choices":{"A":"They have taught others to paint in a way that gives them new ideas.","B":"They have ignored all other artists.","C":"They have traveled to fewer places than anyone else.","D":"They have stopped others from painting."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"To inspire is to affect someone in a way that encourages them to create or act, which is what influential artists do for others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style. That style made her one of the world\u0027s most famous artists, one who has inspired many others.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q002","read_aloud":"How does the author explain the connection between Kahlo\u0027s background and her art? Options: A. Her background had no effect on her art. B. She only painted things she saw in the United States. C. Her background and love for her home influenced the objects she chose to paint. D. She only painted landscapes of cities.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo\u0027s diverse background helped define both her identity and her vision of the world... Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"How does the author explain the connection between Kahlo\u0027s background and her art? Options:","choices":{"A":"Her background had no effect on her art.","B":"She only painted things she saw in the United States.","C":"Her background and love for her home influenced the objects she chose to paint.","D":"She only painted landscapes of cities."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text links her diverse identity and her longing for her homeland to the specific objects in her paintings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo\u0027s diverse background helped define both her identity and her vision of the world... Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q003","read_aloud":"How do we know O\u0027Keeffe loved the Southwest? Options: A. She moved away quickly. B. She never painted anything there. C. She bought a home there and called it the best place in the world. D. She only visited there for one day.","excerpt":"\"In 1934, O\u0027Keeffe bought a home in New Mexico... O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s famous paintings of New Mexico include Black Cross, New Mexico and Dead Tree with Pink Hill. She said of the Southwest, \u0027To me it is the best place in the world.\u0027\"","stem":"How do we know O\u0027Keeffe loved the Southwest? Options:","choices":{"A":"She moved away quickly.","B":"She never painted anything there.","C":"She bought a home there and called it the best place in the world.","D":"She only visited there for one day."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text mentions both her purchasing a home and her direct quote about it being the best place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1934, O\u0027Keeffe bought a home in New Mexico... O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s famous paintings of New Mexico include Black Cross, New Mexico and Dead Tree with Pink Hill. She said of the Southwest, \u0027To me it is the best place in the world.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q004","read_aloud":"Why does the author compare Kahlo\u0027s paintings to \"visual autobiographies\"? Options: A. Because they are always about historical figures from books. B. Because they tell the story of her life and feelings through pictures. C. Because she only painted portraits of famous authors. D. Because she always wrote words on her paintings.","excerpt":"\"No matter where Kahlo lived, she made paintings that were like visual autobiographies. Every painting tells the story of something remarkable she lived through and how she felt about it.\"","stem":"Why does the author compare Kahlo\u0027s paintings to \"visual autobiographies\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they are always about historical figures from books.","B":"Because they tell the story of her life and feelings through pictures.","C":"Because she only painted portraits of famous authors.","D":"Because she always wrote words on her paintings."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An autobiography is the story of a person\u0027s life, so a \"visual\" one tells that story through art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No matter where Kahlo lived, she made paintings that were like visual autobiographies. Every painting tells the story of something remarkable she lived through and how she felt about it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q005","read_aloud":"How did Gauguin\u0027s interest in local history change his paintings? Options: A. He stopped using color. B. He added religious symbols and stories from the islands. C. He started painting only ships. D. He moved back to France to finish them.","excerpt":"\"In Tahiti, he strived to use these qualities in his own artworks... Gauguin also was inspired by the history and the stories of the Pacific Islands. He began to add elements of these stories, such as religious symbols, to his paintings.\"","stem":"How did Gauguin\u0027s interest in local history change his paintings? Options:","choices":{"A":"He stopped using color.","B":"He added religious symbols and stories from the islands.","C":"He started painting only ships.","D":"He moved back to France to finish them."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that he added elements like religious symbols inspired by the local stories.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In Tahiti, he strived to use these qualities in his own artworks... Gauguin also was inspired by the history and the stories of the Pacific Islands. He began to add elements of these stories, such as religious symbols, to his paintings.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q006","read_aloud":"Based on the preview vocabulary, what does it mean to \"imitate\" in art? A. to copy; to try to do the same things others did in their artwork B. to create something completely original and new without copying C. to travel to different countries for inspiration and new ideas D. to sell artwork to wealthy collectors and become famous","excerpt":"\"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone.\"","stem":"Based on the preview vocabulary, what does it mean to \"imitate\" in art?","choices":{"A":"to copy; to try to do the same things others did in their artwork","B":"to create something completely original and new without copying","C":"to travel to different countries for inspiration and new ideas","D":"to sell artwork to wealthy collectors and become famous"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The preview vocabulary defines \"imitated\" as \"copied; tried to do the same things others did.\" The excerpt shows Gauguin did not want to copy other artists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q007","read_aloud":"What is the contrast between Impressionist art and Gauguin\u0027s new style? A. Impressionists used pastel colors and light effects; Gauguin used bold colors and strong lines B. Impressionists painted only city scenes; Gauguin painted only portraits of people C. Impressionists used bold colors; Gauguin used soft pastel colors in his work D. Impressionists focused on strong lines; Gauguin focused on light effects only","excerpt":"\"In Brittany, he started to move away from the Impressionist style that was so popular at the time. Impressionist art often used pastel colors and focused on the effects of light. Gauguin instead started painting scenes of Brittany\u0027s countryside in bold colors, with strong lines.\"","stem":"What is the contrast between Impressionist art and Gauguin\u0027s new style?","choices":{"A":"Impressionists used pastel colors and light effects; Gauguin used bold colors and strong lines","B":"Impressionists painted only city scenes; Gauguin painted only portraits of people","C":"Impressionists used bold colors; Gauguin used soft pastel colors in his work","D":"Impressionists focused on strong lines; Gauguin focused on light effects only"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt contrasts the two styles: Impressionists \"used pastel colors and focused on the effects of light\" while Gauguin painted \"in bold colors, with strong lines.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In Brittany, he started to move away from the Impressionist style that was so popular at the time. Impressionist art often used pastel colors and focused on the effects of light. Gauguin instead started painting scenes of Brittany\u0027s countryside in bold colors, with strong lines.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q008","read_aloud":"What was the effect of Gauguin\u0027s trip to Martinique on his art? A. He began including tropical landscapes and symbols from the Caribbean in his paintings B. He stopped painting landscapes and only painted portraits of people he met C. He decided to move back to France permanently and never travel again D. He copied the style of artists he met in Panama without adding his own ideas","excerpt":"\"In 1887, after a brief trip to Panama, Gauguin visited the island of Martinique, in the Caribbean. The beauty of the Caribbean landscape amazed him. He also became friendly with people on the island. As the result of this experience, he started to include both tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"What was the effect of Gauguin\u0027s trip to Martinique on his art?","choices":{"A":"He began including tropical landscapes and symbols from the Caribbean in his paintings","B":"He stopped painting landscapes and only painted portraits of people he met","C":"He decided to move back to France permanently and never travel again","D":"He copied the style of artists he met in Panama without adding his own ideas"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text uses \"As the result\" to show cause and effect: Gauguin\u0027s Martinique experience led him to \"include both tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1887, after a brief trip to Panama, Gauguin visited the island of Martinique, in the Caribbean. The beauty of the Caribbean landscape amazed him. He also became friendly with people on the island. As the result of this experience, he started to include both tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q009","read_aloud":"If an artist today felt that their current environment was \"artificial and dull,\" what might they do based on Gauguin\u0027s example? A. Travel to a new place that feels more authentic and inspiring to them B. Stay in the same place and wait for inspiration to come without effort C. Copy the styles of famous artists from their hometown to fit in D. Stop making art altogether because they feel uninspired","excerpt":"\"Gauguin was eager to find another exotic destination that would inspire his creativity. He was tired of European culture. He found it artificial and dull. In 1892, he decided to sail for the island of Tahiti, also known as French Polynesia, in the South Pacific.\"","stem":"If an artist today felt that their current environment was \"artificial and dull,\" what might they do based on Gauguin\u0027s example?","choices":{"A":"Travel to a new place that feels more authentic and inspiring to them","B":"Stay in the same place and wait for inspiration to come without effort","C":"Copy the styles of famous artists from their hometown to fit in","D":"Stop making art altogether because they feel uninspired"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Gauguin responded to feeling that European culture was \"artificial and dull\" by seeking \"another exotic destination\" (Tahiti) to inspire his creativity. An artist following his example might similarly seek a new, inspiring environment.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin was eager to find another exotic destination that would inspire his creativity. He was tired of European culture. He found it artificial and dull. In 1892, he decided to sail for the island of Tahiti, also known as French Polynesia, in the South Pacific.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q010","read_aloud":"How did moving to Tahiti change both Gauguin\u0027s subjects and his artistic goals? A. He painted Tahitian scenery and people while seeking simpler, less civilized artistic expression B. He continued painting European scenes but used brighter colors than before C. He stopped painting people and only painted landscapes of the island D. He focused on complex, detailed artwork to impress European audiences back home","excerpt":"\"He moved into a bamboo hut and started to paint the scenery and people of Tahiti. Along with new subjects, he experimented with new techniques and formats. \u0027I am leaving in order to have peace and quiet, to be rid of the influence of civilization,\u0027 he wrote at the time. \u0027I want only to do simple, very simple art....\u0027\"","stem":"How did moving to Tahiti change both Gauguin\u0027s subjects and his artistic goals?","choices":{"A":"He painted Tahitian scenery and people while seeking simpler, less civilized artistic expression","B":"He continued painting European scenes but used brighter colors than before","C":"He stopped painting people and only painted landscapes of the island","D":"He focused on complex, detailed artwork to impress European audiences back home"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt shows Gauguin painted \"scenery and people of Tahiti\" (new subjects) and wanted \"simple, very simple art\" away from \"the influence of civilization\" (new artistic goals).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He moved into a bamboo hut and started to paint the scenery and people of Tahiti. Along with new subjects, he experimented with new techniques and formats. \u0027I am leaving in order to have peace and quiet, to be rid of the influence of civilization,\u0027 he wrote at the time. \u0027I want only to do simple, very simple art....\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"imitated\" mean? A. Created something original B. Copied or tried to do the same as others C. Destroyed old artwork D. Hid paintings from view","excerpt":"\"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different.\"","stem":"What does \"imitated\" mean?","choices":{"A":"Created something original","B":"Copied or tried to do the same as others","C":"Destroyed old artwork","D":"Hid paintings from view"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To imitate means to copy what someone else does.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q012","read_aloud":"How did Gauguin feel about European culture compared to other places? A. He loved European culture. B. He found European culture artificial and dull and wanted something different. C. He thought European culture was perfect. D. He never thought about it.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin was eager to find another exotic destination that would inspire his creativity. He was tired of European culture. He found it artificial and dull.\"","stem":"How did Gauguin feel about European culture compared to other places?","choices":{"A":"He loved European culture.","B":"He found European culture artificial and dull and wanted something different.","C":"He thought European culture was perfect.","D":"He never thought about it."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He was tired of European culture and wanted something more inspiring.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin was eager to find another exotic destination that would inspire his creativity. He was tired of European culture. He found it artificial and dull.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q013","read_aloud":"he wrote. \"I want only to do simple, very simple art. What can you infer about Gauguin\u0027s goal in Tahiti? A. To become rich and famous B. To find peace and make simple, quiet art away from civilization C. To build a big city D. To copy European artists","excerpt":"I am leaving in order to have peace and quiet, to be rid of the influence of civilization,","stem":"he wrote. \"I want only to do simple, very simple art. What can you infer about Gauguin\u0027s goal in Tahiti?","choices":{"A":"To become rich and famous","B":"To find peace and make simple, quiet art away from civilization","C":"To build a big city","D":"To copy European artists"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He wanted peace, quiet, and to make simple art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: I am leaving in order to have peace and quiet, to be rid of the influence of civilization,"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q014","read_aloud":"How was Gauguin\u0027s use of color different from realistic painting? A. He only used black and white. B. He used colors freely, even if they were not realistic. C. He never used bright colors. D. He copied exactly what he saw.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin not only used intense, bright colors to reflect the landscape of the Polynesian Islands, but he also used colors with great freedom. For example, he painted grass red if he felt it should be red.\"","stem":"How was Gauguin\u0027s use of color different from realistic painting?","choices":{"A":"He only used black and white.","B":"He used colors freely, even if they were not realistic.","C":"He never used bright colors.","D":"He copied exactly what he saw."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"He painted grass red if he felt it should be red, not because it was real.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin not only used intense, bright colors to reflect the landscape of the Polynesian Islands, but he also used colors with great freedom. For example, he painted grass red if he felt it should be red.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q015","read_aloud":"If you were an artist inspired by Gauguin, what might you try in your own art? A. Only painting realistic scenes B. Using colors freely and painting simple, bold subjects C. Copying European artists exactly D. Never using bright colors","excerpt":"\"Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art. He inspired artists such as Vincent van Gogh, Henri Matisse, and Pablo Picasso, among others.\"","stem":"If you were an artist inspired by Gauguin, what might you try in your own art?","choices":{"A":"Only painting realistic scenes","B":"Using colors freely and painting simple, bold subjects","C":"Copying European artists exactly","D":"Never using bright colors"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin was known for bold colors and simple, inspired subjects.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art. He inspired artists such as Vincent van Gogh, Henri Matisse, and Pablo Picasso, among others.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q016","read_aloud":"Why did Arthur Wesley Dow think artists should use color, lines, and shading? A. Because those are the only materials artists can use. B. Because those elements help artists show their feelings and ideas. C. Because they are the cheapest materials. D. Because they are the only colors available.","excerpt":"\"There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\"","stem":"Why did Arthur Wesley Dow think artists should use color, lines, and shading?","choices":{"A":"Because those are the only materials artists can use.","B":"Because those elements help artists show their feelings and ideas.","C":"Because they are the cheapest materials.","D":"Because they are the only colors available."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Dow believed artists should express themselves. Color, lines, and shading are tools that help artists communicate their feelings and ideas through their art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q017","read_aloud":"How is the text organized? A. It tells a story about one artist. B. It introduces three artists and explains how travel inspired each of their works. C. It only talks about paintings from one country. D. It is a poem about art.","excerpt":"\"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys.\"","stem":"How is the text organized?","choices":{"A":"It tells a story about one artist.","B":"It introduces three artists and explains how travel inspired each of their works.","C":"It only talks about paintings from one country.","D":"It is a poem about art."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text introduces three artists: Kahlo, O\u0027Keeffe, and Gauguin. For each artist, it explains how their journeys influenced their paintings. This is the structure of the text.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q018","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Stieglitz\u0027s opinion of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work? A. He thought her work was terrible. B. He believed her work was good and worth sharing with others. C. He did not care about her work. D. He wanted to destroy her paintings.","excerpt":"\"In 1917, O\u0027Keeffe met the famous photographer and art dealer Alfred Stieglitz. Stieglitz showed her the work of other modern artists. He encouraged her to continue painting and took some of her drawings to New York.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Stieglitz\u0027s opinion of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work?","choices":{"A":"He thought her work was terrible.","B":"He believed her work was good and worth sharing with others.","C":"He did not care about her work.","D":"He wanted to destroy her paintings."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Stieglitz encouraged O\u0027Keeffe to continue painting and took her drawings to New York to open an exhibit. This shows he believed her work was good and worth sharing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1917, O\u0027Keeffe met the famous photographer and art dealer Alfred Stieglitz. Stieglitz showed her the work of other modern artists. He encouraged her to continue painting and took some of her drawings to New York.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q019","read_aloud":"Why is it important that Kahlo painted her sadness? A. Because sadness is the only thing she could paint. B. Because it shows that art can help people express difficult emotions. C. Because she wanted to make people cry. D. Because she did not know how to paint happy things.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo also painted her sadness about not being able to have children. She had several miscarriages.\"","stem":"Why is it important that Kahlo painted her sadness?","choices":{"A":"Because sadness is the only thing she could paint.","B":"Because it shows that art can help people express difficult emotions.","C":"Because she wanted to make people cry.","D":"Because she did not know how to paint happy things."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Kahlo used her art to express her sadness about not having children. This shows that art can be a way to share and deal with difficult emotions.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo also painted her sadness about not being able to have children. She had several miscarriages.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q020","read_aloud":"What does \"cultural heritage\" mean in this context? A. the traditions, beliefs, and objects passed down from a person\u0027s culture B. the money a person has C. the food a person eats D. the clothes a person buys at a store","excerpt":"\"In many of her paintings, she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"What does \"cultural heritage\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"the traditions, beliefs, and objects passed down from a person\u0027s culture","B":"the money a person has","C":"the food a person eats","D":"the clothes a person buys at a store"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Cultural heritage refers to the traditions, beliefs, and objects from a person\u0027s culture. Kahlo wore jewelry and surrounded herself with objects from her Mexican heritage.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In many of her paintings, she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q021","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q022","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They all painted only city buildings. B. They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas. C. They all used only dull, dark colors. D. They all painted exactly the same subjects.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They all painted only city buildings.","B":"They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas.","C":"They all used only dull, dark colors.","D":"They all painted exactly the same subjects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While their subjects varied (flowers, monkeys, tropical islands), they all looked to their environments for personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l07-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It is a way to stop painting for a while. B. Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential. C. It makes the artist famous without any work. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It is a way to stop painting for a while.","B":"Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential.","C":"It makes the artist famous without any work.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that by moving away from traditional styles and experimenting, these artists gained recognition and influence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""}]},{"level":8,"level_name":"Level 8","difficulty_band":"advanced","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q001","read_aloud":"If an artist were to stop \"imitating\" others, what is the most likely result? Options: A. Their art will look exactly like everyone else\u0027s. B. They will develop their own unique style. C. They will stop painting altogether. D. They will only paint using pencils.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone. In Brittany, he started to move away from the Impressionist style that was so popular at the time. Gauguin instead started painting scenes of Brittany\u0027s countryside in bold colors, with strong lines.\"","stem":"If an artist were to stop \"imitating\" others, what is the most likely result? Options:","choices":{"A":"Their art will look exactly like everyone else\u0027s.","B":"They will develop their own unique style.","C":"They will stop painting altogether.","D":"They will only paint using pencils."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"When someone stops copying, they are free to create their own original work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone. In Brittany, he started to move away from the Impressionist style that was so popular at the time. Gauguin instead started painting scenes of Brittany\u0027s countryside in bold colors, with strong lines.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q002","read_aloud":"How did O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s subjects change when she moved from the city to the Adirondack Mountains? Options: A. She stopped painting entirely. B. She went from painting city buildings to painting close-up nature scenes. C. She started painting only people. D. She went from painting nature to painting only city streets.","excerpt":"\"She made these tall buildings the subjects of such paintings as The Shelton with Sunspots, N.Y.; City Night; and Radiator Building-Night, New York... While there, she began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range, as if she were looking through a magnifying glass.\"","stem":"How did O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s subjects change when she moved from the city to the Adirondack Mountains? Options:","choices":{"A":"She stopped painting entirely.","B":"She went from painting city buildings to painting close-up nature scenes.","C":"She started painting only people.","D":"She went from painting nature to painting only city streets."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows a transition from city subjects to large-scale nature subjects.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"She made these tall buildings the subjects of such paintings as The Shelton with Sunspots, N.Y.; City Night; and Radiator Building-Night, New York... While there, she began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range, as if she were looking through a magnifying glass.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q003","read_aloud":"According to the text, what was the primary benefit of travel for Kahlo\u0027s career? Options: A. It helped her make a lot of money. B. It helped her develop a unique style that influenced others. C. It allowed her to meet all the famous people in the world. D. It helped her forget her past.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style. That style made her one of the world\u0027s most famous artists, one who has influenced many others.\"","stem":"According to the text, what was the primary benefit of travel for Kahlo\u0027s career? Options:","choices":{"A":"It helped her make a lot of money.","B":"It helped her develop a unique style that influenced others.","C":"It allowed her to meet all the famous people in the world.","D":"It helped her forget her past."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text links travel to her identity, her style, and her influence on others.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style. That style made her one of the world\u0027s most famous artists, one who has influenced many others.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q004","read_aloud":"Do you think Kahlo\u0027s decision to paint her homeland instead of the cities she lived in was a good way to show her feelings? Why? Options: A. No, because city buildings are more important than plants. B. Yes, because painting what she missed helped her feel closer to her roots. C. No, because artists should only paint the place they are currently in. D. Yes, because city buildings are easier to paint.","excerpt":"\"Even though she often lived in cities, Kahlo rarely painted urban scenes. She always preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to. Instead of skyscrapers and factory smokestacks, Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland.\"","stem":"Do you think Kahlo\u0027s decision to paint her homeland instead of the cities she lived in was a good way to show her feelings? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"No, because city buildings are more important than plants.","B":"Yes, because painting what she missed helped her feel closer to her roots.","C":"No, because artists should only paint the place they are currently in.","D":"Yes, because city buildings are easier to paint."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Kahlo\u0027s art served as a \"visual autobiography,\" so painting her homeland allowed her to express her true identity and longings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even though she often lived in cities, Kahlo rarely painted urban scenes. She always preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to. Instead of skyscrapers and factory smokestacks, Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q005","read_aloud":"If Gauguin had never traveled, what do you think would have happened to the artists who were inspired by him? Options: A. They would have become exactly the same. B. They might not have been inspired in the same way, and their art could be very different. C. They would have moved to Tahiti on their own. D. They would have stopped painting entirely.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art. He inspired artists such as Vincent van Gogh, Henri Matisse, and Pablo Picasso, among others.\"","stem":"If Gauguin had never traveled, what do you think would have happened to the artists who were inspired by him? Options:","choices":{"A":"They would have become exactly the same.","B":"They might not have been inspired in the same way, and their art could be very different.","C":"They would have moved to Tahiti on their own.","D":"They would have stopped painting entirely."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Since Gauguin\u0027s travel heavily influenced his style, and that style influenced these other famous artists, their work might not have developed the same way without him.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art. He inspired artists such as Vincent van Gogh, Henri Matisse, and Pablo Picasso, among others.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q006","read_aloud":"In the context of art, what does \"compositions\" refer to? A. works of art, such as paintings, and how visual elements are arranged within them B. written essays about travel experiences and personal reflections C. musical scores for traditional Tahitian songs and dances D. scientific diagrams of tropical plants and animals for study","excerpt":"\"He used vivid colors and simple compositions to paint the tropical environment.\"","stem":"In the context of art, what does \"compositions\" refer to?","choices":{"A":"works of art, such as paintings, and how visual elements are arranged within them","B":"written essays about travel experiences and personal reflections","C":"musical scores for traditional Tahitian songs and dances","D":"scientific diagrams of tropical plants and animals for study"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The preview vocabulary defines \"compositions\" as \"works of art, such as paintings and songs.\" In art, composition also refers to how visual elements are arranged, which fits the context of Gauguin\u0027s painting approach.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He used vivid colors and simple compositions to paint the tropical environment.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q007","read_aloud":"What pattern shows how Gauguin\u0027s art evolved while in Tahiti? A. He moved from painting landscapes to focusing on people, then added cultural and religious symbols B. He started with religious symbols, then painted people, then painted landscapes of the island C. He only painted landscapes and never included people or cultural symbols in his work D. He copied European styles and avoided Tahitian culture entirely in his paintings","excerpt":"\"Gradually, he began to focus more on the Tahitian people themselves. He painted many scenes of Tahitians doing everyday tasks, such as weaving baskets. Gauguin also was inspired by the history and the stories of the Pacific Islands. He began to add elements of these stories, such as religious symbols, to his paintings.\"","stem":"What pattern shows how Gauguin\u0027s art evolved while in Tahiti?","choices":{"A":"He moved from painting landscapes to focusing on people, then added cultural and religious symbols","B":"He started with religious symbols, then painted people, then painted landscapes of the island","C":"He only painted landscapes and never included people or cultural symbols in his work","D":"He copied European styles and avoided Tahitian culture entirely in his paintings"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt shows a progression: first focusing \"more on the Tahitian people,\" then painting \"everyday tasks,\" then adding \"elements of these stories, such as religious symbols.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gradually, he began to focus more on the Tahitian people themselves. He painted many scenes of Tahitians doing everyday tasks, such as weaving baskets. Gauguin also was inspired by the history and the stories of the Pacific Islands. He began to add elements of these stories, such as religious symbols, to his paintings.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q008","read_aloud":"How did Gauguin\u0027s approach to color show his artistic independence? A. He chose colors based on his feelings rather than strict realism, showing creative freedom B. He always used the exact colors he saw in nature without any changes C. He only used colors that were popular in European art at the time D. He asked other artists to choose colors for his paintings instead of deciding himself","excerpt":"\"Gauguin not only used intense, bright colors to reflect the landscape of the Polynesian Islands, but he also used colors with great freedom. For example, he painted grass red if he felt it should be red.\"","stem":"How did Gauguin\u0027s approach to color show his artistic independence?","choices":{"A":"He chose colors based on his feelings rather than strict realism, showing creative freedom","B":"He always used the exact colors he saw in nature without any changes","C":"He only used colors that were popular in European art at the time","D":"He asked other artists to choose colors for his paintings instead of deciding himself"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows Gauguin used colors \"with great freedom\" and would paint \"grass red if he felt it should be red,\" demonstrating that he prioritized his artistic vision over realistic representation.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin not only used intense, bright colors to reflect the landscape of the Polynesian Islands, but he also used colors with great freedom. For example, he painted grass red if he felt it should be red.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q009","read_aloud":"Based on the entire text, do you think travel is essential for artists to create great work? Use evidence to support your view. A. Yes, because the text shows all three artists developed distinctive styles and themes through their travels B. No, because the text says travel is only important for famous artists who can afford it C. Yes, but only if artists travel to Europe specifically for inspiration D. No, because the text suggests artists should stay in one place to focus on their work","excerpt":"\"Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin are among the many artists whose works have been influenced by their journeys. It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"Based on the entire text, do you think travel is essential for artists to create great work? Use evidence to support your view.","choices":{"A":"Yes, because the text shows all three artists developed distinctive styles and themes through their travels","B":"No, because the text says travel is only important for famous artists who can afford it","C":"Yes, but only if artists travel to Europe specifically for inspiration","D":"No, because the text suggests artists should stay in one place to focus on their work"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text repeatedly shows how each artist\u0027s travels influenced their themes, colors, and styles. The concluding statement that it\u0027s \"impossible to imagine\" their art without travel supports the view that travel was essential to their artistic development.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin are among the many artists whose works have been influenced by their journeys. It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q010","read_aloud":"Do you think using spider monkeys in so many paintings was a good way for Kahlo to show her feelings about home? Why? A. No, because monkeys are scary. B. Yes, because repeating the symbol made it very clear and meaningful. C. No, because 55 is too many. D. Yes, but only because she had no other ideas.","excerpt":"\"To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. … The animals meant so much to her that of 181 works she made in her lifetime, 55 of them include spider monkeys!\"","stem":"Do you think using spider monkeys in so many paintings was a good way for Kahlo to show her feelings about home? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because monkeys are scary.","B":"Yes, because repeating the symbol made it very clear and meaningful.","C":"No, because 55 is too many.","D":"Yes, but only because she had no other ideas."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Repeating a symbol helps the viewer understand its importance.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"To Kahlo, the spider monkey was a symbol of home. … The animals meant so much to her that of 181 works she made in her lifetime, 55 of them include spider monkeys!\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q011","read_aloud":"Why did the author include these specific details about each artist? A. To show that artists never travel B. To show how specific places and events influenced each artist\u0027s work C. To make the text longer D. To prove that accidents are good for art","excerpt":"The author includes details about Kahlo\u0027s bus accident, O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s summers in Lake George, and Gauguin\u0027s trip to Martinique.","stem":"Why did the author include these specific details about each artist?","choices":{"A":"To show that artists never travel","B":"To show how specific places and events influenced each artist\u0027s work","C":"To make the text longer","D":"To prove that accidents are good for art"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Each detail shows how a place or event affected the artist\u0027s art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The author includes details about Kahlo\u0027s bus accident, O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s summers in Lake George, and Gauguin\u0027s trip to Martinique."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q012","read_aloud":"Do you agree with this statement? Why? A. No, because artists can make art anywhere. B. Yes, because the text shows how travel inspired their themes, colors, and styles. C. No, because travel is not important. D. Yes, but only for Kahlo.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"Do you agree with this statement? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because artists can make art anywhere.","B":"Yes, because the text shows how travel inspired their themes, colors, and styles.","C":"No, because travel is not important.","D":"Yes, but only for Kahlo."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows each artist was deeply changed by the places they visited.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q013","read_aloud":"Imagine you are an artist about to travel to a new place. Based on these artists, what would you bring to capture your experience? A. Only a camera B. A sketchbook, paints, and an open mind to be inspired C. A suitcase full of money D. A ticket to return home immediately","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"Imagine you are an artist about to travel to a new place. Based on these artists, what would you bring to capture your experience?","choices":{"A":"Only a camera","B":"A sketchbook, paints, and an open mind to be inspired","C":"A suitcase full of money","D":"A ticket to return home immediately"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The artists used art supplies and openness to new experiences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q014","read_aloud":"Why was Stieglitz opening an exhibit important for O\u0027Keeffe? A. It meant no one would see her work. B. It gave her work public attention and helped her become known as an artist. C. It meant she had to stop painting. D. It made her work less valuable.","excerpt":"\"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"Why was Stieglitz opening an exhibit important for O\u0027Keeffe?","choices":{"A":"It meant no one would see her work.","B":"It gave her work public attention and helped her become known as an artist.","C":"It meant she had to stop painting.","D":"It made her work less valuable."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An exhibit allows the public to see an artist\u0027s work. Stieglitz opening O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s first exhibit gave her public attention and helped launch her career.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q015","read_aloud":"Why does the author write about these three artists? A. To show that artists should never travel. B. To show how traveling to different places can inspire great art. C. To criticize their paintings. D. To prove that only three artists are important.","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\"","stem":"Why does the author write about these three artists?","choices":{"A":"To show that artists should never travel.","B":"To show how traveling to different places can inspire great art.","C":"To criticize their paintings.","D":"To prove that only three artists are important."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author introduces three artists to show how their journeys inspired their best works. The purpose is to demonstrate the connection between travel and artistic inspiration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q016","read_aloud":"Why does the author include a definition of abstract art? A. To confuse the reader. B. To help readers understand a style of art they may not be familiar with. C. To show that abstract art is bad. D. To make the text longer.","excerpt":"\"In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings. Abstract art is a painting or other art form that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way.\"","stem":"Why does the author include a definition of abstract art?","choices":{"A":"To confuse the reader.","B":"To help readers understand a style of art they may not be familiar with.","C":"To show that abstract art is bad.","D":"To make the text longer."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author defines abstract art to help readers understand what it is. This is important because readers may not know that abstract art does not show things realistically.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1915, she began a series of abstract drawings. Abstract art is a painting or other art form that doesn\u0027t try to show people, places, or things in a realistic way.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q017","read_aloud":"Why might Detroit have influenced Kahlo more than San Francisco? A. Because Detroit was colder and more industrial, which was very different from her warm, colorful Mexico. B. Because San Francisco was exactly like Mexico. C. Because Kahlo never visited San Francisco. D. Because Detroit had better food.","excerpt":"\"But it was time spent in another American city-Detroit, Michigan-that began to influence Kahlo\u0027s paintings.\"","stem":"Why might Detroit have influenced Kahlo more than San Francisco?","choices":{"A":"Because Detroit was colder and more industrial, which was very different from her warm, colorful Mexico.","B":"Because San Francisco was exactly like Mexico.","C":"Because Kahlo never visited San Francisco.","D":"Because Detroit had better food."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text says Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. Detroit was likely very different from Mexico, which may have made her miss home even more and paint objects from her heritage.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But it was time spent in another American city-Detroit, Michigan-that began to influence Kahlo\u0027s paintings.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q018","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s connection to New Mexico? A. She did not like it there. B. She felt deeply connected to the desert and spent her life painting its beauty. C. She only visited once. D. She thought the desert was ugly.","excerpt":"\"After her husband\u0027s death, O\u0027Keeffe moved to New Mexico. She spent the rest of her life there, painting the desert and its flowers, mountains, and bones.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s connection to New Mexico?","choices":{"A":"She did not like it there.","B":"She felt deeply connected to the desert and spent her life painting its beauty.","C":"She only visited once.","D":"She thought the desert was ugly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"O\u0027Keeffe moved to New Mexico after her husband\u0027s death and spent the rest of her life there. She painted the desert, flowers, mountains, and bones. This shows a deep connection to the place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After her husband\u0027s death, O\u0027Keeffe moved to New Mexico. She spent the rest of her life there, painting the desert and its flowers, mountains, and bones.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q019","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q020","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They all painted only city buildings. B. They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas. C. They all used only dull, dark colors. D. They all painted exactly the same subjects.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They all painted only city buildings.","B":"They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas.","C":"They all used only dull, dark colors.","D":"They all painted exactly the same subjects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While their subjects varied (flowers, monkeys, tropical islands), they all looked to their environments for personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It is a way to stop painting for a while. B. Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential. C. It makes the artist famous without any work. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It is a way to stop painting for a while.","B":"Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential.","C":"It makes the artist famous without any work.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that by moving away from traditional styles and experimenting, these artists gained recognition and influence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Kahlo, because she had many health problems. B. Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti. C. O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States. D. None of them, because they did not travel enough.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Kahlo, because she had many health problems.","B":"Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti.","C":"O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States.","D":"None of them, because they did not travel enough."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin\u0027s story involves the most diverse range of locations (Peru, France, Panama, Martinique, Tahiti), making him a primary example of how traveling influences an artist\u0027s entire career. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Picturesque Journeys\" Author: Yanitzia Canetti Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 5, Savvas Learning Company LLC Preview Vocabulary: inspired, express, exhibit, imitated, compositions","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l08-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. caused something to be created; motivated artistic work B. made someone feel tired and sleepy C. confused someone about what to paint D. stopped someone from finishing their artwork","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"caused something to be created; motivated artistic work","B":"made someone feel tired and sleepy","C":"confused someone about what to paint","D":"stopped someone from finishing their artwork"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows locations \"inspired\" painters \"to create their best works.\" This means the places motivated or caused the art to be made.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\""}]},{"level":9,"level_name":"Level 9","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q001","read_aloud":"How does the word \"compositions\" relate to how an artist organizes a painting? Options: A. It refers to the size of the brush used. B. It refers to the arrangement of elements within the work of art. C. It refers to the frame around the painting. D. It refers to the price of the painting.","excerpt":"\"He used vivid colors and simple compositions to paint the tropical environment. Gradually, he began to focus more on the Tahitian people themselves. He painted many scenes of Tahitians doing everyday tasks, such as weaving baskets.\"","stem":"How does the word \"compositions\" relate to how an artist organizes a painting? Options:","choices":{"A":"It refers to the size of the brush used.","B":"It refers to the arrangement of elements within the work of art.","C":"It refers to the frame around the painting.","D":"It refers to the price of the painting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Compositions are works of art, but the term also implies how those works are put together or arranged.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He used vivid colors and simple compositions to paint the tropical environment. Gradually, he began to focus more on the Tahitian people themselves. He painted many scenes of Tahitians doing everyday tasks, such as weaving baskets.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q002","read_aloud":"How did travel change Kahlo as an artist? Options: A. It made her paint more realistic city buildings. B. It helped her clarify her identity and create a unique style. C. It made her dislike all foreign art. D. It made her want to quit painting.","excerpt":"\"Much as she missed Mexico, however, Kahlo\u0027s travels had a major effect on the art she created. Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style.\"","stem":"How did travel change Kahlo as an artist? Options:","choices":{"A":"It made her paint more realistic city buildings.","B":"It helped her clarify her identity and create a unique style.","C":"It made her dislike all foreign art.","D":"It made her want to quit painting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text states travel helped her understand her identity and develop her style.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Much as she missed Mexico, however, Kahlo\u0027s travels had a major effect on the art she created. Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q003","read_aloud":"What does this quote reveal about why O\u0027Keeffe kept painting the same landscape? Options: A. She forgot that she had already painted it. B. She found the beauty of the place so inspiring she wanted to capture it repeatedly. C. She was not allowed to go anywhere else. D. She thought it was the only thing people would buy.","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe took many exploratory drives across the Southwest. After one of her trips, she said, \u0027Such a beautiful, untouched, lonely-feeling place... It is a place I have painted before... even now I must do it again.\u0027\"","stem":"What does this quote reveal about why O\u0027Keeffe kept painting the same landscape? Options:","choices":{"A":"She forgot that she had already painted it.","B":"She found the beauty of the place so inspiring she wanted to capture it repeatedly.","C":"She was not allowed to go anywhere else.","D":"She thought it was the only thing people would buy."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She describes it as a \"beautiful, untouched\" place that she feels a need to paint again, showing strong inspiration.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe took many exploratory drives across the Southwest. After one of her trips, she said, \u0027Such a beautiful, untouched, lonely-feeling place... It is a place I have painted before... even now I must do it again.\u0027\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q004","read_aloud":"Imagine O\u0027Keeffe had not attended that summer class. How might her art be different today? Options: A. She would have continued painting in a purely realistic style. B. She would have painted nothing at all. C. She would have become a photographer instead. D. She would have moved to Japan.","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s style and ideas about art took a turn in 1912 when she attended a summer school class... As a result, the young artist found a new way to share her feelings and ideas through her art.\"","stem":"Imagine O\u0027Keeffe had not attended that summer class. How might her art be different today? Options:","choices":{"A":"She would have continued painting in a purely realistic style.","B":"She would have painted nothing at all.","C":"She would have become a photographer instead.","D":"She would have moved to Japan."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text explicitly states that her series of abstract drawings represented her \"breakup with realism,\" implying she would have stayed with realism otherwise.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s style and ideas about art took a turn in 1912 when she attended a summer school class... As a result, the young artist found a new way to share her feelings and ideas through her art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q005","read_aloud":"Is it better for an artist to follow traditional rules or to use colors with \"great freedom\" like Gauguin? Why? Options: A. Traditional rules are better because they are easier to learn. B. Using colors with freedom is better because it allows for more personal expression. C. Neither approach is good for art. D. Artists should only follow the rules set by their teachers.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin not only used intense, bright colors to reflect the landscape of the Polynesian Islands, but he also used colors with great freedom... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"Is it better for an artist to follow traditional rules or to use colors with \"great freedom\" like Gauguin? Why? Options:","choices":{"A":"Traditional rules are better because they are easier to learn.","B":"Using colors with freedom is better because it allows for more personal expression.","C":"Neither approach is good for art.","D":"Artists should only follow the rules set by their teachers."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"This is an opinion question, but based on the text, Gauguin\u0027s freedom led to his \"huge influence on modern art,\" suggesting that breaking rules can lead to progress and personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin not only used intense, bright colors to reflect the landscape of the Polynesian Islands, but he also used colors with great freedom... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"inspired\" connect the artists\u0027 travels to their artwork? A. It shows that travel caused or motivated the artists to create specific themes, colors, and styles B. It suggests that travel made the artists too tired to work on their paintings C. It means the artists copied each other\u0027s travel experiences in their artwork D. It indicates that the artists avoided painting about places they visited on trips","excerpt":"\"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys. Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\"","stem":"How does the word \"inspired\" connect the artists\u0027 travels to their artwork?","choices":{"A":"It shows that travel caused or motivated the artists to create specific themes, colors, and styles","B":"It suggests that travel made the artists too tired to work on their paintings","C":"It means the artists copied each other\u0027s travel experiences in their artwork","D":"It indicates that the artists avoided painting about places they visited on trips"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The preview vocabulary defines \"inspired\" as \"caused something to be created.\" The excerpt shows travel \"inspired the themes... colors and painting styles,\" meaning journeys motivated specific artistic choices.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys. Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q007","read_aloud":"Excerpt from Kahlo section: \"No matter where Kahlo lived, she made paintings that were like visual autobiographies. Excerpt from O\u0027Keeffe section: \"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings were of oversized flowers, cityscapes, rugged landscapes, remote hills, lonely crosses, and images of bones against the desert sky. How do these excerpts together support the main idea that travel influences art? A. They show that both artists created personal, distinctive work shaped by the places they lived and visited B. They prove that both artists only painted self-portraits of themselves throughout their careers C. They suggest that travel made both artists copy each other\u0027s styles without originality D. They indicate that neither artist was influenced by where they lived or traveled","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from Kahlo section: \"No matter where Kahlo lived, she made paintings that were like visual autobiographies. Excerpt from O\u0027Keeffe section: \"O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s paintings were of oversized flowers, cityscapes, rugged landscapes, remote hills, lonely crosses, and images of bones against the desert sky. How do these excerpts together support the main idea that travel influences art?","choices":{"A":"They show that both artists created personal, distinctive work shaped by the places they lived and visited","B":"They prove that both artists only painted self-portraits of themselves throughout their careers","C":"They suggest that travel made both artists copy each other\u0027s styles without originality","D":"They indicate that neither artist was influenced by where they lived or traveled"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Kahlo\u0027s \"visual autobiographies\" reflected her life experiences across locations, while O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s diverse subjects came from different places she lived. Together, they show how personal artistic expression is shaped by travel and environment.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q008","read_aloud":"What is the cause-and-effect chain described in this excerpt? A. Cause: Gauguin visited different places; Effect: He developed unique style/technique/color experiments; Effect: He influenced modern art and famous artists B. Cause: Gauguin copied European artists; Effect: He became famous; Effect: He stopped traveling to new places C. Cause: Gauguin stayed in France; Effect: He painted only Paris scenes; Effect: He had no influence on other artists D. Cause: Gauguin avoided color experiments; Effect: His style was boring; Effect: No one remembered his work after he died","excerpt":"\"Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art. He inspired artists such as Vincent van Gogh, Henri Matisse, and Pablo Picasso, among others. Today he is known for his unique style and technique, as well as for his experiments with color, all of which were strongly affected by the places he visited and lived.\"","stem":"What is the cause-and-effect chain described in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Cause: Gauguin visited different places; Effect: He developed unique style/technique/color experiments; Effect: He influenced modern art and famous artists","B":"Cause: Gauguin copied European artists; Effect: He became famous; Effect: He stopped traveling to new places","C":"Cause: Gauguin stayed in France; Effect: He painted only Paris scenes; Effect: He had no influence on other artists","D":"Cause: Gauguin avoided color experiments; Effect: His style was boring; Effect: No one remembered his work after he died"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt shows a chain: places Gauguin \"visited and lived\" affected his \"unique style and technique\" and \"experiments with color,\" which in turn gave him \"a huge influence on modern art\" and inspired other famous artists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art. He inspired artists such as Vincent van Gogh, Henri Matisse, and Pablo Picasso, among others. Today he is known for his unique style and technique, as well as for his experiments with color, all of which were strongly affected by the places he visited and lived.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q009","read_aloud":"Do you think artists should include their personal feelings and cultural heritage in their work? Use evidence from the text to support your view. A. Yes, because the text shows Kahlo\u0027s personal feelings and heritage created meaningful, distinctive art that connected with viewers B. No, because artists should only paint what they see, not what they feel inside C. Yes, but only if the artist is famous like Kahlo and has many followers D. No, because personal feelings make art confusing and hard for others to understand","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage. Her use of color, too, often expressed her yearning for home, as well as other powerful feelings.\"","stem":"Do you think artists should include their personal feelings and cultural heritage in their work? Use evidence from the text to support your view.","choices":{"A":"Yes, because the text shows Kahlo\u0027s personal feelings and heritage created meaningful, distinctive art that connected with viewers","B":"No, because artists should only paint what they see, not what they feel inside","C":"Yes, but only if the artist is famous like Kahlo and has many followers","D":"No, because personal feelings make art confusing and hard for others to understand"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows Kahlo\u0027s inclusion of cultural heritage and personal feelings resulted in art that was distinctive and meaningful (\"visual autobiographies\" that help viewers \"understand what was happening at that moment in her life\"). This supports the view that personal expression can create powerful art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage. Her use of color, too, often expressed her yearning for home, as well as other powerful feelings.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q010","read_aloud":"(Weekly Question from text) Based on the text about artists and their travels, if you were to write a short story about someone starting a journey, what two motivations would you include, and why? A. The desire to discover new places that might inspire creativity, and the hope to better understand one\u0027s identity through new experiences, because the texts show travel can spark artistic expression and self-discovery B. The need to escape from all responsibilities forever, and the wish to become instantly famous, because these are exciting goals for any traveler C. The plan to copy famous travelers exactly, and the goal to avoid learning anything new, because these reduce uncertainty and risk D. The intention to stay in one place but imagine traveling, and the hope to never change, because these provide comfort and safety","excerpt":"What motivates people to start a journey?","stem":"(Weekly Question from text) Based on the text about artists and their travels, if you were to write a short story about someone starting a journey, what two motivations would you include, and why?","choices":{"A":"The desire to discover new places that might inspire creativity, and the hope to better understand one\u0027s identity through new experiences, because the texts show travel can spark artistic expression and self-discovery","B":"The need to escape from all responsibilities forever, and the wish to become instantly famous, because these are exciting goals for any traveler","C":"The plan to copy famous travelers exactly, and the goal to avoid learning anything new, because these reduce uncertainty and risk","D":"The intention to stay in one place but imagine traveling, and the hope to never change, because these provide comfort and safety"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows artists traveled to find inspiration (\"different locations have inspired... greatest painters\") and to understand identity (\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity\"). These motivations reflect the texts\u0027 themes of creativity and self-discovery through journeys.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: What motivates people to start a journey?"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q011","read_aloud":"What is a synonym for \"exhibit\"? A. Hidden collection B. Public showing C. Private lesson D. Empty room","excerpt":"\"The famous photographer and art gallery owner Alfred Stieglitz saw O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s abstract drawings and was very impressed. In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"What is a synonym for \"exhibit\"?","choices":{"A":"Hidden collection","B":"Public showing","C":"Private lesson","D":"Empty room"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An exhibit is a public showing of art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"The famous photographer and art gallery owner Alfred Stieglitz saw O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s abstract drawings and was very impressed. In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q012","read_aloud":"Do you think painting grass red is effective in art? Why? A. No, because grass is always green. B. Yes, because art can express feelings, not just show reality. C. No, because red grass is ugly. D. Yes, because all artists paint grass red.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin not only used intense, bright colors to reflect the landscape of the Polynesian Islands, but he also used colors with great freedom. For example, he painted grass red if he felt it should be red.\"","stem":"Do you think painting grass red is effective in art? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because grass is always green.","B":"Yes, because art can express feelings, not just show reality.","C":"No, because red grass is ugly.","D":"Yes, because all artists paint grass red."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Art can be about expression, not just copying real life.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin not only used intense, bright colors to reflect the landscape of the Polynesian Islands, but he also used colors with great freedom. For example, he painted grass red if he felt it should be red.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q013","read_aloud":"O\u0027Keeffe said of the Southwest. What does this quote reveal about O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s perspective on the Southwest? A. She thought it was dangerous. B. She loved it more than any other place. C. She never wanted to see it again. D. She thought it was boring.","excerpt":"To me it is the best place in the world,","stem":"O\u0027Keeffe said of the Southwest. What does this quote reveal about O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s perspective on the Southwest?","choices":{"A":"She thought it was dangerous.","B":"She loved it more than any other place.","C":"She never wanted to see it again.","D":"She thought it was boring."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Calling it the \"best place in the world\" shows deep love.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: To me it is the best place in the world,"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q014","read_aloud":"(about Kahlo) Do you think travel is necessary for an artist to find their style? Why? A. Yes, because no artist can work without traveling. B. No, because some artists find inspiration at home, but travel can help. C. Yes, because the text says so. D. No, because travel is too expensive.","excerpt":"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style.","stem":"(about Kahlo) Do you think travel is necessary for an artist to find their style? Why?","choices":{"A":"Yes, because no artist can work without traveling.","B":"No, because some artists find inspiration at home, but travel can help.","C":"Yes, because the text says so.","D":"No, because travel is too expensive."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Travel helped these artists, but artists can be inspired in many ways.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q015","read_aloud":"If you could add a fourth artist to this text, what kind of artist would you choose and why? A. An artist who never traveled, to show contrast B. A musician instead of a painter, to show other arts C. An artist who painted only in one room, to prove travel is not needed D. All of the above could be interesting","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"If you could add a fourth artist to this text, what kind of artist would you choose and why?","choices":{"A":"An artist who never traveled, to show contrast","B":"A musician instead of a painter, to show other arts","C":"An artist who painted only in one room, to prove travel is not needed","D":"All of the above could be interesting"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"Adding different perspectives could enrich the topic.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q016","read_aloud":"Is \"imitated\" a positive or negative word in this context? Why? A. Negative, because copying is always wrong. B. Positive, because O\u0027Keeffe learned from Dow\u0027s ideas and used them to develop her own style. C. Negative, because O\u0027Keeffe had no original ideas. D. Positive, because Dow forced her to copy him.","excerpt":"\"There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading. She imitated his ideas in her own work.\"","stem":"Is \"imitated\" a positive or negative word in this context? Why?","choices":{"A":"Negative, because copying is always wrong.","B":"Positive, because O\u0027Keeffe learned from Dow\u0027s ideas and used them to develop her own style.","C":"Negative, because O\u0027Keeffe had no original ideas.","D":"Positive, because Dow forced her to copy him."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"\"Imitated\" here is positive. O\u0027Keeffe was inspired by Dow and used his ideas to develop her own work. Learning from others is a normal part of becoming an artist.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"There, she was inspired by the ideas of Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading. She imitated his ideas in her own work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q017","read_aloud":"How does Kahlo\u0027s art help preserve Mexican culture? A. By hiding Mexican traditions. B. By painting objects and jewelry from her cultural heritage, she shares them with the world. C. By only painting American objects. D. By refusing to paint.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"How does Kahlo\u0027s art help preserve Mexican culture?","choices":{"A":"By hiding Mexican traditions.","B":"By painting objects and jewelry from her cultural heritage, she shares them with the world.","C":"By only painting American objects.","D":"By refusing to paint."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Kahlo painted herself with jewelry and objects from her Mexican heritage. By doing this, she shared her culture with people around the world and helped preserve it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q018","read_aloud":"Why does the author mention Starry Night specifically? A. Because it is a famous painting that readers may know. B. Because it is the only painting Van Gogh ever made. C. Because the author does not like it. D. Because it was painted in the Netherlands.","excerpt":"\"In 1888, he went to live in the town of Arles in the south of France. There he created some of his best-known compositions, such as Starry Night.\"","stem":"Why does the author mention Starry Night specifically?","choices":{"A":"Because it is a famous painting that readers may know.","B":"Because it is the only painting Van Gogh ever made.","C":"Because the author does not like it.","D":"Because it was painted in the Netherlands."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Starry Night is one of Van Gogh\u0027s most famous paintings. Mentioning it helps readers connect the text to something they may have seen before, making the information more meaningful.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1888, he went to live in the town of Arles in the south of France. There he created some of his best-known compositions, such as Starry Night.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q019","read_aloud":"How does this show the connection between an artist\u0027s environment and their work? A. It shows that environment has no effect on art. B. It shows that the beautiful, bright South changed Van Gogh\u0027s style to be more colorful and emotional. C. It shows that Van Gogh stopped painting. D. It shows that only dark places inspire art.","excerpt":"\"But the beautiful landscape and the bright light and colors of the South inspired him. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.\"","stem":"How does this show the connection between an artist\u0027s environment and their work?","choices":{"A":"It shows that environment has no effect on art.","B":"It shows that the beautiful, bright South changed Van Gogh\u0027s style to be more colorful and emotional.","C":"It shows that Van Gogh stopped painting.","D":"It shows that only dark places inspire art."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text directly connects the South\u0027s beautiful landscape and bright light to Van Gogh\u0027s change in style. This shows how an artist\u0027s environment can influence their work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But the beautiful landscape and the bright light and colors of the South inspired him. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q020","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q021","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They all painted only city buildings. B. They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas. C. They all used only dull, dark colors. D. They all painted exactly the same subjects.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They all painted only city buildings.","B":"They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas.","C":"They all used only dull, dark colors.","D":"They all painted exactly the same subjects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While their subjects varied (flowers, monkeys, tropical islands), they all looked to their environments for personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It is a way to stop painting for a while. B. Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential. C. It makes the artist famous without any work. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It is a way to stop painting for a while.","B":"Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential.","C":"It makes the artist famous without any work.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that by moving away from traditional styles and experimenting, these artists gained recognition and influence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l09-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Kahlo, because she had many health problems. B. Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti. C. O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States. D. None of them, because they did not travel enough.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Kahlo, because she had many health problems.","B":"Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti.","C":"O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States.","D":"None of them, because they did not travel enough."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin\u0027s story involves the most diverse range of locations (Peru, France, Panama, Martinique, Tahiti), making him a primary example of how traveling influences an artist\u0027s entire career. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Picturesque Journeys\" Author: Yanitzia Canetti Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 5, Savvas Learning Company LLC Preview Vocabulary: inspired, express, exhibit, imitated, compositions","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""}]},{"level":10,"level_name":"Level 10","difficulty_band":"mastery","item_count":25,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q001","read_aloud":"If an artist was invited to put their paintings in a museum, which vocabulary word describes that event? Options: A. Inspired B. Exhibit C. Imitated D. Compositions","excerpt":"\"Notice Generate Questions Connect Respond. First Read... inspiredexpressexhibitimitatedcompositions\"","stem":"If an artist was invited to put their paintings in a museum, which vocabulary word describes that event? Options:","choices":{"A":"Inspired","B":"Exhibit","C":"Imitated","D":"Compositions"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An exhibit is a group of artworks arranged for public viewing.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Notice Generate Questions Connect Respond. First Read... inspiredexpressexhibitimitatedcompositions\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q002","read_aloud":"What is the author\u0027s primary conclusion about the relationship between travel and art for these three individuals? Options: A. Travel is a waste of time for artists. B. Traveling significantly changed their lives and the art they created. C. Art is not influenced by where a person lives. D. Artists should only travel if they lose their jobs.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"What is the author\u0027s primary conclusion about the relationship between travel and art for these three individuals? Options:","choices":{"A":"Travel is a waste of time for artists.","B":"Traveling significantly changed their lives and the art they created.","C":"Art is not influenced by where a person lives.","D":"Artists should only travel if they lose their jobs."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The author states that travel had a major effect and concludes that their lives and art would have been very different without it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q003","read_aloud":"How does the author organize the ideas in this text to prove that travel affects artists? Options: A. By telling a story about one single artist. B. By listing different types of paint. C. By providing three examples of artists and explaining how specific locations changed their work. D. By comparing artists to people who do not travel at all.","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists... visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\"","stem":"How does the author organize the ideas in this text to prove that travel affects artists? Options:","choices":{"A":"By telling a story about one single artist.","B":"By listing different types of paint.","C":"By providing three examples of artists and explaining how specific locations changed their work.","D":"By comparing artists to people who do not travel at all."},"correct_choice":"C","rationale":"The text is structured by detailing the lives and travels of Kahlo, O\u0027Keeffe, and Gauguin to support the main idea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists... visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q004","read_aloud":"Why might an artist want to \"break away\" from the traditions of their culture to create \"simple art\"? Options: A. Because they want to sell their art to fewer people. B. Because they believe that traditional art does not fully express their true vision or feelings. C. Because they cannot afford expensive paints. D. Because they think art should be difficult to understand.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin wrote... \u0027I want only to do simple, very simple art.\u0027... his style began to break away more and more from the traditions of European art. Soon, Gauguin\u0027s use of colors and lines was like no one else\u0027s.\"","stem":"Why might an artist want to \"break away\" from the traditions of their culture to create \"simple art\"? Options:","choices":{"A":"Because they want to sell their art to fewer people.","B":"Because they believe that traditional art does not fully express their true vision or feelings.","C":"Because they cannot afford expensive paints.","D":"Because they think art should be difficult to understand."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin sought \"peace and quiet\" and to be rid of the \"influence of civilization,\" indicating that he found traditional European art limiting for his own creative goals.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin wrote... \u0027I want only to do simple, very simple art.\u0027... his style began to break away more and more from the traditions of European art. Soon, Gauguin\u0027s use of colors and lines was like no one else\u0027s.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q005","read_aloud":"If you were an artist, would you choose to stay in your hometown or travel to a new place to gain inspiration? Explain your reason using the text as a guide. Options: A. Stay home, because the text says artists should paint what they know. B. Travel, because the text proves that new environments can help an artist develop a unique, influential style. C. Stay home, because traveling is too expensive for artists. D. Travel, because it makes you famous quickly.","excerpt":"\"Today her paintings can be found in museums all across the country... her works have been influenced by their journeys. It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"If you were an artist, would you choose to stay in your hometown or travel to a new place to gain inspiration? Explain your reason using the text as a guide. Options:","choices":{"A":"Stay home, because the text says artists should paint what they know.","B":"Travel, because the text proves that new environments can help an artist develop a unique, influential style.","C":"Stay home, because traveling is too expensive for artists.","D":"Travel, because it makes you famous quickly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text consistently argues that travel offers new perspectives, influences themes, and helps artists understand their own identity, leading to more original work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Today her paintings can be found in museums all across the country... her works have been influenced by their journeys. It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q006","read_aloud":"How does the word \"inspired\" work on both a literal and figurative level in this sentence? A. Literally, it means travel motivated artists to paint; figuratively, it suggests places sparked imagination and emotional connection that shaped artistic vision B. It only means artists copied scenes they saw without any emotional connection or personal meaning C. It only refers to the physical act of traveling, not to creativity or imagination or feelings D. It suggests that artists were forced to paint against their will by others who wanted them to travel","excerpt":"\"In their art, these artists captured the landscapes and everyday scenes that inspired their imaginations and affected their art.\"","stem":"How does the word \"inspired\" work on both a literal and figurative level in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"Literally, it means travel motivated artists to paint; figuratively, it suggests places sparked imagination and emotional connection that shaped artistic vision","B":"It only means artists copied scenes they saw without any emotional connection or personal meaning","C":"It only refers to the physical act of traveling, not to creativity or imagination or feelings","D":"It suggests that artists were forced to paint against their will by others who wanted them to travel"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Inspired\" literally means \"caused something to be created\" (travel motivated painting). Figuratively, it suggests places \"inspired their imaginations,\" meaning locations sparked creative ideas and emotional responses that shaped how artists saw and represented the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In their art, these artists captured the landscapes and everyday scenes that inspired their imaginations and affected their art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q007","read_aloud":"Excerpt from beginning: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. Excerpt from end: \"Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin are among the many artists whose works have been influenced by their journeys. It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled. How do these excerpts frame the text\u0027s main argument about travel and art? A. They bookend the text with the claim that travel powerfully influences artists, then support it with three detailed examples showing how journeys shaped each artist\u0027s work B. They suggest that only these three artists were influenced by travel, and no other artists in history C. They argue that travel is dangerous and artists should avoid it to stay safe and focused D. They claim that art is more important than travel, so artists should stay home and paint from memory","excerpt":"","stem":"Excerpt from beginning: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. Excerpt from end: \"Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin are among the many artists whose works have been influenced by their journeys. It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled. How do these excerpts frame the text\u0027s main argument about travel and art?","choices":{"A":"They bookend the text with the claim that travel powerfully influences artists, then support it with three detailed examples showing how journeys shaped each artist\u0027s work","B":"They suggest that only these three artists were influenced by travel, and no other artists in history","C":"They argue that travel is dangerous and artists should avoid it to stay safe and focused","D":"They claim that art is more important than travel, so artists should stay home and paint from memory"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The opening states the main idea (travel affects artists), and the closing reinforces it after providing evidence from three artists\u0027 lives. This structure frames the text as an argument supported by specific examples.","text_evidence":"Use details from the selection to support the answer."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q008","read_aloud":"Why might the author choose this organizational structure for an informational text about multiple artists? A. To help readers see patterns across artists\u0027 experiences while also appreciating each artist\u0027s unique journey and style B. To confuse readers by presenting too much information at once without clear organization C. To argue that one artist is better than the others and should be studied more closely D. To suggest that all artists should travel to the same places to develop similar styles","excerpt":"The text uses a compare-and-contrast structure, presenting each artist\u0027s background, travels, and artistic development in similar sections, while highlighting both similarities (all influenced by travel) and differences (different places, styles, and subjects).","stem":"Why might the author choose this organizational structure for an informational text about multiple artists?","choices":{"A":"To help readers see patterns across artists\u0027 experiences while also appreciating each artist\u0027s unique journey and style","B":"To confuse readers by presenting too much information at once without clear organization","C":"To argue that one artist is better than the others and should be studied more closely","D":"To suggest that all artists should travel to the same places to develop similar styles"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Compare-and-contrast structure allows readers to identify common themes (travel influences art) while also understanding individual differences (Kahlo\u0027s Mexican symbolism, O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s abstract nature, Gauguin\u0027s bold colors). This deepens understanding of both the general idea and specific cases.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The text uses a compare-and-contrast structure, presenting each artist\u0027s background, travels, and artistic development in similar sections, while highlighting both similarities (all influenced by travel) and differences (different places, styles, and subjects)."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q009","read_aloud":"If an artist \"imitated\" another, what did they do? A. They praised the other artist. B. They copied the other artist\u0027s work. C. They destroyed the other artist\u0027s work. D. They taught the other artist.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different.\"","stem":"If an artist \"imitated\" another, what did they do?","choices":{"A":"They praised the other artist.","B":"They copied the other artist\u0027s work.","C":"They destroyed the other artist\u0027s work.","D":"They taught the other artist."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"To imitate means to copy.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q010","read_aloud":"What common effect did new places have on all three artists? A. They all painted only self-portraits. B. They were inspired to use new subjects, colors, and styles. C. They all moved back home immediately. D. They stopped painting altogether.","excerpt":"Review Kahlo (Mexico), O\u0027Keeffe (Southwest), and Gauguin (Tahiti).","stem":"What common effect did new places have on all three artists?","choices":{"A":"They all painted only self-portraits.","B":"They were inspired to use new subjects, colors, and styles.","C":"They all moved back home immediately.","D":"They stopped painting altogether."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Each artist\u0027s work changed because of new places.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Review Kahlo (Mexico), O\u0027Keeffe (Southwest), and Gauguin (Tahiti)."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q011","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about what Kahlo valued most? A. Modern cities and technology B. Her homeland, memories, and cultural identity C. Money and fame D. Other artists\u0027 opinions","excerpt":"\"Even though she often lived in cities, Kahlo rarely painted urban scenes. She always preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about what Kahlo valued most?","choices":{"A":"Modern cities and technology","B":"Her homeland, memories, and cultural identity","C":"Money and fame","D":"Other artists\u0027 opinions"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"She dreamed of returning to her homeland and painted that instead of cities.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Even though she often lived in cities, Kahlo rarely painted urban scenes. She always preferred to paint the world she dreamed of returning to.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q012","read_aloud":"The author organized the text by telling about Kahlo, then O\u0027Keeffe, then Gauguin. If you reorganized it by the places they traveled instead, how might that change the reader\u0027s understanding? A. It would confuse the reader. B. It could show how different artists reacted to similar types of places (like islands or deserts). C. It would make the text longer. D. It would not change anything.","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"The author organized the text by telling about Kahlo, then O\u0027Keeffe, then Gauguin. If you reorganized it by the places they traveled instead, how might that change the reader\u0027s understanding?","choices":{"A":"It would confuse the reader.","B":"It could show how different artists reacted to similar types of places (like islands or deserts).","C":"It would make the text longer.","D":"It would not change anything."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Comparing by place could show similarities across artists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q013","read_aloud":"Which artist do you think was most changed by travel? Support your opinion. A. Kahlo, because she painted her homeland while away B. O\u0027Keeffe, because she moved permanently to New Mexico C. Gauguin, because he left Europe completely and changed his style D. Any answer with good text evidence is acceptable","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"Which artist do you think was most changed by travel? Support your opinion.","choices":{"A":"Kahlo, because she painted her homeland while away","B":"O\u0027Keeffe, because she moved permanently to New Mexico","C":"Gauguin, because he left Europe completely and changed his style","D":"Any answer with good text evidence is acceptable"},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"This is an opinion question. Any choice with strong text support is valid.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q014","read_aloud":"Why does the author use the word \"compositions\" instead of \"paintings\"? A. Because \"compositions\" sounds more formal and artistic. B. Because \"compositions\" only refers to music. C. Because \"paintings\" is too easy to understand. D. Because Van Gogh did not paint.","excerpt":"\"In 1888, he went to live in the town of Arles in the south of France. There he created some of his best-known compositions, such as Starry Night.\"","stem":"Why does the author use the word \"compositions\" instead of \"paintings\"?","choices":{"A":"Because \"compositions\" sounds more formal and artistic.","B":"Because \"compositions\" only refers to music.","C":"Because \"paintings\" is too easy to understand.","D":"Because Van Gogh did not paint."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Compositions\" is a formal artistic term that refers to how an artist arranges elements in a work of art. It sounds more artistic and professional than simply saying \"paintings.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1888, he went to live in the town of Arles in the south of France. There he created some of his best-known compositions, such as Starry Night.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q015","read_aloud":"How does this show that art can be a way to deal with difficult feelings? A. It shows that Kahlo used painting to remember and celebrate her homeland when she missed it. B. It shows that painting makes feelings worse. C. It shows that Kahlo forgot about Mexico. D. It shows that art cannot express feelings.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"How does this show that art can be a way to deal with difficult feelings?","choices":{"A":"It shows that Kahlo used painting to remember and celebrate her homeland when she missed it.","B":"It shows that painting makes feelings worse.","C":"It shows that Kahlo forgot about Mexico.","D":"It shows that art cannot express feelings."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Kahlo missed Mexico, so she painted objects from her heritage. This shows she used art to deal with her feelings of missing home by remembering and celebrating her culture.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q016","read_aloud":"What would have happened if Van Gogh had never moved to the South of France? A. He would have painted the same way forever. B. He might not have discovered his signature bright, emotional style. C. He would have become a musician instead. D. He would have stopped painting completely.","excerpt":"\"But the beautiful landscape and the bright light and colors of the South inspired him. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.\"","stem":"What would have happened if Van Gogh had never moved to the South of France?","choices":{"A":"He would have painted the same way forever.","B":"He might not have discovered his signature bright, emotional style.","C":"He would have become a musician instead.","D":"He would have stopped painting completely."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the South inspired Van Gogh to paint with brighter colors and more emotion. Without moving there, he might not have discovered this important change in his style.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But the beautiful landscape and the bright light and colors of the South inspired him. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q017","read_aloud":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Which answer is best supported by the excerpt about  Use text evidence.?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q018","read_aloud":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"What conclusion should a careful reader draw about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q019","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q020","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They all painted only city buildings. B. They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas. C. They all used only dull, dark colors. D. They all painted exactly the same subjects.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They all painted only city buildings.","B":"They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas.","C":"They all used only dull, dark colors.","D":"They all painted exactly the same subjects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While their subjects varied (flowers, monkeys, tropical islands), they all looked to their environments for personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q021","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It is a way to stop painting for a while. B. Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential. C. It makes the artist famous without any work. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It is a way to stop painting for a while.","B":"Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential.","C":"It makes the artist famous without any work.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that by moving away from traditional styles and experimenting, these artists gained recognition and influence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q022","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Kahlo, because she had many health problems. B. Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti. C. O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States. D. None of them, because they did not travel enough.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Kahlo, because she had many health problems.","B":"Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti.","C":"O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States.","D":"None of them, because they did not travel enough."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin\u0027s story involves the most diverse range of locations (Peru, France, Panama, Martinique, Tahiti), making him a primary example of how traveling influences an artist\u0027s entire career. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Picturesque Journeys\" Author: Yanitzia Canetti Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 5, Savvas Learning Company LLC Preview Vocabulary: inspired, express, exhibit, imitated, compositions","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q023","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. caused something to be created; motivated artistic work B. made someone feel tired and sleepy C. confused someone about what to paint D. stopped someone from finishing their artwork","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"caused something to be created; motivated artistic work","B":"made someone feel tired and sleepy","C":"confused someone about what to paint","D":"stopped someone from finishing their artwork"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows locations \"inspired\" painters \"to create their best works.\" This means the places motivated or caused the art to be made.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q024","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Frida Kahlo was born in Mexico with a diverse family background B. Frida Kahlo did not like her family members C. Mexico City is a very large and busy city D. Frida Kahlo\u0027s father was originally from Spain","excerpt":"\"Frida Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico. Her father was Hungarian, and her mother was of Spanish and Mexican Indian descent.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Frida Kahlo was born in Mexico with a diverse family background","B":"Frida Kahlo did not like her family members","C":"Mexico City is a very large and busy city","D":"Frida Kahlo\u0027s father was originally from Spain"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt tells us where Kahlo was born and about her parents\u0027 backgrounds. This shows her diverse heritage from different cultures.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Frida Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico. Her father was Hungarian, and her mother was of Spanish and Mexican Indian descent.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-l10-q025","read_aloud":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. She stopped playing sports forever and stayed inside B. She continued to play sports and won swimming competitions C. She moved to a different country to get better care D. She became a painter right away instead of playing sports","excerpt":"\"When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other. However, this didn\u0027t slow her down. Kahlo still played sports, and she won several swimming competitions.\"","stem":"How does the excerpt help explain this idea: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"She stopped playing sports forever and stayed inside","B":"She continued to play sports and won swimming competitions","C":"She moved to a different country to get better care","D":"She became a painter right away instead of playing sports"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says polio \"didn\u0027t slow her down\" and that Kahlo \"still played sports\" and \"won several swimming competitions.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other. However, this didn\u0027t slow her down. Kahlo still played sports, and she won several swimming competitions.\""}]}],"standardized_test":{"title":"Standardized Test","item_count":50,"questions":[{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q001","read_aloud":"Based on the whole text, why is \"inspired\" an important word to understand when studying these artists? Options: A. It explains why they moved to new places to find new ideas. B. It shows why they stopped painting. C. It describes the types of paint they used. D. It tells us which artists were the most famous.","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists... different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\"","stem":"Based on the whole text, why is \"inspired\" an important word to understand when studying these artists? Options:","choices":{"A":"It explains why they moved to new places to find new ideas.","B":"It shows why they stopped painting.","C":"It describes the types of paint they used.","D":"It tells us which artists were the most famous."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The entire text focuses on how new locations provided the inspiration for the artists\u0027 themes and styles.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists... different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q002","read_aloud":"Based on the article, why was it important for Gauguin to stop \"imitating\" others? Options: A. So he could save money on art supplies. B. So he could develop his own unique style. C. So he could return to being a stockbroker. D. So he could be friends with more people in France.","excerpt":"\"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone.\"","stem":"Based on the article, why was it important for Gauguin to stop \"imitating\" others? Options:","choices":{"A":"So he could save money on art supplies.","B":"So he could develop his own unique style.","C":"So he could return to being a stockbroker.","D":"So he could be friends with more people in France."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text explains that he wanted to move away from the popular style to create something new.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q003","read_aloud":"Why are exhibits important for artists like O\u0027Keeffe? Options: A. They are the only place artists can paint. B. They allow the public to view and learn about the artist\u0027s work. C. They are where artists go to hide from the world. D. They are used to store old paintings.","excerpt":"\"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"Why are exhibits important for artists like O\u0027Keeffe? Options:","choices":{"A":"They are the only place artists can paint.","B":"They allow the public to view and learn about the artist\u0027s work.","C":"They are where artists go to hide from the world.","D":"They are used to store old paintings."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An exhibit is specifically for \"public viewing,\" which helps share the artist\u0027s work with the world.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q004","read_aloud":"Which statement best summarizes the main idea of the entire text? Options: A. Famous artists rarely travel because it is too distracting. B. Traveling to new places influenced the art and lives of Kahlo, O\u0027Keeffe, and Gauguin. C. Artists only paint landscapes of the places where they were born. D. The stock market crash was the only reason these artists traveled.","excerpt":"\"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys.\"","stem":"Which statement best summarizes the main idea of the entire text? Options:","choices":{"A":"Famous artists rarely travel because it is too distracting.","B":"Traveling to new places influenced the art and lives of Kahlo, O\u0027Keeffe, and Gauguin.","C":"Artists only paint landscapes of the places where they were born.","D":"The stock market crash was the only reason these artists traveled."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The entire selection is dedicated to explaining how journeys impacted the careers and styles of these three specific artists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q005","read_aloud":"Based on the text, what is the most common reason these artists painted what they did? Options: A. They only painted what was popular at the time. B. They painted things that connected them to their personal history, identity, and feelings. C. They painted whatever was the cheapest to draw. D. They painted only to win competitions.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"Based on the text, what is the most common reason these artists painted what they did? Options:","choices":{"A":"They only painted what was popular at the time.","B":"They painted things that connected them to their personal history, identity, and feelings.","C":"They painted whatever was the cheapest to draw.","D":"They painted only to win competitions."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"All three artists are described as using their art to explore their background, identity, or personal experiences.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q006","read_aloud":"Which text structure does the author use to explain the impact of travel on the artists? Options: A. Cause and Effect B. Problem and Solution C. Description only D. Chronological only","excerpt":"\"Text structure refers to the organization of ideas in a text. The most common text structures in informational text are: Chronological, Comparison and Contrast, Cause and Effect, Problem and Solution, and Description.\"","stem":"Which text structure does the author use to explain the impact of travel on the artists? Options:","choices":{"A":"Cause and Effect","B":"Problem and Solution","C":"Description only","D":"Chronological only"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The author consistently explains how the \"cause\" (traveling to a new place) led to an \"effect\" (changes in painting style or theme).","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Text structure refers to the organization of ideas in a text. The most common text structures in informational text are: Chronological, Comparison and Contrast, Cause and Effect, Problem and Solution, and Description.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q007","read_aloud":"What do all three artists have in common according to the text? Options: A. They all were born in the same city. B. They all traveled to different places which influenced their art. C. They all stopped painting at the same age. D. They were all born in the 1900s.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán... O\u0027Keeffe was born in 1887 in the rural town of Sun Prairie, Wisconsin... Gauguin was born in Paris, France, in 1848.\"","stem":"What do all three artists have in common according to the text? Options:","choices":{"A":"They all were born in the same city.","B":"They all traveled to different places which influenced their art.","C":"They all stopped painting at the same age.","D":"They were all born in the 1900s."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text highlights that despite different backgrounds and birthplaces, all three were deeply influenced by their travels.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán... O\u0027Keeffe was born in 1887 in the rural town of Sun Prairie, Wisconsin... Gauguin was born in Paris, France, in 1848.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q008","read_aloud":"How are the artists\u0027 styles similar? Options: A. They all painted only city buildings. B. They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas. C. They all used only dull, dark colors. D. They all painted exactly the same subjects.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"How are the artists\u0027 styles similar? Options:","choices":{"A":"They all painted only city buildings.","B":"They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas.","C":"They all used only dull, dark colors.","D":"They all painted exactly the same subjects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While their subjects varied (flowers, monkeys, tropical islands), they all looked to their environments for personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q009","read_aloud":"Based on the article, why is it important for artists to experiment with new styles? Options: A. It is a way to stop painting for a while. B. Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential. C. It makes the artist famous without any work. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"Based on the article, why is it important for artists to experiment with new styles? Options:","choices":{"A":"It is a way to stop painting for a while.","B":"Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential.","C":"It makes the artist famous without any work.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that by moving away from traditional styles and experimenting, these artists gained recognition and influence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q010","read_aloud":"If you had to choose one of the three artists (Kahlo, O\u0027Keeffe, or Gauguin) to interview, which one would you choose to learn more about how travel changes an artist\u0027s perspective? Provide a reason based on the text. Options: A. Kahlo, because she had many health problems. B. Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti. C. O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States. D. None of them, because they did not travel enough.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"If you had to choose one of the three artists (Kahlo, O\u0027Keeffe, or Gauguin) to interview, which one would you choose to learn more about how travel changes an artist\u0027s perspective? Provide a reason based on the text. Options:","choices":{"A":"Kahlo, because she had many health problems.","B":"Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti.","C":"O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States.","D":"None of them, because they did not travel enough."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin\u0027s story involves the most diverse range of locations (Peru, France, Panama, Martinique, Tahiti), making him a primary example of how traveling influences an artist\u0027s entire career. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Picturesque Journeys\" Author: Yanitzia Canetti Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 5, Savvas Learning Company LLC Preview Vocabulary: inspired, express, exhibit, imitated, compositions","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q011","read_aloud":"What does \"inspired\" mean in this context? A. caused something to be created; motivated artistic work and creativity B. made someone feel sleepy and tired after a long journey C. confused someone about what to paint or how to start working D. stopped someone from finishing their artwork due to distractions","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\"","stem":"What does \"inspired\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"caused something to be created; motivated artistic work and creativity","B":"made someone feel sleepy and tired after a long journey","C":"confused someone about what to paint or how to start working","D":"stopped someone from finishing their artwork due to distractions"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The preview vocabulary and context show \"inspired\" means locations motivated artists \"to create their best works,\" matching the definition \"caused something to be created.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q012","read_aloud":"What are \"compositions\" in the context of art? A. works of art, such as paintings, and how visual elements are arranged within them B. written stories about travel experiences and personal reflections on journeys C. musical songs about distant places and the feelings they inspire in people D. scientific reports about tropical plants and animals for educational purposes","excerpt":"\"He used vivid colors and simple compositions to paint the tropical environment.\"","stem":"What are \"compositions\" in the context of art?","choices":{"A":"works of art, such as paintings, and how visual elements are arranged within them","B":"written stories about travel experiences and personal reflections on journeys","C":"musical songs about distant places and the feelings they inspire in people","D":"scientific reports about tropical plants and animals for educational purposes"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The preview vocabulary defines \"compositions\" as \"works of art, such as paintings and songs.\" In visual art, composition also refers to arrangement of elements, fitting the context of Gauguin\u0027s painting approach.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"He used vivid colors and simple compositions to paint the tropical environment.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q013","read_aloud":"Based on the preview vocabulary, what does \"imitated\" mean? A. copied; tried to do the same things others did in their artwork B. created something completely original without looking at others\u0027 work C. traveled to find new inspiration and ideas from different cultures D. sold artwork to collectors and became famous for their style","excerpt":"\"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone.\"","stem":"Based on the preview vocabulary, what does \"imitated\" mean?","choices":{"A":"copied; tried to do the same things others did in their artwork","B":"created something completely original without looking at others\u0027 work","C":"traveled to find new inspiration and ideas from different cultures","D":"sold artwork to collectors and became famous for their style"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The preview vocabulary defines \"imitated\" as \"copied; tried to do the same things others did.\" The excerpt shows Gauguin wanted to avoid copying other artists.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin felt that many French artists imitated each other rather than trying to create something new and different. He didn\u0027t want to imitate anyone.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q014","read_aloud":"What cause-and-effect relationship is shown in this excerpt? A. Cause: Kahlo missed Mexico; Effect: She included Mexican cultural items in her paintings B. Cause: Kahlo liked jewelry; Effect: She became famous worldwide for her style C. Cause: Kahlo moved to America; Effect: She forgot about Mexico completely D. Cause: Kahlo painted self-portraits; Effect: She stopped traveling to new places","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"What cause-and-effect relationship is shown in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Cause: Kahlo missed Mexico; Effect: She included Mexican cultural items in her paintings","B":"Cause: Kahlo liked jewelry; Effect: She became famous worldwide for her style","C":"Cause: Kahlo moved to America; Effect: She forgot about Mexico completely","D":"Cause: Kahlo painted self-portraits; Effect: She stopped traveling to new places"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The phrase \"That\u0027s why\" signals cause and effect: because Kahlo missed Mexico, she portrayed herself with items representing her cultural heritage.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q015","read_aloud":"What is the correct sequence of events in this excerpt? A. Exhibit opened → became friends → got married → lived in New York B. Got married → exhibit opened → became friends → lived in New York C. Became friends → got married → exhibit opened → lived in New York D. Lived in New York → exhibit opened → became friends → got married","excerpt":"\"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work. Over time, Stieglitz and O\u0027Keeffe became friends as well. In 1924, Stieglitz and O\u0027Keeffe were married, and they lived in New York.\"","stem":"What is the correct sequence of events in this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Exhibit opened → became friends → got married → lived in New York","B":"Got married → exhibit opened → became friends → lived in New York","C":"Became friends → got married → exhibit opened → lived in New York","D":"Lived in New York → exhibit opened → became friends → got married"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt presents events in chronological order: 1916 exhibit → friendship developed → 1924 marriage → living in New York.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work. Over time, Stieglitz and O\u0027Keeffe became friends as well. In 1924, Stieglitz and O\u0027Keeffe were married, and they lived in New York.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q016","read_aloud":"How does the word \"Like\" at the beginning of this sentence help organize the text? A. It signals a comparison, showing that O\u0027Keeffe shares a key characteristic with Kahlo B. It introduces a completely new topic unrelated to the previous section about Kahlo C. It suggests that O\u0027Keeffe copied Kahlo\u0027s painting style exactly without changes D. It indicates that the text is switching to poetry instead of informational text","excerpt":"\"Like Kahlo, the American artist Georgia O\u0027Keeffe was deeply influenced by her cultural background and her travels.\"","stem":"How does the word \"Like\" at the beginning of this sentence help organize the text?","choices":{"A":"It signals a comparison, showing that O\u0027Keeffe shares a key characteristic with Kahlo","B":"It introduces a completely new topic unrelated to the previous section about Kahlo","C":"It suggests that O\u0027Keeffe copied Kahlo\u0027s painting style exactly without changes","D":"It indicates that the text is switching to poetry instead of informational text"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"\"Like Kahlo\" signals a comparison structure, helping readers see that O\u0027Keeffe, like the previously discussed Kahlo, was \"influenced by her cultural background and her travels.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Like Kahlo, the American artist Georgia O\u0027Keeffe was deeply influenced by her cultural background and her travels.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q017","read_aloud":"Where was Frida Kahlo born? A. In Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico B. In Paris, France, where she later traveled as an adult C. In New York City, USA, where she exhibited her work D. In Lima, Peru, where Gauguin spent his childhood","excerpt":"\"Frida Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico.\"","stem":"Where was Frida Kahlo born?","choices":{"A":"In Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico","B":"In Paris, France, where she later traveled as an adult","C":"In New York City, USA, where she exhibited her work","D":"In Lima, Peru, where Gauguin spent his childhood"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt directly states Kahlo \"was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Frida Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q018","read_aloud":"How does describing Kahlo\u0027s paintings as \"visual autobiographies\" help readers understand her art? A. It suggests her paintings tell personal stories about her life experiences and feelings, like a written autobiography but using images B. It means her paintings are exact copies of photographs from her life without any changes C. It indicates she only painted scenes from her childhood home in Mexico D. It suggests her paintings have no connection to her personal life or experiences","excerpt":"\"No matter where Kahlo lived, she made paintings that were like visual autobiographies. Every painting tells the story of something remarkable she lived through and how she felt about it.\"","stem":"How does describing Kahlo\u0027s paintings as \"visual autobiographies\" help readers understand her art?","choices":{"A":"It suggests her paintings tell personal stories about her life experiences and feelings, like a written autobiography but using images","B":"It means her paintings are exact copies of photographs from her life without any changes","C":"It indicates she only painted scenes from her childhood home in Mexico","D":"It suggests her paintings have no connection to her personal life or experiences"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"An autobiography is a written story of one\u0027s own life. Calling paintings \"visual autobiographies\" helps readers understand that Kahlo\u0027s art communicated personal experiences and emotions through images rather than words.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"No matter where Kahlo lived, she made paintings that were like visual autobiographies. Every painting tells the story of something remarkable she lived through and how she felt about it.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q019","read_aloud":"Based on the entire selection, was travel more important for artistic development or for personal growth? Use evidence to support your view. A. Travel was important for both, because the text shows it helped artists understand their identity (personal growth) and develop distinctive styles that influenced others (artistic development) B. Travel was only important for artistic development; personal growth is not mentioned in the text at all C. Travel was only important for personal growth; artistic style is not connected to travel in any way D. Travel was not important for either; the text suggests artists should stay in one place to focus","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style. That style made her one of the world\u0027s most famous artists, one who has influenced many others.\"","stem":"Based on the entire selection, was travel more important for artistic development or for personal growth? Use evidence to support your view.","choices":{"A":"Travel was important for both, because the text shows it helped artists understand their identity (personal growth) and develop distinctive styles that influenced others (artistic development)","B":"Travel was only important for artistic development; personal growth is not mentioned in the text at all","C":"Travel was only important for personal growth; artistic style is not connected to travel in any way","D":"Travel was not important for either; the text suggests artists should stay in one place to focus"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt explicitly states travel helped Kahlo \"better understand her own identity\" (personal growth) AND \"develop a distinct artistic style\" (artistic development). Similar patterns appear for O\u0027Keeffe and Gauguin, supporting the view that travel served both purposes.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style. That style made her one of the world\u0027s most famous artists, one who has influenced many others.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q020","read_aloud":"(Weekly Question) If you were to write a poem about an artist\u0027s journey, what two ideas from \"Picturesque Journeys\" would you include, and how would you express them poetically? A. Idea 1: Places can become part of an artist\u0027s identity; Idea 2: Missing home can inspire creative expression. Poetic expression: Use imagery of landscapes blending with self-portraits, and metaphors comparing colors to emotions of longing and belonging B. Idea 1: Artists should never travel; Idea 2: Copying is the best way to learn art. Poetic expression: Use repetitive lines and avoid descriptive language about places C. Idea 1: Only European places matter for artists; Idea 2: Artists should paint only what they see literally. Poetic expression: Use only literal descriptions with no figurative language or metaphors D. Idea 1: Travel is too expensive for most artists; Idea 2: Artists should work alone without inspiration. Poetic expression: Focus on complaints about cost and isolation from others","excerpt":"What inspires people to start a journey?","stem":"(Weekly Question) If you were to write a poem about an artist\u0027s journey, what two ideas from \"Picturesque Journeys\" would you include, and how would you express them poetically?","choices":{"A":"Idea 1: Places can become part of an artist\u0027s identity; Idea 2: Missing home can inspire creative expression. Poetic expression: Use imagery of landscapes blending with self-portraits, and metaphors comparing colors to emotions of longing and belonging","B":"Idea 1: Artists should never travel; Idea 2: Copying is the best way to learn art. Poetic expression: Use repetitive lines and avoid descriptive language about places","C":"Idea 1: Only European places matter for artists; Idea 2: Artists should paint only what they see literally. Poetic expression: Use only literal descriptions with no figurative language or metaphors","D":"Idea 1: Travel is too expensive for most artists; Idea 2: Artists should work alone without inspiration. Poetic expression: Focus on complaints about cost and isolation from others"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows places shaped artists\u0027 identities (Kahlo\u0027s Mexican heritage in her art) and that missing home inspired creativity (Kahlo painting Mexican symbols while abroa d). Expressing these through imagery (landscapes + self-portraits) and metaphor (colors as emotions) would capture the text\u0027s themes poetically. Section A - Text Information Title: Picturesque Journeys Author: Yanitzia Canetti","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: What inspires people to start a journey?"},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q021","read_aloud":"What did different places do for the artists? A. They made them tired. B. They inspired their themes, colors, and styles. C. They confused them. D. They made them stop painting.","excerpt":"\"Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\"","stem":"What did different places do for the artists?","choices":{"A":"They made them tired.","B":"They inspired their themes, colors, and styles.","C":"They confused them.","D":"They made them stop painting."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The places inspired their art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q022","read_aloud":"To \"express\" yourself in art means to ______. A. Hide your feelings B. Show your thoughts and feelings C. Copy another artist D. Throw away your paints","excerpt":"\"Artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\"","stem":"To \"express\" yourself in art means to ______.","choices":{"A":"Hide your feelings","B":"Show your thoughts and feelings","C":"Copy another artist","D":"Throw away your paints"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Express means to show or communicate feelings.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q023","read_aloud":"What is an exhibit? A. A private storage room B. A public showing of art C. A type of paint D. A frame for a picture","excerpt":"\"Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"What is an exhibit?","choices":{"A":"A private storage room","B":"A public showing of art","C":"A type of paint","D":"A frame for a picture"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"An exhibit is a public showing of artworks.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q024","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of Picturesque Journeys? A. All artists are the same. B. Travel to different places inspired three famous artists\u0027 work. C. Painting is difficult. D. Artists should never leave home.","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"What is the main idea of Picturesque Journeys?","choices":{"A":"All artists are the same.","B":"Travel to different places inspired three famous artists\u0027 work.","C":"Painting is difficult.","D":"Artists should never leave home."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows how travel inspired Kahlo, O\u0027Keeffe, and Gauguin.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q025","read_aloud":"What can you infer about O\u0027Keeffe from this sentence? A. She hated cities. B. New York City\u0027s skyscrapers fascinated her and became art. C. She only painted flowers. D. She was afraid of heights.","excerpt":"\"O\u0027Keeffe was captivated by skyscrapers. She made these tall buildings the subjects of such paintings.\"","stem":"What can you infer about O\u0027Keeffe from this sentence?","choices":{"A":"She hated cities.","B":"New York City\u0027s skyscrapers fascinated her and became art.","C":"She only painted flowers.","D":"She was afraid of heights."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Being \"captivated\" means fascinated, so she painted them.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"O\u0027Keeffe was captivated by skyscrapers. She made these tall buildings the subjects of such paintings.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q026","read_aloud":"What qualities did Gauguin admire in art from other cultures? A. Complicated designs B. Strength and simplicity C. Dark colors only D. Realistic details","excerpt":"\"Gauguin was fascinated by the strength and simplicity of art from Africa, Asia, and Latin America. In Tahiti, he strived to use these qualities in his own artworks.\"","stem":"What qualities did Gauguin admire in art from other cultures?","choices":{"A":"Complicated designs","B":"Strength and simplicity","C":"Dark colors only","D":"Realistic details"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says strength and simplicity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Gauguin was fascinated by the strength and simplicity of art from Africa, Asia, and Latin America. In Tahiti, he strived to use these qualities in his own artworks.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q027","read_aloud":"How did all three artists use their new locations in similar ways? A. They painted only self-portraits. B. They used colors, subjects, and styles from those places in their art. C. They never painted landscapes. D. They painted only realistic scenes.","excerpt":"Compare Kahlo (Mexico), O\u0027Keeffe (Southwest), and Gauguin (Tahiti).","stem":"How did all three artists use their new locations in similar ways?","choices":{"A":"They painted only self-portraits.","B":"They used colors, subjects, and styles from those places in their art.","C":"They never painted landscapes.","D":"They painted only realistic scenes."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Each artist\u0027s work reflected the places they traveled to.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: Compare Kahlo (Mexico), O\u0027Keeffe (Southwest), and Gauguin (Tahiti)."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q028","read_aloud":"Do you think the author\u0027s statement is supported by the text? Why? A. No, because the text does not say much about travel. B. Yes, because the text gives many examples of how travel changed each artist. C. No, because artists are born talented. D. Yes, but only for Kahlo.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"Do you think the author\u0027s statement is supported by the text? Why?","choices":{"A":"No, because the text does not say much about travel.","B":"Yes, because the text gives many examples of how travel changed each artist.","C":"No, because artists are born talented.","D":"Yes, but only for Kahlo."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text provides strong evidence of travel\u0027s effect on each artist.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q029","read_aloud":"If you could give advice to a young artist based on this text, what would you say? A. Never leave your hometown. B. Travel to new places for inspiration, and paint what you feel and see. C. Only paint realistic flowers. D. Copy famous artists exactly.","excerpt":"The whole text.","stem":"If you could give advice to a young artist based on this text, what would you say?","choices":{"A":"Never leave your hometown.","B":"Travel to new places for inspiration, and paint what you feel and see.","C":"Only paint realistic flowers.","D":"Copy famous artists exactly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that new places inspired unique, expressive art. Section A - Text information Title: Picturesque Journeys Author: Yanitzia Canetti","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: The whole text."},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q030","read_aloud":"What does \"inspired\" mean in this sentence? A. stopped someone from working B. caused new ideas and creativity C. made someone sleepy D. broke something into pieces","excerpt":"\"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys. Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\"","stem":"What does \"inspired\" mean in this sentence?","choices":{"A":"stopped someone from working","B":"caused new ideas and creativity","C":"made someone sleepy","D":"broke something into pieces"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says visiting different places inspired the themes and colors of the artists\u0027 works. \"Inspired\" means it caused new ideas and creativity.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Many paintings by artists Frida Kahlo, Georgia O\u0027Keeffe, and Paul Gauguin were strongly influenced by their journeys. Visiting or living in different places inspired the themes of their works and their colors and painting styles.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q031","read_aloud":"What does \"express\" mean in this context? A. to hide everything B. to show thoughts and feelings through art C. to run very fast D. to eat quickly","excerpt":"\"Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\"","stem":"What does \"express\" mean in this context?","choices":{"A":"to hide everything","B":"to show thoughts and feelings through art","C":"to run very fast","D":"to eat quickly"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Dow believed artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading. \"Express\" means to show thoughts and feelings through art.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Arthur Wesley Dow, who believed that artists should express themselves using color, lines, and shading.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q032","read_aloud":"What is the main idea of this excerpt? A. Traveling to new places can inspire artists to create great works of art. B. Artists do not like to travel. C. Only three artists in the world have ever traveled. D. Traveling makes people tired.","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\"","stem":"What is the main idea of this excerpt?","choices":{"A":"Traveling to new places can inspire artists to create great works of art.","B":"Artists do not like to travel.","C":"Only three artists in the world have ever traveled.","D":"Traveling makes people tired."},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt tells us that travel to distant places has a powerful effect on artists. It inspired three great painters to create their best works. This is the main idea.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q033","read_aloud":"What happened last in this sequence of events? A. Kahlo became ill with polio. B. Kahlo was in a bus crash. C. Kahlo\u0027s parents gave her paints. D. Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.","excerpt":"\"When she was six, she became ill with polio. At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering. Kahlo became bored lying in bed. Her parents gave her some paints. She began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\"","stem":"What happened last in this sequence of events?","choices":{"A":"Kahlo became ill with polio.","B":"Kahlo was in a bus crash.","C":"Kahlo\u0027s parents gave her paints.","D":"Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom."},"correct_choice":"D","rationale":"The sequence is: polio at age 6, bus crash at age 18, parents gave her paints, and finally she began to paint everything in her bedroom. The last event was her beginning to paint.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When she was six, she became ill with polio. At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering. Kahlo became bored lying in bed. Her parents gave her some paints. She began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q034","read_aloud":"What can you infer about Kahlo\u0027s feelings toward Mexico? A. She did not like Mexico at all. B. She loved Mexico and missed it when she was away. C. She forgot about Mexico. D. She was afraid of Mexico.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\"","stem":"What can you infer about Kahlo\u0027s feelings toward Mexico?","choices":{"A":"She did not like Mexico at all.","B":"She loved Mexico and missed it when she was away.","C":"She forgot about Mexico.","D":"She was afraid of Mexico."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. She painted herself with objects from her cultural heritage. This shows she loved Mexico and missed it.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo missed her colorful and warm homeland. That\u0027s why in many of her paintings she portrays herself wearing jewelry and surrounded by objects that identify her cultural heritage.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q035","read_aloud":"What did Stieglitz do for O\u0027Keeffe in 1916? A. He told her to stop painting. B. He opened the first exhibit of her work. C. He bought all her paintings. D. He moved her to France.","excerpt":"\"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\"","stem":"What did Stieglitz do for O\u0027Keeffe in 1916?","choices":{"A":"He told her to stop painting.","B":"He opened the first exhibit of her work.","C":"He bought all her paintings.","D":"He moved her to France."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that in 1916, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work in New York City.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"In 1916, in New York City, Stieglitz opened the first exhibit of O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s work.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q036","read_aloud":"How did the South of France change Van Gogh\u0027s painting style? A. It made him use darker colors. B. It inspired him to paint with brighter colors and more emotion. C. It made him stop painting. D. It had no effect on his style.","excerpt":"\"But the beautiful landscape and the bright light and colors of the South inspired him. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.\"","stem":"How did the South of France change Van Gogh\u0027s painting style?","choices":{"A":"It made him use darker colors.","B":"It inspired him to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.","C":"It made him stop painting.","D":"It had no effect on his style."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says the beautiful landscape and bright light of the South inspired Van Gogh. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion. This shows how the place changed his style.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"But the beautiful landscape and the bright light and colors of the South inspired him. He began to paint with brighter colors and more emotion.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q037","read_aloud":"What does this tell you about O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s connection to New Mexico? A. She did not like it there. B. She felt deeply connected to the desert and spent her life painting its beauty. C. She only visited once. D. She thought the desert was ugly.","excerpt":"\"After her husband\u0027s death, O\u0027Keeffe moved to New Mexico. She spent the rest of her life there, painting the desert and its flowers, mountains, and bones.\"","stem":"What does this tell you about O\u0027Keeffe\u0027s connection to New Mexico?","choices":{"A":"She did not like it there.","B":"She felt deeply connected to the desert and spent her life painting its beauty.","C":"She only visited once.","D":"She thought the desert was ugly."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"O\u0027Keeffe moved to New Mexico after her husband\u0027s death and spent the rest of her life there. She painted the desert, flowers, mountains, and bones. This shows a deep connection to the place.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"After her husband\u0027s death, O\u0027Keeffe moved to New Mexico. She spent the rest of her life there, painting the desert and its flowers, mountains, and bones.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q038","read_aloud":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Read the excerpt and choose the best answer. Which choice is best supported about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q039","read_aloud":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Use the evidence in the excerpt to answer. What is the strongest conclusion about ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q040","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? A. She moved to a new country. B. She became sick with polio. C. She started painting. D. She went to school.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ?","choices":{"A":"She moved to a new country.","B":"She became sick with polio.","C":"She started painting.","D":"She went to school."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text clearly states that she became ill with polio at age six.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo showed her determined spirit from an early age. When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q041","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501. A. They all painted only city buildings. B. They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas. C. They all used only dull, dark colors. D. They all painted exactly the same subjects.","excerpt":"\"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 501.","choices":{"A":"They all painted only city buildings.","B":"They all used the natural world and their surroundings to express their personal ideas.","C":"They all used only dull, dark colors.","D":"They all painted exactly the same subjects."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"While their subjects varied (flowers, monkeys, tropical islands), they all looked to their environments for personal expression.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo painted tropical plants and animals from her homeland... O\u0027Keeffe began making large-scale paintings of nature at close range... Gauguin started to include tropical landscapes and symbols in his artwork.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q042","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502. A. It is a way to stop painting for a while. B. Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential. C. It makes the artist famous without any work. D. It is required by law.","excerpt":"\"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 502.","choices":{"A":"It is a way to stop painting for a while.","B":"Experimenting allows artists to create work that is unique and influential.","C":"It makes the artist famous without any work.","D":"It is required by law."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text shows that by moving away from traditional styles and experimenting, these artists gained recognition and influence.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel helped her better understand her own identity and develop a distinct artistic style... she became one of the first American artists to practice a purely abstract style of art... Gauguin had a huge influence on modern art.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q043","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503. A. Kahlo, because she had many health problems. B. Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti. C. O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States. D. None of them, because they did not travel enough.","excerpt":"\"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 503.","choices":{"A":"Kahlo, because she had many health problems.","B":"Gauguin, because he lived in many different countries like Peru, France, and Tahiti.","C":"O\u0027Keeffe, because she only lived in the United States.","D":"None of them, because they did not travel enough."},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"Gauguin\u0027s story involves the most diverse range of locations (Peru, France, Panama, Martinique, Tahiti), making him a primary example of how traveling influences an artist\u0027s entire career. Section A - Text Information Title: \"Picturesque Journeys\" Author: Yanitzia Canetti Source: Student Interactive U1 Week 5, Savvas Learning Company LLC Preview Vocabulary: inspired, express, exhibit, imitated, compositions","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"It is impossible to imagine how different these artists\u0027 lives, and art, would have been if they had never traveled.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q044","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504. A. caused something to be created; motivated artistic work B. made someone feel tired and sleepy C. confused someone about what to paint D. stopped someone from finishing their artwork","excerpt":"\"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 504.","choices":{"A":"caused something to be created; motivated artistic work","B":"made someone feel tired and sleepy","C":"confused someone about what to paint","D":"stopped someone from finishing their artwork"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows locations \"inspired\" painters \"to create their best works.\" This means the places motivated or caused the art to be made.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Travel to distant places can have a powerful effect on people. This is especially true of artists. As the lives of the three artists featured here show, different locations have inspired some of the world\u0027s greatest painters to create their best works.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q045","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505. A. Frida Kahlo was born in Mexico with a diverse family background B. Frida Kahlo did not like her family members C. Mexico City is a very large and busy city D. Frida Kahlo\u0027s father was originally from Spain","excerpt":"\"Frida Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico. Her father was Hungarian, and her mother was of Spanish and Mexican Indian descent.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 505.","choices":{"A":"Frida Kahlo was born in Mexico with a diverse family background","B":"Frida Kahlo did not like her family members","C":"Mexico City is a very large and busy city","D":"Frida Kahlo\u0027s father was originally from Spain"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The excerpt tells us where Kahlo was born and about her parents\u0027 backgrounds. This shows her diverse heritage from different cultures.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Frida Kahlo was born in 1907 in the town of Coyoacán, outside Mexico City, Mexico. Her father was Hungarian, and her mother was of Spanish and Mexican Indian descent.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q046","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506. A. She stopped playing sports forever and stayed inside B. She continued to play sports and won swimming competitions C. She moved to a different country to get better care D. She became a painter right away instead of playing sports","excerpt":"\"When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other. However, this didn\u0027t slow her down. Kahlo still played sports, and she won several swimming competitions.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 506.","choices":{"A":"She stopped playing sports forever and stayed inside","B":"She continued to play sports and won swimming competitions","C":"She moved to a different country to get better care","D":"She became a painter right away instead of playing sports"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says polio \"didn\u0027t slow her down\" and that Kahlo \"still played sports\" and \"won several swimming competitions.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"When she was six, she became ill with polio. It made one of her legs thinner and weaker than the other. However, this didn\u0027t slow her down. Kahlo still played sports, and she won several swimming competitions.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q047","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507. A. She got married to the painter Diego Rivera B. She was in a serious bus crash that injured her C. She moved to the United States to study art D. She painted her very first self-portrait painting","excerpt":"\"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 507.","choices":{"A":"She got married to the painter Diego Rivera","B":"She was in a serious bus crash that injured her","C":"She moved to the United States to study art","D":"She painted her very first self-portrait painting"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The excerpt directly states that at age 18, Kahlo \"was in a bus crash and was seriously injured.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"At age 18, Kahlo was in a bus crash and was seriously injured. She had to spend many months resting and recovering.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q048","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508. A. Because her parents gave her paints while she rested after her injury B. Because she wanted to become famous very quickly C. Because her teacher told her she had to paint every day D. Because she had nothing else to do at school that year","excerpt":"\"Kahlo became bored lying in bed, staring at the ceiling. Her parents decided to give her a box of paints and an easel that she could use in bed. Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 508.","choices":{"A":"Because her parents gave her paints while she rested after her injury","B":"Because she wanted to become famous very quickly","C":"Because her teacher told her she had to paint every day","D":"Because she had nothing else to do at school that year"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"The text shows Kahlo received paints from her parents while resting after her crash, and she began painting what she saw around her bedroom.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Kahlo became bored lying in bed, staring at the ceiling. Her parents decided to give her a box of paints and an easel that she could use in bed. Kahlo began to paint everything she saw in her bedroom.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q049","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509. A. show or tell thoughts and feelings to others through creative work B. hide feelings from other people and keep them secret C. forget about important memories and move on quickly D. copy someone else\u0027s artwork without changing it","excerpt":"\"Because she had a huge mirror in front of her bed, she started to paint images of herself. Kahlo would continue to create self-portraits throughout her life.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 509.","choices":{"A":"show or tell thoughts and feelings to others through creative work","B":"hide feelings from other people and keep them secret","C":"forget about important memories and move on quickly","D":"copy someone else\u0027s artwork without changing it"},"correct_choice":"A","rationale":"Artists use art to \"express\" by showing their thoughts and feelings. This matches the definition of sharing emotions through creative work.","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"Because she had a huge mirror in front of her bed, she started to paint images of herself. Kahlo would continue to create self-portraits throughout her life.\""},{"item_id":"g5-u1-w5-picturesque-journeys-std-q050","read_aloud":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510. A. He said she was not talented and should stop painting B. He told her she was talented and they became friends C. He refused to look at her work or give any opinion D. He bought all of her paintings for a large amount of money","excerpt":"\"One day, she passed by a building where the famous painter Diego Rivera was painting a huge mural. She decided to show Rivera some of her paintings and ask him for his opinion. Rivera agreed to take a look. He told her she was talented.\"","stem":"Which answer best uses the excerpt to respond to this question: ? Choose the answer for practice item 510.","choices":{"A":"He said she was not talented and should stop painting","B":"He told her she was talented and they became friends","C":"He refused to look at her work or give any opinion","D":"He bought all of her paintings for a large amount of money"},"correct_choice":"B","rationale":"The text says Rivera \"told her she was talented\" and that this was \"the beginning of a long friendship between the two artists.\"","text_evidence":"Use the excerpt: \"One day, she passed by a building where the famous painter Diego Rivera was painting a huge mural. She decided to show Rivera some of her paintings and ask him for his opinion. Rivera agreed to take a look. He told her she was talented.\""}]}}]};const target=window.READING_SELECTIONS_DATA||{selections:[]};const existingIds=new Set((target.selections||[]).map((selection)=>selection.selection_id));grade5Unit1Selections.selections.forEach((selection)=>{if(!existingIds.has(selection.selection_id)){target.selections.push(selection);}});window.READING_SELECTIONS_DATA=target;})();
